<HEADLINE>
WELL-READ _ JUST NOT FOM THAT LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventeen out of 100? This is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   When the list of the 20th century's greatest novels in English
came out Monday, cries of dissent quickly followed.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough women writers, some critics carped (only eight books
by women made the list). Too many Americans and Brits, others cried
(aside from James Joyce, who has three books on it, the list
included no other works by English-speaking writers from outside
the U.S. and Britain).
</P>
<P>
   Others found the list arrogant, including the person who posted
this missive on the ``New York Times'' book forum the day the list
was released:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just glanced. What a joke . . . what a bleeping joke. . . .
I've never wanted to be as profane on these forums as I want to be
now. I couldn't read past the first 10. . . . These people are . .
. well, I won't say idiots. . . . Oh, bleep. Intellectual snobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Worthy complaints, all. Well, maybe not that last one. But none
is the one that I first found with the list, and I'll bet many
people shared the same sentiment:
</P>
<P>
   It makes me feel stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Which is another way of saying I haven't read nearly enough of
the books on the list.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think I'm a good reader. I've never done more than
look at the cover of a bodice ripper. I've never once allowed
myself to read a John Grisham potboiler. Yet all of a sudden, I
feel like I ought to look for books in airports instead of
libraries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXCUSES, EXCUSES
</P>
<P>
   I allowed myself a few justifications. This kind of list doesn't
mean anything, anyway (a list released Tuesday by publishing
students at Radcliffe College was far different). The list is
nothing more than a marketing tool for Random House's Modern
Library, whose editorial board compiled it (Random House is going
to place promotional material in bookstores offering novels from
the list). It gives short shrift to modern writers, whose books I
am more likely to read.
</P>
<P>
   Some or all of which may be true. But it does nothing to change
the fact that I have read only 17 of the top 100. (I've cracked six
or seven others but never finished them.)
</P>
<P>
   The trouble starts at the top. I've never finished ``Ulysses,''
by James Joyce, the No. 1 pick. I own it. I've started it. I know
what it's about. I've just never gotten all the way through it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm batting a weak .300 for the top 10: I've read only ``The
Great Gatsby,'' by F. Scott Fitzgerald, ``The Sound and the
Fury,''by William Faulkner, and ``The Grapes of Wrath,'' by John
Steinbeck.
</P>
<P>
   More embarrassingly, I've never even HEARD of some of the books,
such as ``A Dance to the Music of Time,'' by Anthony Powell, or ``A
House for Ms. Biswas,'' by V.S. Naipaul. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MASH' FINALE
</P>
<P>
   Whenever i went over the list with other people, comparing our
shortcomings, I felt mostly shame, interrupted by the occasional
burst of pride. When we would finally get to a book I'd read, I
automatically said something along the lines of, ``Man, that was a
good one,'' even if I hadn't much liked it.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of an old ``Peanuts'' cartoon, in which Lucy Van
Pelt walks around the neighborhood reading a book, telling everyone
who will listen how great it is. In fact, she says, it's the best
book she's ever read. Finally, Violet asks, ``What other books have
you read?''
</P>
<P>
   She lowers the book from her face, and answers, ``This is the
only one.''
</P>
<P>
   One friend had read nine of the top 10, ``but I only understood
three of them.'' A story about the list quoted the writer Cynthia
Ozick; she claims to have read 90.
</P>
<P>
   The path is clear: I must resolve to read more of these books.
I've got to finish the ones I've started. I have to spend more time
improving my mind by reading and less time on such empty pursuits
as watching television and wasting time on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And I will. The minute this ``MASH'' rerun is over.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
