<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Thursday, July 23. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MURDER (Phoenix) - Before Dominique Keys shot her husband dead
Tuesday afternoon, the British couple twice tried to sell his
serial killer confession story to tabloid magazines. But British
police say the murder story is complete rubbish, and now she's the
one facing first-degree murder charges. By CHRISTINA LEONARD. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TRIBES (Washington) - More than $750 million in federal dollars for
Indian social programs isn't being targeted to the tribes needing
it the most, congressional auditors report. The General Accounting
Office found that tribes making millions of dollars from casinos
are, in some cases, receiving more funding than poor tribes for
child welfare, law enforcement and other critical needs. But some
Indians view the report, requested by Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.,
as an assault on tribes that have finally lifted themselves out of
poverty through gaming revenues. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAR DEALERS (Phoenix) - Arizona dealers in General Motors cars and
trucks find supplies on vehicles and mostly parts getting tight,
though it's not as bad in Arizona as it is in some other parts of
the country. The hot-selling Suburbans and Yukons are gone, in some
cases, and customers' cars are stacking up waiting for parts. Worse
is the public perception that dealers are out of cars entirely or
trying to gouge customers for scarce vehicles, resulting in empty
showrooms and and lax sales for July. By BOB GOLFEN. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ABORTION-CLINIC (Phoenix) - The A-Z abortion clinic that employed
Dr. John Biskind is reportedly closing its doors, as are two other
Phoenix area clinics owned by the same New York doctor. The clinics
apparently can't keep any docs or staff members. Meanwhile,
patients' appointments are being canceled and they are being told
to go elsewhere. By SUSIE STECKNER and JODIE SNYDER. Story will
move in the ``A`` category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPIELBERG-MOVIE (Undated) -Steven Spielberg's latest creation,
``Saving Private Ryan,'' is a shock to the system. The battle
scenes contain some of the rawest footage of what it looks like
when human bodies are ripped apart by machine gun fire. ``This is
only a glance at what they had to endure on that beach and live
with for the rest of their lives,'` Spielberg explained. ``I
intended to make the most realistic war film ever.'` Republic
critic Bob Fenster interviews Spielberg, Tom Hanks and Matt Damon.
EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE FRIDAY, JULY 24. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved
in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAVING RYAN-MOVIE (Undated) - War movies fracture along the fault
lines of combat: bravery and cowardice, the quick and the dead,
mission and madness, the officers who give tough orders and the men
on the ground who die carrying them out. ``Saving Private Ryan''
leaves us shaken along all those fault lines. You would not want it
more intense. You may not want it this intense. 5 stars. EMBARGOED
FOR RELEASE FRIDAY, JULY 24. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the
``E'' category.
</P>
