<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A STRANGE TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 23:
</P>
<P>
   First off, it doesn't sound right. Silence in mid-city alerts
the senses the way a loud noise unnerves people in the country.
Here we are at the center of the universe, or more precisely at the
center of our universe, and there are no cars lurching, no taxis
honking, nobody begging quarters or selling cut-rate silk ties or
chanting ``excuse me'' as he shoulders through the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Times Square without traffic or New Year's revelers feels not
only empty but barren, like some big-city version of the deserted
American Main Street where store windows are black and traffic
lights blink at nobody. Manhattan's Main Street, of course, cannot
be entirely vacant after the scaffolding sagged and then fell from
a construction site on Tuesday morning, killing one person and
injuring a dozen. There will be maintenance crews, ambulances and
fire trucks, all trying to ward off a nasty aftershock from a tower
that could at any moment scatter debris throughout the theater
district.
</P>
<P>
   The tides of workers and tourists moved in new currents on
Wednesday, surging from a distance of several blocks to as close as
a few hundred feet from the accident, their paths detailed by a row
of barricades punctuated every few yards by a police officer.
Tourists took it in stride, subtracting plans to see ``Cabaret,''
which was playing at a theater nearly beneath the bad scaffolding,
and adding the crosswalks at 43d Street, where the distant tower
looks like a Lego construction that has been kicked in its
midsection by a frustrated child.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers also adapted, but not always so easily. At 43d and
Fifth Avenue, a policeman was informing an earnest young man on
Wednesday that his bank was not open. ``Why not?'' the New Yorker
snorted, as the unstable tower shimmered in the background heat a
block and a half away. Only a New Yorker would ask such a question.
Nobody needs Chicken Little to know that our skyline is always
falling, shedding bits and pieces like some inanimate equalizer on
high. A chunk of Yankee Stadium, a building facade, a deadly brick,
a subway ceiling _ these dangers force New Yorkers to play a kind
of daily survival Lotto. Now, for a few days at least, the dangers
have rearranged the city center itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
