<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVINGRYAN-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      07-23 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVINGRYAN-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RYAN' CAP TURES WAR'S IN TENSITY, EMOTION  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE FRIDAY, JULY 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - War movies fracture along the fault lines of combat:
bravery and cowardice, the quick and the dead, mission and madness,
the officers who give tough orders and the men on the ground who
die carrying them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' leaves us shaken along all those fault
lines with men who had no choice but to endure what military
historian Stephen Ambrose calls ``the inevitability of combat.''
</P>
<P>
   In his attempt to create the intense reality of battle under
heavy weapons fire, director Steven Spielberg makes ``Saving
Private Ryan'' one of the most realistic and heartbreaking war
stories ever filmed.
</P>
<P>
   You would not want it more intense. You may not want it this
intense.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins on D-Day, June 6, 1944, off-shore of Omaha
Beach, with a company of Rangers landing into the mouths of German
machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Men die by the score. Bodies are ripped apart. Hope is buried
under an endless fusillade.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' attempts to reach shore, to move up the beach, to
survive the day form the most graphically intense battle sequence
yet filmed of modern warfare. It is a scene that would be the
climax of most war movies.
</P>
<P>
   It is only the beginning of ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie then follows one squad of survivors, led by Captain
Miller (Tom Hanks), as they are given a FUBAR mission. Veterans
will recognize that military slang; others will learn its meaning
as the movie progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and his men are sent forward into enemy territory to find
and bring back one soldier, Private James Ryan (Matt Damon).
</P>
<P>
   Why Ryan? His four brothers have been killed in action. Since he
is the sole surviving son, the brass want him sent home, as a
symbol of their efforts to save the American family from being
wiped out by the ferocious onslaught of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's men realize they are being asked to risk their lives on
a PR mission, and they don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   That squad includes:
</P>
<P>
   _Private Reiben (Ed Burns), a veteran of too many battles who is
smart enough to realize how stupid they are for taking the mission.
</P>
<P>
   _Sergeant Horvath (Tom Sizemore), who collects a canister of
dirt from every country he fights through.
</P>
<P>
   _Private Jackson (Barry Pepper), the sniper who takes a
spiritual approach to battle.
</P>
<P>
   _Corporal Upham (Jeremy Davies), an interpreter who is so new to
battle that he thinks there are rules of right and wrong under
combat.
</P>
<P>
   As they gripe their way across the killing fields of France to
find Ryan, director Spielberg paints a grimly realistic picture of
how land wars are fought minute by minute, how a small group of men
with a limited view of the mission and the cause for which they
will die, cling only to the slim hopes of survival and loyalty to
the men on either side of them.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Hanks and Damon, who represent the goodness and hope
of the men nations send off to die, most of the actors are
unfamiliar or rarely seen faces.
</P>
<P>
   This casting adds to the film's sense of authenticity, depicting
ordinary men caught up in extraordinary circumstances from which
they cannot extricate themselves and so must push forward against
their better judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks and the entire cast capture the sensibilities of GIs from
any era, portraying their reluctant heroism in the face of constant
fear.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatically, Spielberg has set himself an interesting dilemma:
The opening battle is so intense that the rest of the film cannot
rise in intensity from that level. The battle for Omaha Beach could
have been a movie unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg deals with this dramatic quandary by taking the story
back down to a more intimate portrait of eight men who have no way
out but to march into doom.
</P>
<P>
   That shift in focus will work for some people, but it may leave
others wondering if they're watching the movie backward.
</P>
<P>
   What should catch everyone is Spielberg's attention to detail
and his ability to capture the frenzied panic of ground battles.
</P>
<P>
   Does he go too far in his efforts to shock with graphic
violence? Yes, he goes as far as a movie can go to re-create the
sights and sounds of actual battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Red One,'' ''Platoon'' and ``Hamburger Hill'' took a
similar approach in their grim depictions of the way heavy weapons
fire can tear apart the human body with indiscriminate dis patch.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Saving Private Ryan'' is even more intense then those
excellent war films because of advances in special effects and
Spielberg's greater command of the emotional uses to which those
effects can be put.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg stays right on the ground with his squad, on one
narrow strip of beach, in one shell-shattered town, with eight
soldiers fighting through the only war they have: the one
surrounding them on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating way to create an epic, not going wide like
``Patton,'' ''The Longest Day'' or ``A Bridge Too Far,'' but going
much deeper. In so doing, he honors ordinary soldiers, survivors
and fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' takes up a position with a short list of
other films that showed a realistic view of soldiers sent out to
die on impossible missions: ``All Quiet on the Western Front,''
``Paths of Glory,'' ``The Sands of Iwo Jima, ``Pork Chop Hill,''
``The Steel Helmet,'' ``A Walk in the Sun,'' ``Hamburger Hill.``
</P>
<P>
   These movies are not about the adventure of soldiering, but
about the price paid by the people trapped in war.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg has brilliantly posed the questions of why men die to
save other men, of why they follow orders, of how bravery is
attained and how a sense of purpose can emerge from the chaos of
war.
</P>
<P>
   Is ``Saving Private Ryan'' too in tense for kids? Obviously. It
should, however, be required viewing for generals and politicians.
Give them something to think about before they start the next war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is rated R for its graphic violence and
heavy profanity. 5 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
