<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SEX-OFFENDERS-PORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE VOIDS BAN ON PORN FOR JAILED SEX OFFENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A federal judge struck down a law Wednesday that
had banned sexually oriented material for inmates at the state's
prison for chronic sex offenders, saying that the law's sweeping
language was unconstitutional and that the state had failed to
prove that such a ban would help rehabilitate the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Alfred Wolin of U.S. District Court in Newark, had
blocked the state from enforcing the law June 29, warning that he
was likely to rule in favor of two inmates who filed a lawsuit to
overturn the measure. But he refrained from issuing a final ruling
at that time, saying he wanted to give the state attorney general's
office another chance to argue the law's merits.
</P>
<P>
   But state lawyers, who had argued that the ban would help
rehabilitate prisoners, chose not to expand their defense of the
law. In his decision Wednesday, Wolin rebuked state lawmakers for
writing legislation so sloppy that in addition to banning
pornographic literature, photographs and other material, it could
also prohibit inmates ``from reading the Bible, fashion magazines,
books, legal documents and sections of newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolin said he did not believe that state legislators wrote the
law intending to help rehabilitate sex offenders at the prison, the
Adult Diagnostic and Treatment Center in Avenel. He noted that the
state Department of Corrections initially opposed the ban, saying
it would not help rehabilitate prisoners. ``The true reason for the
enactment'' of the law, Wolin wrote, ``appears to be public outrage
over some of the heinous, pedophiliac crimes that occurred in New
Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, state Attorney General Peter Verniero
said his office had decided not to try to persuade Wolin after the
earlier decision, but would appeal the latest ruling. ``We made a
strategic decision to move on in an expedited fashion to the Court
of Appeals,'' Verniero said. ``In light of the judge's strongly
worded earlier decision, I did not believe it was in anyone's best
interest, not least of which the taxpayers', to prolong the
District Court's proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolin's decision made it clear that he found himself in the
unenviable position of having to rule in favor of convicted sex
offenders abhorred by society. ``The court reiterates that it is
sensitive to society's concern and interest in defending against
and punishing sex offenders,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said later in his decision, ``This court has a sworn
duty to uphold the Constitution against all competing interests.''
He concluded: ``Here, the fault lies not with the prisoners who
seek freedom of expression, but with an ill-considered and
ill-conceived law that deprives them of that freedom. A law born in
haste merits an equally speedy demise.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which Gov. Christie Whitman signed in January, was
passed unanimously by both houses of the Legislature. The bill grew
out of a visit to the Avenel prison in 1995 by a state task force
studying repeat offense rates among child molesters and the
effectiveness of treatment programs at Avenel. During a tour, some
task force members said, they were stunned to see pictures of naked
women and copies of sexually explicit magazines in some cells.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of Avenel's 750 inmates have committed sex offenses
at least twice and have been classified by judges as ``repetitive
and compulsive'' offenders.
</P>
<P>
   In defending the ban, the state argued that sexually explicit
materials hinder rehabilitation. But counselors and other experts
who work with sex offenders are divided on the issue. In some
cases, experts say, sexually explicit material may help child
molesters redirect their sexual feelings toward adults.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit to overturn the ban was brought by Richard Waterman,
41, who is serving a 54-year prison term for sexually assaulting a
9-year-old girl in Ventnor in 1991, and by Michael Curtis, 56, who
is serving a 20-year sentence after his 1990 conviction for
sexually abusing a 14-year-old boy in Hopewell Township.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lustberg, a court-appointed lawyer who represented the
inmates, applauded the judge. ``Judge Wolin followed the law and
his decision is a courageous one,'' Lustberg said. ``Obviously, he
is well aware of how unpopular it was.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
