A8568 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-23 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slow to embrace &QL; 
home-run pace
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THERE they are, Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr., large-as-life
caricatures grinning away at us from the cover of Time, like they
were major international figures instead of mere major-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Space on the front of Time normally belongs to the Saddam
Husseins and the Monica Lewinskys of the world, not ballplayers.
Guess time _ and Time _ hasn't passed America's Pastime by after
all in this, another hot summer of ongoing absolution for the Great
Strike of '94-95.
</P>
<P>
   But personally, I'm troubled by their bloated assaults on the
home-run records of Babe Ruth and Roger Maris. It's bad enough that
Cal Ripken, Baltimore's Energizer Bunny, has devalued Lou Gehrig
into Tin Man status. Should both Big Mac and Junior now blow away
the tater barrier, too, especially if it happens simultaneously,
it's going to cheapen things further.
</P>
<P>
   And serve to remind us, as if we need it, how truly godawful the
pitching profession has become.
</P>
<P>
   Break record; don't shatter it
</P>
<P>
   Man was not meant to hit 70 homers in a single season, any more
than he's supposed to hit .500. Such outrageous numbers in said
categories can only damage ball, not enhance it over the long haul.
Gross variances from the norm only raise suspicion, rather than
alter accepted standards.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Bob Beamon? Rosie Ruiz? The Chinese swimmers?
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to see McGwire and/or Griffey _ no one else, though; it
gets too cluttered _ enter the final week with 59 or 60 and then
ultimately raise the bar but a hair, to 62 or 63. To obliterate
Maris' name from the record books would be to replace the asterisk
he carried to his grave with an even more glaring one.
</P>
<P>
   The truly dramatic scenario would be to have them reach 59 in,
say, 152 games, thereby painting a bull's eye on the Bambino's
rotund torso. Ruth's 60, smacked in the 154-game season of 1927,
remains the most magical of sports records, single-season variety.
</P>
<P>
   Less sexy but no less intriguing is Juan Gonzalez's testing the
RBI limits. With his five Tuesday night followed by three
Wednesday, the Texas Ranger has 113 in 100 games, on track to drive
home 183 over 162.
</P>
<P>
   Hack Wilson's 190 RBIs in 1930 equate to 200 in the modern
season. Gonzalez would have to push 90 runners across the plate in
his last 63 games to match. No reason to watch him too closely
quite yet, given that no player has surpassed 160 in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the .400 barrier, with Tony Gwynn's time apparently over,
that's not going to fall in our lifetime, either, having already
stood inviolate for 57 seasons. Night ball, pitching by committee
and a general lack of iron-willed, steely-eyed discipline on the
part of the modern hitter have conspired to make it the safest of
all batting thresholds.
</P>
<P>
   Among pitchers, that dying breed, there are virtually no records
made to be broken. Of those in 17 key single-season categories,
subtracting the strictly contemporary subgroup related to relief
pitching, only Orel Hershiser's 59 consecutive scoreless innings
and Nolan Ryan's 383 strikeouts have been posted since 1938. In the
career categories, it's pretty much the same story. I mean, Cy
Young won 511 games while pitching 300 or more innings 16 times,
something no pitcher may do again. When Don Sutton, with his 324
victories, entered the Hall of Fame, he went so far as to pronounce
himself the end of a species.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt very seriously,'' Sutton mused, ``that there will be
another 300-game winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux on target
</P>
<P>
   Had he forgotten Greg Maddux, whose quiet pursuit of immortality
is infinitely more subtle, but no less enthralling, than the
crash-bam McGwire-Griffey show? Maddux is Truffaut to their
Tarantino.
</P>
<P>
   A young 32 and 13-4 at present, he has 197 W's and never has
been on the disabled list. At the same age, Sutton, Nolan Ryan and
Phil Niekro were well behind Maddux's pace, a pace that has seen
him average 17.5 wins per season over the last decade, a towering
achievement for the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Another six seasons, assuming he keeps rolling this summer, and
he's there. Time _ if not Time, which makes references to his
``doughy'' body and ``nerdy'' glasses _ is strongly on his side,
Sutton's harrumphing notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   It's less of an ally for Roger Clemens, who got his 225th
victory Wednesday night. Rocket Roger is 34 with more wear and tear
on his arm, but you figure he'll be afforded the opportunity to
work for as long as he desires to propel a baseball toward home
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't Danny Darwin, Grandpa Death, go against the Astros last
weekend? Such is the dearth of alternatives. While the nation
shouts ``bully!'' for Mac and Junior, I believe temperance is in
order. In truth, they're bullies, exploiting a bad situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
