u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MURDER-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      07-23 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDER-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER ASKS JURY TO SPARE LIFE OF CONVICTED KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ The lawyer for Dalkeith McIntosh, a
convicted double murderer, pleaded Wednesday with jurors to save
his client's life.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, William Tendy, spent nearly an hour asking jury
members to consider the life of a man whose experiences could not
be further from their own. He graphically reiterated courtroom
testimony about the savage beatings McIntosh, 38, had endured as a
child in Jamaica, becoming so emotional at times that his voice
nearly broke.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the same jury convicted McIntosh of killing his
wife and stepdaughter by shooting them in the head on Aug. 12,
1996. Because the jurors' verdict also said that McIntosh committed
the second murder to eliminate his stepdaughter as a witness _ both
to her mother's killing and to the attempted murder of a 6-year-old
boy during the same incident _ they made him eligible for death by
lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors must be unanimous in their decision to impose the
death penalty or chose a sentence of life in prison without the
possibility of parole. If they are unable to agree on either
punishment, Judge George Marlow of Dutchess County Court will
impose a sentence of life in prison and make McIntosh eligible for
parole after he has served at least 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Edward Whitesell, spoke for about 25 minutes,
arguing for death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single time he pulled the trigger, he made a choice,''
Whitesell said. ``Every single time, that choice was to put him
where he is today.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh ``made the death penalty the most fitting and
appropriate sentence in this case,'' the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   Tendy, however, said death was inappropriate for McIntosh, an
indigent Jamaican immigrant of borderline intelligence, who had
endured a brutal childhood and a life of deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is not Ted Bundy or Timothy McVeigh,'' said Tendy,
referring to a serial killer and the Oklahoma City bomber.
``There's got to be some compassion, somewhere deep down in your
hearts. There's got to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitesell did not dispute that McIntosh had led a life of
desperate hardship. He later admitted to feeling drained as the
trial neared a close.
</P>
<P>
   Tendy, who was visibly saddened when the guilty verdict was
announced on July 8, strove Wednesday to find arguments that might
persuade the jury to show mercy. He reminded them of the example of
Jesus, ``perhaps the most famous victim of capital punishment,''
and added: ``If He were alive today, would He be standing here
asking for this man's death? Of course not. He'd be saying,
`Blessed are the merciful.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tendy's final exhortation asked jurors to consider how they
would someday explain the case to their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them how tragic this was,'' he said. ``Tell them about
life in prison. Tell them about the death penalty. Tell them about
the power that you had. And when they look up and ask, `What did
you do?' Tell them, as proudly as you can, `I chose life.'''
</P>
<P>
   After an hour and a half of closing arguments and another hour
of instructions from Marlow, the jurors began to consider
McIntosh's sentence about 1:20 p.m. They retired for the evening at
about 6 without reaching a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations are expected to continue on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
