A8571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-CVS-CLASSIC-835&AMP;A     07-23 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CVS-CLASSIC-835&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENERABLE TOURNAMENT TAKING ITS LAST SWINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its 31-year-old history, there has never been a repeat winner
of the PGA Tour event at the Pleasant Valley Country Club in
Sutton, Mass. And unless one of the 14 former winners in the field
prevails at this year's tournament, which starts Thursday, there
never will be a two-time winner. The only PGA Tour stopover in
Massachusetts is going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   And with the launching next year of three ``World Golf
Championships,'' and another in 2000, each with $5 million in prize
money, the demise of the CVS Charity Classic in central
Massachusetts may turn out to be a harbinger for some other PGA
Tour events, particularly those in smaller markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other tournaments are definitely going to be squeezed out,''
said Ted Mingolla, the owner of Pleasant Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Finchem, he said referring to the PGA tour commissioner,
``told us that they had to strengthen their markets and go to more
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been running this tournament for more than 30 years and
drawing very good crowds, too _ up to 150,000 over the four days.
But there's no loyalty shown by the PGA, no matter how long you've
been running a tournament. I've talked to about half the players in
our field and most of them are livid over what's happened to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Begun by Mingolla's father, Cuz, in 1965, the tournament has had
12 names and eight major sponsors along the way, but much of the
time, Mingolla said, ``we put up our own money.''
</P>
<P>
   CVS, the drugstore chain based in Woonsocket, R.I., became the
first title sponsor in 1996 but the company decided to pull out
upon learning that, starting in 1999, the tournament would be held
the week before the British Open for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``CVS said no to that and asked for a fall date,'' Mingolla
said. ``But the only alternative they offered was the week in
August opposite the NEC World Series of Golf. Again, CVS said no,
since they knew we'd lose 30 or 40 of the top players.''
</P>
<P>
   In its determination to keep the tournament in Pleasant Valley,
Mingolla said, CVS offered to invest $3 million and to buy network
television time if the event were played in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they said no fall dates were available,'' Mingolla said of
the PGA's response, ``although it appears that some will be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After CVS pulled out, we were told that we'd have a month to
try to get another sponsor,'' said Mingolla. ``The PGA Tour said
they'd help us find a sponsor, but so far as I know they never did.
And then, in March, before the month was up, they called and said,
`Time's up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ric Clarson, vice president of tournament business affairs for
the PGA Tour, said that tour officials tried, to no avail, to get a
sponsor for the Pleasant Valley tournament. Clarson conceded,
though, that the tour was seeking more big-market sites. ``We'd
like to have tournaments in Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, St. Louis and
Seattle, among other places,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some limitations that events will encounter based on
their markets,'' Clarson said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the $5 million tournaments _ the Andersen Consulting
Match Play Championship next February in Carlsbad, Calif. the NEC
Invitational next August, the American Express Championship, to be
held for the first time next November in Spain, and the World Team
Championships in 2000 _ are easier to sell than events like the one
in Sutton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The CVS Classic has certainly found that out the hard way.
Largely because it is being held the week after the British Open,
the tournament has drawn only three of the top-25 money winners _
Jim Furyk, Scott Hoch and John Cook, who won the event in 1996.
Mingolla, a former president of the association that represents
tournament directors in the United States, predicted that it will
get even worse for small-market tournaments in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the four World Golf Championship tournaments offering $5
million purses and $720,000 to the winners, I think you'll see the
top players playing a lot less,'' said Mingolla. ``And the ones
that will suffer will be the small-market tournaments. People are
going to be asking `Where's Tiger?' but they're not going to be
seeing him at a lot of the older tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Clarson disagreed. ``I think that actually a lot of players will
play more tournaments,'' he said, ``They'll have to keep playing if
they're interested in their world rankings and if they want to stay
eligible for the World Golf Championship tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, as prize money has risen, it has not caused a
decrease in the number of tournaments players play in,'' Clarson
added, pointing out that under the tour's new incentive plan, the
amount of money that goes into a player's pension plan will depend
on the number of events he plays.
</P>
<P>
   Countered Mingola: ``Eventually, some title sponsors are going
to realize that putting money into a small-market tournament is not
a good investment. And I think you'll see them looking at the
NASCAR circuit and other sports vehicles rather than golf.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the advent of the four big-bucks championships _ and the
PGA Tour's interest in expanding into more major markets _ other
longstanding tournaments may be in jeopardy. They could include the
Tucson Open, which will have to compete against the first World
Golf Championship event, the Andersen Match Play open to the top 64
ranked players; the Greater Milwaukee Open, which will be shifted
to the CVS Classic's dates next summer, and the Deposit Guaranty
Golf Classic in Madison, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Another event that could be endangered is the B.C. Open in
Endicott, N.Y., near Binghamton, which has been a tour fixture
since 1973. It is the only PGA tournament without a title sponsor.
Alex Anderson, the 76-year-old haberdasher-turned-tournament
director, spent $1.8 million to upgrade the town-owned En-Joie Golf
Club and he has committed to at least another four years even
though the B.C. Open has been given dates opposite the British Open
from 2000 through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no choice,'' said Alexander, who claims that he has
more than 500 ``sponsors,'' ranging from Binghamton area
businessmen who put up as little as $300 a year to corporations
from around the country that contribute a ``high'' of $45,000. ``I
feel that it was cut and dried and I'm in no position to negotiate
for good dates. There's no sense in our getting hard-nosed about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tournament is strictly a community effort,'' Alexander
said. ``We need 1,300 volunteers every year, and we have, and we've
raised about $4 million, most of which has gone to hospitals in
Binghamton and Johnson City. We only draw about 70,000 people, but
we feel we've been good for the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   And why hasn't Alexander been able to get a title sponsor all
these years? ``It's because I'm a lousy salesman,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
