<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-C-USA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW MARCHING ORDERS
</P>
<P>
   Army expects tough tour of duty after enlisting in C-USA
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ The ``brave old Army team'' won't be less brave by
any measure as the Cadets compete in a conference for the first
time in the 109 years of West Point's football program.
</P>
<P>
   As the eighth member of Conference USA, Army is forecast to
finish last in the C-USA race, a reasonable forecast, says athletic
director Al Vanderbush, after the team's inconsistent 4-7 record of
a year ago. Half of those four wins were over Division I-AA
Lafayette and Colgate, and the record included losses of 41-0 to
C-USA's Tulane and 39-7 to archrival Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we are picked last, being in a conference gives us
the chance and the expectation to compete for a championship,''
said Vanderbush at the C-USA preseason media day Wednesday. ``It
was important that Army join a conference, and Conference USA fits
our needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not localized, it helps our recruiting and our image,
and it places us in locales where our alumni and members of the
Army can see us play.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Cadets sold 9,000 tickets to the 1996
Independence Bowl after a 10-1 regular season, losing a 32-29
shootout with Auburn. Vanderbush expects a similar turnout from
Texas military bases in Killeen, San Antonio and elsewhere when
Army plays at Houston on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Army coach Bob Sutton began recruiting in Texas for eight years
as an assistant when he was named defensive coordinator on former
coach Jim Young's staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that that state reflected a lot of the same values we
have at West Point,'' he said. ``It's a patriotic state that
certainly prides itself on the intensity of its high school
football, and the things its schools try to teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The type of young men we want exists in that state. The idea
of serving your country is important there, and young people are
taught discipline and commitment that are needed when you attend
West Point.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Vanderbush: ``Whoever comes to West Point has to have good
academics, a motivation to serve, a sense of pride and commitment.
Texas produces those kinds of individuals and great high school
football programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton used to recruit the entire state by himself. Now, he has
two coaches who try to cover Texas: offensive coordinator Ed
Warriner in the Houston-San Antonio-Austin areas and defensive
coordinator Denny Doornbos in Dallas and West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   With 26 Texans on the preseason roster, Sutton expects the
number to increase to about 40 when incoming freshmen report Aug.
9.
</P>
<P>
   The preseason starting lineup includes center Michael Guzman of
Eisenhower, right guard George McIngvale of Memorial, tight end
Shaun Castillo of Willis, quarterback Johnny Goff of Willowridge
and defensive tackle Joe Stanyer of Southlake.
</P>
<P>
   To start a day that begins at 6 a.m. and includes breakfast
formation at 6:25, then can often last to midnight requires a large
measure of the qualities cited by Sutton and Vanderbush.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a junior and senior, you can manage your time,'' said
offensive tackle Neil Ravitz, a preseason all-conference selection.
``But it can still be hard for some guys. Some guys can just sink
into it naturally after a certain time, but at times you do get
jealous of the flexibility of students at other schools with their
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The normal West Point football player has a pre-practice meeting
at 3:20 p.m. for 30 to 45 minutes, two hours on the field, dinner,
study hall at 7:30 p.m., in his room by 11:30 p.m. and lights out
at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Ravitz, who will graduate as a second lieutenant with a
five-year commitment to the Army, believes the Cadets' wishbone
offense can keep them in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to prepare for in three or four days coming off
a Saturday game,'' he said. ``If we cut down the turnovers we had
last year, we're going to give the other team just three or four
possessions in a half, and we'll have the ball for 40 minutes out
of 60 and put the pressure on the other team to score when it does
have the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   If defensive back Kenny Dale Rowland gleaned one thing from
games against C-USA members Tulane last year and East Carolina in
1995, it is that the new league member lacks the foot speed of its
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a lot of speed, a lot of SEC-style play,'' Rowland
said. ``That's something that can kill, and we don't have a lot of
team speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rowland hopes Army's tough mental approach can keep it in
conference games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football probably is the best laboratory you can have for
learning discipline, doing your job when you're dead tired and
you're behind on the scoreboard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Ravitz: ``We play a disciplined type of football. You
learn leadership, how to work with other people. It's a great
proving ground.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, on a much more important scale, that may be what
Ravitz, Rowland and other Cadets will face in their future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
