<HEADER>
A8575 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BIG12SCHEDULE-HNS     07-23 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
 12 SCHEDULE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Dating game
<TEXT>
<P>
   Different philosophies bring about scheduling conflict in Big 12
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ R.C. Slocum can finally play summer golf in peace and
perspiration. No one asks about his cream-puff schedule anymore. He
no longer must defend himself from criticism or explain how his
Aggies came to have Sam Houston or some such presumed pushover on
the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are over.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum now can begin defending his sanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play in these golf events,'' he said this week after a round
with A&AMP;M supporters in San Antonio, ``and they still talk about the
schedule. Now, they ask, `Are you crazy?'
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people question the Florida State thing (the Aug. 31
Pigskin Classic in East Rutherford, N.J.) that I volunteered for.
``If I was a first-year coach, I might try to cover my rear and not
play that game. But long range, this is a great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, Kan., only those who doubt Bill Snyder walks on
water are questioned. But as Kansas State continues to play teams
that are as lacking as Kansas State once was, it might not be
blasphemous to ask, ``Are you kidding?''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder isn't, and he's not apologizing.
</P>
<P>
   But some Big 12 coaches and athletic directors say Kansas
State's way is everything from unfair financially and competitively
to unsporting _ like hunting rabbits with a bazooka.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's bad for college football,'' Colorado coach Rick
Neuheisel said. ``It doesn't give the college football fan the kind
of game the college fan deserves. I think we're providing a
disservice to the fans, playing games that don't have any doubt
about the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, which statistically has had the toughest schedule in
the nation this decade, has played some of its most memorable games
against Michigan and played both national champions (Michigan and
Nebraska) last season. Its neutral-site game with Colorado State in
Denver will be its toughest non-conference test.
</P>
<P>
   Texas takes another shot at UCLA, whose 66-3 pounding of the
Longhorns in a non-conference game last season was the beginning of
the end of John Mackovic's tenure as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Although both have lightened their load, Baylor and Texas Tech
have routinely toured the Top 10 before beginning conference play.
Baylor played Miami and Michigan last season. Tech, which has
played Penn State, Ohio State, Florida State, Miami, Georgia and
Nebraska in Spike Dykes' 11 seasons as coach, opened at Tennessee
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri again faces Ohio State. Nebraska gets a return visit
from Washington. Iowa State annually faces Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, have begun emulating Kansas State. North Texas
plays almost as many teams from the Big 12 (four) as from the Big
West (five). The Big 12 sought to sponsor legislation that would
allow games against Division I-AA schools to count toward the six
victories needed to qualify for bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a difficult schedule can be costly. Because affiliated
bowls choose teams, rather than have them assigned by the
conference, a Big 12 team with a tougher schedule can hurt itself
when competing against a team with a softer schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M and Kansas State could have the same conference
record. But if Kansas State has a better overall record, it could
have a huge edge in landing a bowl spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, Colorado and Kansas State had that happen,''
Neuheisel said. ``We went 9-2, and they went 9-2, and we beat them
in the head-to-head game. Our losses were to Nebraska and Michigan.
Theirs were to Nebraska and Colorado. And they go to the New Year's
game (the Cotton Bowl) against BYU, and we go to the Holiday Bowl.
Their record was totally inflated.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have argued that several schools are contributing more
greatly to the Big 12's television efforts and are at greater risk.
If Texas is willing to play UCLA or Nebraska against Washington,
the value of a contract with ABC ($17.5 million each year through
2003) presumably increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me the most is the television thing,''
Texas athletic director DeLoss Dodds said. ``The network and the
cable people buy and pay for our schedules. Those carrying the load
in scheduling pay for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Big 12 school is guaranteed at least $750,000 in TV
revenue, and the league works to have each receive an extra
$142,000 from ABC and $72,500 from Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage attractive non-conference games, the league
provides an extra appearance fee for such games chosen by ABC. So
Texas' 66-3 loss to UCLA was worth an additional $284,000 to the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't cover a chance of getting beat,'' Dodds said.
``We would have been much better off not playing UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodds said he has brought up the idea of either forcing Big 12
schools to schedule more competitive non-conference games or at
least more effectively encouraging them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a popular idea,'' he said. ``Those are usually very
short discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M athletic director Wally Groff described the ideal A&AMP;M
schedule as ``one marquee game, one name game and one bought
game.'' That goal was delayed by LSU buying out a contract that
would have provided four more games against the Aggies and the
creation of the Big 12, which cost one non-conference game with
Colorado and two with Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   That also can describe Texas' philosophy: the ``bought game''
against an opponent that will agree to play on the road without a
return visit, or to travel twice for one return visit. Those
opponents, almost always games presumed to be mismatches, require
guarantees from $275,000 to $400,000 for the visiting team, but
they help the largest schools schedule at least six home games.
</P>
<P>
   Texas will pay New Mexico State this season but will not return
the visit. Rice agreed to play twice in Austin for one trip to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State built its revival on such games. Relatively few
marquee teams were willing to return visits to Manhattan, Kan.,
citing the small stadium (42,000), difficult travel and a tough foe
that, at the time, did not have enough of a national reputation to
make the risk worth the reward.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Kansas State chooses to schedule as it does
_ and to take the criticism _ because for Kansas State, it has
worked.
</P>
<P>
   Many, including Slocum, argue that a more challenging schedule
prepares teams for tougher games to come. Kansas State has not
beaten Nebraska in 30 years and with an otherwise unbeaten team
lost to Nebraska 56-26 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason I'm doing it,'' Slocum said. ``I think it
can make us better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best season we had was in 1992. We played an early-season
game when we went to California in Bill Walsh's first year back,
the year Stanford won the Pac-10. We won that game and won 12
straight games.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Neuheisel, argue that playing top teams takes
``too great a toll'' to be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what has worked for us, I would not see us changing
our scheduling philosophy in the near future,'' Kansas State
athletic director Max Urick said. ``Playing home games and playing
the caliber of teams we play has been successful for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``What works in Manhattan might not in Ann Arbor or Los Angeles
or Columbus. We know what works at Kansas State. We'll not vary
from it. It would be a mistake to let someone influence us (as to
what our priorities) should be.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, such influence will not come from the Big 12. Few seem
to mind. Fewer want to invite the league into the scheduling
business.
</P>
<P>
   And most, no matter how different they might be in philosophies,
believe they are doing it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say they have an advantage playing weak teams,''
Groff said. ``And you might say it's unfair that someone has an
easier schedule. But it could be unfair to them, too. We could play
the tougher games and get the benefits of winning them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
