<HEADER>
A8576 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-POLICY-HNS &LR;      07-23 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-POLICY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Policy's 
time up 
as Niner
<TEXT>
<P>
   Team president &QL; 
quits amid turmoil
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like a good marriage that turns bad and ends in a bitter
divorce, the longtime friendship and business relationship between
San Francisco 49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo Jr. and team president
Carmen Policy is over.
</P>
<P>
   Policy, who is regarded as one of the best front-office
executives in NFL history, resigned Wednesday and is expected to
join Al Lerner and Bernie Kosar in their bid to become the owners
of the new Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Around the NFL, Policy's resignation was no surprise. He and
DeBartolo, friends for three decades who used to be as close as
brothers, had not spoken since January. Friends and 49ers
executives had tried to intervene in their dispute, but none was
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (his relationship with DeBartolo) in a deep freeze, and
it hasn't been defrosted during the past whatever number of
months,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   When DeBartolo removed himself from day-to-day operation of the
team until his legal troubles were cleared up in Louisiana, he
turned over control to his sister, Denise DeBartolo York, who helps
run the family empire in Youngstown, Ohio. Each owns 45 percent of
the 49ers, who have won five Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo thought Policy used his absence to go behind his back
to try to gain control of the franchise that would ultimately make
Policy a part-owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepping aside is very difficult,'' said Policy, who joined
the organization as legal counsel in 1983 and was promoted to
president eight years ago. ``It's awkward, but it's not impossible.
I'm looking forward to the opportunities ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Policy, who is a mover and shaker when it comes to back-room NFL
politics, would not discuss his plans at his Wednesday news
conference, but sources in Cleveland and San Francisco said he will
join Lerner and Kosar, who head one of at least six groups trying
to be the owners of the new Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some excellent opportunities that are available to
me individually, to me as part of a group, that are very
exciting,'' Policy said. ``I see these opportunities as being
golden, but I see these opportunities as fleeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting Policy is a brilliant and shrewd move by Lerner, who was
Art Modell's partner with the old Browns, who moved to Baltimore.
Kosar, who played quarterback for the Browns, may be the most
popular player in Cleveland's illustrious football history. Adding
Policy, who is highly respected in the NFL, might give them the
inside track over the Dolan brothers, who have Don Shula heading
their effort and Bill Cosby as an investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the job I've done,'' Policy said about his
15 years with the 49ers. ``I feel great about the way I've done it.
I feel reasonably comfortable about the results.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers won four of their five Super Bowls with Policy playing
a crucial role in the front office. He is being replaced on an
interim basis by Larry Thrailkill, chief operating officer of the
Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. in Youngstown. Thrailkill will represent
the 49ers in league matters.
</P>
<P>
   There had been reports that former 49ers coach Bill Walsh, a
favorite of DeBartolo's, would return to run the organization, but
he was nowhere to be seen Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   49ers vice presidents Dwight Clark, who runs the personnel side
of the organization, and Bill Duffy will run the team. They will
report to Thrailkill.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever replaces Policy will have a difficult time being as
successful. Despite losing key players and changing coaches through
the years, the 49ers remained one of the better teams in the
league. They were always a Super Bowl contender. Players on other
teams wanted to play for them. Policy played a huge role in that
success.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, who has kept a low profile over the last months but
is ready to resume control of the team, issued a statement about
Policy's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen leaves our organization with my best personal wishes,''
DeBartolo said. ``He has been an integral part of the 49ers'
success since we named him president in 1991.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the well-publicized division between DeBartolo and
Policy, Wednesday's announcement didn't catch the 49ers by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made transitions in the past pretty seamlessly, and
there's no reason to think we can't do it again,'' quarterback
Steve Young said at training camp. ``There's history for what we're
talking about. Today's a little bit chaotic, but I really think
there will be long-term stability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
