<HEADER>
A8577 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-100-COMMENT-KAN     07-23 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-100-COMMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD AUTHORS SOCIETY: LITTLE ROOM FOR THE LIVING ON TOP 100 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the 20th century speeds to a close, the urge to rank its
achievements is reaching critical mass. The same impulse that
brought us America's ``100 greatest films'' now proclaims the
world's 100 finest English-language novels.
</P>
<P>
   But as might be expected, the list released last week by the
editorial board of the Modern Library has its shortcomings and
peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
   For one, it includes only nine books by women. The work of
so-called minorities, and of writers who aren't American or
British, has been similarly neglected.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing by Margaret Atwood (a Canadian) or Patrick White
(an Australian), who both have international stature. And nothing
by Michael Ondaatje (The English Patient) or Haruki Murakami (A
Wild Sheep Chase), literary nomads who have distinguished
themselves in English.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did any of the novels of two living Nobel laureates _ Toni
Morrison and Nadine Gordimer _ make it onto the list. Most of the
books selected are by authors who are dead _ and long dead at that.
</P>
<P>
   Writers whose names appear twice or more include Joseph Conrad,
William Faulkner, F. Scott Fitzgerald, E.M. Forster, Ernest
Hemingway and D.H. Lawrence. James Joyce occupies both the first
slot (with Ulysses) and the third (A Portrait of the Artist as a
Young Man).
</P>
<P>
   Without question, many of the books cited have merit. But
because few of the selections were published in the latter part of
the century, the list conforms to the sort of xenophobic,
male-dominated, ``great books'' ethic that efforts toward
multiculturalism have sought to alleviate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's loaded with men,'' said Carolyn Doty, a novelist who is a
professor of English at the University of Kansas. ``There's no
Flannery O'Connor. No Eudora Welty.''
</P>
<P>
   James McKinley, editor of the New Letters literary journal based
at the University of Missouri-Kansas City, agreed that much was
missing from the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real short on gifted female and minority writers, and it
seems to be seriously skewed toward the canon,'' McKinley said. ``I
don't know what D.H. Lawrence is doing on there three times.''
</P>
<P>
   A cynic might wonder whether the placement of Lawrence's novel
Sons and Lovers at No. 9 on the list is due more to its
unquestionable literary attributes or to its being published by the
Modern Library.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has been publishing works of English
literature at popular prices since 1917, is a division of Random
House, the huge New York book empire. Of course, it stands to
profit financially from any attention the list generates.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 100 novels selected for the list, 59 are currently
published by the Modern Library or other units of the Bertelsmann
group, the big German book octopus, which recently acquired Random
House. And Modern Library has plans to reissue soon at least 10
other titles on the list.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the scholars, authors and historians who make up
the Modern Library's editorial board _ they include such literary
stars as Britain's A.S. Byatt and Americans Daniel J. Boorstin,
Shelby Foote and Gore Vidal _ are published by Random House or
other Bertelsmann imprints.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Modern Library's emphasis on marketplace-friendly
classics, many of the choices are not surprising. Conspicuous by
their omission are the works of such relatively difficult novelists
as John Barth, Don DeLillo and Thomas Pynchon.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for those seeking the literary edge, the list offers
little more than Kurt Vonnegut's Slaughterhouse Five (No. 18) and
E.L. Doctorow's Ragtime (No. 86). Vonnegut's World War II novel was
certainly unconventional and challenging for its time (the 1960s),
but, like most of Doctorow's fiction, it now hugs the mainstream
shore.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library board apparently applied the ``test-of-time''
standard to such relatively recent work _ including the books by
the few women and minorities included on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this method of discerning the worth of a work
is that until recently writers who were not male or white had a
hard time getting published period _ at least in the mainstream.
And the list reflects precisely this sort of cultural bias.
</P>
<P>
   The highest ranking works by women are Virginia Woolf's To the
Lighthouse (No. 15) and Carson McCullers' The Heart Is a Lonely
Hunter (No. 17). Edith Wharton is recognized twice, for The Age of
Innocence (No. 58) and The House of Mirth (No. 69). Also cited are
works by Elizabeth Bowen, Willa Cather, Iris Murdoch, Jean Rhys and
Muriel Spark.
</P>
<P>
   African-American authors are represented, perhaps predictably,
by Ralph Ellison's Invisible Man (No. 19), Richard Wright's Native
Son (No. 20) and James Baldwin's Go Tell It on the Mountain (No.
39).
</P>
<P>
   Women and minorities fared better on a list compiled last week
by 100 students in a summer publishing course at Radcliffe College.
</P>
<P>
   Also devoted to identifying the century's 100 finest
English-language novels, it made room for the work of such
prominent female African-American writers as Morrison (whose
Beloved placed at No. 7), Alice Walker and Zora Neale Hurston.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the works most likely to be included in the Modern
Library's list were those most compatible with the established
Anglo-American canon.
</P>
<P>
   This helps to explain why novelists hailing from India,
Australia, South Africa, Canada and the Third World largely failed
to find a place on the list. Notable exceptions include V.S.
Naipaul (who was born in Trinidad) and Salman Rushdie (who was born
in India).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a narrow-minded list,'' said G.S. Sharat Chandra, a poet
and fiction writer who is also a professor of English at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although they may have a couple of names like Rushdie and
Naipaul, that does not necessarily mean that there are not other
writers in other countries, and who also write in English, who have
written books that are worthy of being mentioned.''
</P>
<P>
   The biases of the list notwithstanding, a case could be made
that its very existence is a balm to people who fear that the
health of the literary tradition may be threatened by competition
from television and the Internet, and by the concomitant decline of
reading as a leisure activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to understand that this list is only a
benchmark for literary excellence,'' said Therese Eiben, editor of
the New York-based Poets &AMP; Writers magazine. ``It's a celebration
of writing and reading, and I think it lifts all boats _ as long as
it's not taken as definitive.''
</P>
<P>
   That the list may be perceived as even close to definitive is
the danger. The beginning of a new millennium should be a time for
new thinking _ not an opportunity to reinforce entrenched ideas
about what constitutes culture.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult for a writer to stand the test of time if his or
her work has only recently begun to be taken seriously _ much less
embraced as art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
