<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FLIGHT-103-NYT &LR;      07-23 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FLIGHT-103-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUSTICE AND PAN AM FLIGHT 103 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 23:
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly 10 years since terrorists bombed Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people. Early on,
American investigators concluded that two Libyan intelligence
agents had planted the bomb. But despite the pressure of
international economic sanctions, Libya has refused to turn over
the suspects to either Britain or the United States, preventing the
case from coming to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Now President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain
have sensibly decided to explore the idea of holding the trial in
the Netherlands, under Scottish law and presided over by Scottish
judges. Libya proposed essentially the same plan in 1994, and has
repeated the offer since then. The ideal location for a trial is
still Britain or the United States. But justice can be served by
holding a Scottish trial in the Netherlands, if the details of
doing so can be acceptably worked out.
</P>
<P>
   These include establishing the legal basis for such an unusual
proceeding, securing the two Libyans' extradition to the custody of
the trial court and agreeing on the conditions required for lifting
sanctions. At a minimum, the suspects should be in custody and
Libya's cooperation in the trial proceedings assured before
sanctions are suspended.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that Libya was never serious about its offer to
turn the suspects over to a third country. The testimony at a trial
could point uncomfortably close to Col. Moammar Gadhafi and other
Libyan leaders. But the sanctions have hurt Libya's oil industry,
and Gadhafi may be willing to endure the embarrassment of a trial
to get them lifted. Beyond that, Libya has invested considerable
diplomatic capital in getting the Organization of African Unity,
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa and the Arab League to
line up behind the Libyan proposal, and it would face renewed
isolation if it now tried to reverse course.
</P>
<P>
   Erosion of sanctions may well have pushed Washington and London
into embracing a compromise they previously rejected. They should
have explored the idea of relocating the trial long ago. One reason
they did not is opposition from the families of some of the
victims, who bristle at any appearance of a diplomatic concession
to Libya. But the issue here is not scoring diplomatic points. It
is accountability under credible and impartial law. The airliner
bombing was a terrible crime. Justice, long delayed, should have
its day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0010EDT &QL; 
