A8580 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DISTURBING-REVI     07-23 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DISTURBING-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK OF `DISTURBING' AS `THE STEPFORD TEENS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Disturbing Behavior,'' a thriller, is rated R for strong
violence, sexuality, language and drug content. Running time is 1
hour 23 minutes. Two out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Think of ``Disturbing Behavior'' as ``The Stepford Teens.'' It's
a mildly diverting tale of one burg's answer to lazy, antisocial,
underachieving adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer to the picturesque island community of Cradle Bay in
the Pacific Northwest, Steve Clark (James Marsden) is immediately
befriended by Gavin (Nick Stahl), the class doper and poster boy
for teen alienation. With a cynical flourish Gavin describes to the
newcomer the various cliques operating at the local high school.
</P>
<P>
   There are the greasers who live for beer and auto mechanics
class, the techno nerds with their bottle-bottom glasses and
laptops, and the skateboard slackers.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all are the Blue Ribbons, a bunch of squeaky-clean
preppies in blue jackets (they look like the FFA convention, only
with penny loafers instead of cowboy boots). The Blue Ribbons are
beloved by faculty and parents because they behave exactly as
adults would have kids behave. And, believing themselves to be
intellectually, physically and morally superior to their peers,
they sometimes behave like an army of fascist zombies.
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't seem to bother their mentor and school
psychologist, Dr. Caldicott (Bruce Greenwood). In fact, the Doc has
a waiting list of parents who want their sullen, uncooperative
teens to join the Blue Ribbons. With the help of drugs, implants
and lots of electricity, Caldicott can turn a malcontent into a
model citizen overnight.
</P>
<P>
   But Caldicott's brainwashing techniques still have a few bugs.
While their brains have been programmed to abstain from sex, the
bodies of the Blue Ribbons are full of raging hormones. Unable to
reconcile their chaste conditioning with the carnal call of their
loins, the Blue Ribbons regularly flip out in homicidal rages.
</P>
<P>
   First-time director David Nutter and screenwriter Scott
Rosenberg (``Con Air,'' ``Beautiful Girls'') have an insidiously
clever idea here, but they don't push it very far. Who can blame
them? This is a quick-hit commercial vehicle aimed squarely at the
high school audience. No point wasting creativity on a crowd that
isn't going to recognize or appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   The performers are just adequate. Most memorable is Katie Holmes
(of TV's ``Dawson's Creek''), who cements her current status as
rising teen sex goddess with her performance as Steve's romantic
interest, a moody beauty with too much mascara, a ring in her
bellybutton and an attitude of disdainful boredom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
