<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEVISION-FOX-KANSAS     07-23 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-FOX-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AARON BARNHART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 FOX, FIRE and `BRIMSTONE'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Developing an idea into a new TV series is a
process that traditionally takes months of effort and millions of
dollars. And if you're developing it for Fox, it had better conform
to the network's mantra of ``daring, distinctive, clever and
well-crafted.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, the most promising new idea on Fox _ or any
network _ this fall is based on a story we all know from antiquity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brimstone'' is a latter-day retelling of the book of Job, a
man abandoned seemingly by the whole universe, cut off from his
race and set adrift from his maker. It just happens that in this
version, Job wears leather instead of sackcloth and ashes; also, he
seems to be caught up in some kind of creepy vampire movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brimstone'' was easily the highlight of the Fox network's fall
presentation to TV critics, who have gathered here to preview the
forthcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   While Fox entertainment chief Peter Roth delivered his customary
passionate pitch about the Fox shows, embracing each one like a
beloved child, the truth is that not one new fall series has
generated the kind of buzz that accompanies a truly original
effort. That may change once viewers get a look at ``Brimstone.''
</P>
<P>
   The show represents the first foray into TV production by a
young movie-writing team, Cyrus Voris and Ethan Reiff, and stars
Peter Horton (who played Gary, the professor who died on
``thirtysomething'') as Zeke Stone.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 Stone was killed in action while serving as a detective
in New York City. Because of a grievous sin he committed _ killing
the man who raped his wife _ Stone went to hell. But then a
jailbreak of sorts rocked the lower kingdom, and 113 condemned
souls fled to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   There's an order to the universe, even hell, and so the devil is
forced to employ the crafty detective to go back to Earth and
recapture the demons. If he succeeds, Stone is promised some sort
of second chance.
</P>
<P>
   He materializes in New York, near his old precinct. There Stone
begins searching for demons, who have reintegrated themselves among
the living. He also searches for clues into his own humanity, like
Job scraping his sores with broken pottery. A human or two will
befriend him, or try to. And Stone will go looking for his wife,
who has moved to L.A. and has only distant memories of him.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Stone is isolated, morally, physically and
existentially. And yet he is doing God's will. Even stranger, so is
Satan.
</P>
<P>
   Voris and Reiff had originally thought this story would make a
good movie. Then they decided it could also make good episodic TV.
For a year the two struggled to find a premise that would convince
the networks. The result was a cop show.
</P>
<P>
   While the first of the 113 demons Stone pursues is sure to be
controversial _ a mad priest who was executed a century ago for
killing altar boys _ the show's producers look forward to exploring
the banality of evil as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your neighbor could be one of these people,'' explains Michael
Chernuchin, the veteran producer hired by Fox to shepherd
``Brimstone's'' development. ``The one we always joke about is the
guy from DMV being a demon.''
</P>
<P>
   And the role of Satan himself is striking. He and Stone seem not
to have conversations so much as confrontations. Yet who
understands Stone's situation better than he?
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil is still sort of a trickster,'' Voris said. ``Take
the issue of Stone's `second chance.' Is it a second chance at
life? A second chance at heaven? Or something else?''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome is left in the dark, but perhaps ``Brimstone'' will
get 113 episodes to flesh it out.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Roth, however, appears to be looking past ``Brimstone''
and the rest of the fall schedule to midseason, when Fox expects to
unveil three strong animated comedies.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is ``Family Guy,'' created by 24-year-old Seth
MacFarlane. To hype the show, Fox has been showing critics a
7-minute pilot MacFarlane produced in May. That's a strategy very
similar to the one Comedy Central used last year to create advance
buzz for its breakout hit ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The two other shows are ``Futurama,'' from ``Simpsons'' creator
Matt Groening, and ``The PJs,'' featuring the voice of Eddie Murphy
as the superintendent of a big-city housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Fox spent as much time this week pushing these shows _ which
have barely begun to move off the drawing board and into production
_ as it spent promoting the fall schedule. And one fall pilot,
``Hollyweird,'' was withheld because it needed to be reshot
virtually from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   All the networks are currently fiddling with or even overhauling
their new shows. It's part of an elaborate development process that
no longer makes sense to many in Hollywood, not when five out of
six broadcast networks are losing money and cable is able to keep
its development costs to a fraction of what broadcasters pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad system,'' Fox's Roth said Tuesday. ``We have spoken
to all of the studios and we've met with all of the agencies and
declared a new system.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old system, most shows are expected to sink or swim in
the same three-month period in the fall. In the new system,
releases will be spread throughout the year to improve the shows'
survival chances, because individual shows can get more promotional
attention.
</P>
<P>
   In the old system there is a homesteader's rush for talent every
spring at the height of pilot production season. At least one ABC
pilot this year had to be scratched because the producers could not
secure an acceptable lead actor. In the new system, talent that
isn't available in the spring may be available in the fall or
winter. The show's release is timed to the availability of the
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's plan wouldn't necessarily make pilots less expensive or
as numerous, but it could potentially lower the possibility of
failure. And more new releases throughout the year will help stop
the attrition of viewers to cable, as evidenced by improved ratings
Fox had last summer when it aired 40 percent new programming
instead of just repeats.
</P>
<P>
   Such backstage details might make some viewers' eyes glaze over.
But as any TV executive will tell you, the devil _ or is it God? _
is in the details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
