<SLUG> BC-IBM-EXECUTIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM REPLACES CHIEF OF CONSUMER PC BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM replaced the executive in charge of its consumer personal
computer business Wednesday in an effort to turn around a division
that has lagged even as the consumer market has shown steady
growth.
</P>
<P>
   James Firestone, 43, who had headed the unit since August 1995,
will leave to take a similar position at Xerox. In his place, IBM
hired Michael Braun, chief executive of Neuron Data, a software
company. Braun, 48, spent more than 20 years at IBM before being
assigned to run Kaleida Labs, a joint venture by IBM and Apple
Computer to make multimedia software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firestone never got things going,'' said Gary Helmig, an
analyst with Soundview Financial. ``The consumer business had a
good year in 1996, and it has been a drag ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM's share of the consumer PC market fell from 12 percent at
the start of 1997 to 3 percent last October, according to ZD Market
Intelligence. Analysts attributed much of that drop to IBM's
failure to foresee the rise of computers priced under $1,000. It
has since added less costly models, and its retail share has
bounced back to 16 percent. But it still trails Hewlett-Packard,
with 24 percent of the market, and Compaq, with 22 percent, ZD
says.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq and Hewlett-Packard have emphasized selling low-cost
machines to the mass market. IBM, while focusing on higher-margin,
feature-packed machines aimed at demanding, high-end users, has
been wary of competing for market share in the volatile consumer
market. But in a memorandum to employees announcing the appointment
of Braun, David Thomas, head of IBM's overall personal computer
division, said the company's goal was to become the No. 1 seller of
consumer PCs.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined IBM, Firestone was put in charge of an ambitious
effort by the company's chairman, Louis Gerstner Jr., to capitalize
on IBM's brand recognition. In addition to computers, he was to
introduce software, games and online products. Over the years, most
of these consumer initiatives have been scaled back or closed.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining IBM, Firestone ran the home services unit of
Ameritech Corp. Before that, he worked at American Express, with
Gerstner and G. Richard Thoman, who eventually headed IBM's PC
business. Thoman is now the chief operating officer at Xerox, which
has been expanding its consumer marketing with products like small
copiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
