</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King's heirs rebuffed in CBS suit
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice and Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A federal judge Wednesday dismissed a lawsuit filed
by the family of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. against CBS that
sought damages from the TV network for using footage of King's ``I
Have a Dream'' speech in a documentary video.
</P>
<P>
   In a 17-page ruling, Senior U.S. District Court Judge William C.
O'Kelley said the unlimited reproduction and dissemination of the
speech in August 1963 thrust it into the public domain although
King copyrighted it a month later. King's estate accused CBS of
copyright infringement in the suit, filed in November 1996 in U.S.
District Court in Atlanta, and sought unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   The King family referred all questions Wednesday to Joseph Beck,
the Atlanta attorney who handled the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are studying the opinion and likely will appeal,'' Beck
said, declining further comment.
</P>
<P>
   CBS hailed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took on this case to protect the public's right to know,''
CBS News President Andrew Heyward said in a release. ``This
decision means that Dr. King's landmark speech is truly in the
public domain, where it belongs. It is not just CBS News, but the
American public that won today.''
</P>
<P>
   The King estate contends that commercial for-profit ventures
must pay a royalty fee, which is waived for schools, charities and
nonprofit organizations. In 1993, the estate withdrew a lawsuit
against USA Today after the newspaper paid a fee for reprinting the
entire ``I Have a Dream'' speech without permission.
</P>
<P>
   CBS included about 60 percent of King's speech in a ``Twentieth
Century with Mike Wallace'' for-sale video dealing with the civil
rights movement. The network filmed King's speech to 200,000 people
at the Lincoln Memorial, which also was broadcast to a nationwide
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Some media attorneys lauded the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with what the King estate wants is that it goes
too far,'' said Sandra Baron, a First Amendment lawyer in
Washington. ``There is much that is done in public view and for the
public which is part of history. An effort to prevent its use for
historical reference, when it is so clearly of historical value,
was and should be doomed to defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
