<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-SUV-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD ANNOUNCEMENT EXPECTED TO MEAN GOOD NEWS FOR CLAYCOMO PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAYCOMO, Mo. _ Ford Motor Co. expects to make a
long-anticipated announcement today that a new product, most likely
a sport-utility vehicle, will be built at its Claycomo plant.
</P>
<P>
   Jac Nasser, Ford's president of automotive operations, and
Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan have scheduled a 10 a.m. press
conference at the Ford Claycomo assembly plant to discuss ``a
significant plant investment,'' according to the automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and United Auto Workers officials declined to comment
Tuesday on the nature of the investment. However, industry sources
have said for several months that Ford had selected Claycomo to
build a new, compact sport-utility vehicle for the 2001 model year.
</P>
<P>
   The compact vehicle, yet unnamed but known within Ford as
``U204,'' will replace the passenger car line at Claycomo that
builds the Ford Contour and Mercury Mystique. The Contour-Mystique,
which had been hyped as Ford's ``world car,'' has not met sales
expectations in the United States since a multibillion-dollar
launch four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also produces the top-selling F-series pickup at Claycomo.
</P>
<P>
   The Claycomo plant is Ford's biggest in North America, with
about 5,100 workers and a $289.5 million payroll. Although industry
sources said they do not believe a new vehicle will add jobs, the
move seemingly will create a more stable work force at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is expected to heavily retool and renovate the plant, with
reports indicating the cost at $100 million to $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has sought state and local public assistance. The state has
offered Ford income-tax refunds of $2 million for up to five years
if the company chose the Claycomo facility for the new product.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ford last month sought to expand an enterprise zone
at the plant that is jointly administered by Claycomo and Kansas
City. The zone expansion would pave the way for various tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   A retooling could shut down the entire plant, possibly in late
1999. Production on the compact sport vehicle is expected to start
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sources have speculated Ford will team with Mazda in building
the new, four-door compact sport-utility vehicle. It will be
smaller than the Ford Explorer and will compete with vehicles like
the Honda CR-V and the Toyota RAV4.
</P>
<P>
   (begin itals)Automotive News(end itals) recently reported that
Mazda will be responsible for the vehicle's engineering. Mazda will
get an upscale version of the compact vehicle while Ford will build
a low-priced version, according to the trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic passenger car sales have been sluggish in recent years
as more carbuyers have taken to light trucks, minivans and
sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive analysts generally have praised the quality of the
Contour and Mystique, but sales have not reached levels initially
expected when the car was introduced in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has shut down its passenger-car line in Claycomo at various
times the last three years because of slow sales of the
Contour-Mystique. The car line is currently shut down through this
week, but is expected to be back up next week. The F-series
production line, on the other hand, has been on an overtime
schedule the entire decade.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the Contour was priced too closely to Ford's bigger
and more popular Taurus. In addition, analysts said the vehicle is
in one of the most competitive segments in the auto industry, with
Japanese cars dominating sales in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ford sold 151,060 Contours and 41,038 Mystiques, both
double-digit percentage drops from 1996. Ford may move all
production of Contour-Mystiques to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation of a new product at Claycomo excited area Ford
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a great deal,'' said Tom Sight, co-owner of Bob
Sight Ford in Lee's Summit, Mo. ``The fact that they picked this
plant says a lot about the quality of the work force here. It will
keep the Claycomo plant viable for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a manufacturing consulting firm ranked the Claycomo
facility as among the most productive when compared to other
domestic auto plants. According to the Harbour Report, Ford's
Kansas City Assembly Plant placed second among plants producing
compact cars and also was second among factories that build
full-size pickups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
