<HEADER>
A8589 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX_REVENUES-KAN &LR;      07-23 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG ECONOMY GIVE STATES CHANCE TO FATTEN THEIR CASH RESERVES 
</HEADLINE>
 _ REVENUES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Awash in money, state governments across America are
slashing taxes and piling up reserves in economic times that
haven't been this good in almost 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   News of the increasing flow of money into state coffers came
Tuesday at the annual meeting of the National Conference of State
Legislatures being held, fittingly perhaps, in the city where money
is king.
</P>
<P>
   A report released at the convention of more than 6,000 state
legislators and other officials found that 46 states surveyed had
$28.6 billion in their cash reserves, or 9 percent more than they
spent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1980 have states saved 9 percent more than they spent.
And the 1998 figures do not yet include California and three other
states who have yet to report.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri and Kansas are tracking closely with the national
trend, officials of those states said Tuesday, and are among 19
states that cut taxes in the most recent legislative sessions
because of excess revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan and Hawaii _ two states who have seen an economic
downturn in recent months _ warned that the good times won't last
forever.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, most states' pocketbooks are bulging because
taxpayers are making and spending more and more money, said Richard
Finan, an Ohio state senator who is president of the National
Conference of State Legislatures this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is mostly a sales and income tax bonanza,'' Finan said.
State taxes overall have now fallen for four straight years, the
group's report said.
</P>
<P>
   Their spending is driven by low unemployment rates and, to some
degree, the soaring stock market, state officials said during a
session Tuesday on state surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is a psyche thing,'' said Stephen Price,
legislative financial director of the Missouri House Appropriations
Committee. ``They see what is happening in the stock market and if
they have a paper gain or not, they feel good and they feel more
free to spend their money.''
</P>
<P>
   With their coffers full, states generally are choosing to cut
taxes rather than increase spending, Finan said. Public schools and
colleges seem to be the benefactors of most spending increases, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, which by law must refund tax revenue when it exceeds
spending, approved some income tax cuts this year and eliminated
the sales tax on food a year ago. Kansas lawmakers cut property
taxes and some sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have debate already from various factions on where the next
round of cuts will be,'' said Paul West, senior fiscal analyst for
the Kansas Department of Legislative Research. ``There is some
discussion of eliminating property taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a preliminary estimate from the legislatures'
conference, states are cutting $3.8 billion in taxes this year,
including $135 million in Missouri and $225 million in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four Missouri lawmakers registered for the conference,
while Kansas registered 38 lawmakers. In addition, 52 staff members
from both states are attending.
</P>
<P>
   Some states are coming up with unconventional and short-term tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Florida and New York, for instance, will grant some weeklong
reprieves on sales tax for clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana is rebating 1 percent of its sales taxes to local
governments and is gradually doing the same on its 4 percent hotel
and motel tax, a state official said during a panel discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Other states are cutting taxes on fuel, corporate earnings,
hospital revenues and inheritances.
</P>
<P>
   But drinkers and smokers haven't gotten many breaks. No state
reduced sales taxes on cigarettes. New York cut its beer tax and
Indiana cut its tax on hard cider.
</P>
<P>
   Many states are cutting income taxes or giving rebates, but none
as dramatically as Ohio. That state approved a $701 million income
tax rebate this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things we don't understand about this,''
said Dennis Morgan, legislative fiscal officer for Ohio. ``We're
trying to sort it out.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of states are sitting on their surpluses until they figure
out whether to save or spend the money. The survey of state
legislatures found that 23 states plunked their surpluses into
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two states now have nest eggs of more than 10 percent of
their general fund spending budget. Wall Street recommends at least
a 5 percent cushion.
</P>
<P>
   State officials, including Finan, were buoyant yet cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1980, we were flying about as high as we are now and by
1983 we were in deficit financing,'' Finan said of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Finan and others said states are better off to give rebates and
temporary tax cuts than to lower their income tax rates. That way,
hard times are less likely to bring severe revenue losses.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan and Hawaii are two states feeling a downturn right now.
Michigan is losing millions each month because the General Motors
strike, a state official said. Hawaii is suffering because of the
Asian economic crisis and a drop in tourism from Korea and from
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kuroda, fiscal officer for the Hawaii legislature, said it
was hard to even justify spending state money to travel to Las
Vegas for the annual legislative conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late 1980s, when everyone else was hurting, we were
doing well,'' Kuroda said. ``We're hoping for better times but
short-term we're still going to face some difficulties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
