<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FDA-GENETIC-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA PANEL RECOMMENDS CLEARING GENETIC DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An advisory committee to the Food and Drug
Administration on Wednesday recommended approval of the first drug
using a new technology that blocks genes from performing their
functions.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, developed by Isis Pharmaceuticals Inc., treats a viral
infection that can cause blindness in people with AIDS. The FDA
usually follows advisory panel recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, known as antisense, holds great promise for
harnessing genetic information to make potent drugs with few side
effects. It has been difficult to make the technology work in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   But today's action could strengthen the field. ``The main impact
is to prove to the skeptics that antisense works,'' said James
McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, Calif. ``It's sort of the seal of approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Antisense drugs are essentially short sequences of genetic code
that work by preventing formation of specific proteins that cause
or contribute to disease. Most drugs work by trying to interfere
with the functioning of the protein itself, but often interfere
with more than one protein, causing unintended side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The Isis drug, which is called Vitravene, is injected into the
eye. It interferes with the replication of the cytomegalovirus,
which infects AIDS patients and destroys the retina of the eye.
Analysts expect the drug, to be marketed by the Ciba Vision
subsidiary of Novartis AG, the Swiss pharmaceutical giant, will
have annual sales of only $20 million or so. With AIDS treatment
having improved, fewer patients are getting cytomegalovirus
retinitis. There are also existing treatments for this condition.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the clinical trial data were not totally convincing to
the panel or to the FDA staff reviewer, who said the company had
treated too few patients to determine the drug's safety and
efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   But Isis, which is based in Carlsbad, Calif., has other drugs in
clinical trials that are expected to be bigger sellers,
particularly one for inflammatory disorders like Crohn's disease
and rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in Isis shares was halted all day pending the
committee's decision. It closed Tuesday at $13.4375, down 81.25
cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to become the revolution we hoped it would
be,'' said Dr. Stanley T. Crooke, chairman and chief executive of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies working on antisense drugs include Hybridon Inc.
of Cambridge, Mass., which is collaborating with the Searle
pharmaceutical division of Monsanto Co., and Genta Inc. of San
Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
