<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT &LR;      07-23 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SWEEP DOUBLEHEADER FROM BREWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Last year, if there was one trait that defined the
New York Mets, it was their ability to come from behind and win.
One of their major flaws this year, however, has been the inability
to rally to victory.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday night, after a disappointing homestand, the
Mets regrouped for a seven-game trip and not only rallied for a
ninth-inning victory in one game, but also took command and held it
in the second game to sweep a doubleheader from the Milwaukee
Brewers, 7-5 and 6-1. It was the first doubleheader sweep on the
road for the Mets since 1990, when they pulled one off in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo won the second game with seven superb innings, after
Dennis Cook won the opener in relief at County Stadium. The sweep
gave the Mets a 51-46 record and nudged them within two games of
the Cubs, their next opponent, for the wild-card spot in the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who pounded out 26 hits in the doubleheader, also put
some distance between themselves and the Brewers (50-50), a team
Nomo has dominated this season. His two complete games this season
have come against Milwaukee, both while he was pitching for Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Nomo (4-8) helped his own cause with a pair
of singles and even knocked in the Mets' first run. Whatever Nomo
was struggling with since joining the Mets, he seems to have put it
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Over his last three starts, Nomo's earned run average is a
sterling 1.40. And the Japanese right-hander, who allowed one run
and five hits in seven innings with three walks and nine strikeouts
on Wednesday night, has won two consecutive starts after going 80
days without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' last ninth-inning comeback was even longer ago than
that. Entering Wednesday night, they were 1-37 when trailing after
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the Mets were trailing by 5-4 entering the ninth
inning of the first game, after Bill Pulsipher had been knocked
from his first major league start in nearly three years after just
four innings. They were also going up against a reliever in Bob
Wickman, who had converted 15 consecutive save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, things looked bleak. But the Mets rallied for
three runs off Wickman in the ninth, the final two when Edgardo
Alfonzo sliced a two-out double to the opposite field in right. And
then John Franco caught Darrin Jackson looking at strike three with
the bases loaded in the Brewer ninth for his 19th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think that the pendulum swings and swings back,'' an
elated Manager Bobby Valentine said after his team rallied for its
12th victory in its final at-bat this season.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was referring to all those deficits the Mets have not
been able to come back from this season, unlike last year, when
they led the majors by coming from behind to win 47 times and
winning in their final at-bat 24 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's time for it to swing back in our favor again,''
Valentine said after his team came back to win for the 21st time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   How could he not think so after watching the Mets overcome a 5-2
deficit? The Mets got one run in the sixth when John Olerud homered
to right, then scored again in the seventh on a double by Luis
Lopez and a run-scoring single by Rey Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   The winning rally in the ninth consisted of a one-out single by
Lopez, a pinch-hit single into the right-field corner by Todd
Hundley, a game-tying grounder by Lenny Harris, a single to right
by Brian McRae and the game-winning double by Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been coming up short,'' Valentine said. ``And today, we
didn't come up short.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets also bailed out Pulsipher, their starter in the first
game.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, after his start had been switched with Armando
Reynoso's, Pulsipher said it would be tough to keep from thinking
that whether he remained in the majors hinged on his performance
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm human,'' Pulsipher said after Wednesday night's start. And
it was obvious that Pulsipher, who has been taking Prozac for more
than a year to combat anxiety attacks, was nervous from his first
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of his first eight pitches were balls as he made his first
major league start since Sept. 11, 1995. Mark Loretta then took a
pair of strikes and fouled off five consecutive pitches before
lining a single to center to move Fernando Vina, who had led off
the Brewer first with a walk, to third.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Cirillo followed with a first-pitch single to right to
score Vina. It was 1-0 Brewers, there were runners on first and
third and no outs.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher bore down to strike out John Jaha on five pitches,
then fired two quick strikes past Marquis Grissom. But Grissom
singled to left to score Loretta, and Marc Newfield rifled a ball
off Pulsipher's glove to score Cirillo. The Mets were down by 3-0
before Pulsipher finally escaped the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Mets, the Milwaukee left-hander Brad Woodall
appeared just as nervous as Pulsipher. Woodall walked the bases
full to open the second. One run scored when Lopez grounded into a
double play. Another scored on Ordonez's triple to left. All of a
sudden, it was a 3-2 game.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Pulsipher kept it for two more innings. But
Jackson opened the fourth with a bunt single and advanced to second
on a one-out sacrifice by Woodall. Pulsipher then walked Vina, and
Loretta singled to right to score Jackson. When Cirillo singled to
right to score Vina, the Brewers were up by 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   After Pulsipher again struck out Jaha on his 83d pitch, that was
it. In four innings, he allowed eight hits, all singles, and five
runs to raise his earned run average to 7.62 for 13 innings. He
walked two and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pulse gave us what he had,'' Valentine said. ``He gave up some
singles. But it wasn't all that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
