<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-HNS &LR;      07-23 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dodgers
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers attempt to regroup from unusually bumpy season
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a Southern California area accustomed to a few
rumblings, the Los Angeles Dodgers, baseball's model of stability
for years, have sustained one aftershock after another this season.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the moves have been off the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star catcher Mike Piazza, who reportedly sought a contract
worth at least $100 million, was the first to go in a blockbuster
seven-player deal with Florida that also included the Marlins' Gary
Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles Johnson and Jim Eisenreich. Days
later, Piazza was traded to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   After the Piazza commotion came the Hideo Nomo trade _ as well
as the proposed Randy Johnson deal that collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, it gets better.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the organization's most stunning moves yet, Dodgers
executive vice president Fred Claire and manager Bill Russell were
fired June 21. Dodgers president Bob Graziano appointed former
manager Tom Lasorda as general manager, and Glenn Hoffman was
promoted from Class AAA Albuquerque to succeed Russell.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, just before the All-Star break, the Dodgers parted
with heralded young infield prospect Paul Konerko and pitcher
Dennis Reyes to acquire closer Jeff Shaw from the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year of the Fox Group's ownership, things have
begun to settle down. At least for now, as Dodgers players take
each day as if it might be their last in LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, you don't know what to expect when you wake up,''
second baseman Eric Young said. ``It's been one thing after another
all season. You don't expect these things from the Dodgers, because
it's not an organization known for change, but everyone knows
that's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough so that only 14 players remain from the Dodgers'
opening-day active roster. Once the Piazza trade was finalized,
many of the Dodgers players did not suspect any further changes _
and if they did, not so soon afterward. The uncertainty, coupled
with injuries and some players who haven't met expectations, has
kept the Dodgers around .500. Entering Wednesday night's game with
the Astros, the Dodgers were 51-49. It's the first time they have
been that far above .500 since June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is 14 games behind San Diego in the National League
West and trails the Chicago Cubs by 4{ games in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   But with a $57 million payroll, the club's new ownership doesn't
believe the Dodgers are getting their money's worth. Since the May
15 Piazza deal, the Dodgers are 32-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unfortunate situation with all that's been going on,
especially off the field,'' first baseman Eric Karros said. ``The
bottom line is that you can't argue the fact it has impacted us on
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   While the talk has been about the numerous trades, injuries have
been the main cause for the club's difficult season. Starting left
fielder Todd Hollandsworth underwent season-ending shoulder
surgery, and righthanded pitcher Ramon Martinez is out for the year
with a torn right rotator cuff. Bonilla has been on the disabled
list twice and is not expected back until the end of the month at
the earliest with tendinitis in his left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have relied on unproven players to step into
starting roles, most notably third baseman Adrian Beltre, shortstop
Juan Castro and second baseman Wilton Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to establish some chemistry, but that's not
easy to do when there's so much stuff going on all the time,''
Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the turmoil and turnover, Astros manager Larry
Dierker isn't prepared to count the Dodgers out of the NL playoff
chase. The Dodgers are 5-2 against the NL Central-leading Astros
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be a very dangerous team, but the thing that has
always characterized the Dodgers is great pitching,'' Dierker said.
``With Ramon Martinez out, that certainly has an effect on their
pitching. I don't quite think they are the pitching team they once
were. And with Piazza gone and Bonilla out, they probably aren't
quite as powerful as they were early in the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
