<HEADLINE>
THE COMPLICATED LIFE OF KATI MARTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sign outside Kati Marton's Bridgehampton shingle house reads
like the name of a big media law firm: ``Marton Holbrooke
Jennings.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings? As in Peter, her ex-husband and the ABC anchor?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for my children,'' she said cheerfully. ``No, I'm not
hedging my bets.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marton, a former ABC Bonn bureau chief and the author of
four books, has led a complicated life ever since her mother, a
Hungarian reporter for United Press International, was taken from
the family's Budapest apartment, accused of being a spy and jailed
for a year, when Ms. Marton was 7. Her father, a Hungarian reporter
for The Associated Press, spent nearly two years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is too easy to say that the trauma has colored every
aspect of Ms. Marton's emotional life since then. But maybe not.
Friends describe her, accurately, as straightforward, ambitious and
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, things will get more complicated, and interesting,
this fall, when Ms. Marton's husband of three years, Richard
Holbrooke, is expected to be confirmed as the American
representative to the United Nations. Ms. Marton and Holbrooke have
been longtime members of the East Coast power elite, but this
elevates them to a social apex. It also throws Ms. Marton into
making a decision about who she is going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wife of the representative to the United Nations? Kati
Marton, author? Some of each?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give up my day job, which is writing,'' she
said. ``But I know that we're in this together.'' In other words,
when 100 diplomats troop in for a reception, she'll be there. ``And
it won't be an act of enormous sacrifice,'' she said. ``Because I'm
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that Ms. Marton's current book-in-progress,
``First Partners,'' looks at presidential couples from Woodrow and
Edith Wilson through Bill and Hillary Clinton. ``I think I have a
certain sensitivity to, let's say, high-profile marriages,'' Ms.
Marton said.
</P>
<P>
   So far she has interviewed 150 people _ among them Nancy Reagan,
Rosalynn Carter and Lady Bird Johnson _ and has concluded that
first ladies with influence beyond decorating and fashion are ``the
rule rather than the exception.'' Ms. Marton has not yet
interviewed Mrs. Clinton, but thinks she now has the role of first
lady ``just about'' right. ``There's not much scope for
improvising,'' Ms. Marton said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marton, who describes herself as ``skimming 50,'' talked
Tuesday afternoon on the deck of her home, overlooking the
landscapers, who were planting day lilies by the pool. She bought
the house, modest by Hamptons standards, after her 1995 divorce
from Jennings. She has turned it into an airy retreat, now filled
with pictures of a typically rumpled Holbrooke. She fits in better
with the setting: a chic, vaguely exotic woman in black pants and a
crisp white shirt, born in Hungary, raised in Chevy Chase, Md., and
educated at the Sorbonne.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she wasn't relaxed _ she has interviewed too many
people herself for that, and knows the pitfalls _ but was gracious
and open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage is an enormous challenge to make work,'' she said.
``But once you have that, everything flows from that. Because it
frees you. I feel much more together now that I have a successful
marriage. Because I know there's somebody behind me, who thinks
that for me failure is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marton is of course rhapsodizing about a man who has never
been known for his patience, modesty or lack of ambition. ``But I
am able to say to him, `Shut up, Richard, I'm not finished,''' Ms.
Marton said brightly. ``And there is no arrogance. He's tolerant to
a fault of other people's quirks, having so many of his own.''
</P>
<P>
   The two first met as neighbors at the Beresford, the
celebrity-filled Central Park West co-op where Ms. Marton lived
with Jennings and Holbrooke lived with Diane Sawyer, the ABC
correspondent now married to the director Mike Nichols. (Holbrooke
has two ex-wives, but Ms. Sawyer is not one of them. Ms. Marton has
two ex-husbands, the first a former fellow graduate student at
George Washington University. ``A starter marriage,'' she said.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway. As Ms. Marton's marriage to Jennings was ending, she
toured the Loire Valley with her old friend Richard. ``I was seeing
things I'd never seen, because of course Holbrooke does everything
very methodically,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   They were married in May 1995 at the residence of the American
ambassador in Budapest, where Ms. Marton had hidden with her
parents during the 1956 Hungarian Revolution _ just after her
parents were released from prison, and before the family emigrated
to the United States. ``It was the final exorcism of a ghost,'' Ms.
Marton said.
</P>
<P>
   She will never forget the day her mother was taken away: ``I
opened the door to her jailers,'' she said. ``They were dressed as
electricians. I had a sense they were not who they said they were,
but I was playing with an older girl, one who I had a crush on, and
I didn't want to interrupt. So I just called to my mother and went
back to my room. I didn't see her for a year after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The chatter among her friends is that she would make a good
ambassador to Hungary someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to say that my goal in life is to be the spouse
of the ambassador to Hungary,'' said Holbrooke, who did not bring
up his better-known goal to be secretary of state. ``But that's
another play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
