<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DISPLACED HOTEL RESIDENTS, A LONG ODYSSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moments after Tuesday's construction accident in
Times Square, the 275 residents of the Woodstock Hotel, most of
them elderly or mentally ill, were rushed to safety and told they
would be taken care of by city officials, the Red Cross and an
array of nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But 12 hours later, they found themselves cooped up on a hot,
crowded floor of the Times Square Hotel, the victims of
finger-pointing, insurance worries and finally by a mundane, if
familiar, New York City concern: the inability to find inexpensive
hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   They finally were moved to temporary accommodations at 11 p.m.
That was 14 hours after a temporary elevator tower at the Conde
Nast building across the street collapsed and a long section of it
slammed into the hotel's roof, killing an 85-year-old resident and
rendering the building's two top floors unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   In the confusion created by the accident and the hotel's
evacuation, many residents went without medication for 12 hours. A
group of 32 residents were believed by Red Cross doctors to need
medical monitoring. After all the other Woodstock residents were
moved to hotels and YMCA's to sleep, the group of 32 were finally
taken by bus to Bellevue Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Graham, 60, a retired mechanic, said that once the group
arrived at Bellevue, they had to sit through two hours of
processing. ``We didn't get to Bellevue until 2 a.m.,'' he said.
``We didn't get to bed until 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley Varner, 71, a Woodstock Hotel resident, takes four
different pills for heart problems and seizures. He waited at the
Times Square Hotel all day Wednesday after he had to leave the
Woodstock without any belongings, and was finally taken to
Bellevue. ``I didn't get much sleep last night,'' he said. ``I
haven't been taking my medication like I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers involved in caring for the group said the difficulties
they encountered were in some ways the inevitable result of the
confusion that fell on midtown.
</P>
<P>
   But Cynthia Dial, the executive director of Project Find, the
nonprofit organization that runs the Woodstock, complained that
efforts to aid the victims had been hindered because the Durst
Organization, the construction project's developer, and Tishman
Construction Corp., its construction manager, had refused at first
to cover emergency costs. Ms. Dial and Rosanne Haggerty, executive
director of the Times Square Hotel, also said the American Red
Cross had responded slowly after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was that nobody was coming through and the Red
Cross was moving slowly,'' Ms. Dial said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haggerty, executive director of Common Ground, which runs
the Times Square Hotel, was less charitable. ``I was stunned,'' she
said. ``It was irresponsible and callous.''
</P>
<P>
   By roughly 2 p.m. all of the Woodstock residents were in place
and workers at the Times Square began calling hotels in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Best Western chain offered to house all the Woodstock people
in rooms in five of its Manhattan hotels at prices ranging from
$125 to $160. Ms. Dial said she contacted Douglas Durst of the
Durst Organization and officials at Tishman.
</P>
<P>
   She said that both companies told her they would have to check
with their insurance carriers. At 6 p.m., Ms. Dial said, she had
not heard from them. Red Cross officials at the scene told her that
the Best Western room rates were too high and that they could find
alternative housing for the Woodstock's residents by roughly 8 p.m.
The reservations at the Best Western were canceled. Eight o'clock
came and went.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 p.m., Durst, after being contacted by City Councilman
Thomas Duane, called to say he would pay for the first night's
hotel room out of his own pocket. But Red Cross representatives
said they could find housing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Durst confirmed Ms. Dial's account.
He said he received Ms. Dial's first call at 4:30 p.m. but that he
was advised by his insurance company that directly paying any costs
from the accidents would jeopardize his insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke with them again at around 8:30 and said that I would
pick up the tab,'' Durst said.
</P>
<P>
   As the search for hotels drifted past 10 p.m., the first
medications began arriving for Woodstock residents, many of whom
had been without the medicine they need for various illnesses and
psychiatric problems since the 8:30 a.m. accident. Red Cross
spokesman Robert Wingate said the sheer number of people involved
slowed efforts to understand which prescriptions were needed.
``That's a process that takes some time,'' he said. ``Think of the
task of assessing those needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The residents of the Woodstock were not alone. Twenty-eight
members of a Georgia church group in New York on a community
service trip fared little better. They were ordered to leave Lamb's
Church on West 44th Street after the collapse, but had no time to
collect personal belongings. The American Red Cross took them by
bus to two Bronx motels at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after some of its members complained of flea bites,
the group decided to pay for their own rooms at the Hotel Carter,
on 43rd Street, even though the street was cordoned off. Wednesday,
they departed for Georgia, leaving their personal belongings
behind.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2 in the morning when they climbed off their bus in the
Bronx and through the chain-link fences of the Cross-Bronx
Residence on 175th Street or the Baychester Motel on East 202nd
Street. For these church-going teen-agers of prosperous families,
the accommodations were, as one said, ``a real eye-opener _ a whole
new world.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, donations were flowing into the Woodstock. The
Durst Organization and Tishman Construction Corp. agreed to cover
the cost of any accommodations the Red Cross could not afford. Bell
Atlantic agreed to provide the group with a $25,000 donation,
cellular phones and voice-mail services for the residents of the
hotel. Columbia University offered to house Woodstock residents in
empty dormitory rooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
