r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SENIORS-EQUIPMENT     07-23 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORS-EQUIPMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY AIDS SENIORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a Senior PGA Tour-leading four victories this
year and 12 wins in less than two full seasons, Gil Morgan might
not need much in the way of an equipment boost.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1997 senior rookie of the year and champion in two '98
senior majors is happy to take every edge the U.S. Golf Association
allows.
</P>
<P>
   Like his graying peers in a tour filled with players of
gradually diminishing motor skills and physical strength, Morgan
applauded the USGA's recent decision to take no immediate steps to
rein in golf technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are more into the technology stuff,'' Morgan said
of senior tour players. ``Guys trying to maintain their games,
trying to hang on to distance and stuff. They are probably
experimenting with different types of things more so than the
regular tour player at this point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Few pro golfers experiment more than Terry Dill, the 1996 senior
driving leader who just loves what technology has done for his
game. He believes ``beyond any shadow of a doubt'' that improved
equipment helps senior tour players.
</P>
<P>
   Dill has grooves in his putter to promote a quicker roll,
abrasive facing on his irons for tighter landing patterns and
cavity-backed clubs for better bounce. He has long-shafted drivers,
four different types of wedges ... and he keeps an eye open for
anything else that might help.
</P>
<P>
   The former Texas A&AMP;M law school professor and grandfather of
five is hardly in the minority when it comes to keeping abreast of
the latest golf innovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out on our practice tee, you will see all the guys
trying every new thing that comes out to see if it is any edge,''
Dill said.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his 10th year on the senior tour, Dill says he is playing
the best golf of his life. He attributes it to the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``By using a lot of this stuff, you add a little bit here, a
little bit there,'' he said, ``... where the really good (PGA Tour)
players, they are using hardly any high-tech stuff at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need it because they are pure. But we are doing
everything we can to keep on playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dill doesn't think it will be necessary for the USGA to change
the rules to protect courses from technology, saying ``It doesn't
really help good players that much.''
</P>
<P>
   But the USGA might have the final word on that. In announcing no
immediate rule changes last month at the U.S. Open, USGA executive
director David Fay also spoke of a proposed new test to measure the
springlike effect of clubheads.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan wonders what the fuss is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't raise the basketball goal or raise the net in
tennis,'' he said. ``You know, they don't do all those things with
other sports. I don't know why they are continually doing it with
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   As for 11-time senior tour winner Bob Murphy, don't get him
started on the subject of the proposed spring-effect test, which
would include clubs previously tested and approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golfdom is very happy, golfdom is doing very well,'' Murphy
said. ``I don't for one minute believe they should outlaw all these
clubs and whatnot they've already approved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
