<HEADLINE>
KLAHN GETS SPOT IN OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Klahn of Thousand Oaks phoned Riviera Country
Club on Monday, just in case. As first alternate for this year's
U.S. Senior Open, Klahn figured he had a chance for a belated
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   No openings yet, he was told by U.S. Golf Association officials
on site. No problem, said Klahn, who headed out to Riviera for a
practice round, just in case. When he arrived, he found himself in
the field _ a replacement for Tommy Aaron, who had to withdraw that
morning because of a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Klahn, a former teaching professional at Wood Ranch in Simi
Valley, will tee off in today's 1:40 p.m. group, joining 1991 Ford
Senior Players champion Jim Albus and 23-time PGA Senior Tour
winner Bob Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dent, Bud Allin and John Bland withdrew on Tuesday, giving
replacement berths to, respectively, John Baker of Hermitage, Pa.,
Robert Heaton of Antioch, Calif., and Don Shevorski of Anaheim.
Shevorski, 57, is playing in his fourth Senior Open and his second
as an alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Local qualifier: Simi Valley's Bill Brooks, a six-time Sunset
Hills Country Club champion and Wood Ranch member, struggled up the
18th fairway Wednesday and pronounced Riviera fit for a national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' said the 56-year-old retired L.A. policeman, who
earned his Open berth by winning a three-man playoff in a June 29
qualifying event.
</P>
<P>
   The Riviera rough, combined with hitting into the wind on holes
12-16 and greens measuring near 11 on the stimpmeter, made Riviera
a problem for Brooks for a fourth straight practice round.
</P>
<P>
   The key to playing well here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting the fairways,'' he said. ``You've got to stay out of
the rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' practice-round struggles inside the ropes, however, have
been just part of his early Open experience. He also had his
picture taken this week with Arnold Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get it blown up real big and bring it back for
his autograph,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   One of 30 amateurs in the 156-man field, Brooks opens today at
7:50 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Local knowledge: Dave Stockton (1974), Hale Irwin ('76) and Gil
Morgan ('78) have all won before at Riviera, while playing in L.A.
Opens (now Nissan Open) on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Strange but true: Jack Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer, two of the
most successful players in the history of professional golf, have
never won at Riviera. Palmer won three L.A. Opens but all at Rancho
Park. Nicklaus, who never won in the L.A. Open, came closest to a
victory at Riviera when he finished second by a stroke to Hal
Sutton in the 1983 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Honor roll: Nicklaus, Lee Trevino, Gary Player, Billy Casper,
Palmer and Orville Moody are the only players to win both the U.S.
Senior Open and U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Of this week's entries, Tony Jacklin (1970), Hale Irwin (1974,
'79, '90), Hubert Green (1977), David Graham (1981), Larry Nelson
(1983) and Raymond Floyd (1986) have won the U.S. Open part of that
national championship double.
</P>
</TEXT>
