<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADVERTISING
</P>
<P>
   Two marketing research and consulting companies _ Roper Starch
Worldwide in New York and the Response Analysis Corp. in Princeton,
N.J. _ said on Wednesday that they had signed a letter of intent to
combine operations under the Roper Starch name. Financial terms
were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Response Analysis will operate as a division of Roper Starch,
retaining its name and its Princeton location. James Fouss, 57,
president of Response Analysis, becomes vice chairman of Roper
Starch; William Wilson, 62, chairman and chief executive of Roper
Starch, continues in those roles.
</P>
<P>
   Roper Starch has 250 employees and revenue estimated at $40
million from clients like the Colgate-Palmolive Company and the
Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. Response Analysis has 120 employees and
revenue estimated at $16 million from clients like the Banc One
Corporation and the Bell Atlantic Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare health maintenance organizations competing for new
enrollees appear to work at selling themselves to healthier
potential customers, according to a study released by the Kaiser
Family Foundation in Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on an analysis by Porter Novelli, a unit of
Omnicom Group, of marketing practices by HMO's in Cleveland, Los
Angeles, Miami and New York. Researchers reviewed ads in 169
newspapers and on 129 television stations and observed and analyzed
21 marketing seminars to assess the marketing techniques used by
HMO's to attract Medicare enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing efforts seemed to be aimed at the physically
active elderly, the study concluded, rather than the full range of
Medicare beneficiaries, such as those who are older, sick or under
age 65 and disabled. More than half the commercials portrayed older
people engaged in physical or social activities like running and
swimming, the study reported; none showed anyone in a hospital or
using a wheelchair or walker.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly a third of the 21 marketing seminars the researchers
attended were not accessible to wheelchairs, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Needham Worldwide in New York, part of Omnicom Group, took
the Best of Show Award at the 20th annual Ace Awards for
business-to-business communications, sponsored by the Business
Marketing Association in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The top multiple winners, tied with six awards each, were
Clarion Marketing and Communications Group in Stamford, Conn., part
of MacManus Group, for work for clients including Arrow
Electronics, and Mobium Creative Group in Chicago, for work for
clients like R.R. Donnelley &AMP; Sons. Winning five Ace awards each
were Anderson &AMP; Lembke in New York and San Francisco, part of the
Interpublic Group of Companies, for clients including
Ingersoll-Rand, and Campbell Mithun Esty in Minneapolis, which is
majority owned by Interpublic, for clients including the Toro
Company.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   FSI International Inc., Chaska, Minn., a maker of
semiconductor-manufacturing equipment and flat-panel displays, said
it would lay off 220 workers, or about 17 percent of its work
force, and take a charge in its fourth quarter as weak demand
forces it to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   General Scanning Inc.,
</P>
<P>
   Watertown, Mass., a maker of laser systems used to make computer
chips and produce medical diagnostic images, will cut 12 percent of
its work force, or about 110 jobs, as the Asian economic crisis
causes sales to stagnate.
</P>
</TEXT>
