<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAK LINKS: SONS DON'T ALSO RISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Being paired with icon Arnold Palmer in today's
first round of the U.S. Senior Open at Riviera Country Club
shouldn't pose a problem for Bob Duval. He is so comfortable
playing in the shadow of another golfer he doesn't even seek the
sanctuary of his own identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello,'' he'll say to strangers, warmly extending his hand,
``I'm David Duval's father.''
</P>
<P>
   In a classic role reversal, Duval is playing catch-up to his
son, along with every other golfer on the planet. No one is on a
better roll right now than the 26-year-old Duval, who has two wins
this calendar year and eight top-10 finishes in 16 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Duval wishes he could say his son is a chip off the old
block. But the fact of the matter is he's from an altogether
different mold.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, 51, didn't play professionally when his youngest son was
growing up. When he was David's age, he opted for a club pro's
position in Jacksonville, Fla., because the $50,000 annual salary
was more than all but the top 50 touring pros in the world were
earning at the time.
</P>
<P>
   It was a comfortable if not cushy existence. In the summer
months, especially, a club pro's hours are as long as the days. And
the demands of the country club set can leave club pros feeling
more like indentured servants than swing doctors.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval grew up observing all the hoops his father had to
jump through and it deepened his desire to one day be his own boss
on the golf course. He would be an independent contractor on the
PGA Tour or something else altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw how difficult it was answering to the Mrs. Murphys,''
Bob Duval said, ``and decided he didn't want any part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence apparently is a powerful incentive. Long before
Duval ascended to the top of this year's PGA Tour money list with
$1.67 million and counting, the offspring of club pros were leaving
deep divots on the PGA Tour's landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's father was a club pro at Latrobe (Pa.) Country Club and
you'd have to have been lost in Riviera's rough all these years not
to know how Palmer's professional playing career turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Duval, other sons of teaching pros who have gone on
to win PGA titles include PGA Tour members Davis Love III, Vijah
Singh and Jim Gallagher Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the sons of touring pros haven't fared nearly as
well. You'd think that success would breed success, but the truth
is, not many offspring over the years have been able to follow
their fathers' footsteps straight into the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: baseball has Ken Griffey Jr.; golf has Dave
Stockton Jr., who has seven top-10 finishes in five years on the
PGA Tour. Basketball has Kobe Bryant; golf has Brent Geiberger, a
PGA Tour Rookie of the Year candidate in 1997 who tied for second
at the Phoenix Open in January but has missed the cut in six of his
last 11 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know better, you'd think the PGA Tour had some
sort of nepotism policy. Among exempt PGA Tour members, Guy Boros
is the only son of a former PGA Tour champion who has won a tour
event.
</P>
<P>
   When Boros triumphed at the 1996 Vancouver Open, some two years
after the death of his father Julius, it was no minor victory.
Since 1951, only two other sons of PGA Tour winners, Joe Kirkwood
Jr. and Vance Heafner, have finished first in a PGA-sanctioned
event. It just goes to show, champions can't be reproduced as
easily as a set of knockoff irons.
</P>
<P>
   The golf ball clearly isn't impressed by bloodlines, or Gary
Nicklaus, the third of four sons of Jack, wouldn't be toiling in
obscurity on the European Tour and Robert Floyd, youngest son of
Raymond, wouldn't be paying his dues on the Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few of us have had sons and very few have done really
well,'' said Dave Stockton, 56, the 1996 U.S. Senior Open champion.
``I'm just amazed more of our kids are not better players than they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be that when the second generation tees it up, a number
of hazards come into play. Stockton wonders if many of them realize
how hard it is to make a good living at golf. It's a child's
prerogative to believe if dear old dad seemingly does it with the
greatest of ease, how hard can it be?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they have no clue how many hours their dads spent working
to perfect their games before they came along and started hanging
out inside the gallery ropes. Maybe, as Stockton suggested, as the
kids of touring pros get older, ``some of us make it too easy on
them, getting them sponsor's exemptions or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they're like Bryan Geiberger, another one of Al
Geiberger's sons, and grow tired of peoples' heightened
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sometimes see your name on a scoreboard and they assume
because you are a player's son, you should be better,'' said
Geiberger, 21, who is back playing the game after forsaking it for
a few years to pursue other sports.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan is caddying for his dad this week. Some day, perhaps,
he'll play on the PGA Tour. Or maybe he'll wait 29 years and join
the senior tour. In golf, all things are possible. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
