<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8637 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ROLE-MODELS-2takes     07-23 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROLE-MODELS-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD OF ANDERSON, WELBY ONE OF SAGE ADVICE, COMPASSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY REED JOHNSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Robert Young wasn't a real doctor, though he
played one on television.
</P>
<P>
   Nor in real life was Young always the calm, unshakable pillar of
paternal wisdom he appeared to be in ``Father Knows Best,'' a role
that stamped him as a mass-market swami of nuclear-family values.
</P>
<P>
   Off camera, the resident of Westlake Village northwest of Los
Angeles, who died Tuesday at age 91, suffered from terrible bouts
of depression and alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   But to a generation of TV viewers, Young was the ultimate
paterfamilias, a gentle, infallible arbiter both of minor domestic
crises and life-or-death medical matters.
</P>
<P>
   Though he enjoyed substantial success as a film actor, appearing
in such memorable movies as ``Sitting Pretty,'' ``Strange
Interlude,'' ``Northwest Passage'' and ``Journey for Margaret,'' it
was within the cozier confines of television that Young's warmth
and humanity truly shone.
</P>
<P>
   And it was on television that he left his deepest imprint on
popular culture, first in ``Father Knows Best'' (1954-1963), for
which he won two Emmys, then for ``Marcus Welby, M.D.''
(1969-1976), for which he won a third.
</P>
<P>
   From the late 1940s, when ``Father Knows Best'' first hit the
radio waves, until Marcus Welby finally hung up his stethoscope,
Young epitomized what American dads and American doctors were
supposed to be like.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally speaking, the roles of the urbane Dr. Welby and the
small-town insurance agent Jim Anderson were nearly identical. The
gray-haired physician with the empathetic bedside manner, and the
father who always found time to dispense a gentle sermon or a sage
piece of advice, both provided the nation with the image of a
benign, Solomon-like authority during a period of Cold War tensions
and rising social turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a tremendously reassuring figure,'' said Steven Stark,
a commentator for National Public Radio and the author of ``Glued
to the Set: The 60 Television Shows and Events That Made Us Who We
Are Today'' (Free Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly in an era of great unrest in the culture, (CBS
news anchor) Walter Cronkite and Robert Young were pretty much the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   As a father, Jim Anderson was a far cry from the pleasantly
bumbling Fred MacMurray of ``My Three Sons,'' and further still
from the tyrannical Archie Bunker, the boorish Al Bundy or the
endearingly dysfunctional Homer Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   With elbow patches on his jacket and an avuncular twinkle in his
eye, Young's Anderson was the calm center of his household, a
9-to-5 guy who seemingly always left his cares at the office.
</P>
<P>
   While his wife Margaret was suffering remorse for overspending
on a new hat, or accidentally backing the car into the garage,
father Jim usually could be found in the kitchen, easing the
painful transitions into puberty of his eldest daughter, whom he
lovingly called ``Princess,'' while quietly setting a manly example
for his son, Bud.
</P>
<P>
   ``If America was looking for a father figure after World War II,
and I think it was, (Young) combined the best of the male and
female characteristics of parenting,'' said Michael T. Marsden,
dean of the college of arts and sciences at Northern Michigan
University and co-editor of the The Journal of Popular Film and
Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always the counselor, certainly the disciplinarian when
that had to occur, but he was also the compassionate, understanding
disciplinarian.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Anderson, Dr. Welby was probably too good to exist outside
television. Unhampered by HMO bean-counters or breast-implant
lawsuits, he made house calls, treated superiors and underlings
with equal respect, and served as a mentor to his younger, funkier
colleague played by James Brolin.
</P>
<P>
   The show broke ground in addressing subjects like homosexuality
and drug abuse with greater sensitivity and depth than had been
seen on TV until then.
</P>
<P>
   Welby's hands-on style set a humanizing example for the field of
medicine, said Dr. Barbara Korsch, a professor of pediatrics at USC
and author of ``The Intelligent Patient's Guide to the
Doctor-Patient Relationship'' (Oxford University Press).
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, she lamented, in today's modern world of managed
health care, ``There's all kinds of technology interposed, not to
mention that everybody is so concerned about AIDS that nobody seems
to touch a patient anymore without rubber gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Korsch cautioned that Welby fostered an unrealistic
expectation that no medical problem is so complex that it can't be
neatly wrapped up in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors are very success-oriented, and both doctors and
patients like short-term gratification, which was usually available
on the Marcus Welby show,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Nelson, a Utah physician and trustee of the American
Medical Association, described Welby ``as so warm, so kind, you'd
have the impression if you were his patient that he had nothing
else on his mind, you were his sole concern.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``(However) Marcus Welby had one patient a week. I have 40 or 50
a day.''
</P>
<P>
   When Young was in his acting prime, television generally held
dads and doctors in higher regard. Today's physicians are more
likely to be depicted as beleaguered technocrats, occasionally
heroic, often in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As for fathers, you can take your pick between Al Bundy, Homer
Simpson, Tim Allen in ``Home Improvement'' and Dick Solomon of
``3rd Rock From the Sun,'' an extraterrestrial whose very sexuality
is ambiguous at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a show on television where the person who's
nominally the authority figure hasn't been undermined,'' said Karal
Ann Marling, professor of art history and American Studies at the
University of Minnesota. ``Clearly we can't bear being told what to
do. Marcus Welby might be the last one on TV to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder some people may prefer the myth of a
beneficent, all-knowing patriarch to a world in which all
authority, from pediatricians to politicians, is suspect?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different type of world, it was a different type of
family,'' said Los Angeles child psychologist Robert Butterworth,
reflecting on Young's TV legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, Is it better for us to see images that are
real, or images that are idealized?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
