<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BY IRA MILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  
Transition May Mean Trouble  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGAME, Calif. _ This was the third time in a year and a
half the 49ers rented a hotel ballroom to announce that someone was
giving up a position with the organization that he loved.
</P>
<P>
   If history has taught us anything, it's that patience will be
required to sort out the real meaning behind Wednesday's
developments.
</P>
<P>
   You might remember that when George Seifert stepped down as the
team's coach in January 1997, he insisted earnestly that he could
have continued in the job _ and even gotten a contract extension if
he wanted it. Eddie DeBartolo later said that was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   And last December, when DeBartolo stepped aside as managing
owner pending the outcome of legal proceedings in Louisiana, we
were told it would be ``business as usual'' because Carmen Policy
would become a minority owner of the team.
</P>
<P>
   We now know, of course, that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday, when the phrase ``business as usual'' was heard
again at yet another 49ers press conference, we were left to ponder
just what that meant with regard to the team.
</P>
<P>
   As always, they went to great lengths to put the best possible
spin on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be one of the most stable organizations in
professional football,'' claimed Larry Thrailkill, the Nashville
attorney who takes over for Policy as the team's interim chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Depends on how you define stable, I guess. In less than two
years, the 49ers have changed head coaches, offensive coordinators,
defensive coordinators and now club presidents. They have at least
six projected new starters in their on-field lineup this season.
They have undergone transition in their personnel department. Hard
to believe, but Dwight Clark is now the team's longest-tenured
high-ranking football management employee.
</P>
<P>
   For nigh on a decade, pundits have predicted the end of the
49ers' dynasty. No one could have foreseen that the mortal wounds
might be self-inflicted, but how else to describe the sequence of
recent events?
</P>
<P>
   There are three reasons the 49ers have managed to stall a
serious downfall for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, it's the weak opposition in their division; among them,
the Saints, Falcons and Rams have had four winning seasons out of a
possible 24 in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, it had to do with Bill Walsh's prescience, trading for
Steve Young in 1987 when he still had Joe Montana. No NFL team ever
made a smoother transition at quarterback, and that's the area that
caused many past dynasties to founder. Walsh saw greatness in Young
at a time many of the personnel experts in the NFL saw nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, the 49ers stayed strong because their organization
was so strong, so together. Sure, they were backed by DeBartolo's
deep pockets, but they also always seemed to know what move to
make. They made their share of mistakes, certainly, but when they
screwed one up, they usually cut their losses and moved on, and
there were rarely any recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, whenever the 49ers made a decision or a move, it
was always presented as an ``organizational'' event. When they
explained things, they always spoke with a single voice. Nobody
really believed it, but they came as close as any team could to
making outsiders think there was never any internal dissent. If the
Soviets were as good at crushing internal dissent as the 49ers, the
Berlin Wall might still be standing.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who left the front office or the coaching staff never
had a bad word to say about the organization. The 49ers didn't
invent the golden handshake, but at least in the NFL, they surely
perfected it. Policy won't leave empty-handed, either.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that facade is forever shattered, and, more than anything
else, it presages a different era for the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be hard for them to find a new chief executive, whether
it is Bill Walsh or someone else, with a better knowledge of and
background in football than Policy. Within the next year and a
half, it could even be Mike Holmgren, who has found Green Bay too
confining and longs for a chance to run an organization.
</P>
<P>
   They won't, however, find someone who can be a smoother voice
for the organization or present a better image than Policy. Few in
sports work a crowd better than Policy, who, typically, tried to
soften the occasion Thursday by opening with a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Until that someone is in place, Clark will be under a
microscope. His influence has grown in the past year or two, as
Policy became distracted by league matters and the pursuit of a new
San Francisco stadium. Now, even with an interim CEO, Clark has
gone all the way from all-pro player to the top of the
organizational chart.
</P>
<P>
   And even here, there's a question worth asking. We all know
DeBartolo and Clark were close when Clark was playing. But no one
knows where that relationship stands now. Clark is a team player,
and in the recent past, he played for Policy's front-office team.
If DeBartolo gets back in control, will his relationship with Clark
again be what it was?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, coach Steve Mariucci really was hired by
Policy, not DeBartolo. So were executives like Bill Duffy, the
business vice president and chief financial officer. What happens
if DeBartolo comes back? What happens to personnel boss Vinny
Cerrato if Walsh, who has been privately critical of many 49ers
personnel decisions in recent years, comes in?
</P>
<P>
   Many questions. Few answers.
</P>
<P>
   For the immediate future, the 49ers have a bigger problem than
their front office, anyway. They remain a team in transition.
Players like Young and Jerry Rice will be gone long before that
planned stadium is built, if in fact it ever is built. The next
quarterback transition can't possibly be as successful as the last
one and, even if Rice makes it all the way back from his two
surgeries, how long can he go?
</P>
<P>
   Strange isn't it? With Walsh and Montana and Rice and Ronnie
Lott, four present or future Hall of Famers, the good times rolled
on for the 49ers. But it looks like the punctuation mark on the end
of an era will not involve a player, but the departure of Policy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
