<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD UNDETERRED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers' Gary Sheffield is expecting a better
outcome than his sparring partner Jason Kendall of the Pittsburgh
Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   After a collision at the plate on June 28, Sheffield and the
Pirates' catcher were involved in a fight that provoked a
bench-clearing brawl. Both were later given three-game suspensions
that they decided to appeal. On Tuesday, however, Kendall was put
on immediate three-game suspension after National League president
Leonard S. Coleman Jr. upheld the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruling on Kendall, Sheffield said Wednesday he feels
confident he will be cleared from serving his suspension when he
receives his ruling in New York before the Dodgers meet the Mets on
Aug. 3. Sheffield has said he was provoked to fight after Kendall
shouted obscenities at him. Kendall won't be eligible to play again
until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my chances are good,' said Sheffield, who went to UCLA
Medical Center after suffering a cut above his left eyelid during
the fight. ``If they really want to know the facts, they can look
at the tape and get it resolved. I don't see (myself) losing. I
know I'm totally right and there is no reason to think negative.''
</P>
<P>
   If the suspension is upheld immediately on Aug. 3, he would miss
the game against the Mets that night and two games at Montreal on
Aug. 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman said, ``I hope it works out for
him. Especially with the way he is playing.'
</P>
<P>
   Wagner gets attention: Houston closer Billy Wagner, who was
struck in the head by a line drive at Arizona on July 15, did not
accompany the team to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who suffered a concussion and a soft-tissue injury to
his left ear, was placed on the 15-day disabled list Monday. The
left-hander, who was bothered by dizziness and headaches after the
incident, has been prescribed a series of light physical exercises,
including jogging and weights.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who is sixth in the National League in saves with 22,
will be a guest on ``ESPN UpClose'' today at 3 p.m. via satellite
from his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get hit in the head for people to know who I am,''
said Wagner jokingly on Monday. ``I was 22 for 24 in saves and I
couldn't get on that show. I get hit in the head and now I am
there. Go figure.'
</P>
<P>
   Jarrin live: Baseball announcer Jaime Jarrin's induction into
the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., on July 26 will be
broadcast by KWKW-AM (1330) from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. Jarrin, who is
in the midst of his 40th season as the ``Spanish voice of the
Dodgers,'' is also the 1998 recipient of the Ford C. Frick
broadcast award, presented annually to a broadcaster for
contribution to baseball broadcasting.
</P>
</TEXT>
