<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NEVIUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
More Drama Unloaded on 49ers  By C.W. NEVIUS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    BURLINGAME, Calif. _ And so, in the end, everyone loses. When
team president Carmen Policy announced his resignation from the
49ers Wednesday, the shock waves shuddered through the
organization.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Policy has to leave the team he loves, the 49ers' players _
rousted out of bed at 11 Tuesday night to hear the news from coach
Steve Mariucci _ are wondering what hit them, and Eddie DeBartolo
continues to mutter darkly to himself about conspiracy theories and
hidden agendas.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a football team, it's ``Hamlet.'' Alas, poor Carmen,
we knew him well.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even gotten to Act V yet, where the story starts
to make sense, even if it turns out that some of our favorite
characters aren't going to make the final curtain.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest thing that we can say about the future of the
49ers is that it has nothing to do with Jerry Rice's knee, Steve
Young's elbow or whether or not they fumble against the Green Bay
Packers. This whole franchise is left in limbo, waiting to see what
happens with a Louisiana grand jury that continues to sit silently
in judgment of Eddie DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports that something is about to break down
there in the bayou, and that certainly would explain some of what
happened Wednesday. If it is true that DeBartolo has managed to
find a way to put the allegations to rest, you can see why Policy
would grab his Armani jacket and head out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, he was gone anyhow if Eddie regained control of the
team _ the feud between them was that bitter. Ever since Policy was
forced to handle the old scoop shovel during the stadium ballot
issue, with Eddie and his advisers playing the part of the
elephant, the relationship has been strained.
</P>
<P>
   Policy cleaned up the messes, and the stadium bill passed, but
it wasn't much fun. By the start of last season, Policy had
acquired his own private box for 49ers games so he and Eddie
wouldn't have to sit together.
</P>
<P>
   And let's be honest, once DeBartolo got into trouble with the
feds, there is every reason to think that Policy did some serious
research into putting together the financing that could buy the
team. There are people who will tell you that he had a deal set to
go and had made a pitch to Denise DeBartolo York.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, it looked like a no-lose situation for the
organization. If Eddie escaped the clutches of the government,
everything would run as it had, with DeBartolo writing the checks
and Policy running the front office. If something bad happened in
Louisiana, Policy was there to take over the team and they wouldn't
miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we have this. Policy is out, DeBartolo continues to
twist in the Louisiana wind, and DeBartolo York has been ``forced''
_ her word _ to run the team. DeBartolo York's guy, corporate
lawyer Larry Thrailkill, who flew in Thursday to take charge, made
it clear that he was as surprised as anyone to be CEO of a
five-time Super Bowl winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-four hours ago,'' Thrailkill drawled, ``I was minding
my own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I hope you're a quick study, Larry, because business is
booming _ and not in a good way, either.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Thrailkill seems like a nice-enough chap. Thrown into
the media whirlpool, he sat there next to Policy Thursday and hit a
few nice volleys as reporters took their best shots. After all, it
isn't as if he doesn't know anything about the game _ ``I played in
high school,'' he said, getting a nice laugh.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the tone Thursday couldn't have been more polite and
cordial, which is often the case at a formal beheading.
</P>
<P>
   Policy, of course, set his famous charm on ``stun,'' and not
only thanked everyone present, he went out of his way to say kind
things about his former friend, wishing Eddie the best of luck and
graciously leaving the door open to a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo York, in a long, formal statement, also took the high
road, saying she was ``both surprised and disappointed'' when
Policy offered his resignation. She thanked him for past
contributions and wished him well ``in his future endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie, meanwhile, managed to cough out a 26-word farewell to
Policy on a single piece of plain, white paper, which read as if it
had been pulled from his mouth with pliers: ``Carmen leaves our
organization with my best personal wishes. He has been an integral
part of the 49ers' success since we named him president in 1991.''
He had more to say, but that was all he devoted to his buddy.
</P>
<P>
   But this is just the beginning of a long, tangled tale. Now that
we have set the scene, all we can do is sit back and wait to see
how it unspools. There are games to play, federal marshals to
answer and a struggle for power.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Well, at least one source Thursday said we
shouldn't hold our breath waiting for Bill Walsh to be asked back.
Walsh is interested, he said, ``but he may not get the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. All we know so far is that if something really bad
happens in that Louisiana courtroom, and if the 49ers' ship begins
to take on water, Policy won't be around.
</P>
<P>
   That lifeboat just left. Someone strike up ``Nearer My God to
Thee.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
