<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX ABORTION CLINIC TO BE EVICTED, LANDLORD SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER AND SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The landlord of a controversial Phoenix abortion
clinic said Wednesday that he will evict his tenant, which has come
under fire after the recent death of a patient and a failed
abortion that ended in the delivery of a full-term baby.
</P>
<P>
   And the state Board of Nursing confirmed Wednesday that it is
looking into whether licensed nurses were involved in the April
death of a woman at the A-Z Women's Center on East McDowell Road or
in the June delivery of a 37-week-old baby that a doctor believed
was only 23 weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Ridenour, nursing board director, said her office doesn't
know whether any nurses were involved but decided it needed to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Arizona Board of Medical Examiners suspended the
license of Dr. John Biskind, the doctor involved in the cases. His
suspension is pending a hearing by the state Office of
Administrative Hearings, which is expected to meet in 30 to 60
days.
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa County Attorney's Office and the Phoenix Police
Department also are investigating Biskind for possible criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Their investigation centers around the death of 33-year-old
LouAnne Herron, who bled to death after receiving an abortion from
Biskind in April. Police and prosecutors also are examining the
case of the baby that Biskind nearly aborted in June. It received
lacerations and a skull facture in the process. She will be adopted
by a Texas couple.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the state medical board censured Biskind for gross
negligence after another patient bled to death.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the landlord of the A-Z Center, who asked that his
name not be used, said, ``They will shortly be leaving. We're
giving the time that they are allowed under the law.'' He declined
to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   His statement directly contradicted those of clinic personnel,
who insisted Wednesday that A-Z was remaining open despite reports
to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the media is saying. We're not closing,'' said the
administrator, who declined to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of A-Z, Dr. Moshe Hachamovitch of New York, also
operates two clinics _ on 27th Avenue in west Phoenix and on
Scottsdale Road in Scottsdale _ under the name Family Planning
Institute. The McDowell Road administrator said neither of those
clinics is closing.
</P>
<P>
   At the Scottsdale center, however, shelves were empty Wednesday,
and cardboard boxes filled the reception area. Employees said they
were cleaning and declined further comment. They said the center
was not seeing patients Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   An employee at the 27th Avenue clinic referred all calls about
appointments to the McDowell Road center.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Finkel, a Phoenix doctor who provides abortions, said
his office received calls Wednesday from women who had been turned
away from A-Z.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are being told that their doctor is supposedly ill and
they will have to reschedule their appointment somewhere else,''
Finkel said. &QL; 
 &UR; Jodie Snyder can be reached at 444-8667 or at jodie.snyder &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL; 
 &UR; Susie Steckner can be reached at 444-2413 or at
susie.steckner &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
