<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS SPARKING FANS' HOPES  
 OFF-SEASON MOVES BRING SMILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ The argument started on a dusty, softball
field and then moved to the Dirty Drummer bar in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Cardinals basher announced to all who would listen
that the team, 4-12 last season, would stink again this year.
</P>
<P>
   A Cardinals official watched in amazement as the bar patrons
shouted down the skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They jumped on him and said how good the Cardinals are going
to be,'' the team official said. ``I've never seen that happen
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals fever, catch it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a 14-year veteran offensive tackle buying season tickets
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Lomas Brown, a seven-time Pro Bowl selection, picked up his five
season tickets, four in the loge section, Wednesday before he drove
up the mountain for today's start of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first time buying tickets,'' Brown said after arriving
in Flagstaff. ``I haven't been this excited in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Eric Swann also has the spirit. He bought two
season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Swann can afford it. He signed a five-year, $25 million contract
in the off-season that included a $7.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth, the team's unsigned
first-round draft pick, might get even a bigger bonus than Swann.
That's because former Michigan cornerback Charles Woodson received
an $8 million signing bonus when he signed with the Oakland Raiders
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Swann said he didn't care whether Wadsworth gets the biggest
signing bonus in team history.
</P>
<P>
   This is Camp Happy. The more money, the merrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry about that,'' Swann said. ``To me, that's
immature. You have to be happy with what you can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see my dimples and smiles all year long. I'm happy with
my contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimism abounds. Swann said that everywhere he has gone in the
Valley during the off-season, fans are talking about the new and
improved team.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are excited because they like what the organization is
doing _ the trades, the free agents, shuffling in the draft to get
good players and another great pick (from San Diego) next year,''
Swann said. ``Fans see that these are smart moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's edition of ``The Sporting News'' ranked the
Cardinals as having the best off-season in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, vice president of player personnel, is credited
for many of the moves.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, who helped build Super Bowl teams at Buffalo and
Denver, said he knows there is great anticipation going into this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go,'' Ferguson said. ``Unfortunately, I'm too old
and too fat to put on pads. We have got to finish what we started.
. . . We've got to finish these games and show we know how to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals suffered their first four losses a year ago by a
total of 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Arizona State product Jake Plummer became
the starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been here, the fans never have really liked the
(starting) quarterback,'' said outside linebacker Jamir Miller, the
fifth-year pro. ``Now they have Jake, whom they love. They feel
we're finally getting over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Beyer, who manages the Sportsfan sporting goods store in
the Arizona Center, said Plummer mania is infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a quarterback who only played a half a year, we just sold
our last authentic (Plummer) jersey,'' he said. ``We have replicas.
It's the most popular jersey of any NFL player in stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyer said store patrons are excited about the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been (in the Valley) for 10 years and always have seen
the darkness lurking behind the team's brightest moments,'' he
said. ``The only other time people were this excited was Buddy
Ryan's first year (1994). He fell flat on his face and then people
turned on them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan didn't have Plummer, who set most of the team's rookie
quarterback records last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe expectations are a little too high,'' said Greg Gennaro,
who runs Diamond Cleaners in Tempe, only a few blocks away from the
team's training facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, absolutely, people are excited. I've heard so many
positive things. People like the draft and feel Jake Plummer is the
one to get them over the top.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
