<HEADLINE>
CARDS LOSE VET ERAN SAFETY MALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 and STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ The Cardinals had been riding a wave of
optimism and good fortune through the off-season. And then reality
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as players reported for training camp, they got a
nasty surprise when safety Van Malone, a starter for the Detroit
Lions last year, failed his physical because of a hip injury. He
was released.
</P>
<P>
   With Brent Alexander and Matt Darby, the Cardinals' starting
safeties the past two seasons, gone, Malone was being counted upon
to contend for a starting position.
</P>
<P>
   Malone suffered abdominal injuries at Detroit, but when the
Cardinals signed him, he was healthy and set to play. He
participated in the team's minicamp and veterans camp in May. But
according to team officials, he suffered the hip injury in an
off-season workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we kind of anticipated the past couple of
weeks,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``It never got any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone was to receive $397,000 on a make-good contract with no
signing bonus, so the Cardinals will suffer no salary cap
repercussions by letting him go.
</P>
<P>
   But the stunning news leaves the team scrambling at a position
that already was of prime concern. Kwamie Lassiter, who played
sparingly during his first three seasons with the Cardinals, signed
his one-year contract Wednesday and now is the projected starting
free safety. He would be backed by Kenny Harris, who made the team
as an undrafted rookie last year, and rookie Pat Tillman, a
seventh-round pick from Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter has played mostly on special teams and in nickel and
dime coverages. Harris played primarily on special teams the final
11 games after spending the first five on the practice squad.
Tillman is making the switch from linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders at strong safety are Tommy Bennett and rookie
Corey Chavous, who as of Wednesday night had not signed his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   In Tobin's defense, the safety positions are nearly
interchangeable, so there could be switching in the wake of the
Malone news. The club likely will shop for a veteran safety. Among
those unsigned and available are Darby, Chris Shelling, David
Hendrix and Brian Walker. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
