<HEADLINE>
COYOTES BOLSTER DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes added another free-agent defenseman
Wednesday, signing New Jersey Devils' farmhand Bryan Helmer to a
multiyear contract.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but sources said Helmer
agreed to a two-year deal that will pay him $350,000 in 1999-2000
on a one-way, NHL contract. Helmer will play on a two-way contract
next season, meaning his salary stands to be considerably less if
he plays in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to signing Helmer, the Coyotes announced later in
the day that they re-signed restricted free agent defenseman Sean
Gagnon to a one-year contract after the Dallas Stars surprisingly
had signed the minor-league, penalty-minute king to a $350,000
offer sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix immediately matched it. And the Coyotes General Manager
Bobby Smith raised the ante by accusing the Stars of improperly
driving up the cost of the unproven enforcer whom the Coyotes
planned to sign anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bewildered,'' Smith said. ``And I really don't appreciate
other teams trying to dictate our salary structure when they know
they have no chance of signing the player. It's absurd, and I'm not
very happy about it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 210-pound Gagnon, one of the busiest fighters in
the minors, probably could have been re-signed by Phoenix for less
than $200,000 on a two-way contract. He led the Coyotes' AHL
affiliate in Springfield last season with 330 penalty minutes. The
year before, he led the International Hockey League with 457
minutes in just 57 games for the Fort Wayne Komets.
</P>
<P>
   Helmer, 26, has spent the past five seasons in the American
Hockey League with the Albany River Rats. Last season, he finished
third on the team in scoring and led all Albany defensemen with a
career-high 14 goals, 49 assists and 63 points. He also had 101
penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Listed at 6-foot-1, 200 pounds, Helmer was named a first-team
AHL All-Star. He recorded 189 points and 422 penalty minutes during
his career with the River Rats.
</P>
<P>
   Helmer, a native of Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario, has never
appeared in an NHL game but likely will battle prospects Jason Doig
and Deron Quint for a roster spot when the Coyotes open training
camp in early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, he'll push for a spot with us,'' Coyotes assistant
general manager Taylor Burke said. ``He's been buried in a very
deep organization, defensively. But we're trying to bring in guys
who can compete for the last couple spots on the NHL roster, and we
think this guy definitely can. We're pretty solid with our top five
(defensemen), but beyond that, we're going to have some
competition, and this guy will be right in that mix.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments, Smith has talked with the agent for
goalie Bob Essensa regarding a possible backup job to Nikolai
Khabibulin. Essensa, 33, has spent the past two seasons with the
Edmonton Oilers after playing his first six NHL seasons with the
Winnipeg Jets. He is an unrestricted free agent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
