<HEADLINE>
STAND TALL, WORLD CUP PLAYER TELLS YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Eddie Pope's message was short and direct: Be proud to
be an American soccer player.
</P>
<P>
   Pope was the keynote speaker at the Snickers US Youth Soccer
National Championship players' luncheon Wednesday. He is one of the
first graduates of the US Youth Soccer Association to make the big
time. The 1997 Player of the Year competed in World Cup '98, has
helped D.C. United to back-to-back Major League Soccer titles and
played in the '96 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the top young defenders in the world, Pope could
follow some of his fellow American stars and take his game abroad.
But the North Carolina native prefers to be a part of the growth of
soccer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players represent the best in American soccer,'' Pope
said after the luncheon. ``All they have to do is believe in
themselves and believe in American soccer. If we're ever to gain
respect in the world, it has to start right here in the United
States and with each individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the message I wanted to get across to these players,
because that's the message I would have wanted someone to tell me
when I was in their position.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pope, 24, is looking toward the future, he said the memory
of the national team's poor showing in World Cup '98 last month
will not soon go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of dissension that hurt the morale of the
team,'' Pope said, referring to the disputes between some players
and Coach Steve Sampson. ``It was disappointing for players and
coaches to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was also disappointing that we didn't play to our
potential. I remember watching the U.S. team in the '94 World Cup
and being so proud of what they accomplished. We all worked so hard
to try to be a part of that but just didn't get it done.'' &QL; 
Arizona's finest &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cisco Flames, Arizona's representative in the nationals,
will take on the Dallas Texans Red in the U-19 boys semifinals at
7:30 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the final four, motivation is so important,''
said Petar Draksin, head trainer for the Cisco Soccer Club.
``Playing at home in front of friends and family means so much to
these kids, and I hope that gives us an edge. It's very special to
play at home for a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (Coach) Willie Watson (Tuesday night) and he said
the kids have their game faces on, they're ready, having fun and
are just very upbeat.'' &QL; 
Staying home &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The San Bernardino Blast, which won the Far West Regionals U-17
boys title in Albuquerque last month, has been disqualified from
the national championships.
</P>
<P>
   A San Bernardino player was given a red card during the final of
the CalSouth State Cup, making him ineligible for the first match
of the regionals. Because of a paperwork snafu, the player competed
in each game of the regionals, and the mix-up wasn't detected until
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The San Juan Arsenal of CalNorth, which lost to San Bernardino,
2-1, in the regional title game, will replace the Blast in the
nationals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
