<SLUG> BC-SOC-SNICKERS-MERCURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD STRAIGHT CHAMPIONSHIP MOTIVATION ENOUGH FOR SQUAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Although the Central Valley Mercury breezed through
the Far West Regionals in Albuquerque last month, outscoring their
opponents, 41-1, the San Jose-based team didn't achieve all its
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury didn't score off a corner kick in its 8-1 victory
over Colorado Littleton United in the U-18 girls regional
championship match.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can't win 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury's dominance in girls soccer is such that at times,
Coach Vicki Wagner must find ways to challenge her players, give
them incentive beyond merely winning matches.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when you've won two straight national championships,
when you're 85-0-1 the past two years and when you haven't lost
since the start of the 1995-96 season, staying motivated can be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set specific goals each game, like scoring off a header,''
Wagner said. ``We try to give the girls a challenge like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to set such goals for this week's Snickers US
Youth Soccer National Championships at the Rose Mofford Sports
Complex in Phoenix. Winning an unprecedented third consecutive
national title is challenging enough.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the Mercury will have to compete without star
player Alyson Wagner. The coach's daughter suffered a torn anterior
cruciate ligament in her left knee on July 6 during a workout with
the U-20 U.S. national team in Portland. The injury will force
Alyson to redshirt next season at Santa Clara University.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was pretty much devastated,'' Vickie Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Alyson's second ACL injury; she injured her right knee in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's our quarterback, so we'll have to make some
adjustments,'' Wagner said. ``The team has played without her
before (in the 1996 regionals) and I have every confidence that
they'll be up to the task this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Alyson, the Gatorade National Player of the Year and ``Parade''
Co-Player of the Year, will be missed, but this is a team loaded
with talent. Anna Kraus and Danielle Slaton also are on the U-20
national team and were joined by Krista Boling on the ``Parade''
All-America team. Thirteen of the 17 players will compete for
Division I colleges in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really fortunate,'' Wagner said. ``Most of time at this
age when players have college commitments, they don't come to
practices. We don't have that problem. We have a tremendous
commitment from the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation of the team was laid nearly 10 years ago. Alyson
Wagner, Krista Boling and her twin, Breana, and Anne Griffith
started playing together at age 8. Three more current Mercury
players joined the team at the U-12 level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one by one, kids trickled onto the team and we've had
very little turnover,'' Vicki Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't recruit,'' she added, ``because it's illegal
where we come from and we don't have to. We just hope they
recognize we have a good program, and then they will come to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner has had players come to her since she started coaching
her daughter 13 years ago. She knows she has something special in
the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most gratifying thing is to see the response and
reaction from coaches across the country who watch the girls
play,'' Wagner said. ``I had one prominent coach tell me that if
these girls had been recruited as a team by one college, they would
finish in the top 10 in the country as freshmen and win it all as
seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury players are looking forward to doing something no
team has ever done.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are excited,'' Wagner said. ``They would really like to
be the first team to win nationals a third time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
