<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX WILT LATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ It's a loser's lament to blame a game on an umpire's
call. More so a one-run game in which the losing team has three
baserunners thrown out at the plate and has its best two hitters at
the plate with the bases loaded in the ninth inning and fails to
score.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also an unprecedented event when Nomar Garciaparra is
the one pointing the finger.
</P>
<P>
   In a clubhouse that was seething from the manager's office to
the locker of losing pitcher Rich Garces to the cubicle where
Garciaparra silently dressed, the shortstop expressed the
frustration the Red Sox felt after Wednesday night's 4-3 loss to
the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad,'' Garciaparra said, ``when your pitchers
come in and do their job and you've got to lose on a bad call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad when your catcher isn't even worried about
the guy running because he's running into the dugout on the third
strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was referring to the seventh inning, when plate
umpire Larry McCoy looked at a 1-and-2 fastball that Garces threw
to Indians strongman Jim Thome and called it a ball. A couple of
pitches later, Garces threw a lollipop changeup that Thome hit into
the center-field seats for a two-run homer that wiped out a 3-2 Sox
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strikeout _ you can see it on the video,'' said El
Guapo, who had not surrendered a homer to a lefthanded hitter all
season but probably wouldn't have been in the game if Jim Corsi
hadn't slipped in the shower and sprained his right wrist, an
injury that put him on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch was right there. It wasn't even middle in. It was
right there. What can you do? There's no consistency. Sometimes
it's a strike, sometimes it isn't. I don't understand it. It's out
of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome's home run brought a crashing end to a 2-4 trip in which
the Sox lost two of three to both the Tigers and Indians, with a
four-game showdown against the Toronto Blue Jays in Fenway Park on
deck.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had a chance to tie in the ninth when Mike Benjamin
opened with a bloop single and dashed to third on Midre Cummings's
single to center. But Benjamin was cut down at the plate on a
tapper to the mound, just as Cummings had been thrown out at the
plate on another chopper to the pitcher in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   After reliever Mike Jackson walked Darren Bragg to load the
bases, he retired Garciaparra on a soft liner to Thome that came
within inches of clearing the leap of the 6-foot-4-inch first
baseman, about the same distance by which Garciaparra's
third-inning triple missed being a homer.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson then ended the game by striking out Mo Vaughn, whom he
induced to chase a full-count fastball out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to get the game tied,'' said Cummings,
who had swung at a pitchout and reached on catcher's interference
in the fifth, when the Sox scored twice, then singled home their
third run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't ask for a better situation than Nomar and Mo
coming up. But you live with your guns and die with your guns.
That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he wasn't going to die with his gun unholstered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got me,'' Vaughn said. ``You know I'm going to be
aggressive in that situation. He threw a ball at the top of the
zone. It was ball four. But I'm not going to strike out looking. I
can't look for the perfect pitch. He isn't going to let me beat him
in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss spoiled what had been a superb emergency start by John
Wasdin, who has been demoted twice this spring but allowed just a
run in 5 1/3 innings upon his recall, which may be a brief one.
</P>
<P>
   The early line on this game was that it would qualify as a
future episode of ``Home Run Derby.'' Former University of
Connecticut star Charles Nagy had given up more home runs than any
other pitcher in baseball (27), while Wasdin's homer-to-innings
ratio (1 for every 5.5 innings) was just a hair better than Nagy's
(1 per 4.7).
</P>
<P>
   When Brian Giles took Wasdin deep to give the Indians a 1-0 lead
in the second inning with his 13th home run, it appeared form would
hold.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the only hint of long ball in the early going,
although Garciaparra just missed leaving the building when his
third-inning triple hit inches below the yellow line at the top of
the left-field fence. All was quiet on the homer front until Thome
connected, capping an inning that began with Cleveland trailing,
3-1. But Pat Borders doubled and eventually scored on an Omar
Vizquel sacrifice fly, and David Justice, the last batter faced by
Derek Lowe, singled with two out, setting the stage for
Garces-Thome.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin, whose last demotion came July 4 to make room for
Thursday night's starter, Korean Jin Ho Cho, shrugged when asked if
he expected to be around long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' he said. ``I don't know. Only time will tell.
I'll just try to make every day count. Whatever happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
