<HEADLINE>
SPARKS NEARING ANOTHER SHAKE-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Yes, the Mercury is 1-5 against other likely WNBA
playoff teams. Starting shooting guard Bridget Pettis averaged only
8.8 points in the just-completed homestand. And starting power
forward Toni Foster has been on the injured list for almost a month
because of a stress fracture in her right leg.
</P>
<P>
   But Phoenix's problems are minuscule compared with those of the
Los Angeles Sparks, stumbling toward an organizational shake-up
even larger than the one that claimed Coach Linda Sharp 11 games
into last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were 4-7 then, en route to a 5-10 start before
scrambling to .500 (14-14) and almost catching the Mercury for the
Western Conference title. Going into tonight's game against the
Mercury (12-5) at the Great Western Forum, LA is 5-11, putting the
future of not only Coach Julie Rousseau but General Manager Rhonda
Windham in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller said last year that her former
Southern California teammate, Windham, not her former USC coach,
Sharp, was to blame for personnel decisions that handicapped Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Windham also promoted Rousseau, whose previous coaching
experience was at the high school level, from assistant to interim
head coach before deciding to retain her for this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks still are only three games behind Cleveland (9-8) in
the loss column for the fourth and final playoff berth, but they
also must haul down New York (10-9) and Detroit (10-9) to achieve
that.
</P>
<P>
   With small forward Allison Feaster (fractured foot) and backup
center Haixia Zheng (knee surgery) on the injured list, the odds
that the Sparks will go on a major roll in their final 14 games are
slim.
</P>
<P>
   Barring that, Windham and Rousseau could be fired at season's
end so the Sparks can call on the elite women's college coaches to
turn their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate concern is starting center Lisa Leslie, who
missed practice Wednesday to be evaluated for wrist, groin and knee
injuries. She is probable for tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Leslie has a league-high 10 double-doubles in what
sometimes seems like a single-handed effort to keep Los Angeles
afloat. She almost compiled another (24 points, 9 rebounds) Tuesday
in a 92-77 loss to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie leads the WNBA in rebounding (10.2 average) and is tied
for second in scoring (19.1) with the Mercury's Jennifer Gillom,
who is fifth on the boards (7.2) and has four double-doubles.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury, playing on the road for the first time in 15 days,
is excited about the change of scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to getting on the road,'' point guard
Michele Timms said. ``We had six games at home, and we had a lot of
things that needed to be worked through. I think we're ready to
take the next step and beat teams on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix plays four straight and nine of its final 13 away from
America West Arena, including a July 31 encounter against the
Sparks and two games (Tuesday and Aug. 6) against league champion
Houston. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
