<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BOWHUNTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWS AND GIRLS, IT'S A HAPPENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. - This was competitive archery, but all that could
be heard was talking and laughing. The five women strode through
the forest with their bows, conversing and giggling like old
friends, stopping occasionally to unleash an arrow at a target with
their compound bows.
</P>
<P>
   It was about 10 a.m. Friday morning, the first day of the
three-day Bowhunter Happening at the Coconino Fairgrounds south of
here.
</P>
<P>
   The event has taken place for about 15 years. Sponsored by the
Arizona Bowhunters Association, it began with a few and has
increased to multitudes. The organization now contends that it is
the largest family-oriented archery event in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It draws about 2,000 shooters, and once families are included,
an estimated 12,000 to 15,000 people experience the Happening.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing is that only about 300 of the registered
shooters come for competition. The rest take part in
non-competitive target practice.
</P>
<P>
   All the targets are three-dimensional, meaning they are
foam-made, full-bodied animals _ everything from bears to turkeys
to deer. The various 20-target ranges are laid out in stations back
in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Adult archers stand near one marker to shoot at the target.
Young archers have a closer marker. Shooters might be looking down
at a target through a clump of trees or up through the rocks at
another.
</P>
<P>
   Each station has its own challenges. The five women are
competitive archers. They're out to win but insist on having fun
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cerreta of Glendale has made most every Bowhunter Happening
but has yet to shoot. That's because he spends his time helping
supervise the archers. Those involved in staging the event take
great pride in making it extremely successful.
</P>
<P>
   Among the competitive archers, he said, women and children have
the most fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women, especially, will laugh when they miss,'' Cerreta
said. ``The men cringe. They're much more intense. That's why you
see more women and kids than men.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the five women is Hope Hewitt of Prescott Valley. This is
her second year of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is an archer, and my daughter has been shooting for
about 10 years,'' she said. ``I decided it was time for me to get
involved. Archery is a family thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The women joke as they make the rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been a man who set up these kills,'' said one,
referring to the difficulty of some targets.
</P>
<P>
   Another hit low on a standing bear target and worried if she had
``ruined its manhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Harris of Flagstaff said she'd been shooting for about
18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started going out with friends that shoot,'' she said. ``I
would walk around with them and keep score. But, naturally, I got
the fever and started shooting with them.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether she hunted, too, Tish Harper of Tucson said
she did, ``but all we eat is foam game,'' referring to the targets.
</P>
<P>
   For both men and women, the sophisticated compound bows were
predominant because of their sights, long distance and great
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   But John Gordon of Kingman was competing in a class with a
traditional bow. He had trouble hitting the longer targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' he said. ``A traditional bow is more fun.
Besides that, you can build your own. I built this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the courses for competitors and practice shooters, the
Happening also offers a free course for the little ones.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 wee shooters usually go through that course,
according to Paul Line and Bill Loughrey, both of Mesa, who run it
each year.
</P>
<P>
   The course offers free T-shirts to the kids and loaner bows and
arrows to participants who don't have their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the same targets the big guys have,'' Loughrey said
of the foam animals. ``Some people who don't shoot just come out
here to have a picnic and let their kids shoot on the range.''
</P>
<P>
   They are particularly proud of a shoot for handicapped children
on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But this is much more than a shoot. It is an event. Three
buildings house vendor booths. Another archery company has a
tractor trailer than converts into an archery store.
</P>
<P>
   Food vendors feed the hungry crowds. There are varmint, elk and
turkey calling contests.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the world aerial championships, where competitors
from large to small use short-distance arrows to shoot at
Frisbee-like targets in the air. It's like a trap shoot, only with
bows.
</P>
<P>
   And wherever you look, there are families _ some carrying bows,
some just looking around.
</P>
<P>
   For some participants, it's a chance to hone their hunting
skills. For others, it's just a chance to shoot at targets or just
be with their families. For all, it's one of the biggest,
most-enjoyable outdoor events in the state. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
