<HEADER>
A8665 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     07-23 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT ASTROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers traded for Brian Bohanon because he
showed flashes of brilliance as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday night, they finally saw those flashes work to
their benefit as the left-hander earned his first win with the club
_ a 6-4 victory over the Houston Astros in front of 31,365 at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who also had three home runs in the victory,
increased their winning streak to three games. The Dodgers, who
stayed 4{ games behind the Chicago Cubs in the wild card race, have
a chance tonight to earn a four-game win streak for the first time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   After going 0-2 with a 4.66 ERA during his first two starts with
the Dodgers, Bohanon (3-6) stymied the Astros by allowing just one
run on two hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon was acquired in a trade with the New York Mets on July
10 for right-hander Greg McMichael. Although he spent most of his
career as a reliever, the Dodgers' new fifth starter showed promise
as a starter and was 1-1 with a 3.00 ERA in that role with the Mets
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing the game, Bohanon opened some eyes by allowing
just one earned run _ a Mark McGwire home run _ on two hits in 52/3
innings during his previous start at St. Louis on July 17. And
after a tough first inning, Bohanon went on to dominate the Astros
and surely make interim general manager Tommy Lasorda proud about
making the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon's start was rough, as Bill Spiers _ who walked _ scored
on a one-out double by Derek Bell that gave the Astros a 1-0 lead
in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the first, usual Dodger reserve Wilton Guerrero showed
some hustle by earning an infield single off Houston start Jose
Lima (8-6). And in the third, he showed the same grit by getting a
leadoff double after hitting a ball to the gap in left-center and
advancing to third after Bell bobbled the ball. Guerrero then tied
the game at 1-1 after Juan Castro's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from Guerrero, Raul Mondesi used the same
enthusiasm after he followed Castro with a single. Mondesi went on
to steal second and then raced to third after Brad Ausmus' bad and
low throw ended up in center field. With two outs, Eric Karros gave
the Dodgers a 2-1 lead when he brought in Mondesi with an RBI
single.
</P>
<P>
   After using so much energy to score runs, the Dodgers made it a
little simpler with the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Charles Johnson hit a ball by the shallow
left-field foul line and watched Houston third baseman Spiers and
shortstop Ricky Gutierrez run into each other as the ball drop
fair. After the ball dropped, Johnson was booed by the fans since
he barely made it safe at first in time.
</P>
<P>
   Those jeers, however, turned to cheers when Johnson hit his 14th
home run of the season off Lima with one out to give the Dodgers a
3-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the Dodgers battered Lima with the long ball again
with back-to-back home runs from Gary Sheffield and Karros that
pushed their club ahead 5-1. Sheffield's 18th home run came on a
two-out 0-1 pitch from Lima that landed in the right field
bleachers. And Karros followed on the next pitch with home run
No.11 that landed in the left field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back home runs marked just the second time that the
Dodgers accomplished that feat this season. The only other
occurrence came during the Dodgers' home opener on April 7, when
Todd Hollandsworth and Thomas Howard hit back-to-back home runs
against Arizona in the fifth inning. Hollandsworth is out for the
season with a left shoulder cartilage tear, and Howard was
designated for assignment on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   After being up 5-2 in the seventh, the Dodgers went back up by
four when Karros hit a two-out RBI double to left-center that
scored a racing Mondesi from first base. Karros, who entered the
game batting .342 with three home runs with runners in scoring
position, batted 3 for 4 with a home run and three RBI.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw ended a scoreless streak
by allowing a solo home run to Everett that cut Houston's deficit
to 6-4. Shaw, however, recovered to earn his 28th save by striking
out the next three Astros.
</P>
</TEXT>
