<HEADLINE>
RANDY JOHNSON OFF THE MARK AS TAMPA BEATS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ If, by chance, this was the last pitching
appearance by Randy Johnson in a Mariner uniform, it will be
remembered a lot like his final season for Seattle _ enigmatic,
edgy and ultimately unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   In a game that called to mind too many other Mariner games this
year, the M's lost to expansion Tampa Bay here Wednesday night,
7-5, despite having their best pitcher on the mound and having
disposed of the Devil Rays' All-Star right-hander, Rolando Arrojo.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, continually the subject of trade rumors even as the
club says it won't happen, wasn't especially lucky in the four-run
seventh inning that beat him. But then, he wasn't especially heady,
either.His eighth error of the season made all four runs unearned
and tagged the M's with a giveaway loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it be concentration?'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella
asked pregnantly, in reference to Johnson's unusually high error
total.
</P>
<P>
   To the suggestion that this was the first time in a while the
M's had reverted to their altruistic, throw-it-away days, Piniella
paused long and said, ``Yeah. It might not be the last.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss didn't cost the M's anything in the standings, with
Texas' loss to Kansas City leaving Seattle 9{ back in the American
League West. But the onus is on the pursuers, and now the Mariners
begin a demanding 11-game stretch against red-hot Baltimore and two
division leaders, Cleveland and New York, one that could
conceivably destroy their fragile playoff candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets draining,'' sighed John Marzano, the catcher,
referring to five unearned runs, ``because we've seen it all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This was going to be an enticing pitching matchup, Johnson
having thrown two straight shutouts and Arroyo, with 11 victories
and a 2.87 earned-run average, one of the best young prospects in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Neither guy had his ``A'' material.
</P>
<P>
   ``His location was off tonight,'' said Marzano, talking for
Johnson, who hasn't spoken publicly for weeks. ``He missed a lot of
spots tonight. If you see the replay on TV, if I set up inside,
he'd throw the ball outside _ and did for a couple of innings
straight. He hasn't been like that the previous five starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Johnson on an off-night is sometimes good enough. And
when the M's tore into Arrojo for a pair of two-out, two-run homers
by Marzano and Alex Rodriguez in the sixth inning, it gave Seattle
a 5-3 lead that looked promising.
</P>
<P>
   But then luck, location and wits all deserted Johnson in the
seventh. On an 0-2 pitch to Quentin McCracken leading off, Johnson
got the ball up and McCracken doubled to right. Then Mike Kelly
sent a checked-swing bouncer back to Johnson, who spotted McCracken
roaming dangerously far off second.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, pitching coach Stan Williams talked about how
young pitchers will try to save one run and in the process give up
three. In this case, it was a 10-year veteran doing that and giving
up four.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to first with the ball, and get the out,'' said
Piniella. ``We work our way out of that inning.''
</P>
<P>
   A good throw from Johnson to shortstop Alex Rodriguez probably
gets McCracken. But with Rodriguez on the move toward second for
the throw, Johnson heaved it high to the shortstop side for an
error that opened the gates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he had enough to punch out John Flaherty and Paul
Sorrento with crackling fastballs, and he was on the verge of a
third straight against leadoff hitter Randy Winn.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson came inside on Winn, and second baseman Joey Cora, who
had already made another inscrutable throwing error, took a step
toward second, perhaps anticipating that the ball would be hit to
his right. Instead, Winn fought it off, chopped it to right and the
run-scoring hit made it 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see Cora anywhere near it,'' said Winn. ``He probably
thought I'd pull it or hit it up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sustained, the Rays struck for two more hits and three more
runs. Miguel Cairo tied the game with a bouncer that Rico Rossy
couldn't glove at third, and Bobby Smith hit the game-winner, a
two-run single through the shortstop hole.
</P>
<P>
   It was all a little galling for the M's, who had trailed Arrojo
_ author of nothing but seven-inning performances or longer since
late in May _ 3-1 in the sixth before Marzano and Rodriguez
connected. It was Marzano's first homer of the year, eighth of his
career and only the second of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room, he would find it a mixed blessing, enduring
inferences from his buddy Ken Griffey Jr. that his bat was corked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' Griffey continued, referring to a Griffey-Marzano home
run entry, ``we got 41 now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the only light moment in the clubhouse. The M's now go on
to Baltimore for three games starting Friday night in search of
some more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
