<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERICKSON WILLING TO LISTEN, TRY `FRESH IDEAS' WITH SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ The Seahawks no longer wait until the end of
practice to drill the special teams. Someone learned a lesson last
year. Dennis Erickson understands he must expand his horizons and
bring in ``fresh ideas.'' Otherwise his job as coach of the
Seahawks will come to a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wait until the end of practice to work on special teams,
it's almost like it's punishment,'' Erickson said Wednesday about
the new approach to one of the Seahawks' most glaring flaws last
season.
</P>
<P>
   As Erickson leads the Hawks through his fourth camp, he has
taken the advice of his new assistant head coach, Pete Rodriguez.
Special teams matter. Changes were necessary. Erickson had to open
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodriguez has his approach to the special teams at practice,
which is to work in the middle, with the whole team there, which I
haven't been around before. So that will help,'' Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about it, you learn every year. I think
the guys who have been in the league 20 years learn something new
all the time. Fresh ideas come in. Sometimes when you have a
coaching change, you don't like to have them because you like
continuity, but you bring new guys in. And all of a sudden there's
fresh ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Erickson has prized loyalty in his coaching
ranks. Perhaps it was a product of his college breeding. During his
stint at the University of Miami, Erickson had to learn to watch
his back. One never knows which of his guys would turn around and
do anything to become The Guy.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, loyalty might have crushed Erickson's
chances to be a successful NFL coach last season. Granted, Erickson
is right to assert that it takes five years to rebuild a football
team, which is why he might have preferred an expansion franchise
for a better chance at instant success.
</P>
<P>
   And injuries were a big part of the problem last year, but even
that litany (only seven players started all 16 games) could not
cover up the glaring weaknesses and weak links in a coaching staff
that could not give the upgraded Seahawk talent the tools to win.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries did not cost the Seahawks a shellacking in the opener
to the Jets. Nor were they the reason the special teams cost the
Seahawks four wins.
</P>
<P>
   There were gaps in the defensive and offensive schemes the
coaching staff provided. Linebacker Chad Brown could not get a
scheme that would help him blitz, his trademark. Speedster Joey
Galloway, promised again and again that he would get the ball more
often, was hardly exploited.
</P>
<P>
   It was critical for Erickson and the Seahawks to remedy these
problems, immediately, or risk knowing that all the big-money
talent that the Hawks have signed could go unused.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the amount of injuries we had last year, it basically
derailed our season, so it was tough,'' Brown said about Erickson's
growth as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a college coach, you've got 100 guys on your team. You
play maybe 11 or 12 games. We (in the pro game) have 45 guys and if
you go to the Super Bowl, you play 25 games. So you have to
approach things differently from a training camp perspective to
practice perspective. He's learned to ask guys like (free agent
veteran) Brian Habib: `What did you guys do in Denver? How were you
guys successful?' So (Erickson's) learning and we appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Seahawks president Bob Whitsitt searched for a big-name
general manager in the offseason, the contracts of many of the
assistant coaches were allowed to expire. As some of those
assistants decided to take jobs elsewhere, Erickson was forced to
interview new assistants, with an emphasis placed on coaches with a
ton of NFL experience.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Rodriguez, an 11-year veteran with successful stints
in Oakland, Washington and Phoenix, Erickson's other major hire was
linebackers coach Jim Johnson, a 13-year veteran who was the
defensive coordinator with the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   The players were eager for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I don't think we had anyone on staff who was really
familiar with all the zone blitz stuff,'' said Brown, the former
AFC linebacker of the year who wants to get back to quarterback
attacks, which is how he made his dominating mark with the
Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was very frustrating from the respect that I had one
or two blitzes, but after the third or fourth week of the season,
everyone was pretty much picking them up. This year, we'll probably
have some answers.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still a sense in camp that the talent on the team might
be ahead of the coaching staff's ability and vision to provide
meaningful preparation, winning schemes and adjustments. But better
pieces might now be in place, especially in the critical areas of
defense and special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win. I want to go to the playoffs. That's why I came
here. I signed a five-year contract. We need to get it done. We
need to get to the playoffs. That's where the pressure comes from.
And there's more because we're better,'' Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces are in place. All Erickson must do to deflate the
pressure is make sure they fit together and work.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
