<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT ASTROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UPDATES WITH QUOTES, DETAILS 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers traded for Brian Bohanon because he
showed flashes of brilliance as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday night, those flashes finally worked to their
benefit as the left-hander earned his first win with the Dodgers _
a 6-4 decision over the Houston Astros in front of 31,365 at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who had three home runs, won their third straight
for the first time since sweeping three at Texas from May 30-June
2. The Dodgers, who stayed 4{ games behind the Chicago Cubs in the
wild-card race, have a chance tonight to earn a four-game win
streak for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (52-49), who haven't been three games over .500
since since May 3, and the Detroit Tigers are the only major-league
clubs that haven't won four straight this season.
</P>
<P>
   After going 0-2 with a 4.66 ERA during his first two starts with
the Dodgers, Bohanon (3-6) stymied the Astros by allowing just one
run on two hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just making good pitches to get out of innings, and I
ended up with the win,'' said Bohanon, who snapped a career-high
losing streak at three games.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon was acquired in a trade with the New York Mets on July
10 for right-hander Greg McMichael. Although he spent most of his
career as a reliever, the Dodgers' new fifth starter was 1-1 with a
3.00 ERA in that role with the Mets this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon opened some eyes by allowing just one earned run _ a
511-foot Mark McGwire home run _ on two hits in 52/3 innings during
a loss in his previous start at St. Louis on Friday. He got in
trouble early this game, as Bill Spiers scored from first on a
one-out double by Derek Bell that gave the Astros a 1-0 lead in the
first inning. But that would be all the damage that Bohanon would
endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bohanon) pitched well tonight,'' said Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman. ``He is a strong competitor, and that is what I like to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon said, ``I felt like I threw the ball well the last time
out, and I did again tonight. Hopefully, it will continue for a few
games.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Wilton Guerrero, usually a reserve, hustled
to third base after his leadoff double was bobbled by Bell. He
scored on Juan Castro's sacrifice fly, tying the score at 1.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi followed Castro with a single. He stole second and
raced to third when catcher Brad Ausmus' low throw ended up in
center field. With two outs, Eric Karros gave the Dodgers a 2-1
lead with an RBI single that scored Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   After using so much energy to score runs, the Dodgers made it a
little simpler with the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson hit his 14th home run of the season off Jose
Lima in the fourth to give the Dodgers a 3-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the Dodgers battered Lima again with back-to-back,
two-out home runs from Gary Sheffield and Karros for a 5-1 lead.
Sheffield's 18th home run came on a 0-1 pitch from Lima that landed
in the right-field bleachers. Karros followed on the next pitch
with his 11th home run.
</P>
<P>
   The only other time the Dodgers hit back-to-back home runs this
season was April 7, when Todd Hollandsworth and Thomas Howard did
it against Arizona in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sucked tonight,'' said the loser Lima (8-6), who is 0-3
against the Dodgers this season. ``I left the ball up and got
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who hit an RBI double in seventh to put the Dodgers up
6-2, went 3 for 4 with a home run and three RBI.
</P>
<P>
   On his first pitch in the ninth, Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw ended
a scoreless streak of 14 innings by allowing a Carl Everett solo
home run that cut Houston's deficit to 6-4. But he recovered to
earn his 28th save by striking out the next three Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club is playing pretty well,'' said Shaw. ``Hopefully, we
can keep it going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
