<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE KEPT QUIET, BUT GIANTS FALL AGAIN 
BY HENRY SCHULMAN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Those among the 40,147 who paid good money to
see Mark McGwire hit a tape-measure home run Wednesday night left
3Com Park unhappy. Now, those who showed up to see Gary Gaetti hit
one of his patented opposite-field homers that scrape the back of
the outfield fence had a night of sheer ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   As for those who came to see the Giants win, well, if they have
paid attention for the past two weeks, their expectations were
probably not high to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' second-half tumble reached 2-10 with Wednesday
night's 3-2 loss to the St. Louis Cardinals. Mark McGwire (0-for-4,
including a double-play grounder) was not the story. The Giants'
inability to score more than twice against the normally generous
Redbirds' pitching staff was.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat dropped the Giants a dirty dozen games behind the
first-place San Diego Padres in the National League West and 21/2
games behind the wild-card-leading Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to score some more runs,'' an exasperated Giants
manager Dusty Baker said. ``I know everyone is trying exceptionally
hard, maybe too hard. Everybody just has to relax. Everybody wants
to be the one to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' brass was so concerned after last night's defeat
that general manager Brian Sabean called a half-dozen veteran
player into Baker's office for a lengthy meeting long after the
final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good,'' said center fielder Darryl Hamilton. ``They
just asked us what was going on and what we thought the team needed
to do. It shows what kind of organization we're dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Sabean did not leave the clubhouse until close to
midnight, even though they had to return for a 12:35 p.m. game
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have scored 42 runs in the 12 games since the break,
an average of 3.5 per game, which has not been enough to back an
injury-weakened pitching staff that is not performing as well as
did in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants actually got a fine start Wednesday night from Kirk
Rueter (10-6), who lasted seven innings for the first time since
May 31. But Gaetti's two-run homer in the second inning and Brian
Jordan's solo shot in the fourth were enough to doom Rueter to his
third straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   The gopher ball is becoming a problem for Rueter. He has thrown
15 in his past 16 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Gaetti hit a pretty good pitch. He went the other
way with it. I tip my hat to him,'' Rueter said. ``Jordan, I made a
mistake. He's a pretty good hitter, and he didn't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   All of St. Louis' scoring came on the two homers. Gaetti hit his
with one out in the second inning after Rueter walked the leadoff
man, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants tied the game with a two-out, two-run single by
Hamilton in the bottom of the second, their only run-producing hit
of the night. But Jordan gave St. Louis the lead for good when he
smacked Rueter's first pitch of the fourth inning, a changeup that
Jordan was expecting, over the bleachers in left for his 17th
homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many guys who can hit a first-pitch changeup out
of the park,'' said an admiring Cardinals manager Tony La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   Hitters on a lot of teams like to challenge each other on their
home-run numbers, but not on a team led by McGwire's 43.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an unfair contest. Mac would win hands down,''
Jordan said. ``He is a power hitter. Other guys on the team don't
say they're power hitters. I don't. If I hit a home run, I hit a
home run. I like to go for the gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   A guy with 17 homers in July is not a power hitter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say I was a  &LR; weak  &LR; hitter,'' Jordan said. ``Sometimes
I can power it up and hit it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants would love to power it up, too. They mustered just
three hits after the second inning against Bobby Witt, a Texas
castoff who had a 7.77 ERA when the Rangers dumped him last month,
and two relievers. La Russa was asked if he thought the Giants
looked flat.
</P>
<P>
   His answer: ``I saw a lot of good body life, a lot of good
at-bats. It's a long season. You have ups, you have downs. They
looked like they were going at it like they always do.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort may be there, but the results are not, which is
really all that matters. What will it take for the Giants to escape
the funk they are in?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get into a funk and you don't know why,'' Baker
said. ``If we could come up with a definition of `funk,' we'd know
how to cure it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
