</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPARD-OBIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAN SHEPARD, FIRST AMERICAN IN SPACE  
 BY MICHAEL TAYLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan B. Shepard Jr., one of the original astronauts who had
enough of the ``right stuff'' to become the first American in space
and the only man to play golf on the moon, died Tuesday night in a
hospital in Monterey, Calif. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Sen. John Glenn, an old friend of Shepard's from the days
when they were both Mercury Project astronauts, said Shepard, who
lived in Pebble Beach, died after a long battle with leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him not too long ago,'' Glenn said in Washington
Wednesday. ``He said he wasn't as strong as he used to be. He said
he was running about half throttle. He died in his sleep _ a good
way to go, I guess. He will truly be missed in a great way. He was
a close friend and a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said Shepard was intensely interested in Glenn's planned
flight this October on the space shuttle, when Glenn will be 77.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be there if he could, didn't know if he could,''
Glenn said. ``He was interested in some of the things I'd been
training on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an interest the two men shared for nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   On May 5, 1961 _ just three weeks after the Soviets had sent
cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin into a complete orbit of Earth _ Shepard, a
Navy commander at the time, rode a rocket that shot him and his
``Freedom 7'' Mercury capsule 116 miles straight up from Cape
Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's tiny capsule then hurled him downrange 302 miles and,
forever after, into the history books as an authentic American
hero, idolized by youngsters and envied by anyone who had ever
thought about flying off into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us who were alive then will ever forget him sitting so
calmly in Freedom 7 atop a slender and sometimes unreliable Mercury
Redstone rocket,'' President Clinton said Wednesday. ``Those of us
who are old enough to remember the first space flights will always
remember what an impression he made on us and on the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At NASA headquarters, Shepard's home for some 15 years as both
an astronaut and an executive, administrator Daniel Goldin said
Shepard's journey ``made a whole bunch of us engineers excited
about the space program. His flight was a tremendous statement
about tenacity, courage and brilliance.''
</P>
<P>
   That quarter of an hour in space came at a time when nearly
everything about space travel was exotic news. The journey
catapulted Shepard into a rarefied level of fame _ the flight was
watched live on television by millions of people, and after he
splashed down, he jubilantly radioed the world, ``Everything is
A-OK!'' thereby coining an indelible addition to American slang.
</P>
<P>
   After he was plucked from the Atlantic Ocean, Shepard was
honored with huge parades in New York, Los Angeles and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after Shepard's suborbital flight, President John F.
Kennedy, buoyed by the roaring success of Freedom 7, announced that
the United States ``should commit itself to achieving the goal,
before the decade is out, of landing a man on the moon and
returning him safely to Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal was met in July 1969, when Apollo 11 successfully put
Neil Armstrong on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, it was Shepard's turn _ at the age of 47, he
commanded the Apollo 14 mission and, after it landed, hauled out a
makeshift six-iron and whacked a few balls down what passes for a
green on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The moon landing was the culmination of a career that began on
the eve of World War II, when Shepard was accepted into the U.S.
Naval Academy at Annapolis. He graduated in 1944, and was
immediately commissioned an ensign and dispatched to the Pacific,
where he served out the last few months of the war on the destroyer
Cogswell.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Shepard desperately wanted to be a Navy pilot.
While training in Texas and Florida, he became so impatient that on
his own time and his own dime he took private flying lessons to
hurry the process along.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Shepard joined the Navy's Test Pilot School in Patuxent
River, Md., and soon was testing high-altitude planes and in-flight
refueling systems.
</P>
<P>
   When NASA's call went out in 1959 for volunteers in the manned
space flight program, Shepard leaped at the opportunity. He
competed against 109 other test pilots and in the end was one of
seven hotshots chosen for the Mercury Project, along with Glenn,
Scott Carpenter, Virgil (Gus) Grissom, Walter Schirra Jr., Donald
Slayton and L. Gordon Cooper. (Of those original seven, only Glenn,
Cooper, Carpenter and Schirra are still alive.)
</P>
<P>
   In April 1959, the space agency presented the astronauts to the
world at a big press conference. With Life magazine contracts and
the press constantly hovering, the Mercury 7 became America's most
celebrated heroes. Some 20 years later, they were immortalized in
Tom Wolfe's dead-on appreciation, ``The Right Stuff,'' and, four
years later, in the movie version of the book.
</P>
<P>
   The Right Stuff, as Wolfe defined it, was a combination of
outrageous cockiness, ambition, patriotism, a well-honed aversion
to bureaucracy and, by the way, no small measure of talent. The
original Mercury 7, if Wolfe got it right, had those qualities in
spades.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the epitome of `the Right Stuff,' however trite that
might sound,'' said Jack King, NASA public information officer for
Shepard's flight. ``He was a first-class guy, at times egotistical,
but first class.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Mercury flight, however, Shepard, eager to join the
Gemini program and, later, the Apollo missions, discovered that he
suffered from Meniere's syndrome, a devastating disease of the
inner ear that causes dizziness and loss of balance. He was taken
off space flight status and made chief of NASA's astronaut office,
where he spent his days watching others prepare for the moon
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Shepard refused to let his illness sidetrack him.
After six years of treatment, he was cured and NASA gave him the
A-OK to return to space flight.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, three years after his moon mission, Shepard retired
from the Navy, as a rear admiral, and also from NASA. Always known
as a tough and fearless competitor, he became a highly successful
businessman, buying a bank, developing real estate properties and
investing in quarterhorses and oil wells.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard is survived by his wife, Louise; his daughters Julie,
Laura and Alice; and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be private. The family suggests donations
to the Astronaut Scholarship Foundation, 6225 Vectorspace Blvd.,
Titusville, Fla., 32780.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle news services contributed to this report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
