<P>
   NEWS and FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2465 -- July 23, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. KEEPING THE BOOM FROM BUSTING U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin understands that what began as a devaluation in Thailand may
yet bring the U.S. economic boom to a close. He knows we're now
dealing with issues the world has never dealt with before. His
consistent approach to the Asian economic crisis has been : There
is something worse than Country X going down, which is Country X
going down and taking $10 billion in U.S. money along with it. By
Jacob Weisberg. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words. 2.
RADIATION AFTER LUNG CANCER SURGERY COULD DO MORE
</P>
<P>
   HARM THAN GOOD Patients who undergo radiation treatment after
surgery for the most common form of lung cancer may do worse than
patients who do not undergo post-operative radiation. A new study
has found that the risk of dying in the four years after surgery
was 21 per cent higher among those who had radiation treatment,
compared to those who had surgery alone. The cause of the deaths is
likely to be due to radiation-induced damage to healthy lung
tissue. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
GUARDIANS OF THE GOLDEN FLEECE Reviving a colourful Incan ritual,
Peruvian villagers rescue the vicuna from the brink of extinction
and begin cashing in on one of the world's most luxurious fibres.
By Jonathan Miller. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
THE LINE ON PHONE MANNERS Many people dislike and complain about
the aggressive and aggravating ways the telephone is used to
interrupt and annoy us at home and work. Yet it remains a fact,
writes Connon Barclay, that the phone does have potential for good
and decent work and even increased sales. 1,100 words
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
FIRST, DO NO HARM In the 1970's, neurosurgeons began performing a
brain operation designed to save lives. It actually risked them.
But no one bothered to determine that for 20 years. By Frank T.
Vertosick Jr. Discover magazine. 1,600 words + photos
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. FROM EUROP MAGAZINE :
</P>
