<HEADER>
A8949 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-VOUCHERS-NYTS     07-23 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-VOUCHERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN GIVES GO-AHEAD TO SCHOOL VOUCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    On June 10, Wisconsin's Supreme Court issued an historic
decision, the first in America by a high court, to permit state
funding of a voucher system enabling up to 15,700 low-income public
school students to attend religious schools.
 &HT;    By a 4-2 vote the court said the Milwaukee Parental Choice
Program does not violate either the First Amendment or the
Wisconsin Constitution's provisions prohibiting public funding of
religious schools.
 &HT;    Gov. Tommy Thompson, who pushed for the law, exulted:
``Religious values aren't our problem. Dropout rates and low test
scores are. This is not only going to allow for choice, but for
competition among schools -- public and private.''
 &HT;    Indeed, in Milwaukee Public Schools, fewer than 4 out of 10
graduate from high school, while 95 percent of students in Catholic
schools graduate.
 &HT;    The original version of the Choice law, passed in 1990, provided
state funding for 1,500 vouchers for students from low-income
families to attend private, non-religious schools in Milwaukee.
After five years, a Harvard study found those students' test scores
rose 3 to 5 percentage points higher in reading and 5 to 12 points
higher in math than students who wanted, but were unable to get,
the limited number of state scholarships.
 &HT;    These results are so significant that researchers predict that,
if applied nationally, the gap between white and minority student
test scores could narrow by 33 percent to 50 percent, according to
the 1998 edition of ''School Choice Programs'' published by the
Heritage Foundation.
 &HT;    Therefore, Wisconsin's legislature voted in 1995 to expand the
Choice program to include a tenth of Milwaukee's children, 15,700
of those from homes whose incomes were within 175 percent of the
poverty line, a figure that makes 65,000 to 70,000 Milwaukee kids
eligible.
 &HT;    Schools would be paid for their operating costs or the average
per-pupil school aid to the city's schools ($4,900 this year),
whichever is less.
 &HT;    In recent years, 20 Catholic elementary schools and six high
schools have had to close, due to falling enrollments. The diocese
hired Dan McKinley to help raise funds to keep schools open. But
few showed interest until he organized a group independent of the
diocese, known as PAVE, Partners Advancing Values in Education.
 &HT;    Suddenly, perhaps due to sympathy that the state subsidies could
only help kids attending non-parochial schools, he was able to
raise enough to give 1,900 scholarships in 1992-3 to children
attending not only 40 Catholic elementary and seven high schools,
but 28 Missouri Synod, four Jewish and three Muslim schools.
 &HT;    After the 1995 expansion of state vouchers was passed by the
Legislature, the ACLU and teacher unions filed a suit, blocking the
spending of any new money, one day before school started. Children
who had enrolled in the religious-based schools were suddenly
without support. PAVE was able to raise $1.6 million and give 50
percent scholarships to 2,000 students.
 &HT;    This year PAVE gave 4,400 scholarships worth $4.2 million,
underwriting a third of Catholic school students, with much of the
support coming from the business community.
 &HT;    The Wisconsin Supreme Court opinion was carefully written to be
able to meet criteria set down by the U.S. Supreme Court as to what
is constitutional in the separation of church and state.
Wisconsin's court said the Choice program does not violate the
First Amendment's ''Establishment clause because it has a secular
purpose, it will not have the primary effect of advancing religion
and it will not lead to excessive entanglement between the state
and participating sectarian schools.''
 &HT;    Why? Because decisions on whether children go to religious or
non-religious schools are left up to individual parents. The court
said, ''Wisconsin has traditionally accorded parents the primary
role in decision-making regarding the education and upbringing of
children.'' It quoted an 1899 Wisconsin Supreme Court decision
saying that parents have ''the most effective motivation'' and
''the strongest obligation'' to give their children ''nurture,
education and training.''
 &HT;    Therefore, parents should be trusted to be ''neutral between
sectarian and non-sectarian alternatives.'' The court added,
''Public funds generally may be provided to sectarian educational
institutions so long as steps are taken not to subsidize religious
functions.''
 &HT;    The decision is so strongly worded that the ACLU and teachers
have not decided whether to appeal it to the U.S. Supreme Court.
Voucher advocates hope it is appealed, confident the U.S. Supreme
Court would affirm Wisconsin's landmark ruling.
 &HT;    James Skillen, director of the Center for Public Justice, says,
''This case puts an end to using First Amendment arguments to keep
from reforming education via vouchers. We will see more and more
voucher proposals that will let the parents of poor children choose
non-governmental schools, including religious ones. This is the
wave of the future. We are over the hump.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
