<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX     07-23 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Helms blocks way to world court agreement
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few in this country beyond our foreign-policy cognoscenti
noticed, but while the world was recently and enthusiastically
adopting a basic American ideal, Washington copped out. There were
two reasons: ``Jesse'' and ``Helms.''
</P>
<P>
   After a month of intense negotiations in Rome, 120 nations voted
to create a standing world court with jurisdiction to try
government leaders or their agents for war crimes and for crimes
against humanity; that is, for genocide or lesser atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   We joined Libya, Iran, Iraq, Qatar, Yemen, China and Israel in
opposition _ not altogether swell company.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's unease _ and Israel's, for they are similar _ is
not irrational. There is always a ready motley of nations keen to
decry the odd American misstep as proof the United States is the
world's great human-rights abuser, while giving a bye to despots
who torture dissenters for after-dinner entertainment or wipe out
national minorities while nobody is looking.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon in particular worries that any permanent world
court could be misused against U.S. armed forces sent on
politically contentious peacekeeping operations like the one in
Bosnia or, earlier, the mess in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations, however, produced a system that is loaded at the
front end against harassing or tendentious use of the court.
Crucially, no one could be hauled to the bar unless the home
country defaulted its jurisdiction. The United States reliably
brings its bad eggs to legal account.
</P>
<P>
   Our closest allies _ Britain, Germany, Canada and so on _ signed
on and urged Washington to. But we'll never know whether their
reassurances were sound, because the Clinton administration refused
to submit the idea to the political process, the venue which should
be best suited to parse it and come to a reasoned conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Seeming to negotiate, the administration was in fact backing
away from the Rome talks from their start, and small wonder.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee, throwback Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who undermines U.S. participation in
international organizations whenever he can, had declared
membership in a world court dead on arrival if President Clinton
dared to present an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Even if, just for political mischief, Helms had let the idea out
of his committee, it would have failed in the current Senate. And
senators who voted for it would have found themselves being savaged
on talk radio and in re-election campaigns as anti-American
one-worlders.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton White House declined to take on the Pentagon over a
futility and put itself and Senate Democrats at gratuitous
political risk, and it is impossible to argue with the calculation.
But if the quailing was understandable, it was still regrettable.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the degree to which our political culture has
degenerated that a concept of our own provenance, going back to the
Nuremberg trials after World War II, could expect no better these
days than fatal demagoguery even in the Senate, once considered a
relatively serious deliberative chamber. We should be embarrassed
but, then, to be embarrassed we'd first have to care, wouldn't we?
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
