<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9021 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKREVIEW-FARRELLY24     07-23 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKREVIEW-FARRELLY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``The comedy writer'' aims high but takes a pratfall
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE COMEDY WRITER, by Peter Farrelly. Doubleday; 351 pages;
$12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Halloran is reeling. Amanda, his girlfriend in Boston, has
dumped him, and she was only perfect. It's not as if he was going
to marry her or anything, but he hadn't planned on getting dumped.
</P>
<P>
   So Henry does the least logical thing: He heads west to write
movies. There's nothing keeping him in the Northeast, and, at 32,
with a rotten job, he might as well roll the dice.
</P>
<P>
   Henry writes a script called ``How I Won Her Back,'' more or
less the story of his relationship with Amanda, except with a happy
ending. It's a good script; it gets Henry an agent, it gets Henry
meetings around town. And it enables him to keep obsessing about
Amanda, keep calling her even though it's clear she wants nothing
to do with him.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry is doomed. Soon after he arrives in Los Angeles, he
notices a woman perched on the top of a building. In a clumsily
handled scene especially regrettable because it's the motivating
force for the entire ramshackle novel that is ``The Comedy
Writer,'' Henry tries to talk her down. But Henry's bad luck with
women continues, and she takes the long leap.
</P>
<P>
   Henry writes a piece about the encounter that's published by The
Los Angeles Times; soon, he finds the woman's deeply strange sister
on his doorstep, wanting to find out about her sister's last
moments; soon, she's moved in on him.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Farrelly has written one previous novel, as well as
co-written and co-directed ``Dumb and Dumber,'' the erratic but
awesomely funny Woody Harrelson/Bill Murray movie ``Kingpin'' and
the new ``There's Something About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might guess from his credits, Farrelly writes good
locker-room badinage and good one-liners. As you also might guess,
he's considerably less adept when he tries to deal with anything
approaching emotional reality.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his movies, Farrelly is after more than hearty laughs
here. On some level, he wants us to feel discomfort and, I think, a
grotesque kind of anguish, and it's impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Farrelly's inspiration is clearly Nathanael West's ``The Day of
the Locust'' _ the circle of weirdos in Henry's apartment complex
could be taken as an homage to Todd Hackett's neighbors _ with
maybe a touch of ``The Cable Guy.'' It's a literary marriage made
in hell.
</P>
<P>
   Farrelly continually juxtaposes his fictional small-timers with
very real contemporary eminences, apparently for the sake of
verisimilitude. Henry strikes up a conversation with Robert Redford
in an elevator, tries to strike sparks with Jerry Seinfeld in a
pitch meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help either Henry or the novel, and it makes Farrelly
look desperate. West created characters of sufficient believability
that he didn't have to toss in special guest appearances from, say,
Tyrone Power or Jack Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most irritating thing about the book is the sheer
unlikability of its characters. Henry is impossible _ a neurotic, a
hypochondriac, a mope, a loser.
</P>
<P>
   It's like a novel with George Costanza as the leading character.
Even though comedy writers are usually funny only when they're
writing, Henry abuses the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   So you trundle along, forced to satisfy yourself with the
occasional incidental pleasure. Farrelly has a nice line in nasty
patter, half-Shecky Greene, half-Raymond Chandler: ``She was about
forty with Dow Corning breasts and a face the color and texture of
luggage.''
</P>
<P>
   And I like Herb Silverman, Henry's neighbor, whose real name is
Tom Sullivan but who changes his name because he figures he needs
to be Jewish to make it in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the big deal?'' he asks Henry. ``Jews are always giving
themselves WASPy names: Jerry Lewis, Winona Ryder, Bob Dylan,
Marvin Davis. Why can't I become a Jew? This is a tough business.
Every little bit helps.''
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy for novelists.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
