<HEADER>
A9022 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPRUDER24-COX     07-23 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A bullet blows away notions of Camelot
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ A new, digitally enhanced version of the Zapruder film
was released last week on video. Surprise, surprise, people are
getting all nutty about it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what won't happen: People will not hold viewing parties
where spicy chicken wings are served on paper plates with ranch
dressing. Video stores won't display the tape on the ``death
films'' shelf, around which acne-dappled boys in Pantera T-shirts
debate if car wrecks or Asian tribal rituals afford the most gore.
We'll be at work on Monday; the nation will not mourn all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what will happen: Viewers will learn a little bit about
Abraham Zapruder, a 60ish dress-maker who looked remarkablylike
Donald Pleasance and whose words were creased by a faint Russian
accent. They will learn that he required his assistant, Marilyn
Sitzman, to stabilize him as he shot the home movie, because he was
standing on a block of cement and suffered vertigo. They will see a
'60s news anchor suck a real cigarette on the air and witness the
large bird sculpture that was Geraldo Rivera's hair in the '70s.
They will also hear the blow-by-blow story of what Zapruder did
with the film moments and days after the assassination. (``Irwin,
it was terrible,'' he told a co-worker minutes later. ``I saw his
head come off.'')
</P>
<P>
   And you will see the President's head come off.
</P>
<P>
   For a history buff (not a conspiracy buff) like myself, the
enhanced Zapruder film makes great viewing. It's scary, horrifying,
sickening. Good film extracts those reactions from us. Real life
does it even better. This is both.
</P>
<P>
   Like the wincingly raw Rodney King tape, this is important,
life-altering viewing. If you want to see another wedge of life's
bitter pie and know just a little more about what this crazy world
is all about, it's all there. Two thumbs up. Four stars. The
feel-bad movie of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, questionable marketing tactics are being deployed to
hawk the tape, which has just been released on VHS and comes out on
DVD next week. But when is marketing, once perfected by a man named
Goebbels, ever truly tasteful?
</P>
<P>
   The company releasing the Zapruder tape, MPI Home Video, bills
the new computer-enhanced version as a solid research tool. Hooey.
There's nothing new offered in the way of unriddling the event's
imposing mystery. No shadowy figures on the neatly mowed knoll, no
fuzzy shots of Bigfoot passing in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   What's new is the red. What's new is seeing how much destruction
a single bullet can wreak on the human head. What's new, what's
stunning and breathtaking and belly-twisting, is seeing a huge
crater of pink hamburger materialize where dark hair once was on
President Kennedy's head.
</P>
<P>
   And with that image, our dewy-eyed notions of the assassination,
especially for those of us born well after the tragedy, are
instantly ripped clean of romance, glamor and comfortable
historical distance. Blam. The inflexible truth of what
``assassination'' means rushes forward to poke us in the eye. To
watch Kennedy slump forward, so catastrophically disfigured and
ruined, nearly blots out all the idyllic photos of Camelot that
came before.
</P>
<P>
   It is important not to confuse emotional arousal for
entertainment. There's too much heft here for the Zapruder footage
to be used solely for a prurient charge. Accusations of voyeurism
fail miserably. That's what people do; we watch.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapruder film is like the famous footage showing the
Hindenburg's gaseous demise. Thirty-six people were incinerated and
a man cried ``Oh, the humanity.'' Transformative movie watching
doesn't get better. Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
