<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quake damaged basilica preserved in beautiful book
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ If you have tears, prepare to shed them now.
</P>
<P>
   Ghigo Roli had just finished photographing the Basilica of St.
Francis of Assisi when the initial earthquake struck that, a few
days later, resulted in the collapse of sections of the dome.
Destroyed were irreplaceable frescoes by Florentine painters Giotto
and Cimabue.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams has published ``The Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi:
Glory and Destruction'' ($24.95), a book that will now serve as an
epitaph for one of the most beautiful artworks of the Western
world.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been to Assisi, but what is amazing about the
frescoes, aside from their quality, is their condition _ gorgeous,
vivid colors, beautifully preserved.
</P>
<P>
   For each photograph, the book prints a diagram of its place in
the overall cathedral and denotes what parts, if any, were
destroyed. Also published are some shots of the cathedral as it
stands today and images from some video that was being shot as the
ceiling came down, killing four _ two friars and two art experts
who were examining the structure for damage from the first quake.
</P>
<P>
   A must-have for art historians of any stripe.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE CONTINENT . . . During a recent trip to England, I
noticed the offerings of a new company called Pushkin Press. Their
initial list encompasses four short novels (by Raymond Radiguet,
Arthur Schnitzler, Stefan Zweig and Louis Couperus, whoever he is.)
</P>
<P>
   They're small-format paperbacks on excellent paper, a pleasure
to hold and read. Next up is a series of titles inspired by Venice,
including a selection of letters by Henry James. Pushkin is looking
for a U.S. distributor. May they find one in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE HE WAS DRINKING ROGAINE . . . Bison Books, an imprint of
the University of Nebraska Press, one of the most innovative
college presses, tends to reprint lots of valuable books on the
subjects of the Old West and baseball. But now they're branching
out.
</P>
<P>
   They've issued Robert Louis Stevenson's ``The Strange Case of
Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde'' in a tidy little paperback. This is the
edition that originally came out in 1990, with a dozen woodcut
illustrations by Barry Moser and an introduction by Joyce Carol
Oates.
</P>
<P>
   A nice package for $10.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``It is a sign of vanity that one fails
oneself perpetually.'' _ Rosellen Brown
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
