<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDE-SIDE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strip joint jargon
 &HT;    Sidebar to LIVE-NUDE
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As in any business, those in the adult entertainment industry
have a sort of shorthand for various aspects of their work. Author
J.P. Danko gives us a peek in his book Live Nude Girls:
</P>
<P>
   STRIPPER RADAR _ An imagined sixth sense by which stripteasers
are capable of spotting a patron willing to spend money.
</P>
<P>
   DODGING THE OCTOPUS _ Avoiding the groping hands of an
overzealous customer. Appropriate contact includes a casual
touching of a dancer's arm, shoulder or hand, or sometimes a slight
hug or peck on the cheek. Anything else is out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   LAP DANCE _ A private performance by dancer for patron. Also
known as a `friction dance' or `Texas-style couch dance.'
</P>
<P>
   THE GAZE _ A cross between lobotomized idiocy, transcendent
bliss and solemn practical appraisal, the fixed gaze is the
countenance on the face of every patron enjoying a lap dance.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEER LINE _ A buffer zone designated by a local legislative
body that separates nude dancers from beer-chugging patrons. The
line may be an actual white stripe placed around the stage.
</P>
<P>
   FUNNY MONEY _ Fake bills issued by a club and obtained by
customers via credit card. Such a practice allows a customer to
have a good time, knowing that the credit-card bill will show a
name other than that of a strip club.
</P>
<P>
   SHOWER OF BILLS _ This classy tipping practice involves a
handful of bills, usually no less than a dozen singles. The patron
approaches the stage and, with a flick of the wrist and an
open-handed release, tosses the bills into the air to flutter about
like wind-borne leaves. He appears aloof about the dough he's
tossed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
