<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9028 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEA-WORLD24-COX     07-23 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-WORLD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (backslash)plashy rides, tales of whale love await you at Sea
World
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ The Great WhiteSea World Where: San Antonio
Texas. Directions: I-35 South to FM 1604 West Hours: 10 a.m. to 10
p.m. through Aug. 9; (fall hours vary so check with the park before
you visit) How much: One day pass costs $30.95 for adults (12 or
older), $20.95 for children (3-11), children 2 and younger are free
Info: (210) 523-3606 or www.SeaWorld.org
</P>
<P>
   It's hot, but the summer movies have been so bad this year that
it's not worth cooling off in a theater, the malls are an
air-conditioned bore and ice skating, no matter how cold the ice,
is for wimps. So where can you go to cool off and simultaneously be
entertained? I suggest you take the trip to Sea World in San
Antonio, Texas. As Sea World's name reflects, everything in the
park has to do with the sea, water or something in the water or
something wet, so if you are not into any of these things or not
aquatic in the least, this might not be the right place for you.
</P>
<P>
   For about $45 (entrance fee and food money), a bathing suit (to
swim in or to wear around the park) and sunglasses (to look cool)
you can have a fun-filled afternoon and keep out of the heat in the
process. Although your day at Sea World can start as early as 10
a.m. when the park opens, I suggest a later arrival time. In this
way, you catch the lag between the parental dawn patrol dragging
their screaming, funnel cake-eating kids and the screaming,
high-school, funnel cake-eating teens with their season passes who
tend to arrive about 3:30 p.m. A well-planned trip can avoid both
these groups, thus rendering the day devoid of lines and, most
importantly, noise-induced headaches.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, plan to arrive about 1:30 p.m. Warning: It will be
hot, so immediately put on that suit and head to the ``Lost
Lagoon.'' This is the water park within Sea World that features two
body slides and two tubing slides. There is also a wave pool and
faux beach where you can hang out. While in the Lagoon, a fun thing
to do is stand by the alligator pool and say, ``Has anyone seen my
little boy? Last time I saw him, he crawled over the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3:30 p.m., head to the Water Ski Stadium for the first of
your shows, ``The Intensity Games.'' This is a land and sea show
that is part competition, part drama. Think: ESPN ``X-Games'' meets
a really good episode of ``American Gladiator.'' The next show to
see is at Sea Lion Stadium at 4:30 p.m. This show proved once and
for all to me that seals and other furry water mammals are funny.
``The Pirates of the Pinniped'' is a goofy, slapstick story of an
evil captain with a seal and an otter saving the day. It might
sound dumb, but so did the movie ``Andre the Seal'' and that was
funny, right?
</P>
<P>
   After the seal takes care of the evil captain and the otter
dances around with a Pepsi can (product placement subtly
infiltrates the park at every turn), head for the Clydesdales. If
you didn't already know, Anheuser-Busch owns the park, yet the
company is pretty classy in its self-promotion. You have to look
pretty hard to find a beer stand or a Budweiser T-shirt (which can
be found in the gift shops for $14.99).
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 p.m., head to the Shamu Stadium (where, happily, there
is a beer stand) to see the show that features the sea-faring
mammal with enough clout to have a Southwest Airline plane
fashioned after it. The new ``Shamu's Splashin' Sensations'' begins
at 5:30. If, at this point, you're hot, I suggest you sit in the
front nine rows which, conveniently, are labeled the ``Splash
Zone.'' For the truly cocky, I suggest taking a place under the
announcer's stand.
</P>
<P>
   Sea World touts itself as ``educating through entertainment.''
The Shamu show, in all its fun and majesty, does just that. Did you
know, for example, a killer whale is part of the dolphin family?
After hearing just about as much as you would ever want to hear
about killer whale those ``crazy river'' rides intended only to get
you wet. I shared a ``boat'' with a family of three who outweighed
me six to one. ``Weight is a factor on this ride,'' explained the
well-fed father in the Dallas Cowboys tank top. The family had been
there all day and had figured out the physics of ``Rio Loco'' after
riding it four times.
</P>
<P>
   He was right and, with his deft touch, he showed me the funny
art of getting the skinny guy wet. After thanking them for the
lesson and promising I would ``get the next guy,'' I headed to
``The Great White,'' the only ``inverted'' steel coaster in Texas
(where your feet are dangling). As I was being strapped in, the
attendant told me to secure loose items. ``Why?'' ``Because you go
upside down twice,'' he answered. After the fifth loop, pulling
about 4.6 G's, I realized he'd lied. Was it scary? Let me just say,
it was a good thing my pants were already wet.
</P>
<P>
   When you get off ``The Great White'' be sure to check out the
picture they take of you in mid-fright. It's pretty hard to look
cool (even with those sunglasses on) while being mercilessly
whipped around at 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Now would be the time to either eat, if you have the stomach for
it, or check out the dolphin pool and Shark/Cor al Reef exhibit. If
you choose the former, there is the Skiside Cafe, which offers
``famous fried chicken'' ($4.95 with fries). For the more formal
dining experience, The Oaks Cafe for a pepperoni pizza ($3.99 with
fries).
</P>
<P>
   For the weaker stomachs, the dolphin pool provides a calming
experience. Here, the dolphins, which you can pet, swim right out
of your reach, unless you have a fish in your hand. The Shark/Cor
al Reef exhibit is an ice-cold air-conditioned aquarium which, if
nothing else, will make you glad you don't have to hang out in a
tank with sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clyde and Seamore's Comedy Cruise,'' at the Sea Lion Stadium
at 8 p.m., might be a goofy name for a show, but, as said before,
seals are funny. This show is great because it parodies everything
you've seen so far, from the heartfelt stories told by Shamu's
trainers to the sharing of bird knowledge at ``Birds of a
Feather.'' And, of course, it's all done with Clyde the seal and
his otter and walrus friends.
</P>
<P>
   If by this point, you're sick of watching aquatic animals do
really cute stuff, you're in luck. The night ends with the new
``Red Bright and Blue'' fireworks and laser extravaganza (Waterski
Stadium at 9:40 p.m.). After a puppet Shamu uses his Southwestern
Bell cell phone (again with the product placement) to start the
show, fireworks, lasers and images projected into a water wall will
delight. The 3-D glasses are a must and they're free, so bring your
friends home a pair.
</P>
<P>
   A full day of watching, riding, eating and sliding at Sea World
can stop even the biggest heat whiner from complaining. Instead,
you'll leave with an everlasting memory of the day you were kept
cool by the tail of a whale. I know I did. Shows not to be missed:
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot going on at Sea World, which ultimately leads to
arguments with loved ones over whether to go here or there. One of
the problems with this place is you always feel you're missing
something. So stop the arguing and let me take the blame. Here are
the shows not to be missed while visiting Shamu's home: Shamu's
Splashin' Sensations _ How can you go wrong with Shamu, the star of
Sea World? After the weepy, heartfelt stories told by Shamu's
trainers from kayaks (Why kayaks? Your guess is as good as mine.),
you are treated to a close-up view of the truly majestic animals.
Watch as they swim, jump and drench their sub-superior human
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Symphony of the Sea _ When I went to this show it revolved
around watching the new baby dolphin get aquainted with its mother
and hearing a lecture on the earth's smartest mammals. According to
reliable sources, on a normal day, this is one of the best shows at
Sea World. It features the amazing acrobatics of dolphins and
beluga whales.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde and Seamore's Comedy Cruise Show _ This show works on two
levels: the goofy slapstick level kids love and a truly satirical
level that you'll love. The Comedy Cruise Show questions and makes
fun of all the goofiness and aquatic animal education overplay
you've been experiencing the entire day. Example: A man comes out
wearing a kayak (like the one in the Shamu show). ``You might ask
yourself why, during a Shamu show, am I riding in a kayak? (comic
pause) I have no idea.'' Red Bright and Blue _ If you can endure
the shameless use of product placement in the form of an oversize
cell phone (as a puppet Shamu starts the show), this is a pretty
darned impressive ending to the evening. Fireworks, lasers and a
very cool projection of film on a gushing wall of water.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Kallenberg is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
