<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9030 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWII-FLICKS24-COX     07-23 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-FLICKS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The few -- the proud -- the cliched
 &HT;    By Palm Beach Post staffwriters
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg has brought back a long-lost genre - the World
War II movie.
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan is the story of a GI squad sent in to save a
young private whose three brothers have already been killed in
battle (shades of The Fighting Sullivans). It's described as
unflinchingly realistic in depicting the bloody D-Day battle at
Normandy. But listen up, soldier. A World War II movie is still a
World War II movie. And that means we're going to meet that
familiar platoon: young, scared, ethnically balanced.
</P>
<P>
   And cliched.
</P>
<P>
   THE SERGEANT
</P>
<P>
   Cliches: Always called `Sarge.' Tough. Whips the raw recruits
into men. Often dies in the big battle, but the spirit of the
platoon lives on.
</P>
<P>
   Best movie Sarges: John Wayne in The Sands of Iwo Jima, Robert
Mitchum in The Story of G.I. Joe, Lee Marvin in The Big Red One.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's sarge: Sergeant Horvath (Tom Sizemore). Known,
naturally, as Sarge. Has one goal: get his men out alive. THE FARM
BOY
</P>
<P>
   Cliches: Hayseed, baby-faced private. Sure to get killed after
one scene that establishes his decency and naivete.
</P>
<P>
   Best movie farm boy: Richard Jaeckel in Guadalcanal Diary,
Richard Jaeckel in The Sands of Iwo Jima, Richard Jaeckel in
Attack.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's farm boy: Private Jackson (Barry Pepper), a
Bible-spouting dead shot from Tennessee. Has he heard of Alvin
York? THE GUY FROM BROOKLYN
</P>
<P>
   Cliches: Wisecracker. Looking out for Number One. Hides horror
through humor. Usually Italian. Can be interchanged with a Jew from
a different borough. Talks about the Dodgers (Brooklyn), mom's
spaghetti, and stickball.
</P>
<P>
   Best movie guy from Brooklyn: Sam Levene in The Purple Heart
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's guys: Private Reiben (Edward Burns), who won't let
up about how thrilled he is to be saving Private Ryan. Or Private
Mellish (Adam Goldberg), the Jewish kid from Yonkers who knows why
he's fighting the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   SOME THOUGHTS ON WAR FROM GEN. GEORGE C. SCOTT.
</P>
<P>
   OOPS, WE MEAN PATTON.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I want you to remember that no bastard ever won a war by
dying for his country. He won it by making the other poor dumb
bastard die for his country.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When you put your hand into a bunch of goo that a moment
before was your best friend's face, you'll know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I don't want to get any messages saying that we are holding
our position. We're not holding anything. Let the Hun do that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I love it. God help me, I do love it so. I love it more than
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST WWII COMBAT MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Story of G.I. Joe'' (1945) Long unseen because of legal
problems, this William Wellman movie is based on war correspondent
Ernie Pyle's stories of men in battle. The movie made Robert
Mitchum a star.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``They Were Expendable'' (1945) John Ford's melancholy movie
about the development of PT boats for use in the Philippines during
the early days of the war _ a campaign we lost.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Battleground'' (1949) Wellman, a veteran of World War I,
knew what war felt like and in this movie captures the Battle of
the Bulge. The inspiration for some war scenes in ``Saving Private
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Big Red One'' (1980) Sam Fuller's last film documents an
infantry platoon and the battle-hardened sarge who leads them. Lee
Marvin's last great role.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Das Boot'' (1981) Wolfgang Petersen's gripping tale from the
other side, about the claustrophobia and futility that builds
during a German U-Boat's mission undersea.
</P>
<P>
   Others: ``The Longest Day,'' ``12 O'Clock High,'' ``The Sands of
Iwo Jima.''
</P>
<P>
   Other films touch on different aspects of the war:
</P>
<P>
   THE POW MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bridge on the River Kwai'' (1957) David Lean's masterpiece
about British soldiers in a Japanese prison camp who are forced to
build a bridge. Better than ``Lawrence of Arabia'' because it has a
story.
</P>
<P>
   Others: ``The Great Escape,'' ``King Rat,'' ``Stalag 17.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HOMEFRONT MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Years of Our Lives'' (1946) William Wyler's moving
portrait of veterans coming home to uncertain futures, amazingly
mature after more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Others: ``Since You Went Away,'' ``Swing Shift.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HOLOCAUST MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   ``Schindler's List'' (1993) Not a perfect movie, but a deeply
moving one from Spielberg about a German who saves more than 1,000
Polish Jews. ``The list is life.''
</P>
<P>
   Others: ``Shoah,'' ``The Sorrow and the Pity,'' ''Night and
Fog.''
</P>
<P>
   THE WAR COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   ''To Be Or Not To Be'' (1942) Ernst Lubitsch's black comedy
about incompetent Polish actors pretending to be vicious Nazis to
escape their clutches. A masterpiece, with Jack Benny as ``that
great, great Polish actor, Joseph Tura'' and the luminous Carole
Lombard as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Others: ``The Miracle of Morgan's Creek,'' ``The Great
Dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   TORA! TORA! BORE-A!
</P>
<P>
   THE WORST WORLD WAR II MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   _ Tora, Tora, Tora.
</P>
<P>
   _ Midway.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Harm's Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Or anything with Audie Murphy, Charlie Chan or Tarzan fighting
the ``Nadzies.''
</P>
<P>
   MOST UNLIKELY MOVIE DOGFACES
</P>
<P>
   _ Joey Bishop in The Naked and The Dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ William Bendix in Wake Island and Guadalcanal Diary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bobby Darin and Bob Newhart in Hell is for Heroes.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD'S TRUE-LIFE WAR HEROES
</P>
<P>
   _ WAYNE MORRIS. The B-picture actor was Hollywood's most
decorated soldier, with four Distinguished Flying Crosses and two
Air Medals (Remember, Audie Murphy didn't become an actor till
after the war.) Morris received the credit for sinking three ships
and shooting down seven Japanese planes.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES STEWART. He flew about 20 missions as an Air Force
bombing pilot, and was decorated for his service.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLARK GABLE. After the death of wife Carole Lombard while
promoting war bonds, Gable flew with a photography unit on five
risky combat missions and received an Air Medal.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOUGLAS FAIRBANKS, JR. He was decorated for his service under
fire as a Naval officer on the Italian coast.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget middle-aged directors like John Ford,
George Stevens and John Huston, who went to war and made great
documentaries while the bullets were flying all around them.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD'S BIGGEST WAR SLACKER
</P>
<P>
   JOHN WAYNE. That's right, the Duke dodged the war, churning out
so many patriotic-themed movies that some think he single-handedly
won the war. But he was more worried about his career, and with a
family-support deferment, he never got around to enlisting.
</P>
<P>
   OVER THE RIDGE
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend. Six movies about World War II are being planned by
Hollywood, including ``The Thin Red Line,'' with Sean Penn, John
Travolta and George Clooney, a film based on James Jones' novel and
directed by the reclusive Terrence Malick, who hasn't been seen
since ``Badlands'' and ``Days of Heaven'' in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
