<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suffering makes me ready for tough nursing home regulation
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ It has been three years now, almost to the
day, that I walked into a Fort Worth nursing home to see my sister.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer heat, that summer did not match this one, but that
particular day was remarkably hot. It was at least 100 degrees and
probably several degrees
</P>
<P>
   hotter than that.
</P>
<P>
   And when I opened the door to the nursing home I discovered, to
my surprise, that it was almost that warm inside.
</P>
<P>
   The air conditioning had died, not that day but the day before.
The nursing home staff was trying to use a series of small box fans
to keep the place
</P>
<P>
   cool.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing I noticed was the usual group of elderly folks
gathered around the front door -- all wearing sweaters or long
robes. Sweat streamed
</P>
<P>
   down their faces like tears. They did not know they were
overheating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   I walked around the hall to my sister's room to find her naked,
lying on the bed in a pool of her own vomit. She had dumped a
pitcher of water on her
</P>
<P>
   head in a vain attempt to cool down. Though my sister was only
five years older than me, she was dying and incoherent most of the
time. She likely
</P>
<P>
   also did not know how hot it was in the building.
</P>
<P>
   As I began to search the halls for a nurse -- there were always
too few to do too much work -- one came from behind me. Before I
had a chance to say
</P>
<P>
   anything she said to me:
</P>
<P>
   ``Help us. Call someone. Make them get this fixed. These people
are going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency in her voice could not be mistaken, though even
standing in that heat I thought she might have been overstating the
danger. I thought
</P>
<P>
   that until I located a thermostat that was pegged out at 90
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I didn't know who to call. I assumed state offices would
be closed on a Saturday. Being a newsman, I did the best thing I
could think of: I
</P>
<P>
   called the Associated Press. From inside the nursing home I told
an AP reporter what was going on. In just a few hours, she had a
story on the
</P>
<P>
   wire. That set the Fort Worth Star Telegram off to do their own
story.
</P>
<P>
   When contacted by the press, the nursing home owner -- a
corporate outfit from somewhere -- said that they had tried their
hardest to get the air
</P>
<P>
   conditioning fixed but that they could not find a new compressor
to install.
</P>
<P>
   Let me get this straight. In the entire Dallas-Fort Worth area
there was not a compressor to be had? I don't think so. Perhaps
there was none to be
</P>
<P>
   had at the right price, more likely the corporation had a single
supplier of compressors who gave them a cut rate and the
corporation did not want to
</P>
<P>
   spend the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the employees contacted by the newspaper said
that the system had been not working properly for days before it
finally broke down
</P>
<P>
   completely Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With both the AP and the Star Telegram hounding them, somebody
did something. By late Sunday the air conditioning had been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   I was not exactly greeted as a hero by the nursing home staff
when I came back on Sunday. The corporate supervisors had come
through with a terrible,
</P>
<P>
   swift sword, threatening anyone who spoke to the media. The
clamps had been installed.
</P>
<P>
   I advised them to get ready, because I intended to complain to
the state agency overseeing nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if they laughed when I walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Because Monday morning, when I called the Texas Department of
Health, division of Long Term Care, it was much as if I was calling
the corporate
</P>
<P>
   offices for the nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of acting as a watchdog, the person I talked to was more
of an apologist for the nursing home and the industry as a whole.
It took just a
</P>
<P>
   minute to know that I would be getting no action from the state.
Nursing homes across this state must know about the lax treatment.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that there are not good nursing homes but, if
one is good, it is not because the state demands it. I cannot tell
that the state
</P>
<P>
   demands much at all. To be sure, there are reams of rules, but
almost none of them, if broken, will result in any real punitive
action against the
</P>
<P>
   nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I was interested to hear that President Bill
Clinton wants congress to tighten the rules against nursing homes,
a move that was
</P>
<P>
   welcomed by Sen. Charles Grassley, a Republican from Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ``other side'' has already fired a first shot. The
Associated Press quoted Dr. Paul Willging, executive vice president
of the American
</P>
<P>
   Health Care Association, which represents 11,000 nursing homes,
thusly: ``Enforcement activity alone is not the answer. In fact, a
single-minded
</P>
<P>
   emphasis on enforcement will ultimately hurt quality.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time I could have laughed at such complete nonsense.
Laughed, had I not seen the people suffering with my own eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
