<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVE-NUDES24 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bare facts: West Palm club makes book of best strip joints
 &HT;    Has sidebars: NUDE-SIDE-1, NUDE-SIDE-2
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If a crazy idea is worth anything in
this world, J.P Danko might just be the Bill Gates of the Crazies.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the fact that he persuaded a book publisher to fork
over a five-figure advance for the sole purpose of finding
America's 100 best strip clubs, including one in Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Then he persuaded his mom to lend him her 1985 Volkswagen
Vanagon for the 15,000-mile skin excursion.
</P>
<P>
   And he persuaded his girlfriend, Wendy, to continue in that
capacity twice - once before the trip and once after she broke up
with him while he was out on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Men, you owe J.P. Danko a debt of gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Night after hellish night, for three months he endured a
grueling blur of silicone, skimpy lingerie and surly bouncers, all
so that there might be an authoritative guide to the
highest-quality adult nightclub entertainment our nation has to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The result: a light-hearted 160-page opus titled Live Nude Girls
($14.95, St. Martin's Press). It's a practical, tongue-in-cheek
book that will bring a smirk or a dirty laugh of recognition to
anyone familiar with so-called gentlemen's clubs.
</P>
<P>
   He toured 31 states (including Hawaii), as well as the District
of Columbia, Quebec, Ontario and Baja California. As Danko sees it,
Florida is the best strip-club state, with 15 institutions ranking
in the top 100. There are 15 from California in the book, too, but
the Sunshine State offers something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida had a great diversity of clubs, and the women were tan
and beautiful, of course,'' Danko said. ``I liked the upscale
clubs, but since I consider myself a populist, I also like going
into a dive bar, if nothing more than for the people-watching. If
you don't have a lot of money, you can go into a dive with a couple
bucks and still have a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   His observations on some South Florida saloons:
</P>
<P>
   Crazy Horse Too, Pompano Beach: ``Purchase a fine cigar from the
gift shop, and while you're there, how about something for the
little lady back home? The black satin jacket is a perfect choice.
Like Vegas lights and South Florida nights, black satin is always
in style.''
</P>
<P>
   Pure Platinum, Fort Lauderdale: ``After the boat show expo - or
whatever lame excuse brought you to town - you and your college
friends can relive the spring break partying days of yore and fall
in love once more with your South Florida dream girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mermaid Bar, West Palm Beach: ``A hand-carved mermaid and
old-style wooden fixtures give this joint a classic vibe as groups
of idle dancers sit around talking and smoking like extras on a
swashbuckler flick.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Charlie Covington, a former bouncer who bought the
Southern Boulevard club in April 1997, laughed with a snort when
told his less-than-glamorous club had made the top 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really a club, we're more of a bar,'' he said. ``We
get all kinds of guys in here - guys in suits, guys in jeans, you
name it. And we've got all kinds of girls, too - little girls next
door, big girls next door, good-looking girls and, let's be honest,
some ugly girls, too. But that's what makes it a bar where anyone
can hang out. There are real people here.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more impressive when you understand that the low-key
Mermaid, which has been open a stone's throw from Palm Beach
International Airport's runway since 1972, beat out such venerable
haunts as T's Lounge in West Palm Beach and Tiffany's Cabaret in
Boynton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Danko had a range of clubs in mind when he first envisioned his
trek - from flashy to seedy. The idea for the ultimate strip-bar
bible came while he and a friend were visiting a club. Watching the
display, the friend bemoaned the fact that there was no guide to
the best erotic establishments. An unemployed writer at the time,
Danko decided to be the carnal Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was less than thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't ask too many questions,'' he said. ``After a while,
she really preferred not to know anything. But, given the choice
between unemployment and writing a book about strip clubs, I think
this was the less of two evils.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days he'd drop in on as many as 10 clubs. Most times he'd
go with a friend who was all too happy to tag along in exchange for
free lodging. In Tijuana, Mexico, he saw one buddy propose marriage
to a stripper, while another got into a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he drank occasionally. And yes, he tipped the dancers. ``I
learned that in order to be a decent customer you have to tip,'' he
said. ``Not that much, but often.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-looking women worked on the weekends, he said, but
there were no other absolutes. Daytime dancers proved just as
entertaining. ``If you go in off-hours during the day, you get all
the attention, which is good. But if you get all the attention, you
have to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way were some downright weird spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   In Fayetteville, N.C., he watched a veteran stripper teach a
young novice the proper way to work the go-go pole, while two or
three patrons watched the on-the-job training with glazed eyes. At
another club, a patron paid one of the strippers $500 for her
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   In Anniston, Ala., an ambulance pulled up to a club and unloaded
a guy on a stretcher. The attendants propped him up next to the
stage. Standing around the stage was a no-no at that club, but no
one said anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he was on the way to the hospital, I don't know,'' Danko
said. ``I didn't ask.''
</P>
<P>
   The traveling got boring. Going from club to club got boring.
Nursing the ailing Vanagon got a bit tedious.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, it was tough, and my energy and interest did lag,
but it's remarkable how your interest improves once you're about 10
or 15 feet from a club's door, and you realize you're about to see
dozens of naked women,'' he said. ``Funny how that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
