<SLUG> BC-MECHANIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not all compression ratios created equal
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Ask a guy at work how to charge a battery, and he'll
tell you how it's built and why it works.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a simple question generates a complicated answer. To
understand the cause and effect of a situation, the ``whys'' need
to be supported by the ``hows'' and ``whats.'' I refuse to teach my
students simply how to fix a particular car problem without
supplying the ``how and why'' it works.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Grossman asked about fuel octane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I purchased a 1998 Buick Regal GS, which has a GM 3800 series
II, supercharged V-6 engine. The manual calls for premium gas. The
same engine without a supercharger uses regular. The salesperson
told me that I could use regular if I didn't have any pinging or
run-on, which I don't. Am I doing the right thing?''
</P>
<P>
   This question actually has a couple of answers. One pertains to
the octane requirements of the vehicle, and the other addresses the
vehicle's response to the lower octane fuel via the engine's
computerized management system. Before I get into the ``whys'' of
octane, let's look inside the engine.
</P>
<P>
   During the intake stroke of a four-stroke piston engine, the
piston is moving downward and the intake valve opens, allowing fuel
and air to enter the cylinder. The intake stroke is followed by the
compression stroke. The intake valve closes, sealing the chamber.
The piston moves upward in the cylinder, compressing the air fuel
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the term ``compression ratio'' comes from. The
distance between the bottom of the piston travel and the top of its
travel, where the air and fuel are maximum squished, is a ratio. If
the piston is squishing the mixture to one-ninth of the total
distance between top and bottom, the engine is said to have a 9:1
compression ratio; if it compresses to one-twelfth of the volume,
the ratio is 12:1. When the mixture is compressed, it creates heat.
The higher the compression ratio, or the more compressing the
piston has to do, the more heat produced.
</P>
<P>
   The hot, squished, air/fuel mixture then is ignited by the spark
plug. This creates the controlled explosion that pushes the piston
back down on the power stroke, the source of engine momentum. The
exhaust valve opens, and the piston moves upward again, pushing the
(hopefully completely) burned fuel mixture out of the cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   This cycle repeats itself at an incredibly rapid speed. An
example is, a six-cylinder engine running at 3000 rpm must deliver
a spark-ignited power stroke 150 times a second.
</P>
<P>
   Most engines are naturally aspirated, meaning the air entering
the combustion chamber has the same atmospheric pressure as the
outside air, 14.7 pounds per square inch at sea level and less as
elevation increases.
</P>
<P>
   When the piston compresses the air/fuel mixture, the total
volume is limited to what is naturally pushed (and sucked) into the
cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   A supercharger boosts the intake air pressure above atmospheric
pressure, meaning the total volume of the mixture to be compressed
is increased. So, given two engines with compression ratios of 9:1,
a naturally aspirated engine has less squishing to do than one with
boosted air pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the compression ratios are the same, the heat
generated in the combustion chamber of the boosted engine is
higher.
</P>
<P>
   So back to octane. Simply put, an engine's fuel octane
requirement is directly proportional to the amount of heat produced
in the combustion chamber. More on that next week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-22-98 1749E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
