<HEADER>
A9035 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN24-COX     07-23 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pass the karma, please: Growth comes back to haunt
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With elections just over, I had planned to use this
space for an in-depth analysis of the results. Unfortunately, the
perils of semirural living intervened and that will have to be left
to less astute observers.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago a real estate lady sold the soybean field
adjacent to our peaceful family farm to a developer. I can't blame
the real estate lady. Actually, she is very nice and was only
trying to supplement her spouse's Social Security check and keep
him up in the style to which he became accustomed when he was
gainfully employed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither can I blame the owners who put the soybean farm up for
sale after their mother died. They had long since moved to Florida
and had been renting the farm for a fee that barely paid taxes.
Getting along in years, they didn't have much choice.
</P>
<P>
   I wish the real estate lady could have found a buyer who would
keep on planting soybeans, or use the land for a cattle farm. But
not many farmers are looking to cultivate crops or raise animals in
Fayette County these day, except for a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   The developer naturally wanted to make a profit on his
investment, and so I can't be too angry with him either, even after
he sent in bulldozers to cut streets and grade lots, stirring up
red mud that silted my pond and ruined the fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The developer then built houses. Real estate persons in cahoots
with the real estate lady who sold the soybean field sold the
houses to city folks, and even some to Yankees. The law being the
way it is, I don't know what can be done about that.
</P>
<P>
   My family has been here since we ran the Indians out. It would
be nice, now that we're rid of Indians, to make it illegal for
anyone to buy land, or build a home, in Fayette County unless their
families have lived here since before the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The courts, when pressed, seem to have a different opinion. It
would help if we had a law making it illegal to sell land unless it
is going to be used exactly like our grandfathers used it. I'd like
that, until I got bad sick, or divorced for tracking mud in the
house, and had to have a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   When we moved to the farm 25 years ago we lived on a dirt road.
The idea of living on a dirt road seemed romantic until we started
doing it. We had to drive the boys to meet the school bus on the
paved road. When it rained, we sometimes got stuck. The car stayed
so dirty my wife was ashamed to go to church unless I got up early
and washed it on Sunday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt road had its pluses. We didn't have a road sign or a
house number. Friends who lived in Atlanta couldn't find us and my
wife couldn't call Neiman-Marcus and Saks to have things FedExed.
When I jogged, my knees didn't hurt. We didn't have to worry about
the cows getting out of the pasture and into the road. I could go
to the mailbox without being nearly run down by a speeding yuppie.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I made weekly trips to the courthouse to complain
about mud holes and dust. The commissioners eventually agreed to
pave our road. After the road was paved, my old-maid cousins were
able to sell their home place across from our house. They had
inherited it, but couldn't pay the taxes until they moved off to
Atlanta and got jobs. They were old and sick and needed the money.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed since we came back home, first from College
Park to escape jet noise, then hopscotching down the road when
Fayetteville needed a second traffic light to handle all the
immigrant drivers. We're still fairly rural at certain times of
day. At twilight a family of five deer cavort in the driveway,
before sneaking into the garden for a midnight snack.
</P>
<P>
   We saw seven peacocks on an afternoon stroll. Canada geese are
regular visitors, with mallard ducks dropping in now and then.
Other visitors include fox, raccoons, beaver and opossums. Stan
Thain encounters coyotes behind the pond. Our latest campers are
two sets of mama and papa turkeys, 14 offspring between them. With
such a menagerie, it's sad the cows have to go.
</P>
<P>
   I was peacefully tending the charcoal grill under an oak tree in
the back yard when a subdivision neighbor drove up, slightly irate.
Our cows were in his back yard. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they aren't my cows. They're my semi-farmer son's
cows. Since the courts have been leaning toward holding parents
responsible for offspring actions and inactions, I canceled supper
and paged our semi-farmer son. The 11 o'clock news had finished
showing dead bodies and interviewing witnesses in tank tops when we
finally got the cows back home with the help of Sid Drake, a
neighbor who understands cow emergencies. Sid's grandpa was Mr.
Dewitt Oakley, who tended a herd until he died last year, in his
90s.
</P>
<P>
   Until somebody figures out a way to keep trees from falling on
fences, there's no fool-proof way to keep cows, or goats, in a
pasture. In the old days, Mr. Oakley would drop by in his pickup to
tell you your cows were out and that he had run them into his barn
until you had time to come get them. Subdivision neighbors don't
have barns, and couldn't herd cows into one if they did.
</P>
<P>
   Our semi-farmer son will soon be making a trip to Jackson, where
they sell cows to packing houses on days they don't have anything
going in the electric chair. Somewhere in the Happy Hunting Ground
Indians are laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
