<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strippers' favorite? The rolodex guy
 &HT;    Sidebar to LIVE-NUDE
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrons at adult entertainment clubs fall neatly into several
categories, according to author J.P. Danko.
</P>
<P>
   THE FRAT BOYS _ Identifiable for three reasons: They're young,
they're obnoxious, and they travel in packs. Frat Boys tend to
fancy themselves too cool to be spending time in a strip club. They
try to flirt with the girls without spending money, wrongly
believing the strippers will respect them more if they don't spend.
</P>
<P>
   THE REGULAR _ A nightly visitor, he takes his usual seat at the
club. Everyone knows his name, his favorite drink and his favorite
dancer, although he usually sits at the bar and doesn't spend much.
</P>
<P>
   THE ANTI-TIPPER _ Remains aloof and tips only to reward what he
considers a very special or exceptional talent.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOYFRIEND _ Drops by his local bar now and again to visit
friends and keep an eye on his main squeeze. Everyone knows him, so
he's not pestered about tipping. He's ``stripper-friendly'' and is
probably just killing time between rolling out of bed and heading
off to band practice. On occasion, he drinks too much and gets
paranoid, worrying that his girlfriend is getting overly intimate
with her clientele.
</P>
<P>
   THE RACE FANS _ Largely a Southern phenomenon, this group of
verbally expressive, beer-guzzling, car-crazed rowdies floods strip
clubs wherever the NASCAR racing circuit takes them. They don't
make much money, but they tend to spend all they have.
</P>
<P>
   THE ROLODEX GUY _ Usually buys a private dance from each girl
and, when the dance is over, moves on to the next one. Not one to
engage in small talk, the Rolodex Guy is a dancer favorite because
he spreads a lot of cash around to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   THE COOL GUY _ Usually young, handsome and self-assured, the
Cool Guy enters a strip club with one goal: to leave with a
stripper. He lavishes money and charm. One problem: Dancers shed
their skivvies to make money, not bump into prospective partners,
so Cool Guy rarely has any luck.
</P>
<P>
   THE WET BLANKET _ Doesn't want to be there, but as a part of a
larger group of guys, he had little choice. The idea of spending
money with no possibility of tangible return drives him absolutely
nuts, so he scowls, behaves rudely and refuses to pitch in.
</P>
<P>
   THE SENSITIVE GUY _ Seeks to justify his presence by engaging a
dancer in a lengthy, heartfelt conversation, attempting to convince
her that he views her as a real person _ not as a sex symbol _ and
isn't like the other customers (Read: he doesn't tip). He goes
after her real name, where she's from and how she got into the
business, but from the dancer's perspective, he's the worst
customer, since he talks too much, doesn't spend money and insists
on dwelling on a topic she either isn't interested in or long ago
laid to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
