<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test Drive: From staid to stylish
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Mergers, acquisitions, retro cars such as the
Volkswagen Beetle and the popularity of massive vehicles such as
the Lincoln Navigator have made for strange times in the auto
industry. To even casual observers, however, nothing seems stranger
than the idea of staid, safety-oriented Volvo introducing certified
head-turning cars.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way it is with the Volvo C70 coupe and
convertible, a pair of Swedish-built vehicles best considered safe,
swift, good-looking and pricey. The look-at-that quotient --
particularly among Volvo loyalists -- rivals that of the new VW
Beetle. Oddly, though, the coupe provoked more questions, grins and
thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   Equally unusual is that their prices shocked neither teens,
senior citizens nor those in between who are the target market for
the sporty C70 models. The coupe, available now, is base-priced at
$39,970, while the topless version is expected to list for about
$43,000 when it begins arriving in showrooms in August.
</P>
<P>
   Both are likely to delight the Volvo faithful, although it'll be
interesting to see how many new buyers spring for the 3,000 or so
C70s Volvo plans to sell in the United States. Volvo hopes
newcomers will be impressed by the array of standard features,
which include nifty leather-and-walnut trim, a dash-mounted
three-disc CD player, trip computer, power/manual driver's seat
with memory, convenient console-mounted drink holders that really
grip, and power locks and windows.
</P>
<P>
   Both C70s slip smoothly into the fun-driver category, because of
accurate rack-and-pinon steering, nicely taut suspensions, strong
brakes and enough power to make it seem they're carrying highly
developed six-cylinder engines rather than turbocharged
five-bangers.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo's ``light-pressure'' 2.4-liter engine makes 190 horsepower
and 199 pounds-feet of torque, while the 2.3 whomps out 236 hp with
243 pounds-feet of torque. The horsepower doesn't peak until the
rpms hit the 5,000 level, but the torque comes on nicely -- once
the turbo is going -- in the 2,000 rpm range, giving the
3,500-pound C70s 0-to-60-mph times in the eight-second bracket.
</P>
<P>
   The interior features a layout easily recognized as Volvo, as is
the exterior, with its traditional square-V design front and grille
with the slash mark Volvo logo. There are few sharp angles on the
exterior, which is rounded and aerodynamic enough for the
convertible to be shockingly quiet, but not turbulence-free at
speed with the top down.
</P>
<P>
   The power top with its glass rear window is another one of those
mechanical marvels, lowering and hiding itself and vice versa in
less than 30 seconds, although it's best not to think about the
complex hand-cranking that must be done if it fails.
</P>
<P>
   Rear-quarter visibility isn't bad in the coupe but is as poor as
expected in the convertible when the top's up. That's about all
that will disconcert drivers of either, unless it's the little
uncertainty the four-speed automatic develops when slow-and-go
traffic leads to turbo-on, turbo-off motoring.
</P>
<P>
   The fit and finish of both models was up to Volvo's usual
standards, although the plastic bubble covering a clump of
electronic gear at the center front edge of the convertible top
needs better anchors than the non-working snap-ons on the
early-built tester.
</P>
<P>
   Audiophiles will love the powerful three-channel surround sound
stereo with its in-dash three-disc changer; others may feel the
surround speaker on the top center of the dash spoils what's
otherwise a reasonably graceful, but marginally over-engineered
packaging of controls and instrumentation. The turn signals on both
the saffron coupe and the light blue convertible were unduly lax
about canceling, but -- like the convertible's lack of top-up
visibility -- driver adaptability lessens the aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   Offsetting pluses include rear seats that accept adults who
don't mind compromised legroom, the expected durability of Volvo's
vehicles and the overall appeal of a sporty coupe/convert-
</P>
<P>
   ible that is foremost devoted to occupant safety.
</P>
<P>
   Chart:
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicles: 1998 Volvo C70 front-drive coupe/convertible
</P>
<P>
   Base prices: $39,970 for coupe; $43,000 for convertible
(estimated)
</P>
<P>
   Prices as tested: $41,825 for coupe; convertible unannounced
</P>
<P>
   Available options include: surround-sound stereo with 12
speakers, $595; traction control, $450; heated front seats, $235
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, dual side air bags, power
anti-lock disc brakes, switchable traction control, daytime running
lights, pop-up rollbars on convertible
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrains: 2.3-liter, five-cylinder turbocharged engine (236
horsepower), 2.4-liter five-cylinder turbocharged engine (190 hp),
four-speed automatic overdrive transmission with economy, sport and
winter modes, five-speed manual transmission
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 18 mpg regular unleaded city; 25 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
