<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Versatile dremel tool's many uses praised
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I come to sing the praises of a tool more often
considered hobbyist equipment than a serious woodworking implement.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Dremel tool, the little hand-held rotary grinder that
used to be called the Moto-Tool, but has more recently been renamed
the MultiPro. It is, in many respects, the WD-40 of tools.
</P>
<P>
   With a little imagination, you can do an amazing number of
things with it.
</P>
<P>
   I've had my Moto-Tool for so long I can't remember when or why I
first acquired it. It was certainly long before I got into
woodworking.
</P>
<P>
   I first used it in woodworking when I was going out of my mind
trying to get hinges installed properly on jewelry boxes. I was not
adept enough with chisels to get the mortises flat and at the right
depth.
</P>
<P>
   I must have read somewhere that Dremel made a router base for
the tool. I rushed out and bought it, along with a couple of
flat-bottom router bits.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose one could use a laminate-trimming router for the same
thing, but even that tool would be a little large. My old
single-speed Moto-Tool, mounted in the simple little router base,
did fine. It's powerful enough to do the job, but not powerful
enough to get away from you -- and small enough so you can see what
you're doing well enough to freehand most of the work.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I acquired one of the new variable-speed MultiPro
tools, which has five steps from 5,000 to 30,000 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   My first serious use of this tool was more in the line of home
repair than woodworking. At my daughter's house, my granddaughter
Alyson's bedroom door was suffering from seasonal problems and
wouldn't stay closed. The young lady understandably wanted it
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Upon examination, it became apparent that the bottom of the
latch was running perhaps 1/8 inch below the escutcheon covering
the door jamb. In common terms (I don't know the technical ones)
the latch wasn't going into the hole, and thus the door kept
falling open.
</P>
<P>
   There are several possible solutions to this, most of them
absurd, but being of a rather ponderous mind in such matters I ran
through all of them.
</P>
<P>
   I could take the door off the hinges and adjust its hanging. I
could move down the whatcha-macallit on the door jamb. I didn't
think I could move the door knob and latch assembly, however.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mismatch was so small, all of these solutions, in
addition to being a lot of work, seemed rather overdone.
</P>
<P>
   Why not simply lower the hole in the wood and extend the
matching escutcheon hole to match?
</P>
<P>
   Elementary. I brought over my new Dremel tool, attached one of
the small grinders that came with it, and ground about 1/8 inch off
the bottom of the metal escutcheon hole. Then I substituted one of
the sanding drums and cleaned out the wood behind it. The door shut
nicely. It took about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I see now that in addition to the router base, Dremel has a
little router table available for the tool, along with a drill
press attachment and a flexible shaft.
</P>
<P>
   There is a little end cap guide you can get along with the
appropriate tools for making cutouts in drywall and ceiling tile,
and cutting wall tile into shapes to fit around various fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   The cutoff wheels are also very useful; I first used these to
cut track when I was a model railroader. They're also mighty useful
for cutting down, or cutting off, bolts that are too long, or whose
nuts are rusted. Much easier than a hacksaw.
</P>
<P>
   The original point of the tool, probably, was grinding,
sharpening, sanding and polishing. Dremel has a bewildering array
of grinders, sanders and polishers available in every kind of
material, from diamond to rubber. I've seen jigs for using a Dremel
tool to sharpen saw chains. I'm working myself up to trying a
little gunsmithing with some of the mild polishers.
</P>
<P>
   This is an incredibly useful tool. The problem is to remember
what it can do. Mine came with a very useful booklet called ``175
Uses for the Dremel MultiPro,'' and I can see I've definitely been
underusing mine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
