<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: List makers' rank attempt to size century
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ As the 20th century winds down, the media
are celebrating by creating new and grander versions of this
century's preeminent literary form -- the list.
</P>
<P>
   With the millennium poised to reset us and our computers to the
Year Zero, we are being bombarded with top-100 lists that pay
homage to the past 98 years and assume nothing much will show up
over the next year and half.
</P>
<P>
   There's the 100 Most Important People of the 20th Century as
pronounced by Time Magazine. There's the America Film Institute's
Top 100 films. TV Guide and Nick at Nite did the 100 Greatest
Television Episodes of All Time. And now, the editorial board of
the Modern Library presents us with the 100 best English-Language
Novels of the 20th Century.
</P>
<P>
   This last list declares James Joyce the boss, the maximum
mack-daddy of 20th century letters and settles an old score by
pronouncing F. Scott Fitzgerald a better writer than Ernest
Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just me, but I believe Papa Hemingway was robbed. His
only work to make the list was the ``The Sun Also Rises'' and even
that work rated a paltry 45th place. That's only 10 places above
the badly aging beatnik speed-typing of Jack Kerouac's cult-novel
``On the Road.'' It's three big steps below James Dickey's
``Deliverance.''
</P>
<P>
   Harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Let it merely be noted in passing that Joyce, Dickey, Kerouac or
Fitzgerald do not inspire look-alike contests anywhere in Florida.
And for sheer number of bad imitators, not even Kerouac comes
close.
</P>
<P>
   Enough said. This is not about quibbling. Lists, like other
forms of literature, necessarily involve arbitrary and jarring
choices. Any list built on this scale is an automatic invitation to
an argument, a call to step outside, a challenge to one's
tastemanship.
</P>
<P>
   As usually practiced, the 100-list is a more intimate art form.
Most of the time, lists work well, or at least less annoyingly, on
a smaller scale -- the 100 Most Interesting Convicted Felons of
1997, the 100 Best-Groomed Sportswriters of the '90s, the 100 Songs
that Defined the Modern Accordion, The 100 Most Hummable Tunes ...
</P>
<P>
   Taking on a century of civilization is a big order for a top-100
list. Probably too big.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep of the entire 20th Century probably would probably
defeat any general-purpose top-100 list. It exhausts the medium.
This is the period of history when people first made airplanes,
spiral-bound notebooks, Orphan Annie mugs, atom bombs and electric
guitars. When people decided to have world wars because the old
kind didn't cut it any more. A time that first developed the
top-100 list as a way for folks to bring order to the chaos of
their times without having to read too much.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting a fairly busy century, person by person, object by
object, forces nonsensical judgments: Do Post-It Notes rank above
Viagra but below the stapler? Is ``Stairway to Heaven'' more
important than ``Yes Sir, That's My Baby''? Where do William
Jennings Bryan and Newt Gingrich rank in their respective ability
to be loud, self-righteous and annoying? Which world war was
better? Whose revolution was more fruitless?
</P>
<P>
   The mind boggles.
</P>
<P>
   And the lists are just beginning to pour in. There are two more
years of aggressive list making before us.
</P>
<P>
   I expect that well before December 1999 -- probably around the
time groups of experts will assemble their list of the Top 100
Lists of the Century -- many people won't be able to look at
another listing. They'll be listless. They won't even be able to
walk into a grocery store with one in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   But that's still far in the future and I'm not worried yet. I'm
content to stick with my own top-100 listing project. I intend to
declare top-100 lists to be No. 28 among the 100 Most Annoying
Things About 20th Century Daily Life. Well below busy-signals and
shock jocks but above flickering fluorescent lights, candy that
hangs up in vending machines and cars with starting cranks.
</P>
<P>
   There's still time for new entries and I might need to include
the Millennium Computer Bug, as well. Too soon to tell. I'll wait
to see if the computer will print out the list.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
