<HEADER>
A9042 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-SALAD24-COX     07-23 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SALAD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool carry-outs
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frying, searing and melting? Then you're experiencing the South
Florida summer with the rest of us. So who cooks when it's this
hot?
</P>
<P>
   Still, you have to eat. What you need is something cold and
savory _ and here's the key _ prepared by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Try the ultimate in summer meals to go: The takeout salad.
</P>
<P>
   Quit thinking of boring greens and unripe tomatoes with Italian
dressing in a squeeze pack. Instead, come with us on a search for
great salads from a variety of sources.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid the salad buffets or bars _ order yours made to go for top
freshness. For traditionalists, the delis and sandwich shops
frequently make their sandwich salads available by the pound _ you
can buy egg, chicken and ham salads, then put them on your own bed
of greens, or serve them from a bread bowl. Be creative.
</P>
<P>
   But don't leave your takeout salad in a hot car. Take a cooler
with ice to pack it in if you'll making stops once you pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some of the best salads we found:
</P>
<P>
   _ Asian influence: At Saigon Garden, a cozy Vietnamese
restaurant in Lantana, they prepare a refreshing mix of shredded
cabbage, carrots, and grapefruit sections, which can be topped with
your choice of shredded chicken, sliced pork or squid rings, all
sprinkled with chopped peanuts. Nuoc nam, the Viet version of Thai
fish sauce, is sweetened with sugar and flavored with more peanuts
to make the fresh dressing. It's a nice alternative to green
salads. ($5.25, about 1 1/2 servings as a main meal. Saigon Garden
is at 3618 Lantana Road, Lantana.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Dilly affair: Fresh chopped dill distinguishes the chicken
salad made by the CR Chicks folks. The chicken is in large strips,
enough for two servings from one salad, and if you make a pasta or
other food to accompany it, it could stretch to feed four. The
fresh dill and light mayonnaise binding are blended with the
chicken _ their signature food _ which has been rotisserie roasted
over wood. While you're there, pick up a pint of gazpacho, the cool
tomato onion and cuke soup, to go with the meal. Don't forget to
ask for croutons. ($3.25, for one salad that will feed two;
gazpacho is $1.50 for a cup. CR Chicks has several takeout stores:
in Stuart on U.S. 1; in Lake Park on Northlake Boulevard and in
Palm Springs on Congress Avenue.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Opa! A bread bakery is an unlikely place to find great salads,
but that's just what they've got at the Old School Bread Co. in
Delray Beach. The Greek is only one of several on the menu. Fresh
greens, chunks of feta cheese, calamata olives and the perfect
oregano-laced vinaigrette made this a winner. The special salad of
the day, a salad nicoise, made with fresh seared tuna, also looked
delicious and their soups were inspired. The bonus is the bread, of
course, for which the bakery is known. ($5.79; feeds one. At the
corner of Atlantic Avenue and First Avenue, across from Old School
Square in Delray Beach.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Say ole. Montezuma is a cozy Mexican restaurant in West Palm
Beach; the owner and his family are from Mexico. This is the real
thing. The cheese atop the salad is not Jack or cheddar, but
Mexican queso blanco, a creamier white cheese that resembles feta.
Shredded beef instead of ground beef is spread not into a huge
shell, but on fried tortillas. The salad is mounded atop it, and
dressed with a light mole. ($5.95, feeds one. Montezuma is at 5607
S. Dixie Highway, West Palm Beach.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Antipasto, anyone? You bet: this is nice enough for company.
Luna's, an Italian pizzeria and restaurant serves up little rolls
of salami, ham and provolone, dotted with pepperoni. They're
perched like blossoms among olives, onion rings and tomatoes that
top a fresh mix of greens. A fresh Italian vinaigrette is sent
along as dressing. But oh, those garlic knots! These rolls elevate
garlic bread to ambrosia. ($5.95, feeds two generously. Garlic
knots: $3 a dozen. Luna's is in downtown Stuart at 49 Flagler Ave.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Love that lobster. If it's seafood you crave, an obvious
choice for summer salads, then get the freshest you can find.
Seafood shops are a good choice _ try the one from Cod and Capers
in Palm Beach Gardens. There, if you call ahead, they make your
salad fresh to order. Lobster salad is a bit pricey at $19.95 a
pound, but then again, it's 90 percent lobster. Celery, onions and
mayonnaise help hold it all together. This is the classic mix they
use on those great lobster rolls from Boston to Maine, by the way.
You can specify Florida or Maine lobster in your salad for the same
price. ($19.95 a pound; figure three or four servings per pound,
depending on other foods served with it. Cod and Capers is in
Loehmann's Plaza on PGA Boulevard, just east of I-95.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Creative creations. Why not mix salads from a deli to get
something of your own creation? With a variety of prepared salads,
a deli or salad buffet gives you endless possibilities. For an
example, we ordered a half-pint of chilled roasted eggplant salad
from Torchio's in Boynton Beach, and added it to their pasta salad,
to come up with one of our own. A perfect luncheon salad.
</P>
<P>
   You could do the same with tuna or shrimp salad and pasta, or
tuna and a couscous salad from the health food store. If you can
find tabbouleh, the classic couscous with mint mix, try it with
some chicken or roasted lamb from a Middle Eastern deli. A fresh
spinach salad from the health food buffet, with fresh fruit on top
and a lemon yogurt dressing is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO CAPTIONS:
</P>
<P>
   TRY A CREATIVE COMBO Mix two salads for one hearty lunch or
dinner. Roasted eggplant and pasta salads from Torchio's in Boynton
Beach make a great combination.
</P>
<P>
   GO WITH A GRECIAN FORMULA A Greek salad from the Old School
Bread Company in Delray Beach may make you feel like you're dining
in the Mediterranean. Specialty breads round out the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
