<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ If you have tears, prepare to shed them now.
Ghigo Roli had just finished photographing the Basilica of St.
Francis of Assisi when the initial earthquake struck that, a few
days later, resulted in the collapse of sections of the dome.
Destroyed were irreplaceable frescoes by Florentine painters Giotto
and Cimabue. Abrams has published ``The Basilica of St. Francis of
Assisi: Glory and Destruction'' ($24.95), a book that will now
serve as an epitaph for one of the most beautiful artworks of the
Western world. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKREVIEW-FARRELLY _ THE COMEDY WRITER, by Peter Farrelly.
Doubleday; 351 pages; $12.95. As you might guess from his credits,
Farrelly writes good locker-room badinage and good one-liners. As
you also might guess, he's considerably less adept when he tries to
deal with anything approaching emotional reality. Perhaps the most
irritating thing about the book is the sheer unlikability of its
characters. Henry is impossible _ a neurotic, a hypochondriac, a
mope, a loser. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
