<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-SALAD _ Frying, searing and melting? Then you're
experiencing the South Florida summer with the rest of us. So who
cooks when it's this hot?
</P>
<P>
   Still, you have to eat. What you need is something cold and
savory _ and here's the key _ prepared by someone else. (Norris,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SALAD-SIDE _ Takeout is our first choice for quick, cool summer
meals, but if you're going to make your own, keep it simple. The
most you should do is boil pasta, as for the first recipe by Marcel
Desaulniers. The recipe is featured in his new book, ``Salad Days''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $27.50.) Note that the recipes in the book,
while inspired, are lengthy and involve several steps. (Recipes
follow.) Sidebar to SUMMER-SALAD. (Norris, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ If you have tears, prepare to shed them now.
Ghigo Roli had just finished photographing the Basilica of St.
Francis of Assisi when the initial earthquake struck that, a few
days later, resulted in the collapse of sections of the dome.
Destroyed were irreplaceable frescoes by Florentine painters Giotto
and Cimabue. Abrams has published ``The Basilica of St. Francis of
Assisi: Glory and Destruction'' ($24.95), a book that will now
serve as an epitaph for one of the most beautiful artworks of the
Western world. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKREVIEW-FARRELLY _ THE COMEDY WRITER, by Peter Farrelly.
Doubleday; 351 pages; $12.95. As you might guess from his credits,
Farrelly writes good locker-room badinage and good one-liners. As
you also might guess, he's considerably less adept when he tries to
deal with anything approaching emotional reality. Perhaps the most
irritating thing about the book is the sheer unlikability of its
characters. Henry is impossible _ a neurotic, a hypochondriac, a
mope, a loser. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN-ANNIVERSARIES _ It's the golden age of the golden
anniversary, thanks to couples who got hitched soon after World War
II. More than 6.1 million couples married between 1946 and 1948,
paving the way for the baby boom. In 1948, 1.8 million marriages
took place, a number that would not be matched again until 1966.
(Harper, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN-PARTYTIPS _ Tips for throwing a golden anniversary
get-together. (Harper, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
