<P>
   These columns for release Friday, July 24, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ It has been three years now, almost to the day,
that I walked into a Fort Worth nursing home to see my sister. The
air conditioning had died, not that day but the day before. The
nursing home staff was trying to use a series of small box fans to
keep the place
</P>
<P>
   cool. It wasn't working. As I began to search the halls for a
nurse -- there were always too few to do too much work -- one came
from behind me. Before I had a chance to say anything she said to
me:''Help us. Call someone. Make them get this fixed. These people
are going to die.'' (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ With elections just over, I had
planned to use this space for an in-depth analysis of the results.
Unfortunately, the perils of semirural living intervened and that
will have to be left to less astute observers. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ As the 20th century winds
down, the media are celebrating by creating new and grander
versions of this century's preeminent literary form -- the list.
With the millennium poised to reset us and our computers to the
Year Zero, we are being bombarded with top-100 lists that pay
homage to the past 98 years and assume nothing much will show up
over the next year and half. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal)
MOVED.
</P>
