<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, July 23, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LANDSLIDE-BUYOUTS (San Francisco) _ In a major policy shift, the
federal government has decided to make $20 million available to El
Nino's California landslide victims who agree to leave their houses
and relocate. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   KELLY-AFB (San Antonio) _ Despite protests from San Antonio
boosters, the Air Force has ordered Kelly Air Force Base to start
preparing to shift hundreds of jobs to a rival depot in Utah, with
some jobs moving in just two months. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-GUNS (Matamoros, Mexico) _ In prisons across Mexico, more
than 80 Americans are serving time for carrying a gun or possessing
ammunition. Many say they are unwitting victims of Mexico's tough
anti-gun laws, while the Mexican government says it stands by its
strict rules against bringing weapons across the border. By SUSANA
HAYWARD, PHILIP TRUE and JODI BIZAR. (For release Sunday, Jan. 26)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-UGLY-AMERICANS (Mexico City) _ For millions of Americans,
Mexico is a country no more distant than the width of a river, or
even a fence. Because of the ease of crossing ``al otro lado'' (the
other side), some travelers forget that are drastic differences _
in laws and mores, to name two. By PHILIP TRUE. (For release
Sunday, Jan. 26)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-PRISONS (Matamoros, Mexico) _ Human rights organizations
have criticized Mexican prisons, saying many are overcrowded and
dilapidated, with inadequate food and health services. But the
Santa Adelaida state prison defies the notion that life behind bars
in Mexico is hell on Earth. The reason, officials say, it that it
runs smoothly. By SUSANA HAYWARD. (For release Sunday, Jan. 26)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT-BUTTER (San Antonio) _ The Great American Food Almanac
tells us the average American student will have consumed 1,500
pounds of peanut butter and jelly sandwiches by the time he or she
graduates from high school. Guess what? Those popular sandwiches
are actually good for them. By BONNIE WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   INDOOR-TANS (San Francisco) _ Self-tanning requires a little bit
of planning and some fairly simple steps. You cannot just slop the
stuff on and get a terrific tan. Like a painter preparing his
canvas to accept color, you've got to prepare your skin. By CYNTHIA
ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SEAGATE-SHUGART (San Francisco) _ Most executives ``leave to
pursue other interests,'' retire or invoke some other catch phrases
to mask a sacking by the board of directors. But Seagate Technology
Inc.'s flamboyant founder and CEO, Al Shugart, was just plain,
outright fired by the world's largest computer disk-drive maker. By
MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SF-TRAFFIC (San Francisco) _ Traffic congestion in the San
Francisco Bay Area is expected to increase nearly 250 percent by
2020. In two decades, commuters can expect 366,000 hours of
collective daily delays, compared with the 105,000 hours they
waited on any given day in 1990, according to a study. By ANASTASIA
HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOMES (San Francisco) _ The median price of an existing,
single-family detached home in the Bay Area climbed 17.1 percent in
June to $335,740, a record high. The national median price is
somewhat less: $129,400. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PREVIEW-BOBBY (San Francisco) _ Oscar-winning actress Susan
Sarandon has signed on to make an NBC-TV movie about young Bobby
Griffith, who jumped to his death from a freeway overpass after
fighting for years to change his sexual orientation, as his
fundamentalist family and church said he should. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DRUDGE (Pasadena, Calif.) _ A man who once worked in the gift
shop at CBS and dug through the garbage, putting ``news'' and rumor
on-line from a dingy apartment in Hollywood, has become a celebrity
bigger than he could imagine and the man many believe will spell
the end of journalism all together. No, he's not Peter Arnett. He
is Matt Drudge. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-LISTS (San Francisco) _ On the heels of the hundred most
important people and the hundred best American films comes the
hundred best English-language novels of the century, trumpeted this
week by a panel of literates from Modern Library. It's another sign
of the sound-biting of the American intellect, of cutting culture
down to USA Today size, making it manageable and easy-to-swallow.
By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-CARMEN-POLICY (Burlingame, Calif.) _ As you knew he would,
Carmen Policy said what he wanted to say, the way he wanted to say
it, and left you to read the volumes between his lines. So we
shall. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ People always ask why there isn't
more good news in newspapers. A suburban Phoenix paper actually
tried to put out an all-good news edition on Tuesday. It got me
thinking. It may be possible to present all kinds of news as good
news, perhaps even San Francisco news. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I believe that all living
creatures, plants included, have an instinctive ``sense'' of inner
balance. Mess with the status quo and, don't kid yourself, the
creature is aware of the messing. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   AISAN-HOLOCAUST (Oakland, Calif.) _ The photos and text of ``The
Forgotten Holocaust'' exhibition at the Navy Library on Treasure
Island could nauseate viewers, but that is the point. The
organizers wanted to drive home the view that unspeakable
atrocities, perpetrated by the Japanese military in Asia from 1931
to 1945, aren't all that well known in the West. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
