<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9179 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-COSSACKS-$ADV2     07-23 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-COSSACKS-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S FEARED HORSEMEN TO RIDE AGAIN -- AS CRIME-BUSTERS
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, July 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ In bygone centuries the Cossacks were
loyal servants of Russia's czars who struck fear in the hearts of
their victims. They had a deserved reputation as expert horsemen
and merciless killers.
</P>
<P>
   This tradition-steeped warrior caste soon will ride again.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg officials plan to use Cossacks to patrol city
parks and assist regular police in fighting crime -- a variation of
the Guardian Angels, Russo-style.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is organized crime, why not an organized defense?''
said Arkady Kramarev, leader of the 2,000-strong Cossack community
of St. Petersburg and member of the local legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminals are really afraid of the Cossacks. The moment they
realize there are Cossacks on horseback they will run away,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The city's new police chief, Viktor Vlasov, has embraced the
idea and plans a pilot project this summer to deploy groups of 10
to 15 Cossacks in various city parks, where they will be supervised
by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he said, they will not carry swords, guns or weapons of
any kind. The local government is debating just how large the
contingents of Cossacks should be, whether they should be placed on
routine duty and whether they should be armed.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in the plan is the reality that Russia's police force,
ill-equipped and rife with corruption, is losing the war on crime
that sprang from the economic upheaval following the Soviet Union's
demise in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Cossacks arose in the 15th century from a loose community of
peasants, outlaws and mercenaries along Russia's southern border.
The nobility granted them freedom and other considerations in
exchange for defending the frontier against Turks, Tartars and
other invading tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Today throughout Russia, the Cossacks are undergoing a revival
of sorts after being submerged for decades by the Soviet Union.
Russians are seeking to learn more about their Cossack roots. Armed
Cossack paramilitary units have been formed in some areas of
southern Russia, home to most of the country's estimated 10 million
Cossack descendants.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Russian Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin
endorsed the idea of employing Cossack units along the country's
troublesome southern flank in the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have warned that Cossacks, with their ardent
patriotism and imperial origins, are potentially dangerous.
Cossacks earned their fearsome reputation in part by hounding and
executing Jews and other minorities during czarist times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attempts to flirt with the Cossack movement will lead to no
good,'' Sergei Kovalyov, a parliament member and human rights
advocate, told a news conference last fall.
</P>
<P>
   His human rights group, Memorial, issued a report in October
1997 which condemned the use of Cossacks and other nationalist
groups by the local authorities in the southern region of
Krasnodar. Regional administrators were encouraging the groups to
help impose order yet also ``inciting them to violence'' against
ethnic minorities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin -- sometimes called ``Czar Boris'' given
his powerful place in Russian politics -- has encouraged the
revival of the Cossack's culture and tradition. But after the 1996
presidential race, the Kremlin rejected an offer by Cossacks to
form an elite presidential guard.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg officials insist that their law-abiding Cossacks
will supplement, not supplant, the regular police. They already
have demonstrated their effectiveness, the police chief said.
</P>
<P>
   In his former job as head of the transportation police in the
northwestern region, Vlasov in 1993 established Cossack foot
patrols at stations and on trains traveling to and from St.
Petersburg. The idea came to him amid a wave of attacks on
passengers, and it worked. Crime aboard trains dropped and the
patrols continue today -- with no recorded complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Kramarev, the Cossack ``ataman'' or leader, also points to a
tourism dividend for the former imperial capital. Cossacks on
horseback, with traditional sheepskin hats and colorful uniforms
reminiscent of their 19th-century garb, would be an entertaining
addition to the landscape of grand palaces and palatial parks, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with tradition, the Cossacks will not be paid. They will
provide their own horses, but the city will help them with the
costs of feeding and caring for the animals.
</P>
<P>
   In imperial times, Cossacks were exempt from taxes and allowed
to retain the booty from their marauding. Vlasov said ``a certain
system of incentives,'' which he did not specify, will be set up
for St. Petersburg's Cossacks based on their performance -- the
more arrests they help police make, the more perks they'll receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the Cossacks are restoring their own society all over
Russia,'' said Vlasov, whose wife comes from a Cossack family.
``For them it is important to feel they are contributing to the
life of the city and are useful.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
