<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RAINMAKERS-BOS     07-23 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RAINMAKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL STOP THE RAIN? THE MAYOR WILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Tamara Volkova hates holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Volkova, an engineer for the Mir space station's mission
control, lives in a northwest suburb of Moscow. And whenever the
Russian capital celebrates a special occasion, she prepares for
rain _ lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain, rain, rain, rain,'' Volkova grumbled. ``Every time they
put on a big show, we get downpours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' is the city of Moscow, which on Sunday wrapped up the
first annual World Youth Games, an athletic competition that city
officials hope will boost their campaign to bring the Summer
Olympic Games back to Moscow in 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that Mother Nature might rain on Moscow's parade, City
Hall did what it often does on special days: It sent a squadron of
cloud-seeding planes into the skies to ensure fair weather for the
opening and closing ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Seeding does not evaporate rain clouds; it makes them dump their
precipitation someplace else. And in the case of Moscow, that
someplace is usually the northwestern suburb where Volkova lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have rain on the brain,'' Volkova grumbled. ``We pay
the price for their sunshine in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not entirely. Designer weather is an expensive proposition
for Moscow. The city set aside some $400,000 to chase the clouds
away, although the actual cost may be more, according to Anatoly
Yakovlev of Russia's federal weather service, whose specialists do
the seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Moscow, like the rest of Russia, is chronically short
of funds, spending so much money on the weather may seem frivolous.
But that is not how Moscow officials see it, not in a city whose
name derives from an ancient Slavic word for ``wet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was the money well spent? Yes,'' said Galina Sugak of the
Moscow mayor's office. ``Otherwise we would have spent this
important occasion sitting in a constant shower of rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of places use cloud seeding to prevent dangerous hail or as
an aid to farmers. But the former Soviet Union does vanity cloud
seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds were seeded on many a May Day and during the 1980 Summer
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   For a Soviet leadership that irrigated deserts, built big cities
in the tundra, and tried to reverse the flow of rivers, a little
climate control was a drop in the bucket by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's ambitious mayor, Yury Luzhkov, who likes to put on big
events to show off his city, has made meteorological manipulation
one of his trademarks. Last September, planes kept the skies clear
for three days during Luzhkov's celebration of the city's 850th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The principle of cloud seeding is fairly simple. Clouds are made
up of tiny droplets of water that become rain when the droplets
grow heavy enough to fall. The planes douse the clouds with
chemicals that make the droplets expand and fall before the clouds
get to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   People in the suburbs do not like it, but no one complains too
loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia still does not have the kind of civil society where
people stand up and say, `Why do we have to accept their rain on
our heads?''' the weather service's Yakovlev observed.
</P>
<P>
   And cloud seeding for odd anniversaries and dubious occasions is
catching on throughout the former Soviet Union. Among the weather
service's recent clients was the southern Russian city of
Stavropol, which eliminated the chance of rain on its 220th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the clouds are too thick, or the storm fronts too
numerous, for cloud seeding to prevent rain. That looked to be the
case for the July 13 opening festivities of the World Youth Games.
</P>
<P>
   But Luzhkov, who had workers spruce up the city and police ship
homeless people out of Moscow to prepare for the games, ordered the
cloud seeders to redouble their efforts. The seeding did not
completely stop the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when Mr. Luzhkov opened the games, there was a ray of
sun,'' Yakovlev said. ``And so he was happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
