<HEADLINE>
_2 VACCINES ON TRACK TO CURB LYME DISEASE  
 _HEART RISK FOUND HIGH FOR TYPE 2 DIABETICS  
 _ITCHING FOR A MANGO? BEWARE THOSE RINDS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 2 vaccines on track to curb Lyme disease
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not one but two vaccines to prevent Lyme disease _ the nation's
most common insect-borne infection with more than 16,000 cases in
1996 _ are on track toward final approval on the basis of studies
published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccines were between 76 and 92 percent effective in
preventing doughnut rash, fever, joint pain, and other symptoms of
the tick-bite disease after a series of three injections over a
one-year period, according to reports involving more than 21,000
adults that appear in the current New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The drug companies behind the two vaccines are sparring over
which one is better, but Lyme disease experts said the results look
pretty comparable.
</P>
<P>
   One vaccine, developed by the French firm Pasteur Merieux
Connaught, lowered the risk of Lyme disease symptoms by 68 percent
in the first year after vaccination, and 92 percent among those who
got a one-year booster shot. But men over age 60 had a second-year
efficacy rate of 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The other, formulated by SmithKline Beecham Pharmaceuticals, had
a 49 percent efficacy rate in the first year and 76 percent after
the booster shot.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Allen C. Steere of New England Medical Center and Tufts
University Medical School noted that the SmithKline vaccine was 100
percent effective in preventing infections of the Lyme disease
organism that did not produce symptoms, at least not during the
study. That can be important, Steere said, because some percentage
of these asymptomatic infections can produce arthritis or
neurological disease months or years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can say whether one is better than the
other,'' said Dr. Leonard H. Sigal of the Robert Wood Johnson
Medical School in New Brunswick, New Jersey, who led the test of
the Pasteur Merieux product. ``What one can say is the two vaccines
are safe and effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Tests in children, who suffer 23 percent of reported Lyme
disease cases, are just beginning. Researchers and the drug
companies hope to get approval for the adult vaccines before ticks
carrying Lyme disease begin biting next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Steere and Sigal said the vaccines should be targeted to people
living in high-risk areas such as the south coast of New England
who are likely to be exposed to ticks carrying the Lyme disease
organism. But Dr. John M. Zahradnik, Pasteur Merieux's director of
clinical research, said: ``The people who are going to get the
vaccine are those who really want it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Heart risk found high for type 2 diabetics
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a red flag for people with type 2 diabetes and their
doctors: Even if they have not had a heart attack, their risk of
having one or dying from coronary disease is just as high as
nondiabetic individuals who have suffered heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetics' coronary risk, reported in a study in the current New
England Journal of Medicine, was surprisingly high, said Dr. Steven
M. Haffner of the University of Texas Health Sciences Center in San
Antonio, the study's first author.
</P>
<P>
   Among diabetics with no prior history of heart attacks, 20
percent suffered one over a seven-year period. If they had had a
heart attack, their chances of suffering a second one jumped to 45
percent. Nondiabetics had a 3.5 percent chance of a first-time
heart attack and a 19 percent risk of a repeat attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication is that very aggressive treatment of diabetics
may be important,'' Haffner said. That means diet and medicine to
lower elevated blood pressure and cholesterol, vigorous weight
control and smoking cessation, and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Itching for a mango? Beware those rinds
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do mangos and poison ivy have in common? A 27-year-old
Texas man discovered the answer was as clear as the palm of his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   After peeling a mango, the man rested his hand on his thigh
while talking on the telephone. He subsequently suffered an itchy
red rash on his leg in the shape of his hand, a picture of which
appears in the current New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a boy, the man had been sensitized to poison ivy and
poison oak, said Dr. Mark O. Tucker and Dr. Chad R. Swan of St.
Joseph Hospital in Houston. The sap in mango rind contains resins
similar enough to those in the poisonous plants to confuse the
immune system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-23 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHINING A LIGHT ON THREE HOT PERENNIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American gardeners have become recreational shoppers, browsing
nurseries and catalogs for new flowers that will give them
something unusual to enjoy in their gardens and to show off to
their friends. Through stepped-up breeding programs, international
trade, and plant exploration, nurseries are filling this demand.
New plants were high on the agenda of the 900 garden professionals
who attended the national meeting of the Perennial Plant
Association here in Boston earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Three rising stars of the perennial border that enjoyed the
spotlight at the symposium were hellebores, geraniums, and
clematis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hellebores are some of the hottest plants available right
now,'' said Thomas Fischer, executive editor of Boston-based
Horticulture magazine, who maintains a 60-foot border of the newest
hellebore hybrids in his Jamaica Plain garden.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? A March bloomtime when not much else is going on in
the garden, and an explosion in new forms and colors produced by
breeders overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer thinks hellebores are the perfect perennial for shade.
``Keep your hostas and hemerocallis _ give me H. xhybridus!'' he
said at the symposium at the Westin Hotel at Copley Place.
</P>
<P>
   Often called ``orientalis hybrids,'' H. orientalis, or Lenten
rose, the popular garden hellebore is actually a genetic mishmash
of various hellebore species, said Fischer. Available only in murky
shades of green, white, or purple a few years ago, the 2-inch
flowers now come in clear new tones of yellow, apricot, maroon, and
pink. There are also picotee flowers (with colored rims) and
doubles that look almost like perfect miniature peonies, quite a
prize when snow is still on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   A partly shaded hillside that you can see from inside the house
(since they bloom so early) is the ideal location for this tough
little plant that only requests good drainage. The foot- high
foliage is evergreen, but so battered by winter's end that it
should be cut to the ground as new foliage and buds emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Since these slow growers can't be reproduced through ``test
tube'' methods, young plants are seed-grown and expensive. Fischer
urges gardeners to grow their own from fresh seed (see sidebar), a
three-year process. He buys seeds from Gisela Schmiemann of
Cologne, Germany, who has improved on a base of stock plants from
the late Helen Ballard, the century's premier hellebore breeder.
</P>
<P>
   But there are so many of the new hellebores in production now
that an onslaught of potted plants will soon arrive. For instance,
Briggs Nursery of Olympia, Wash., will be shipping 100,000 mostly
red and pink hellebores of the new Royal Heritage(TM) strain to
regional nurseries this fall and they should begin appearing for
sale next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hardy geraniums are a passion of Robert Herman, new director of
horticulture at White Flower Farm, the Litchfield, Conn., catalog
giant. Herman spoke at the Perennial Plant Association symposium.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have long preferred its ubiquitous cousin, the potted
annual geranium, which sports stiff bright lollipops of color all
summer. In contrast, hardy geraniums look lax and informal as
wildflowers, with many blooming in watercolor tones of pink, blue,
and purple.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fit in with the new design trends. People want a relaxed,
natural garden with very little maintenance, and these plants have
almost no insect or disease problems,'' said Herman.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting is Brookside, which has the desirable blue
flowers of longtime-favorite Johnson's Blue but blooms three times
as long.
</P>
<P>
   White Flower Farm is greatly expanding its geranium offerings.
This fall they offer the new Alpenglow, a prolific carmine red
selection of Geranium saguineum.
</P>
<P>
   Geraniums are treasured for a long bloom period from late May
through July. Some new cultivars are extending that into fall,
including Ann Folkard, with purple flowers and chartreuse spring
foliage, and Mavis Simpson. Another is Patricia, one of some 350
crosses made by reclusive Alan Bremner of the Orkney Islands off
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Next spring WFF will offer Bremner's Phillippe Vapelle, a cross
that combines the lovely foliage of G. renardii and the large
purple flowers of G. platypetalum. Also being offered next spring
are Rosemoor, a selection of G. magnificum with large violet
flowers, and the unusual deep pink Sirek, both new selections from
Dr. Hans Simon of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many different geraniums becoming available, in
fact, that you need a score card to make your selections. Herman
has one and it goes like this: G. wlassovianum has the best fall
foliage color; Lily Lovell is the prettiest G. phaeum for dry, part
shade; Spinners has the bluest flowers; Brookside is the longest
blooming blue; G. cantabrigiense makes the best ground cover with
great fall color; G. oxonianum Claridge Druce is the
fastest-growing if you want a more rampant ground cover; A.T.
Johnson is the best of the carefree oxonianum geranium varieties
for looks and good behavior; and Amy Doncaster is the best
sylvaticum geranium for dappled shade or a woodland's edge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Sue Austin opened her Completely Clematis Specialist
Nursery in Ipswich 13 years ago, her business has doubled every
year. (Austin also spoke at the Perennial Plant Association
symposium.)
</P>
<P>
   Americans are discovering new ways of displaying clematis, such
as letting them clamber up beanpole tripods in the middle of the
border, or up lilacs, cedars, and other trees and shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more interested in climbers and structures now,''
said Austin. ``But you can have clematis without having walls for
them to climb on. Let them ramble. I have Polish Spirit running
around in the border. They weave. I say let them rip.'' In short,
don't truss them up like Joan of Arc on the stake.
</P>
<P>
   Austin obviously favors a relaxed approach. ``It doesn't matter
if you undercut or overcut. And if you don't like where they're
growing, most clematis are easy to transplant.'' But she does urge
gardeners to plant new clematis several inches deeper than where
the stem starts growing so they can produce new shoots if disaster
befalls them.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is a champion of small-flowered clematis, which though
less flashy and widely available than their large-flowered cousins,
are winning fans for their toughness and resistance to dreaded
clematis wilt.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the breeding is taking place in Europe and Japan.
``There are plenty of new ones and some of the new introductions
are great. Barry Fretwell of England is breeding a lot with the
small-flowered viticellas, alpinas, and macropetalas,'' Austin
said, citing three species of small-flowered clematis. ``He created
C. alpina Jacqueline du Pre, which has small bells of a bright
pink. We brought the new small-flowered C. albina Helsingborg and
C. macropetala Jan Lindmark into this country, which were bred by
Magnus Johnson of Sweden.''
</P>
<P>
   People are ``nuts for fragrance now,'' said Austin. All the
montana clematis are sweetly scented, especially the new Mayleen.''
She also recommends C. rehderiana and C. recta for scent.
</P>
<P>
   Most clematis breeding takes place abroad. Even the new
red-flowered Clematis texansis Lady Bird Johnson comes from
England, though it traces its wild roots back to Texas. ``It's a
wonderful plant, but the name's a marketing ploy,'' said Austin.
But no marketing ploy can outdo the Princess Diana clematis, an old
variety that was recently renamed. ``It used to be called The
Princess of Wales, but since it's been around for 50 or 60 years,''
said Austin, ``it was originally named for a different princess.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCES FOR GARDENERS &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some plant sources. Most will wait until fall to ship:
</P>
<P>
   _Collector's Nursery, 16804 NE 102nd Ave., Battle Ground, WA
98604; phone 360-574-3832. Catalog $2. Geraniums, good hellebores
mostly from English sources, other plants.
</P>
<P>
   _Completely Clematis Specialty Nursery, 217 Argilla Road,
Ipswich, MA 01938-2617; phone 978-356-3197. Catalog $3. Open Monday
through Friday, 8 a.m. to 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _Heronswood Nursery Ltd., 7530 299th St. NE, Kingston, WA 98346;
phone 360-297-4172, fax 297-8321. Catalog $5. Geraniums,
hellebores, small-flowered clematis, and other plants.
</P>
<P>
   _Gisela Schmiemann, Belvederestrasse 45a, D-50933 Cologne,
Germany. Seeds of species and distinct color groups of Helleborus x
hybridus. Free seed list.
</P>
<P>
   _White Flower Farm, Box 50, Litchfield, CT 06759-0050; phone
800-503-9624. Free catalog. Geraniums and other nursery stock.
</P>
