<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN WHO LIVE ON A DIFFERENT PLANET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the days when I was inordinately fond of male attention,
I met a handsome guy at a cocktail party. He was unhappily married,
he told me, looking deep into my eyes. His wife not only didn't
understand him, she neglected him, leaving him to watch television
by himself night after night while she fiddled in the kitchen or
busied herself upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   My heart went out to this poor guy who was being abandoned every
evening in spite of his smoldering eyes and seductive gaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is she doing with herself, do you think?'' I asked,
trying to fathom how any woman in her right mind could be so
foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fussing over the kids,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have kids? How old are they?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, 3 and 6,'' he said with a shrug. He was eager to get back
to more congenial topics like ways I could help to brighten his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean she's cleaning up after dinner and putting three
little kids to bed alone and you resent that she's not watching TV
with you?'' He was flattered by my response. He took the wild look
in my eyes to mean I was getting excited, but a friend, who noticed
that I was pawing the ground like a maddened bull, hurried over,
took me by the shoulders, and led me away before I did him serious
harm.
</P>
<P>
   Let me say here that I know that not all men are this lazy, this
self-centered, or this insensitive. Let me reassure you that in the
stories that follow, the men in question bear no resemblance to the
man I married, any husband of any of my friends, or any man I have
ever met in this or any former life. These stories are strictly
hearsay, unreliable gossip about the habits of a group of men who
dwell on the western rim of Saturn's innermost ring. I retell them
here only to make us all deliriously happy that we do not have guys
like this on our planet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there was a fellow who was convinced that the woman
in his life liked making things unnecessarily difficult? He tried
to be helpful by saying things like, ``Sweets, don't make this
harder than it has to be,'' or ``Relax, hon. We can let that go
another week.'' He was known far and wide as the man who never saw
a refrigerator that needed to be cleaned or a dish that needed to
be washed. He considered it his valuable contribution to the
relationship that he could always decrease the volume of work
needed to be done (while he was around).
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the guy who took housework so seriously that he
insisted upon taking full responsibility for his part. When he
emptied the dishwasher, he'd sing ``I did it my way'' at the top of
his lungs as he carefully tucked the serving utensils into the
drawer with the frying pans. This fellow felt deeply hurt when
criticized. The injured tone in which he delivered, ``Well, if you
wanted it done a certain way, you should have done it yourself,''
is currently being replayed on a Web site called
busydivorcelawyersofamerica.com.
</P>
<P>
   How about the guy whose only reason for ever sitting down was
because it was the best position in which to wait to be asked? He
never heard the dirty dishes ask, ``Will you wash me?'' or the
trash begging to be taken out. He was waiting for specific
instructions from his significant other, preferably in writing, at
which time it is presumed he would have swung into immediate
action. We will never know, however, because one night, when his
wife climbed into bed, she discovered their dog had died there
hours earlier. The poor man never did understand why she was upset
that he hadn't removed the body. Puzzled to the end, his final
words were, ``All she had to do was ask me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the romantic guys who can always be counted upon
to fend off housework by whispering into a delicate ear, ``Let's
forget about all this and go have fun.'' There are the athletes who
are indefatigable on the golf course, only to find themselves
fading fast after folding two king-size sheets. There are the poor
CEOs who cannot figure out how to run a washing machine for the
life of them. Soul-searchers all, they rate themselves all the way
from ``extremely helpful'' to ``supremely helpful,'' while
bemoaning the lack of mathematical ability in females that prevents
an accurate assessment of the size of their contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The latest reports from Saturn indicate that the few women who
have not taken the easy way out and flung themselves off the edge
of a ring have fled the galaxy, making even more remarkable the
conflict-free existence led by so many loving helpmates here on
Earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
