<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-23 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO JERRYS CALLING JORDAN'S BLUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two Jerrys are about to declare official war on Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Floyd has resigned at Iowa State and is now in Chicago. If
Jerry Reinsdorf and Jerry Krause name Floyd coach of the Chicago
Bulls, they are declaring that a rookie college mentor is more
important to the team than Michael Jordan. What other conclusion
can anyone draw?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the Jerrys are calling Jordan's bluff. No. 23
has said repeatedly that he would not play for anyone other than
Phil Jackson, who resigned at the conclusion of the playoffs. But
Michael has occasionally softened that stance, indicating that in
his mind, there still is some wiggle room on the issue, except that
said wiggle room specifically excluded Tim Floyd, scarred for life
in Jordan's mind as an FOK (Friend of Krause).
</P>
<P>
   It is a truly bizarre situation. Here, on the one hand, is the
world's greatest player, still a clear step or two ahead of the
field. Here, on the other hand, is a college coach of modest
accomplishment. Jordan vs. Floyd ... which way will the city of
Chicago go? Tough call, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Without Jordan, the Bulls are just another fairly decent team.
In terms of winning a seventh championship, it really doesn't
matter who coaches them if Michael isn't around. Floyd adds
nothing. If I were a Bulls fan, I would be apoplectic.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball fans in Moscow, Idaho; New Orleans; and Ames, Iowa,
know who Tim Floyd is. Dedicated readers of the Blue Ribbon
Basketball Yearbook know who Tim Floyd is. But Michael Jordan
doesn't know who Tim Floyd is, and he doesn't care, either. Michael
doesn't have the patience to wet-nurse a college coach.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Jerry Krause production, pure and simple. It speaks to
the astounding faith and confidence Mr. Reinsdorf has in his
secretive general manager. The Jerrys (itals)might(unitals) _ I
stress the word _ have been able to sell both Jordan and the
Chicago basketball public on a George Karl or even a Paul Silas.
Jordan might very well have decided he could easily live with
Silas. But this college guy has no shot, especially since his claim
to Windy City fame is that he is a fishing buddy of the
much-despised general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan camp is hardly in need of smelling salts. ``I think
it would have been a shock to anyone close to the scene if Tim
Floyd had (itals)not(unitals) been hired,'' David Falk told the
Associated Press. ``This was a decision that was made a year ago.''
Falk, in case you don't know, is the superagent whose great fortune
in life is to represent Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they may say that, but having the name out there is one
thing, and it now being an apparent reality is another. You'd hear
it and you'd think about it and you'd say, ``Nah.'' You'd run all
the possible candidates through your mind and you'd wind up saying,
``Tim Floyd? Why?'' You just couldn't believe that Jerry Krause
would be brazen enough to do it, because there could be no surer
way of driving Michael Jordan away than by selecting as Phil
Jackson's successor an inexperienced college coach (itals)who
actually enjoys sitting in a boat for hours on end with Jerry
Krause.(unitals) If you happen to be Michael Jordan, that is an
incomprehensible thought.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's name has been in the public discourse for at least two
years. There was a mild flap last summer when Floyd was invited to
the wedding of a Krause daughter and Jackson wasn't. Krause
attempted to defuse that by explaining that the Krauses and
Jacksons have never really socialized and that in his view, a
wedding invitation was supposed to be for a friend, not a business
associate. At no point in the past two years had Krause actually
acknowledged any intention of naming Floyd coach.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Krause is not known as ``The Sleuth'' without reason,
is he? As Jerry himself has said many times, ``I don't want
everyone to know my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause watchers think naming Floyd is a classic Krause-like move
because Krause has spent the last decade searching for a coach who
would let him be a buddy. But what's with Reinsdorf? ``This is one
of the great mysteries of life,'' marvels a longtime NBA insider.
``Jerry Reinsdorf has a choice between Phil Jackson and Jerry
Krause, and guess what. He has a choice between Michael Jordan and
Jerry Krause, and guess what. He has a choice between Scottie
Pippen and Jerry Krause, and guess what. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   'Tis said there is nothing new under the sun, and that's the
gospel truth, because what's going on in Chicago is no different in
the essentials than what took place here in Boston 32 years ago.
Red Auerbach had announced his retirement, and the Celtics needed a
coach. The only catch was that Red knew very well that the team's
key player was such a singular presence that he wouldn't play for
just anybody. This is just one more example of the amazing parallel
between Bill Russell and Michael Jordan, the two greatest winners
the sport of basketball has ever known. Anyway, Red gently tossed
one name at Russell (some say it was then Brandeis coach Bob
Brannum, a former Celtic for whom Red had enormous fondness), and
Russell demurred.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Red went to Plan B. Figuring that Russell
wouldn't be comfortable playing for anyone but himself, he made him
player-coach. The Celtics won two more championships.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure that was never an option in Chicago, because the NBA
has been allowed to get too complicated. The idea of a player-coach
in a league where teams routinely have three assistant coaches
(this past season, the Bulls had four) and where there is
micromanagement of every offensive possession is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what I would have done.
</P>
<P>
   What's the big deal? Tex Winter is still there, and the Bulls
could still run his triple-post offense. Frank Hamblen and Bill
Cartwright are still there, and they could be the general eyes and
ears on the bench while Michael is out on the floor. Michael is the
conscience of the team as it is. If he didn't like the way someone
was playing, he could get the offending party out of the game any
time he liked.
</P>
<P>
   I mean it. The logistical details could be worked out. Michael
would have what he always wants and probably deserves: namely, the
final say. The Russell-Jordan parallel is perfect. Russell was just
as important to the Celtics 32 years ago as Jordan is to the Bulls
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate game of chicken with the world's greatest
athlete,'' says our insider. ``And the two people who are
shuddering the most today are David Stern and Dick Ebersol.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that Jerry Reinsdorf is making a choice between
Jerry Krause and Michael Jordan, and he is choosing Jerry Krause. I
certainly understand why Jerry Krause has always insisted that
Jerry Reinsdorf is the greatest owner in sports.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that in Chicago, Mr. Krause holds a minority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
