<SLUG> BC-NY-SHAKESPEARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALK-ONS PART OF PARKING LOT BARD IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nowhere in Act One of ``Othello'' does Shakespeare
call for an old Chinese woman to lumber across the stage, but one
did just that the other night in a production of the play put on by
the Expanded Arts theater company.
</P>
<P>
   Such things happen all the time in this company's shows, for
they are performed in an outdoor parking lot on Manhattan's Lower
East Side.
</P>
<P>
   You've probably heard of ``Shakespeare in the Park'' _ the late
producer Joseph Papp's celebrated idea of staging Shakespeare plays
for free in Central Park. Well, Expanded Arts took the concept a
few steps further and launched ``Shakespeare in the Parking Lot.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes the neighborhood's stragglers, sirens, screaming
children, and oblivious passersby become as much a part of the
action as the actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locale definitely has its problems,'' said Jennifer Spahr,
the company's 30-year-old executive director, laughing. ``But we
try to turn the problems into assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Spahr remembers three summers ago, during the series' first
season, when, right in the middle of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,''
a garbage truck roared into the parking lot at the same time each
night.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring there was no way to outshout the noise, the cast made
the truck a part of the show, bowing before it as if it were some
sort of chariot of the gods.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, during a ``Road Warrior''-like modernization of
``Macbeth,'' a member of a real-life youth gang who was watching
the show one night hopped on the motorcycle that Macduff had ridden
on to the set. When the show's director discreetly asked the
interloper to get off the bike, the teen tough pulled out a knife.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis was resolved when the actors _ dressed like
street-gang punks themselves _ came growling over to the bike with
their clubs, hubcaps, and various other weapon-props, and scared
the kid off.
</P>
<P>
   Spahr and her husband, Robert, who codirects Expanded Arts, got
the idea for their peculiar variation on street theater shortly
after they moved their company's slightly more legitimate indoor
theater from the East Village to Ludlow Street, a half-block south
of Delancey. (They live with their 2-year-old son, Zachary, in an
apartment above the theater.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very small theater, and we would look out on this
enormous parking lot across the street, and notice that it wasn't
used at night,'' she recalled. ``It was an empty space. And I
couldn't help think of Peter Brook's line that all empty spaces can
be theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the lot is city-owned, she made inquiries at the
Department of Transportation, which directed her to the local
Community Board and Business Improvement District, which told her
she would have to get residents to sign a petition, stating it was
fine with them to play host to an outdoor theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Spahr went on, ``almost nobody in the neighborhood
spoke English, so I went to someone at the Baskin Robbins and had
him translate the petition into Chinese.'' She then went around,
stopping people on the street and showing them the document. More
than 250 signed it.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband still argue over which one of them came up
with the inspired moniker, Shakespeare in the Parking Lot.
``Whoever it was, we just died laughing when we first heard it,''
she recalled. ``We couldn't believe nobody had ever thought of it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The spectators, who usually number around 100 and sit on folding
chairs, tend to be young _ mainly under 30 _ but otherwise reflect
the diversity of the area. There are the alternative-theater mavens
who cross Delancey from SoHo and the Bowery; the Chinese teens from
around the corner, who come to gawk and jeer but sometimes stay,
entranced; the Hasidic Jews, who dwell in the high-rises near the
Williamsburg Bridge, a few blocks away; and those, from all over
town, who have spotted a blurb in the Village Voice or Time Out New
York and come out of sheer curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Papp's successors uptown have little cause for worry.
Shakespeare in the Parking Lot is, of necessity, a rather chintzy
affair. The backdrop for its ``stage'' is the graffiti-scrawled
brick wall of a T-shirt factory, not the spectacular sunset and
skyscrapers enveloping Central Park. There are few costumes and
fewer props. The actors are unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Near the beginning of ``Othello,'' when the script calls for
Desdemona's father to lean out his bedroom window after being
awakened by Iago and Roderigo, this production must settle for
having him stand atop the foot-high ledge of a sign reading ``4
Hour Parking Limit _ 25(cents) Per 20 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Spahr said, smiling, ``we're not the Publick, but I
hope there's a certain heart and soul here that you don't find
elsewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
