<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-MOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BETTER MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, the Anir Mouse from Animax International of
Oslo, doesn't look like a computer mouse at all _ more like a
mutant joystick. Then there's the name: What's an Anir? Some
ill-tempered Norse god?
</P>
<P>
   But then I wrapped my hand around it for a few weeks and
realized that the Anir Mouse is the most comfortable device of its
kind I've ever touched.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand why the $50 Anir Mouse is so comfortable
simply by resting your forearm on a table. Just plop it down on the
surface. Now notice how it's lying. Chances are that most of the
weight is resting on the outer edge of your arm and hand, with your
thumb facing upward.
</P>
<P>
   The designers of the Anir Mouse have created a device that takes
advantage of this natural resting position of the arm. With a
standard mouse, you twist the wrist to put your hand in the right
position, and to slide the mouse around. It's a slight effort, but
hours of mousing around can take a toll on your arm.
</P>
<P>
   With the Anir Mouse, I simply drop the edge of my hand on the
base and curl my fingers around the grip. My thumb rests easily on
a rocker switch at the top of the grip. I can make left or right
mouse clicks simply by tilting my thumb from side to side. A third
mouse switch is embedded in the grip, where I can click it with the
slightest pressure.
</P>
<P>
   To move the mouse, I just pivot my elbow from side to side or
pull it back and forth from the shoulder. I never have to twist my
wrist.
</P>
<P>
   It took me a day or two to get used to the way the Anir Mouse
works. For example, to use it properly, you must rest your forearm
on the desk. That means the Anir Mouse will take up more room on
your desk than a traditional mouse. But what you lose in desk space
you gain in comfort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9227 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-23 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE HOPING SURFERS WILL COME TO THE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp. has taken quite a beating from
Microsoft Corp. But so far, there's no sign of brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape once held over 80 percent of the market for Internet
browsers, with people paying up to $79 a copy. Today the company
is &UR;  &LR; forced to give them away, and still Netscape's market share
dwindles _ it's &UR;  &LR; down to about 52 percent now, with Microsoft at 45
percent and gaining fast.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no longer much hope of relief from that federal
antitrust case against Microsoft's browser-marketing practices.
Last month, a federal appeals court said that Microsoft has every
right to build its own browser directly into the Windows operating
system, even if it hurts Netscape's business. And whatever the
final outcome of the case, it'll likely come far too late to
provide Netscape with any relief.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation time? I'll say. But you can be desperate and shrewd
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; I've been playing with a beta-test version of the newest
Netscape browser software, Communicator 4.5. For the most part it's
just another browser, with some fresh new bugs added. But Netscape
has added some clever new features that will appeal to serious Web
surfers, while setting the stage for Netscape's plan for long-term
survival.
</P>
<P>
   Having fallen on hard times in the software business, Netscape
is now trying to become an Internet media company. Already its
Netcenter Web site is one of the 10 most visited Web sites, largely
because users of Communicator get taken automatically to the
Netcenter home page.
</P>
<P>
   The newest Communicator features reinforce this idea. Indeed,
every time you use the browser, it'll seek out ways to bring you
back to the Netcenter portal.  &UR;  &LR; Netscape is trying to drive traffic
to its portal, so it can attract paying advertisers and sponsors,
and so it can persuade you to shop at Netscape's on-line retail
mall.
</P>
<P>
   The company is doing this the right way _ with a system called
Smart Browsing that links Netcenter and the browser in ways that
make life easier for the common Web surfer.
</P>
<P>
   Say you're looking for Delta Airlines. These days, you'd
probably head to Yahoo or AltaVista to look up the Web address. Or
you could just type Delta Airlines in the address space of the new
Netscape browser.
</P>
<P>
   In a flash, the browser contacts Netcenter, where Netscape has
compiled an index of thousands of businesses and organizations. The
index finds a listing for Delta, and the company's Web address. The
information is relayed to your browser, and up pops the site.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape didn't invent this idea. Visit http://www.realnames.com
for a similar service. But Netscape is the first to build it right
into the browser. It's the best effort so far to liberate us from
the tyranny of typing dot-com. &UR;  &LR;  But there's more. Click a button
marked ``What's Related.'' Netcenter whips up a list of 10 other
Web sites with similar content, and flashes it on your screen. If
you change your mind about flying Delta, a couple of clicks takes
you to the Southwest Airlines site instead.
</P>
<P>
   You never even know you've paid a visit to Netcenter &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; it all
happens behind the scenes. But say you want generic information on
a particular topic, like cars. When you type in the word
``automobiles,'' up pops Netcenter, with a listing of popular
automotive Web sites, and some strategically placed advertisements.
It's the ads that bring in the money, and by routing your eyes past
them, the browser will fatten up Netscape's cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody likes this idea. Type a generic word in today's
browsers, and the browser simply adds a ``www'' in front and a
``.com'' in back. If you type ``automobiles'', you wind up at a
car-buff site called Automobiles.com. Knowing this, lots of
companies own generic-sounding Web addresses. But with the new
Netscape browser, type ``automobile'' and you go to a Netcenter
page with information on cars instead. This could hurt traffic at
many other Web sites. Several businesses are already complaining
about this, and Netscape is working on ways to mollify the
companies, perhaps by giving their sites a prominent space on
Netcenter.
</P>
<P>
   There's definitely a hint of desperation in Netscape's new
strategy. Here's a company that once thought to dominate the
Internet software business, reduced to scrabbling after the fickle
eyeballs of Web surfers. Oh, well. You do what you have to do, and
on the whole, Netscape is doing it rather well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
