<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINO-HOMOPHOBIA-2TA     07-23 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-HOMOPHOBIA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING OUT IN SPANISH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raymond Pifferrer's father, a Cuban-born janitor, threw him
through a window when he told his father he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   When Lawrence's Ingrid Rivera, 26, came out as a lesbian to her
Puerto Rican mother six years ago, she was told that she was still
loved, but that ``out of respect'' she should never raise the issue
again.
</P>
<P>
   And when Luiz Villalona-Perez, 34, filed a petition in
Massachusetts two years ago for political asylum from the Dominican
Republic _ on the grounds that he would be imprisoned or killed
there for his homosexuality _ human rights groups backed his
claims.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Christian Coalition campaign against homosexuality in
the nation's newspapers suggests that it is not easy to come out as
gay or lesbian in the United States, period. And rising regional
hate crimes against gays and lesbians, meanwhile, show that
Massachusetts, which likes to think of itself as a liberal mecca,
is no safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to be Latino or Latina and homosexual in Massachusetts
can be particularly difficult, as demonstrated in May when Latino
parents in Lawrence organized to bus more than 200 children out of
state for a day rather than have them witness a gay pride parade in
that city.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 17 subcultures embraced by the term
``Latino,'' encompassing nearly 35 million Americans. Within each
of those groups there are many races, classes, and levels of
acculturation. Nonetheless, research indicates that homophobia is
prevalent in many Latino communities in the United States, though
it generally becomes less severe as education and acculturation
levels increase. For example, when the South End's Russ Lopez, a
college student, came out to his middle-class, third-generation
Mexican-American parents in San Jose, Calif., he says, ``It was
really, totally no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Massachusetts, the majority of Latinos are young, first-
or second-generation immigrants or transplants from the Dominican
Republic and Puerto Rico, and as of 1990, were the poorest
Hispanics in the nation, according to the US Census. Poverty, low
educational levels, traditional religious and social values, and
rigid gender roles (i.e. machismo) in the local Latino population
have contributed to what Boston University social scientist
Hortencia Amaro calls ``narrow views on sexuality and gender roles
in general, and homophobia in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   While many traditional immigrant communities could be said to
hold similarly narrow views, the difficulties for gay and lesbian
Latinos are often amplified by the cultural norm of
``personalismo,'' a strong emphasis on the maintenance of smooth
social relations at any cost _ even if that requires telling
half-truths, remaining silent about problems, or lying about sexual
orientation to avoid conflict. Personalismo often conflicts with
the American idea that openness and self-expression are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Peculiarly, the Latino culture of machismo dictates that a man
is gay only if he is the receiver in a homosexual encounter. Public
health officials say this is part of the reason Latinos nationwide
are more affected by the AIDS epidemic than is the Anglo
population. Although Latinos represent only 9 percent of the
national population, they make up 17 percent of all AIDS cases,
according to the Centers for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   For all of these reasons, there is widespread public denial of
homosexuality in the community, particularly among males, says
Luisa Medrano, a psychologist who works with Latino AIDS patients
at Massachusetts General Hospital. Often, she says, those infected
through gay sex prefer to tell their families they got AIDS from a
prostitute or from intravenous drug use. This, in turn, may also
skew regional AIDS statistics. The Northeastern United States, home
to many newly arrived Caribbean Latinos, is the only place in the
nation where the majority of male Latinos report contracting AIDS
through drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for Latinos seeking kinship in the dominant
Massachusetts gay community, the picture is not much better, says
Orlando del Valle, former director of the Latino Health Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Says del Valle, ``Gay culture in Boston means white,
middle-class gay culture. At best, Latinos and other minorities
feel they are seen as cute or exotic. At worst, they are seen as
less than, and inferior.''
</P>
<P>
   Amaro, a lesbian, says, ``The mainstream gay culture is not
immune to the same racism and prejudice that exists in the straight
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Too often, gay and lesbian Latinos straddle two worlds, fully
accepted by neither.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide rates among gay and lesbian Latino youth are the highest
in the state, Medrano says. According to a 1995 youth risk behavior
study, Hispanic high school girls attempted suicide at twice the
rate of Anglo or African-American girls, with the causes often
linked to rigid gender roles. In gay and lesbian youth, these
issues are amplified and augmented by the inability to find a
comfortable identity.
</P>
<P>
   When Pifferrer came out, he says, he felt he had to identify as
white to fit in. This is not an atypical reaction, says Lourdes
Rodriguez, a local psychotherapist. ``You hear it all the time,''
she says. ``Many of us joke that `I am out in English, but not in
Spanish.' But it's not really a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston has no pure social organizations for gay or lesbian
Latinos. Grupo Antorcha, the only such club, dissolved within three
years of its conception in 1987, around nationality conflicts among
the Latino ethnic groups. Now, the only places Latino homosexuals
can go to talk about their shared experiences or struggles are gay
Latin nights at the nightclubs Chaps (Thursdays) and Buzz
(Fridays), or organizations centered around AIDS outreach work.
</P>
<P>
   According to Leo Negron-Cruz, founder of Worcester's Gay and
Lesbian Latino Organization, this sends the wrong message. ``It's
telling Latinos that it's only OK to be out when alcohol, drugs, or
disease are involved,'' he says. ``Given what we have to go through
in our own communities, that's really sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Lourdes Rodriguez, 50, of Boston did not come out as a lesbian
until she was 29 years old, one month after arriving in Boston from
Puerto Rico, because she never had a name for what she was until
then.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Cuba, Rodriguez was raised in Puerto Rico by strict
Catholic parents in a neighborhood where, she says, everyone knew
everyone else's business, and roles for women were rigidly and
clearly defined: You were a good girl, or you were a bad girl.
Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your choices are either you are the virgin or you are the
whore, then there's really little room left to be a lesbian,'' says
Rodriguez, a psychotherapist. ``I knew no lesbians growing up. You
never heard about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Latino homosexuals in Massachusetts said in
interviews that the homophobia they face is directly linked to
narrow traditional Latino gender roles. The rules surrounding
gender roles in traditional Latino cultures are strict and
unwavering, says Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINO-HOMOPHOBIA-2ND     07-23 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-HOMOPHOBIA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... says Rodriguez.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Machismo and misogyny play a fascinating role in Latino
homophobia,'' says Matthew Florence, the director of Men of Color
Against AIDS in Boston. ``Gay men are hated or mocked not because
they choose to love other men. Rather, it is simply because they
have voluntarily given up the power that goes along with being a
man, and have by choice relegated themselves to the subservient
role of woman.'' Says del Valle, ``Gay men are seen as choosing to
be women. And if women are slaves, why would anyone in their right
mind choose to be one?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole notion of identifying yourself as a gay individual
is very, very American,'' says Pifferrer, who does diversity
consulting in Boston. ``What we think of as gay culture is
American. You don't find that in Latin America, unless it's
imported.''
</P>
<P>
   Negron-Cruz, who grew up in Puerto Rico but has been in
Massachusetts for 14 years, says he has met numerous men who ``are
married or have a girlfriend and think that if they have oral or
anal sex with a very effeminate man, and they are the active
partner, then they are not gay at all because to them that man is a
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For many Latino men it is perfectly reasonable to have sex
with men and still be straight,'' says Pifferrer. ``It's called
denial here, but it's much more complex than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesbianism remains invisible in traditional Latino cultures.
Within the confines of traditional Latino gender identities,
women's sexuality does not exist, says Amaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's sexuality is invisible in our community. It is seen as
unimportant and nonthreatening,'' says Amaro. ``Motherhood is
totally desexualized. In traditional cultures, women are not
supposed to be sexual. The fact that lesbians are not even
discussed is a symptom of our desexualization of Latina women.''
</P>
<P>
   When lesbianism is discussed, the woman is often seen as a
victim of some trauma that ``made her that way,'' says Rodriguez.
Often, the family or church intervenes to ``fix'' her, as in the
case of Rivera, whose mother insisted her daughter must have been
``corrupted'' somehow. After all, she had dated men before, and
even had a daughter. ``My gay cousin, meanwhile, was accepted as
having been born that way,'' Rivera says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, we always knew about a gay man somewhere in the
community,'' says Rodriguez. ``The extreme guys, the one on the
street who wore lipstick, or someone's crazy uncle. But you never,
ever heard about lesbians.''
</P>
<P>
   The ironic flip side to the cultural obstacles faced by many gay
and lesbian Latinos is that once they do come out to their families
and communities, if they are accepted, they are more often than not
totally accepted. This comes thanks in part to the Latino cultural
norms of ``familismo,'' ``respeto,'' ``dignidad,'' which, according
to Lina Castellanos, project director for Casey Mental Health
Initiatives in Miami, emphasize supportive behavior toward family
members, respect for others (especially elders), and ``the innate
worth and integrity of all people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an all-or-nothing situation for most of us,'' says
Jarrett Barrios, a Cambridge lawyer who is gay and is running for a
State House seat. ``If they accept you, they totally accept you. If
they don't, you lose everything. Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Often this means that, as in Rivera's case, the theme of
homosexuality will not be openly discussed in the family or the
community, even though it is implicitly understood.
</P>
<P>
   There are even Latino celebrities who defy gender stereotypes
and may be homosexual, but continue to be adored because they don't
admit any such thing. Walter Mercado, a famous television psychic,
appears on Univision in flowing robes, with heavy makeup and
painted fingernails, seated on a throne. Albita, a popular Cuban
singer in Miami, flaunts her androgynous style, and has become an
icon in the gay and lesbian community nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very interesting dynamic in Latino families,'' says
Barrios. ``On the one hand, they may say they are horrified, that
gayness is a taboo. But on the other hand, they can almost always
overcome it by pretending.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my Anglo friends that I bet there is more rejection of
gay kids in their families than there is in ours, even though we
are more openly homophobic,'' says Rodriguez. ``That's because
there is unconditional acceptance in many Latino families, as long
as you never name your homosexuality. My partner comes to Christmas
dinner, my parents come to my house and see that we share a bed.
They love her like a daughter, as long as we don't say what is
obvious, because then they'd have to make a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as local Latino communities struggle with issues of
homosexuality, there are signs in the United States that Latino
society on the whole is heading _ albeit slowly _ toward a more
tolerant view of gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Cristina Saralegui, the popular Miami-based Univision talk show
host, has said that educating Latinos to accept homosexuals is a
priority. Her show is seen in 100 million homes worldwide. She has
been given awards by gay and lesbian organizations and by the
United Nations for her work involving homosexuality and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Actor John Leguizamo, whose one-man Broadway show ``Freak'' has
garnered rave reviews, makes sympathetic homosexual characters part
of his performances, in honor of an uncle he says introduced him to
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, the Boston psychotherapist, says she would not have
done an interview with a newspaper 10 years ago for fear of losing
clients. ``But now, I feel safer,'' she says. ``In a strange, sad
way, the AIDS epidemic has made us face the fact that a lot of the
wonderful people we knew, a lot of our community leaders, were
gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Two such leaders, Jorge Hernandez and Mauricio Gaston, died of
AIDS, which both said they contracted through gay sex. Both men had
presented themselves to the community as straight, until their
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was the founder of the Villa Victoria housing
development in the South End, and the performance space there is
named after him. At the University of Massachusetts in Boston, the
Latino studies department is named after Gaston, its founder.
</P>
<P>
   The suffering of these community leaders has deeply affected
many leaders in the local community.
</P>
<P>
   When Alex Rodriguez, the former chairman for the Massachusetts
Commission Against Discrimination, announced his candidacy for
Congress, he did so at the Jorge Hernandez Cultural Center.
Rodriguez is straight, but said he chose the space as his launching
pad in part to emphasize the need for diversity and tolerance among
all people, Latinos included, and as a tribute to his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very personal statement for me,'' Rodriguez said in a
phone interview. ``Those of us who knew Jorge knew how much he
suffered under the weight he carried of living in the closet. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Secrets are the most disturbing things to carry. You've got to
be out, you've got to be who you are. The fact that we have members
who stand proudly and gay enriches our community. I encourage every
Latino who is gay to come out and be who you are. You're carrying a
burden you don't need to carry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
