<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9239 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-ART-BOS &LR;      07-23 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A TREEHOUSE, LIFE JUST DOESN'T GET ANY BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephanie Schuller and her little sister Kimberly have the best
of two worlds. They have two houses. Not bad for an 8-year-old and
a 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Well, one of the houses is a treehouse, and it's in the back
yard of the big house, owned by Steve Schuller and Ellen Glew,
their parents. But it's still a house, with a roof, carpet, windows
with funky shutters, and window boxes with real flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Glew had the idea that all little girls should have a
treehouse, and commissioned Schuller to go to work. In fact,
Schuller said, ``She pestered me into building the treehouse.'' But
he took it on with enthusiam and a certain flair.
</P>
<P>
   A new structure was something new for Schuller, who with his
wife and the girls live in an 18th-century house in North Reading,
Mass. The parents also operate the Restoration and Renovation Show,
an international trade show with emphasis on, well, restoration and
renovation, making sure grand old houses are fixed up properly and
with the right materials. The show is held all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue in building a treehouse is finding the right
tree,'' said Schuller, which he did, halfway down his back yard:
perfectly spreading branches for holding the frame, and not too
high up. Six feet up, to be specific. Schuller used no plans, and
by salvaging some of the wood and recycling others, spent a grand
total of $30, adding that, if he can do it, anyone can.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was another tree a little further down the yard,
where some boys had built a treehouse long ago, but it was 20 feet
high. The house is gone, and there is no sign of anyone having
fallen out of it, but even so, 20 feet is just too high, Schuller
decided.
</P>
<P>
   Schuller set up 2 x 8 joists left over from a project, between
the branches rather than on them. That way he could make the floor
a little bigger, not needing to cut anything to fit on top of the
branches. This arrangement is kind of nice, because it gives the
impression that the tree is gathering the house to its bosom.
</P>
<P>
   Schuller set the joists with long deck nails, but they were not
long enough, nor strong enough, because they sheared off quickly
with the movement of the tree. While the floor of the house is only
about six feet off ground, and the trunk and branches are huge,
there was still enough movement to scuttle the deck screws.
</P>
<P>
   So Schuller replaced them with 12 eight-inch lag screws a full
5/16-inch in diameter. With this added strength, Schuller is still
keeping a sharp eye on them, ``just in case.'' Said he, ``The house
dropped only a few inches when the screws sheered, but that was
more than enough for me to replace them.''
</P>
<P>
   That done, Schuller built roof and sides with wood salvaged from
a large packing crate left by one of the exhibitors in last
spring's show.
</P>
<P>
   Asphalt roof shingles were also leftovers from another project,
Schuller said.
</P>
<P>
   Schuller built the house six feet wide and three feet deep. ``A
tidy little house,'' he thought. When Glew was invited to the
unveiling, she said, ``Is that all?'' So Schuller doubled the size.
Building the house half sized, then doubling it, is a good lesson
when you build anything: Generally, if possible, double the size of
your project or, within reason, increase it by half.
</P>
<P>
   Schuller applied a coat of new Cabot's OVT barn red stain,
matching the trim on the main house.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to floor carpeting, Schuller put in a drip edge,
gutters made of a plastic pipe split in half, and a plastic
downspout. The door spring is a bungee cord.
</P>
<P>
   The screened windows will be covered with Plexiglas for the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Glew will do the fine arts work indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Getting in and out of the house is tricky, but not for the
girls, Schuller said. He built a rope ladder with three ropes and
five rungs, secured on the ground as well as at the door. Lubbers
can use a regular ladder if they want to, or have to.
</P>
<P>
   Schuller also built a badminton court and swing set. ``It's a
regular community for the 8-year-old set,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And over to the side is Schuller's and Glew's own private
grown-up preserve: a large vegetable garden, fed by well water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found an old dug well in the front yard,'' he said. ``The
water was six feet down and eight feet deep.'' He bought a pump
from the Want Advertiser and couplings from a lumber store for
hooking up to a hose. He uses the well only for watering the grass
and garden, and likes the price of the water.
</P>
<P>
   If more than 10,000 gallons are used in a quarter year, it costs
$6.20 per thousand. ``My well water costs 12 cents per thousand,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
