<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9242 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-RAILROADS-ART-     07-23 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-RAILROADS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKYARDERS WITH ONE-TRACK MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manny Ferrante calls the Everett Springs &AMP; Eastern Railroad the
best-kept secret in Everett, Mass., and who would disagree? The
ES&AMP;E, all 600 feet and four tiers of it, takes up pretty much
everything in Ferrante's small back yard that isn't taken up by the
swimming pool. It was founded innocently enough in a corner of the
yard a decade ago, but has since devoured everything in its path,
including the long-gone garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's addictive, like smoking or drugs,'' declares the
52-year-old Ferrante, who likes to sit in the pool and admire, say,
a locomotive hauling three cars toward a coal loader that squats on
a Manny-made ``mountain'' some 15 feet above the ground. ``It's so
hard to stay away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a small world, this garden railroading, and not just
because it's a G-scale planet where 1 inch of model train equals
about 24 inches of the real deal. The notion of running miniature
railways through back-yard flora and fauna has existed in England
for decades, but it didn't arrive here in the Colonies until some
20 years ago. Ferrante's Northeast Garden Railway Newsletter has
only about 75 subscribers, although this is considerably more than
the dozen or so that it reached when he founded it in 1992. But
despite recent growth in numbers, Garden railroaders remain a
select group that frequently gathers at ``open houses'' in each
other's back yards to swap stories of lugging crushed rock to be
used as roadbed or to croon over the latest German-made locomotive
from LGB, the Mercedes of G scale.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ferrante, most garden railroaders are incapable of stopping
what they start. Their layouts just seem to grow and grow, eating
up both real estate and time. There's land to be graded, track to
be laid, and entire villages to be built. And what about the
gardening part of garden railroading, all that Alberta spruce and
all those small-leafed euonymus bushes? ``These things are always
works in progress,'' Ferrante points out. ``Just when you figure
you can't do anything else, you find something else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And more money to spend: Low-level G scale starter kits can be
purchased for as little as $125, but some LGB locomotives fetch as
much as $1,600. So how much has Ferrante, who runs a small
restaurant with his wife, Carol, invested in the ES&AMP;E? ``About as
much as I would have if I'd bought a Porsche instead,'' he muses.
</P>
<P>
   Spend some time with a garden railroader and you'll probably
find someone who had an electric train as a kid because he
carefully composed a letter to Santa Claus and was rewarded with a
Lionel or an American Flyer on Christmas morning. When he grew up,
he may have built a meticulous N scale (1:160) layout in the
basement or the attic. But eventually the back yard beckoned.
Hand-built trestles! Gurgling waterfalls! Tunnels carved through
real granite! Not to mention timing systems that can simultaneously
run a half-dozen trains while the railroad's president gently sips
a Bud in admiration.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these folks, of course, cannot only wax romantic about
trains but can also spew out railway minutiae with the same
obsessiveness that baseball fans dissect batting statistics. But
many are also like George Sloan of Norwell, Mass., for whom the
true pleasure of owning the pristine Meadowbrook Railroad is
derived from having built it. Three years in the making, the
Meadowbrook is an impressive 600-foot, three-line layout in which
trains actually enter and exit Sloan's finished basement through a
window that has a hinged door custom-made of Plexiglas. The
railroad is dotted with tiny Alberta spruce and features an azalea
that hangs over its picturesque pond. A miniature wedding is taking
place in the miniature town's miniature chapel, and a group of rock
climbers can be spotted on a nearby cliff. Sloan, the 62-year-old
owner of a plastics company, maintains a stable of about two dozen
engines and some 80 cars, most of which are carefully displayed in
his basement.
</P>
<P>
   But don't ask him for details about this rolling stock. He'd
rather talk about hand-building redwood trestles or painstakingly
soldering jumper wires across each rail joint. And when he
complains that maintaining the Meadowbrook takes up so much time
that he couldn't possibly expand, he's announcing a moment later
that he's seriously considering planting a Japanese garden and
running a loop of track right through it. ``I already have the
Orient Express,'' he points out enthusiastically, ``and I could
build some little Japanese houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even when you finish building a garden railroad, Mother
Nature may insist that you rebuild it. Ferrante's ES&AMP;E, for
example, was nearly wiped out five years ago when a tree fell on it
during a windstorm. Alas, most natural disasters tend to be
ongoing. In Foxborough, Mass., Ken Rich Jr. not only works hard to
contend with the English ivy that doggedly attempts to cover his
480 or so feet of track, he has also fought a series of skirmishes
with the groundhogs and rabbits that have repeatedly dined on his
flowers. About the only thing that is immune to attack by critters
is what Rich calls the ``umpteen trailer loads of rocks'' that, in
order to give his railroad ``the canyon look,'' he fetched during
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Rich is complaining. How other than doing this, he asks
as he stands behind his two-family home and surveys an L-shaped
layout that features 75 feet of handmade trestles and three
tunnels, can you simulate the headaches of owning and operating
your very own railroad? ``With a little indoor layout, all you have
to do is dust it,'' explains the 51-year-old auto technician, who
ran such a railroad for several years. ``But out here, outside,
it's like ... like the real thing. You have to clear the track and
worry about weather. You have to deal with frost heaves and trim
the trees. You play engineer, oiler, maintenance man. It's just
more realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Garden railroading would seem to be a guy thing, but that has
been changing lately. Couples such as Doug Maki and Andrea Kolb of
Lowell, Mass. are finding that, lo, it combines what were
heretofore separate hobbies into a single activity. ``I like
woodworking and electronics. Andrea likes gardening,'' declares
Maki, a 52-year-old engineer. Result: the Fort Hill Line, named for
a nearby park, a small but growing layout that features 150 feet of
track, a collection of 10 locomotives and a couple of dozen cars, a
gaggle of homemade buildings fashioned out of bird houses, a varied
assortment of a half-dozen or so plants and flowers, and a 12-foot
hawthorn tree that rises in the middle of it all.
</P>
<P>
   This particular division of labor _ Man builds, Woman plants _
was evident when Maki and Kolb attended a garden railroading
convention in Florida last year. (Yes, there are such events, as
well as a national magazine called Garden Railways.) ``At the
gardening seminars, you'd see more women,'' recalls Kolb, a
54-year-old accountant. ``And at the building seminars, you'd see
more men.''
</P>
<P>
   On Halloween, Maki and Kolb stock the Fort Hill Line with candy,
which neighborhood kids pluck from the small railroad cars. At
Christmastime, their hawthorn tree shimmers with lights. You might
think that garden railroaders, particularly those in New England,
would shut down for the winter. But you'd be wrong. After all, do
real railroads shut down?
</P>
<P>
   So what happens when it snows? Stupid question. ``You just hook
up a snowplow to the front of an engine, put four or five engines
behind it, and plow the snow off the track,'' Manny Ferrante
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Just like a real railroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
