<HEADLINE>
IN CASE YOU MISSED IT, AND YOU SHOULD HAVE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Was it the best of summers? Was it the worst of summers?
</P>
<P>
   Outbreaks of toxic sincerity on television talk shows threatened
to spread to the general population, prompting the FCC to warn
viewers that believing anything they see or hear on ``Regis &AMP; Kathy
Lee'' or ``Howie Mandel,'' among other programs, could be dangerous
to their mental and emotional health.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer stock skyrocketed with sales of Viagra, then plummeted
when the company announced plans to seek FDA approval for Miasma, a
drug that would make women over 40 sexually irresistible to men of
all ages. Plans to market the drug were scrapped when laboratory
tests indicated the same results could be obtained with breast
implants.
</P>
<P>
   The Beanie Baby bubble burst after a ``60 Minutes'' report
revealed that the once-popular collector's items are nothing but
glorified bean bags. Prices plummeted as millions of worthless
Beanies were dumped on the market. Reports of Beanie cannibalism
surfaced, as desperate, starving collectors ripped open the Babies
and cooked the contents.
</P>
<P>
   Mesclun riots and arugula uprisings broke out in several
culinary capitals as heat and severe droughts took their toll on
crops, resulting in salad shortages. As the heat wave continued,
law enforcement officials in New York, Boston, San Francisco, and
other cities braced themselves for more greens-related trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the powerful self-esteem industry refused to
accept the results of a study of 500 college students that
indicated that having too much self-esteem can backfire, causing
complacency and sabotaging academic achievement. ``We are special,
we are great,'' replied a self-esteem spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Disney announced plans to acquire the federal government and
name Tina Brown queen. Some members of Congress resisted
privatization on sartorial grounds, saying they wouldn't comply
with an order from CEO Michael Eisner that required them to dress
as Disney characters. They relented when Eisner pointed out that
their constituents probably wouldn't even notice the change and, as
an inducement, threw in free passes to the Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore confused Michael Jordan with Michael
Jackson, who in turn, confusing Gore with Dan Quayle, challenged
him to spell the word ``potato.'' Michael Jackson confused
everybody, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart threw herself into the flames of the flag-burning
controversy when she churned out another bestseller, ``Flag: The
All-American Dish,'' 50 creative ways of preparing flag for the
dinner table. ``Why burn flag when there are so many other
delicious ways to prepare it?'' asked the Goddess of the American
Hearth, rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the literary front, inspirational author Nicholas
Grunes had another best-seller with ``The Zen of Muddling
Through,'' in which he explores the revolutionary notion of
refusing to view baseball, golf, fly-fishing, basketball, horse
racing, sneedball or any one of dozens of other sports as metaphors
for life.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Popular Culture Society is compiling
end-of-the-century ``100 Best'' lists for a comparative study, and
has 5,234 so far, on subjects ranging from albinos to zippers.
Lists continue to pour in, said acting president Ramona Weedle.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez and Mo Vaughn have lent their names to the
formation of the Massachusetts chapter of the American Society for
the Prevention of Cruelty to Overpaid Athletes. During an emotional
fund-raiser at the Foxy Lady, outside Providence, R.I., a
spokeswoman said the organization's goal is to make fans sensitive
to the needs of all professional athletes with seven-figure annual
incomes, regardless of race, creed, or talent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
