<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOM ALLOWS STATES TO GIVE BACK WHAT THEY HAVE RECEIVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ For state government, it doesn't get any better than
this.
</P>
<P>
   When Acting Governor Paul Cellucci this week signed a $770
million reduction in personal income taxes, Massachusetts was
hardly alone: Nineteen other states had already cut taxes this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cutting trend is the bounty of a national economic
expansion now in its eighth year. Revenues have poured into the
coffers of state governments, which ended last fiscal year flush
with a record $28.6 billion in total budget surpluses _ the most
they've had to fight over since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And quite a fight broke out on Beacon Hill. Lawmakers spent
months debating how to use the state's surplus as they jockeyed for
voters' favor in an election year. In their zeal, they voted for
record income-tax cuts and followed with a record $19.5 billion
budget that added $1 billion to programs ranging from day care to
public works projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was too much money around and everyone had three ways to
spend it,'' Senator Stanley C. Rosenberg (D-Amherst), chairman of
the Senate Ways and Means Committee, said Monday when the budget
passed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Lawmakers won't be so happy if the tax cut, a permanent
reduction in the state's revenue source, forces them to cover
shortfalls in funding for essential programs that inevitably occur
when the economy slows and revenues drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things turn down, all of a sudden you're in trouble in
education or you're in trouble in health care,'' said
William &UR;  &LR; Pound, director of the National Conference of State
Legislatures, a Denver research group that released a new study of
state budgets around the country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; States, on the whole, have acted responsibly, Pound said. This
is an unprecedented fourth consecutive year in which states, in
aggregate, reduced taxes. But 24 states, including Massachusetts,
also made deposits to rainy day funds established for emergencies,
according to the conference report.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts lawmakers increased the maximum share of state
revenues that can go to the fund to 7.5 percent, from 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to predict what will happen years down the road
as a result of the budget decisions today.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Massachusetts taxpayers get in the fiscal 1999
windfall?
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature reduced personal income taxes in two ways: by
doubling the personal exemption for virtually all state taxpayers,
and by slashing in half the tax rate on income earned by those with
investment portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut gives a disproportionate boost to each wealthy
individual, according to the Tax Equity Alliance for Massachusetts,
a liberal lobbying group, in an election-year package in which
candidates are courting not only Republicans but Democrats with
swelling investment portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature slashed the rate at which investment income _
stock dividends and interest on bank accounts _ is taxed, from 12
percent to 5.95 percent. The personal income tax rate remains
unchanged, at 5.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; According to TEAM's analysis, $492 million in reductions
because of higher personal exemptions would be spread among most of
the state's 2.9 million taxpayers. Only 770,000 _ about one-fourth
of all taxpayers _ would share in the $239 million savings from
lower taxes on investment income. That averages out to $310 each,
TEAM said. The richest 5 percent of taxpayers would get about $828
each.
</P>
<P>
   TEAM's executive director, James St. George, said a high
personal exemption makes the tax system more fair. To make the
investment tax credit fair, he said, it could be targeted to those
who need it most: ``Middle-income elderly with investment
portfolios but not a 40-year-old stock broker or mutual fund
manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts's personal tax exemption was already bigger than
those in other states. When it is doubled, taxpayers would deduct
$4,400 from their taxable income; couples filing jointly would
deduct $8,800.
</P>
<P>
   The $770 million tax cut was generous when compared with other
states. Georgia lawmakers approved a $205 million tax reduction,
increasing personal exemptions by $1,200, to $2,700. Maryland
doubled its personal exemption, to $2,400. Illinois's personal
exemption of $1,000 also doubled _ albeit in stages over three
years. Kansas raised the exemption by $250, to $2,250.
</P>
<P>
   Increases in personal exemptions are meant to win the loyalty of
the average wage earner: Since the personal exemption is subtracted
from taxable income, it most benefits those who earn less. On
average, a single individual would save $131 on his tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   David Tuerck, director of the Beacon Hill Institute at Suffolk
University, said the problem is that this measure ``exerts a drag
on the economy'' by punishing high-income individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high cost-of-living state,'' Tuerck said, adding this
``makes it less attractive to move into state and makes it tough
for Massachusetts employers to recruit workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers were able to slash taxes this year because of
unexpectedly high revenues in fiscal 1997. Revenues from income
taxes, the biggest single source of funds from taxpayers, were up
nearly 12 percent last year, the Department of Revenue reported.
Withholding and sales taxes increased by 9.3 percent and 3 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were increases in every major tax category,'' Revenue
Commissioner Mitchell Adams said recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
