<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUDIATED STORIES NO LONGER FADE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to the wonders of technology, anyone with Internet access
could have tuned in Wednesday to a live conference featuring Jack
Smith and April Oliver, the CNN producers fired for their role in
the ill-fated ``Operation Tailwind'' story alleging that the U.S.
used nerve gas on a secret 1970 mission in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to the wonders of a churning journalistic culture in
which self-examination seems to dominate, people like Smith and
Oliver no longer need to take disgrace lying down. Wednesday in New
York -- one day after the Pentagon released its report debunking
the Tailwind story -- the two producers mounted a vigorous
counterattack. In a discussion sponsored by the prestigious Freedom
Forum think tank and moderated by former New York Times media
writer Alex Jones, Smith and Oliver defended their reporting and
portrayed their CNN bosses as nervous nellies who buckled under
Pentagon pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's event coincided with the release of Smith's and
Oliver's 78-page rebuttal to the 54-page report filed by media
lawyer Floyd Abrams. Abrams was hired by CNN to conduct a Tailwind
post-mortem and the network embraced his conclusion that the story
was unsupportable. The Smith-Oliver report attacks the Abrams
investigation on a variety of fronts, charging that it was
completed too hastily, took crucial information out of context, and
unfairly attacked the crediblity of important sources.
</P>
<P>
   In stories of this nature, as in war, truth will likely remain a
casualty, given that it involves a three-decades old secret
mission. But where Smith's and Oliver's argument may resonate --
particularly among their media colleagues -- is in its portrayal of
CNN as a company without the intestinal fortitude to defend a
controversial piece of reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said that prior to the Tailwind story airing, her CNN
bosses ``were thrilled with it. They were sending me flowers.'' It
was painful to watch the ``CNN executive suite just collapsing'' in
the face of the anti-Tailwind backlash said Smith, adding that
``CNN management made a leap after the Abrams report...to the new
standard of proof (of accuracy) that applies in the criminal
justice system,'' but not in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also ventured that the Abrams report was rushed to
conclusion so that the CNN executives could meet an ``artificial
deadline'' -- the gathering of television critics in Pasadena
California earlier this month. CNN News Group president Tom
``Johnson, (CNN/U.S. President Rick) Kaplan and all the rest of
those guys wanted to go out there with the apology in hand,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver and Smith faced some tough questioning Wednesday, but won
a strategic victory in keeping the issue alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would bet that this story is not going to be over now,''
said Jones as he brought Wednesday's conference to a close.
</P>
<P>
   And that's another feature of the modern media environment. In
an era of journalistic decentralization -- a time when big media is
almost as distrusted as big government or big business -- Tailwind
is sure to find a warm reception somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Gary Webb, who authored a 1996 series for the San Jose
Mercury News called ``Dark Alliance'' alleging CIA complicity in a
Los Angeles crack cocaine epidemic that helped fund the Nicaraguan
Contras. In 1997, after the series had been savaged in the
mainstream press, Webb's editor publicly repudiated it and Webb
resigned in anger. Like Smith and Oliver, he claimed his bosses
didn't have the guts to face down critics.
</P>
<P>
   So a defiant Webb struck out on his own and wrote a book
propounding his ``Dark Alliance'' thesis. At last count, it was
number 12 on The San Francisco Chronicle's best seller list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
