<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GUNS-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN-TOTING AMERICANS FIND HARSH REALITY IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD,  
 PHILIP TRUE and JODI BIZER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATAMOROS, Mexico _ In prisons across Mexico, more than 80
Americans are serving time for carrying a gun or possessing
ammunition, practically God-given rights in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Both are a crime in Mexico, where gun-control laws are strict
and unforgiving, even if weapons or bullets are unintentionally
taken across the border.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Neil Johnson, a top manager for a San Antonio
grocery company, exemplifies the trouble some gun-carrying
travelers have encountered at the border.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 57, spent three months in a Nuevo Laredo prison last
year, initially charged with transporting military weapons after
Mexican Customs officials found a .22-caliber rifle and a deer
rifle in his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the most frustrating experience in my life.
I've never been in jail,'' Johnson said. ``The first week I was
there I was scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was one of more than a dozen Americans interviewed for
this story who had served time for breaking Mexico's tough gun
laws.
</P>
<P>
   It is illegal to carry weapons and bullets into Mexico without a
permit. Permits are difficult to get and are mostly issued for
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The violation for weapon offenses is so serious that bond is
automatically denied. Charges normally carry a mandatory five-year
sentence, but that can soar to as high as 30 years in prison if the
firearms are considered military style _ any weapon greater than
.38-caliber.
</P>
<P>
   There are 363 Americans jailed in Mexico, 83 of them for
firearms charges, according to the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City. The
majority of the others are imprisoned for drug-related offenses,
followed by theft and assault.
</P>
<P>
   Not even American law enforcement officers are exempt from
Mexico's weapons laws.
</P>
<P>
   Leonel Herrera, a deputy sheriff in Jim Hogg County, Texas, had
a box of .44-Magnum bullets in his car when he crossed the border.
He was caught and spent 80 days in Nuevo Laredo's La Loma state
prison before being released May 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just forgot,'' said Herrera, 58. ``People down here have to
be very careful. It's ridiculous. You hire a Mexican lawyer to
represent you, and they charge you thousands of dollars and there's
no guarantee you can get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Esteban Gonzalez, who works in the Iowa beef industry,
wonders when he will get out.
</P>
<P>
   He has been in the Santa Adelaida state prison in Matamoros
since May 10, when he drove across the border with two 9mm pistols
he uses for target practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined this is where I'd end up,'' Gonzalez, a
burly, shy and homesick 26-year-old, said as he fought back tears.
``I've never been in prison, never done anything bad.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. citizens, whose right to bear arms is written into the
Constitution, often claim ignorance about the strict anti-gun laws
south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are not aware that even a small firearm, like a .22,
is considered a threat in this country,'' said David Stewart, U.S.
deputy consul general in Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, where two American
citizens are jailed on weapons charges. ``People are unaware just
how strict this Mexican law is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans also are unaware that they are breaking U.S. law if
they take a firearm out of the country and don't register it with
the Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico maintains gun control is essential to national security.
</P>
<P>
   With a rebel standoff in Chiapas, guerrillas uprising in
Guerrero and drug cartels responsible for much of the country's
violence, Mexicans say they can't be too careful because American
guns could end up in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are quick to point out the gun that killed
presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio in 1994 was traced to a
Texas dealer.
</P>
<P>
   But many Americans who spent time in a Mexican jail say the law
doesn't differentiate between an arms dealer and the person who
forgot the gun in his vehicle, as the majority of Americans claim,
or those who don't know about the law.
</P>
<P>
   Many also complained about an expensive legal system in which
they paid high dollars to lawyers but saw little in return. Figures
given for legal costs ranged from as low as $2,000 to as high as
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   In one high-profile case, Tommy Bean, an auto and gun dealer,
was incarcerated March 14 at Nuevo Laredo's La Loma prison after he
attended a gun show and drove across the border in a Chevrolet
Suburban for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   A hunter, Bean, 59, had about 200 rounds of ammunition from
various calibers in plain view in the back seat. Some of the
bullets were high caliber.
</P>
<P>
   The Texan got a five-year sentence. His appeal was denied July
8.
</P>
<P>
   His family has gone through several lawyers and thousands of
dollars, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Bean did not want to be interviewed for this story. But his
wife, Sara Bean, spoke in a telephone interview about the pain the
situation is causing the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mental, the physical, the emotional anguish is unbearable.
The law is very cold,'' she said. ``They are looking at a
59-year-old man with a bum knee, a bum back, who has high blood
pressure, who is obviously not a gun smuggler.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weapons issue grabbed the attention of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, who raised the subject during a recent meeting of the Border
Governors Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for the governor, said Bush told
his Mexican counterparts that he was ``concerned about the growing
number of innocent individuals who inadvertently brought a gun or
ammunition into Mexico from Texas and are detained.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While the governor acknowledges Mexico needs to enforce its
laws, he asked the Mexican governors to exercise some flexibility
for these innocent individuals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Alarcon, a noted Nuevo Laredo lawyer hired by the Bean
family, said Mexican law makes no exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is very impersonal. It's for everybody. In the case of
Mr. Bean, who had no intention to commit a crime, but he did, the
law makes no distinction between whether you wanted to (break the
law) or not,'' Alarcon said. ``You have to prove really well that
there was no intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon said the answer lies in better informing the public
about Mexican law.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Antonio Chacon, assistant director of Customs in Nuevo
Laredo, rolls his eyes when told that many people forget they have
weapons in the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they forget, how come we find guns hidden in the glove
compartment, inside tires, inside the air conditioning, under the
seat?'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
