 &HT;    TOBACCO LEGISLATION PUTS BLACK N.C. LEGISLATOR IN A TIGHT SPOT
 &HT;    With TOBACCO-FACTS. For release Sunday, July 26.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With black teenagers smoking in record numbers,
it's not easy being an African-American member of Congress
representing a tobacco-dependent state.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., says she is ``in a difficult
position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't smoke. I don't advocate it. I am not for teenage
smoking,'' Clayton said. She said she would support legislation to
curb teen smoking as long as was ``balanced'' and included
protection for tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's either/or,'' she said. ``The government
should be looking out for farmers as well as looking out for
teenage smokers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the House prepares to tackle the controversial issue of
national legislation to regulate tobac
