<HEADLINE>
MEXICO WRESTLES WITH THE `UGLY AMERICAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For millions of Americans, Mexico is a country no
more distant than the width of a river, or even a fence. A quick
trip to a restaurant or bar for a meal or a few rounds of
margaritas.
</P>
<P>
   But the ease of crossing ``al otro lado,'' the other side, masks
just how great a trip it really is, said Jorge Bustamante,
president of the Tijuana-based Colegio de la Frontera Norte.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000-mile, U.S.-Mexico border is the world's longest, most
porous interface between the First and Third Worlds. It is also the
place where 500 years of Roman Catholic Spanish heritage runs up
against northern Europe and the Protestant Reformation, Bustamante
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the United States frequently ignore these vast
differences,'' he said. ``We in Tijuana have more in common with
people in Buenos Aires than those in San Diego.''
</P>
<P>
   American tourists fail to educate themselves about the customs
and laws in Mexico, said Jose Hinojosa, a political scientist at
the University of Texas Pan-American at Edinburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ugly American attitude surfaces in odd places,'' Hinojosa
said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans ``don't recognize that when we go to (Mexico), we are
dealing with new laws, mores and practices,'' he said. ``We think
we can do what we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the border, an increasing number of American motorists
have been arrested for trying to cross into Mexico with guns or
ammunition, which are illegal in Mexico without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans say they didn't know about the Mexican law or
just forgot they had a gun or a box of ammunition in the car. The
consequences more often than not mean jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican immigration authorities count more than 300 million
border crossings a year in both directions.
</P>
<P>
   While fences and border guards control the flow of people,
attitudes pass unrestricted, Bustamante said. Those attitudes often
sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the North American Free Trade Agreement, we have a
growing integration with our two economies. Yet at many parts of
the border, the United States has built nine-foot steel fences,''
he said. ``The conflicting image is that of Mexico as valued
trading partner and also enemy turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is the United States' third largest trading partner and
on track to be its second. More than $150 billion worth of goods
and services passes between the two countries annually, with about
half of that trade either originating in or passing through Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that fact often is lost among the headlines that Mexico's
chief exports are narcotics and illegal immigrants, Bustamante
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an ideology that Mexicans are a bunch of criminals,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an assumption that all rules should be those of the
United States, and preferably written in English, and if Mexico
does not agree, it is because it is backward,'' he said. ``There is
a great surprise when somebody applies a law that is different from
that in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the clearest example of arrogance occurs each spring
with the annual invasion of South Padre Island by tens of thousands
of partying American college students, said Gary Mounce, who
teaches criminal justice at the University of Texas Pan-American.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of students sun all day, then troop to the tourist
zone of Matamoros to drink all night. Drunken revelers often are
arrested for urinating on public streets, or other violations of
Mexican sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids from the United States obviously need training'' about
what is acceptable in Mexico, Mounce said. ``But then, so do
adults, who often just forget that there are rules in Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
