<HEADLINE>
PRISON LIFE IN MEXICO NOT ALWAYS HELL BEHIND BARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATAMOROS, Mexico _ The bright mural outside the Santa Adelaida
state prison here tells a tale of perdition and redemption: a man
who led a criminal life filled with drugs, women and booze finds
success working, studying and praying _ in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Prisons in Mexico are officially ``Centers for Social
Readaptation.''
</P>
<P>
   Many look like cities within cities. Many are overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful entrance to Santa Adelaida, 20 miles south of
Matamoros, reflects conditions inside.
</P>
<P>
   When the steel gates open, what emerges is a town where children
play, women cook and television sets blare. The smell of sizzling
meat drifts from corner restaurants, and a myriad of tiny grocery
stores sells everything from cold sparkling water to canned goods.
</P>
<P>
   Men work as mechanics in auto shops or carve shiny picture
frames in wood shops. Nearby, they lift weights in a gym or shoot
hoops on a playground.
</P>
<P>
   A fledgling garden sprouts carrots, onions and other produce. A
manicured baseball field thrives despite the blistering heat of
drought-stricken northern Mexico, thanks to the loving care of an
American inmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my little piece of apple pie here,'' boasts Louis
Stephens, 45, a Brownsville, Texas, man serving time on drug
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Adelaida defies the notion that Mexican prison life is
hell on Earth. Here, prisoners are locked up only at night and
conjugal visits are almost a daily ritual.
</P>
<P>
   The prison is filled to its capacity of 1,290 inmates _ about 90
of them women. Unlike most prisons, it is not overcrowded, a reason
officials say it runs smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the La Loma prison in Nuevo Laredo _ across the Rio
Grande from Laredo, Texas _ was built to hold about 200 inmates but
often has up to 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first go in there you are put in an observation
cell,'' said Mike Hinojosa, who spent eight days at La Loma for
having 13 bullets in his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no ventilation, you sleep on the floor, there are no
bunks. There is no water to drink, no toilet,'' he said from his
home in Corpus Christi, Texas. ``It stunk. It smelled like human
waste and dirty, sweaty people. It made your stomach go sick ... I
was in a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Both prisons house state and federal inmates, who committed
crimes ranging from homicide, assault, robbery and sale of
narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   At Santa Adelaida, women prisoners sleep in their own quarters,
but during the day they roam with men. Dating and marriage among
prisoners is not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Female prisoners may also have their children living with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American (prison) system is very good, but they don't have
the humanity _ the human contact that everybody needs. It's hard to
separate the family,'' said prison guard Jose Antonio Izquierdo
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   The good life costs money, though. The more money a prisoner
has, the better life is, and inmates have to pay for their keep.
They must supply their beds, pillows, blankets and any other
comforts.
</P>
<P>
   Food can be brought in by family, and inmates also can order
takeout, provided the restaurant delivers.
</P>
<P>
   One American prisoner who didn't want his name used has two
color television sets in his cell, which is filled with magazines
and books, a stereo and a new air-conditioning unit.
</P>
<P>
   He pays another prisoner to do his laundry and clean his cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to do my time in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Are there drugs in prison?
</P>
<P>
   ``We stay calm,'' he said, noting marijuana, cocaine and alcohol
are available for a price.
</P>
<P>
   Everything has its price.
</P>
<P>
   The poor have to work for their keep, even if it is earning
money toiling for other prisoners, washing their clothes or
cleaning rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything here costs money. You pay for everything,'' said
Antonio Manchaca, a Brownsville car dealer jailed on arms-smuggling
charges. ``It's better than an American prison, but you have to
work for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In its report on Mexican prisons, the international organization
Human Rights Watch said many are overcrowded and dilapidated, with
inadequate food and health services.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, there are positive features of Mexican
prison life,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In virtually all state prisons, prisoners exercise significant
control over their daily routines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
