<HEADLINE>
THE BARE FACTS ON GETTING AN INDOOR TAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Self tanning requires a little bit of planning
and some fairly simple steps. You cannot just slop the stuff on and
get a terrific tan. Like a painter preparing his canvas to accept
color, you've got to prepare your skin.
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't mean a cursory go-round with some nice-smelling
hand soap and a washcloth. To get your skin receptive for all the
glories of a deep, satisfying and totally safe tanning experience,
you've got to exfoliate, or get rid of dead skin cells.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way is to get yourself a loofa and some gentle
exfoliating gel _ Frederic Fekkai has a new Body Scrub with Shea
Butter ($27.50, order by calling toll-free 1-888-FFEKKAI) that
polishes rough, dry skin; Lancome makes Exfoliance Fraichelle
Invigorating Body Scrub and Clinique developed the refreshingly
minty-scented Body Sloughing Cream ($14.50). Use on the large areas
of the body and then concentrate on elbows, knees, ankles, wrists
and the backs of your heels where the skin is thicker.
</P>
<P>
   For an even application, start with your lowest extremities,
always. You may, however, want to skip your feet, because this
stuff wears off. Sandals, for instance, can rub tanners away and it
will look like you've got straps on your feet. If you're going to
spend a lot of time barefoot, then slather it on by all means and
reapply daily.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to use enough tanner on your legs and thighs, making
sure that the product covers your legs smoothly. Self-tanners come
in creams, lotions, oil sprays and mousse. Since your knees crease,
you might want to put a little body lotion on them (elbows, too)
and then apply the tanner to prevent dark build-up in the natural
wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   You can give yourself a bikini line or use tanner all over your
body. Don't put on clothing over the tanner until it is completely
dry (about a half-hour) _ and you don't want to wash the tanner off
or even exercise heavily for at least three hours, because sweat
will streak the tanners.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest thing is to sit on a towel for a while so you won't
stain anything. Some of the tanners, particularly Sun Laboratories
products (which are used at spas) or Lauder's new Go Bronze for the
face, are tinted, which helps you see where you're putting it. But
they do stain when they're wet.
</P>
<P>
   Do your chest, arms, neck and shoulders last, particularly if
you've covered your stomach and abdomen. If you bend, you can get
crease marks.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest place for a home-alone person to get is the
``boyfriend'' spot in the middle of the back. No arms are that
long. So here are a few suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   If you've got a boyfriend, a husband, son, girlfriend, daughter
or lover, wait until they are home so they can get your back for
you. If there is no one around, maybe your neighbor. Or ... a
back-scratcher with a pad of cotton doused with the stuff. Other
than that, too bad. Just don't wear anything so low-cut in the back
that your ``tan line'' will show.
</P>
<P>
   There are salons that will do a tanner application for you which
will eliminate that tricky ``boyfriend spot'' problem.
</P>
<P>
   The tricky part to applying tanner is the hands. This stuff will
stain your palms if you do not wash them with soap and water after
you are finished ``tanning.'' How to get it on our hands _ where it
belongs? Apply tanner to the backs of the hands and rub them
together. Or use a cosmetic sponge to get the tops of the fingers
coated well. You will notice, however, that your hands will fade
first because you are constantly washing them.
</P>
<P>
   To increase color intensity, plan to reapply the next day. Then
be prepared to touch it up every few days if you want to maintain
an even tan. Again, be generous and apply to clean skin. You do not
have to exfoliate your second or even third application.
</P>
<P>
   How long will it last? Say, four days. But if you use a shower
brush or washcloth, you will notice that the color will begin to
slough off naturally a bit sooner.
</P>
</TEXT>
