<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, July 24, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RYAN (Undated) _ Steven Spielberg's near-three-hour
``Saving Private Ryan'' is quite simply one of the most powerful
war movies ever made, and a shattering emotional experience. Be
warned: this one is not for the faint of heart. By forcing its
audience to experience what war is really like, ``Saving Private
Ryan'' is not only an extraordinary educational experience that
widens our awareness, it's a cinematic event that could change
forever the way popular culture views the phenomenon of war.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MAFIA (Udated) _ On paper, the idea of an
``Airplane!''-like parody of classic gangster movies sounds great _
especially with ``Airplane!'' co-director Jim Abrahams on board as
writer-producer. But in execution, ``Mafia!'' is tedious, only
sporadically funny and distasteful in a way its predecessors in the
genre (``Naked Gun,'' ``Top Secret!'') were not.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CRITICS (Pasadena, Calif.) From the TV critics' press tour in
Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
