<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PREVIEW-BOBBY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV FILM IN WORKS ON YOUNG GAY'S SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just as America's Christian right launches
another crusade to brand gays as sinners with a choice,
Oscar-winning actress Susan Sarandon has signed on to make a
network television movie about a tragedy that happened because of
such beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has just cut a deal with Sarandon and a trio of co-producers
to dramatize the story of Bobby Griffith, who jumped to his death
from a freeway overpass at age 20 after fighting for years to
change his sexual orientation, as his fundamentalist family and
church said he should.
</P>
<P>
   If everything goes right _ and with a TV movie that's a big if,
the producers stress _ ``Prayers for Bobby'' could be broadcast
sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it could be out right now, with all that stuff going
on,'' said Mary Griffith, Bobby Griffith's mother, a central
character in the story, referring to ads placed in three national
newspapers by 15 Christian-right groups last week calling on gays
to find Jesus and go straight.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mary Griffith who told her son over and over that he was
a sinner to be gay. And it was she who, after his suicide in 1983,
re-examined her religious beliefs, came to believe in a more loving
God, and has worked unceasingly over the past 12 years to improve
life for young gay and lesbian people.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Bobby and Mary Griffith is familiar to the 20,000
or so people who bought ``Prayers for Bobby,'' a 1995 book by
former Oakland Tribune executive editor Roy Aarons.
</P>
<P>
   Disney originally optioned Aarons' book for a movie in 1996, but
nothing came of it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then three young Hollywood producers _ Daniel Sladek (``Talos
the Mummy'' for Miramax is his latest movie), his production
partner Chris Taaffe, and David Permut (``Face/Off'' is his most
recent release) _ grabbed it and took it to Sarandon. For her first
venture into movie production, she'd been looking for a project to
take to NBC, according to Aarons.
</P>
<P>
   Although Aarons and others are hoping the star of ``Atlantic
City,'' ``Bull Durham'' and ``Dead Man Walking'' will decide to
play Mary Griffith in the movie, she has only committed to
producing, her agent, Martha Luttrell in Los Angeles, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very interested in the story and thought it was
important,'' Luttrell said. Sarandon was not available to explain
her interest, but she's known for doing work with social meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Aarons and Sladek were ecstatic that a Hollywood star of
Sarandon's stature would back the project and said that makes it
more likely it will be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hollywood, it's a very controversial story because it
combines three hot issues _ religion, homosexuality and suicide,''
Aarons said. ``We knew we had to get someone with real clout behind
it to make it a viable project.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC said its policy is not to comment on projects in
development. But the Hollywood Reporter quoted the network's head
of movies, Lindy DeKoven, as saying she was ``thrilled to have the
opportunity to do a project with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Sarandon on board, Aarons and Sladek cautioned that
this is just the first step in a long process, with many obstacles
along the way, among them possible opposition to the movie's
themes.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC has shown its willingness to take on hot topics,
producing ``Roe v. Wade'' and the 1995 film ``Serving in Silence:
The Margarethe Cammermeyer Story,'' which stirred things up with an
on-screen shot of two women kissing in the story of a decorated
lesbian's efforts to stay in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Aarons cautioned, ``Don't hold your breath. With
Hollywood, you never know. But this is a major step forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
