   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation: Cockel, lead Secret Service agent, expected to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The House votes to override
Clinton's veto of the partial birth abortion bill, as it has in the
past. The Senate vote _ in September _ will be critical once again.
By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ House votes on environmental
issues on appropriations bills. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FARMERS (Washington) _ He meets with Democratic
congressional leaders on farm issues, and does a broadcast
interview on the subject. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Five Democrats have now entered
the race for mayor now that Barry is out. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-MANHUNT (Dateline to kum, N.C.) _ The search for Eric
Robert Rudolph, wanted in the bombing of an Alabama abortion
clinic, continues in the woods of western North Carolina. The team
of agents pursuing him has been more than doubled from its previous
size of 35. Bloodhounds have also been tracking him and the search
has left people in the towns weary and divided. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   ODWALLA-FOOD-SAFETY (Chicago) _ In what federal officials say is
the largest food safety settlement, Odwalla has settled its
criminal case on charges that it produced tainted apple juice that
killed a 16-month old girl and injured 70 others. Company has
agreed to plead guilty to sixteen counts of violating food saftey
laws and will pay a fine of $1.5 million. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLONER-PROFILE (Undated) _ Man in the News: Dr. Ryuzo
Yanagimachi, the man who cloned mice, followed advice given him by
a mentor more than 30 years ago: take the grant money and spend
three days a week doing the research you said you would do. Then
spend the other two days doing anything you want. What he wanted to
do was clone, disregarding the prevailing view among reproductive
biologists that mice would be the most difficult of all mammals to
clone. As for cloning humans, he politely but firmly declined to be
drawn in. ``If all the humans on the face of the earth were
infertile, this may be justified,'' Yanagimachi said. ``But until
then we should stick to reproduction the way that Mother Nature did
it for us.'' By Gina Kolata. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN (Cairo) _ An Iranian court sentences Tehran's mayor to five
years in jail and bars him from holding public office for 20 years
on charges of graft, depriving President Khatami of a potent ally;
a pro-Khatami newspaper is shut; more on the Iranian missile test.
By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-U.S. (Washington) _ More reaction to the Iranian missile
test.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-BISHOPS (Rome) _ Seeking to curb the independence of
bishops, the pope issues an apostolic letter that tightens Rome's
control over 108 bishops' conferences around the world. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-GOLD (Berlin) _ In a twist to the Nazi gold saga, German
officials acknowledge that 26 crucial, secret files chronicling
receipts of gold stolen from Jews in concentration camps had
mysteriously disappeared from German archives long after World War
II. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Political developments in the hunt for
a new prime minister. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-COLLAPSE (New York) _ Developments in the scaffold collapse
at the Times Square construction site.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-EXPAND (Washington) _ By the turn of the century, the
initial stages of a global electronic financial marketplace could
be in place, and Frank G. Zarb, the chairman of the National
Association of Securities Dealers, the parent company of the Nasdaq
stock market, wants to be leading the way. He has folded the
American and Philadelphia stock exchanges into his exchange and has
struck up merger or alliance discussions with the Pacific exchange
in this country and the Frankfurt exchange in Europe. He is aiming
to create what he calls a ``market of markets,'' a global financial
network that will pose an even greater challenge to the New York
Stock Exchange. Story also includes today's announcement that the
boards of the Chicago Board Options Exchange and the Pacific
exchange have agreed on their merger. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments in the UAW strike
against General Motors. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MICROSOFT (Washington) _ Executives from some of
Microsoft's biggest rivals testify before the Senate Judiciary
Committee, which is looking into competition in the software
industry. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T's earnings from continuing
operations and before extraordinaries rose 60 percent in the latest
quarter as cost cuts helped offset stalled revenue growth. AT&AMP;T
will also buy back $3 billion in shares. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Boeing's second-quarter earnings
fell 46 percent on higher production costs and expenses for phasing
out a McDonnell Douglas jetliner. The company expects to cut as
many as 28,000 jobs by the end of 1999. The stock declines 13
percent. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS-TRUST-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Bankers Trust's
second-quarter earnings rose 7 percent as net income from
investment banking and equity investments offset losses in Asia and
Latin America. The bank took a $60 million provision for
trading-related credit losses because of Asia's market rout. By
Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-FRAUD (Undated) _ Regulators in 28 states have brought
enforcement actions against dozens of securities firms for criminal
and fraudulent ``boiler room'' tactics, selling everything from
stock and currency to investments in ostrich meat. It is the second
time in two years that the states have brought such a large,
sweeping case against such firms, which deal in ``microcap''
stocks. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   NABISCO-EARNINGS (Undated) _ RJR Nabisco's profit before charges
fell 24 percent in the second quarter, hurt by on lower profits
from the company's international cigarette business and its Nabisco
cookie and cracker businesses. By Constance Hays.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Xerox's profit before a charge rose
17 percent in the second quarter, above expectations. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-BRAZIL-CARS (Ushuaia, Argentina) _ In a blow to South
America's $15 billion auto industry, Argentine and Brazilian
officials fail to reach a long-awaited agreement for common car
tariffs that was supposed to be signed by the Presidents of the
four Mercosur countries gathering today for an economic summit. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-FUEL (Washington) _ As the U.S. Enrichment Corp. begins
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, opponents of the
corporation's privatization say the sale appears more certain than
ever to ruin a deal for the United States to buy bomb-grade uranium
from the Russian Republic and dilute it for use as reactor fuel. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   REUTERS-LIPPER (Undated) _ Reuters Holdings buys the mutual-fund
information business of Lipper Analytical Services for an
undisclosed amount. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was down 92 points at 2 p.m.
</P>
