   ABORTION _ WASHINGTON _ The Housed was expected Thursday to
override President Clinton's veto of a bill banning certain
late-term abortions. The ``partial-birth'' abortion ban, however,
faces a mnore difficult test in the Senate later. (Sherman, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-RELIEF - President Clinton and Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman announced 254 counties eligible for emergency aid
Thursday. The counties, which include all of East Texas, have been
devastated by the recent heat wave. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   GA-GOVERNOR _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Secretary of State Lewis Massey
dropped out of the governor's race Thursday, throwing his support
behind rival state Rep. Roy Barnes, thus avoiding a potentially
bloody and expensive runoff for both candidates. The move puts
Barnes in a much better position for the fall match-up with Guy
Millner, who barely escaped a GOP runoff with Mike Bowers.
(Walston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-REACT _ Trying for an interview with family members of
2-year-old McCall Akin for story on the family's prayerful 6-week
vigil at the girl's bedside. Story may detail how family created a
Website to keep relatives and friends up to date with daily entries
and to appeal for prayers. Website entries, pictures available.
Also tracking the latest developments in the investigation and the
condition of the last remaining hospitalized victim of the outbreak
and seeking comment from families of other kids infected at White
Water. (Guthrie/Anderson/Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-POOLREGS _ State officials say the death of a 2-year-old
in the White Water E. coli outbreak may cause greater urgency in a
review of current pool regulations, and whether stricter chlorine
guidlines should be adopted in Georgia and other states.
(Lore/Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-SOURCE _ Food safety advocates criticize the state for not
working harder to find the origins of the E. coli outbreak at White
Water. How much progress has been made, and how significant is it
for investigators to know how the bacteria made its way to White
Water in the first place? (Lore/Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RUFFIN _ Ben Ruffin is the first African American to head the
University of North Carolina's Board of Governors. He's also the
first tobacco executive. The RJ Reynolds Tobacco vice president
talks about his new academic responsibilities and his own worries
about addictions. He grew up in an alcoholic family on the poor
side of Durham. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ MURPHY, N.C. _ Watching daily developments in the
search for Eric Rudolph, wanted in the fatal bombing of a
Birmingham abortion clinic. (Scruggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GULF _ Looking into meetings of special advisory board on Gulf
War illness. (ABrice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
