<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DRUDGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX NEWS ADDS DREARY DRUDGE TO ITS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It has come to this. A man who once worked in
the gift shop at CBS and dug through the garbage, putting ``news''
and rumor on line from a dingy apartment in Hollywood, has become a
celebrity bigger than he could imagine and the man some people
believe will spell the end of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   No, he's not Peter Arnett.
</P>
<P>
   He is Matt Drudge. Drudge believes he's leading the charge of
people everywhere to take back the news. He calls himself a
``citizen reporter'' and has, as the hype and controversy around
him has swelled, become a cartoon figure who is both laughable and
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   And now, apparently, legit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the news organization christening him is the Fox News
Channel, so take from that what you will. The Fox News Channel airs
``Drudge,'' which is little more than a televised version of his
Web site, ``The Drudge Report.'' And now, as Fox jumps late _ very
late _ into the newsmagazine business with ``Fox Files,'' it has
added Drudge as a ``commentator.''
</P>
<P>
   This reeks of business-as-usual for Fox News, which was started
by people who thought TV news was too liberal, which is peopled by
lots of conservatives and ``reporters'' who have worked for the
likes of ``Inside Edition.'' Fox News _ still struggling like
counterpart MSNBC to find an audience _ will try anything to be
different. It sought the youth viewer and hired Chuck D., a rap
star whose Public Enemy group helped revolutionize the hip-hop
genre. It hired Brit Hume to add credibility in established
journalistic circles. Then the channel came up with this slogan:
``We report. You decide.''
</P>
<P>
   It began airing all kinds of pompous ads meant to distance
itself from the national network news and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it said, ``We're fair, they're biased.''
</P>
<P>
   It criticized everyone else while essentially doing the same
thing _ spinning the news with shows like ``Special Report With
Brit Hume,'' ``The O'Reilly Factor'' and finally ``Drudge.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is progress, journalistically, Lord help all of us. When
the press screws up _ as CNN did with its Vietnam gas story _
everyone takes the hit. But only Fox News tries to say it won't
happen to them. But giving Matt Drudge air time only further
exposes the real truth about Fox News and its new baby, ``Fox
Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Drudge came to prominence because his rumor-filled Web site and
newsletter was dishy and entertaining and harmless until people
started treating it like fact, like this unconnected man sitting in
front of his computer was really plugged in. What Drudge was doing
was reading a lot of newspapers and on-line newspaper and wire
services and then reporting what was about to be reported.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated news. He didn't report it. As he gained in
popularity, he got anonymous tipsters. And he posted a story that
said Newsweek was going to print a major story about President
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky. When they didn't, he made headlines by
``breaking'' the story that ultimately got out.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge has been billed as ``the first star of the Internet'' _
not true; porn was the first star of the Internet _ and he has
turned this infamy into a job and higher profile. Ailes, chairman
and chief executive of the Fox News Channel, says ``Matt Drudge is
just a guy who figured it out first and got it first,'' although
Drudge has been proven wrong numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   In defense, Drudge will say, ``I've broken dozens of national
exclusives that I've written from my dirty Hollywood apartment.
It's a romantic period where many voices can be heard and may the
most interesting one win.''
</P>
<P>
   Established journalists dislike his lack of fact-checking,
rumor-mongering. That Fox News has picked him up only confirms the
worst fears of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   But Drudge is loving this. He says ``romantic'' and ``citizen
reporter'' a lot, like he's living a black and white movie. He
wears an old-school reporter's hat (it doesn't have a press card
stuck on the side because Drudge likes to be an outsider and
wouldn't consider registering for credentials).
</P>
<P>
   He has become a cartoon, a guy who has the sass of Quentin
Tarantino but not even the experience of a high school newspaper
reporter. Now he has a TV audience, like Dan Rather and company.
</P>
<P>
   Ailes was asked if he was going to give Drudge a lesson in
Journalism 101. ``Two years ago nobody in this room thought I knew
anything about it,'' he said, surly and defensive as always. And he
was right. Nobody trusts Fox. Not then. Especially not now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
