<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9396 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PI-REVIEW-LADN     07-23 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PI-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PI' EQUALS EDGY MATH MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Higher math scares most of us. Writer-director
Darren Aronofsky employs this basic truth as a jumping-off point
for his dementedly clever, award-winning feature debut ``Pi.''
</P>
<P>
   A low-budget thriller (Aronofsky got friends and relatives to
invest $100 each) with horror movie overtones and more imagination
than it can comfortably contain, ``Pi'' reinforces the heartfelt
assumption, shared by anyone who flunked calculus, that numbers can
drive you nuts.
</P>
<P>
   That's sure what's happening to ``Pi's'' prophetically named
Maximillian Cohen (Sean Gullette). Holed up in his dingy New York
apartment, all but personally wired-up to a jerry-built, tubes- and
wires-sprouting computer called Euclid, the obsessed Max is trying
to figure out the mathematical key to everything in the universe
(although he'd settle for a formula that just cracks the stock
market).
</P>
<P>
   Utterly anti-social, Max's only desired human contact is with
Sol (Mark Margolis), a former professor whose own deep math
explorations led to a stroke. But the world has a way of seeking
out the disinterested Max, most emphatically in the form of Wall
Street functionary Marcy Dawson (Pamela Hart) and Talmudic scholar
Lenny Meyer (Ben Shenkman). The former has purely profit-motivated
reasons. The latter thinks Max's theories will help his similarly
obsessed rabbi break some numerical code that will reveal the true
meaning of the Torah and, by extension, God.
</P>
<P>
   Each camp will stoop to the most coercive means necessary in
order to pick Max's brain. The trouble is, that increasingly
fevered organ is undergoing ever more frequent seizures, and the
indispensable Euclid is crashing from the strain, too.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in high-contrast black and white, ``Pi'' is overloaded
with disorienting camera tricks _ overlapping images, time-lapse,
extreme close-ups and such _ meant to evoke Max's subjective,
paranoically deteriorating mental state. On the other side of the
equation, his brilliant fascination with geometric forms is given
poetic life by oddly lovely shots of leafy trees and cream
spiraling in coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, ``Pi'' is a frantic sensory assault that feels,
more than anything, like watching and hearing ``Eraserhead'' for
the first time all over again. On fast-forward.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not everyone's cup of cream-circling coffee, ``Pi''
may be relentless, but its form fits its content. Aronofsky matches
every assaultive aural and visual idea with an intriguing,
intellectual one. His only sin, really, is putting more of it into
one movie than most of us can calculate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1445EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
