<SLUG> BC-GRAFFITI-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARING THE NOSTALGIA ON NOSTALGIC FILM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Candy Clark recalls the cold. Cindy Williams
thinks of bad hair. Ad-libbed lines come back to Charles Martin
Smith. Meanwhile, the precocious Mackenzie Phillips was having the
time of her life, and Kathleen Quinlan was in awe.
</P>
<P>
   These co-stars of ``American Graffiti'' reunited July 17 with
director George Lucas for a 25th-anniversary celebration and
screening of this ode to cruising and crossing the threshold into
adulthood at the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences'
Goldwyn Theatre in Beverly Hills. The audience members _ some of
whom were too young to have seen the movie in 1973 _ cheered
through the opening credits and spontaneously for the nostalgic one
hour, 50-minute collage of teenhood, street rods, aimless summer
and oldies radio.
</P>
<P>
   The audience reserved some of its loudest applause for the late
Wolfman Jack, who played himself, and for Harrison Ford, who was
unable to attend. All members of the talented ensemble cast, with
the exception of Ford, Ron Howard, Suzanne Somers and Richard
Dreyfuss, participated in a panel discussion after the screening.
</P>
<P>
   The collective cast, crew and director Lucas shivered through
the 28-night shoot on the streets of Petaluma and San Rafael in the
early 1970s. The sting of those chilly nights has stuck with the
actors, who in some scenes ducked down in the back seats of cars
during filming to stay warm.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas revealed that Universal executives were unhappy with the
film, even to the point of being embarrassed to exhibit it. But at
its initial screenings, ``American Graffiti'' blew away audiences _
and the studio's reservations _ a la John Milner (Paul Le Mat's
character) racing down Paradise Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult thing was that the first cut of the film
came out to be three hours. We spent the next six months trying to
get it to two hours and stay as good,'' Lucas explained, calling
the whittling process the single biggest challenge of ``American
Graffiti.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who played the role of the big-haired and big-hearted
Debbie, was asked by moderator Leonard Maltin about that shock of
blond hair she sported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wig,'' the now sun-bleached actress gushed.
``Actually, that wig was made of yak hair. I and the hairdresser
picked it out because it wouldn't lose its curl. It would just
swell in the dampness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a hairdresser?'' Cindy Williams shot up in disbelief.
Seeing herself again in ``American Graffiti'' brought back hair
memories for the petite Williams, who still wears a short style.
The words ``hated it'' pretty much sum it up.
</P>
<P>
   Williams revealed that when she heard a film titled ``American
Graffiti'' was being made, she didn't have a clue what it was
about. A look at the script, however, and she was begging for a
role. Only, being the good-girl Laurie wasn't what she had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play Debbie or Mackenzie's part (Carol). I would
have put braces on my teeth,'' she said in mock desperation.
</P>
<P>
   It was less of a reunion and more of a get-acquainted session
for Quinlan, who was just a baby-sitting teen-ager when she
attended the mass audition for a girl to play Laurie's friend Peg
at the sock hop. Despite being on a movie set with Howard and
Williams, she felt right at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my high school,'' she said, motioning to the other
cast members. ``I didn't even meet most of you. You all were movie
stars to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She later was reunited with Howard, this time as her director,
more than 20 years later on ``Apollo 13.'' She played the wife of
astronaut Jim Lovell on the ill-fated mission to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Hopkins, the ringleader of the Pharoahs, had his own
greasy-hair memories, and he figured his accent in the film was
``halfway between Gomer Pyle and David Brinkley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured the guy (his character Joe) had heard New York guys
and tried to sound like them,'' he added in his natural drawl.
</P>
<P>
   A radiant Phillips, who is a recovering substance abuser, was
brutally honest about how this surprise hit took the then
12-year-old from a lead in grammar school performances to celebrity
status in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened so many doors for me that I proceeded to shut
myself,'' Phillips said candidly. ``It was a wonderful experience
for me. They treated me like a little sister. And riding in that
car with Paul Le Mat ... ooh.'
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who called himself a ``serious actor studying at Cal
State Northridge at the time,'' was surprised at how many flubs
Lucas edited into the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would always assure me, `If we need to, we can shoot that
again later,''' Smith said, spinning his own yarn. ``And then, he'd
edit it in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
