<HEADLINE>
ALL THE GOOD NEWS THAT'S FIT TO PRINT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ People always ask why there isn't more good news
in newspapers. A suburban Phoenix paper called the Tribune actually
tried to put out an all-good news edition on Tuesday, renamed ``The
Good News Tribune'' for the day.
</P>
<P>
   It featured stories like how delicious suburban Phoenix tap
water has become. Never mind that Arizona may run out of tap water
in the not-so-distant future. I guess the good-news headline then
will be ``Scottsdale golf courses dry up and blow away.''
</P>
<P>
   It got me thinking. It may be possible to present all kinds of
news as good news, perhaps even San Francisco news. Therefore I
present the first all-good-news San Francisco column:
</P>
<P>
   ``Rookie Muni driver doesn't have third crash.''
</P>
<P>
   As of this writing, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This unnamed new driver lost control of a bus on her second day
of work early in June, and took out trees, a parking meter and a
hydrant on Geary Boulevard. Last Friday her bus jumped a curb when
it rolled away from a bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   That's another good-news headline: ``No one killed in two
crashes by rookie Muni driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Or you could put it the way Muni boss Emilio Cruz put it on
``Mornings on 2'': ``It wasn't an accident _ it was an oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   You see, she forgot to set the emergency brake when she got out
of the bus, which I would call lack of foresight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policy generously offers reporters mints.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about the only good news, or any news, at Carmen Policy's
press conference announcing his resignation from the San Francisco
49ers on Wednesday. On every reporter's chair at the Burlingame
Marriott, someone had placed a notebook, a pen and a chocolate
mint.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the kind of mint they put on pillows in hotels. What
does that mean? You will sleep with the mints?
</P>
<P>
   And sleep they did at this weird press conference. The only
interesting thing Policy said was how he hasn't always meant it
this year when he has wished Eddie DeBartolo the best, but now he
really means it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policy leaves. Western civilization survives.''
</P>
<P>
   After all the news coverage, it's hard to believe, but true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Brown doesn't tick off every resident of San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   No, just tenants, who are 70 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants groups say they'll fight a proposed $503 million bond to
rebuild Laguna Honda Hospital if the cost is passed on to renters.
Recently, Brown persuaded the Board of Supervisors to pass on
bond-related tax hikes to renters instead of landlords, who are
coincidentally represented by Brown's friend and consultant Jack
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Brown could lose the next election, if he had an opponent. Now
that would be a good-news headline.
</P>
<P>
   ``BART to provide world's longest stretch limousines to
airport.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what they'll be calling them, when the fare to the
airport from San Francisco is $4.50, as projected when the line is
supposed to open in 2001, a BART odyssey. Maybe transit agency's
cars will even have hot tubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland promotes bicycling.''
</P>
<P>
   The city on the other side of the San Francisco Bay confiscates
cars belonging to those arrested for allegedly soliciting drugs or
prostitution, even though the drivers haven't been convicted.
They're guilty until proven innocent, and carless forever.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't Oakland confiscate cars belonging to individuals who
solicit for stadiums? Or why doesn't Mayor Jerry Brown ban cars
altogether, thereby reducing gaseous emissions other than his own
speeches?
</P>
<P>
   ``California schools not as bad as we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   A new achievement test shows that California's scores are below
the national average, but not at the very bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, educators (as they call themselves) expected the worst, and
they only got the pretty bad. If the educational establishment had
high expectations, maybe the kids would out-do those, too. Maybe
high expectations are too much to ask.
</P>
<P>
   I've been trying to put a good-news spin on this one, but there
is no good news.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Golden State, the land beyond the valley of the
silicon chips, the home of great universities, and pretty soon most
citizens won't be able to read good news or bad news.
</P>
<P>
   That's very bad news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
