<HEADLINE>
MONICA SAYS SHE AND BRANDY STILL MIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Teen r&AMP;b chanteuse Monica says those rumors that
she and chart-topping duet partner Brandy hate each other are pure
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so untrue,'' Monica (last name Arnold) said. ``It's
hilarious to me now, but none of those things are true.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica released her debut, ``Miss Thang,'' three years ago at
the age of 14. Her latest, ``The Boy Is Mine'' (Arista), which
includes the No. 1 hit duet with Brandy of the same title, was just
issued.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy's new album, ``Never S-a-y Never'' (Atlantic), also
includes ``The Boy Is Mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica, who lives in College Park, Ga., says the duet could
never have happened if the two singers didn't blend vocally.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were no problems at all. We worked it all out in the
studio together.''
</P>
<P>
   While Monica won't perform ``The Boy Is Mine'' unless Woodland
Hills resident Brandy is present, she revealed the two may sing the
song Sept. 10 at the 15th annual MTV Video Music Awards, where the
single is up for video of the year and best r&AMP;b video.
</P>
<P>
   Monica said the duet, which has topped the pop singles chart for
two months, was ``an event. People look at this as a new
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   LIFE AFTER `HELL': When the Squirrel Nut Zippers scored an
alt-rock radio hit with the Cab Calloway-flavored ``Hell'' last
year, nobody was more surprised than singer-guitarist-saxophonist
Tom Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of giddy bewilderment,'' Maxwell said. ``We never
suspected alternative radio would ever give us a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The wacky Chapel Hill, N.C., outfit's latest release,
``Perennial Favorites'' (Mammoth), is due Aug. 4, the same date the
band appears at the Palace in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recorded this album in late 1996 _ before `Hell' ever hit
at radio,'' Maxwell explained. ``We were still touring in a van. We
found this old house and were under the impression we would turn
out a record a year.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Hell'' became a hit, the label decided to promote the
heck out of the band's then-current release, ``Hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell said the Zippers' definition of success is unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't count whether we have a hit on radio or how many
units are sold,'' he said. ``But if the new record doesn't do as
well as `Hot,' my ego will be bruised because I think it's a
superior effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ALANIS ANALYZED: Just out in paperback is ``You Live, You Learn:
The Alanis Morissette Story'' (Berkley Boulevard, $5.99) by Craig
Tomashoff. The book tells of the inspiration for the lyrics on
Morissette's multimillion-selling ``Jagged Little Pill,'' among
other things.
</P>
</TEXT>
