<HEADLINE>
AWARENESS OF ALL THINGS GREAT AND SMALL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When I heard about the dog who'd had his
testicles replaced with silicone implants and ``never knew he lost
anything,'' I winced but figured, hey, what do I know?
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was the dog's adoring owner who claimed her
16-month-old Chinese pug ``doesn't know anything's missing, and
that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later though, I read about a new technique that
has been perfected by a couple of San Francisco Bay-area
scientists. Aiming for an antibody serum to fight off human viruses
and diseases, the microbiologists ``took a mouse and removed its
mouse antibody genes.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the scientists, Nils Lonberg of GenPharm International
Inc., in Palo Alto, put it: ``They (the mice) are quite happy. They
aren't even aware of the process they're a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I am no genetic engineer or even a dog owner. But my _ you
should excuse the term _ animal instinct tells me these folks are
in denial.
</P>
<P>
   Any dog who wakes from an anesthetic with little silicone bags
where his real cojones used to be has to know something's a tad
off.
</P>
<P>
   And any mouse who has had his or her DNA stripped of its
uniquely mousey antibody genes may indeed be happy as a clam. But
the poor little devil must at least feel that things are vaguely
different than before.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, I am not one who believes animals experience
everything that humans do. (I'm not proud of this, but it's a
fact.) For example, while I don't imagine that commercial chickens
enjoy living almost immobile in squashed coops until they're fat
enough to have their heads cut off, I don't think they ``know''
that life is far better out there for their free-range
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Same for cows, pigs, ducks, fish and, yes, once in awhile,
lambs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do I fool myself about the kind of end they all come to. But
_ ``Babe'' notwithstanding _ I don't believe the critters know
about the end. And that enables me to eat them with a relatively
free conscience.
</P>
<P>
   What I do believe though is that all living creatures, plants
included, have an instinctive ``sense'' of inner balance. Mess with
the status quo and, don't kid yourself, the creature is aware of
the messing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this sense is what some people call a soul, the connection
between all life and its eternal creative source (aka God). The
soul ``knows'' when fundamental alterations have been made, even if
the soul can do nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the company that manufactures the silicone canine
testicles _ called Neuticles Naturals _ says his product is
supposed to diminish trauma by making the dog think nothing has
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the original polypropeline Neuticals, which resemble big
marbles, the silicone implants have ``the feel and texture of a
gummie bear,'' said CTI Corp. President Gregg Miller.
</P>
<P>
   OK. I'll buy the idea that Frodo, the 16-month-old Chinese pug
who went to sleep with his own equipment and woke up with gummie
bears, was not as bewildered as he would have been had he awakened
with marbles.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing will convince me that, like those mice with the
disappeared antibody genes, Frodo's soul ``doesn't know anything's
missing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
