<HEADER>
A9425 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-TOURISM-$ADV26-C     07-23 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-TOURISM-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRANIANS HOPING FOR MORE U.S. TOURISTS
 &HT;    With IRAN-US-$ADV26
 &HT;    Photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server and available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, July 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Bring your conservative clothes, leave your
alcohol and credit cards behind. Iran's mountains, mosques and
mullahs await you.
</P>
<P>
   With hints that relations between the United States and Iran
could warm up, Iranian officials say they are seeing an increase in
American tourists in the land of ancient Persia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourism is a great thing for developing peace and
friendship,'' said Iranian tourism director Mohsen Emami in a
recent interview with Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian officials say 4,184 people visited Iran with U.S.
passports in 1997, up from 3,478 the year before. Those could
include tourists, business people, journalists or expatriate
Iranians visiting their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are still a tiny portion of the nearly 700,000
visitors last year, but their increasing numbers appear to coincide
with the election last year of Iranian President Mohammed Khatami,
seen as a more moderate leader than his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   It's good news to a country with a sluggish economy and an image
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Iranian takeover of the U.S. Embassy in 1979, starting
a 444-day hostage ordeal for 52 Americans, Iranians have been seen
largely as anti-American religious zealots.
</P>
<P>
   But visitors get a different view. Iranians are usually friendly
and hospitable. There is very little crime and plenty of upscale
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy to see you,''' said Tina Patterson, director
of group travel for Distant Horizons, a Long Beach, Calif., agency
that books trips to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   For about $5,000 per person, Distant Horizons sends Americans on
18-day tours.
</P>
<P>
   The country has plenty of sites. There are ornate mosques and
museums and bazaars lined with Persian carpets. The Caspian (Sea)
region to the north offers cool mountains and caviar. Tehran has a
ski resort nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Americans will also notice the building-sized murals depicting
ayatollahs and, in some, warnings against U.S. aggression.
</P>
<P>
   There are adjustments that must be made to conform with Islamic
law.
</P>
<P>
   Like Iranian women, western women must keep their hair covered
with scarves and their bodies covered with capes or raincoats. Long
sleeves are recommended for the men.
</P>
<P>
   Non-married couples traveling together will have to say they are
married if they want to share a hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   No alcohol is permitted and, because of a U.S. economic embargo,
credit cards from U.S. banks are worthless. Also, there is a $100
limit on bringing Iranian goods into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Travel in groups is recommended to help avoid bureaucratic
problems with visas. Officials with the U.S. State Department,
which still tells Americans to avoid Iran, warn that there is no
U.S. embassy there to help travelers in trouble. American concerns
are handled at the Swiss embassy in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
