<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-US-$ADV26-COX     07-23 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-US-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRAN AND U.S. CAUTIOUSLY TESTING CHANCES FOR BETTER RELATIONS
 &HT;    With IRAN-TOURISTS-$ADV26
 &HT;    Photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server and available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, July 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Maybe this 18-year-old Iranian is a sign of
things to come.
</P>
<P>
   Farhat Malek's hair is slicked and a Michael Jordan jersey peeks
out from under the large Iranian flag draped over his shoulders --
his attire for watching the two countries' soccer teams square off
last month.
</P>
<P>
   He is hopeful, but realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iran and the United States have had a little war these last 20
years,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, reports emerged that Iran recently tested
missiles that, in a few years, could reach American allies like
Israel and Saudi Arabia. The history of the ``little war'' between
the two adversaries includes a captured American embassy, a
shot-down Iranian airliner, an American embargo and 19 years of
angry rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   But, In the last several months, leaders in Iran and the United
States have cautiously explored better relations.
</P>
<P>
   For the U.S., a friendly Iran could enhance stability in an
oil-rich and increasingly well-armed part of the world. In
addition, U.S. companies want access to the country's market of 60
million Iranian consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For Iran, a friendly U.S. could end the embargo that has been a
drag on its economy. It could also help protect Iran from
contentious next-door neighbors in Iraq and Pakistan, which
recently tested nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Progress will require the untangling of decades of grievances,
from the symbolic to the financial. But, the time might be right
for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is a young country. Half its population is under 20 years
old and many, like the young Malek, say the ritual chant of ``Death
to America'' at Friday prayers is a has-been slogan with a
dwindling audience.
</P>
<P>
   In Tehran, you can see old Chevy Camaros and Ford Mustangs
speeding past ``Down with U.S.A.'' graffiti on city walls. Leonardo
DiCaprio T-shirts are common and, though Islamic laws ban it from
theaters, ``Titanic,'' is a hit on the widespread black-market
video circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a U.S. embargo, American consumer goods are common, if
over-priced, and people lunch at imitations of American restaurant
chains.
</P>
<P>
   But, the average Iranian also believes that the United States,
which did supply weaponry to Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein,
orchestrated the costly eight-year Iraqi-Iran war in which more
than 240,000 Iranians died.
</P>
<P>
   They know that the U.S. propped up the brutal Shah of Iran, who
Iranians toppled with the Islamic Revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Any doubts they might have about whether the U.S. had evil
intentions were erased in 1988, when a U.S. Navy ship shot down an
Iranian airliner, killing more than 200 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though consumer goods are available through third
countries, the embargo has made it difficult to get equipment for
Iran's huge oil industry and major public works projects.
</P>
<P>
   They say the U.S. policy in the Middle East centers on
dominating oil production and protecting Israel -- an enemy to
Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   However, Iran's fundamentalist leaders seem to almost go out of
their way to cause worry among not only Americans, but others. A
major avenue in Tehran is still named after the Islamic extremist
who lead the assassination of famed Egyptian President Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Iranian leaders just last year reaffirmed the bounty on
the head of British-based Salman Rushdie, author of ``The Satanic
Verses,'' a novel deemed blasphemy by Iranian clerics.
</P>
<P>
   The major U.S. grievances against Iran focus on three main
areas: Terrorism, its missile and nuclear program, and its
opposition to the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department named Iran among seven countries that
sponsored terrorism in 1997, calling Iran the most active.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the Iranian government supported 13
assassinations of political opponents outside Iran last year. Most
were in northern Iraq. Iran reportedly hosted the representatives
of several terrorist groups last year.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the U.S. Congress have become increasingly concerned
about Iran's efforts to develop long-range missiles that, within a
decade, could reach even Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional hard liners say that a country so rich in oil and
natural gas has no reason to build a nuclear reactor, which Iran is
doing, unless it wants to use it for developing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the U.S. wants Iran to drop its opposition to the Oslo
peace process, meant to arrange a deal between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian leaders object to the American ``accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   They deny seeking nuclear weapons and say that, while they
oppose the Oslo process, they will not interfere with it.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Iranian President Mohammad Khatami a year ago
has provided an opening. Though he is not the ultimate authority in
the Iranian government, he is popular and has expressed more
moderate views than Iran's other recent leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami several months ago stated in a televised interview that
relations between the Iranian and American people need to improve.
President Bill Clinton has answered with his own vague wishes of
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have to move away from the past mentality,''
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Javad Zarif said in an interview
recently. Otherwise, he warned, the chill between the two countries
could lead to a ``clash of civilizations . . . (which) would harm
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Zarif said any warmer relations will start on the level of
``civilizations,'' not governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very serious misunderstandings and misperceptions about Iran
exist in the United States,'' he said. He conceded that Iranians
harbor their own difficult ``political psychology'' against
America.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Optional add. Story can end here).
</P>
<P>
   So far, both sides accuse the other of being all talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not going to make any compromises, what's the point
in talking to them,'' asks Patrick Clawson, director of research at
the Washington Institute for Near East Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say the United States has to be wary of internal
Iranian politics. If America cozies up to Khatami too quickly, it
could cause a backlash against him from Iranian religious
hardliners.
</P>
<P>
   Clawson said the United States should not focus on Khatami, but
try to win over the Iranian people by giving them more access to
consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   In Tehran these days, you can meet Iranians who say they have
agreements to represent U.S. companies if the embargo ends and,
recently, Italian intermediaries helped set up a tour of Midwestern
U.S. executives to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But, it may be that tangible improvements cannot be made until
after a period of the symbolic, rhetorical, steps.
</P>
<P>
   John Woods, Iranian history expert at the University of Chicago,
said that Iranian culture dictates that enemies do not talk until
they formally reconcile and apologize. He suggests the U.S. start
by apologizing officially for shooting down the airliner in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
