<HEADER>
A9474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-SPIELBERG- &LR;      07-23 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-SPIELBERG- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRECTION-LADN 
SPIELBERG'S WAR OF INDEPENDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(NOTE: The byline has been corrected) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Steven Spielberg loved his fantasies so much that
he made the world share them.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most talented member of the generation of film
directors that took over Hollywood in the 1970s, Spielberg was the
least interested in addressing reality in his work. And that made
him the most popular director in movie history.
</P>
<P>
   But after a decade of immersing himself _ and us _ in killer
sharks, benevolent aliens and whip-cracking pulp heroes, Spielberg
began casting his imaginative eye on more plausible, often
profoundly disturbing subjects. Beginning with the 1985 ``The Color
Purple,'' he balanced the derring-do and latter-day dinosaur rides
with increasingly complicated and demanding explorations into the
kinds of hard, historical truths that Hollywood, and especially the
Hollywood that Spielberg dominated, uses all its tricks to deny and
deflect our attention from.
</P>
<P>
   This approach resulted in one of the most beloved and admired
films of all time, the uncompromising Holocaust drama ``Schindler's
List.'' It's also given us ``Empire of the Sun'' and ``Amistad,''
both perceived as rare Spielberg failures but, in fact, rigorous
and probing examinations of what's emerging as the director's great
theme: the elusive, often contradictory and always costly struggle
for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these films express a struggle within Spielberg, that of
a serious artist trying to emerge from the shadow of a consummate
showman. With his new film, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' a horrendously
graphic depiction of the D-Day landing and its brutalizing
aftermath, Spielberg may be digging for something deeper, though:
proving the adage the truth will set you free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan'' is honestly ambiguous enough to be labeled many things.
But one of them is definitely Spielberg's declaration of
independence from his own enslavement to the Hollywood fantasies
that conquered his imagination as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, who's 81 n/n 2 &QC; ught in the air force in Burma
in World War II,'' says Spielberg. ``He had reunions with his
fighter squad a lot, so, as a kid I had occasion to hear them
telling stories about what it was actually like _ stories that were
so different from the movies that Hollywood was showing me. I
didn't know who to believe, but I chose to believe the war movies
because my dad's stories were so outrageously harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I realized that my dad had been telling the truth all
along and Hollywood had been fibbing about what it was like. For 50
years, most films about World War II have been sanitized. During
the war, the movies were almost what we would call a recruitment
tool, showing the honor and the glory of serving your country to
get a lot of young men to enlist. After the war, films glorified
our victories. They made audiences understand the sacrifices, too,
but in a way that was always very safe and wholly untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg has set a number of films _ the Indiana Jones
adventures, the misfired comedy ``1941,'' ``Empire'' and
``Schindler's'' _ in the wartime and immediate pre-war eras. But
for his first real combat film, he vowed ``to acquit the veterans
and what they experienced, as opposed to using World War II as just
another springboard for an action-adventure movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a fictional script by Robert Rodat, informed by
numerous veterans' accounts and by Stephen E. Ambrose's acclaimed
nonfiction books ``Citizen Soldiers,'' ``Band of Brothers'' and
``D-Day: June 6, 1944: The Climactic Battle of World War II,''
``Ryan'' set out to depict the chaos and horror of battle like no
movie ever had before.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-minute, Normandy landing sequence that opens the film,
for example, is an unflinching blood bath, a GI's scrambling view
of fire, blood, men being torn apart, deafening noise and
overwhelming fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew nothing, but I learned from the people who were
there,'' Spielberg notes. ``I thought Omaha Beach was a victory. I
thought Normandy was a victory; we got everybody on shore, after
all, and we began to push inland the next day. I didn't realize,
until I began reading Ambrose and talking to Omaha veterans, that
it was a chaotic disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the German defenders put up their toughest fight against
the invaders at the Omaha landing site, by the end of June 6 all
five Normandy beaches had been secured. But it would be months
before Allied forces fought their way into the rest of France.
``Ryan'' regroups a few days after the landing, when a squad of
eight D-Day survivors led by Capt. Miller (Tom Hanks) is ordered
behind enemy lines to find a paratrooper, Matt Damon's Pvt. Ryan,
lost in the thoroughly botched, pre-invasion airdrop.
</P>
<P>
   His three brothers had been killed within the same week, so the
U.S. Command wants to send Ryan home intact to his grieving mother.
Providing he's still alive, or that the eight resentful men in
Miller's squad can find him before they're all killed.
</P>
<P>
   Although this main part of the movie explores the truly knotty
issues more associated with films about the Vietnam War than
America's idealized Good War, it's that bloodily realistic D-Day
sequence that has everybody talking.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too grisly for audience sensibilities conditioned by
decades of glamorized, as well as sanitized, movie violence? Should
it have earned the film an NC-17 rating, instead of the R it got?
Should the director-executive have been less graphic in the hope of
greater box-office acceptance _ especially since DreamWorks, the
mega-company he heads with Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen, has
yet to enjoy the kind of blockbuster hits like ``Mask of Zorro,''
``Men in Black'' and ``The Lost World'' Spielberg still produces
for other studios?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the freedom to make a movie like `Saving Private Ryan'
necessarily rough,'' he says, ``as opposed to having a studio boss
say, `Distill it and water it down like all those other World War
II movies, so maybe we can make a profit.' If I shoot myself in the
foot by making `Private Ryan' too much of a tough journey, at least
I made that choice. And that's what success allows you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to give the audience a physical experience,
not just a voyeuristic one. I did everything in my power to create
a visceral, honest look back at something that actually happened.
If the film had been rated NC-17, I would have accepted the rating
without protest. But I would not have cut the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think there are people who will submit to the film. It's
a very potent cocktail, and people will be both shaken and stirred
by it. And if they give it a chance, there will be those who say,
`It's too real,' and there are others who will say, `I think it was
a very honest re-creation.'''
</P>
<P>
   Shot on a Normandy-like stretch of the Irish coast (with the
Irish army, as it did for ``Braveheart,'' supplying hundreds of
extras), the D-Day sequence was filmed during four six-day weeks,
more or less in the chronological continuity with which it unfolds
on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Always the consummate formal geniuses, Spielberg and his
director of photography, Janusz Kaminski, shot the whole thing with
handheld, unstabilized cameras from low angles, approximating the
``scared-of-getting-their-heads-shot-off'' perspective of real
combat photographers. Sixty percent of the footage's color
saturation then was drained out, giving the images a slightly
antique quality that somehwK enhances, rather than mutes, their
horror.
</P>
<P>
   When such artistry is put in the service of locating visual
truth, can the creator go back to the business of making really
convincing-looking velociraptors?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can always wear two hats, believe me,'' Spielberg says.
``I'm not a born-again sociologist with a camera. I love
entertainment, I understand how to do that kind of picture _ and
I'm learning how to do a picture like this.''
</P>
<P>
   And learning from it. While his commitment to more mindless fare
sounds solid, Spielberg also is nursing some serious doubts about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always going to make movies that are entertaining, and
that trade on violence for entertainment,'' he says. ``That's just
the reality of the industry. But you know, the problem these days _
and I am right in the middle of the culpability for this, so please
don't think I'm this holier-than-thou person giving a lecture _ is
that we've desensitized audiences through violence that is both
entertaining and creative.''
</P>
<P>
   And, it might be added, with movies that are simultaneously
stimulating, reassuring and manipulative in patently false ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, I feel that `Schindler's List' and now `Saving
Private Ryan' can re-sensitize people to realistic experiences'' at
the movies, he says. ``They're not just saying, `You're going to be
safe voyeurs in this movie theater.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asking a lot of the audience,'' he acknowledges, and in
that realization you can detect the risk and exhilaration that
always accompanies liberation. ``I'm asking them to participate in
the experience of those soldiers who had to do their jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
