<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLY-FILM-REVIEW-500     07-23 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLY-FILM-REVIEW-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BILLY'S HOLLYWOOD SCREEN KISS': SWEETLY GOOFY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the opening moments of ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss,''
when the title character blithely chirps, ``I am a homosexual,''
it's clear that in its erotic nonchalance, this envelope-pushing
romantic comedy picks up several steps beyond where ``The Opposite
of Sex'' left off.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is West Hollywood, and the central character, Billy
Collier (Sean P. Hayes), is an ingenuous, slightly geeky-looking
young art photographer who rates himself a six on the Kinsey
one-to-six scale measuring homosexuality. Billy even jokes about
having inherited ``the show-tune gene.''
</P>
<P>
   If this sweetly goofy film, written and directed by Tommy
O'Haver, doesn't feature any famous show tunes, it might still be
described as a nonsinging musical comedy in which boy meets boy,
boy loses boy, and boy _ well, it would be unfair to give away the
bittersweet ending.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about the movie, except its realistic performances,
feels playfully surreal. When Billy recalls his youth, he displays
a series of witty candid snapshots that exist only in his mind. (He
couldn't have taken them, because he's in the photos.) Instead of a
traditional Broadway chorus line, the movie presents a mocking
Greek chorus of three comic drag queens lip-syncing the '60s hits
of Petula Clark. These gauzy musical baubles lend the movie the
same spirit of campy uplift that the hits of Mama Cass brought to
the film ``Beautiful Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' is really about the way the
idealized romantic fantasies peddled by Hollywood in the 1940s and
'50s continue to exert an inordinate power over our lives. When
Billy first sees his 19-year-old dream lover, Gabriel (Brad Rowe),
in a West Hollywood coffeehouse, which suggests the late-'90s
equivalent of a corner soda shop in an Andy Hardy film, he is
instantly smitten.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel, an aspiring musician who works as a waiter at the
coffeehouse, exudes the downy-cheeked glow of a shrink-wrapped boy
toy imported directly from the set of ``Baywatch.'' Although
Gabriel has left a girlfriend behind in San Francisco to pursue his
fortune in Los Angeles, he is unfazed by Billy's obvious romantic
interest. Their friendship reaches a crossroads in a suspenseful
scene in which they share a bed and Billy tremblingly makes his
move.
</P>
<P>
   Not just his romantic life but Billy's work revolves around
Hollywood fantasies. Encouraged by a mentor (Richard Ganoung) who
is as besotted with Billy as Billy is with Gabriel, he decides to
put together a photography show in which male couples recreate
famous Hollywood love scenes. For his first photo shoot, Billy
persuades Gabriel to re-enact with the former Warhol drag star
Holly Woodlawn the steamy surfside clinch of Burt Lancaster and
Deborah Kerr in ``From Here to Eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest failure of the movie is that it gets virtually no
comic mileage from the amusing notion of having drag queens
impersonate former film goddesses in classic love scenes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Buoying the film are some sharply drawn minor characters.
Georgiana (Meredith Scott Lynn), a painter who is Billy's roommate,
doesn't think twice about sleeping with a jerk if he provides good
sex. When she and Billy descend on Catalina, where Gabriel has been
whisked off by a lecherous older photographer (Paul Bartel) to
appear in a fashion spread, she gamely endures the hilariously
stoned-out groans of a hippie sailor (Carmine Giovinazzo) who picks
up a guitar and serenades her with an excruciating love song he has
composed in honor of their one-night stand.
</P>
<P>
   It would be stretching a point to compare ``Billy's Hollywood
Screen Kiss'' with Shakespeare. But when most of the characters
converge on Catalina, this island where sexual chaos erupts begins
to resemble an up-to-the-minute West Coast composite of the dream
worlds of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' ``The Tempest'' and
``Twelfth Night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' isn't at all deep. But in its
cheerful, fun-loving way, it reminds us that in our endlessly
self-referential, image-conscious pop culture, fantasy is what
makes the world go 'round.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BILLY'S HOLLYWOOD SCREEN KISS' Written and directed by Tommy
O'Haver; director of photography, Mark Mervis; edited by Jeff
Betancourt; production designer, Franco-Giacamo Carbone; produced
by David Moseley; released by Trimark Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sean P. Hayes (Billy), Brad Rowe (Gabriel), Meredith Scott
Lynn (Georgiana), Paul Bartel (Rex Webster), Richard Ganoung
(Perry) and Carmine Giovinazzo (Gundy). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 92 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has sexual situations
and frank sexual talk.
</P>
</TEXT>
