<SLUG> BC-TV-EUBANKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THAT JAZZ WITH LENO? JUST MUSIC TO HIS EARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Kevin Eubanks doesn't make many moves without
someone noticing. And this goes way back. When he began recording
for the instrumental-pop-oriented GRP Records in 1983, the jazz
press frowned, whining about an utter compromise of ``musical
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Eubanks _ a fine guitarist whose 1988 album
``Shadow Prophets'' was Radio and Records' top contemporary jazz
album of the year _ has always found that a moralistic attitude
toward his art results in creative limitations he refuses to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine jazz purists dropping dead as word spread in
1992 that he had signed with Branford Marsalis to play in the house
band for the musically challenged ``Tonight Show'' with Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over as music director for Marsalis three years
ago, Eubanks has become quite entrenched, a Hollywood player
unaware of his growing stature, but keenly knowledgeable of his
place in the center of the ongoing debate about musicians and
soul-selling. The 40-year-old Eubanks has found a fluid, creative
relationship with the host of a bland, middle-of-the-road talk
show, a guy who relies on their exchanges to keep the show's flow
steady and the proceedings cheery.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most persistent questions Eubanks fields these days
isn't whether he has sold out, but how he could possibly remain
creative while anchored to a daily network television gi  &QC; here
comedic chit-chat is required.
</P>
<P>
   This is senseless to Eubanks, because playing in front of
millions nightly, backing everyone from Garth Brooks to Luther
Vandross, doesn't change anything about his music. In fact, he
feels it merely broadens his range, expands his awareness and
creates even more opportunities to enjoy his kind of music.
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, with a shrug of the shoulders, ``You know, people
will always say something no matter what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite hanging with Leno weekdays, Eubanks spends some weekends
on the road _ he just returned from Portland, Ore., and heads to
Nashville, Tenn., next month. And the ``Tonight Show'' connection
has given him and his band members the kind of exposure many
musicians would kill for.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other night, the band's saxophonist, Ralph Moore;
drummer, Marvin ``Smitty'' Smith; and bassist, Bob Hurst, kicked it
at Club Brasserie in the Bel Age Hotel. Judging by what was played
(tunes from John Coltrane and Benny Golson, to name two) and the
audience's approval, this crowd wasn't made up of heartland
tourists lured by a TV star.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get on something like Leno and all of a sudden you're no
longer the stereotypical starving musician dying for his art,''
Eubanks says. ``There's the perception that you have just kind of
forgotten about the music you've loved all your life. Does that
make any sense?''
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks didn't hesitate to replace Marsalis, even amid rumors
that Marsalis was feeling creatively bankrupt and could no longer
stomach the shot-the-breeze chats with Leno. Where Marsalis felt
uneasy, Eubanks feels at ease, even when inserted into scripted
comedy skits or unscripted banter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really just a matter of developing a feel for your place
on the show, and that's to go back and forth with Jay,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an actor,'' Eubanks says. ``I just say things that
come to my head. It works. The more you get to know somebody the
easier it is to talk. You don't have to think of anything to say.
It just comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks grew up in Philadelphia but has spent most of his adult
life in New York be-bop clubs. He sold lots of records in the '80s
and signed on with Blue Note Records in the early '90s, teaming
with bassists like Dave Holland. And living in Los Angeles, Eubanks
still makes time to write, rehearse or simply jam with the horde of
migrated New York musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking anything away from the musicians here, but the
LA thing is more of a presentation,'' he says. ``New York is kind
of what it is; LA is kind of what it ``looks'' like.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it doesn't matter how much you're on TV, how many
movies you're on or whatever you do. It's not going to help you
play better. It's not going to help you get to the next chord or
write that next song. That comes from rehearsal, gigs,
dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
