<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN' IS POWERFUL, SHATTERING EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I might as well say this straight off: Steven Spielberg's
near-three-hour ``Saving Private Ryan'' is quite simply one of the
most powerful war movies ever made, and a shattering emotional
experience. Be warned: this one is not for the faint of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to earlier reports, it's not exactly an anti-war film.
Though it plays with a central incongruity and makes us want to get
as far away from war as possible, it believes in the crusade
against Hitler, and displays little of the irony or ambivalence of
its reputed model, David Lean's ``The Bridge on the River Kwai.''
</P>
<P>
   It's essentially a combat film: a gritty, harrowingly authentic
account of what it must have been like to be a dogface in the midst
of America's bloodiest war _ so real and immediate and unrelenting
that it creates much of the same kind of battle stress in its
audience that the real participants must have felt.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with a devastating, 30-minute sequence of the
D-Day landing on Omaha Beach during World War II: a sequence shot
mostly in a jumpy, handheld-camera style, but that is so skillful
and so progressively unsettling that it soon wipes away our memory
of ``The Longest Day,'' ``Platoon,'' and just about every other war
movie ever made. It puts us in a different psychological place
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The script then settles into its premise: a story about a
special mission given a veteran Army captain (Tom Hanks) to find a
certain Private Ryan (Matt Damon) whose three brothers have been
killed in combat that same week and who General George Marshall
(Harve Presnell) personally wants to get back to his mother in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The captain gathers a squad of men, and the rest of the film
follows their episodic journey deep into France as they look for
the illusive title character who parachuted behind enemy lines on
D-Day _ culminating in yet another extended battle sequence in a
French village that is almost as horrifying as the opening scenes.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way he managed to find an upbeat message in the
Holocaust (``Schindler's List'') and the shame of American Slavery,
(``Amistad'') Spielberg's message here is a positive one. As futile
and even absurd as it may seem to risk the lives of eight men to
``rescue'' a man who might already be dead, Spielberg sees the
mission as one of nobility _ the kind of nobility of spirit that
differentiated us from our enemy in that conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's so hyper-realistic for such a long period of screen
time, and the audience goes (literally, I'll wager) into such a
state of shock, that this message falls a bit flat. It's hard to
feel anything but primal fear, and hard to even notice the subtle
theme, the innovative camerawork of Janusz Kaminski and the fine,
understated performances of Hanks, Damon, Tom Sizemore and the rest
of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the gore either _ the arms blown off, the heads
removed from bodies before our eyes, the faces reduced to
hamburger. We've seen all this before. The horror of the film is
more in the way it conveys a sense of utter helplessness, the
perverse element of chance at work and the sheer magnitude and
impersonality of the slaughter. Combat on film never has seemed so
agonizingly unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   How then do you classify such an experience? Art? Entertainment?
An epic adventure? To be accurate, it's none of the above. Nor is
it a thriller, a character piece, or a penetrating study of men in
war. Despite the presence of mega-star Hanks in the lead, he's so
constrained and understated it's not even a star vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The film is more properly a ``trip'' movie, a Spielbergian
theme-park ride that induCe$Y[W-91
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1600EDT &QL; 
