<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9550 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MATTDAMON-TEX     07-23 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MATTDAMON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SUDDEN FAME, DAMON STAYS FOCUSED _ EVEN AT WORK WITH HERO
SPIELBERG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How the hell,'' asks Stephen Ambrose, ``does Matt Damon handle
it?''
</P>
<P>
   The tough, outspoken historian and author of several books,
including ``Citizen Soldiers,'' which is the spiritual basis for
much of ``Saving Private Ryan'' scratches his head about the nature
of celebrity. The man he wonders about _ and likes _ is nonplused
by it as well. ``I gotta tell you, man,'' Damon says, surrounded by
a pile of cigarette debris and looking slightly embarrassed. ``It
is totally surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon could be discussing the World War II epic ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' in which he has a slim, but key, role. Instead, the
27-year-old actor is talking about the fame that has enveloped him
since last winter's ``Good Will Hunting.'' Damon's life has gone
from staid to turbulent. Every date _ especially those with
ex-flame Minnie Driver _ every meal, every public moment has become
the subject of tabloid scrutiny. But that hasn't stopped him from
concentrating on his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely odd, because I am totally the same guy. So to
walk into a room six months ago and not turn any heads. And now
...'' His voice trails off as he watches the cigarette smoke curl
up lazily from the ashtray. ``For me, it's just a clear
demonstration of how powerful the medium is. It has nothing to do
with me, or my work, in a lot of ways. I mean, `Good Will Hunting'
was the first thing I'd been in that people saw. I've been in huge
bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those was 1993's ``Geronimo: An American Legend,'' in
which he played a part that bears some similarities to the
character he plays in ``Ryan.'' Damon was Britton Davis, the
good-natured observer who bore witness to the U.S. Army's shameful
treatment of Geronimo and his tribe. In ``Ryan,'' he's the man who
has to be brought home to his family after his brothers are killed
in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis had such decency. In reading his book, he was such an
impressive guy. And Ryan is a symbol for everybody's brother,
everybody's chance to go home. They are both similar in a lot of
ways. They're both symbols of America's future. And they're both
catalysts, each carrying his own sense of guilt into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   By guilt, Damon means that Ryan has a lot to live up to, seeing
the men come to take him home. ``Well,'' he says, lighting up, ``we
catch him at the most critical time in his life, when he hears the
worst news he could possibly hear. So the decision he makes _ not
wanting to go home _ makes a lot of sense to me. I'm not sure if I
could make that choice. I would think that, if it were me, I'd go
running home to my mom after having seen what he saw. But at the
same time, it was a different era, people were different. And the
news he got could get your hackles up enough to make you do just
about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's willfulness isn't that far from Will Hunting's tenacity.
It makes one wonder whether Damon is attracted to characters with a
hot self-destructive streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' he blurts out, laughing. ``That self-destructive
thing, it's a very dramatic impulse. In `Good Will Hunting,' that
impulse set the action in motion. If it wasn't about a guy who was
going out and drinking all night and beating people to within an
inch of their lives, it wouldn't be much of a story. Instead, it'd
be about a guy who's gone to get a job at Raytheon. What kind of
movie is that?''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles. ``I guess you could say the same for Davis in
`Geronimo.' In writing the book about the campaign, he sacrifices
his future _ his standing, perhaps _ for the truth. But it's
interesting when people are being true to themselves and following
the road that can lead to self-destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon also played a character who fell apart under war, in
``Courage Under Fire,'' and whose life afterward also led to a kind
of self-immolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what that character was to me. I wanted to show a man
who was completely ravaged by what had happened to him, decisions
he had made _ to be active or not active _ in a split second.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no self-destructive impulse about Damon's signing on
to work with legendary director Steven Spielberg. ``I knew,'' he
says, ``that this was gonna be the chance of a lifetime. What I
found was that he was really accessible. Because all the young guys
in the audience, they're all filmmakers _ writers and directors.
And Steven was attracted to that. I think he sees himself in that.
He took the time to tutor us. Believe me, I asked him every single
question you could ask. He was totally enthusiastic, and I was just
a scrub on the set.''
</P>
<P>
   His mounting enthusiasm in discussing Spielberg's command
explodes upon discussion of a specific scene in which one actor
runs from a battle site to the top floor of a chateau. The scene
was captured in a single shot.
</P>
<P>
   Damon stands and shouts gleefully. ``Oh, my God. I couldn't
believe it. It's insane. How does somebody even think of something
like that? It's ridiculous. I'm tellin' everybody about this shot,
man, because I was right next to him when he did it. And it wasn't
planned! He just decided to do it, and it only took half a day. And
he never loses the story. That's where young directors trying all
of this flashy stuff fail. Because they make the mistake of just
trying to show off. To be next to him when he's making those
decisions, with total confidence, that would have me hemming and
hawing for years!''
</P>
<P>
   He slumps back into his chair and shakes his head, unable to
dislodge the grin from his face. ``I don't think anybody should be
that confident. I said to him, `What were you thinking, not
storyboarding this movie?' And (Spielberg) said, `It's the
adrenaline rush!'''
</P>
<P>
   Damon's next picture picks up the thread of self-damage; in
``Rounders'' set for release this fall, he and Edward Norton play a
pair of compulsive gamblers. But the movie he's about to start
shooting is the story of a man who both damages himself and turns
it back on others. He's starring in Anthony Minghella's (''The
English Patient'') adaptation of Patricia Highsmith's ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   He has trimmed down for the role; he's barely bigger than one of
the cigarettes he's chain-smoking. ``I'm heading off to Italy to do
it. Y'know, it's got this great obsession of unobtainable love and
this guy who destroys everything that he does love,'' he says,
chuckling, with a glint in his eye that couldn't be further from
Tom Ripley's amoral manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' Damon says, laughing abashedly and hissing a
plume of smoke. ``It's an embarrassment of riches.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
