<HEADLINE>
DISK-DRIVE MAKER OUSTS ITS LEADER IN SUDDEN SHAKEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Most executives ``leave to pursue other
interests,'' retire or invoke some other catch phrases to mask a
sacking by the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   But Seagate Technology Inc.'s flamboyant founder and chief
executive, Al Shugart, was just plain, outright fired by the
world's largest computer disk-drive maker.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Tuesday, the Scotts Valley, Calif.-based
company announced that Shugart was ``leaving Seagate at the request
of the company's board of directors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(T)he time had come to make a change in the leadership of the
company,'' Seagate said in the announcement. Shugart was replaced
by Seagate president and chief operating officer, Stephen Luczo.
</P>
<P>
   But Shugart refuses to go quietly. Not surprising, considering
the executive's bombastic past.
</P>
<P>
   While leading Seagate, the 67-year-old Shugart has been the
flamboyant point man on initiatives limiting lawyer contingency
fees and shareholder lawsuits, and helped head a failed push for
no-fault auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Shugart said the ouster was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was doing a really good job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get anything out of them. They said it was time for
a leadership change. You won't resign. So you're fired. I was
contacted by the company's outside board members on Saturday. On
Sunday we had a telephone board meeting, and I was fired,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shugart said, however, that he remains a member of the company's
board of directors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
