<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO HELP INVESTORS, 250 CORPORATIONS ARE EVALUATED ON SOCIAL ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being a socially responsible investor isn't as easy as it may
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the Texas State Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted recently to sell its $46 million worth of Walt
Disney Co. stock after viewing violent and sexually explicit clips
from films made by Miramax Films, a Disney subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   But was it the children's school money going to unseemly films
that sparked that decision, or the pressure from the year-old
national boycott of Disney by the Southern Baptism Convention over
Disney giving benefits to gay and lesbian domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   And what about other Disney issues. Sure, they just built this
great zoo theme park in Florida that creates hundreds of acres of
natural habitat for its animals, but isn't this the same company
that was stopped by the Environmental Protection Agency, historians
and other groups from trying to build a theme park on historic
grounds in Virginia?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the National Hispanic Media Coalition has also called
for a Disney boycott over its record of hiring Latinos.
International labor groups have called for a boycott of its toys
made in China, Haiti and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But let's also look at some of the other holdings of the Texas
board's portfolio, such as Harrah's Entertainment and
Anheuser-Busch Cos. Could those investments be deemed inappropriate
as well?
</P>
<P>
   Such is the brave new world of one of the hottest and most
controversial investment trends today: socially responsible
investing.
</P>
<P>
   This trend is skyrocketing. In 1997, $1.2 trillion in assets in
the United States were in what was deemed socially and
environmentally responsible portfolios, up a whopping 85 percent
from 1995, according to a Social Investment Forum study.
</P>
<P>
   A new book chronicles the trend and provides information and
ratings on 250 major corporations.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``The Corporate Report Card: Rating 250 of America's
Corporations for the Socially Responsible Investor'' (Dutton, 260
pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $1 out of every $10 invested in U.S. stocks is socially
managed, either through screening, voting proxies or filing of
shareholder resolutions, according to the book, which was written
by the staff members of the Council on Economic Priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This growing phenomenon illustrates that investors are
increasingly showing a preference for well managed companies that
operate on principles of long-term profitability inextricably
linked to social responsibility,'' CEP says.
</P>
<P>
   The council, formed in 1969 in New York City, has been active in
developing several programs to not only provide information and
ratings on corporations to investors, but also to use its
information to influence the corporations.
</P>
<P>
   For example, CEP's studies have provided the pressure needed to
improve the pulp and paper industries, as well as other major
polluters. Also, the council's Campaign for Cleaner Corporations
program has identified 23 corporate polluters, and each of the
companies has discussed its performance with CEP, negotiated change
and made improvements.
</P>
<P>
   CEP also awards companies with corporate conscience awards for
such issues as charitable contributions, community involvement,
equal employment opportunity, family concerns, global ethics,
animal rights and education.
</P>
<P>
   Now, CEP offers a book that evaluates 250 corporations on such
issues as the environment, woman and minority advancement,
charitable giving, community outreach, family benefits, workplace
issues and social disclosure. Along with a grade from ``A'' to
``F'' ranking these issues, CEP provides a short analysis
discussing recent court cases, Occupational Safety and Health
Administration action, corporate policies and other records.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies information that may muddy the waters of investor
decisions rather than clarify. For example, CEP gives Exxon an
``A'' rating on the environment, then proceeds to tell readers that
the company's average toxic releases have increased a sixth
annually, ``one of the worst performance within the industry
sample.''
</P>
<P>
   In another entry, Nike was given an ``A'' with a question mark
for workplace issues (the question mark indicates the grade is
based only on partial information.) But in the notes entry, CEP
says that in West Java, where the majority of Nike shoes are made,
most workers earned Java's minimum wage, were subjected to forced
overtime, punished for taking sick leave and lacked decent drinking
water on site.
</P>
<P>
   Still, taken on its whole, especially reading the company notes,
the book can provide investors with a great deal of information on
socially related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it's up to the investor to make the tough decisions.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
