<HEADLINE>
`MAFIA': A MAD LOOK AT THE MOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(th) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mafia!'' makes an offer you could probably refuse. But its
Mad-style, hit-or-miss humor has enough hits, pardon the
expression, to keep it breezy and reasonably bright.
</P>
<P>
   This time Jim Abrahams, once part of the ``Airplane!'' team and
since then the auteur behind the ``Hot Shots!'' parodies, directs
his try-anything enthusiasm to the Godfather genre and comes up
with anything from canned meatballs by Spalding to a
turn-of-the-century Sicilian village with a ``Got vino?''
advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In much the same spirit, Abrahams' official biography notes his
past work and adds: ``In addition to these pictures, Abrahams has
also attended screenings of `Gandhi' (1984), `Wall Street' (1988),
`Dances With Wolves' (1991) and `Silence of the Lambs' (1992).''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that a Mafia sendup without a single horse in a movie
producer's bed (and without anyone who sounds like Joe Pesci) has
left a stone or two unturned. It's also true that ``Mafia!'' has a
predictably gross, sophomoric streak and that some of it _ like the
original title, ``Jane Austen's `Mafia!''' _ has a way of falling
flat.
</P>
<P>
   But Abrahams dutifully takes on classics of the genre,
``Casino'' and the ``Godfather'' films, and succeeds in having his
share of irreverent fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not my father, Diane, just as you're not your father,''
the film's Michael Corleone type (Jay Mohr) tells his waspy fiance
(Christina Applegate). ``If we were our fathers, what we did last
night would be legal only in Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain familiar scenes are inevitably revisited, like the
shooting of the patriarch called Don Cortino. (Lloyd Bridges, to
whose memory the film is dedicated, again showed how wonderfully
sporting and debonair he could be under the zaniest circumstances.)
</P>
<P>
   The Don appears to be dancing the macarena while being riddled
with bullets, and he later winds up unattended in a hospital room.
``No doctors, no nurses _ there's no one here to help him!'' Diane
exclaims. ``Diane, he belongs to an HMO,'' the Don's son explains.
</P>
<P>
   This parody also visits the Las Vegas of ``Casino'' to absurd
effect. (At the gaming tables, they're playing Chutes and Ladders
and go fish.) But it gets crazier and less obvious when it starts
throwing in everything but the kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   So during a ``Godfather''-esque montage mixing violent events
with a church ceremony, little baby raptors out of ``The Lost
World'' somehow figure in the equation. ``Jaws,'' ``Forrest Gump,''
the Lord of the Dance troupe and ``The English Patient'' also have
their unlikely places here, although the last one is used to
notably crude effect.
</P>
<P>
   Movies this summer seem determined to reveal how many new ways
there are to vomit, and so far there's no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mafia!'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned). It
includes many numerous gross-outs and occasional mildly lewd gags.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MAFIA!'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jim Abrahams; written by Abrahams, Greg Norberg and
Michael McManus; director of photography, Pierre Letarte; edited by
Terry Stokes; music by Gianni Frizzelli; production designer,
William Elliott; produced by Bill Badalato; released by Touchstone
Pictures. Running time: 86 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jay Mohr (Anthony Cortino), Billy Burke (Joey Cortino),
Christina Applegate (Diane), Pamela Gidley (Pepper Gianini),
Olympia Dukakis (Sophia), Lloyd Bridges (Vincenzo Cortino) and
Jason Fuchs (Young Vincenzo). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
