<HEADLINE>
FEMA TO HELP CALIFORNIA LANDSLIDE VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a major policy shift, the federal government
has decided to make $20 million available to landslide victims in
California who agree to leave their houses and relocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about buyouts. ... Purchase of the property. No
new construction,'' Michael Armstrong, associate director of the
Federal Emergency Management Agency, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, FEMA has provided financial assistance to victims
of fires, floods and earthquakes, but not landslides or mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains blamed on the El Nino weather phenomenon spawned
landslides that caused extensive damage to several dozen homes in
San Mateo and Sonoma counties.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Office of Emergency Services has just mailed grant
applications to 1,050 city and county managers, who will
investigate homeowner claims and recommend grant awards.
</P>
<P>
   Jurisdictions must submit notices of interest to the Office of
Emergency Services by Aug. 7. Individual homeowners must apply at
city halls or county seats from July 27 to Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local governments are expected to identify specific properties
for buyout,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   OES Deputy Director Cheryl Tateishi said her office intends to
submit the list of approved applications for grants to FEMA by Oct.
19. Armstrong said successful applicants who are approved for
buyouts should start receiving their money in early November.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for assistance, the property must be at ``imminent
landslide risk'' and uninhabitable. The cost of removal must not
exceed $140 per square foot of enclosed, heated living space, and
the property owner must relocate without rebuilding on the same
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a voluntary action,'' Armstrong said. Once the property
is acquired for public use by the local jurisdiction, it becomes
permanent open space, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
