</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: OVER THE TOP WITH DESIGN IN EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For our great-grandfathers, the concept of
commissioning a house or a room in a single, coordinated style was
novel. For them, art meant painting and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   But the Esthetic Movement, which came to the United States from
England in the 1870s, emphasized the role of art in the creation of
furniture, fabrics, wallpaper, pottery and stained glass. Designers
like the Herter Brothers and Louis Comfort Tiffany felt confident _
as did Frank Lloyd Wright a few decades later _ that they could
design everything: the architecture and what went inside it,
including textiles, tables, chairs and lighting.
</P>
<P>
   And their clients believed they could, too. William H.
Vanderbilt had a Japanese parlor in his New York City mansion, just
as John D. Rockefeller had a Moorish smoking room. Margaret
Caldwell, a private Manhattan dealer in 19th-century American,
French and British furniture, explained that proponents of the
Esthetic Movement ``took design to a new, more opulent level for
clients who had made fortunes as profiteers in the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These people wanted to go over the top,'' she said. ``They
were nouveaux riches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Esthetic Movement, which began in the mid-19th century as a
critique of the cold, factory-made products of the Industrial
Revolution, led to an insatiable appetite for exalted craftsmanship
and highly decorated material goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget, they called this `art' furniture,'' Ms. Caldwell
said. ``It was listed as a specialty among furniture makers, and
clients considered their work radical and chic.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is difficult to visualize the interior of a grand
Esthetic Movement house. There was pattern everywhere: on the
walls, ceilings, carpets, draperies, pillows and sofas. Ornament
covered everything. There were more tasseled lamps, vases, art
glass and upholstered furniture than you could shake a stick at.
</P>
<P>
   When you understand the visual complexity of the decorating
schemes, it becomes possible to appreciate that each piece of
furniture had to be able to stand on its own four legs, so to
speak. Ms. Caldwell has such furniture.
</P>
<P>
   She is selling two white oak dining chairs (from a set of 36)
that the Herter Brothers designed in 1879-83 for William H.
Vanderbilt's house at Fifth Avenue and 57th Street. Each chair has
a carved cornucopia and ribbon tied in a bow, a la Louis XV, on the
crest rail. Under the seat, the side stretchers are decorated with
a Greek key motif. The knees and ankles of the chairs have brass
plates, like Japanese furniture. On the skirt under the seat rail a
small peapod bursting with fat peas is carved discreetly at the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these cultural references have been put together on
purpose,'' Ms. Caldwell said, ``but people don't understand them
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caldwell also has a circa 1878 library table ($95,000)
designed by Frank Furness, the Philadelphia architect made famous
by his flamboyant building for the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine
Arts in 1876, the year of the American Centennial. The Circassian
walnut table was designed for Henry Gibson, the president of the
Academy, in the Gothicized style created by Bruce Talbert, a
British architect who was the leading interpreter of the reform
Gothic style in England in the 1860s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is close to the English Arts and Crafts style and rare,''
Ms. Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   On the more whimsical side, she has a Moorish Revival display
cabinet that she thinks was shown in the Chicago Exposition of
1893. It is a rosewood confection, totally asymmetrical, with
display shelves and drawers and specially made gilded brass
hardware. The secondary woods in the interior are mahogany, poplar
and white oak. There is a secret pen dawer in it, and the whole
cabinet comes apart in two pieces.
</P>
<P>
   It's a show-stopper, but it is not signed. As Ms. Caldwell said:
``What's so exciting about this field is that there is so little
known. There have been only a handful of museum shows, so it's one
of the last areas in the decorative arts to be explored.''
</P>
<P>
   Margot Johnson, a longtime private dealer in Manhattan
specializing in Esthetic Movement antiques, thinks the period has
appeal today because ``it has a modern look to it _ it's so
streamlined.''
</P>
<P>
   She has a large Esthetic Movement mirror of ebonized cherrywood
($125,000) that was made for the George Beale Sloane mansion in
Oswego, N.Y., in 1872. Its corners are inlaid with paler woods
depicting lion masks. There are Japanesque rosettes in ivory,
gilding around the frames, and gilded reeding.
</P>
<P>
   She is also selling a square rosewood occasional table with a
Japanesque flavor. It has one shelf with three slender spindles.
The top is inlaid with brass stringing, depicting a spider, a fly
and a butterfly. There are inlays of copper, mother of pearl and
pewter. It was made by A.&AMP; H. Lejambre of Philadelphia around 1880
and is very similar to a Lejambre table in the collection of the
St. Louis Art Museum, which was in the Metropolitan Museum of Art's
1987 show ``In Pursuit of Beauty: Americans and the Esthetic
Movement.''.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Johnson, the whimsical Lejambre table epitomizes the
best of the Esthetic Movement. ``There is no heaviness
whatsoever,'' she said. ``This is the most delicate, refined table
you could ever imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Another singular piece Ms. Johnson is selling is a Louis Comfort
Tiffany three-panel screen made for the Kimball House in Rochester
in 1882. In the center of its rosewood frame is a large sheet of
amber glass covered with a fine, wirework design of Moorish
inspiration. The frame is embellished with Tiffany glass jewels in
a Moorish pattern. The sides are painted Whistler blue, and the
back of the screen depicts a Whistleresque nocturne. This may not
look modern, but it is as fabulous as any peacock. Price: $395,000.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are only beginning to appreciate the design,
craftsmanship and assemblage of materials that the Esthetic
Movement represents. They already know, however, that they need not
put these pieces back into their original environments. The total
look in Esthetic Movement antiques is beyond the skill (and
pocketbook) of most designers.
</P>
<P>
   These antiques have all the bells and whistles they need, all by
themselves, to grace even the most minimalist of interiors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
