<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With TOBACCO-BLACKS. For release Sunday, July 26.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FACTS ABOUT AFRICAN AMERICANS AND TOBACCO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An estimated 48,000 African-Americans die from smoking related
diseases each year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  African-American smokers have a 50 percent higher probability
of developing lung cancer than whites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Between the 1950s and the 1980s, lung cancer deaths increased
381 percent in black men and 440 percent in black women.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Smoking has increased 80 percent in the past six years among
black youths. With the increase, about 20 percent of all black
high-school students smoke.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the general population, lung cancer accounts for 13 percent
of all cancers. In African-American men, it accounts for 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 81 percent of black male smokers with lung cancer die,
compared to 54 percent of their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Last week, a House Appropriations committee approved an
amendment to add a new label to cigarette packages warning of a
particular health danger of smoking to African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: American Lung Association, U.S. Surgeon General,
National Cancer Institute, Kaiser Foundation studies.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO INDUSTRY CONTRIBUTIONS
</P>
<P>
   House, 1997-8 election cycle
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C. _ $8,300
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rep. Bob Etheridge, D-N.C. _ $20,750
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rep. Walter Jones, R-N.C. _ $14,100
</P>
<P>
   Senate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sen. Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C. _ $108,486 since the election
cycle ending in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. _ $105,200, from 1991-1996.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
