<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARMEN-POLICY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO INTERPRET THE POLICY LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGAME, Calif. _ As you knew he would, Carmen Policy said
what he wanted to say, the way he wanted to say it, and left you to
read the volumes between his lines.
</P>
<P>
   So we shall. Policy spent Wednesday morning waving so long to
the area he called ``God's Garden Isle,'' and will be flashing his
sometimes mesmerizing smile to a gathering of Cleveland media some
time in the next two or three days as part of the proposed new
Browns' ownership group led by Al Lerner.
</P>
<P>
   All the better, one presumes, to exact a slow but steady revenge
upon the man who chased him out of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   True, starting a professional football team from scratch with an
idea toward catching the 49ers isn't exactly the same as doing a
book report on ``Green Eggs And Ham'' based solely on the Cliff
Notes. If he really wanted to drop the surest and swiftest hammer
on his new enemy-for-life, Eddie DeBartolo, he would have taken a
job in the NFL office, taken the 49ers out of the NFC West and then
made them play 13 road games every year.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the road he chose, albeit one step ahead of the tall
skeletal figure with the scythe and the bad tailor. And while he
sat with his interim successor, Larry Thrailkill, acting the
cordial departee, he couldn't make the show go as smoothly as the
DeBartolos hoped he would.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Denise DeBartolo York, with whom he was supposed
to have a tenuous relationship, spoke warmly when he handed in his
key to the executive one-chaired library, but said his relationship
with Eddie ``has been put through the deep freeze, and it hasn't
defrosted through the last number of months.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Eddie still regards Policy as treacherous and
will hold that grudge deep into the next millennium. Policy even
said when a rapprochement comes, ``I'll be the one to pick up the
phone.'' In other words, they'll see each other again with a
funeral notice in the survivor's hand.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ``keeping my options open,'' claiming that the
time was just right to go.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Cleveland thing was coming to a head,
Eddie's indictment seemed less likely than his return to full
operational control, and there was no guarantee that the getting
was going to be any better than it was right now.
</P>
<P>
   He joked with Thrailkill about ``getting a ring'' when the 49ers
win Super Bowl XXXIII. Thrailkill, a business guy who works in
Nashville, Tenn., and has not done press conferences as a regular
part of his job with the DeBartolo Corp., looked like he'd been
asked to swallow a live baby otter.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, someone with a jumbo air brush is going to start
looking through the old scrapbooks for pictures of Eddie and Carmen
together.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he thought his legacy in San Francisco would be,
Policy dived in with both feet. ``I'd like my legacy to be one in
which I was a problem-solver, I handled stress and adversity and
transition in a straightforward, intelligent and appropriate way.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he wants people to think that he consistently
saved the 49ers' considerable chestnuts from potential disaster.
Now who do you think could be included in that back end of that
response?
</P>
<P>
   As always, Policy was subtle, at least enough to make the
uninitiated think for a moment that he was leaving with something
other than a burning pike in his hand and a map to the thatched
roof of the DeBartolo mansion. He took care not to include Denise
York in that group, and was cordial enough to Thrailkill to
convince anyone who wondered that he had no problem with his
interim successor.
</P>
<P>
   But Eddie, he let swing in the breeze. He was no longer on
retainer to ``handle stress, adversity and transition'' for the
family. Let them solve their own problems now.
</P>
<P>
   What he leaves behind is an organization that Thrailkill will
soon wish he wasn't running. Thrailkill seemed surprised that
someone would question the organization's stability, which is very
much at the heart of Policy's departure. After all, Thrailkill said
no fewer than five times that he was only an interim successor.
</P>
<P>
   And immediately names came firing back _ Bill Walsh, Mike
Holmgren, Mike Shanahan. Policy hadn't even settled into his seat
in first class and already people were trying to fill Dwight
Clark's job, and scouting director Vinny Cerrato's, and maybe even
coach Steve Mariucci's as well.
</P>
<P>
   Stability? Are you kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Policy made his mistakes, to be sure. His tin ear as regards the
clumsy and noisome departures of Joe Montana, Ronnie Lott and
George Seifert gnaw at the edges of his resume, and he helped
distribute the panic DeBartolo felt when the Super Bowl was not
won.
</P>
<P>
   But he also gave the organization a tone for the post-Walsh era,
one that carried their run out of the '80s and into an improbable
18 years _ a level below the Yankees and Celtics, but on a par with
the Cleveland Browns of the '40s and '50s and the Canadiens of the
'50s and mid-'60s. And now he is leaving, with a footprint on his
hinder and bruises on his knuckles from the quicksilver jabs he
flicked on his way out. Mostly, he left upright, as you knew he
would.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
