<P>
   VATICAN-BISHOPS (Rome) _ Seeking to curb the independence of
bishops, the pope issued an apostolic letter that tightened Rome's
control over 108 bishops' conferences around the world. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN (Cairo, Egypt) _ In a new setback to President Mohammed
Khatami, a Tehran court convicted the capital's long-serving mayor
on charges of corruption and mismanagement, sentencing him to five
years in prison, and barring him from public office until 2018. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MCCURRY (Washington) _ In a sign of growing confidence
at the White House that it is weathering the Lewinsky
investigation, Michael McCurry, who has used an agile wit and
aggressive tactics to promote the administration while defending it
from scandal, will resign as press secretary this fall, President
Clinton announced. By James Bennet
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ODWALLA-FOOD-SAFETY (Chicago) _ In what federal officials say is
the first criminal conviction in a large-scale food poisoning
outbreak, Odwalla Inc. pleaded guilty to violating food safety laws
and agreed to pay a $1.5 million fine because of a 1996 outbreak of
tainted apple juice that killed a 16-month old child and sickened
70 others. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-MANHUNT (Dateline to kum, N.C.) _ There is a part of this
town that is rooting for accused abortion clinic bomber Eric Robert
Rudolph to elude the camouflaged G-men. Add together an underlayer
of anti-abortion sentiment, an innate distrust of government and
local pride in the ability of a ninth-grade dropout to outwit more
than 200 investigators, and it begins to become apparent why a
local man has sold more than 200 T-shirts bearing the slogan: ``Run
Rudolph Run.'' By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLONER-PROFILE (Undated) _ Man in the News: Dr. Ryuzo
Yanagimachi, the University of Hawaii researcher whose cloning of
adult mice has amazed fellow biologists, describes himself as a man
devoted to one passion _ probing the boundaries of scientific
knowledge. He surrounds himself with acolytes, often doctoral and
postdoctoral students from other countries. ``Many Americans are
interested in easy jobs,'' he explains. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COLLAPSE (New York) _ Thursday, on Day Three of a real-life
disaster story that could be titled ``Chaos in Times Square,''
personal tales of dislocation and disruption took on a more
stressful tone, particularly the plight of 300 people forced out of
their apartment building on 44th Street. Businesses complained that
they were hemorrhaging money. And pressure mounted on the city to
get the area back to normal as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT (Poughkeepsie, N.Y.) _ Tawana Brawley did not
appear in court as scheduled Thursday, and her absence exposed a
deep rift among her advisers in the final days of the defamation
case brought against them by Steven Pagones, the white former
prosecutor they accused of rape. Miss Brawley's absence was a sharp
embarrassment to C. Vernon Mason, the adviser who invited Miss
Brawley to end her silence here, in the damages portion of the case
in which the jurors have already determined that her story was
false.
</P>
