<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POODLE SPRINGS': A MARRIED MARLOWE AND A STRETCHED CHANDLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILL JOYNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To expand on the work of Raymond Chandler, who succeeded in
making literature out of the hard-boiled detective novel,
undoubtedly takes the sort of nerve that Chandler endowed upon his
proud, lonely philosopher-king of a gumshoe, Philip Marlowe.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, Robert B. Parker took such a gamble by finishing
a last Marlowe novel that Chandler, who died in 1959, had laid
aside after only a tentative start.
</P>
<P>
   The result, ``Poodle Springs,'' was a defying-the-odds delight,
a homage to Chandler and his ideas about personal integrity that
artfully avoided parody.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Poodle Springs'' the movie, which will have its
premiere on HBO Saturday night at 9, and it represents just as
great a gamble as that taken by Parker. Not only does this ``Poodle
Springs'' evoke Chandler's distinctive sentences and Parker's deft
approximation of them; it also summons memories of highly regarded
films of Chandler novels like Howard Hawks' ``Big Sleep'' and of
portrayals of Marlowe by actors as versatile as Humphrey Bogart,
Robert Mitchum, Elliott Gould and James Garner.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Marlowe is played by the equally worthy James Caan. The
film was directed by the old pro Bob Rafelson (``Five Easy
Pieces,'' ``The King of Marvin Gardens'') from a screenplay by the
playwright Tom Stoppard. The talent involved can't be questioned,
and the movie, skillfully set against those misleadingly
sun-splashed landscapes of long-ago Southern California, is a lot
of fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it succeeds as a tribute to Chandler as well as Parker's
novel did is highly questionable, though _ largely a matter of how
an individual understands the essence of Chandler, a matter as
complex as a Chandler plot itself.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the novel ``Poodle Springs'' is the shocking
fact that Marlowe has suddenly got himself married, to Linda
Potter, the lovely, wealthy daughter of the California power broker
Harlan Potter, and moved from Los Angeles to a blossoming desert
oasis near the Nevada border. This situation naturally tests
Marlowe's identity: he truly loves his wife, who is a good deal
smarter than her idle, hard-drinking friends, and he wants to try
to live with her in opulent digs, attended by Tino, a houseboy who
turns out to be a kindred independent spirit. But the detective
insists on making his own way financially and sets up shop in tony
downtown Poodle Springs.
</P>
<P>
   A case with typical Chandler ingredients comes his way: Muffy
Blackstone, another young Poodle Springs heiress whose father
wields power, has been abandoned by her husband, who has skipped on
a large gambling debt and turns out to be living a double life,
with a different wife, amid a pornography racket on the seamy side
of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   As Marlowe travels in his weathered Olds back and forth between
his new home and his old Los Angeles milieu, resolution of the case
becomes less important than resolution of his existential
predicament: Now that he has indulged the romantic side of himself,
can he survive as a romantic while still investigating the squalid
realities of humankind?
</P>
<P>
   In creating the movie, Stoppard and Rafelson started with the
basics of the book but jumbled certain aspects of the story line,
changed some names and then upped the ante on the whole enterprise
of standing in for Chandler: they moved the time frame of ``Poodle
Springs'' from the '50s up to 1963, a year loaded with obvious
significance in American cultural mythology.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the time shift enhances Marlowe's emotional
crisis. The age gap between him and his wife (Dina Meyer) is
increased, which gives Caan plenty of creative room to explore the
fleetingness of hope and dignity, even given true love. And in his
dated fedora and simple black suit, he goes about it in a wonderful
way.
</P>
<P>
   He's bloated but able to throw a punch. He's elderly but
believable in the arms of a gorgeous woman. Most important, in his
delivery of one-liners and in a wordless shift of an eye, Caan
knows how to communicate the deep levels of wise, tough sympathy
that have defined Marlowe from ``The Big Sleep'' on.
</P>
<P>
   In another sense, however, the time shift tends to work against
Caan's authentic characterization of Marlowe's internal drama by
injecting into the movie details of historical tension that belong
to a different era of American thriller. The specter of
presidential assassination; conspiracies among big business, big
crime and big politics that are national and global rather than
local; the fact that Marlowe's young wife is a lawyer: all of this
feels standard and beside the point. It doesn't help much that the
supporting cast is a well-chosen one that includes, most notably,
David Keith as the wayward husband, Nia Peeples and Julia Campbell
as his cheated-upon wives and Brian Cox and Joe Don Baker as the
power-broker fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler always set the mystery of Philip Marlowe against the
mystery of American culture, but in his hands, the background never
fought the foreground. Here, despite the work of many talented
people, Marlowe starts to seem oddly _ and wrongly _ insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `POODLE SPRINGS'
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Saturday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Pollack, William Horberg, Jon Avnet and Jordan Kerner,
executive producers; Geoff Stier, co-executive producer; Tony Mark,
producer; screenplay by Tom Stoppard; Bob Rafelson, director;
presented by HBO Pictures in association with Universal Television
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: James Caan (Philip Marlowe), Dina Meyer (Laura), David
Keith (Larry Victor), Brian Cox (Clayton Blackstone), Nia Peeples
(Angel), Julia Campbell (Muffy Blackstone) and Joe Don Baker (P.J.
Parker).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
