<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9654 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-RYAN-COMMENTARY-     07-23 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RYAN-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAR MOVIE THAT DELIVERS A MESSAGE THAT IS PROFOUNDLY ANTI-WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be warned if you haven't seen it already. The new movie ``Saving
Private Ryan'' is not entertainment. When the final credits roll,
audiences will sit in stunned and exhausted silence. Many will have
left the theater by then, forced away by the unrelenting gore from
Steven Spielberg's latest masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the words jotted in my notebook during a recent
screening:
</P>
<P>
   Guts.
</P>
<P>
   Limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Noise.
</P>
<P>
   Intestines.
</P>
<P>
   Cries for mama.
</P>
<P>
   Sulfur on wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cries for morphine.
</P>
<P>
   Chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Critics hail ``Saving Private Ryan'' as the best war movie ever
made, which may or may not be true. What is inarguable is that the
film starring Tom Hanks and Matt Damon is history's most
``realistic'' movie about combat ever made.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening sequence, American GIs are slaughtered
indiscriminately on Omaha Beach during the landing at Normandy. We
have known of that slaughter since high school civics. But, for the
first time, we watch from a few inches away, riding in the same
troop carrier through choppy seas, as bullets penetrate foreheads,
as limbs are torn from torsos, as intestines hang open like thick,
coiled pasta, as blood-reddened sea water washes up over scores of
corpses on the sand.
</P>
<P>
   We watch as life slowly oozes from an American infantryman who
begs for morphine as blood pumps from a stomach wound and comrades
caress his face with bloody hands. We watch as American GIs shoot
German prisoners of war. Our ears echo from the noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens in real life, in real war,'' says Stephen
Ambrose, the pre-eminent World War II historian who was a
consultant for the film. ``The only thing missing from this movie
is the smell of battle.''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Spielberg has
given us two of the most disturbing films of our time. But in
``Schindler's List,'' the evil was more implied. We knew the Jews
were destined for horrible ends, but in most cases we never saw
them die. In ``Private Ryan,'' very little is left to the
imagination. A GI carries his severed arm across the beach. Bodies
are tossed like rag dolls by exploding artillery shells.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happens in war.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I am of a generation, not yet born for World War II and Korea,
too young for Vietnam, for whom war remains an alien concept. The
notion of being called to arms and ordered to kill is surreal. When
it comes to war, we enjoy the luxury of dark curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   We played soldier as boys, imitating the guys on the hit TV
series ``Combat,'' where each week Vic Morrow and his squad
prevailed against the Germans. American deaths in that show were
quick and clean, done for dramatic effect alone. The same was true
in our favorite movies, like ``The Battle of the Bulge'' and ``The
Longest Day.''
</P>
<P>
   War was glamorous to us then, somewhat less so years later when
we listened to Walter Cronkite speak of Vietnam body counts, read
of ambushes, saw older brothers and friends and cousins come home
in body bags, saw other veterans return to something called
post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   But Vietnam, in its ambiguity, was different. Who ever heard of
post traumatic stress among veterans of World War II, where the
objective was so clear? Somehow, the rightness of our cause in
World War II mitigated its horror, made it more like TV shows and
movies where American GIs, if they had to die at all, died quick,
bloodless deaths. The enemy always had it worse in the end. Or so
we were allowed to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Then, only four years ago, a few paragraphs in a newspaper story
began the process of stripping away my naivete. The story told of
American paratroopers during the invasion of Normandy, landing not
on dry ground, but in fields flooded by the Germans precisely for
the purpose. Scores of paratroopers drowned that way, sucked to the
bottom by their own equipment. Comrades listened helplessly to
their screams before going through with their missions. No soldier
died like that on ``Combat.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years to follow, I read the books of historian Stephen
Ambrose and interviewed a couple dozen surviving World War II vets
_ paratroopers, infantrymen, now in their late 60s and 70s _ hoping
eventually to weave their stories into a meaningful work of
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   There was hand-to-hand combat on Normandy, they said, and frozen
American GIs in the Battle of the Bulge, stumbling through
waist-deep snow into the teeth of German defenses, cut down one
after another, lumps of bodies in the snow until the days when
sheer Allied numbers prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   There was the nervous fury of WWII veteran Otis Mackey's
rocking, back and forth in his chair, as if the pace of his rocking
could somehow becalm memories no human should have to bear.
</P>
<P>
   In his first day of combat, Mackey told me one day last year, a
good friend was shot through the neck and killed. Sometime later in
the war, while hiking down a road to Berlin, Mackey's sergeant
tripped a land mine only a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leg with combat boot and all ... I had to duck,'' said
Mackey, a man now in his 70s. ``I seen it coming at me. I just
ducked, and McGhee's leg went flying right by my head. ... I was
right there ready to step on that mine. ... I never could figure
out why it was him and not me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came out, I drank quite a bit,'' Mackey said of
the war. ``I don't know why my wife even stayed with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Through men like Mackey, World War II was transformed in my mind
into a war of awful death and flying body parts. Of buddies shot
through the throat. Of the smell of human entrails laid open by hot
metal. Of weeks on the front without showers or hot food. Of dads
and grandfathers who for decades remained mute about the horror,
who lived in fear of their nightmares and worked 16-hour days to
keep the bad dreams at bay.
</P>
<P>
   So I knew before ``Saving Private Ryan'' that our last good war
was as appalling as the rest. But nothing short of actually having
been there will prepare a person for the unblinking genius of
Steven Spielberg, who lets us see it in person.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   There is no big picture in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' no
intimation of the grand strategy for conquering Hitler, of why such
carnage that unfolds onscreen is necessary. And that's the way it
is in combat. There's little rhyme or reason to it. Not for the
little guy, the grunt soldier. Just an intense focus on immediate
surroundings, on survival. Chaos and gore. Some moviegoers will
turn away in horror. But Spielberg makes it clear that soldiers a
half-century ago never had that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   So rather than entertainment, ``Saving Private Ryan'' is a dark,
no-holds-barred allegory, terrible medicine to inoculate the world
against future outbreaks of war fever. It is an important movie.
But those who attend would do well to brace themselves. Everyone in
the audience pays for a ticket, and then the movie extracts an
emotional price, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't set out to do an anti-war movie. He sets out to do
a war movie, but the effect is a movie that is profoundly
anti-war,'' says Stephen Ambrose. ``I guess it reinforces, in a
way, that when you go to war, man, do it prayerfully. Do it
carefully. Make goddam sure you don't have any alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
