<HEADLINE>
`CANNIBAL: THE MUSICAL': GOLD, GORE AND A SINGING CANNIBAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try to arrive a few minutes late for ``Cannibal: The Musical.''
That way you'll miss the revolting sight of bloody, amputated body
parts, the trademarks of Troma, the filmmakers who gave the world
``The Toxic Avenger'' and ``Surf Nazis Must Die!''
</P>
<P>
   After the gory first scene, the movie is not completely
appalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cannibal! The Musical,'' which was completed in 1994, is
making it into theaters now largely because of Trey Parker and Matt
Stone, the young creators of ``South Park,'' Comedy Central's
animated series about third graders and four-letter words. Parker
wrote, directed and stars in the film. Stone plays a prospector and
is one of the producers. Their work here is still amateurish but
has flashes of real humor.
</P>
<P>
   The film is inspired by the true story of Alferd Packer (
Parker), an 1870s gold prospector, and how he came to be convicted
of cannibalism. In the beginning, Alferd is a happy-go-lucky guy
who loves his horse, Leanne, and just being alive, as you can tell
from the lyrics of his first song: ``The sky is blue and all the
leaves are green. The sun's as warm as a baked potato.'' A few
lines later, he sings, ``My heart's as full as a baked potato.''
</P>
<P>
   The men he travels with from Utah to Colorado are not a
particularly bright or tough bunch. When they meet a group of
trappers, they're horrified to learn that trapping involves killing
little animals. When a man gets unruly, he's sentenced to a
20-minute ``time out.'' When they come across the Grand Canyon, one
says: ``We'll just walk around it. It can't be that big.'' When
they run into a band of ``Indians'' who are clearly Japanese, they
don't notice anything unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, before the cannibalism, they build a snowman,
encounter a Confederate cyclops and pursue a horse thief. Alferd
tells his story to pretty Polly Prye (Toddy Walters), a sympathetic
listener who turns out to be a reporter for The Denver Post. This
all leads up to a huge musical number in which the jubilant
townspeople dance and sing in the streets about the joys of
watching a hanging. (A typical line: ``When his tongue rolls out,
we'll know.'')
</P>
<P>
   It's all pretty stupid, but at times, there are refreshingly
ludicrous notes that even people old enough to see this movie
without a guardian can appreciate. One approach: Imagine the film
taking place in ``South Park'' animation. If Cartman were ripping
that man's arm off and eating it, it might be cute.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``CANNIBAL! THE MUSICAL''
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Trey Parker; directors of photography,
Robert Muratore and Chris Graves; edited by Ian Hardin; music by
Parker and Rich Sanders; production designer, Dave Hedge; produced
by Alexandra Kelly, Hardin, Jason McHugh, Matt Stone and Parker;
released by Troma Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Trey Parker (Alferd Packer), Toddy Walters (Polly Prye),
Jason McHugh (Frank Miller), Matt Stone (Humphrey), Jon Hegel
(Israel Swan) and Dian Bachar (George Noon).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
