A9666 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-     07-23 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T GO JUMP IN A LAKE WITHOUT THINKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many dead grasshoppers add up to one dead cow?
</P>
<P>
   All those grasshoppers floating on North Texas lakes last week
didn't increase the risk of disease, but they did add a whole lot
more organic material for bacteria to eat and multiply, says James
Perdue of the Infectious Disease, Epidemiology and Surveillance
Division at the Texas Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, most of them were just cooling off _ not drowning. But
thousands of them were floating in Eagle Mountain Lake northwest of
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the insects ended up as fish food, I hope. But I called
Perdue, who tracks possible health hazards associated with fresh
water and other environmental elements in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grasshoppers don't carry disease,'' he said. ``But, any
increase in organic content potentially increases bad bacteria in
fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't get in the water if there were a dead cow in the
water, so I guess you could figure out how many dead grasshoppers
make a dead cow,'' Perdue said, only partly in jest.
</P>
<P>
   I say partly because Perdue takes health hazards very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   With the temperature rising, it isn't surprising that so many
people are looking to water to cool off. But as the heat goes up
and water levels go down, the potential for health problems grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at the problems associated with swimming in fresh
water like a pyramid,'' Perdue says. ``At the broad bottom, you
have a lot of microorganisms and bacteria that can cause such mild
problems as ear infections, swimmer's itch or intestinal diseases.
At the top point, you have the very dangerous but relatively rare
problems such as primary amoebic meningoencephalitis.''
</P>
<P>
   This infection, which public health officials dub ``PAM,'' is
caused by a common microorganism found in most untreated surface
water and in all types of soil. It killed five people in Texas in
the summer of 1995, including a child from Euless learning to water
ski in a quiet cove at Possum Kingdom Lake.
</P>
<P>
   During drought and high temperature conditions, concentrations
of the naegleria fowleri amoebas that cause PAM increase as they
feed on the bacteria in the warm water. The organism thrives in a
water temperature above 80 degrees. PAM is most often associated
with water forced up the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you put your head underwater in a stagnant pond or
inlet, think about it,'' Perdue says. ``If the water looks yucky,
don't get in.''
</P>
<P>
   TDH offers these recommendations to avoid infection:
</P>
<P>
   _Never swim in stagnant or polluted water. Take ``No Swimming''
signs seriously.
</P>
<P>
   _Hold your nose or use plugs when jumping into water.
</P>
<P>
   _Avoid swallowing water when swimming.
</P>
<P>
   _Keep wading pools clean and change the water daily.
</P>
<P>
   _Wash cuts and scratches with clean water and soap after
swimming.
</P>
<P>
   _Use earplugs, swim goggles or masks if you tend to get ear or
eye infections.
</P>
<P>
   _Swim in properly maintained pools treated with chlorine, shower
before swimming, and take young children to the restroom
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIFFANY-EXHIBIT-970(2     07-23 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIFFANY-EXHIBIT-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOUIS COMFORT TIFFANY': TIFFANY AS DESIGNER, DECORATOR, PRODUCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibition notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Austere is not the usual modifier when it comes to
Louis Comfort Tiffany. In the last two decades of the 19th century,
the interior decoration company carrying the name of this
painter-turned-designer defined the height of luxury for wealthy,
esthetically adventurous New Yorkers and set standards of
ostentatious propriety in churches across the country.
</P>
<P>
   His name conjures up all kinds of visual extravagances: the
glowing opulence of stained-glass windows and the shimmering
surfaces of vases resplendent with peacock-feather and lily-pad
motifs. His lavish private interiors, few of which still exist,
were legendary for their mixtures of exotic materials and cultural
sources _ Japanese, Chinese, Celtic, Indian and American Indian.
And don't forget Tiffany lamps, whose stained-glass shades are
seemingly heavy with rich colors and overripe patterns of fruit or
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   But the exhibition that the Metropolitan Museum of Art is
devoting to this leader of the Esthetic Movement, which
forward-looking American artists had imported from England by the
1870s, is startlingly spare and understated. The 130 items on view
are all drawn from the museum's sizable Tiffany collection, which
it began to accumulate as early as 1896. The works are mostly small
and are generously spaced, if not isolated, in noticeably plain and
ungussied galleries.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first watercolors in the show suggests that this
low-key setting may differ from the installation Tiffany himself
would have come up with. It is a design for a gallery that was
built at the Art Institute of Chicago to hold a bequest of
19th-century French paintings: apple-green velvet walls, a metallic
stenciled screen and a fireplace faced in bronze and black-glass
mosaic and flanked by six ebony columns.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was organized by Alice Cooney Frelinghuysen,
curator of decorative American arts at the Met, and, in yet another
questionable instance of overtly self-promoting corporate support,
is sponsored by Tiffany &AMP; Company. It gives a fairly full
accounting of the kinds of objects produced by Tiffany's company
(which was first known as Louis Tiffany &AMP; Co. and later as the
Tiffany Glass Co., the Tiffany Glass and Decorating Co. and,
finally, the Tiffany Studios). In addition to the windows, vases
and lamps and a few detailed studies for interiors that hint at the
perfect-pitch eclecticism that Tiffany could muster, there are
examples of boxes in enamel or carved wood, jewelry, furniture,
ceramic vases, candelabra and andirons, favrile and gilt bronze
desk sets and one of the few surviving examples of Tiffany-designed
fabric, a dove-gray silk velvet printed with pale red floral
designs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Met's pared-down presentation, Tiffany's vision is
conveyed in small doses that you can savor in detail and
cross-reference with one another. Here one can consider his
experimental ways with materials, especially glass; his oscillation
between accurate representations and semi-abstractions based on
natural forms, and his uncanny range of beautiful engrossing
details, some of them serendipitously accidental, others reflecting
an almost excruciating level of control.
</P>
<P>
   The first gallery contains an early warning sign of just how
detailed things can get: the sloping arms of a pair of armchairs
are dotted with small diamonds of wood inlay. Look very closely:
the inlay, based on American Indian textile designs, feature nearly
microscopic grid patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany was born in New York City in 1848 into comfortable
circumstances. He was the son of Charles Lewis Tiffany, founder of
Tiffany &AMP; Co., the jewelry company, which was becoming known
throughout the world for its designs in silver. Louis Comfort
Tiffany, given a Frenchified version of his father's name,
originally intended to become a painter; he studied informally with
the painter George Inness, first exhibited his work at the National
Academy of Design at the age of 19 and became a member four years
later. But something pulled him toward design.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been his exposure to the decorative arts as
exemplified by the displays of silver, jewelry, and ceramics in his
father's Union Square showroom, or a trip to Egypt and Northern
Africa with the painter (soon to turn designer) Samuel Colman in
the spring of 1870. It may have been the influence of George Moore,
the brilliant chief designer at his father's company, who had an
extensive library of books about the world's decorative arts _
ancient, Asian, medieval, Islamic _ and an impressive collection of
objects representing those different cultures, many of which
inspired his own designs. Both the library and the collection were
bequeathed to the Metropolitan at Moore's death in 1891.
</P>
<P>
   Moore advised Tiffany to take up interior decoration. In 1879,
the year he formed an interior decoration company with Colman, the
furniture designer Lockwood de Forest and the textile designer
Candace Wheeler, he wrote to Wheeler of his new profession: ``I
believe there is more in it than in painting pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition begins with two rather unimaginative paintings _
``Snake Charmer at Tangier, Africa'' (circa 1872) and ``Marketplace
at Nuremberg'' (circa 1893) _ and bears out this conviction.
Tiffany never stopped making paintings, but he did not exhibit
publicly after the late 1870s. By the early 1880s, he found a new
outlet for his painterly talents, in the medium of glass. By 1892,
he had invented and named the favrile glass process, which involved
blending different colors of semimolten glass.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that Tiffany was a painter in glass, that he expressed
himself most fully and most radically in this material, is several
decades old. But that doesn't make it any less interesting to see
it demonstrated in actual artworks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In stained-glass windows like ``Magnolia and Irises,'' Tiffany
folded and shaped semimolten glass to form expanses of white
blossoms, whose different thicknesses create a dimensional effect,
and whose varying whites suggest veining, shading and natural
light. In ``Autumn Landscape,'' a work of striking if cloying
verisimilitude, the glass was swirled and rippled to create the
effect of rocks and a rushing brook and embedded with tiny flakes
of paper-thin glass to simulate the uneven reds and oranges of
turning leaves.
</P>
<P>
   This last work, a large three-part window from 1923-1924, is not
in the current show but is on permanent display in the Charles
Engelhard Court outside the American Wing, where this exhibition is
located. Also in the court is a large glass mosiac, ``Landscape and
Fountain,'' an installation of the big lily-topped columns and
mosaic-covered lintel that formed the entrance to Laurelton Hall,
Tiffany's home in Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y., along with several
other works. Together they give an idea of Tiffany on a grander
scale.
</P>
<P>
   The appreciation of Tiffany's innovations can be sharpened by
comparing the colors and painterly variations of his stained-glass
windows with the rich but even tones that prevail in the windows
included in the fascinating Edward Burne-Jones exhibition, also at
the Metropolitan. William Morris, who fabricated the windows from
Burne-Jones' designs, researched and resurrected medieval
stained-glass techniques; Tiffany reinvented them.
</P>
<P>
   In the favrile glass vases, Tiffany, or his artisans, learned to
guide contrasting colors of semimolten glass into precise (and
repeating) linear patterns that suggested feathers, leaves and
vines. In his ``Cypriote'' vases, he approximated the shimmering
encrusted surfaces of ancient glass; in one irregularly shaped
work, he contrasted pearlescent passages with rough black areas
that suggest lava. In some works he suspended colored shapes
between layers of translucent glass; in others, the glass is shiny,
opaque and intensely colored, like glazed ceramic.
</P>
<P>
   In the large, round favrile vase from 1903, green and red shapes
loosely suggestive of leaves, vines and berries have been
ingeniously sandwiched between layers of matte translucent glass
that has a goldish tint in certain lights. The effect is hypnotic
and reverie-inducing, of plants floating just beneath the surface
of a pool, softening toward disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   With this vase and with a few others whose skeins of color are
similarly relaxed and even more random, Jackson Pollock's drip
paintings may come to mind. This is not at all surprising. Such
gestural abstraction appeared first in the decorative arts _
usually in ceramics, including Tang vases, early Edo tea bowls and
the humble Redware pots of early 19th-century America. Tiffany's
favrile vases were simply one of the last stopping-off points
before such painterliness entered the realm of painting proper.
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, in step with developments on canvas, Tiffany looked
back across his career and wrote, ``The sovereign importance of
color is only beginning to be realized.'' In words remarkably
reminiscent of Kandinsky's writings, he continued: ``These
light-vibrations have a subjective power and affect the mind and
soul, producing feelings and ideas of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Louis Comfort Tiffany at the Metropolitan Museum of Art
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition remains at the museum, Fifth Avenue at 82nd
Street, through Jan. 31. It is sponsored by Tiffany &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
