<SLUG> BC-SF-HOMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIAN PRICE OF A HOME IN THE BAY AREA HITS NEW RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The median price of an existing, single-family
detached home in the San Francisco Bay area climbed 17.1 percent in
June to $335,740, a record. The national median price is $129,400.
</P>
<P>
   The California Association of Realtors also reported that sales
of homes rose 17.1 percent in June, compared to June 1997. The
report covers seven counties in the San Francisco Bay area, but not
Napa and Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``While sales and price gains are expected to moderate somewhat
as the impact of the Asian economic crisis reaches California
shores, the San Francisco Bay area's real estate market will remain
strong as equity-rich homeowners trade up to bigger homes,'' said
Tim Corliss, the association president, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   These statistics from John McInerney, managing broker of the
95-broker office of TRI/Coldwell Banker Real Estate in San
Francisco, neatly illustrate the real estate phenomenon:
</P>
<P>
   There were 65 San Francisco home sales in the first six months
of the year at prices in excess of $1 million each. And for the
past four months, McInerney said, 50 percent of San Francisco
listings sell above the asking price.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this has to do with our multifaceted economy _
healthy in all sectors,'' McInerney said. ``There is a large influx
of people to satisfy the new jobs and more competition for housing.
... We live in a very wealthy area, so people bid up.''
</P>
<P>
   The June price rise is consistent with the double-digit
year-on-year increases reported monthly for the past two years,
ranging from 12 to 20 percent, said G.U. Krueger, deputy chief
economist for the California Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers may be comforted by the fact the June-to-June increase
was not as sharp as the increase between May 1988 and May 1989,
when it was 36 percent. However, Krueger said, economic conditions
were remarkably similar then and now.
</P>
<P>
   Although 1989 was followed by a recession, economists today
believe the near future may bring only an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The California Association of Realtors also found that the
number of days it took to sell a single-family home in the San
Francisco Bay area had declined to 27 days in June 1998 from 35
days in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The median prices in the area and the year-on-year increases
are:
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County, $267,020, up 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Contra Costa County, $357,200, up 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Marin County, $429,410, up 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Solano County, $157,080, up 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco County, $332,430, up 16.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   San Mateo County, $449,500, up 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara County, $383,870, up 20.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
