   TV-EUBANKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Kevin Eubanks doesn't make many moves without
someone noticing. And this goes way back. When he began recording
for the instrumental-pop-oriented GRP Records in 1983, the jazz
press frowned, whining about an utter compromise of ``musical
integrity.'' Never mind that Eubanks _ a fine guitarist whose 1988
album ``Shadow Prophets'' was ``Radio and Records''' top
contemporary jazz album of the year _ has always found that a
moralistic attitude toward his art results in creative limitations
he refuses to accept. So you can imagine jazz purists dropping dead
as word spread in 1992 that he had signed with Branford Marsalis to
play in the house band for the musically challenged ``Tonight
Show'' with Jay Leno. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL;  &QL; 
