<HEADLINE>
THE RAT PACK: THEY'RE BACK
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.)  (EDS.: Angus MacFadyen is cq.) 
World rights except Great Britain and Australia  Color slide and
black and white photo of Angus MacFadyen, Ray Liotta, Don Cheadle
and Joe Mantegna in HBO's ``The Rat Pack.'' 
 BY IVOR DAVIS  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Even before Frank Sinatra died, his Rat Pack was making a
comeback.
 &HT;    The time was ripe. Youngsters, eons too young to identify with
the jug-earred, thin-as-a-pool-cue, saloon singer of the 1940s, are
swinging to big band music in bars where they serve martinis and
Manhattans, and wear '40s fashions.
 &HT;    Now Martin Scorcese is teaming up with screenwriter Nick Pileggi
to film Nick Toesche's book about the Rat Pack's Dean Martin, with
Tom Hanks as Martin. HBO in August unveils its Rat Pack story with
Ray Liotta as Frank, Don Cheadle as Sammy Davis Jr., Angus
MacFadyen as Peter Lawford and Joe Mantegna as Dino. AMC will
screen the clan's l964 romp, ``Robin and the Seven Hoods,'' on July
29th.
 &HT;    And two recent books, ``Rat Pack Confidential,'' by Shawn Levy,
and ``The Rat Pack - the Hey Hey Days of Frank and the Boys,'' by
Lawrence J. Quirk and William Schoell, went behind the scenes from
Hoboken, N.J., to Las Vegas, from the White House to Hollywood to
lay out the pack's good, bad and the ugly.
 &HT;    Of course Frank's death is sure to give these projects an added
boost. Not that they need it. A few weeks before Sinatra died in
May, the cable channel TV Land scored its highest ever rating with
the benefit concert the pack filmed in St. Louis in 1965 for a
halfway home for ex-cons. Viewers sat mesmerized as Johnny Carson,
substituting for Pack member Joey Bishop, struggled to mimic his
savoir faire.
 &HT;    In all of the stories, Sinatra is the leader. The rest were
along for the party at Frank's command. Only Frank could command
their appearance at a tip of his fedora.
 &HT;    When the original pack, the coterie of pals who hung around
Humphrey Bogart and Lauren Bacall, faded after Bogart's death,
Sinatra, the most junior member of the group, reformed it with his
buddies: Dino, Sammy, Lawford, Bishop and Shirley MacLaine, the
only woman allowed.
 &HT;    So why did the country virtually come to a halt when Frank died?
Why, in spite of what we know about Mafia connections, his boorish
actions to those who he felt slighted him, political toadying to
the Kennedys, and later to his crony Spiro Agnew, do we glory in
his behavior and thrill to his pals' perpetually juvenile banter?
 &HT;    Levy, author of ``The Rat Pack,'' thinks he knows why.
 &HT;    ``This was the last group of pop culture stars who were
grown-ups,'' he explains. ``Dylan wasn't, the Beatles weren't,
Jerry Garcia wasn't a grown-up. Sinatra and pals, whatever else
they were, were grown-ups. They smoked and they drank and they went
with beautiful women. It was the last stage before the teen culture
took over.''
 &HT;    It's no wonder their act, a paen to unapologetic masculinity,
appeals at a time when the ``new man'' seems to constantly be
apologizing for brutishness. To hear the pack today doing their
thing on stage is to go back to an era before political
correctness.
 &HT;    ``I'd like to thank the NAACP for this wonderful trophy,'' said
Martin in St. Louis, picking up Davis, carrying him on stage. They
got away with it because we knew this was the most unprejudiced
group in the country.
 &HT;    Like Sinatra, most were a mass of contradictions, except Dean
who didn't give a damn, and therefore was the coolest. Sammy was a
dynamo of raw talent who cared desperately about the slights he had
to endure because of his race, yet who constantly demeaned himself
as the price of admission.
 &HT;    Lawford was the epitome of the aristocractic English gentleman
and brother-in-law of the president, but underneath a degenerate
who ended up face down in a pool of booze and drugs.
 &HT;    But the greatest contradiction was Frank himself -- who wouldn't
swear in the company of a woman and was always first to light her
cigarette, but who could vilify a female journalist with language a
gutter fighter would have hesitated to use. He was generous to a
fault, giving millions of dollars a year to worthy causes and
individuals, yet could be as mean and vindictive as hoods whose
company he apparently enjoyed. He was progressive politically, a
champion of the working man who had been in the forefront on civil
rights and ended up buddies with Agnew.
 &HT;    ``He was a lonely man,'' says Levy. ``Those lonely ballads have
something very sincere about them. He was an only child, which
considering he was an Italian-American of World War I vintage, was
very unusual. He hated to be alone. He had the big band entourage
around him in the '40s. He lost everything in the '50s and then
when he got back on top he needed a bunch of guys to hang out
with.''
 &HT;    These guys made it look as if they were hosts of the greatest
party anywhere.
 &HT;    ``They were the Woodstock of the cocktail era with great women,
stars, the glamour, the danger of Vegas, the cavorting into the wee
hours, the ribbing of friends,'' says Levy.
 &HT;    But underneath was something more dangerous, less cool.
 &HT;    ``Like every golden age,'' says Levy, ``It's only golden in
retrospect. I've tried to remind people what was happening under
the veneer... the mob connections, and the fact that together the
work they produced was mediocre - films like `Oceans Eleven,'
`Sergeants 3' and `Robin and the Seven Hoods.' And the live
recordings that trickled out from them are not their best work.''
 &HT;    But then Sinatra could go off by himself and produce genius.
 &HT;    ``I continue to be amazed by the vastness of his ability to hold
contradictory impulses and ideas, '' says Levy, ``to
compartmentalize his personal life and his public cavorting. His
politics are over here... his music over there. The morning after
some outrageous event ... he goes into a recording studio for some
of the most beautiful ballad singing ever. I don't understand the
greatness of spirit that takes ... He could walk into the studio
and turn off everything except the music.''
 &HT;    The Pack may have been a passing phenomenon, not so Sinatra,
says Levy.
 &HT;    ``This is one of the great lives of the twentieth century. He
produced inaugural galas for both Kennedy and then decades later
for Reagan. He was recording well into his seventies and not
revivals - new material.''
 &HT;    And the bad Sinatra, who beat up people, acted like a dictator,
who introduced mobster Sam Giancana to John F. Kennedy Jr., how
does that even the legend?
 &HT;    Not at all says Levy. ``Listen, Picasso was a creep with women.
It doesn't matter if James Joyce and Beethoven were wretches. It
makes their art more impressive that they can lock out the
personal.''
 c. 1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) 
