<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: DVD RACE; `AVENGERS' REDUX; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How Big a Race For the DVD?
</P>
<P>
   Purveyors of digital video disks and players report steady sales
growth this summer. What's needed now, they say, is a burst of
acceleration to establish the format. Distributors describe
themselves as being in a race. Will enough people be firmly in the
habit of buying and renting the disks before rival technologies
arrive with their own ways of ordering movies?
</P>
<P>
   At present, 450,000 to 500,000 DVD players are said to have been
bought by consumers. Some DVD industry advocates hold that 10
million players need to be sold in the next three to five years if
the disks are to have the momentum necessary to keep people going
to stores for a new breed of packaged goods when they might stay at
home and resort to a less time-consuming form of delivery _ digital
satellite, for example, or digital cable or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But others in the business don't see the deadline as being quite
that defined or dire. Michael Fidler, who manages DVD marketing for
Sony, said that other applications of the disk _ for example, its
nonmovie uses with personal computers or its portability as a CD _
insured its staying power beyond movies.
</P>
<P>
   That might allow more breathing room to establish DVD as a movie
format, not that distributors are wasting any time. ``We're seeing
an extension of infrastructure,'' Fidler said. That's marketing
executive talk for price reductions of disks (to as low as $15 in
some cases) and players (to the $400 level for some machines) and
an increase in the number of stores carrying DVD.
</P>
<P>
   `Avengers' Revisited
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, ``The Avengers'' became the first British television
show to be shown coast to coast by an American network (ABC). By
then the stars, Patrick Macnee and Diana Rigg, had barnstormed the
country to introduce themselves. Ms. Rigg, who was to become
virtually immortal as Emma Peel, the gorgeous, self-reliant
colleague of secret agent John Steed (Macnee), raised eyebrows in a
miniskirt that was daringly brief for the era. ``It was looked on
with horror,'' said Macnee, 76.
</P>
<P>
   But people were curious about the show, which was a hit in
England. ``I told them it was about a man in a bowler hat with an
umbrella and a woman who throws men over her shoulder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, A&AMP;E will release two boxed sets of the series, with two
episodes on each of six cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rigg, who turned 60 this week, joined the show two seasons
before it came to the United States and left it in 1967. With its
mix of elegance, witty sang-froid, sedate violence, mildly kinky
sexual references and inalterably British manner, ``The Avengers''
became hugely popular here as the original tongue-in-cheek spy
show.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Americans had to tinker. ``After the first season, a
young man with sweaty palms and a nasty attitude was sent from the
United States to, as he put it, `slightly adapt the show for
American tastes,''' Macnee said.
</P>
<P>
   That meant purging or toning down sexual content, which on
occasion included some good-natured ``perversity,'' as Macnee
called it. ``Someone dressed up in rubber or leather,'' he said.
``Tie them to the bedpost. We showed you could have some fun doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Live Flesh
</P>
<P>
   After an impromptu sexual encounter with the wild druggy Elena
(Francesca Neri), Victor (Liberto Rabal) finds her less than
pleased to see him again. Their row attracts two policemen, and one
of them, David (Javier Bardem), is shot and paralyzed. Unjustly
blamed, Victor is sent to prison where one day on television he
sees David playing basketball for the Spanish national wheelchair
team, Rooting him on is Elena, who has become David's demure wife
and the operator of a child-care center. When his time is served,
Victor is gripped by his old lust and a desire for revenge. Only in
a Pedro Almodovar movie could such a situation come to a good end,
sort of, in, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, a ``stylish,
sexy film noir.''
</P>
<P>
   1997. Orion. $100.96. 110 minutes. Spanish with English
subtitles. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nil by Mouth
</P>
<P>
   Gary Oldman's fierce first feature film tells of working-class
South London women trying to live under the fist of the drunken
Raymond (Ray Winstone). For Ray's wife, Valerie (Kathy Burke), life
is a grim accommodation with a reality she chooses not to escape.
Nevertheless, left with no choice but to deal with the abuse as
best she can, she emerges with her spirit intact, a feat made all
the more powerful by ``the pragmatism within the depths of Ms.
Burke's extraordinary performance'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. . 128 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Marshals
</P>
<P>
   Twitching jaw muscles and hard brown eyes signal a Tommy Lee
Jones so much on the brink of explosion that not even
cartoon-balloon dialogue can dilute the intensity. Stuart Baird
resurrects the old pursuit-of-the-fugitive routine, with a plane
crash replacing the famous train wreck of the earlier adventure.
That's all right, but Wesley Snipes, empty of expression, makes a
lame substitute for the volatile Harrison Ford character. Yet what
this film does have that ``its forerunner possessed in equal
measure is an unceasingly infectious beat'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $107.37. Laser disk, $39.98. 95 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Hard Rain
</P>
<P>
   It's a dark and stormy night in Huntingburg, Ind., as a security
guard (Christian Slater) tries to salvage $3 million from an
armored car that is the target of a gang of thieves led by Jim
(Morgan Freeman). Jim sure would like that money to retire on, but
in his way are a dam that is about to burst, a disgruntled sheriff
(Randy Quaid), and other stumbling blocks in a film for which
``deep waters and shallow characters tell the story'' (Lawrence Van
Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Paramount. $102.56. Laser disk, $34.95. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   LOU REED: ROCK-AND-ROLL HEART. Timothy Greenfield-Sanders'
documentary catches the artist at various points in his highly
influential 30-year career, a story that begins with his days as a
student of Delmore Schwartz at Syracuse University and moves on to
the formation of the Velvet Underground and his successes as a solo
performer. Much attention is paid to the glam rock period, when
Reed was in his androgynous phase, the world of drugs and Andy
Warhol's star machine. David Bowie, David Byrne, Patti Smith,
Philip Glass and even Vaclav Havel contribute commentary. 1998. Fox
Lorber. $19.98. 75 minutes. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   PRETTY VILLAGE, PRETTY FLAME. A tunnel from the days of Tito's
Yugoslavia becomes a symbol of unification as well as a hiding
place for a detachment of Serbian troops under attack by Muslims in
the 1990s. Flashing back and forth between factions and time
periods, Srdjan Dragojevic's film pounds relentlessly at the
insanity of war. 1997. Fox Lorber. $89.98. 128 minutes.
Serbo-Croatian with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   FULL OF LIFE. Judy Holliday stars as a young woman of no
particular religious persuasion who marries into a hidebound
Italian-Catholic family. Thing is, she's eight months pregnant, but
according to the view from the groom's camp that doesn't make a
church wedding any less necessary. 1956. Columbia Tri-Star $19.95.
91 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
