<HEADLINE>
NIGHTMARE AHEAD: TRAFFIC CONGESTION IN BAY AREA TO GROW 250 PERCENT
BY 2020 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yes, it can get worse. And it will. Traffic
congestion in the San Francisco Bay area is expected to increase
nearly 250 percent by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   In two decades, commuters can expect 366,000 hours of collective
daily delays, compared with the 105,000 hours they waited on any
given day in 1990, according to a Metropolitan Transportation
Commission report forecasting the future of regional freeways in
the nine-county Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it points out is that even as we make the improvements
that are planned _ which are significant _ the congestion problem
won't be solved, so we have to look at alternatives,'' said
Michelle Morris Brubaker, an commission planner who helped
calculate the predictions.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the computer-generated data also indicated
that in the future fewer people will be willing to spend more time
idling in bumper-to-bumper conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a threshold of just how much congestion they are
willing to take before they inevitably move closer to work or do
something to avoid it altogether,'' Brubaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland resident Nouri Akli, who works for Pacific Bell in San
Francisco, sees himself as a prime candidate for that kind of
change if the traffic gets as bad as anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, then I will probably start looking to
transfer to the East Bay so I don't have to commute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it takes 45 minutes to get to work, when it only
takes 15 minutes without congestion,'' he said. ``If it increases
even more, that will definitely cross my threshold.''
</P>
<P>
   The 88-page draft report details how the commission's $88
billion projected budget will be divided among the region's 7,000
miles of transit, 1,700 miles of highways and 18,000 miles of
streets and roads.
</P>
<P>
   It emphasizes using the majority of future state and federal
funding to maintain the systems in place, and the rest to improve
public transportation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
