<SLUG> BC-DECALOGUE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DECALOGUE': MODERN MORALITY TALES FROM A MASTER POLISH
FILMMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: ``The Decalogue'' was first shown at New York's Walter Reade
Theater in 1996. The following review appeared in The New York
Times on March 8, 1996.) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would be a mistake to think of ``The Decalogue,''
Krzysztof Kieslowski's dramatic series of made-for-television films
inspired by the Ten Commandments, as cinematic interpretations of
biblical teaching. These 10 hour-long movies are elliptical stories
that draw no easy moral conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Like the great Polish director's full-length features, they are
obsessed with the elements of chance and fate in modern life. Of
``The Decalogue,'' the director himself has said, ``I simply wanted
to show that life is complicated ... nothing more,'' adding that
the series' only message is to ``live carefully, with your eyes
open, and try not to cause pain.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet there are stronger moral reverberations in many of these
10 movies than in Kieslowski's other recent work. The first film is
the tragic tale of a brilliant, computer-wise 11-year-old. The boy
drowns when he ventures out onto ice that his father's computer
calculations have shown to be thick enough to hold him. The story
goes out of its way to make a point that the father, a lecturer on
linguistics, is not religious. The movie could be read as a
cautionary fable about a world that places too much faith in
technology while losing touch with a deeper, more intuitive
spiritual connection with nature.
</P>
<P>
   In the second story, a pregnant concert violinist, whose husband
is near death from an unidentified illness, is revealed to be
carrying the child of her lover. Depending upon a doctor's
prognosis, she must decide whether to have an abortion. Again, the
story finds people asking for clear-cut scientific answers to
problems that can't be neatly quantified.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 stories are set in a Warsaw housing development that is
as drab as it is expansive. Each film is a self-contained story
with a different cast. Besides the setting, the only common element
is the appearance of a stranger at the climax of each story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Decalogue'' shows Kieslowski to be a modern filmmaker of a
stature comparable to Ingmar Bergman. If Kieslowski's films are as
serious as Bergman's, their lack of psychologizing lends them a
deceptive weightlessness. The characters often find themselves
existing in a moral void that for all its creature comforts doesn't
feel right. These uneasy people are tempted, despite themselves, to
decipher answers from the seemingly random events that determine
their lives. And maybe, the director implies, they are right to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 films, each lasting from 53 to 57 minutes, will play at
the Walter Reade Theater, at Lincoln Center, 165 West 65th St.,
Friday through Thursday. Schedule information: (212) 875-5600.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
