<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES: SELLING ICONS OF MODERN ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While much of the art world slows down in the summer, for
auction house experts it's one of the busiest times of the year.
July and August are when they travel the world, trying to get
property to sell for the big auctions in November. And when a house
obtains an important collection to sell, it is generally announced
as soon as possible to encourage other sellers to follow.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Sotheby's got the goods. It will be selling seven
works with an estimated value of $13.5 million that belong to the
Boston collectors Mildred and Herbert Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lee had an eye and taste ahead of her time. In the early
1960s, she began buying contemporary and modern art, collecting
iconic images of the period by artists like Warhol, Robert
Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns.
</P>
<P>
   One of those images is Johns' ``White Numbers,'' from 1958. It
is among the rarest of works in the collection that Sotheby's will
sell this fall. The artist executed three ``White Numbers.'' One
belonged to the New York collectors Victor and Sally Ganz, and was
sold at Christie's last year for $7.9 million. The other is in the
Ludwig Museum in Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lee bought her ``White Numbers'' in 1962 and since then, it
has been off the market. Sotheby's experts estimate it will sell
for between $7 million and $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also for sale will be Picasso's ``Head of a Woman,'' a portrait
of Francoise Gilot, one of the artist's companions, which he
painted in 1952. It is a prime example of Picasso's deconstructed
heads in vibrant colors, and is bordered by thick black bands that
create an effect of stained glass. It carries an estimate of $2
million to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both these works are about surface and texture,'' said Tobias
Meyer, head of Sotheby's department of contemporary art worldwide.
``They're very sensual.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer described the collection as quintessentially American and
very personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Lee was one of the earliest Johns collectors,'' he added.
``In fact, all these works have great provenances.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. Lee are not the only family members who collect
important contemporary art. Their son Thomas H. Lee, a
leveraged-buyout specialist, has been a big spender at auctions for
years. He is also a trustee of the Whitney Museum of American Art
and last year, when he gave the museum a lot of money, he asked
that its two-floor galleries be named after his parents.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why they decided to sell part of their collection,
Mr. Lee, 83, and Mrs. Lee, 78, would say only that it was a family
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Everyday and Someday
</P>
<P>
   There's lots of biennale news this week, from Australia as well
as Italy. First, about the Sydney Biennale, which is scheduled to
run from Sept. 18 through Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 25th year, this international exhibition of
contemporary art will include 103 artists from 28 countries. The
theme, ``Every Day,'' was chosen to reflect the fact that artists
are increasingly looking closer to home for inspiration, said
Jonathan Watkins, artistic director for the Biennale. He was in New
York this week to announce his plans.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said this year's biennale was by far the most expansive.
Rather than being held at its regular sites, the Art Gallery of New
South Wales and the Museum of Contemporary Art, it will be in about
10 different venues around Sydney. There will also be site-specific
installations at the Sydney Opera House, the Royal Botanic Gardens
and the grounds of the government House.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Venice Biennale, officials there say they still do
not know whether the next Biennale will be presented as scheduled
in 1999, or in 2000. But the Biennale's administration has named a
director for the visual arts Biennale _ Harold Szeemann, a
65-year-old curator and art historian who was the director of
``Documenta 5'' in Kassel, Germany, in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Szeemann was also a co-organizer of the Venice Biennale in 1980,
and an originator of the Aperto exhibitions, which show younger
artists at the Venice Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, Szeemann has lived in Switzerland and been an
independent curator. He is replacing Germano Celant, an Italian
critic and part-time curator at the Guggenheim Museum, who ran the
visual-arts Venice Biennale in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On the Move to Chelsea
</P>
<P>
   Two well-known Soho galleries, Jay Gorney Modern Art and Bravin
Post Lee, are joining forces and heading to Manhattan's Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Gorney has just closed his space on Greene Street; Bravin
Post Lee closed its Mercer Street gallery last year. The two
companies will become Gorney Bravin &AMP; Lee, combining the last names
of its principals, Gorney, Karin Bravin and John Post Lee. While
they are currently working in temporary quarters on Broome Street,
they said they were close to finding a Chelsea location.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we talked about sharing a space but then it seemed
like there was more energy and power in joining forces,'' Gorney
said. ``I bring a stable of well-known artists like Gillian
Wearing, Lari Pittman, Jessica Stockholder and Alexis Rockman, and
they bring artists like Fabian Marcaccio and Emil Lukas.''
</P>
<P>
   Both galleries sold their Soho leases. Now the owners say they
feel committed to Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see everyone moving to Chelsea,'' Gorney said. ``Part of my
soul rebels, but Chelsea just seems to make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Renovation in London
</P>
<P>
   Although the Victoria and Albert Museum in London is one of the
last of the big museums to receive significant lottery money, the
$25 million the decorative arts museum was awarded this week from
the Heritage Lottery Fund will mean it can completely rethink and
renovate its famed British galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries, which take up about 10 percent of the museum's
exhibition space, span British design from 1500 through 1900 and
include its much-loved period rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The project will cost a total of $51.7 million, and the museum
is busy getting corporate and private financing to pay for the
rest. So far it has raised about $5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
