<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE IT A REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Are we ready for this?
</P>
<P>
   Now that the outgoing head of the Justice Department's probe
into campaign finance abuses has recommended that yet another
independent counsel be authorized to pursue the extent of White
House involvement, Attorney General Janet Reno is once again on the
hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   She has resisted Republican demands for an outside probe of 1996
Democratic campaign fund-raising tactics since the scandal broke
nearly two years ago, insisting that her department can handle the
issue satisfactorily. She stubbornly reiterated that position again
earlier this month in testimony before a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   The political pressure on her to capitulate escalated
dramatically when the department's own campaign finance prosecutor,
Charles LaBella, joined FBI Director Louis Freeh in urging that
Justice back off and turn the issue over to a court-appointed
investigator. Both believe that the department has an appearance of
conflict of interest, since the purpose of most of the alleged
illegal contributions was to re-elect Reno's boss.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who is no Clinton crony, resents the assumption that she
cannot be trusted to enforce the law. She has, after all, already
authorized no less than seven independent counsels to probe charges
against the president, Cabinet officers and other high-ranking
officials. And she gave Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr approval
to look beyond Whitewater into the Monica Lewinsky mess.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she would review LaBella's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   But does America really need another uncontrolled, ambitious
Starr clone with unlimited funds, time and subpoena power but no
sense of judicial proportion? Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   What's so magical about a special counsel anyway? Let's stop
being academic about ethical purity and get real here.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has made a joke of the original notion that an independent
counsel would automatically pursue allegations of wrongdoing in
high places in a nonpartisan, judicious manner. His vindictive
behavior (the endless prosecution of Susan McDougal, for instance)
and cozy relations with anti-Clinton conservatives long ago
stripped away any pretense of impartiality and fair-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   And just what horror is this new deus ex machina supposed to
investigate at taxpayer expense?
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department inquiry has so far produced indictments
of 11 fund-raisers or donors who were not affiliated directly with
the White House and whose names are not household words. The
Democratic National Committee returned roughly $3 million in
contributions of dubious legality. But the scandal has not brought
down any important White House official.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate committee investigated Democratic campaign fund-raising
practices but disbanded without proving its most damning charges
that foreign contributors actually influenced the election. A
similar House committee collapsed under partisan wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-controlled Congress has kept the focus on Democratic
fund-raising, but there is plenty of evidence that the Republicans
were not pure in their fund-raising methods either. The hypocrisy
level of this scandal is in the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   And if Congress is outraged over excesses in campaign
fund-raising, it is a big fat secret. Reform of the system is
stalled in both houses. Voters don't much care, either, telling
pollsters campaign finance reform doesn't have a high priority with
them.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the big deal about naming a special counsel? The goal
seems more to be about harassing President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore going into a new presidential election season
than about seeking the truth behind the bipartisan selling of our
political soul.
</P>
<P>
   The basic unanswered issue is whether Clinton, Gore and their
top advisers conspired to take illegal contributions or were
unaware of their improper origins, as they insist. And Republicans
would like to hassle Clinton and Gore some more about fund-raising
coffees, Buddhist monks and phone calls from the White House that
may have violated the spirit of the law if not its substance.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena power of another special counsel to rummage in
White House documents and interrogate White House officials to
examine campaign finances tops the Republican wish list. Having
watched the wreckage of Starr's rampage, Reno would be a fool to
grant it.
</P>
<P>
   From what we know thus far, the targeted wrongs here are mostly
small potatoes. The real scandal is the bipartisan pattern of
raising campaign money by promising not only access to leaders but
political favors, which neither party has the will to change. In
particular, this practice would be horrific if a foreign country,
say China, benefited at the expense of our national security.
</P>
<P>
   But public figures know how to manipulate what they are doing
and saying so that bribery is virtually impossible to prove. There
are so many entangling relationships among donors, politicians,
lobbyists and workerbees that it is difficult to separate
legitimate contributions from prosecutable paybacks.
</P>
<P>
   There may yet be something serious that can be uncovered in the
1996 Democratic fund-raising scramble, which looks reckless in the
extreme. But the Justice Department is qualified to pursue whatever
trails there may be, and Reno is right to be outraged at
suggestions that she cannot be trusted to do her job honorably.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson, not
exactly an unbiased observer, demanded that she bow to the
lower-ranking LaBella, contending she owes her loyalty to ``the
rule of law, not the men who appointed her.'' What an insult to a
woman of great integrity.
</P>
<P>
   As for the special counsel law, it expires next year and should
not be renewed in anything remotely resembling its present
unaccountable form, if at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
