<SLUG> BC-KELLY-AFB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS FIGHT TO KEEP MILITARY WORK IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force has ordered Kelly Air Force Base to
start preparing to shift hundreds of jobs to a maintenance depot in
Utah, with some jobs moving in two months.
</P>
<P>
   A June 30 memo from the Air Force Materiel Command, which
oversees Kelly, orders base officials to ``please begin the early
move'' of the base's gas turbine engine workload to Hill Air Force
Base in Ogden, Utah, ``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly spokesman Glen Whiton said none of the 600 or so
engine-maintenance jobs at the base had been transferred.
</P>
<P>
   But some will move to Utah in September, Hill spokesman Bruce
Collins said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the Air Force's decision came as a blow to San Antonio
Mayor Howard Peak and others who have tried to keep the work in
Texas when Kelly closes in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always disappointed, but unfortunately over time I have
ceased to be at least completely surprised'' by news about jobs
leaving Kelly, Peak said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win some, you lose some in these situations,'' said Rep.
Ciro Rodriguez, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Kelly's gas turbine engine work has been in
question for months as Rodriguez and others in Washington have
fought Air Force plans to move the work to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are several hundred jobs now at Kelly that are pegged
for transfer to Hill at the start of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has said that 290 maintenance jobs and 97
white-collar jobs likely will go to Utah. Collins said the number
of workers could rise as high as 600, with most of the workload
transfer to be complete as Kelly closes in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs have an average annual salary of $37,690, Whiton said.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan coalition of lawmakers led by Rodriguez and Sens.
Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison, both Texas Republicans, has
sought to move the Kelly jobs to the Corpus Christi Army Depot.
</P>
<P>
   That would allow Kelly workers to follow the jobs and also save
taxpayer money, since Hill must spend about $4.6 million on new
construction to handle the engine workload, coalition members have
said.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of Texas lawmakers has urged Deputy Defense
Secretary John Hamre to postpone a final decision on the transfer
until a Pentagon agency studies the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency, the Defense Depot Management Council, approved
an Air Force request to transfer the workload to Utah during a Jan.
14 Pentagon meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rodriguez said ``there's some degree of hope'' the work
would remain in Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
