<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR JULY
23, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALASKA -- ANWR. Sen. Frank Murkowksi sought answers from
administration and state officials on the use of new technology in
the refuge toward finding oil at a Senate hearing today. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- RIGGS. (probable) The House is expected to
consider an amendment by Frank Riggs, R-Napa, that would cut
federal housing funds for San Francisco that are used to implement
the city ordinance requiring groups doing business with the city to
provide domestic-partner benefits to their employees. The amendment
is the first of what is expected to be a series of anti-gay rights
provisions that will be attached to appropriations bills. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- INCUMBENTS. Colorado's incumbent Congressmen have
more than 40 times the campaign coffers as their challengers, and
have out-fundraised their opponents by a five-to-one margin,
according to reports filed with the Federal Elections Commission.
Zaret
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- Y2K. The medical community needs the government
to establish a national clearinghouse to provide information about
which hospital instruments will function properly in the next
millenium, medical experts told a Senate panel today. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- FEC. With no opponents to their re-election bids this
fall, U.S. Reps. Dan Miller and Porter Goss toned down their
campaigns during the second quarter of this year. Williams
</P>
