<SLUG> BC-COX-ABORTION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP HOUSE MEMBERS BID TO VETO CLINTON BAN ON CERTAIN ABORTIONS
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Using words like ``execution'' and ``infanticide,''
Republicans led the House of Representatives in a bid to override
President Clinton's veto of a ban on certain late-term abortions
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the vote eight months after Clinton's veto and
less than four months before congressional elections drew cries of
protest from the mainly Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-seven Democrats joined 219 Republicans to provide more
than the two-thirds vote needed to overcome a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the procedure known as partial-birth abortions
supplied graphic descriptions and florid language to drive home
their point. ``We're talking about killing, killing healthy
babies,'' said Rep. Sue Myrick, R-N.C. ``It's closer to infanticide
than to abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris Smith, R-N.J., a leader of anti-abortion forces in
the House, likened the procedure to an ``execution.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill Clinton vetoed in October would bar doctors from using
a procedure in which a fetus is partially delivered vaginally, feet
first, and then an incision is made in a barely visible skull and
its contents drained. It would allow exceptions only when the
mother's life is in jeopardy .
</P>
<P>
   The anti-climactic vote in the House _ which already had
provided veto-proof support of the abortion ban _ sets the stage
for the Senate's consideration of Clinton's veto, probably sometime
in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 64-36 last year to ban partial-birth abortions,
three votes shy of a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that we face an uphill battle in the Senate,'' said
Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., chief sponsor of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's allies in the House said the ban is unconstitutional
and chided GOP leaders for trying to make it an election-year
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political issue for the 1998 election,'' said Rep.
Diana DeGette, D-Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich and other members of Congress gathered
with Christian and Jewish clergy just before the vote to prod the
Senate to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happening now is an answer to prayer,'' said
Rabbi Joseph Ehrenkranz of Fairfield, Conn., one of three rabbis to
appear with Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has twice vetoed bills to outlaw the abortion
procedure, has said he would sign a partial-birth ban into law if
it provided ``a limited exception for the small number of
compelling health cases where use of this procedure is necessary to
avoid serious health consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   But Canady said Clinton has demonstrated his unwillingness to
sign a bill with meaningful ``restrictions on partial-birth
abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans already this year have held a number of votes
intended to please their conservative base and Thursday's appeared
to be no different. Officials of the Christian Coalition also
attended the Gingrich news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The House also recently passed a bill to prohibit people from
taking minors across state lines to evade some states' parental
notification laws on abortions. That legislation, however, did not
pass with a large enough majority to overcome a veto.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
