<HEADER>
A9831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAUST-THEATER-REVIEW-     07-23 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAUST-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOETHE'S PASSWORD? A CLASSIC TALE RETOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (Eds: The word (AT) throughout story should be replaced by the
symbol)  
 (af)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember how smitten you were, how bowled over and
enchanted, by your first foreign film? The experience was in every
sense an eye-opener: the exotic words from the lips of heavy-lidded
actors, the voluptuous camera work, the smoky, seemingly
unrestrained carnality.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sitting through ``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0,'' the live,
multi-media piece by the Spanish theater company La Fura dels Baus,
is the opposite of that. A compression of the epic verse play that
took Goethe a lifetime to compose, ``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0'' is a
disenchantment that manages to close the mind in an economical 100
minutes. It's as muddled and gratuitously profane as a particularly
juvenile effort by a group of first-year film students.
</P>
<P>
   The production at the New York State Theater, part of Lincoln
Center Festival `98, will no doubt have its partisans, although the
performance I saw seemed to leave the audience sort of woozy and
baffled.
</P>
<P>
   La Fura, a troupe founded in Barcelona in 1979, specializes in
visual spectacle, and if it's music-video style razmatazz you're
after, you may find what you're looking for here. The company sets
off fireworks with the precision of the Gruccis.
</P>
<P>
   The vast State Theater stage looks as if it has been redecorated
by Mummenschanz going through a heavy-metal phase. Two towering
steel sculptures _ one of whirling cylinders, the other, a giant
fan blowing through billowing tubes _ stand guard at stage right
and left. (At one point in the show, the fan is turned on, a la one
of those curtain songs in old Broadway musicals, apparently to
distract the audience from some onstage personnel-shifting.)
Modular screens fold and unfold, actors dangle upside down from
rotating platforms, a video of a raging inferno metamorphoses into
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   What does any of this have to do with Goethe? Good question. La
Fura seems to be trying to translate the nearly two-century-old
German work into some universal language of the late 1990s, cobbled
together from television and video-game images and computerese.
</P>
<P>
   But all the troupe really accomplishes is transforming a
masterpiece into techno-gibberish. Consider La Fura's own
justification, contained in its press materials:
</P>
<P>
   ``The saturation of information in the computer web, often read
from an optimism which is heir to the optimism of progress, does
not improve, nor transform the human condition, created without
purpose by evolution's laws of chance: tied to the imperious
demands of primary instincts against which the retaining walls of
social rules are erected.''
</P>
<P>
   You want me to run that by you again? It often appears to be the
case in the theater these days that the more a company has to
explain, however ineptly, what it is trying to do, the less
successful it is in actually doing it.
</P>
<P>
   (According to the handout, even those whirling cylinders and
billowing tubes have hidden meaning, as symbols intended to
correspond to themes in the music. Uh huh.)
</P>
<P>
   ``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0'' _ the title, of course, is a software
term _ transports the legend of Faust to the World Wide Web. In
this adaptation, performed in Spanish with a mediocre simultaneous
English translation, Faust (Santi Pons) is fed up with the
knowledge he has gained through computers and, with some nifty
horror-movie special effects, hangs himself from a sparking
electrical cord.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your existential crises: after he's dead, Faust meets
Mephistopheles, played with authority by Miquel Gelabert as a kind
of thuggish, supernatural Goodfella, who in their famous pact
whisks Faust away from the world of knowledge with an offer to
expose him to the pleasures of the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue is filled with pseudo-intellectual aphorisms (like,
``Art is long; your life is short'') that put you in mind of a
half-baked extension-school philosophy course _ ``Existence: Good
or Bad?'' And the humor is of the lamest sort: late in the
proceedings a game-show parody, of all tired things, is staged.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, much of ``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0'' is neither
computer-driven nor pensive in that cerebral way we think of as
``European.'' It's just kind of smutty.
</P>
<P>
   The obscene acts _ a drag queen masturbating as Faust watches, a
man anally raping his sister _ are presented for their shock value.
There's a sense of adolescent rebellion about these moments, as in,
``How much can we get away with?''
</P>
<P>
   The members of the troupe have been quoted as saying that
``F(AT)ust, Version 3.0'' is their first production with a written
text. It shows. As with so much of what is presented in the
contemporary theater, this ``Faust'' is a vanquishing of the script
by the blueprint. ``Razzle-dazzle 'em, and they'll make you a
star,'' goes the line in ``Chicago.'' Well, not always. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F(AT)UST, VERSION 3.0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on ``Faust'' Parts 1 and 2 by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe.
Directed by Alex Olle and Carlos Padrissa; conceived by Pablo Ley,
Alle, Padrissa and Magda Puyo; stage direction by Ms. Puyo; texts
by Ley; special collaboration and costumes by Jaume Plensa; film
direction, Franc Aleu and Emmanuel Carlier; sets by Roland Olbeter;
lighting by Albert Faura; sound by Marc Sarda; music by Big Toxic
and Alex Martin. La Fura dels Baus. Presented by Lincoln Center
Festival '98. At the New York State Theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Younes Bachir-Lafritz (Student and witch), Carles Figols
(Wagner), Jorge Flores ``Dr. Flo'' (Deejay), Miquel Gelabert
(Mephistopheles), Anable Moreno (Marthe), Santi Pons (Faust), Jordi
``Kai'' Puig (Valentin) and Sara Rosa (Margarethe).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
