<HEADER>
A9845 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CRAM-NAT     07-23 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CRAM-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SENATE TAKES ON PHONE CRAMMING
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Megan Feldman  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 23-- A Maine resident recently found a
mysterious $10.25 charge on his local telephone bill for a credit
card he does not have.
</P>
<P>
   An Indiana woman was charged on her phone bill for a psychic
club membership she never agreed to. And a New Yorker was charged
for a personal 800 number that he tried in vane to stop the phone
company from charging him for.
</P>
<P>
   These mystery charges are small in nature, but they have
appeared on phone bills across the country. Known as ``cramming,''
it is now considered the largest telemarketing scam in the nation
by consumer groups, with 300 written complaints sent to the Federal
Communications Commission (FCC) every month.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in billing people for services they never ordered
sparked a Senate investigation and led the FCC to push local
telecommunication companies to devise guidelines to combat the
fraudulent practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have zero tolerance of this kind of fraud, which
uses a vital utility like telephone service to rip off American
families,'' said Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, chairwoman of the
Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations (PSI), who led Thursday's
hearing on cramming.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, any business can enter into a contract
with a local telephone or billing company to charge consumers
through their phone bills. No questions asked by the phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the culprits include singles lines, voice mail services
and Internet access companies that charge monthly fees to people
who may not even have a home computer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new guidelines, which the FCC released Wednesday,
phone companies would screen products for which they are asked to
provide billing and immediately provide credit to customers who say
they've been ``crammed,'' said Lawrence Strickling, deputy chief of
the Common Carrier Bureau of the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins called the guidelines a ``good first step,''
doubting their effectiveness because local phone companies are not
bound to abide by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have concerns about the voluntary nature of the
guidelines,'' she said, ``would this make for inconsistent
enforcement and protection?''
</P>
<P>
   But Roy Neel, president of the United States Telephone
Association, was confident that the newly composed list will curb
cramming and protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer protection is good business, and I'd like to see the
competition between companies to protect consumers run its course
before imposing any new federal laws,'' said Neel, who represents
local phone companies' interests in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission apprehended Online Consulting
Group, Inc., which made $5 million in one year by advertising
``free-matching'' services with local singles. Once the single
called, for free, someone from the company immediately returned the
call -- and charged the person $4 per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill, agreed with Collins that enforceable
regulations were needed to protect consumers. ``People shouldn't
need a microscope or a bloodhound to check their phone bills, he
said.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9851 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-LIST-HNS &LR;      07-23 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN LIBRARY OPENS A NEW CHAPTER IN LITERARY LISTLESSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Making lists used to be a crazed and personal
thing.
</P>
<P>
   But now conglomerates have taken over, printing lists by
committee, and the best five isn't enough. It's 100 at a time _ the
fast-food mentality brought to history, art and literature.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of the hundred most important people and the
hundred best American films comes the hundred best English-language
novels of the century, trumpeted by a panel of literates from
Modern Library. It's another sign of the sound-biting of the
American intellect, of cutting culture down to USA Today size,
making it manageable and easy-to-swallow.
</P>
<P>
   People will argue that anything that'll move the huddled masses
closer to books is a good thing, but marketing tools like the
Modern Library list are a demeaning way to do it, a kind of
time-clock, corporate look at writing.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library's top five are ``Ulysses,'' ``The Great
Gatsby,'' ``A Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man,'' ``Lolita''
and ``Brave New World.'' There aren't many surprises after that,
unless you cough loudly at the first Hemingway novel appearing at
No. 45, J.D. Salinger's ``The Catcher in the Rye'' coming in at 64,
or the pronounced absence of comic novels.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library panel, unlike the whoopee cushions that voted
for the 100 best films, has impeccable credentials. The 10-man
panel, which included authors Gore Vidal, Shelby Foote and William
Styron, offered a list of 100 books virtually impossible to argue
against.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the American Film Institute, which did well with its
top five before going immediately into the toilet, the first five
on the Modern Library list are out of kilter. Even panel members
say so.
</P>
<P>
   With the wealth of English writing in this century, one author
should not appear twice in the top five, and James Joyce's ``A
Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man'' doesn't belong at No. 3.
Panelist Edmund Morris, a historian, said the book doesn't deserve
that high a slot, calling it ``a sketch for `Ulysses.''' He also
questioned the placement of ``Brave New World.'' It's not Aldous
Huxley's best, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Foote agreed, saying he had no problem with ``Ulysses'' and
``The Great Gatsby,'' but had ``trouble with the others,''
preferring D.H. Lawrence's ``The Rainbow'' and William Faulkner's
``As I Lay Dying'' in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. ``As I Lay Dying'' is a better book than ``The Sound
and the Fury,'' the perennial frosh-soph Faulkner read that came in
at No. 6. And Faulkner's ``Absalom, Absalom'' is a better book than
the panel's 54th choice, ``Light in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as ``Touch of Evil'' should get serious consideration as
one of the best American movies on the strength of its opening
time-bomb scene, ``Absalom, Absalom'' should get consideration
among the 100-best novels because it offers what some believe to be
the best opening chapter in the language.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner has three books on the list. So does Henry James. So do
Joyce and D.H. Lawrence. Joseph Conrad, a true artist of the
language, led all authors with four books, topped by ``The Secret
Agent'' at No. 44.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Heart of Darkness'' is more compelling than ``The Secret
Agent,'' and the list wouldn't have suffered if Conrad's fourth
book, ``Lord Jim,'' had been left off. The same is true for Joyce's
``Finnegans Wake,'' an in-house pick of pompous English professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finnegans Wake'' has more fun with words than any 10 other
books, but c'mon. Even when it's fairly accessible, it's
pretentious as hell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Wolfe didn't make the list, presumably because his style
has fallen out of favor. Wolfe can be tiresome, yes. But for
sustained pretension he has nothing on Joyce. ``Finnegans Wake,''
even at No. 77, doesn't belong.
</P>
<P>
   There are no other books that beg to be jettisoned, although
Styron making the list with ``Sophie's Choice'' is bound to raise
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a rhythm to the entries that is kind of odd, with
names bunching up together.
</P>
<P>
   Three times authors are listed back-to-back: James at 26 and 27,
Conrad at 46 and 47, Lawrence at 48 and 49, which does not speak to
much originality from the panel. And there are books that fairly
scream their absence. Harper Lee's ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
Carson McCullers' ``A Member of the Wedding.'' James Agee's ``A
Death in the Family.'' Thomas Pynchon's ``Gravity's Rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel shied away from contemporary authors because it wanted
books that have had time to filter down to genius, which may be the
reason John Updike, Zora Neale Hurston and Ray Bradbury aren't
listed. But then why do Styron, William Kennedy and Salman Rushdie
make the cut?
</P>
<P>
   There is also a dearth of laughing novels. Where is anything by
Kingsley Amis or P.G. Wodehouse, by Brendan Behan or William
Saroyan? And how about mystery and intrigue? Eric Ambler has to be
on that list, with ``Judgment of Deltchev'' or ``The Schirmer
Inheritance.'' So does Raymond Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Dashiell Hammett's ``The Maltese Falcon'' comes in at 56, but
there's no sign of ``The Big Sleep'' or ``The Long Goodbye,'' of
``Farewell, My Lovely'' or ``The Little Sister''? Phooey. And while
we're at it, where's Dorothy Sayers' ``Nine Tailors''?
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many war novels, either, for a century that's been
defined by war. ``Catch-22'' deserves its No. 7 ranking, but then
it's a greased slide to Norman Mailer's ``The Naked and the Dead''
at No. 51, another 11 spots to ``From Here to Eternity,'' 12 more
to ``A Farewell to Arms.'' And those aren't the best novels on this
century's wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naked and the Dead'' takes too many yawn-inspiring detours,
James Jones' ``A Thin Red Line'' is arguably better than ``From
Here to Eternity,'' and ``Farewell to Arms'' has fathered more bad
films than anyone thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Modern Library panel favors writers who sustained
their artistry over three, four or five books, the list overlooks
authors whose one-shot novels were pretty good. George Mandel's
``The Wax Boom,'' for instance. ``Paths of Glory'' by Humphrey
Cobb. Harry Brown's ``A Walk in the Sun.'' Frederic Wakeman's
``Shore Leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Even writers whose work turned mediocre can point to impressive
pieces _ James Gould Cozzens' ``Guard of Honor,'' Irwin Shaw's
``The Young Lions'' and David Ormsbee's ``The Sound of an
American.''
</P>
<P>
   The list lacks women, too. There are eight, with Virginia
Woolf's ``To the Lighthouse'' at No. 15 and McCullers' ``The Heart
Is a Lonely Hunter'' close behind. But there could be so many more
_ Sayers, Hurston, Doris Lessing, Mary McCarthy, Eudora Welty, Edna
Ferber, Daphne DuMaurier for ``Rebecca.''
</P>
<P>
   South African mystery writer James McClure deserves mention for
``The Artful Egg'' or ``The Gooseberry Fool.'' Herman Wouk's ``The
Caine Mutiny'' should be there. Maybe William Goldman's ``Soldier
in the Rain,'' and Charles Jackson's ``The Lost Weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of skewed things about the list, not the least
of which is the mind-set, the massive hubris that says it needs to
be done at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
