<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BOXING-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SENATORS SEEK TO REFORM BOXING INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 23 -- The notorious power enjoyed by a few
promoters and managers in professional boxing is under attack by
members of the U.S. Senate who envision dramatic changes in the way
the sport is run.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation is pending in the Senate that would overhaul
professional boxing from the personal contracts boxers sign with
promoters to the rating system that ranks fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The bill -- named after boxing legend Muhammad Ali -- is
designed to put an end to anti-competitive and unethical business
practices rife in a sport that has no national oversight authority,
said the bill's two authors Sens. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., and John
McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said a number of forces -- especially greed -- is ruining
professional boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A combination of problems has made boxing less attractive as a
sport,'' he said. ``And in some instances make it almost impossible
for the best fighters in the world... to fight against one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the professional boxing community visited the
nation's capital Thursday to testify before the Senate Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee and endorse, at least in
theory, the bill's main thrust.
</P>
<P>
   However, two of the sport's biggest promoters were noticeably
absent. Bob Arum declined the Senate's invitation and Don King
failed to respond to it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada and New Jersey boxing commissioners testified that there
is a need for federal laws to control the unscrupulous practices
they say are eating away at the popularity of professional boxing.
</P>
<P>
   To protect the boxer's rights, the bill would place a one year
limit on promotional rights that promoters could place on boxers to
participate in a particular match; prevents a boxer from being
forced to hire an associate or relative of the promoter; prohibits
a promoter from also managing a fighter's finances; and requires
both the promoter and sanctioning organization to disclose all
finances associated with the fight to the state boxing commission.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also require sanctioning organizations staging
bouts in the U.S. to establish consistent criteria for rating
professional boxers.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Futch, who trained 22 world champions including Joe
Frazier, Michael Spinks, and Riddick Bowe, told the committee an
overhaul of the rating system needs to take place to prevent
sanctioning organizations from manipulating the rankings for their
own financial gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of competition has gone down drastically, and I
want to see this repaired,'' Futch said. ``Unless we continue to do
something about it, it will continue to erode.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Stone, counsel for the International Boxing Federation
(IBF), told the committee he was not opposed to the bill, but said
it did not address the increasing economic influence television and
pay per view has over the sport. Bryan said he is open to making
changes to the bill if the results are good for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Sulaiman, president of the World Boxing Council (WBC), said
he was interested in working to bring reform to the sport, but
resisted suggestions that the ratings system should be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson, a former client of King's, did not attend the
hearing but expressed support for the bill in a letter he sent to
the committee. Tyson said his financial career ``was placed in the
hands of a promoter and managers who were allowed to run amuck in
the ... unregulated world of boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson estimates he lost $65 million since 1995 and places part
of the blame on his ``promoter.'' Tyson never mentioned King by
name in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, said he expects a vote in the Senate this year, but with
only a handful of legislative work days left this year it is
unlikely the House will have a chance to review the bill. And
McCain predicts it will take a few years before the reforms become
law.
</P>
</TEXT>
