<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGE-OF-GOETHE-ART-REV     07-23 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGE-OF-GOETHE-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: POETRY, SCIENCE AND HISTORY IN THE AGE OF GOETHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is at the Frick Collection a loan show of
drawings that is just the thing for high summer. Entitled ``Fuseli
to Menzel,'' it is small (80 items in all) and mostly downstairs.
Everything in it speaks for Germany in what is called ``the Age of
Goethe.'' The age in question can be elasticized, but basically it
spans the first half of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The Age of Goethe was a memorable time for drawing in Germany. A
major participant in the show, Moritz von Schwind, was to say later
that ``it was to drawings, rather than to paintings, that we looked
for what was rich and important in the way of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like a putdown for painting. But what von Schwind
meant was that in the Age of Goethe, drawing and thinking had a lot
in common. Drawing had not been mere penciling. It was the partner
of poetry, and of the natural sciences, and of a sense of history.
Draftsmen in the Age of Goethe did a great deal more than draw.
</P>
<P>
   Like Caspar David Friedrich (the cream of the crop), many of the
draftsmen in the present show also excelled as easel painters.
Others were active as muralists, battle painters, stage designers,
professors of optics or doctors of philosophy. (Yet another, Carl
Gustav Carus, was both a pioneer biographer of Goethe and a
professor of obstetrics in Dresden.)
</P>
<P>
   Whole cities were to bear the mark of individual draftsmen as
architects, town planners, curators and collectors, leaders of
taste and teachers of history. They didn't have to be grizzled
veterans, either. The short-lived Friedrich Gilly (1772-1800) was
named chief inspector of buildings throughout Prussia when he was
only 25. The present show includes a recently rediscovered
watercolor by Gilly of the almost ruined castle church of
Marienburg, then in eastern Prussia, now in Poland. It was thanks
to him that the restoration of Marienburg was set in hand as a
national responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The artists in the present show drew because _ either with
pencil and paper, or with brush and watercolor _ they could give a
lean and uncluttered account of what they saw. They could also, by
implication, find out what kind of people they themselves actually
were. What they produced were not ``exhibition drawings.'' They
were fragments of autobiography and, as such, haunting.
</P>
<P>
   Goethe himself produced many drawings of that sort. There is,
for instance, a raw urgency about the drawing in the Frick of some
blocks of weathered granite that he had first seen on a
mountainside in Upper Franconia in 1785. So vividly did he remember
them that he went back to see them 35 years later and made the
annotated drawing that is in the present show.
</P>
<P>
   It related to a long-running controversy about the creation of
the earth. Himself a lifelong student of geology, Goethe did not
believe that these stones had been tumbled this way and that by
ancient and colossal convulsions. On the contrary, he thought that
their evolution had been both calm and slow. His little drawing is
not, and was not meant to be, a ``thing of beauty.'' But there is
no mistaking the intensity of the conviction behind it.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1810, Friedrich and his colleague Georg
Friedrich Kersting climbed up to around 4,000 feet in a mountainous
part of what is now the Czech Republic. They were looking for the
source of the Elbe river, which then as now was indispensable to
central and northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It was not yet a tourist attraction. The way led across a meadow
that looked like a gigantic eiderdown that had been left out in the
rain. But with time, Friedrich and his friend came upon a narrow
ditch that widened for just a yard or two. What looked like a
puddle on the move was the source of the Elbe.
</P>
<P>
   It was from this narrow slit in cheerless ground that Dresden
would draw power and strength, as would Prince Hamlet's Wittenberg,
and Martin Luther's Magdeburg, and the great Hanseatic city of
Hamburg. Friedrich's unemphatic image draws us back to that distant
but all-important puddle at 4,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   The draftsman as historian is also uppermost at the Frick in
``The Miracle of Blossoms'' by Wilhelm Tischbein. This relates to
the time when Napoleon's armies occupied Hamburg and introduced a
reign of terror there. In May 1813, orders were given that
everything should be razed and every tree cut down in a wide swath
around the fortified city.
</P>
<P>
   Tischbein did not spell out the misery and humiliation that this
caused. Instead, he portrayed the miracle of nature by which an
apple tree, cut down at that time, managed to bloom in the spring
of 1814. This brought hope to the inhabitants _ one of whom is
touchingly portrayed by Tischbein _ that Hamburg itself might also
rise again. (And sure enough, no later than May 31, 1814, the
German armies recaptured Hamburg.)
</P>
<P>
   The look of Germany in the Age of Goethe (and after it) owed
much to the draftsmen in this show. Munich in its heyday was
largely the creation of Leo von Klenze, architect and town planner.
In the 1820s and '30s Karl Friedrich Schinkel made over the
personality of Berlin in ways that are still treasured. Draftsmen
were much befriended, moreover.
</P>
<P>
   Von Schwind as a young man in Vienna was a close friend of Franz
Schubert. Johann Christian Reinhart was a lifelong friend of
Schiller, the poet and dramatist. Another draftsman was a
brother-in-law of the composer Felix Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the artists in this show also endeared themselves to
people of substance who liked to have them around in big country
houses for month after month. This, if ever, was the heyday of the
``spare man,'' and Hinrich Sieveking, in the exemplary catalog of
the present show, defines their role as a combination of
``confidant and draftsman-chronicler.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything in the show comes from the collection of a Munich
lawyer called Alfred Winterstein. He was fired up to start buying
German romantic drawings in 1927, when they were not much sought
after, and he kept at it until he died in 1976. His wife was
directly descended from a high official who was also a friend and
patron of one of the stars of this show, Johann Georg von Dillis
(1759-1841).
</P>
<P>
   It is von Dillis who sends the visitor home in a high good
humor. He puts before us a steep stretch of woodland. The sun
shines, the breeze exhilarates and the company is the best that
Munich could offer. There is Count Rumford, the initiator of the
English Garden in Munich. There is his friend Countess Baumgarten,
thanks to whom Munich got the premiere of Mozart's ``Idomeneo.''
</P>
<P>
   Other painters at other times would have settled for a formal
pose, but not this one. Like Henri Cartier-Bresson with his camera
200 years later, he caught his two friends when they were a little
way ahead of him and weren't looking round.
</P>
<P>
   The show also includes a very good joke. In his ``History
Painter,'' Johann Christian Reinhart makes irresistible fun of the
fashion at that time for paintings of heroic horsemen. Not only is
there no live horseman in this drawing, but there is no live horse,
either. What we see is a man painting a uniformed mannequin astride
a cloth-covered wooden stand. All is pretense, and Reinhart savored
every inch of it.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Fuseli and Adolph Menzel have top billing but serve
respectively as prelude and aftermath to the show. The gruesome
fancy of the one and the bonhomie of the other are nicely adjusted
to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuseli to Menzel: Drawings From the Age of Goethe'' remains at
the Frick Collection, 1 E. 70th St., Manhattan, through Sept. 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDBLATT-PHOTOGRAPHY     07-23 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDBLATT-PHOTOGRAPHY-REVIEW-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PHOTOGRAPHS FROM SOUTH AFRICA': INTRIGUING IMAGES OBSCURED BY
TEXT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Goldblatt sold his family's menswear business
in South Africa to become a photographer in 1962. But the pictures
he made of the nation under apartheid suggest that there was one
thing in the rag trade he refused to leave behind: the practice of
taking inventory.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition ``David Goldblatt: Photographs From South
Africa,'' at the Museum of Modern Art, includes 46 pictures of
churches, monuments, shantytowns, apartment houses, graveyards,
toilet seats, billboards, hedges and house trimmings: a veritable
inventory of South Africa's store of goods, running from 1964 until
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bernd and Hilla Becher, who photographed water towers,
blast furnaces and other quasi-architectural objects, Goldblatt is
interested in man-made things. But he is not exploring the curious
and beautiful variations on a utilitarian theme. Instead, he
practices a kind of social iconography, looking for ordinary images
that are packed with historical and sociological meaning. Goldblatt
chose to focus on unexceptional objects in South Africa, he once
said, because he was drawn ``to the quiet and commonplace, where
nothing `happened' and yet all was contained and immanent.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, all is not contained and immanent in these
images. Many of the pictures cry out for explanation, and their cry
is answered with a torrent of text. Every photograph is supported
by a few hundred words. Sometimes the text helps, turning what are
cool, uninflected pictures into illustrations of the twisted social
relations and hideous inequalities of apartheid. Sometimes, though,
the text is just a tidal wave in which the sought-for crucial
information drowns.
</P>
<P>
   The successes in this show are the mystifying objects that yield
to explanation but retain their visual presence. For example, the
exhibition opens with an odd structure that appears to have been
made out of tin ceiling tiles, corrugated metal and a small wheel.
Goldblatt explains that this is a ``Cafe-de-Move-On,'' one of the
coffee carts that African workers in Johannesburg would visit for
tea, lunch, conversation and even, occasionally, a place to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, there were thousands of these carts, made from castoff
materials from white Johannesburg. By 1965, though, the carts, long
deplored by the government, had been destroyed. At first, Goldblatt
writes, the workers had to eat in eating houses, fish friers and
cafes, and then, beginning in the 1970s, in ``factory canteens,
long established for whites but thought by many employers to be
`unnecessary' for blacks, and which workers had resisted as being a
ploy by bosses to keep wages down.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a picture as intriguing as this, though, can suffer from
too much text. Here Goldblatt indicates clearly that the
destruction of the coffee carts was a bad thing, but then goes on
to give an opaque explanation of the significance of the opening of
the company canteen to blacks. Was it in fact social progress or
part of a ploy to keep wages down? He doesn't say.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Telling the history of a nation through its objects is
nonetheless a heroic endeavor, especially when the history goes
back thousands of years. As proof that Africans civilized the veld
thousands of years before the Europeans came, Goldblatt includes a
late-Iron Age settlement on the grasslands of the highveld: a pile
of rocks with a square crawl passage. In order to show the first
signs of separatism, he takes a picture of the hedge that was
planted at the Cape by the first European settlers in the middle of
the 17th century to keep the indigenous Khoikhoi out. A curlicue
scroll ornament on a pure white stairway at one of the richest
farms at the Cape is a sign that conspicuous consumption went all
the way back to the late 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition, most of the objects photographed are
apartheid-era structures. A broken toilet seat sitting in the
middle of a vast grassland is proof that many African East Cape
farmers were forced off their land and into resettlement camps that
contained no farmland but 1,500 ``long-drop'' latrines. A 1990
picture of a shiny shelter of new corrugated metal in the Transvaal
is evidence that new shacks were being built even as apartheid was
being dismantled. A 1988 real estate ad for whites in the Natal
region showing a house with an African man and his son standing in
front is the salesman's hint that the man and his son are among the
``assets'' of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was said,'' Goldblatt writes, ``but much was
implied.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of the photographs speak louder than their explanations.
One is of a bleak cemetery for white members of the security forces
killed in what was called the ``Total Onslaught,'' in the
Transvaal. It is a fenced-in area in a field, with an arched
gateway carrying the inscription ``We are for you, South Africa,''
a line from the Afrikaans national anthem. This place was clearly
supposed to honor the whites who fell fighting for apartheid; it
is, after all, called The Heroes' Acre. But because it resembles a
concentration camp gate, it slyly suggests that the fences of
apartheid were doubly oppressive, not only keeping blacks out but
also shutting whites in.
</P>
<P>
   Like Eugene Atget, who photographed Paris' deserted streets,
closed storefronts and quiet courtyards, Goldblatt rarely includes
people in his photographs. He wants each object to speak frankly
about the people who are not there to hear.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most remarkable pictures, though, reverses
Goldblatt's usual formulation of walls without people. It is of a
mother and child lying on a mattress. They appear exactly as you
would expect if they had been in the privacy of their home,
surrounded by their possessions, chairs and a table. The child is
asleep. The mother watches him. The only thing amiss is that the
walls of the shelter are gone. Mother and child are lying out in
the middle of some sand surrounded by bushes and trees.
</P>
<P>
   As Goldblatt explains, ``The shelter was a framework of Port
Jackson brushwood staked into the loose sand of the Cape Flats and
covered by plastic sheets.'' But in 1984, he continues, ``a team of
five overalled black men, supervised by an armed white, lifted the
entire structure of frame and plastic skin off the ground and
placed it nearby. Then they pulled off the plastic, smashed the
framework, and threw the pieces onto a waiting truck.'' The convoy
then ``moved toward the next group of shelters. For a while the
woman lay with the child. Then she got up and began to cut and
strip branches of Port Jackson bush to make a new framework for her
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though this photograph has living, breathing subjects, it
carries the same affectless quality that pervades Goldblatt's
inventory of inanimate objects. Why? One can only conclude that
this is the look of apartheid: oppressive, futile, hopelessly
still.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DAVID GOLDBLATT: PHOTOGRAPHS FROM SOUTH AFRICA'
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition remains at the Museum of Modern Art, 11 West 53rd
St., through Oct. 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
