<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cooler and less humid air will engulf New England and the
northern Middle Atlantic states Friday as a cold front moves
offshore. Breezes from the northwest will be accompanied by
sunshine mixed with puffy clouds. A shower is possible over
interior northern New England, while locations along the coast are
dry and seasonably warm. High pressure will also grace the upper
Ohio Valley and Great Lakes with comfortable humidity levels and
ample sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   The front separating this cooler air mass from sultry air over
the South and southern Plains will be the focus for clusters of
thunderstorms from Kansas to the Carolinas. Flooding rains are
possible with some of the storms as steering winds aloft are quite
weak. Elsewhere, a pocket of cold air at 20,000 feet will lift
muggy air into towering thunderheads with tropical downpours along
the central Gulf Coast. The Florida peninsula will be drier than
recent days, as warm air aloft aids in suppressing afternoon
thunderstorms. An exception will be in southern areas where
isolated showers are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, searing heat will continue to plague interior
Texas and Oklahoma. High temperatures will be near 100 degrees in
many areas. Meanwhile, afternoon thunderstorms will develop again
as monsoon moisture remains in place over the interior Southwest.
Some of the storms will produce flooding of low-lying areas. Dry
and seasonably hot air will cover central California and interior
Washington and Oregon while low clouds cling to the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Swarm of Storms
</P>
<P>
   For the past several afternoons, a swarm of scattered
thunderstorms have sprouted over the high peaks of the Rockies.
Tall mountains are ``elevated heat sources.'' That is, as the sun
heats the top of a mountain, the high ground heats the air in
contact with it. In turn, the warmed air becomes less dense
compared to the surrounding air not in contact with the mountain.
Like a hot-air balloon, the air then rises, and, if there is
sufficient moisture, blossoms into a roiling cumulus cloud. This
week, moisture has streamed northward from Mexico, providing fuel
for the swarm of storms. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     07-23 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RYAN' HEADED FOR AN OSCAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Is the Oscar race already over?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. But ask any producer, talent agent or studio executive
in town about the leading contender for the Academy Awards, and
they'll respond with three words: ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The World War II epic, directed by Steven Spielberg, opens on
Friday but has already been preceded by the best reviews of
Spielberg's film career. Spielberg won the Academy Award in 1994
for best director for ``Schindler's List,'' which collected a total
of seven Oscars, including best picture.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusually early to speak of Academy Awards, which will be
handed out on March 21. Anything can happen. And certainly ``The
Truman Show,'' and films opening later in the year, will compete
for Oscars, too.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Saving Private Ryan,'' written by Robert Rodat and
starring Tom Hanks, seems to have the perfect Academy pedigree. Its
early reviews have been extraordinary, with the word
``masterpiece'' tossed around.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-hour 35-minute film is so emotional that some members of
the audience leave in silence and burst into tears outside the
theater. And while the movie unflinchingly depicts the blood and
terror of war, it's also unfailingly patriotic.
</P>
<P>
   The film tells the story of an eight-man unit's search for a
soldier, Private Ryan, whose three brothers have died in battle.
The group's task is to take him away from the front lines. Other
members of the cast include Matt Damon, as Private Ryan; Tom
Sizemore, and Edward Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Press, the marketing chief at Dreamworks, which, with
Paramount, made ``Saving Private Ryan,'' acknowledged that it was
risky to release the film in the summer, normally a time of action,
family and escapist movies.
</P>
<P>
   November and December are the months for serious and weighty
films because critics tend to make their top-10 lists at the time,
and year-end releases are considered to be fresher in the minds of
members of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, who
nominate the films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not kidding ourselves,'' Ms. Press said. ``It's a risk
to put it out in the summer. But we also think that audiences are
starved for something of substance in the summer. And we have
little doubt that people will remember this film at the end of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 17 years, Spielberg has agreed to
undertake a nationwide tour to sell his movie, in this case to
discuss ``Private Ryan'' on television shows and in numerous other
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks and other members of the cast are also promoting the film,
which cost $63 million, as is Stephen E. Ambrose, whose historical
works on World War II were used in the research material for the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   At Ambrose's private screening of the film, he asked the
projectionist to turn it off at one point because he was so
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Selling the movie, with its raw depiction of battlefield
violence and terror, is a delicate job. ``We have to be careful not
to mislead people that this was a soft-soap war story but also find
a way to encourage them to go and see it,'' Ms. Press said.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg has promised the Motion Picture Association of
America, which rated the film R (anyone under 17 must be
accompanied by a parent or guardian), that he would not flinch in
discussing the level of intensity of the film. He has said in
interviews that he thinks no one under 14 should see the film.
</P>
<P>
   Its premiere in Hollywood on Tuesday night was unusual. Normally
such affairs are red-carpet events, with preening stars and a
glitzy party afterward. This one was low key, and there was no
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been inappropriate,'' Ms. Press said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Spoof of the Mafia
</P>
<P>
   As a boy in Sicily, Vincenzo Cortino was driven from his home
town and forced to (italics)swim(end italics) to America. He grew
up to become a Mafia patriarch who, in his final years, must hand
over the reins of power to one of his two sons: the psychotic and
very stupid Joey or the war hero Anthony. Treachery follows.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds familiar, well, it was designed that way. Jim
Abrahams, who helped create spoofs like ``Hot Shots,''
``Airplane!'' and ``The Naked Gun,'' has turned his focus on ``The
Godfather,'' ``Casino'' and other somber movies about the mob. The
result is ``Mafia!,'' which opens on Friday, a really silly spoof
starring Lloyd Bridges, in the Marlon Brando part, as well as Jay
Mohr, Olympia Dukakis, Christina Applegate and Billy Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Abrahams said the idea for ``Mafia!'' came to him while reading
reviews for the television series ``The Last Don.'' He recalled:
``The tone of the reviews was: `How could they recycle this stuff
again? Have they no shame?' It awakened me to the fact that here's
a genre taking itself very seriously that's just waiting to be sent
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrahams, who wrote the film with Greg Norberg and Michael
McManus, said he followed the pattern set by his former partnership
with his old friends David and Jerry Zucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You write stuff that makes you laugh and cross your fingers
that you're in tune with the moviegoing audience,'' he said. What
Abrahams sought was, as he put it, ``the cliches in the genre: the
hothead son, the wise son, the revered patriarch, the WASP
girlfriend, the loyal thug corporal. They're all there.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrahams' humor masks what has been far more serious work that
has consumed him and his wife, Nancy, for more than five years. In
1993, their youngest child, Charlie, who was not yet 1, was
diagnosed with a severe form of epilepsy, which, if unchecked,
causes severe mental retardation.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors prescribed anticonvulsant drugs and brain surgery, but
nothing stopped the child's seizures, which took place up to 100
times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, the Abrahams began their own research at medical
libraries and discovered a ketogenic diet _ high fat, high protein,
low carbohydrate _ that had been used since the 1920s to treat
epilepsy. The Abrahams and their son flew to Johns Hopkins Hospital
in Baltimore, one of the few hospitals in the United States that
administer the diet. Within days, the boy's seizures stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Abrahams later used his experience to direct Meryl Streep in a
1997 ABC television drama, ``... First Do No Harm,'' a true story
about a mother who struggles to save her son from epilepsy when she
learns about the little-known diet.
</P>
<P>
   Abrahams said doctors often didn't pay much attention to the
diet, and brushed off its impact on epilepsy cases as merely
anecdotal evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Abrahams' son is doing well. ``Even talking
about it now, years later, I can feel the hair raised on the back
of my neck,'' the 54-year-old filmmaker said. ``When your kid is
having a seizure, and you're desperate, these arguments are
idiotic.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The era of movie musicals is over. But Hollywood studios are
preparing adaptations of two well-known stage musicals that, if
successful, could open the way for a resurgence of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``Dreamgirls,'' the 1981 musical directed and
choreographed onstage by Michael Bennett, about a singing group
like the Supremes that rises from the ghetto to national fame in
the 1960s. The movie adaptation, to be directed by Joel Schumacher,
is tentatively set to start production next year.
</P>
<P>
   The producers are David Geffen, one of the stage producers, and
Warner Brothers. Lauren Hill, lead singer of the Fugees, is the
leading contender for the role of Deena Jones, the Diana Ross-like
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher, director of ``Batman'' and ``A Time to Kill,'' said
``Dreamgirls'' is hardly like the old-style MGM musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're telling a story of people who perform in clubs and
theaters and sing for a living,'' he said. ``The music is
integrated into their rehearsals, their performances. No one walks
down the middle of the street singing, `I love you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``Chicago,'' the John Kander-Fred Ebb-Bob Fosse 1975
musical, which was successfully revived on Broadway in 1996 and is
still playing, is set to be turned into a movie next year. The film
will star Goldie Hawn as Roxie Hart, a former chorine charged with
the murder of her lover, the part played by Ann Reinking in the
revival, and Madonna as Velma Kelly, Roxie's murderous rival, the
Bebe Neuwirth role.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Hytner, who recently staged Lincoln Center's ``Twelfth
Night,'' is the director. The story is a corrosively funny fable
set mostly in the Cook County jail in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the perfect time for `Chicago,' _ it's edgy, dark and
provocative,'' said Laurence Mark, one of the producers of the
film, which will be released by Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Hollywood musicals have fared unevenly.
Disney's 1992 effort at a live-action musical, ``Newsies,'' grossed
a disastrous $2.8 million. But earlier this year, Paramount's
reissue of ``Grease,'' originally released in 1978, was a success,
grossing $12.7 million in its opening weekend, coming in second
after ``Titanic.'' Overall, the ``Grease'' reissue took in $28.4
million, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc., which monitors
box office figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think that this is a genre waiting to be reinvented,''
Mark said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
