<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-FIREARMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO, RILEY DEPLORE CONGRESS' REJECTION OF GUN LEGISLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno and Education Secretary
Richard Riley on Thursday lamented Congress' rejection of
legislation that would hold adults criminally responsible for
failing to keep guns away from minors who use the weapons in
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote against the legislation was ``the defeat of just
a common-sense, reasonable solution to make sure that guns are not
accessible to children,'' Reno said during a news conference with
Riley. They previewed an anti-youth violence advertisement that
features images from recent fatal schoolyard shootings.
</P>
<P>
   By a 69-31 vote, the Senate late Wednesday turned back a
proposal that had been endorsed by President Clinton to make it a
federal offense if an adult does not securely store a gun that a
minor later uses to shoot someone.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored by Sen. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill., would
have imposed a maximum year in prison and a $10,000 fine on anyone
convicted under the new law. Durbin tried to add the gun safety
proposal to a $33 billion spending bill for the Justice, Commerce
and State departments.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that parents should not be prosecuted for crimes
committed by their children, Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, persuaded
his colleagues to instead expand a test program designed to combat
youth crime and to increase prosecution of people who illegally
deliver weapons to youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can make parents criminals,'' said Craig, a
board member of the National Rifle Association. He argued that
Durbin's measure ``would take the victim who had his or her firearm
stolen and make him the criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Durbin measure, co-sponsored by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I.,
did not apply to firearms stolen through an illegal entry or
break-in. The Durbin-Chafee proposal was similar to a law in Texas
and 14 other states that provide criminal penalties for adults who
allow children unsupervised access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Senate Republicans defeated an effort by Democrats
to require all handguns sold in the United States to be equipped
with child safety locks. Senators approved an alternative proposal,
which also was offered by Craig, to require gun dealers to make the
safety devices available. At the same time, the Craig proposal
would not penalize dealers who fail to stock the devices.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Riley said the administration was not giving up on
tightening restrictions. ``Reasonable people ought to see this
really as a child safety issue, and that's how we hope it goes
forward,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The ad previewed by Reno and Riley begins with the image of a
pistol being fired as the folk group Peter, Paul and Mary sing
``Where Have All The Flowers Gone?'' The ad continues with the
number of shooting victims _ dead and wounded _ in Jonesboro, Ark.,
Pearl, Miss., and Springfield, Ore., scrolling across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The ad draws to a close with a crying child embracing a fellow
survivor of a campus shooting and the end of the song's lyrics:
``Where have all the children gone? Gone to graveyards one by one.
Oh, when will we ever learn?''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said a review of the campus shootings found a greater need
for adults to talk more to children. ``One of the saddest findings
to come out of all these killings is that many young people in the
school were aware that something was going on and they didn't
involve adults in that conversation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
