<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-OUTRIGGING-ART-     07-23 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-OUTRIGGING-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTRIGGER RACES IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By JOE GLICKMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To the bikers, bladers and joggers cruising along the
path next to the West Side Highway, it had to look like a scene
from the Elvis film ``Blue Hawaii,'' as directed by Fellini. More
than 200 paddlers in bikinis or baggy print shorts, sandals and
shades milled about a flotilla of 45-foot outrigger canoes on Pier
25, which juts into the Hudson River in the shadow of the World
Trade Center. A fiberglass iguana, as big as an outrigger and
mounted to a trailer where a Brazilian artist sculptures the wood
pilings he finds floating in the Hudson, stares ominously over the
West Side Highway.
</P>
<P>
   This aquatic anomaly _ urban outrigging _ was nonexistent in New
York City until three years ago. But the Liberty World Challenge, a
15-mile paddling marathon, now in its second year, has already
become the sport's premier event on the East Coast, drawing dozens
of teams from outrigger hot beds like Hawaii and California, as
well as Vermont, Maine and Canada, where outrigger sightings were
once as common as UFOs.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the opening credits on ``Hawaii Five-O,'' where
a six-man canoe surges down the face of an angry wave, few North
Americans would ever have seen one of these incredibly seaworthy
Polynesian craft. The basic design has not changed in 1,500 years:
the outrigger, or ama, an upward-curved stabilizing arm that
resembles an elephant's tusk, is lashed on the port side of the
canoe to wood beams called iako. The original models were carved
out of massive koa trees. While the fastest craft are now molded
fiberglass, koa canoes, which can cost $25,000, are still made and
raced.
</P>
<P>
   Prehistoric Hawaiian outriggers were used for fishing,
transportation, war and racing. Racing was serious business. A
competitor might wager his land, possessions, wife or even his life
on the outcome. Tommy Holmes, author of ``The Hawaiian Canoe''
(Editions Limited, 1993), writes, ``In its import, the canoe stands
to ancient Polynesian culture as the invention of the wheel to
ground transportation, as the spaceship to man's spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hawaii, where there are roughly 60 outrigger clubs, the
spiritual element of canoeing remains strong. A Hawaiian priest
(kahuna) drapes leis around new koa canoes and blesses them before
the members of the club. Sheila Beahm, a pilot for Aloha Airlines
and longtime paddler, says, ``Sometimes in a close race a steersman
will chant, `Mana, mana,' which means spiritual power, almost as if
they were appealing to the life force of the boat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   How the Liberty Cup came to New York City is another story
entirely. Roger Meyer, an Upper West Side resident who has spent
the last 15 years kayaking in the Hudson, saw an outrigger for the
first time in 1994 in Long Island Sound near Norwalk, Conn.
Thinking that racing such a craft afforded a great athletic
challenge, he decided to start a team.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing outrigger paddling to Manhattan was only slightly less
difficult than finding beach volleyball players at the Arctic
Circle. But Meyer, who at one time or another has been fanatical
about running, gymnastics and hockey, went to gyms in the city and
countless canoe races in New England and asked anyone with a broad
back if they wanted to try paddling the six-man outrigger he had
chained to a log on the Long Island Sound in Connecticut. I was one
of his early recruits.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, operating on the ``build it and they will
come'' principle, Meyer hauled a six-seat outrigger into Manhattan
and eventually found a home for his $8,000 canoe at Pier 63, near
the Chelsea Piers Equestrian Center on 23rd Street. The 35-year-old
graphic designer then bought a dock, one- and two-man outrigger
canoes (light, tippy 25-foot outriggers used for training and
racing), and the New York Outrigger Club, which now has roughly 50
members, was born.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Meyer staged his first Liberty Cup. Fourteen crews
showed up, a solid turnout for a first-year event. While the sport
is part of the social fabric in Hawaii and popular in southern
California, it has just taken hold on the East Coast and seems to
be spreading at a healthy clip, recreationally and competitively.
</P>
<P>
   While I missed the first Liberty Cup, I signed on for the
second. Meyer told me that there would be 36 crews _ 14 of them
women in a separate race _ including an all-star collection of
Hawaiians. So a month before the race we met weekly to train.
</P>
<P>
   Our first paddle together on a Tuesday afternoon in May was
memorable. Heading south on the Hudson on a two-man outrigger into
a 15-knot wind, Meyer showed me the three phases of the
single-blade stroke: the entry or catch, the pull or draw, and exit
or recovery. We'd start on opposite sides of the boat, take 10 to
15 strokes with our ultralight, bent-shaft carbon fiber paddles and
change sides when he shouted ``Hut!'': canoe-speak for switch. As a
competitive kayaker, I was fit and had boat skills, but unlike
double-blade paddling, the canoe stroke was different enough to
make me feel nearly like a beginner.
</P>
<P>
   Things were going well until we turned with the wind and began
surfing back, only to find a wall of storm clouds hurtling our way.
Before you could say ``the Intrepid,'' the sky turned black and the
stiff south wind collided with stronger gusts from the north,
causing the river to haystack like a washing machine gone mad.
Paddling furiously, we sought shelter from the vicious lightning at
Engine Company 1 on a pier a dozen blocks south of Pier 63. Sipping
coffee in the cozy station house, we watched 60-mile-an-hour winds
rake the river and listened to tales of the rescues they'd made on
the mercurial Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   That was practice. The race itself came on a hot Saturday in
June. My teammates and I were an eclectic bunch: two from Guam, two
from Canada and two New Yorkers. Officially, we were called the New
England Free Agents, but our steersmen, Grafton Howard, a beefy
Bronx native who has lived in the South Pacific for the last 20
years, called our boat Paluman Tasi, a Guamanian word which means
sea bird.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, when the starter's horn blasted to begin the men's
race, 132 paddlers in 22 400-pound boats hammered south on the
wind-swept Hudson. The explosion of water, the din of a hovering
helicopter, the echoed cry of ``hut!'' from competing crews and the
drone of the escort boats that led the contingent around the tip of
Manhattan made it the most exciting _ and novel _ start to any boat
race I'd been in.
</P>
<P>
   Having only paddled as a team briefly that morning, we struggled
to find a rhythm. While the basic technique is relatively simple,
the art of paddling is in the feel and timing. The length of the
draw and force applied during the power phase of the stroke
determines how fast the canoe travels. Miss a beat and the boat
slows, as they say in Hawaii, ``like a caterpillar with a broken
leg.''
</P>
<P>
   As we headed past the South Street Seaport up the East River,
Team Hawaii, a Who's Who of single-blade steam engines, led the
field in the direction toward New York Harbor. Tanned, tattooed,
with backs as broad as barn doors, they moved as one, paddling so
smoothly it looked leisurely. Giving chase was Manu'iwa, a
collection of East Coast hot-shots paddling like galley slaves
carrying ice to an emperor.
</P>
<P>
   As the two crews moved around Governors Island, Manu'iwa
surprised themselves and Team Hawaii by closing the gap. Blake
Conant, a 44-year-old steersman and native Hawaiian living in
Connecticut, sensed the surge of adrenaline in his boat and tried
to hold them back. ``The analogy,'' he said, ``is that they're my
horses, and I just tried to keep them calm and make sure we stayed
smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   While the top two crews battled back and forth, we chopped
through the turbulent water in the middle of the pack.
Occasionally, we'd click and surge on the boat ahead of us; this
inspired us, gave us more momentum, and our vessel would pick up
yet again as if we were headed downhill. Other times, we were out
of sync and felt like the proverbial hobbled caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating on the task at hand was a challenge. In addition
to staying in rhythm, we constantly had to shift our weight to keep
from flipping in the rough water. For much of the race I couldn't
stop thinking about the pain in my lower back and shoulders. The
sweeping lines of the Brooklyn Bridge and skyline of Lower
Manhattan were also distracting. Trying to focus, I stared at the
lumpy muscles of the Canadian's back in front of me, or at the
blade of the fellow from Guam in Seat 2. Still, there was the
marauding Staten Island Ferry to worry about. And as we rounded
Ellis Island and the Statue of Liberty, I caught myself daydreaming
about my grandparents, who came to America 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   We finished 10th in 2 hours 21 minutes, exhausted _ not quite
exalted _ but thoroughly pleased to have fought hard and done
something memorable. Team Hawaii, the heavy favorite, edged
Manu'iwa by a mere 48 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   First, second or 10th, each crew was engaged in the elusive
search for that perfect rhythm, the synchronized application of
power where six individuals work as one. ``Staying in that
groove,'' said Conant, `is what outrigger paddling is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WATER:
</P>
<P>
   To join the New York Outrigger Club (dues are $150 a year) or
for more information about outrigger paddling in New York City,
call Roger Meyer (212) 580-0442 or e-mail: NYOutrlg(AT)aol.com. For
information about events on the East Coast, call Blake Conant,
president of the East Coast Outrigger Racing Association, (203)
877-4778. For hourly sessions or half-day excursions around Ellis
Island, the Statue of Liberty or the Financial District, call (212)
684-0812.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
