<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONIQUE-PHOTOGRAPHY-R     07-23 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONIQUE-PHOTOGRAPHY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONIQUE'S KINDERGARTEN': SIMPLICITY AND SERENITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibit notes are at end of review) 
(mk) 
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like a late-20th-century Atget, the British-born
photographer Michael Kenna insists on seeing the quietly luminous
in landscapes molded by the human hand. Atget had a gift for
evoking the human presence in his photographs of Paris without
showing a single soul. And Kenna, too, suggests the human presence
in pictures taken at night or in the early morning _ at the Rouge
steel plant in Dearborn, Mich., for instance, or at the gardens in
France designed by Andre le Notre, the great 17th-century French
landscape architect _ when there is no one around.
</P>
<P>
   In Kenna's recently completed series of photographs of a Waldorf
kindergarten in San Francisco, currently on view at the Robert Mann
Gallery on the Upper East Side, one might expect his signature
black-and-white calm and elegance shattered by clamoring, frenetic
kindergartners. But one would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Seen through Kenna's still lifes of the objects the preschoolers
use or play with, the world in the series ``Monique's
Kindergarten'' is Shaker-like in its serenity, simplicity and
attention to design detail. The children may be absent _ the
photographs were taken on Sunday mornings or in the evenings _ but
their presence is almost palpably felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monique'' in the exhibition's title is Monique Grund, who
taught at a Waldorf school in France before she came to San
Francisco in 1978 to start the kindergarten, which has since grown
into an elementary and high school.
</P>
<P>
   The first coeducational Waldorf school opened in 1919 in
Stuttgart, Germany, founded by the Austrian philosopher and
scientist Rudolf Steiner for the children of employees at the
Waldorf-Astoria cigarette factory. Integrating the arts with
academics, the private, nonsectarian school offered equal education
for all children, whether they were headed for trade or the
university. Since then, hundreds of Waldorf schools have opened
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition's companion book, published by Nazraeli Press,
Ms. Grund explains that through carefully selected objects, she
helps kindergartners, many of whom are used to sitting passively in
front of television sets, learn to play and imagine.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, one of Ms. Grund's kindergartners was Kenna's
daughter, Olivia. Picking her up at school one day, Kenna was asked
by Ms. Grund to take color pictures of the kindergarten, so she
could send them to her family in France.
</P>
<P>
   While he was there on a Sunday, when the kindergarten was free
of the hubbub of children, Kenna discovered what he describes as
``curious and delightful presences,'' the objects the children
played with. Many were made by Ms. Grund out of wool and fabric;
some, by the children themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until 1993, after Kenna was given a four-by-five
view camera by a photographer who no longer wanted to haul the
heavy equipment about, that he began the kindergarten series.
</P>
<P>
   He had last used a large-format camera, which requires a tripod,
when he worked as a commercial photographer more than two decades
earlier. Since then he has preferred the flexibility of the
medium-format camera, which can be hand held, for his landscape
photography. Kenna's images of parks, whether industrial or
recreational and invariably in gorgeous tones of grays and black,
are meditative studies in stillness _ metaphorically, people at
rest.
</P>
<P>
   But by using the larger, heftier, slower camera, Kenna has
created pictures of Ms. Grund's kindergarten that are striking in
their intimacy, tactility and warmth. The photographs _
sepia-toned, gelatin-silver contact prints _ are an affectionate
and affecting portrait of a world of gentle make-believe, quiet
beauty, mystery and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the arrival of the children, the objects seem to be in
a state of suspended animation, and yet they also seem very much
alive, like the toys in a fairy tale that come magically to life
when humans are asleep.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that an impressionistic stork in the grass might be
mistaken for the real thing. A jangle of much-used teaspoons are
the real thing, made more so by Kenna's meticulous attention to the
scratches on the spoon bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Where there are small children, cuteness usually lurks. But in
his series, Kenna firmly keeps it at bay. What saves ``Summer
Dress, 1997'' _ featuring a single diminutive sun dress on a wire
hanger that has a whimsical heart-shape center _ from cute is his
contrasting the dress with the dark tones of a solid wood frame,
from which the dress hangs, and with an unevenly shadowed wall.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in ``Sweepity-Sweep, 1995,'' a brush whose handle is
a wooden doll wearing a conical hat is echoed on the wall by a
pointy shaft of light. And shown against an inky black backdrop,
the translucent animal in ``Paolo's Beeswax Dog'' seems to be a
walking apparition, its ghostly body reflected on the nearby smooth
surface.
</P>
<P>
   There is unexpected beauty in the ordinary. In the exquisitely
textured ``Birdhouse and Wind Chimes,'' the hard peaked roof of the
wooden birdhouse is duplicated in the soft folds of the roof of a
fabric house, and the sharply defined chimes stand in marked
contrast to the blurred lines of the backdrop folds and the pale
gray shadows beyond.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of sweet, a number of the still lifes are strong and
austere, especially ``Morning Bells, 1994,'' with its mysterious
patches of light rising in an apex behind the bells, and ``Games in
the Sun, 1997,'' with its shadowed glass marbles.
</P>
<P>
   In this kindergarten, a peacock feather is anything but
ostentatious, and Kenna records it as a pared-down marvel, with
delicate tendrils flowing from a straight stem, atop which is a
cropped fan-shaped tuft of dark feathers.
</P>
<P>
   At times in his landscape photography, Kenna reduces what he
sees to minimalist abstractions, and in this show, ``Kinder Harp,''
too, shows an object that resembles an odd parking meter with a
transparent top and in it, thin parallel black lines. It seems that
in the silently alive Monique's kindergarten, things often have a
way of turning into something else.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBIT NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Monique's Kindergarten' remains at the Robert Mann Gallery, 42
E. 76th St., Manhattan, through Aug. 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
