<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9894 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-TECHNOLOGY-NYT &LR;      07-23 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-TECHNOLOGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET-SAVVY CAR TAKES COMPUTER FOR A RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Story is also moving in the ``a'' news
file.) 
(cb) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ What's the next big thing? To judge from many of the
concept cars at this year's auto shows, it is an on-board computer
that would allow a driver or passenger to log onto the Internet to
read or send e-mail, check stock quotes or get traffic reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler Corporation wants to give customers a chance to
surf the World Wide Web, too, but it has come up with a
bring-your-own approach to computing.
</P>
<P>
   One of Chrysler's showcase concepts this year, the Dodge ESX2,
has drawn attention for its lightweight body, which could be made
of polyethylene terephthalate, or P.E.T., the material used for
plastic soda bottles, and for its hybrid powertrain, which combines
a diesel engine and an electric motor. The ESX2 also takes an
unusual approach to on-the-road computing: Instead of permanently
installing a computer with Internet access, as other manufacturers
have done, Chrysler built in a docking station for a small,
portable computer. A user would plug in his or her own computer,
then use it to call up, say, real-time traffic reports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the ESX2, a hand-held Hewlett-Packard 620LX sits on a small
shelf in the center of the dashboard, secured by Velcro. In the
back of the computer is a Motorola module that uses an infrared
interface, similar to a television's remote control, to link the
computer to the car. Once the computer is docked in the car, the
driver can display menu choices that include the audio and climate
controls, traffic information, weather forecasts, Internet and
cellular phone connections and software that would give customers
remote control over devices at their homes, including appliances,
lights, sprinklers and security systems. A diagnostics option would
help to pinpoint any problem with the vehicle and provide
step-by-step instructions for simple repairs, like replacing a flat
tire.
</P>
<P>
   The driver selects choices from the menu by touch, though
computers like these will eventually be operated by voice commands.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler's approach has several advantages over the permanent
installation of a computer in a vehicle, Steve Buckley, an
electronics specialist for Chrysler, said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it helps to hold down the cost of an
Internet-capable car, because built-in computers and modems add
hundreds of dollars, perhaps more than $1,000, to the purchase
price. Chrysler says the docking station would cost no more than
$100. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hand-held computers, which have become increasingly popular
mass-market products, cost from $500 to $1,000. Most of these do
not currently come with modems for connecting to the Internet,
which add another $200 to $700.
</P>
<P>
   Flexibility is increased because the hand-held computer can do
double or triple duty: in the car, at the office, at home.
Chrysler's docking station is compatible with various computer
sizes and brands that use Microsoft's Windows CE operating system.
</P>
<P>
   And because the computer is not built in, the car would not
spend much of its useful life with an obsolete gadget imbedded in
the dashboard _ the digital equivalent of an eight-track tape deck.
The hand-held computer can be removed and replaced, its software
can be updated and features can easily be added long before the
vehicle itself is replaced. Pointing out how quickly computer
technology changes, Buckley said that within the 10 months he spent
developing the ESX2's docking station, he used three generations of
hand-held computers. Voice-recognition software was unavailable
when he started; it is now available and can be added on, which
would provide a boon to drivers who will be able to surf the Net
without looking away from the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally on my third home computer, but I can't afford
to buy a new car every time the computer technology becomes
obsolete,'' Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler plans to use the ESX2 to gauge consumer interest in the
in-car docking stations for hand-held computers. The module that
would make this kind of communication possible in existing
production cars and trucks could be installed as an after-market
option within two years, Chrysler said. The devices could be made
available through the company's dealerships. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
