<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Childress' `Gone' falters on visit to island of lost souls
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Childress has given novel readers some great moments
between book covers. In ``Crazy in Alabama'' (1993), he displayed a
genius for eliciting the grotesque and the grinnable out of our
American landscape. ``Gone for Good,'' however, is not so good,
partly because Childress strays from an American setting. On his
way to a concert, Ben ``Superman'' Willis, a super-famous rock star
in 1972, is forced to crash-land his plane on a tropical island
that is inhabited by famous people who have disappeared (Jimmy
Hoffa, Michael Rockefeller, Princess Anastasia, Amelia Earhart) or
died (Marilyn Monroe and JFK).
</P>
<P>
   Superman resists his Edenic surroundings and wants to return to
his shallow wife, a former Miss Southwest Louisiana, and his lonely
son living in Opelousas, La. Eventually, he gives in to Marilyn's
seductions for eight years. But things are not right on the island,
overseen by an unknown authority who wants to build a luxury hotel
for nefarious reasons. Superman, who learns to magically fly
without a plane, disastrously incites the population to revolt.
When his grown son comes searching for him, the result is a
``Twilight Zone'' episode gone astray.
</P>
<P>
   Childress, an Alabama native who lives in Costa Rica, is not
afraid of risks, but it's hard to grasp his view of pop culture in
this semiallegorical exploration of disappearance. It's telling
that the best scenes occur in Opelousas between his son and the
grandmother raising him. Childress' fiction flourishes better in
the likes of Jackson, Miss., than in the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Gone for Good.
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Childress. Knopf. $25. 370 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A novel about missing characters flies off course.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
