 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Remnick's posting elicits bit of envy, and much elation
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ihave a friend, one of the most polished writers I know, who has
the misfortune of measuring the trajectory of his career against
that of David Remnick. They started out together at The Washington
Post in the early '80s, both of them unknown and untested. Remnick
was a year younger, which has made it that much harder. There are
people who cannot see their own achievements because of someone
else's shadow. And Remnick's only lengthened. His name was turning
up everywhere _ over long, richly detailed articles filed from the
former Soviet Union, in the better magazines, in The New York
Review of Books.
</P>
<P>
   My friend, whom we'll call Jack, did not begrudge him a Pulitzer
Prize, which Remnick won in 1994 for his book ``Lenin's Tomb.'' Not
that Jack wept with happiness, but there wasn't much he could say.
</P>
<P>
   So I called Jack one day recently and said, ``Well, I guess you
saw who was named editor of The New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   From the other end of the line I heard in a low voice his
familiar, droll ``Yes, I did'' offered in weary acceptance of fate.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving an imprint on journalism
</P>
<P>
   If it was cruel of me, it was also perversely affectionate. As
wonderful a writer as Jack is, he's not David Remnick and neither
is anyone else. Now, alas, Remnick is no longer a writer but an
editor. It is the difference between a peacock and peahen. The one
dazzles, the other only enables him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But Remnick's dazzle was the kind that left an imprint, not the
transient flash of a showboat. He could write about seemingly
anyone and anything _ Joseph Brodsky to Michael Jordan, Ralph
Ellison to Boris Yeltsin, the Jewish Daily Forward to USA Today _
and do so with a depth and range unusual even in the best
journalism. There was firmness, not fluff, at the core.
</P>
<P>
   This, no doubt, explains the relief, even joy over his
appointment among those associated with The New Yorker. ``He's my
hero,'' Henry Louis Gates Jr., a frequent contributor, was telling
me a few months back. At the time, no one thought Tina Brown's
departure as editor was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of others, of course, doesn't assure The New
Yorker's future. Here is a magazine with a circulation of 800,000,
one whose history and distinctive typeface are synonymous with such
names as E.B. White and James Thurber, A.J. Liebling and Edmund
Wilson, and yet it's losing money. It's lost money for each of the
past 13 years, one more victim of a glutted magazine market and a
culture that expects to see celebrities on covers and smell perfume
on slick pages.
</P>
<P>
   In her seven years as editor, Brown tried to resuscitate a
magazine suffering from advanced atherosclerosis. She brought
touches of color without cheapening the magazine's appearance. She
brought more coverage of politics and pop culture. She brought to
its pages new writers, among them Remnick.
</P>
<P>
   Under Brown, The New Yorker was livelier, but it also lost a
certain heft. It's hard to recall more than a few articles of any
real consequence _ and many of those seem to have been written by
the man who, at only 39, is now editor.
</P>
<P>
   A shift to `deep reporting'
</P>
<P>
   Remnick is careful to credit the changes Brown brought. But he
also says he wants The New Yorker to thrive on more foreign
coverage and ``deep reporting,'' by which he presumably means the
meaty narratives of which he was a master. In his preface to ``The
Devil Problem and Other True Stories,'' a collection of journalism
published two years ago (much of it first appeared in The New
Yorker), he wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``We order and excite our mental lives with stories. Mostly,
they are the same stories over and over again. The tabloids (in
print and, now, on television) have their set of stories: the
wealthy brought low, betrayal in marriage and commerce, the murder
of the innocent, the humbling of the celebrity, the ordinary man's
triumph. They differ from the novels of, say, Dreiser, or the plays
of Shakespeare, in the richness of detail, the complexity of
thought and incident, the wealth of language, but in the story of
O.J. Simpson (the tabloid story of the millennium) there were
surely elements of `An American Tragedy' and `Othello.' There are
other textures of mental life _ the analytical, the pure emotions
of lust or rage _ but stories, the telling and listening, are much
of what we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people have an intuitive understanding of this. History
itself is a story, etymologically and otherwise. But the media
market congregates nowadays at the shallow end of the pool, where
stories appeal only to our baser instincts. For some of us, those
waters have been getting fouled and scummy. If David Remnick can
keep The New Yorker afloat and free of the spreading bacteria,
he'll be a hero not only to his admirers but to the privately
envious.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
