 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Why fight it? The weather is what it is
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old editorial writer on The Hartford (Conn.) Courant who
wrote that everybody talks about the weather but nobody does
anything about it should be living today. Nowadays everybody is
going crazy trying to conquer the weather. And I'm here to say I'm
very tired of it.
</P>
<P>
   I like weather _ all kinds _ and I have spent a lifetime
accepting it as it comes. No more. We substitute a fan for that air
conditioner in the living room since the conditioner doesn't do
anything much but whine.
</P>
<P>
   The fan blows all the papers off a table (I still haven't found
some of them) and is dangerous when the baby is around. It's the
kind of place he'd like to stick one of his pretty little pink
fingers. We try one of those reversible fans in the kitchen window,
and it ruins the air on the back porch. I move it to the back
porch, and it is so noisy, porch sitters have to rearrange their
chairs for any hope of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   At the office in July we wear sweaters. At least some of us do.
The young ones like being cold and joyfully expose their elegantly
tanned arms and legs to the arctic air that pours into our rooms
from some mysterious machine somewhere in the bowels of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   The weather prophets keep telling us how hot it is, as if we
weren't tough enough to take whatever weather comes our way. We
haven't always been comfortable, and I don't see why we should work
so hard to be comfortable now. It's July, for goodness' sake. Go
swimming, eat watermelon, sit on the porch and fan.
</P>
<P>
   The old Atlanta Constitution building on the corner of Alabama
and Forsyth streets aimed to be modern, although it was a wonderful
old Victorian pile with cupolas and elegant touches of marble on
its red brick exterior. Cool off the hired hands, somebody
directed, and they brought in oscillating fans and put them on
little shelves high up on the posts that held the floor above up.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't do much to cool us. The windows were open, and hot
air and train smoke blew in. But they were cheerful with their
little songs, and when you were struggling for a lead you could
turn your head back and forth with the rhythm of the oscillator.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody we knew in Mobile County when I was a child had an
electric fan _ and a lot of them didn't even have electricity. We
happened to have that from a waterwheel in the mill, but we didn't
use it up and wear it out trying to be cool. We sat on the open
porch and fanned and doused ourselves with oil of citronella to
ward off mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   A woman friend of mine said the other night, ``Whatever happened
to sweat?'' She wasn't talking about the kind that dews your brow
when you work in the yard or take a walk down the road. She
specified the kind that stained shirts and blouses and ruined your
new pongee frock when you walked down the street in the summertime.
I'm sure it's out there, but it has a lot to combat when all those
walkers come out of air-conditioned buildings numb with cold and
duck into their air-conditioned cars.
</P>
<P>
   All this will pass, I know. We'll have storms and floods and
cold winter winds one of these days. And I suppose we'll fight
nature's bounty there in our zeal to get comfortable. I have a
notion we should feel the weather, should be hot when it's hot and
cold when it's cold and wet when it rains.
</P>
<P>
   That comes from the old Mobile sea captain of whom I've written
before. He gave me his slogan. He ignored storm warnings and sailed
the Gulf of Mexico when he had business to do so. His slogan: ``God
makes the weather and I make the trips.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
