<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLINGCRUISE-COX     07-23 2032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CRUISE-COX &HT;    `Cruise to Nowhere'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS -- In the Show Lounge of the Enchanted Capri cruise
ship on a Friday afternoon, a grandmother swirls her beige bra in
the air to the cheers of a rowdy crowd of heartlanders and Bible
Belters.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, this is before the cross-dressing fashion show or the
virgin sacrifices. Before I'm served eggdrop soup with Vienna
sausages floating in it. I haven't yet heard the very, very
international staff sing ``Hoppy Bur-day'' in perfect monotone for
the 15th time in the dining room. And the on-board casino, the
raison d'etre for this seabound bacchanal, hasn't even opened yet.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I realized that gambling is about the most wholesome
activity the Enchanted Capri has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   But let's start at the beginning. A few hours earlier, this ship
left New Orleans for what's known in the gaming industry as a
``Cruise to Nowhere,'' a two-day excursion into international
waters, where gambling can go on without a state license. That's a
real plus when sailing out of Louisiana, where the number of gaming
licenses is capped at 15 statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises to Nowhere are new to these parts, but they have been
setting sail from Florida's ports for several years, and one now
leaves from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gained popularity as
</P>
<P>
   gambling has picked up as a mainstream pastime as a more
legitimate way to spend money,'' says Les McMackin, marketing
director for Casino America, which operates four Isle of Capri
Casinos in the South _ and one on board the Enchanted Capri.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, this is my first cruise, so I have nothing to
compare it to. And part of the weirdness of this particular cruise
is due to some glitches that still need fixing. This is only the
second month the Enchanted Capri has been afloat. No doubt the
dining room staff, virtuallyouldn't communicate with each other
during an emergency drill. On one of the first sails, the crew
loaded bags of garbage into the cargo hold instead of luggage and
forgot the keys to many of the cabins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems with the language? That would be an understatement,''
says McMackin.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he notes, although rigorous staff training is starting
to pay off, he's not ready to offer complimentary trips to his Isle
of Capri high rollers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make a good impression when they come on board,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Head goes here
</P>
<P>
   After setting sail at 3 p.m. _ an hour late _ I stuff myself at
the lunch buffet, settle into my first frozen drink and seek out an
English-speaking crew member to ask when we will reach
international waters. To everyone's surprise, the answer is 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long time,'' huffs Calmeater Jones, who flew in from
Chicago to meet her sister _ Janie Hicks of New Orleans _ for the
cruise. Hicks takes a look at the casino and declares it rather
puny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was gonna take up more of the ship,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It may look small, especially with the lights off, but there are
200 slot machines, several black jack tables and a craps table. All
that for 230 cabins _ a much higher ratio than you'll find on a
regular cruise ship, assures McMackin.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do until 10 p.m.?
</P>
<P>
   Back to grandma and her bra. Cruise Director Walter Elvy has
corralled everyone into the Show Lounge for ``Afternoon Madness,''
a sort of raunchy scavenger hunt. Passengers gather into teams and
deliver what Elvy requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a lipstick!'' he shouts, and teams dig through purses
and stampede forward, tubes in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need the shirt off a man's back, and he has to keep it off
for the rest of the game!''
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts and golf shirts fly over heads, unleashing beer bellies
of mythic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I need a warm, worn bra, and the woman who was wearing
it's gotta bring it up,'' Elvy says, his voice turning slightly
sinister. His crowd falls into a daquiri-induced frenzy. Women of
all ages and sizes lunge at him, struggling out of their bras while
barely keeping their shirts on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna give away a bottle of champagne to the largest bra
in the house!''
</P>
<P>
   There are several contenders, including Grandma, who performs a
mini burlesque show as she wiggles out of her 38C. But another
woman has this contest sewn up. She walks up, chest rolling like
waves, and presents Elvy with the prize winner _ a 44D in light
blue denim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoah! Right here baby!'' he shouts, waving the bra in the
air. ``Now, I wanna see a man in a bra, earrings and lipstick, and
his shirt's gotta be off!''
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of men in the audience game enough for this
test. After being strapped into borrowed underclothes, the men
parade around like Shriners at a lingerie sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanna see a VIRGIN!''
</P>
<P>
   College girls bounce up, smiling as chastely as they can. One
woman comes forward, her 8-year-old daughter in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now here's a virgin! Who wants her?'' Elvy says. The little
girl smirks and runs back to her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Oh the humanity. Children aren't allowed in the casino, but they
can be sacrificed to a hungry crowd of gamblers-in-waiting. A woman
in the front row sums it up:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better than the Jerry Springer Show!''
</P>
<P>
   Head goes here
</P>
<P>
   Wanna sober up quick? Try a ``muster drill.'' After Elvy's
games, the loud speakers announce that passengers must return to
their cabins, don bulky orange life vests, and proceed to an
assigned deck. Gives you a new appreciation for the passive
emergency run-through you get on an airplane. All 400 of us stand
in the scorching sun _ without our drinks, by the way, because we
were instructed to leave them behind _ and line up, women and
children first. We are still on the river, but the oil refineries
have disappeared and swampland surrounds us as we make our way down
the last fingers of land that stretch off of south Louisiana. The
open sea can't be far off.
</P>
<P>
   I look down at my vest and notice a hammer and sickle emblem and
the letters ''USSR.'' I later find out the folks steering and
engineering this ship are Ukranian. I try to talk to one who is
doing maintenance work on the bow. He looks at me dazed: ``No
English.''
</P>
<P>
   Head goes here
</P>
<P>
   ``On regular cruise ships, casinos are a diversion as opposed to
a destination,'' says Jim Sullivan, head of Commodore Cruise Lines,
the boat part of this casino/boat joint venture. ``On this ship,
the casino is a much more significant part of the trip. This is a
new formula and we have created a tremendous amount of synergy
combining what the casino people do well with what we do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Synergy. Cool. I check my watch. Almost time for dinner!
</P>
<P>
   In the dining room _ think Soviet banquet hall meets hospital
cafeteria _ I see that everyone has made up for lost drinking time
since the muster drill. Dominating our side of the room is a table
of eight 20-something girls from Lafayette, La., who have lost all
capacity to talk in normal voices and are screaming at each other
and everyone else. They've also taken to calling their waiter,
Jesus from the Dominican Republic, by the American pronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Hey-soos,'' he begs.
</P>
<P>
   But they bellow, ``JESUS! More wine over here, hey! JESUS
CHRIST, more rolls!!!''
</P>
<P>
   I am at a more sedate table.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five children,'' says Earline Caruso, with a big
smile. She tells us she's from a suburb of New Orleans. Her
husband, Steve, nods. She mentions the size of her family 25 times
over the course of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   David Wagner, a quiet psychologist in a wing-collared tuxedo
shirt with sequined saxophones at the button holes, used to be a
professional gambler. ``I paid my way through graduate school in
illegal card games around New Orleans,'' he says. He shares a nice
little story about a woman who had a heart attack during a game
many years ago. And how the other players suggested putting her out
in the street before calling 911, so they wouldn't get busted.
``Instead, we just hid the cards and pretended we were having a
birthday party,'' he says. ``She was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about 9:30 p.m. when the waiters parade through the dining
room with flaming baked Alaskas on their heads, singing ``Ole Ole
Ole Ole!'' They run out of the dessert before getting to our table.
Apparently an entire table didn't even get their entrees.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares? The casino has opened!
</P>
<P>
   The machines are singing. Bells are ringing. The smoke is thick.
The machines are paying out, and players are squealing delightedly
with good frequency.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 minutes at the black jack table, Wagner wins enough to
cover the price of his cruise ticket _ $150.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when to stop,'' he says coolly. He may know, but he
doesn't stop _ he plays the rest of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Calmeater Jones wins $900 the first night. Earline Caruso wins
$300, enough to buy Nintendo for her kids. ``I love my kids,'' she
says, pulling the handle on the ``Filthy Rich'' slot machine.
</P>
<P>
   I lose $20 in two minutes. I don't want to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   While the Carusos, Wagner and most other cruisers burn out and
go to bed around midnight, the hard core gamblers press on.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Magill from Lawrence, Kansas, plays until 2 a.m. and is
up again at 4 a.m., going back and forth between the craps table
and the slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just fun, and my husband's so noisy, I couldn't sleep,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   And how's her luck?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, just up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 8:30 a.m. on Saturday, Magill's husband, daughter and
son-in-law have come into the casino and stand behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my breakfast team has arrived,'' she says. ``I'll be
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   They hesitate, then leave her. She throws the dice a few more
times, then goes to breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you later,'' says the dealer, Janice Spraggons of England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you will!''
</P>
<P>
   John Springer from Houston plays most of the night too. He built
his own craps table at home, says his wife, Rhonda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice all the time,'' she says. ``He does all the fancy
stuff. I just roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelique Rushing, from Gonzalez, Louisiana, plays long and late
as well.Though she says she doesn't really know how to play craps _
she just rolls the dice _ the chips begin to stack up in front of
her.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday afternoon, far from shore in the Gulf of Mexico,
luck dries up.
</P>
<P>
   Jones loses the $900 she won last night. Rushing loses as well.
``Still up and down,'' says Magill, but she sounds a lot more down
than up.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little quieter at dinner Saturday; hangovers and losses
are having a subduing effect.
</P>
<P>
   But there are an unusual number of birthdays in the room. The
waiters have to rush from one table to the next, barely having time
to run into the kitchen and dip into what must be an endless supply
of sprinkle-covered birthday cakes. I overhear someone admit their
birthday was actually last month. I wonder aloud if maybe all this
practice will help the staff find the proper key. Then, just to
entertain myself, I order up a cake for the Carusos, who told me
their anniversary was last month.
</P>
<P>
   The cake comes with ``Happy Birthday'' written on it, but the
staff does remember to say ``Anniversary'' in their song. The
Carusos seem genuinely touched.
</P>
<P>
   Head goes here
</P>
<P>
   By 11 p.m. Saturday, we are approaching Louisiana waters. I am
in the casino, figuring the management will be dragging compulsive
gamblers out by their collars. But apparently, most folks have
already had enough. Or perhaps the ship's other activities have
become more alluring. The action tonight is outside by the pool,
where Elvy is running Conga lines and limbo contests.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, I wake up and look out my window. The French
Quarter drifts by. Home at last.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend may sound like ``The Love Boat'' meets ``The
Twilight Zone.'' But I'm already making plans for a return trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Enchanted Capri sails from New Orleans every Friday.
Reservations required. Cost, per cabin, for two nights at sea and
all meals, ranges from $159-$499. Information: 800-843-4753.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
