<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAPPER-DUPRI-COX     07-23 1698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPPER-DUPRI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Record exec Dupri takes mike on solo `Life in 1472'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- There's real life and then there are rap lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   But with Jermaine Dupri _ the man whom MTV calls ``the mayor of
Atlanta'' and whom Mariah Carey goes to for hits _ there appears to
be little difference.
</P>
<P>
   The interview begins. Dupri switches on the radio in his BMW
735i. And as if his life were being orchestrated by the
manipulative director in ``The Truman Show,'' Dupri's voice, on his
current No. 17 single, ``Money Ain't a Thing,'' just happens to be
on:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Ferrari or Jaguar switching four lanes with the top
down, screaming out, `Money Ain't a Thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most rappers boast about the platinum Rolex and Land Rover they
don't have. Dupri _ already a millionaire _ has had a few of each.
He's been a successful producer for more than five years _ with
acts ranging from R&AMP;B's latest sensation Usher to Da Brat, the
first female rapper to sell a million albums. He's president of the
Atlanta-based So So Def record label. And now, with the release
last week of his first solo album, ``Life in 1472,'' he's a rapper.
</P>
<P>
   There are going to be benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And behind the two gates that lead to his Fayetteville home,
voila, benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The red Land Rover Dupri actually owns is near the entrance to
the pool. That's just behind the large but comfortable house he
shares with his mother, Tina. It's just up the street, by the way,
from Evander Holyfield's, er, home.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned Ferrari (this one's black) is backed against
the open three-car garage, where his Rottweilers are caged and two
of his racks of clothes are housed. The camel colored Jaguar XJ6
convertible is opposite the Land Rover, next to the white
convertible Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and when Dupri extends his hand to greet you on this day
it's with a tattooed arm lit up at the wrist by a platinum Rolex.
</P>
<P>
   In his lingo, money ain't a thang. But respect is.
</P>
<P>
   The release of ``Life in 1472,'' ``is kind of just to show
people I can do this,'' says the 25-year-old Dupri, switching lanes
on I-85 north.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't know all the things I've done,'' he
continues in a tone that's more ``oh well'' than cocky. ``People
always want to foil me ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Foil'' is a verb Dupri uses often. A certain music magazine
didn't want to put him on the cover because they ``wanted to foil
me like I don't have a history in this business.'' Rap Sheet did
put him on the cover, but with the dubious headline ``The Hardest
Working Producer You Don't Know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not underappreciated. Anybody in this world, this Puffy
world, is underappreciated,'' says Keith Clinkscales, president of
Vibe magazine, referring to the omnipresent producer-rapper-label
president and Dupri peer, Sean ``Puff Daddy'' Combs. ``And unless
you completely Puff yourself out, it's going to be hard to be
appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is Jermaine's work all across the board has been
exceptional,'' he continues. ``JD (Dupri's nickname) is just one of
these guys people feel. His ability to spot talent and make things
happen going all the way back to Kris Kross is just awesome. And
he's really done a solid thing with So So Def, the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Dupri's now passing by the Day-Glo So So Def
billboard he's renting along I-85. If you're headed downtown from
the airport it's the one on the right with the guy with the big
Afro. As if you could miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put that up there so people know Atlanta is the home of So
So Def Records,'' explains Dupri, using almost the exact words on
the billboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a name for this story yet?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the headline should read, `the heartbeat of Atlanta'.
That's what I'm starting to tell people. That's my new slogan.
Because I keep Atlanta's name in my music and I keep this city on
people's minds musically.''
</P>
<P>
   These days that's pretty hard to contest. While his peer,
Atlantan Dallas Austin co-produced the current No. 1pop and R&AMP;B
Brandy/Monica hit ``The Boy Is Mine,'' Austin's focus on his
now-defunct Freeworld Records has turned the volume down on the
Grammy nominee's career. Grammy-nominated producers Organized
Noize, also Atlantans, had a lot of momentum after TLC's
``Waterfalls,'' En Vogue's ``Don't Let Go (Love)'' and the Outkast
and Goodie Mob projects. But judging by Goodie Mob's current chart
status _ the gold-selling album they produced is at No. 37 on the
R&AMP;B album chart _ they seem to be sputtering.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri, on the other hand, is responsible for the current single
by Aretha Franklin (``Here We Go Again''), No. 28 on the R&AMP;B
charts; the first single from Monica's new CD (``First Night'');
and the gold-selling, No. 13 R&AMP;B ballad by his own So So Def
quartet, Xscape (``The Arms of the One Who Loves You''). And that's
all in addition to his own CD, which should be on the charts this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jermaine's just coming with the hot records,'' pronounced R&AMP;B
teen vocalist Monica.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the man can do no wrong,'' adds Usher, with whom
Dupri penned ``You Make Me Wanna,'' ``Nice and Slow'' and current
No. 3 pop release, ``My Way.''
</P>
<P>
   On MTV, sometime ``Jams'' host/radio personality Angie Martinez
introduces Dupri as ``the mayor of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dupri is treated like it when he reaches Buckhead restaurant
Pricci. It's prime waiting list time but he is greeted by four of
the employees _ all standing at the host table as if about to be a
part of a military inspection _ and is escorted to a table with a
view of nearly the entire room.
</P>
<P>
   After two Shirley Temples and a salmon filet he flattens into
his mashed potatoes with his fork, he's ready to stomach, and deal
with, some of the less flattering comments made about his work.
First, the most popular barb: ``Jermaine Dupri is just trying to be
like Puffy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people just want to see me and Puffy have a problem. They
just want to start something. And that's real stupid to me because
we're the people that's providing the music. Why do they want
something to happen to both of us so that stops?
</P>
<P>
   But to answer the question ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah I admire all that Puffy's done. And yeah when I saw him
go out front and do his thing last year _ big _ I thought this
might be the time. But I check out what everybody in the game is
doing. I take all of that in, and I do my music my way.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to Dupri and his family, he had the opportunity to
move center stage long before Combs came out with his first single
``Can't Nobody Hold Me Down.'' Hip-hop legend has it that when
Dupri's father put the then-10-year-old on stage to dance during a
Diana Ross concert, the star was born.
</P>
<P>
   But as his father recalls, 1985 was the year he could have
started as a rapper. ``During the Fresh Festival in '84 he was like
the opening act, a mascot,'' said Michael Mauldin, who let his only
son tour with him while he worked as an artist manager. ``And I
allowed him the freedom to kind of socialize a bit. A little bit.
Because he was only 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he turned 13 Dupri had written a song with MC Shy-D,
called ``It's Me.'' ``I got the track finished for him, and I think
when the Fresh Festival was in Cleveland, he performed it. He had a
whole little routine for that one song. With a wardrobe change _
well he changed his jacket _ and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks started then about signing Dupri to a deal, claims
Mauldin, now president of black music at Columbia Records (Maxwell,
The Fugees). ``But they just couldn't get a deal to me that made
sense. So right or wrong I just decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin pauses, as if he still wonders if he could have chosen
an even better career path for his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he finally concludes, ``with the career this kid
has had I think we made the right choice. He's finally gonna be out
there doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   And doing it only once, Dupri claims. Headed south now back
towards the house, Dupri insists this turn as an artist will simply
be completing a circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done everything,'' the 25-year-old says.'' ``I was a
dancer first. I became a successful producer and have remained a
successful producer. So I guess that completes that entertainment
circle and I'll just go back to producing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no energy to be an artist, and after `Life In 1472',
the album and the movie do what they're going to do, I won't be
doing this artist thing again,'' repeats Dupri. ``I wanted to be an
artist like years ago. But then I fell in love with producing and
creating other artists. Telling them what to do and watching it
work. Kris Kross was an image made from my mind. (So So Def rapper
Da) Brat is an image of me in a girl's body. If I was a girl I
would have acted like Brat. And Usher is more like me if I was an
R&AMP;B artist.''
</P>
<P>
   And who is Jermaine Dupri as Jermaine Dupri?
</P>
<P>
   Well, after a while with him, you get the feeling the
5-foot-2-inch man thrives off this underdog vibe he emits. The ``I
ain't really big yet'' talk. ``People foil me.'' It keeps him
hungry for the next hit.
</P>
<P>
   An example: As he parks the BMW behind the same model he bought
for mom for Mother's Day, he won't get out of the car. His ear is
turned so close to the radio you would think it was about to play a
Jermaine Dupri- produced song for the very first time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, V-103 FM evening personality Greg Street is just
counting down his nightly ``Top Eight at 8.'' And during the ride
back, Dupri has been counting aloud how many songs he has on it.
Three so far. And it's down to the top position ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And the number one jam on the `Top Eight at 8' is ... `It's
All Good' by the Mo Thugs Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope, that wasn't produced by Dupri. Foiled again.
</P>
<P>
   Guess ``Life in 1472'' doesn't always mean you're number one.
``I'm just a little ghetto producer in College Park,'' Dupri laughs
as he heads towards his home studio.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Now which of your eight luxury automobiles are you taking
to that Vibe party downtown this evening?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
