<SLUG> BC-STYLE-SNAKESKIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slide into snakeskin for a richly textured look this summer
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    BY A. SCOTT WALTON / c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether it's real or faux, printed or embossed, a little bit of
snakeskin can go a long way toward giving your summer wardrobe new
bite. But the array of snakeskin styles available is wide enough to
rattle even the savviest shopper.
</P>
<P>
   If you like the look of snakeskin but don't know what style to
choose, be afraid. Be very afraid. The smart way to select clothes
with snakeskin motifs is to approach them with caution.
</P>
<P>
   Start with something small and relatively harmless; snakeskin
belts, wallets and eyeglass cases, for instance, make charming
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Next, take on something a bit bigger and more daring, such as a
handbag or pair of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Swope, the Atlanta-based general manager for Ticketmaster
Southeast, says she consistently gets favorable comments on her
strappy snakeskin sandals by Kenneth Cole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them because they're so fun and playful,'' Swope, 39,
says.
</P>
<P>
   She wears the sandals with a black-and-yellow floral dress by
Betsey Johnson or with a business suit and coordinating jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wear them forever because they look so timeless,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   The time may come when you're tempted to wear more than
snakeskin accessories. If you simply can't resist serpentine suits
or separates, keep in mind that they must be worn with care.
</P>
<P>
   Snakeskin patterns don't mix or match easily. A safe way to go
is to pair a patterned piece with a solid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
