</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BEHAVIOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Derivative teen flick promises scares, depth but never delivers
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens whenever something makes money: The hot new product
is followed by a flood of cheap knockoffs. Think Cabbage Patch
dolls and Tamagotchis.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the goods are made of celluloid. ``Scream''
started it, resurrecting the teen horror flick. The same thing
happened 20 years ago, when ``Halloween'' scared the pants off the
Clearasil set. But by the mid-1980s, that movie's own bad sequels
and the endless tawdry encores from Freddy Krueger and Jason sealed
the genre back inside its crypt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because the sharp ``Scream'' and ``Scream 2'' _ plus the
mediocre ``I Know What You Did Last Summer'' _ raked in bucks, here
comes an onslaught of teenagers-in-peril movies ... with
ever-diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: ``Disturbing Behavior,'' a high-concept pitch with
zero follow-through. It's ``The Stepford Teens,'' with a touch of
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers,'' ``Heathers'' and ``A Clockwork
Orange.'' It's supposed to be scary and funny, but isn't either
one, and it doesn't have a single original moment.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, James Marsden plays Steve, a newcomer to
small-town Cradle Bay. At his high school, he encounters a
letter-jacketed band of frighteningly clean-cut teens who call
themselves the Blue Ribbons. They hang out at the yogurt shop like
a band of fascist Archies and, with the help of the school
psychiatrist (Bruce Greenwood), ``recruit'' a new classmate into
their group every few days.
</P>
<P>
   There's a satire trying to get out here. ``Behavior'' wants to
celebrate the pierced, tattooed slackers who reject things like
academic achievement and showers. But the movie is too busy
offering fake scares and generic teen-clique jokes to give its
premise any spin.
</P>
<P>
   At least the movie has some of the polish of ``The X-Files,''
thanks to series composer Mark Snow and director David Nutter. And
Vancouver, British Columbia, contributes its familiar drizzly, dank
menace. But there's nothing inside this slick package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disturbing Behavior''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring James Marsden and Katie Holmes. Directed by David
Nutter. Rated R for profanity, violence and simulated fellatio. 1
hour, 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Disturbingly lame.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
