<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-CLOCKWATCHERS-     07-23 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CLOCKWATCHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A temp's-eye view of corporate culture
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kafka may be long dead, but the Kafkaesque corporate hell he
conjured up so expertly is still with us. Thus, ``Clockwatchers,''
a kind of Gen-X ``9 to 5'' that applies a subversive wit and a
funky slacker mentality to that organized abuse commonly known as
the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Our focus is on four young women who work as temps at Global
Credit. They strive mightily to keep their sense of themselves (and
their sense of humor) intact as toxic Muzak pours through the
dehumanizing maze of sterile cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   Iris (Toni Collette from ``Muriel's Wedding'') is the new girl
and our narrator. She's befriended by the three other temps, whose
lowly status makes them veritable lepers in the eyes of the
full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   Paula (Lisa Kudrow) is a leggy blonde with acting aspirations
that seem more talked about than acted upon. Jane (Alanna Ubach) is
the least worried about her career. She has an out, the culturally
sanctioned escape route known as a fiance and a wedding date. Their
ringleader is Margaret (Parker Posey), who keeps herself from going
ballistic by committing random acts of rebellion and minor
sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   This girl gang of four bond over happy-hour chicken wings and
shared grievances. Their unity is reinforced when a new young woman
is hired. She's full-time and permanent, and therefore a common
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Jill Sprecher has made a small-scale, wickedly
savvy film that should appeal to anyone who's ever felt a wave of
nausea when summoned to the obligatory employee of the month
awards. She knows the territory well, from the long hours with
nothing to do but look busy (at one point, Kudrow paints her
fingernails with white-out) to the small-minded middle managers who
so obligingly adopt a kiss-up/kick-down attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Sprecher also knows that life doesn't usually imitate the
movies. When one character is unfairly given the boot _ ``You can't
fire me; you don't even know my name!'' she protests _ no one pulls
a ``Spartacus'' on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The picture gets somewhat sidetracked by a who's-the-culprit
plot about petty thefts; it's far better when it sticks to the
subtle nuances of the typical dysfunctional corporate family.
Still, its insights are often priceless and its cast dead-on.
</P>
<P>
   Especially Posey, who embodies every overqualified employee ever
stuck in a moronic job and forced to smile at doubly moronic
supervisors. She turns high-strung self-awareness into an art form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clockwatchers''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Parker Posey, Lisa Kudrow and Toni Collette. Directed
by Jill Sprecher. Rated PG-13 for language. 1 hour, 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A wicked take on workplace hell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
