<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-JEALOUSY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director's comedic gift shines in `Jealousy'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he proved in his debut feature, ``Kicking and Screaming,''
Noah Baumbach is a filmmaker with an ear for funny dialogue and an
eye for tender hearts. His sophomore effort, ``Mr. Jealousy,'' is a
Manhattan-set comedy of insecurity in which love sometimes finds a
way and sometimes doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are semi-neurotic romantics, less like people out
of a Woody Allen film than people who grew up watching Woody Allen
films. Lester (Eric Stoltz) is a would-be writer with a humongous
jealous streak he recognizes but can't control. His new love,
Ramona (Annabella Sciorra), is a vivacious art historian, working
her way through school by conducting tours at the Brooklyn Museum.
She's also someone with a jam-packed romantic past; by Lester's
count, she's had 26 lovers before him.
</P>
<P>
   His jealous nature gets the better of him. Discovering that one
of her exes is Dashiell Frank (Chris Eigeman), a writer who's been
dubbed ``the voice of his generation,'' Lester weasels his way into
Dashiell's therapy group. Complications ranging from mistaken
identity to mixed-up lovers ensue.
</P>
<P>
   The picture's major failing is that the complications don't
enrich either Baumbach's characters or his themes. The escalating
deceptions move toward the brittleness of farce rather than the
emotional satisfaction of romantic comedy. But the well-written
characters provide some balance, as do a number of well-sketched
(and well-played) smaller roles: Bridget Fonda as Eigeman's
stuttering girlfriend, director Peter Bogdanovich as the group's
therapist, Marianne Jean-Baptiste (``Secrets &AMP; Lies'') as someone's
fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the film is brimming with the sort of witty references
that don't call attention to themselves in that
aren't-we-smart-New-Yorkers way.
</P>
<P>
   Think of ``Mr. Jealousy'' as the sort of accomplished, pleasant
diversion that makes you look forward to whatever Baumbach does
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jealousy''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eric Stoltz and Annabella Sciorra. Directed by Noah
Baumbach. Rated R for language. At Tara. 1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A small-scale, smart-talking charmer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
