</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-RYAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Saving Private Ryan' stunningly combines the glory and horror,
the heroism and madness of war
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hell doesn't begin to describe the war that Steven Spielberg
shows us in his superb new film, ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Nor do
the conventional words usually attached to war movies apply. The
director has reinvented the World War II film and imbued it with
the hallucinatory horrors typically associated with Vietnam movies,
while hewing strongly to the traditional soldier-on courage and
common-man decency we've long associated with ``the last good
war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' can in no way be called a pro-war movie;
it's too crammed with blood 'n' guts reality for that. At the same
time, it's not precisely anti-war, either. Spielberg never condemns
nor condescends to the soldiers who fought. Rather, he comes to
praise them and, of necessity, to bury them, with honors. And
sadness.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins where most movies would end, with a stunning,
hold-onto-your-hats, cover-your-eyes re-creation of the Allied
invasion of Normandy on D-Day. It is, perhaps, the most powerful
combat sequence ever put on film _ a plunge into the inferno as
Spielberg and his cinematographer, Janusz Kaminski, inundate us
with the blood, terror and sheer chaos of the assault. Intestines
ooze and the sea turns red with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Death isn't just horrifying here; it's horrifyingly random.
There's no reason why one man makes it and another doesn't. That
randomness _ that death is neither proud nor picky _ remains with
us throughout the picture.
</P>
<P>
   After the D-Day landing, Spielberg introduces his plot proper.
Among the survivors are Capt. John Miller (Tom Hanks) and his men.
In a nice bow to tradition, the squad comprises what critic Pauline
Kael once called ``a '40s-movie bomber-crew cast'': the
wisecracking, cynical New Yorker (Edward Burns); the hunky,
kind-hearted Italian-American (Vin Diesel); the rock-solid sergeant
(Tom Sizemore); the I-know-what-you're-doing-to-my-relatives Jew
(Adam Goldberg); the calm, conscientious medic (Giovanni Ribisi);
the seemingly fearless Bible Belt sharpshooter (Barry Pepper); and
the new addition, a translator (Jeremy Davies) who's never been in
combat before.
</P>
<P>
   Their assignment is to bring back alive a paratrooper, one Pvt.
James Ryan (Matt Damon). His three brothers have been killed in
action, and that multiple tragedy, according to top brass, has
earned him a ticket home. But his rescuers wonder, and grumble
about, whether he'll still be alive when they find him. And, if so,
why is his life worth risking all of theirs?
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Tennyson wrote, ``Theirs is not to reason why.'' So
they trudge onward. As they do, their various encounters,
adventures and skirmishes strangely recall ``Apocalypse Now'' _
different objectives, different wars, different directors,
different audiences. Yet the goal remains the same: Accomplish the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in their journey, ``Saving Private Ryan'' also
becomes a movie about saving Capt. Miller. Or, maybe, what's left
of Capt. Miller. Hanks' incandescent performance, a masterwork of
subtle emotionality, lays it right on the line. If this decent man,
who's a natural leader yet can't keep his hand from shaking,
manages to make it home, just who is coming home? Can he, after
this life-altering experience, ever be the person he was before he
was cast into this charnel house?
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's one misstep is a present-day prologue and epilogue
in which a veteran visits a military grave. It's a neat bit of
diversionary-tactic filmmaking, but, heartfelt as they are, the
bookended scenes don't have the appalling poetry of what happens in
between.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's a very minor quibble. ``Saving Private Ryan'' weds
the action-savvy Spielberg of ``Jaws'' to the ethical, reflective
Spielberg of ``Schindler's List.'' After seeing this movie, you'll
know not only how we won the war, but how we fought it _ one day,
one life, one incalculable act of heroism at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tom Hanks, Directed by Steven Spielberg. Rated R for
extreme violence and some vulgar language. At metro theaters. 2
hours, 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Part gung-ho heroism, part in-your-face horror
show, Spielberg's masterful film is World War II as you've never
seen it before.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
