<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: All bridesmaids can do is wish couple the best
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman who is having a bridesmaid luncheon for 25 at some spot
in Michigan called the other day to ask me if I knew the history of
bridesmaid luncheons and if I could give her some other interesting
details to enliven the occasion. I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   I was a bridesmaid once, but there was no luncheon. Our police
reporter on The Mobile(Ala.) Press and the assistant society editor
had been visibly in love for some time, and late one day they
decided to get married. ``Come go with us,'' they said to me. ``You
can be maid of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   I went happily _ until the bride looked at my wrinkled voile
dress and said, ``I should have given you time to change clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth was that I didn't have anything special to change to.
The voile, wrinkled or not, was as good as I had. But they had a
wonderful marriage, which ended in death for both of them only a
few years ago. I used to baby-sit their first child, and later on a
trip through Chicago on the way to the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota, I
met their second daughter, a beautiful girl.
</P>
<P>
   In time, I lost touch with my friend, the ex-society writer, but
the police reporter went into advertising, grew prosperous with his
own agency and, better still, helped launch Alcoholics Anonymous
throughout the country. He'd come to Atlanta on AA business and
always visit us. He told me about his experience with AA. Reared a
Catholic, he had departed the church, if not the faith, and become
a pretty bad drunk.
</P>
<P>
   His alcoholism cost him his agency and friends, but not his good
wife. She stood by and when he hit bottom, she was there to help
pick him up. He told me in graphic detail of that moment. He had
been drunk for days, he said, and had ended up in a vacant,
dilapidated building on Chicago's Skid Row. He was huddled on the
floor, freezing and vomiting, he said, and he finally did what he
had eschewed since childhood. He prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `God help me,''' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   I guess he dozed off or lapsed into unconsciousness, because
when he came to, his wife and an AA friend were with him and had
begun to get him out of the dump. He began going to AA meetings,
and before long he was an inspiration and a help to other drunks.
When he would come to Atlanta, he had returned to being a handsome,
well-dressed man with a prosperous business to back him up, and he
was still proud of his daughters and in love with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I saw him, he had visited us on 13th Street and
called a cab to take him back to his hotel _ the old Winecoff, I
think. I went out to the curb, and he hugged me and said,
``Goodbye, bridesmaid. You did a wonderful job.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I had nothing to do with it, except that I loved them
both and was happy in their happiness. That may be the historic
role of bridesmaids. I didn't think to say that to my caller about
the Michigan luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   When my front room tenant, Ann Wood, married Martin Waldron
(both were of our staff, but later of other newspapers, including
The New York Times), I went to Ann's home in Birmingham to lend a
hand _ I thought. Her mother had been ill, but about all I could do
was meet people at the airport and pick up the cake. Ann had a
luncheon for her bridesmaids (I wasn't there), but they hadn't
worked out their attire.
</P>
<P>
   I can hear her wailing, ``What are we going to do with the
bridesmaids' heads?''
</P>
<P>
   None of our suggestions _ hats, veils, flowers _ worked. Finally
Martin, wearying of the subject, said, ``May I suggest that you
serve them on trays?''
</P>
<P>
   We all had an unfortunate picture of pretty girls walking into
church with their heads on trays like Salome with John the
Baptist's. It ended the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they are wise who never, never ask my advice on social
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
