<HEADER>
A9924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDEN-ANNIVERSARIES-     07-23 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-ANNIVERSARIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The best years of their lives
 &HT;    By Marques G. Harper
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their eyes don't reveal any last-minute jitters or secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of love and marriage is simply told in the way they
hold each other's hands, standing in front of the rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Margol, who is 70, wears a white, two-piece outfit, no
veil, and carries a bouquet of deep pink roses. Her groom, Howard,
74, wears a simple black tuxedo.
</P>
<P>
   On their 50th wedding anniversary, they've gathered original
bridesmaids and groomsmen, friends and family to renew their vows
and celebrate their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like it to last a long time, but who's kidding
whom?'' Mrs. Margol says about the next 50 years of marriage. It's
the golden age of the golden anniversary, thanks to couples who,
like the Margols, got hitched soon after World War II. More than
6.1 million couples married from 1946 to 1948, paving the way for
the baby boom. In 1948, 1.8 million marriages took place, a number
that would not be matched again until 1966. With Americans living
longer, more couples are notching a half-century of togetherness.
Hallmark Cards took notice of World War II-era weddings in 1991
with a card for its anniversary lineup. The company expected to
sell more than 100,000 of the cards in 1996, a peak year for golden
anniversaries. (Nearly 2.3 million couples married in 1946.)
Instead, it sold 350,000. The newest addition to the lineup is a
card for couples who married just after the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time you live together for 50 years, you become bonded
in such a way,'' says Jackie Boles, a sociology professor at
Georgia State University. ``That is something in this day and time
to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with 10 years ago, more people are acknowledging their
50th anniversary by throwing parties, says Patrick Cuccaro,
president of Off-Premises Caterers Coalition, a group of metro
Atlanta caterers.
</P>
<P>
   And members of the most affluent over-65 generation ever are
more likely to shell out for golden anniversary celebrations, says
Brad Edmondson, former editor of American Demographics magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrations can be as casual as a buffet, Martha Stewart
advises in her magazine, as romantic as a weekend getaway or as
elaborate as the Margols' black-tie affair at the Academy of
Medicine in Midtown. Church receptions, family get-togethers _ even
parties where guests are asked to dress in their military uniforms
from World War II _ are other ways that couples mark the occasion.
``People are going back to the church for the wedding and the
50-year receptions,'' says Windsor Jordan, owner of Mary Jordan
Caterers. ``They are getting back to the honor of being together
for 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   When selecting a party theme, consider pegging it to favorite
movies or events from the time period, suggests Barbara Roos, owner
of Event Design Group, an Atlanta party planner. ``We try to do a
walk through 50 years,'' she says. Bobbie and B.B. Wingo of
Hampton, who celebrated their golden anniversary this year, did so
amid magazines from 1948, wedding pictures and photos of their
children and grandchildren over the years.
</P>
<P>
   About 180 people attended the Wingos' celebration, including
friends, the best man and maid of honor at their wedding and
several members of McDonough Presbyterian Church, where the
reception was held.
</P>
<P>
   Roselyn Clay, one of the Wingos' daughters, says her mother
began thinking about the bash soon after celebrating her 45th
anniversary. Clay and her sisters started planning their parents'
golden anniversary about a year ago. In early 1997, Clay, 49, and
her sisters also started making a quilt to give to their parents as
an anniversary gift. Each square represents their family's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got married, it was very small. It was at my home.
That's why I think the girls wanted this one to be a big affair,''
says Mrs. Wingo, 69. Frank Thomas, an Atlanta lawyer, wasn't sure
how his parents, Frank and Joyce, wanted to celebrate their 50th
anniversary this year. He offered them a cruise or a trip to the
West Virginia resort where they honeymooned in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   They preferred an evening with friends, so Thomas, 47, and his
siblings threw an outdoor dinner for 98 people at his Buckhead
townhouse this year. ``I think anyone who makes it 50 years
deserves a medal,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ceremony at her party, Mrs. Margol, an energetic
mother of four and grandmother of seven, read from her husband's
old love letters and reminisced about the blind date that started
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``No e-mail in those days,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she switched to the final act of her show, introducing her
husband and their cast of bridesmaids and groomsmen. After renewing
their vows, the Margols kissed to seal their promise to love, honor
and cherish each other.
</P>
<P>
   As the Margols took the first dance to their favorite song,
``Moon River,'' niece Judy Landey gazed at the couple and said,
``It's like history repeats itself.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mr. Margol, the anniversary had a slightly different
meaning: ``We're celebrating the fact that we're still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
