<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-PARTYTIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Party ideas
 &HT;    By Marques G. Harper
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some suggestions for planning a 50th-anniversary party:
</P>
<P>
   -- A year is not too far in advance to start planning,
especially if you want to book an art museum or hotel ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   -- Consider the couple's personalities when deciding what type
of party to give. Unless it's a surprise party, consult them early
in the planning.
</P>
<P>
   -- Use old photos and font styles to create an invitation that
will set the tone of the party.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you're throwing a party with siblings, agree in advance on
a budget and how you're going to split the costs of the affair.
</P>
<P>
   -- For a nostalgic touch, ask guests to give speeches about the
couple. Create a scrapbook by asking friends and family to send in
letters, photos or memories before the party.
</P>
<P>
   -- Use photographs from the past 50 years as decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
