A9926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILITH-BLACKS-COX     07-23 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILITH-BLACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Learning to sing in `more than one voice': Tour adds Queen
Latifah's hip-hop to mix
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- First Lilith Fair had to prove that an all-female
bill could attract audiences. What kind of music the women sang was
almost secondary. And who bought tickets didn't matter as much as
that tickets got bought.
</P>
<P>
   So last year's inaugural tour came and went, and so did the
record-breaking audiences. Mission accomplished. The first mission,
that is. Now there's the matter of moving past the novelty; Lilith
was a pretty homogeneous event the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everybody was along the pop-folk vein,'' says
jazz-based vocalist Holly Cole, who is on this year's bill. ``And _
how do I put this? _ a lot of the people who came looked a lot like
the people onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Lilith founder Sarah McLachlan needed to do was
``help do the stereotyping the world has done a pretty good job of
already,'' Cole adds. ``Women have more than one voice, do more
than one kind of music.''
</P>
<P>
   And come in more than one color.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Lilith is acknowledging the blackness this year,'' says
rapper and actress Queen Latifah. In 1997, folk's Tracy Chapman and
jazz's Cassandra Wilson were part of the rotating lineup, but
neither are mainstream black artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hip-hop is still very much in that early rock 'n' roll state
of mind,'' says Latifah, 28. ``You think `hip-hop' and the general
public automatically thinks `male.' A hard-core,
grabbing-his-(genitals), not-smiling man who will only let a woman
on his side if she acts just like him. And I mean, I won't even get
into the misogyny and whatever people who don't listen to a lot of
rap think it's all about. To put it simply, the image of hip-hop is
`hard,' so that almost automatically doesn't say `woman.'''
</P>
<P>
   But it was within hip-hop culture that the Newark, N.J., native
grew up. And, female or not, ``when I felt this was what I wanted
to do, I was going for mine,'' says Latifah, who has just released
her fourth album, ``Order in the Court.'' ``It's been rough. You
know, first going out there into this male-dominated, male-minded
music and telling the women to stand upright and hold their own.
Then I started Flavor Unit (a management company) and there were
doubters. (I) went into acting, doubts. But you know, a lot of
women with ambition to do whatever face the same thing. The only
difference, I think, is that I started out in a business, in a kind
of music, in which many wrongly think it's almost mandatory to hate
women.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rebekah, a 25-year-old Cleveland native, her sex hasn't
been the issue; it's her race. ``Obviously I'm black, and when you
listen to my music, it becomes quite obvious that it's not music
typically done by black females,'' says the singer, whose debut is
titled ``Remember to Breathe.'' ``But people can't proceed from
there. Sometimes radio and retailers don't quite know what they
should do with me. They're like, `She doesn't sound like Brandy.'
So they put my record in the rap section.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I've been fighting people and stereotypes and it's taking
time, but I'm patient. It's working. This black girl playing rock
music is really starting to sink in.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Rebekah's people and Cole's people can share marketing
plans, as Cole faces a similar difficulty. ``When your music is a
hybrid based in jazz that branches off into country, rock, R&AMP;B and
blues, you're just asking for trouble in this business,'' says
Cole, 33. ``Asking for it. You're just too hard to pigeonhole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But business is not what I'm doing this for,'' continues the
vocalist, whose latest release is ``Dark Dear Heart.'' ``This is
not an artistic battle, it's a marketing battle. And frankly,
marketing is not my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Latifah, hip-hop's Missy (``The Rain'') and R&AMP;B's Erykah Badu
(``On &AMP; On''), all on the Lilith tour this year, do qualify as
mainstream black artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good, smart start,'' says Village Voice cultural
critic Greg Tate. ``The question now is, Will Erykah and Missy's
fans come out to a show that is still mostly not what they hear on
the radio? I don't think so. I think Lilith will still be
entertaining the same audience with a broader bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that progress?'' Tate asks rhetorically. ``But, oh well,
effort duly noted.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
