<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILITH-MAIN-COX     07-23 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILITH-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venus rising: Lilith acts find success
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Like its ethereal logo of Venus rising, the Lilith
Fair music festival has blossomed into much more than a celebration
of women. In its second year, Sarah McLachlan's all-female road
show, which pulls into the Lakewood Amphitheatre today, has taken
on mythic proportions as one of the most significant events in the
history of pop music.
</P>
<P>
   An overblown assessment? Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Women have always had a presence in rock, pop and rhythm and
blues, from the sweet soul sounds of the Supremes to Janis Joplin's
sandpaper screams to Madonna's crotch-grabbing. But they have never
dominated music charts or generated the tour revenues of their male
counterparts. No matter how popular she got, Stevie Nicks could
never catch up with Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   ``When programming music, we were always told that it wasn't
good to play two females back to back,'' says Leslie Fram, program
director of Atlanta new-rock station WNNX-FM. ``They thought it
would be confusing, that all female voices blended together. But
how could that possibly be more confusing than two male artists
played back to back? But I can tell you that the average radio
listener can tell the difference between Sheryl Crow and Sarah
McLachlan.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, tour promoters (mostly male) considered most female
artists the ``chick opening act,'' and few women could fill concert
arenas as headliners. That, in turn, often meant they weren't able
to tap into the big money or exercise significant control over
their own careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single day was a fight,'' recalls 1980s pixie rocker Pat
Benatar. ``Only one woman was allowed, so there was so much
competition and no camaraderie among women artists whatsoever. We
were the first daughters of the women of the women's movement, and,
for us, everything was a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 things changed. For the first time, female artists had
more hits on the Top 20 music charts than men. It was the year of
the Strong Solo Woman: Toni Braxton, Mariah Carey, Celine Dion,
Alanis Morissette, Wynonna and Shania Twain. The next year, against
opposition from tour promoters, McLachlan launched Lilith Fair,
which surprised the music world by becoming the
second-highest-grossing concert tour of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening with women and Lilith Fair is every bit as
revolutionary as when Elvis went into the Sun Records studio with
Scotty (Moore) and Bill (Black),'' says James Dickerson, a music
journalist and author of the new book ``Women on Top: The Quiet
Revolution That Is Rocking the American Music Industry.'' ``What we
are seeing are the fruits of the women's movement. Sarah and the
women in Lilith Fair are saying things that are speaking to women
and men. I haven't seen a sense of fellowship like this since the
'60s, when 95 percent of the artists felt the same sense of
fellowship around a cause'' _ the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   A look at McLachlan's own history bears this out. The
30-year-old singer-songwriter was raised in Canada by U.S.
expatriates who were dodging the war. She exudes a modern blend of
strength, confidence and sensuality _ not as severe as the
hard-core feminists of the past (Joan Baez, Joan Jett), and not as
kittenish as pop's playthings (Paula Abdul, the Go-Gos). As with
Carole King or Carly Simon, the themes of her songs are universal,
more introspective than angry. Admittedly, the majority of those in
the Lilith Fair audience are females in bluejeans _ mothers,
daughters, sisters, girlfriends. Last year's crowd was estimated to
be about 70 percent female.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the female pop artist, however, can be attributed to
more than consciousness raising. According to Dickerson, two
pivotal events _ one legal, one logistical _ helped break down
barriers and pave the way for Lilith Fair.
</P>
<P>
   From the birth of modern rock in the 1950s through the 1980s,
the music business was notorious for its bottom-pinching
behind-the-scenes treatment of women. Like female recording
artists, women who worked at record companies were often considered
ornaments for the taking. Few ``girls'' made it past the
receptionist's chair, and most who did climb the ladder still had
to endure the often grossly sexist expectations of the male
executives around them.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1991, a secretary named Penny Muck filed a sexual
harassment lawsuit against Geffen Records, home of
testosterone-rock acts such as Guns N' Roses and Aerosmith. She
claimed that her boss, a high-ranking manager, had masturbated in
front of her and fondled her breasts. After other female employees
came forward, she was awarded about half a million dollars in an
out-of-court settlement. Few music fans know Muck's name, but her
lawsuit brought national attention to the ``bad boy'' behavior of
many in the music industry and was a catalyst for change.
</P>
<P>
   The second crack in the system that led to Lilith Fair was a
change in the makeup of record and promotion companies. There now
are more women in executive, decision-making positions than ever
before. And they, in turn, are signing female acts and committing
promotional and marketing dollars to them. As a result, albums by
women are turning platinum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have sales like Sarah McLachlan's or Alanis
Morissette's without men buying your CDs too,'' Dickerson says.
``You can get into the Top 20, but to be that successful, you have
to have male buyers as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lilith Fair grossed $16.4 million last summer, more than any
other concert tour except George Strait's country music festival.
McLachlan has said she is happy with the tour's success but also
aware that it took dollar signs to get attention.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of this year's Lilith Fair tour, she told Newsday,
``It's unfortunate that the only reason the industry recognizes us
is that we have become a viable commercial commodity. I'm not naive
enough to think that it's changed men's attitudes. But I do like to
think that some education and awareness can take place. Every
little step forward is a step in a positive direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
