<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MARIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hormones rage on Riviera_ that's the point of `Marie'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you say ``Beach Blanket Bingo'' in French?
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Manuel Pradal's debut film, ``Marie Baie des Anges'' is
considerably hotter than anything Frankie Avalon and Annette
Funicello ever tried, but at heart, it's just as teen-temptingly
silly.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is set on a ravishingly beautiful slice of the French
Riviera, Nice's Bay of Angels, where, we're told, the angels in
question are actually angel sharks. It centers on sultry,
15-year-old Marie (Vahina Giocante) and Orso (Frederic Malgras), a
foxy, 17-year-old petty thief.
</P>
<P>
   For the first part of the film, he gets into trouble with the
authorities while she gets, well, friendly with some sex-starved
American sailors who apparently don't know (or care) what the
French word is for ``jailbait.'' Somehow, the two find each other
and embark on a ``Blue Lagoon''-ish idyll on a mostly deserted
island (one says ``mostly'' because, when the director so chooses,
there are bottles of wine or happily dancing tourists to complement
the romantic mood).
</P>
<P>
   Pradal gets one thing very right. Just about every scene is
charged with sex, danger or both as Marie works her nubile charms
on the Americans or on Orso's pals, a roving band of feral youths
riding motorbikes. Her power, fleeting as it is, is displayed with
immense assurance and Lolita-ish smolder by young Giocante.
</P>
<P>
   Still, gorgeous as she, Malgras and the Riviera are, the movie
never becomes anything more than a lot of pseudo-cool hooey,
intoxicated with its own studied eroticism. More often than not, it
comes off as an unintentional parody of all those ``hot'' art
flicks of the late 1950s and early '60s. Like its young leads,
``Marie Baie des Anges'' has lots of attitude and not a coherent
thought in its pretty head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marie Baie des Anges''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vahina Giocante and Frederic Malgras. Directed by
Manuel Pradal. Subtitles. Rated R for nudity, brief violence and
sexually charged situations. 1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: All hot and bothered in paradise, but not
especially coherent or thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
