</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few fresh faces appear among acting nominees
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now he's saving the Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks, whose critically hailed big-screen film ``Saving
Private Ryan'' opens today, racked up a leading 17 Emmy nominations
Thursday, including a nod for best director, for his stellar HBO
miniseries ``From the Earth to the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks, a two-time Oscar winner, is the most powerful,
recognizable face to become a major Emmy player in years.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, most of this year's TV nominees are the same old
nominees we've been getting for much of the '90s: Anthony Edwards
on ``ER,'' Kelsey Grammer on ``Frasier,'' Julia Louis-Dreyfus on
``Seinfeld.'' Blah _ blah blah _ blah blah.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he isn't talented, but will you really relish wading
through a four-hour Emmy show Sept. 13 just to watch John Lithgow
be handed yet one more of TV's precious hood ornaments?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this year's Emmy nominations list reads like a
less-than-new-to-you rerun: ``ER,'' ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``The
X-Files,'' ``Tracey Takes On ...'' And who couldn't guess that
``Ally McBeal'' (10 nominations, including best sitcom and comedy
actress) would be so heavily honored?
</P>
<P>
   But besides Hanks, there are other interesting aspects to this
year's list of nominees:
</P>
<P>
   -- The best surprises: Camryn Manheim got a supporting nod for
her dynamite delivery as Ellenor Frutt on ABC's ``The Practice.''
And her show eked into the race for best drama against ``ER,''
``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``The X-Files'' and ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The very deserving: Andre Braugher of ``Homicide: Life on the
Street'' and Jimmy Smits of ``NYPD Blue'' are both up for best
drama actor for their final seasons.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lest we forget them: Phil Hartman (``NewsRadio''), Lloyd
Bridges (a guest spot on ``Seinfeld'') and J.T. Walsh (TNT's
``Hope'') all got nominations.
</P>
<P>
   -- The overlooked: ``Seinfeld's'' Michael Richards was passed
over in a season when Cosmo Kramer was arguably the best thing
about the show.
</P>
<P>
   -- The small-screen stuff: TNT's ``George Wallace'' got eight
nominations as did HBO's ``Don King: Only in America.'' Gary
Sinise, who played Wallace, and Ving Rhames, who was King, both got
nods.
</P>
<P>
   -- Great performances: Emma Thompson was nominated for playing
herself in a guest spot on ``Ellen''; Jack Lemmon got a nod for
Showtime's ``12 Angry Men.''
</P>
<P>
   -- What were they thinking? Kirstie Alley is up for comedy
actress for ``Veronica's Closet.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Not that there's anything wrong with that: For its final
season, ``Seinfeld'' pulled in a meager five nominations. HBO's
``The Larry Sanders Show'' fared much better for its swan-song
year: it got 10, including well-deserved acting nods for Garry
Shandling, Rip Torn and Jeffrey Tambor. Besides ``Seinfeld'' and
``Sanders,'' the other sitcom nominees are ``McBeal,'' ``Frasier''
and ``3rd Rock From the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
