</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIBER-LIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What to do at the fiber conference
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Public recognition. That's what Sandra Bowles,
executive director of the Handweavers Guild of America, hopes will
come out of ``Convergence '98,'' its conference and the
accompanying art exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a large fiber community here and strong grass-roots
support,'' says Bowles, whose organization recently relocated to
Atlanta. ``I think these events will give a presence, an
appreciation and awareness of fiber arts, and this public awareness
will help the artists, many of whom are in the Southeast.''
</P>
<P>
   These exhibits are open to the public:
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Gallery. ``Shared Journeys,'' mixed-media installation by
Linda A. Hightower, and ``The Needle's Eye,'' hand-sewn fiber
