<HEADER>
A9935 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIBERCONFERENCE-COX     07-23 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIBERCONFERENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fiber, fiber everywhere_ and not a bite to eat
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fiber isn't just weaving anymore. It's sensuous contemporary
yardage. Unusual tapestries. Yarns, beads and buttons. Basketry.
Rag rugs. Sculptures. Quilts and fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The brave new world of fiber includes all these and other works
of art whose only connection to loomed pieces is the material out
of which they are made.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, metro Atlanta is Fiber Central. The Handweavers
Guild of America brings its conference south for the first time,
and local galleries have responded with more fiber exhibitions than
you can shake a shuttlecock at.
</P>
<P>
   Both the international biennial conference, ``Convergence '98:
Rhythms &AMP; Hues,'' which began Thursday and continues through
Sunday, and these myriad shows revel in the long and varied
tradition of fiber art. There will be workshops devoted to making
Scottish tartans and Africans demonstrating the art of kente cloth.
Georgia's Mary Hambidge, who revived weaving traditions here, is
the subject of a show at the Atlanta History Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``For fiber, the last 30 and 40 years ... have been a period of
expansion,'' says Atlanta basketmaker Michael Davis. ``Everything
has been questioned. The basket came off the loom. Clothing is a
huge part of it. There's a lot more interesting work done now than
even 15 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Convergence,'' which brings 2,000 fiber artists and fans to
town, creates an unusual opportunity for Atlanta. ``People will see
things they've never seen before, on a scale that they will never
see again,'' Davis says. ``It should be an inspiration to local
artists, too.''
</P>
<P>
   MUST-SEE FIBER
</P>
<P>
   Our list of recommended stops at Convergence '98, which
continues through Sunday at the Atlanta Market Center
(770-351-0233), and at Atlanta galleries:
</P>
<P>
   -- Vendors' area: Atlanta Market Center, second floor, where 300
vendors will show and sell yarns, beads and buttons. $10 one-day
pass includes exhibit area.
</P>
<P>
   -- Exhibit area: Atlanta Market Center, third floor, where
artists will show the scope of fiber art. $10 pass includes
vendors.
</P>
<P>
   -- Scottish waulk: 4:30 p.m. today, Atlanta Market Center.
Tartan weaving and bagpiping. $10 pass.
</P>
<P>
   -- Connell Gallery: ``Figurative Fiber,'' an exhibit of two- and
three-dimensional fiber art. Free. Through Aug. 15. 404-261-1712.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jon Eric Riis: Atlanta artist's tapestries. Atlanta
International Museum. Free. Through Aug. 22. 404-688-2467.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
