<SLUG> BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX INCREASES ITS ANIMATION DRAW BY 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With ``The Simpsons'' and ``King of the
Hill,'' Fox has proven there's an appetite out there for chewy,
well-done animated fare in prime time. But on the assumption that
our appetites are insatiable, the network early next year will lay
out a veritable animation smorgasbord, adding three more series,
including a new sci-fi entry from ``Simpsons'' creator Matt
Groening.
</P>
<P>
   If all five animated series are on the schedule at the same
time, they will comprise 25 percent of Fox's prime-time
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Groening's new effort is ``Futurama.'' He said the action takes
place a thousand years from now and features three main characters,
all with the familiar big eyeballs and overbites that Groening
ascribes to ``the tragedy of limited drawing skills.'' The main
character right now is a ``lovably corrupt'' robot named Bender,
possibly the first robot in science fiction that shoplifts.
</P>
<P>
   Joining ``Futurama'' on Fox's tentative midseason schedule are
``The PJs'' and ``Family Guy.'' ``The PJs'' is an Eddie Murphy
project about life in the projects _ the PJs _ with ``foamation''
by Portland's clay-animation pioneer, Will Vinton. The funniest of
the bunch may be ``Family Guy'' from Seth MacFarlane, a 24-year-old
animator with an odd view of the ``typical'' suburban family.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious appeal of ``The Simpsons'' and ``King of the Hill''
has other networks paying attention. This summer, The WB tested
``Invasion America,'' an animated drama from Steven Spielberg's
company, and NBC is working on an Americanized version of a British
animated comedy, ``Stressed Eric.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ally McBeal'' cast grows this fall with the addition of
Portia de Rossi, who plays attorney Nell Porter. De Rossi describes
Porter as ``a very strong character, a good lawyer who is
intelligent and makes her own way.''
</P>
<P>
   De Rossi, who studied law in Australia before pursuing an acting
career, said Richard Fish (Greg Germann) hires Porter as a
rainmaker, someone who can attract well-heeled clients to the firm.
As to how Porter interacts with Ally (Calista Flockhart), de Rossi
said, ``We'll just have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Scott Bairstow, who lives in Mukilteo when not working in
L.A., will join Fox's ``Party of Five'' this season as the
boyfriend of Julia Salinger's (Neve Campbell) college roommate.
Bairstow starred last season in the short-lived ``Significant
Others,'' which was produced by the same people who do ``Party of
Five.''
</P>
<P>
   Josie Bissett, another native of the Seattle area, rejoins
``Melrose Place'' this season after a self-imposed time away.
Though she visited the set occasionally to be with hubby Rob Estes,
she says she didn't watch ``Melrose'' on TV too often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only watched it when Rob and Heather (Locklear) had love
scenes,'' she laughed. ``It turns me on. What can I say?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
