<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9952 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-COMPETITION     07-23 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COMPETITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ATTACKED BY SEN. HATCH AND RIVAL COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Software giant Microsoft came under attack again
Thursday from a leading senator and from executives of rival
companies, who called the firm a monopoly that threatens innovation
in the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical debate, many believe, is the extent to which
Microsoft is exploiting its current monopolies both to kill off
potential threats, and to leverage these monopolies to control new
technologies which will define the future of computing, of the
Internet and of how we conduct much of our daily lives,'' said Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which was
holding its second hearing into Microsoft's business practices,
said the Redmond, Wash., company ``certainly appeared to have
engaged in anti-competitive behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   At a previous hearing in March, billionaire Microsoft Chairman
Bill Gates defended his company's actions as those of an
``aggressive'' firm. However, at Wednesday's hearing, neither Gates
nor any other Microsoft official testified before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he had asked Microsoft officials to come to the
hearing, but they declined. He added that some other companies
asked to testify on Microsoft's behalf had turned down the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that our doors have not exactly been knocked down
with companies asking to defend Microsoft's business practices,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which is fighting an antitrust lawsuit by the Justice
Department and 20 states, said it would be inappropriate to appear
since the trial in that case is scheduled for September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear that additional testimony from Microsoft will
serve any purpose,'' the company said in a statement, which noted
Hatch's frequent attacks.
</P>
<P>
   However, outside the hearing room, Microsoft did receive support
from Sen. Slade Gordon, R-Wash., who held a press conference only
minutes before the hearing started.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing but another show for unsuccessful competitors
to make their complaints against one of America's most successful
companies,'' he said, adding that the hearing was ``another chapter
in Sen. Hatch's vendetta against Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   But inside the hearing room, heads of rival companies painted a
totally different picture of Microsoft and Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Glasser, chairman of Seattle-based RealNetworks, which
makes software that allows people to watch video across the
Internet, said Microsoft was attempting to undermine his product.
</P>
<P>
   Glasser, who worked for Microsoft for 10 years and said he was a
friend of Gates, charged that Microsoft's version of the video
software, known as Windows Media Player, blocks consumers from
using his product.
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, Glasser entered a site on the World Wide Web
and played a news video, which used his software product. Glasser
then downloaded Windows Media Player and re-entered the same Web
site. The video failed to play.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in a statement released responding to Glasser's
testimony, said the company ``does NOT disable'' the RealNetworks'
product.
</P>
<P>
   After Glasser testified, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., read an
affidavit from a Microsoft official that accused the RealNetworks
chief of seeking to use his appearance before the committee as
leverage to force Microsoft to make a deal with his company.
</P>
<P>
   In the affidavit, Paul Maritz, a Microsoft vice president, said
that on Wednesday Glass offered to withdraw as a witness if
Microsoft would accept a new licensing agreement with RealNetworks.
Its current licensing agreement with Microsoft expired Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that he spoke with Microsoft officials on
Wednesday, Glasser said it was only to brief them on what he was
going to say at the hearing. He called the claim that he tried to
force them into a deal ``completely untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Gates' rival, Lawrence J. Ellison, chairman of Oracle
Corp., based in Redwood Shores, Calif., told the committee that
Microsoft would never be satisfied with only part of the software
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is already the most powerful company in the world,
and you ain't seen nothing yet,'' said the Ellison, whose company
is the world's second-largest independent software company.
</P>
<P>
   He said Microsoft was using the dominance of its Window's
operating system _ the program is installed in 95 percent of new
computers _ to stifle competition and take over other software
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison said Microsoft's response to the success of Netscape
Corp.'s Navigator, the Mountain View, Calif., company's Internet
browser, has been typical of what he called Microsoft's
``predatory'' business practices.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when Netscape Navigator emerged as a key portal to
the World Wide Web, Microsoft quickly copied the technology and
introduced its own browser, called Internet Explorer. Microsoft
then added, or ``bundled,'' Internet Explorer to the company's
Windows program. The result is that people who buy a new computer
with Windows already installed no longer need Netscape Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Microsoft's share of the Internet browser market has
increased steadily for the last year, and the company now has
nearly 50 percent of the market. Netscape Navigator's share of the
market has fallen from around 80 percent to less than 50 percent in
that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill wants to add everything to Windows,'' Ellison said. ``And
every time he succeeds, that's the end of innovation in that
product.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last month, a federal appeals court overturned a U.S. District
Court injunction that had prohibited Microsoft from requiring
computer manufacturers to install Microsoft's browser software for
navigating the World Wide Web as a condition of installing Windows
95.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said Microsoft had the right to add whatever
new features it wanted to its operating system, even if that
included ``bundling'' other products, as long as the result
benefits consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court's ruling came as blow to 20 state attorneys
general and Department of Justice officials, who have alleged in a
lawsuit that Microsoft is illegally tying its Windows 98 software
with its Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that Microsoft is using its dominance of the
operating systems market to gain control of the Internet software
industry. By placing Internet Explorer on Windows 98, the updated
version of Windows 95, and excluding other browsers, they contend,
Microsoft stifles innovation and competition.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials argue that integrating the Internet browser
into Windows benefits users. They also say that the Internet has
become such a fundamental part of computer use that access to it
should be part of the any operating system.
</P>
<P>
   A browser is software that allows users to access information on
the Internet's World Wide Web, which offers text, pictures and
sound.
</P>
