<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-BIRTHRATE-NYT (Washington) _ Married black women gave
birth to 357,262 babies in 1970. But, by 1996, the last year for
which complete figures were available, that figure had dropped to
179,568, a decline of nearly 50 percent, nearly twice the drop in
the birth rate among married white women. By Steven A. Holmes.
 &UR; Moved 7-21. With photo. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT (Washington) _ The struggle over patients'
rights legislation has scrambled old alliances and created some
extraordinary new ones. It is throwing together doctors, trial
lawyers and consumers, and pitting them against insurers and
managed care companies, who in many cases are fighting each other
over how much regulation they can take. By Peter T. Kilborn.  &UR; Moved
7-21. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILES-BLOOD-BOS _ Go ahead and swat, but the dreaded greenhead
fly driving its saw-like pincers into your thigh as you lie on the
beach may save your life some day. Harvard University researchers
are looking for an elusive protein in fly saliva that thins the
blood of victims, allowing greenheads to feed amply off the crimson
flow. That knowledge could lead to drugs to help people fight
strokes, heart attacks, and other cardiovascular disease. By Marie
C. Sanchez.  &UR; Moved 7-21. With photo. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS _ A lot of ordinary folks quietly do heroic
duty every day caring for frail elders at home. But not without a
cost, in terms of stress and health problems, that researchers are
just beginning to understand. By Richard A. Knox.  &UR; Moved 7-20. With
photo. &LR;  See also SCI-OLDER-TEST-BOS.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOMEN'S HEALTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-IMPLANTS-NYT (Washington) _ After 16 years of
litigation and scientific controversy over the safety of silicone
breast implants, a panel of independent experts Wednesday began its
own inquiry into the dispute, which pits researchers who say there
is no link between implants and disease against tens of thousands
of women who say the devices made them sick. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.  &UR; Moved 7-22. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS-HEALTH-NYT _ Cosmetic surgery to enlarge the
breasts (which does not include reconstruction after mastectomy) is
regaining popularity after falling out of favor in 1992. By Denise
Grady.  &UR; Moved 7-20. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TINIEST-BABY-BOS (Boston) _ She began life last October as a
14-ounce preemie, the size of a Pepsi can, her mother recalled.
Twice since then she came close to dying, but she didn't, and now
Shaniqua Leatherwood owns a distinction. She's tied with another
baby as the smallest ever born in Boston to survive. By Marie C.
Sanchez.  &UR; Moved 7-20. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIDS-RELATED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-REGISTRY-BOS (Washington) _ High-ranking officials of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, in what AIDS activists
angrily call a ``traveling road show,'' are crisscrossing the
country lobbying state health officials to report the names of
people who test positive for the AIDS virus. By Louise D. Palmer.
 &UR; Moved 7-21. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TREATMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MARKET-BLOOM (Bridgewater, N.J.) _ That strong, sudden
urge. Having to go so often. Fear of wetting accidents. Those
symptoms are read off in the opening sequence of a television
commercial making its national debut this week. The ad is the
opening salvo in a media blitz that drugmaker Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn
Inc. hopes will boost sales of its bladder-control drug Detrol
before competitor Alza Corp. gets permission to sell its new
treatment for the disorder, Ditropan XL. By Jim Finkle.  &UR; Moved
7-22. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CANNABIS-BOS (Oakland, Calif.) _ In test cases that are
being monitored by marijuana advocates from Maine to Alaska, the
Oakland Cannabis Buyers' Cooperative and a handful of others are
operating in violation of a federal court injunction. Lynda Gorov.
 &UR; Moved 7-21. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXERCISE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXERCISE-COLUMN-BOS _ It's not how fast you swim, it's how.
By Barbara Huebner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH-NYT _ There seems to be a week for just about every
health problem that afflicts a significant number of Americans. But
where is the week for those ``poor, poor feet'' celebrated in song
a generation ago in ``The Pajama Game''? Let's face it, our feet
take a beating, bearing our full weight for a lifetime of walking
and running, often in shoes that squeeze, rub or deform them. By
Jane E. Brody.  &UR; Moved 7-20. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service. &LR;
