<HEADLINE>
BC'S MARTY REASONER SIGNS WITH BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston College's NCAA runner-up hockey team suffered a
significant loss Thursday when All-America center and team captain
Marty Reasoner signed with the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoner, who was drafted by the Blues as a freshman and has
been a force for the Eagles for three seasons, signed a reported $1
million deal. He is taking classes this summer, and a BC degree is
high on his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   A BC source said, ``Marty had to sign. What he was offered was
just too much to turn down. I feel he has the blessing of the
Boston College family.''
</P>
<P>
   In his three seasons as an Eagle, Reasoner played in 111 games,
collecting 69 goals and 93 assists for 162 points. He is tied for
11th on the all-time school scoring list with Billy O'Dwyer (1982)
and Doug Brown (1986).
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach coach Jerry York for comment Thursday were
unsuccessful, but he has said repeatedly, ``Marty is a high-caliber
person and player. He always demands respect. What too many people
don't realize is how dangerous he is even without the puck. He sees
the entire ice, plays two ways, and knows where everyone is all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   During Reasoner's career, BC compiled records of 11-22-2,
16-17-3, and last season's 28-9-5 breakthrough. As a junior,
Reasoner played in all 42 games and had 33 goals and 40 assists. He
led the Eagles to the NCAA final, where they lost to Michigan in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   There were only two seniors on the 1997-98 Eagles: defenseman
Ken Hemenway and forward Jamie O'Leary. With the departure of
Reasoner, York's next team will consist of eight seniors, five
juniors, and eight sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoner, a 6-foot-1-inch, 206-pounder from Honeoye Falls, N.Y.,
played for Team USA in the 1996 and '97 world championships, was
named Hockey East Rookie of the Year as a freshman, and earned
All-New England honors twice at Deerfield Academy, where he tallied
112 points in two seasons. He was named Hockey Night In Boston MVP
in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
