<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEEP IN YOUNG PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ The Patriots have 19 first- and second-year
draftees, plus undrafted second-year men like Mark Tate and Bernard
Russ who are playing well enough to make the 53-man squad.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams would call this rebuilding, but the Patriots merely
think of it as an example of constantly developing from within and
staying young, strong, and athletic to reinforce an established
core of players.
</P>
<P>
   With that mind-set, the Patriots are not apt to let many
youngsters go. They believe the players from last year's draft, who
did not receive high grades around the NFL, may make a contribution
this season. And Pete Carroll believes this rookie crop is far
ahead of its 1997 predecessor in terms of fitting into the system.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Patriots attempt to build a championship-caliber
team, they'll do it with a dose of youth that could amount to
almost a third of the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are into our football now,'' said Carroll of the
'97 draftees. ``We're not seeing Florida State or somebody else's
stuff. We're seeing our stuff. They can line up and make some
calls. They can line up and make adjustments. That's pervading
throughout our offense and defense. You can see the quickness of
the decision-making right before your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll thinks huge progress is being made by the young
offensive linemen _ Ed Ellis (University of Buffalo), Scott Rehberg
(Central Michigan), and Damon Denson (Michigan).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a unit coming together with that second line,'' he
said. ``They came off the ball very nice in practice. They're
starting to get a feel for what's expected of them. I mean, they
had no clue last year. That helps. The whole idea is to get a
number of areas and just get a little bit better. That will make
our whole team better. The second-team defense understands line
calls. The end result will be it will make us a better football
team.''
</P>
<P>
   In the best of worlds, the younger players push the veterans.
That seems to be the case here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that's happening,'' said Carroll. ``I know what the
competition is in certain areas. We did some one-on-one drills with
the offensive line against the defensive line today just so we can
start to get an accurate gauge of which guy is doing what against
whom. That's just one ingredient of making a decision. Today was
the most competitive camp we've had. There will be times we'll be
switching people to give our second guys a chance to play on the
first team. But we want to see what happens when (Heath) Irwin is
in with the first team or Rehberg has to step in.''
</P>
<P>
   While top 1998 pick Robert Edwards remains impressive with his
running and receiving ability (though he did fumble in the morning
session), Carroll also is pleased with sixth-round pick Harold
Shaw, a 6-foot, 240-pounder from Southern Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was breaking though the middle, shaking off tacklers, and
putting the hurt on the linebackers in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making a good impression,'' said Carroll. ``We're trying
to press the line of scrimmage with the backs and get them an
attitude about hitting the line of scrimmage. He had a pretty good
day. He got through some tackles. He worked pretty hard. We drafted
him knowing we were getting a bigger back. He's not spending too
much time juking from right to left. He's getting it done north and
south right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw may make more of an impact on special teams, where Carroll
is looking for a spark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to break into the starting lineup on this
team,'' said Carroll. ``We need a spark here and there. We're OK
and we have some areas where we're very good, but we need that
energy. Maybe it comes out of Marty (Moore) or (Larry) Whigham, but
if we can get it out of one or two other guys like Chris Floyd or
Russ or a Greg Spires and Harold can add to the group ...''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he hasn't played too much on special teams except for
returning kicks, but ``I think I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He feels comfortable sometimes but still has moments when he's
lost. So the best way for him to show something is to be physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try sometimes to hit them before they hit me to ease the
pain,'' said Shaw. ``Right now my goal is to make the team.''
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite side, Russ has been impressive, applying tough
hits on the running backs. Used mostly as a special-teams player
toward the end of the year, the West Virginia product has been
impressive as an outside linebacker. Ditto Vernon Crawford, last
year's fifth-round pick from Florida State, who has been excellent
on coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Also sticking out is Spires, a quick defensive end from Florida
State who at 6-1, 265, was supposed be too small for the NFL,
according to some draft experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this guy,'' said Carroll. ``He's a tough sucker. He's
had some problems with special teams and assignments and he's got a
ton to learn. If he can sustain the toughness and the intensity,
he's going to have a lot to offer us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's second-round pick, Brandon Mitchell from Texas A&AMP;M,
has also impressed the coaching staff, switching inside to
defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Tate, who spent much of last year on the practice squad, may be
challenging Chris Canty at cornerback. With early injuries to Steve
Israel and Tebucky Jones, the 6-1, 185-pound Tate has had an
opportunity to showcase himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the guys we have were already here,'' said Willie
Clay. ``They get more confident and experience, and that creates
more competition. Everybody is getting better throughout the
system. Chris Canty has had a very good camp, and Mark is a guy who
keeps coming on.''
</P>
<P>
   With youth come mistakes, however. That's the inevitable
downside to having so many young players. When a young corner blows
his coverage, it could be a touchdown. When a young back fumbles,
it could turn the momentum of a game, or if he doesn't pick up
blitz coverage, it could get Drew Bledsoe injured. These are things
the Patriots will have to live with. They've decided that youth
will give them speed, athleticism, and a future.
</P>
<P>
   They hope they have enough veteran leadership to smooth over the
rough spots caused by inexperience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
