<SLUG> BC-EMMY-NOMINATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO'S `MOON' MINISERIES LEADS EMMY FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tom Hanks' 12-part HBO miniseries, ``From the
Earth to the Moon,'' earned the most Emmy Award nominations of any
program, with 17, and NBC earned the most of any network, with 86,
when nominations for the 1997-98 television season were announced
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   HBO had 72 nominations, ABC 54, CBS 36 and Fox 35. The winners
will be announced in the 50th annual Emmy Awards broadcast on Sept.
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal,'' the Fox comedy about a winsome young lawyer,
had a strong showing for a first-year comedy, earning 10
nominations, one fewer than NBC's ``Frasier,'' and tied with HBO's
``Larry Sanders Show'' and ABC's drama ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The only shows that earned more nominations were the dramas
``ER'' (NBC) and ``The X-Files'' (Fox), with 16 each, and the NBC
miniseries ``Merlin,'' with 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal's'' showing was also unusual because the program
is an hour long, and the most popular television comedies are a
half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Also surprising, critics here for the television critics' press
tour said, was that Jerry Seinfeld received no acting nomination,
even though this was his show's last season. ``Seinfeld'' was
nominated for best comedy series and received four other
nominations, including best supporting actor in a comedy (Jason
Alexander) and supporting actress (Julia Louis-Dreyfuss).
</P>
<P>
   Critics were also surprised that neither ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' the CBS comedy, nor its star, Ray Romano, were
nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Seinfeld, several other actors who are leaving roles
after long runs received nominations. They include Garry Shandling
(``Larry Sanders'') and Ellen DeGeneres (``Ellen'' on ABC) in the
comedy category, and Jimmy Smits (``NYPD Blue''), Andre Braugher
(NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the Street'') and Jane Seymour (CBS's
``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman'').
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart, who plays Ally McBeal, and Jenna Elfman, who
plays Dharma in the ABC comedy ``Dharma and Greg,'' were newcomers
to the best actress in a comedy category, joining Ms. DeGeneres,
Helen Hunt (NBC's ``Mad About You''), Patricia Richardson (NBC's
``Home Improvement'') and Kirstie Alley (NBC's ``Veronica's
Closet'').
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice,'' ABC's drama about a group of hard-pressed
young lawyers in Boston, was the only newcomer in the best dramatic
series category, joining ``ER,'' ``NYPD Blue,'' ``The X-Files'' and
NBC's ``Law and Order,'' last year's winner. Nominated along with
``Seinfeld'' for best comedy were ``Ally McBeal,'' ``Frasier,''
``Larry Sanders'' and ``Third Rock From the Sun.'' Writer David E.
Kelley earned an unusual double, with nominations as best writer
for both a comedy series (``Ally McBeal'') and a drama (``The
Practice'').
</P>
<P>
   As has become its habit, HBO dominated the made-for-television
movie category, with three of the five nominations: ``A Bright
Shining Lie,'' ``Don King: Only in America,'' and ``Gia.''
Showtime's ``12 Angry Men'' and CBS's ``What the Deaf Man Heard''
received the others.
</P>
<P>
   Last year HBO received attention for nearly equaling the top
broadcast network, NBC, in nominations (92 to 90). This year, HBO's
total was less surprising. Down most dramatically, though, was CBS,
from 60 nominations to 36.
</P>
<P>
   PBS earned 14 nominations for prime-time shows, down from 18
last year, including for outstanding nonfiction series (``The
American Experience'') and outstanding nonfiction special
(``American Masters: Don Hewitt, 90 Minutes on `60 Minutes'''), and
several performance specials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
