<HEADER>
A9992 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-EMMYS-BOS &LR;      07-23 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EMMYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 `ALLY MCBEAL' NOMINATIONS CHEER WRITER KELLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; More than surprise, more than jubilation, ``Ally McBeal''
creator David E. Kelley felt a bone-deep sense of relief Thursday
when he learned that his Boston-based TV series had won 10 Emmy
Award nominations in the best comedy category.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, you see, has gotten the joke.
</P>
<P>
   Whether she is pursuing her law career, her romances, or that
elusive Dancing Baby, Ally McBeal exists in a state of comic
dither. The punditocracy has responded to the miniskirted fidgeter
with a resounding harrumph; just last month Time magazine ran a
photo of the star of ``Ally McBeal'' above this portentous inquiry:
``Is Feminism Dead?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me was probably desperate for it to be declared a
comedy,'' Kelley said in an interview with the Globe. ``We get so
many letters that take episodes to heart: `How dare you do this or
that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response is usually: `The show is a comedy. Don't take us
too seriously,' '' he added. ``Now that the Emmys have declared us
a comedy, maybe everyone will get the message that we're not
speaking for society; we're speaking for Ally.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC led the Emmy-nomination parade with 86, including 11 for
``Frasier,'' the top-nominated comedy. Next was HBO with 72
nominations, including an Emmy-leading 17 for Tom Hanks' 12-part
miniseries on the space program, ``From the Earth to the Moon.'' In
third place was ABC with 54, including, ironically enough,
nominations for the canceled ``Ellen'' and its star, Ellen
DeGeneres. Fourth was CBS with 36, followed by Fox, with 35 _
including the 10 nominations for ``Ally McBeal'' _ and TNT with 18.
</P>
<P>
   The cascade of Emmy nominations capped a remarkable year for the
protean, 40-year-old Kelley, a 1983 graduate of Boston University
Law School who practiced law in Boston before heading to Hollywood,
where he married actress Michelle Pfeiffer five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a feat that astonished many in the television industry,
Kelley wrote all 22 episodes of ``Ally McBeal'' last year as well
as most of the 22 episodes of ABC's ``The Practice,'' a
Boston-based legal drama he created that also was nominated in the
best drama series category.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Ally McBeal'' became the first hourlong show in three
decades to be nominated as a comedy, Kelley admitted that the
nomination of ``The Practice,'' a show that he said had been ``kind
of forsaken,'' was perhaps most gratifying of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago `The Practice' was on Saturday night, and ABC's
statement to the contrary notwithstanding, they put it there to
die,'' he said. ``Now, here we are a year later with a good time
slot on Monday nights and an Emmy nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks, who left television 15 years ago to become a movie star
after the forgettable ``Bosom Buddies'' was canceled, climaxed his
triumphant return to the medium with a harvest of nominations for
``From the Earth to the Moon,'' a miniseries for which he served as
executive producer (he also acted in one part and directed
another).
</P>
<P>
   In awarding more nominations to ``From the Earth to the Moon''
than to any other show or series, the Academy of Television Arts &AMP;
Sciences delivered a stinging rebuff to the broadcast networks. The
networks had protested the submission of ``From the Earth'' into
the miniseries category, arguing that it was too long to be so
considered.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest and most bitter chapter in a long-running
battle between broadcasters and the cable networks over whether
cable outlets enjoy an unfair advantage in the miniseries
competition because they can devote more time and money to a few
big projects per year, while broadcast networks must program 22
prime-time hours per week.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the inroads cable has made into the dominance
of broadcast networks, 15 cable networks received a total of 139
Emmy nominations, the most ever for cable programming.
</P>
<P>
   The pace-setting showing by ``Frasier'' will hearten programmers
at the Peacock Network who recently anointed the urbane sitcom as
the Thursday-night successor to ``Seinfeld'' this fall. The
most-nominated dramas were NBC's ``ER'' and Fox's ``The X-Files,''
tied at 16 nominations apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Kelley, Hanks, and ``Frasier,'' Emmy smiled upon
numerous actors and TV shows that will no longer be on the air when
the winners of the 50th Annual Primetime Emmy Awards are announced
on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Hartman, slain by his wife in May in a murder-suicide, was
nominated as best supporting actor for his role in NBC's
``NewsRadio.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous stars and shows that won't be returning were also
nominated: NBC's ``Seinfeld'' (though series creator and star Jerry
Seinfeld was snubbed); HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show'' and its
star, Garry Shandling; ABC's canceled ``Ellen'' and its star, Ellen
DeGeneres; Jane Quinn of ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman'', which CBS
canceled over Quinn's vehement objection; Andre Braugher of NBC's
``Homicide''; and Jimmy Smits of ABC's ``NYPD Blue,'' who will
leave after a few more episodes.
</P>
<P>
   As for David E. Kelley, he is staying right where he is, with
his nose to the most creative grindstone in television today.
</P>
<P>
   Observing that ``Ally McBeal'' is ``kind of a different
animal,'' he said he intends to write most episodes of the show for
the upcoming season, though he said he may delegate some of ``The
Practice'' scriptwriting chores.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley freely acknowledged that ``Ally McBeal'' does not contain
as much Boston flavor as ``The Practice.'' He said he set ``Ally''
in Boston for ``economic reasons,'' noting that it was more
efficient for his production company in gathering courtroom
exteriors and other scene-setting shots.
</P>
<P>
   According to TV historian Alex McNeil, ``Ally McBeal'' is the
first hourlong show since ``Love, American Style'' in 1969-70 to be
nominated as best comedy series. (``Love, American Style'' later
switched to a half-hour).
</P>
<P>
   Kelley makes clear that he will continue to chronicle Love, Ally
Style in his own inimitable fashion, regardless of brickbats from
the humor-impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really braced for that reaction right away,'' he said.
``Even during the development of the pilot, I said `You do realize
this will be ripe for attack, because there will be people out
there who will say how dare you create this character who's smart
and has a degree of sophistication and success and yet somehow
declares herself empty because she doesn't have a man' '' and is
otherwise willing to admit confusion in her life.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley himself was feeling anything but empty as the Emmy news
rolled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in production, you can't take too many moments,''
he said, adding jokingly. ``I vicariously take a moment through
Peter MacNicol's character on `Ally' (`the Biscuit'). But I'd be
lying if I didn't say we're all thrilled today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
