<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-HITLER-480&AMP;AD     07-23 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-HITLER-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH PLOTTED TO KILL HITLER, NEWLY RELEASED DOCUMENTS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British agents planned a series of bizarre plots to
assassinate Adolf Hitler during the last months of World War II,
according to wartime papers made public Thursday by the Public
Records Office.
</P>
<P>
   A 120-page dossier prepared by the secret Special Operations
Executive, a unit charged with wreaking havoc behind enemy lines,
laid out elaborately detailed operations to eliminate Hitler,
complete with maps and photographs of his living areas and notes on
his personal habits.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended approaches included sniper attacks on him as he
took his morning stroll, the aerial bombardment and paratrooper
assault of his Berchtesgaden Alpine retreat, blowing up his
personal train, the Fuehrerzug, as it went through a tunnel,
poisoning his tea and impregnating his clothes with anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   The outlandish plans were never acted upon because there was
sufficient objection to delay them and the war was winding down,
with Hitler becoming an increasingly erratic and unreliable leader.
High-ranking British officers argued that his strategic blundering
made him more valuable to the Allies alive than dead.
</P>
<P>
   The undertaking was called Operation Foxley and was cleared by
Foreign Secretary Anthony Eden and reported to Prime Minister
Winston Churchill as a project endorsed by his defense chiefs. The
head of the unit, Maj. Gen. Colin Gubbins, gathered his senior
staff officers together in the War Office in June 1944 and said
they would have to discover Hitler's whereabouts and practices and
then work out a way to ``deal with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rallying his men, Gubbins said: ``At some time or other in the
near future, Hitler must in any case disappear from the scene, even
if we should not be the direct agents for his elimination, and we
can at least prepare such action to be taken on his disappearance
as will contribute best towards the situation most favorable to the
Allied nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Field Robertson, head of the secret office's German
section, thought the notion foolhardy and argued passionately
against it. He warned that the Germans would ``canonize'' Hitler as
a martyr, while it would be disastrous for the Allies if it was
believed they had had to resort to ``low methods'' because they
were unable to defeat the Germans militarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a strategist, Hitler has been of the greatest possible
assistance to the British war effort,'' he said, adding, ``I have
no hesitation in saying that his value to us has been the
equivalent to an almost unlimited number of first-class SOE agents
strategically placed inside Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Expressing the view that prevailed, the Special Operations
Executive's air adviser, Vice Marshal A.P. Ritchie, said Hitler had
a ``mystical hold'' on the German people. ``Remove Hitler, and
there is nothing left,'' he concluded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to the blueprint, Hitler was most vulnerable to sniper
attack as he took the same leisurely 15-minute walk each morning to
a teahouse at Berchtesgaden. He was guarded from a distance since
``he cannot bear to feel himself watched,'' the dossier said, and
this gave agents, dressed in fake German mountain-troop uniforms,
the opportunity to place themselves in strategic positions
undetected.
</P>
<P>
   If their mission failed, two other assassins would be lying in
wait around the corner with antitank rocket launchers to destroy
his car as he was driven back to the Berghof, his private
residence.
</P>
<P>
   In the train scenario saboteurs would lay remote-control charges
on tracks without arousing guards' suspicions because they would be
dressed as railway police officers and accompanied by a man in the
kind of suit that Gestapo men favored. The report said that tunnels
and bridges were less well guarded in Germany than in the occupied
territories and that, with all able men at the front, the quality
of the railroad watchers was low.
</P>
<P>
   The report detected one difficulty in the plan to poison his tea
_ the drug to be used, codenamed ``I,'' made tea cloudy _ and laid
out a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler, according to reliable information, is a tea addict,''
it said. ``But he always drinks it with milk. Since the milk is
poured first into the cup, it is unlikely that its opalescence
would be noticed as it came from the teapot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
