<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release FRIDAY AMs, July 24, 1998  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NUCLEAR (Moscow) -- Strikes at Russian nuclear facilities
underscore the fiscal problems undermining nuclear weapons
reduction talks. By David Filipov. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCCURRY-RESIGNS (Washington) -- President Clinton appoints
deputy Joe Lockhart to replace White House press secretary Michael
McCurry, who will step down when Congress recesses in October. By
Ann Scales. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-ABORTION (Washington ) _ House votes 296-132 to override
President Clinton's veto of a bill to outlaw ``partial-birth
abortion. By Chris Black. 800 words..
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-RIGHTS (Washington) US Rep. Joseph Kennedy releases new
information linking US Army School of Americas graduates to human
rights abuses in Colombia. By Chris Black. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAWLEY-TRIAL (Poughkeepsie, N.Y.) _ A decade after charging she
was raped by a gang of white men, Tawana Brawley fails to appear at
the defamation trial of her three advisers. By Fred Kaplan. 600
words.
</P>
<P>
   FBI-MOB (Boston) -- US Attorney and the top FBI agent in Boston
respond to a Globe examination of the relationship between the
agencies and Boston gangsters. By Mitchell Zuckoff. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-TEACHERS-TESTS (Boston) -- Recent teacher certification tests
produced a low of a 100 percent failure, (all of Mt. Ida College's
five candidates) and Northeastern's 83 percent failure rate, to the
high passing rates of Harvard, BC and BU. By Ellen O'Brien. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-EMMYS (Undated) _ Nominations include: HBO's ``From the Earth
to the Moon'' (top nominee; 17); NBC top network (86, HBO second);
``ER,'' ``X-Files'' (16). ``Ally McBeal'' is rare hourlong comedy
nominee (10). By Don Aucoin. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UNITED-ASSET (Undated) -- Profits at United Asset Management, a
Boston-based investment company that is one of the nation's largest
money managers, plunge in the second quarter. By Lynnley Browning.
500 words.
</P>
<P>
   REEBOK-EARNS (Undated) -- Reebok's second-quarter results are
expected to show lower earnings. Company touts a new shoe
technology that will help it through the continuing glut on the
athletic shoe market. By Gregg Krupa. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   RAYTHEON-EARNS (Undated) -- Raytheon posts strong quarterly
results, but warns that its engineering business continues to
weaken, prompting analysts to reduce their earnings estimates for
the year. By Joann Muller.
</P>
<P>
   MA-DEREG-REFERENDUM (Boston) -- Setting the stage for a big,
monied battle in November, Massachusetts' highest court eliminates
the last obstacle to a referendum to repeal the new electric
deregulation law. By Gregg Krupa. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-BLUEJAYS-REDSOX (Boston) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BBA-COMMENTARY (Undated) _ By Larry Whiteside.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Smithfield, R.I.) -- The Patriots have 19 first-
and second-year drafted players who are playing well enough to make
the 53-man squad. By Nick Cafardo.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FLOYD (Undated) _ Bulls name Tim Floyd head of operations.
By Michael Holley.
</P>
