<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0018 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUDAN-FAMINE-ART-2TAK     07-23 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-FAMINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE AID, FAMINE SPREADS IN WAR-TORN SUDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANTHOU, Sudan _ She straggled into the government-held town of
Wau on Tuesday on legs no thicker than broomsticks, a gaunt and
skeletal figure with hollow eyes, her skin hanging loose over her
bones.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had left three of her children under a tree a few
miles back. They were too weak to go on after a four-day walk from
Gogrial County to find food. Three other children had already died
of starvation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have run out of everything,'' the woman, Akon Akol Ding,
said weakly, as she waited with a half gourd in her hands for aid
workers to give her something to eat. ``Our cows have been looted.
There has been no rain, so we don't cultivate.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside a compound on the northern outskirts of Wau, there were
more than 100 newly dug graves with rude wooden markers. They were
shallow. The smell of human corpses hung above the turned-up brown
earth.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, a few aid workers were doling out sugar water in plastic
cups to new arrivals like Mrs. Ding. The people who had not yet
died sat and lay in rows in a dirt courtyard, emaciated, weak and
incoherent, raising their empty hands and bleary eyes to visitors
in a silent request for sustenance. Many had walked for several
days to reach Wau. Some had seen their children and other loved
ones starve to death on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a massive airlift of more than 12,000 tons of food over
the last three and a half months, a famine has begun to take a
significant number of lives in some parts of Bahr el Ghazal state
in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Aid officials say the severe shortage of food is likely to
worsen in the next six months because the rains that normally fuel
the next harvest in October have arrived late and are falling
sporadically.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rough terrain and poor communications in Sudan,
it is unclear precisely how many people are dying, aid officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   But in the town of Wau alone between 20 and 50 people are
perishing every day, United Nations nurses say. Tuesday morning, 51
people died of starvation and famine-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout southern Sudan, U.N. officials estimate, at least 1.2
million people face severe food shortages this year, though most
people have not yet reached the point of starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, people have begun dying in significant numbers in several
communities where refugees displaced by fighting earlier this year
are camped, a visit to two rebel-held communities and the
government-held garrison town of Wau revealed.
</P>
<P>
   In rebel territory, the worst-hit community appears to Ajiep, a
town 20 miles north of Wau where more than 6,000 displaced people
are camped near a dirt airstrip. More than 20 children died last
week in feeding centers in Ajiep. Aid workers there estimate at
least six adults are dying every day.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that the situation is deteriorating, a June
survey of children in nine Bar el Ghazal villages showed at least
one in every five is severely malnourished, far above what would be
expected in a normal year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people dying are among more than 100,000 refugees
who fled from Wau and other towns in Aweil and Gogrial counties in
February after a flare-up in the 15-year-old war. Wandering for the
last three months, the majority of these refugees have been
surviving on wild fruits and greens.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, about 60,000 people have trickled into Wau in search
of food. Many are on their last legs after traveling long distances
from northern Bahr el Ghazal. Several other towns where the United
Nations has set up feeding centers have become magnets for starving
people throughout the region, including Ajiep, Panthou and Mapel.
</P>
<P>
   The current crisis began in February, when local warlord
Kerubino Kuanyin Bol, who had been fighting for the government,
rejoined the rebellion and attacked the garrison in Wau. That set
off a new round of violence in Sudan's seemingly endless civil war
between the Moslem north and the predominantly Christian south.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting exacerbated an already dismal situation. After two
years of drought and bad harvests, most farmers in Bahr el Ghazal
had few seed stores left to plant when 1998 began, and while the
people in this flat savannah usually face lean months in June and
July, constant cattle raids and guerrilla fighting in recent years
has undermined their traditional ways of getting through hungry
times.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of refugees from Wau and other insecure regions
overburdened communities whose food resources were already
stretched to the limit, aid workers say.
</P>
<P>
   Most families in the region have eaten all the seed stores they
had planned to use for planting. Others have lost most of their
cattle in raids by Arab militias allied with the government and
rogue rebel factions over the last decade of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the traditional coping mechanisms are shot,'' said
Ted Chaban, the deputy chief of operations for the U.N. Childrens'
Fund in southern Sudan. ``There is definitely a famine in certain
pockets of Bahr El Ghazal and there are a larger number of places
in a pre-famine mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Islamic government in Khartoum and the main rebel
faction _ the Sudan People's Liberation Army, led by John Garang _
agreed to a one-month cease-fire to help relief reach the hungry,
but aid officials say the truce has come too late. The rainy season
has finally arrived, a month late in many places, making it nearly
impossible for aid workers to deliver food on the ground in any
cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a complete halt in fighting, aid officials said, there
remain major logistical barriers on the transportation routes into
the region, from flooded roads, to bandits along rail lines, to
clogged river channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis for the aid agencies is far from over,'' said
Michelle Quintaglie, a spokeswoman for the World Food Program.
``Even if everyone laid down their weapons right now, we would not
be able to rush in there with thousands of tons of food because of
the terrain we are dealing with in Sudan.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, four huge C-130 cargo planes take off from a base
at Lokichoggio in northern Kenya while a fifth flies out of El
Obeid in northern Sudan, carrying tons of grain in the largest
airlift of food in the World Food Program's history.
</P>
<P>
   The planes fly to 38 locations in Bahr el Ghazal and drop tons
of food in 100-pound bags. Aid workers on the ground distribute the
food to starving children at emergency clinics as well as parceling
it out to the general population.
</P>
<P>
   The airlift operation alone is costing more than $21 million a
month, and though 12,000 tons have been shipped into the region in
the last three months, more is needed to avert a full-scale
catastrophe, U.N. officials say.
</P>
<P>
   With another poor harvest predicted for this fall, relief
officials say they expect the airlift will have to continue through
at least another 18 months to avert a cataclysmic famine like the
one that killed nearly 250,000 people in Sudan in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   It was that crisis that prompted the United Nations to set up
Operation Lifeline Sudan, the relief operation that is still in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   The current phase of Sudan's civil war has been dragging on
since 1983, and more than 1.5 million people have died in fighting
and in two previous famines spawned by the violence.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing consensus among diplomats and U.N. officials
that famines like the one taking root here are inevitable as long
as the war grinds on and peace talks founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solution to this won't come from humanitarian
intervention, it has to be political,'' said Carol Bellamy, the
executive director of the U.N. Children's Fund, who visited Wau and
other distribution sites here this week. ``The pressure for
resolving this war has to come from outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who maintain they represent the majority in the
mostly Christian and animist south, say they have been fighting to
free themselves from what they see as a repressive Islamic regime
in Khartoum, dominated by people of Arab origin.
</P>
<P>
   But while rebel leaders say they are struggling for religious
freedom, a secular government and more autonomy, their movement has
been crippled for years by factional fighting and tribal divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Several rounds of talks have failed to produce peace. Last year,
the Khartoum government signed a separate peace accord with six
Southern rebel factions, agreeing to lift Islamic laws in the south
and to hold a referendum on independence within four years.
</P>
<P>
   But Garang's Sudan People's Liberation Army has continued to
fight, arguing the government's promises are nothing but tricks to
buy time and divide the rebellion. A fresh round of talks is
scheduled to take place in Addis Ababa next month, and an extended
ceasefire is likely to be on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   For many people in Bahr el Ghazal, a peace agreement cannot come
soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   The children are the first to die. In the town of Mapel, three
children are dying each week at a feeding center for the severely
malnourished run by Doctors Without Borders.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, there were dozens of shrunken children at the center
receiving emergency rations. Sitting on plastic sheets in the dust
of a shady grove, tired mothers spoon-fed emaciated babies formula
and gruel.
</P>
<P>
   One infant, Aken Akol, was near death. His cheeks were sunken
into his miniature face, and his body had been reduced to a
birdlike skeleton covered with wrinkled skin. An aid worker poured
a sugar-and-salt solution into his mouth, which he gulped
desperately. His mother, Angam Mawien, sat next to them, too
malnourished to produce milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what has happened,'' his mother, Angam Mawien,
said, pinching her empty breasts. ``God has created a drought.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many towns affected by the crisis, Mapel is a paradox.
Since the rains arrived two weeks ago, the place has turned green
and lush. The people are surviving fairly well and have pinned
their hopes on the next harvest. But they have nothing extra to
give to the displaced who have arrived hungry and without
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have big problems here,'' said Peter Madhieu, a civilian
official in Mapel. ``Many people have migrated from other counties
because of hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   A hundred miles to the north, a similar scene has unfolded in
the village of Panthou, where at least a quarter of the children
are severely malnourished despite the fact that local farmers have
a good crop of corn coming up.
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the promise of food, thousands of starving people have
been pouring into Panthou from other parts of Aweil and Gogrial
counties. Many have been pushed by Arab militias who have been
raiding Dinka villages along a nearby railway since April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is good because the crops are growing well, as long
as the rains continue this way,'' one elder in Panthou, Kuol Chuny,
said. ``But the little being cultivated here will not be enough to
feed all these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Deng Deng, a farmer in his 30s, arrived in Panthou last weekend
with his stick-thin wife and two children. His youngest child died
of malnutrition a week earlier in their home region of Aguak, where
he said people are living on leaves and tamarind beans.
</P>
<P>
   Deng said he failed to plant a crop last year because raids by
Kerubino's forces forced him to a flee his home for several months.
Then in April, his cattle were stolen by Arab militias from the
north, who call themselves Public Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no grain, and I have no cows I can sell,'' he
explained, moving his hands with the slow-motion gestures of the
starving. ``I didn't plant last year because of Kerubino. I am here
because you are here, dropping food from the sky, feeding people.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Kerubino's decision in February to rejoin Garang's rebel
movement that touched off the latest fighting, and even though he
is now in the rebel camp, many people here trace the current crisis
to the incessant looting his faction perpetrated in 1997 when he
was fighting on the government's side.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the starving people who arrived in Wau on Tuesday
said they came from regions in northern Bahr el Ghazal that had
been raided first by Kerubino's forces, then by the Arab militias
this year. Some even accused Garang's forces of looting their
stores as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months ago all my cattle were stolen by Arab militia
raiders,'' said Manyuat Akol, a 50 year old man from the Kowach
region who no longer had the strength to stand. ``All my seeds are
gone. The little I had to eat has been stolen by everyone,
including the rebel soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Ajok Tong, a 38 year old woman from the village of
Lukluk, was grieving the deaths of two children she lost on the
walk to Wau.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to eat where we are,'' she said. ``People are
living on wild food. There has been no rain for us to cultivate. So
we came here for food, for survival.''
</P>
</TEXT>
