<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-550&AMP;ADD     07-23 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAK QUARTERLY EARNINGS FOR AT&AMP;T 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ AT&AMP;T Corp. announced quarterly earnings Thursday that
modestly exceeded analysts' expectations. But its sales continued
to grow at an anemic rate, reinforcing concerns about plans by the
telephone giant to keep pace in the fast-growing communications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The weak revenue results were overshadowed in financial markets
by AT&AMP;T's announcement that it would buy back up to $3 billion
worth of its stock. The repurchase plan is an attempt to reduce the
dilution of AT&AMP;T earnings that would be caused by the pending $31.8
billion acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's No. 2
cable television company behind Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the repurchase announcement, AT&AMP;T shares, the most
widely held in the nation, gained 93.75 cents, closing at $58.625
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-term issue facing AT&AMP;T is how to grow at a rate
equal to that of the overall telecommunications industry. Though
AT&AMP;T remains the No. 1 long-distance phone carrier, it has lost
share in the long-distance market every year since 1984. In the
second quarter, revenue from its consumer long-distance business
declined by 3.7 percent from the comparable period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The company has made bids to expand into new areas, such as
local phone service, but those efforts have yet to generate much
revenue. Most analysts think that C. Michael Armstrong, who took
over as the company's chairman last fall, is making many of the
right moves. But even Armstrong says AT&AMP;T must accelerate its
revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not growing enough,'' he said Thursday in a
conference call with analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, AT&AMP;T sales were $12.86 billion, only 1.02
percent higher than the $12.73 billion reported during the
comparable period of last year.
</P>
<P>
   That growth represented an improvement from the first quarter,
when revenue grew by less than seven-tenths of a percent. But it
was still below the company's stated goal of increasing revenue
this year by 2 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the revenue shortfall in the first half, AT&AMP;T will have to
increase its growth rate substantially over the second half to meet
that target. To record an annual growth rate of 3 percent, for
instance, the company would have to increase revenue for the second
half by about 5.1 percent over the $25.62 billion in sales the
company posted over the last half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have got to have double-digit growth in this industry,''
said Eric Strumingher, a telecommunications analyst for Paine
Webber. ``That's the real issue for this company to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T says it has consciously sacrificed revenue by moving valued
customers to optional calling plans that offer lower rates while
de-emphasizing less-profitable customers who make fewer calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent a lot of time working on improving the quality
of our revenue base so we have a base we can grow off of,'' Daniel
Somers, AT&AMP;T's chief financial officer, said in an interview,
adding that the process of moving customers to special plans would
be mostly complete by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Somers estimates that the telecommunications industry is growing
at 8 percent a year and says AT&AMP;T intends to be growing at that
rate by the end of next year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A bright spot in the second quarter was AT&AMP;T's wireless
operation, which increased sales by 11.4 percent, to $1.24 billion.
A major factor that could propel revenue growth in the second half
of this year is AT&AMP;T's imposition of flat monthly fees on its
customers to help cover the cost of subsidizing communications
services in poor and rural areas and for schools and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the slow revenue growth, AT&AMP;T has been able to post
strong earnings gains by cutting costs. In the second quarter,
selling, general and administrative costs were 27.6 percent of
revenue, down from 30 percent in the comparable period of last
year. The reduction was caused partly by a program to cut the
number of employees. By the end of next year the company wants to
reduce that figure to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting one-time charges and gains, the company's continuing
operations (those that have not been sold) earned $1.49 billion, or
91 cents a diluted share, up 59.6 percent from 57 cents a share
during the second quarter of 1997. Analysts polled by First Call,
the financial research firm, had predicted a profit of 90 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Including special charges and gains, the company earned $1.15
billion, or 71 cents a diluted share, up 20.3 percent from 59 cents
during the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom Inc., the No. 4 long-distance company, also released
quarterly financial results Thursday. It earned $220.9 million, or
21 cents a share, up from $47.38 million, or 4 cents a share,
during the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom revenue grew by 45.3 percent, to $2.61 billion from
$1.8 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
