<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-HOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO OVERRIDE CLINTON VETO ON PARTIAL-BIRTH ABORTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted Thursday to override President
Clinton's veto of a ban on so-called partial-birth abortions as
Republican leaders made good on an election-year promise to force
another legislative showdown on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 296-132, was largely symbolic since even supporters of
the ban concede that they do not have enough support in the Senate
to override the veto there.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up the issue after it returns
from its Labor Day recess in September. But supporters of the ban
say they likely will fall at least three votes short of the 67
needed to repeat the House action.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote, which marked the second time in two years that
the Republican-controlled chamber had voted to override a Clinton
veto of the ban, energized anti-abortion forces and turned up the
pressure on the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tate, executive director of the Christian Coalition, said
his organization would begin lobbying senators hard to ``reaffirm
our most fundamental right as Americans _ the right to life.''
</P>
<P>
   In a May meeting with leaders of the religious right, who had
threatened to withhold their support in the fall elections,
Republican House leaders promised to put the abortion issue ``front
and center'' on their agenda for the rest of the year. They
delivered on that promise in the abortion debate, as Republican
supporters of the ban painted in highly emotional and graphic terms
why they feel the late-term abortion procedure, where a fetus is
partly delivered feet first and then aborted with an incision to
the base of the skull, should be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's vote today to defend those little babies who cannot
defend themselves,'' said Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, who called the
procedure, known medically as intact dilation and extraction, ''a
violent and gruesome act`` that involves the ``killing of a baby
just seconds before it takes its first breath outside the womb.''
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., went
further, labeling it ``infanticide.'' He called the procedure an
example of the nation's moral decay and said those who perform or
view it as an acceptable medical procedure must have ``a heart of
stone and soul of ice.''.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote against this motion (to override the veto) is to
legitimize an ... unspeakable cruelty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the ban, however, questioned the timing of the motion
to override and accused Republicans of playing politics with the
lives and health of women. They said the decisions about late-term
or any other kinds of abortion procedures should be left to women
and their physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation puts the lives of women at risk and it
tramples on the constitutional right of every woman in this
nation,'' said Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., adding that Congress should
not interfere in such a ``personal decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people realize this is something you do not go lightly
into,'' said Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, adding that the
procedure is used rarely and to help save the life or protect the
health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are arguing for is the right of the woman, with her
doctor, her God and her family, to choose what is best for her,''
Jackson Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of us support this procedure,'' said Rep.
Ken Bentsen, D-Texas. But he agreed that it was sometimes necessary
to protect a woman's health.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen called the Republican attempt to criminalize the
procedure an election-year ploy aimed at appeasing the religious
right at the expense of women faced with painful and difficult
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this is about. It is not about the health of
women. This is politics pure and simple and it is about as indecent
as this House can get,'' Bentsen said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill banning partial-birth abortions, vetoed for the second
time by Clinton last October, addresses only one specific medical
procedure and makes no exception for the life or health of the
mother. But it does not prohibit other forms of late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have introduced a bipartisan alternative bill
that would prohibit all late-term abortions, except in cases where
the life or health of the woman is at risk. But the Republican
leadership has so far refused to allow a vote on that measure.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said that he would sign a bill prohibiting
all late-term abortions if it allows exemptions to protect the
health of the woman. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
