<SLUG> BC-SHEPARD-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA TO HOLD MEMORIAL FOR SHEPARD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A memorial service for Mercury astronaut Alan B.
Shepard Jr, who died earlier this week, is planned for Aug. 1 in
Houston, NASA said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The service at NASA's Johnson Space Center will be limited to
members of Shepard's family, invited dignitaries and space agency
employees.
</P>
<P>
   However, the memorial will be televised on NASA-TV, said space
agency spokesman Rob Navias. Other details of the memorial still
were being planned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, 74, died late Tuesday, following a lengthy illness at a
California hospital near his home in Pebble Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On May 5, 1961, Shepard became the first American in space. A
decade later on his second and final trip into space, Shepard
became one of only a dozen humans to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a spokesman for Shepard's wife, Louise, said funeral
services for the astronaut will be private.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be private, with family only. As to the date and the
place, those plans will not be made public,'' said spokesman Howard
Benedict, who serves as the executive director of the Astronaut
Scholarship Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was founded by Shepard and the other Mercury
astronauts, or their surviving family members, to assist college
students interested in science and engineering careers.
</P>
<P>
   The Shephard family has requested that in lieu of flowers
donations be made to the foundation. The organization is
headquartered at 6225 Vectorspace Boulevard, Titusville, Fla.,
32780.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
