<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0048 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-23 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MESSAGES FROM THE MISSILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAN and IRAN-U.S.) 
(bl) 
 By A.M. ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The missile launched by Iran on Wednesday had a payload of
messages to nations around the world _ other Muslim nations of the
Middle East, Israel, Europe, the United States _ and to the Iranian
people.
</P>
<P>
   Among the messages was the military intelligence coming from the
launch.
</P>
<P>
   The range was 800 to 900 miles. Almost every Middle Eastern
country is now within reach of the missiles that Iran manufactured
from components bought abroad. And so now are all U.S. forces in
the Mideast, or ever likely to be.
</P>
<P>
   The missile was reported in the West as sold by North Korea,
China's dependency. But before the test launch, Israeli
intelligence knew, and has told the West, that components from
Russia were also in the missile. It was sent off from a mobile
launcher, hard to spot, harder to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   Washington says it will keep trying to prevent missile parts and
technology from reaching Iran. Dandy. But America and its European
partners have not even been able to stop Bulgaria, Cuba, China and
other countries from supplying weapons to Ethiopia and Eritrea, now
at war again. Compared with the allure of the buying power and
world-roving salesmen of Iran, the Africans are a penny-candy
machine.
</P>
<P>
   The West estimates that Iran needs at least five more years to
produce missiles that could reach Europe with chemical and
bacteriological weapons. Unfortunately Iran, Iraq, North Korea and
similar political garden spots have a way of suddenly jumping up
and saying ``Look what we have!'' while the democracies are still
staring at the mirage of a safety gap.
</P>
<P>
   Each recipient of a message from the missile will react in its
own way. The Saudis did not really need the warning. They have
moved from being a prime Iranian target to attending an Islamic
conference in Iran. As they dine at parties in the Saudi Embassy in
Washington, American guests might remember that their hosts refuse
to give the United States information that would link Iran to the
murder of U.S. soldiers in their apartment building in Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Israel got the small compensation of confirmation of years of
warning about Iranian plans for missiles with far greater range
than the stockpile of Iran's Scuds.
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare of Israelis opposing a Palestinian state is that
such a state will open itself to Muslim troops or terrorists from
other countries, particularly Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The missile launch will strengthen Israelis who believe that for
that reason alone Israel should not agree to a Palestinian state _
not even if the rest of the world recognizes it.
</P>
<P>
   So the missile could make Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
life even more difficult and peace harder to reach _ both the
passionate intent of the ayatollah government that rules Iran.
</P>
<P>
   To Iranians, the missile carried the plain message that those
ayatollahs were the rulers of Iran, not the comparatively moderate
elected president, Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami and Washington have put out tentative feelers about
Iranian-U.S. talks. But to hold them he would need approval of the
ayatollahs, who run the police, armed forces and missile
production. They also decide on such matters as the number of
lashes and years in prison that were the sentence Thursday of the
former mayor of Tehran, a supporter of Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has said the United States
has certain thoughts about U.S.-Iranian relations, which seem to
amount to conditions for talks _ particularly the end of Iran's
role as chief terrorist against America, Israel, Germany, Turkey,
Argentine Jews and other targets that make the ayatollahs salivate.
Khatami's foreign minister said that was Cold War talk.
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, the former Soviet political prisoner who is now
an Israeli Cabinet member, says the Soviet empire was kept alive an
extra 20 years by the power of fear and appearance of might that
came with its missiles and warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's ayatollahs rule by terror at home and terror exported.
They count on terror to extend their reign a lot more than 20
years. Their end will come not by suicide _ the voluntary surrender
of terrorist power by bomb, lash or missile. The end will come when
the Iranian people overthrow them.
</P>
<P>
   They did not intend it, but that was the most important message
sent by the ayatollahs, on that missile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
