<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Friday, July 24. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
FARM KIDS (Undated) - A 4-year-old and 11 other children under 12
were found picking onions on Maricopa County, Ariz., farms during
surprise visits by federal Department of Labor investigators in
May. Last week, three growers and three farm labor contractors were
fined nearly $20,000 for violating child labor laws. Nationwide,
this is a hidden but common practice on commercial farms. The
Arizona sweeps were part of federal crackdown on use of child
farmworkers. So far this year, 50 young children have been found
working on farms in Texas, New Mexico and Louisiana in addition to
those in Arizona. By GRACIELA SEVILLA. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
VISAS (Washington) - The Senate agreed Thursday to delay for five
years a planned ``laser-card visa'' that Arizona officials feared
would stifle trade by making it too costly for Mexican shoppers to
cross the border. The new agreement also would waive the $45 cost
of the card for children under 15. Arizona border towns are
relieved. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SYMINGTON-VACATION (Phoenix) - Former Gov. Fife Symington,
convicted of bank and wire fraud, wants to spend a leisurely
Christmas vacation in Honduras. Fedearl prosecutors stand in his
way, telling a federal judge in briefs filed Thursday that
Symington does not deserve to have his passport restored. By PAT
FLANNERY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DEATH AWARD (Undated) - A jury returned an $8 million verdict
Thursday against Southwest Gas Co. in the death of an 11-year-old
boy who was was killed by a drunk driver in a Rolls Royce on a
Scottsdale, Ariz., street. Southwest Gas failed to take precautions
for pedestrians when it ripped up a street to do some work.
Christopher ``Kip'' Turner and his dad, Ted, were forced to walk in
the road to get around the construction site, which ultimately cost
the boy his life, attorneys for Kip parents argued. His parents,
Ted Turner and Deborah Luck, were each awarded $4 million in the
verdict. By VICKY HARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAR DEALERS (Undated) - Arizona dealers in General Motors cars and
trucks find supplies on vehicles and mostly parts getting tight,
though it's not as bad in Arizona as it is in some other parts of
the country. The hot-selling Suburbans and Yukons are gone, in some
cases, and customers' cars are stacking up waiting for parts. Worse
is the public perception that dealers are out of cars entirely or
trying to gouge customers for scarce vehicles, resulting in empty
showrooms and and lax sales for July. Reskedded from Wednesday. By
BOB GOLFEN. Story will move in the ``F`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GENRICH-COLUMN (Undated) - Studies show that children who have been
in day careare likely to suffer a series of health maladies. But
now comes a theory that attendance at day care contributes to
children misbehaving badly. By MARK GENRICH.Story will move in the
`K` category. &QL;
