<BODY>
 THE EX GAMES  
 By WILLIAM SALETAN 
 (www.slate.com) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This month a coalition of conservative Christian groups placed
ads in national newspapers arguing that gays could be ``healed'' of
their homosexuality through religious therapy. ``We're standing for
the truth that homosexuals can change,'' said one ad. ``I'm living
proof that Truth can set you free,'' said another, which featured a
self-described former lesbian. The ads quoted Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, who recently likened homosexuality to alcoholism
and kleptomania.
</P>
<P>
   The media and gay rights groups pounced on the ads, treating
them as a religious-right ploy to raise money and rouse the
anti-gay rabble for the 1998 elections. They also suggested the ads
were simply false. On ``This Week,'' Sam Donaldson compared the
proposition that ``homosexuals can change'' to the proposition that
``the world is flat.'' On ``Face the Nation,'' Elizabeth Birch,
executive director of the Human Rights Campaign, a gay rights
group, said, ``I resent these ads because they present gay and
lesbian Americans as damaged goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Both critiques miss the point. Start with the accusation that
the ads are just a fund-raising scheme for anti-gay groups.
Contrary to this naive cynicism, the shrewdness of the ads isn't in
their motive. It's in their message: not that gays are wicked but
that they should be taken seriously when they choose to redefine
themselves. This marks a strategic inflection point in the debate
over gay rights. The basis for judging the propriety of a person's
sexual orientation is shifting from an intuitive, objective
standard (orthodoxy) to an empirical, subjective standard
(happiness). This puts the anti-gay movement on firmer footing for
now but, as we will see, it comes at a price.
</P>
<P>
   It's equally naive to dismiss the ex-gay movement as a total
fraud. As Bill Kristol succinctly put it on ``This Week,'' ``These
people exist.'' On ``Face the Nation,'' anti-gay activist Gary
Bauer explained: ``I have met hundreds of people who were in that
lifestyle and are now out and are married, have children, and are
living happy lives as married couples. How do we argue with that?''
Indeed, many of us are indirectly if not directly familiar with the
proverbial college lesbian who has since married a male investment
banker and has two kids. Maybe she's really a lesbian, maybe she's
not. But who are we to say?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of denying the ex-gay movement, gay rights advocates
would be wiser to embrace the paradigm shift it represents.
Consider the analogy of ``post-abortion syndrome.'' Years ago,
pro-lifers began to organize and promote groups of women who
regretted their abortions and had decided never to repeat the
experience. Rather than dismiss those women, abortion rights
advocates learned to embrace and recast them as exemplars of
choice. These women had every right to choose not to have
abortions, the pro-choicers conceded. But by the same token, other
women should have the right to choose the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-gay movement presents a similar opportunity. ``Gays came
out of the closet 25 years ago,'' Kristol observed. ``Now
ex-gays--I don't know how many, there clearly are hundreds, maybe a
few thousand--are coming out of the closet and saying, 'In every
case at least, homosexuality is not genetically ingrained.' They
have a right to say this.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they do. But this principle, newly embraced by the right,
goes both ways: It's OK to be yourself, and it's not OK for someone
else to deny your experience and your choice. On ``This Week,''
Clarence Page reported that one of the activists who had funded the
ex-gay ads ``said he doubts that two-thirds of those who have
changed (to become heterosexual) are going to stay changed; ...
most of them will go back.'' And if they do, what can Kristol and
Bauer say?
</P>
<P>
   On July 19, the Human Rights Campaign replied with its own
newspaper ad. It features a photograph of a mother, father, and
their adult lesbian daughter over the headline ``We're living proof
that families with lesbian and gay kids can be whole, happy and
worthy of all that this great country promises.'' But someone is
missing from the photograph: The couple's other daughter, who, as
they explain in the ad's fine print, ``happens to be
heterosexual.'' Both daughters were permitted to discern and define
their identities. One decided she was gay; the other decided she
was straight. Religious conservatives now claim to be fighting for
the right to make the latter decision. It will be hard for them,
with a straight face, to justify opposing the former.
</P>
<P>
   -------
 &UR; (WILLIAM SALETAN writes ``The Week/The Spin'' column for Slate.)
 &UR; Copyright 1998 Slate &QL;  Visit Slate on the Web at:
http:www.slate.com &QL;  (Distributed by New York Times Special
Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
