<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENRICH-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEE A MALADJUSTED CHILD? LOOK AT TIME SERVED IN DAY CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK GENRICH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - I have a theory about children raised in day-care
centers.
</P>
<P>
   My theory is based upon empirical evidence, nothing scientific.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a few observations by some experts:
</P>
<P>
   Karl Zinsmeister, editor in chief of the journal``American
Enterprise'' and a fellow at the American Enterprise Institute _
someone who believes that it is ``unwise'' to encourage the use of
day care _ points to an ``American Journal of Public Health''
report indicating children in day-care centers incur overall
medical expenses that are two to three times as high as those of
children cared for at home.
</P>
<P>
   A Rand Corp. study that analyzed data on 3,841 children ages 6
months to 5 years showed that attending a day-care center
``increases bed days for young children by 30 percent,'' while
youngsters attending home-based day care have 19 percent more bed
days (both compared to parent-reared children).
</P>
<P>
   A 1990 poll of U.S. pediatricians conducted by the Thomas
Jefferson School of Medicine in Philadelphia showed that 77 percent
believe babies 6 months or younger ought to be cared for only at
home.
</P>
<P>
   A different survey of 1,100 baby doctors carried out that same
year by the American Academy of Pediatricians reported that a
``substantial majority of physicians consider full-time day care
harmful for children under age 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Another expert writing in the ``Wall Street Journal'' earlier
this year pointed to the National Institute of Child Health and
Human Development study involving 1,364 children from 10 states
including diverse ethnic and socioeconomic back grounds. It
reported that a child's placement in day care provided a
``significant prediction'' of poorer mother-child interaction and
reduced cognitive and linguistic development.
</P>
<P>
   Another study at Pennsylvania State University found that
full-time day-care babies are at risk of ``heightened
aggressiveness, non-compliance and withdrawal in the preschool and
early school years.''
</P>
<P>
   So here's my theory about day care:
</P>
<P>
   The obnoxious, noisy child who is kicking the back of your
airline seat probably has some day-care experience. Perhaps the
most disturbing element about this theory is that these children
seem to be everywhere, taken to quiet restaurants, movie theaters,
plays, places of worship, graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   They are taken by parents in search of ``quality time'' with
their day-care children. It no longer seems to matter how young the
child is, it doesn't seem to matter how ill-behaved, rude, sick or
obstreperous.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Zinsmeister emphasizes that not all children who go into
day care will end up with ``weak parental bonds, aggressive
tendencies, academic problems, personal insecurities, difficulties
in peer relations, or other evidence of emotional or cognitive
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   He says lots will bounce through with few obvious effects.
Individual circumstances like a youngster's temperment, sex, and
home influences all determine how a child fares.
</P>
<P>
   But empirical data suggest that the screamer in the booth across
from you at the restaurant, or that whining child in the church pew
a few aisles back _ the one who refused attendance in the cry room
_ has some day care in his or her background.
</P>
<P>
   No public function seems to be off-limits for attendance by
unruly children. In days gone by, obstinate children were kept at
home until they could behave _ either that or they were immediately
removed from a public setting if they offended those nearby. Not
anymore. This widespread misbehavior seems rooted in parents who
surrender responsibility to day care for reasons that range from
necessity to greed to parental self-centeredness.
</P>
<P>
   But, remember, this is just a theory. &QL; 
Mark Genrich is an editorial writer for the Arizona Republic. He
can be reached at MLGEDIT(at)AOL.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
