<HEADER>
A0104 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAKER-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-23 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STRANGE CHANGE OF VENUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RUSSELL BAKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I am amazed to learn that Art Buchwald, dean of
American humor columnists, has moved to New York. Buchwald's home
base has been Washington ever since the British burned the White
House. They would have gone ahead and burned Georgetown too, he
wrote, but it was teatime.
</P>
<P>
   He is such a fixture down there that anybody who mentions the
Washington Monument is assumed to be talking about Buchwald. Who
could imagine Buchwald moving to New York? Would the pope move to
Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   With his flair for irony, Buchwald has already solved the first
problem facing everybody with New York in mind: finding a place to
live. Too stingy to pay $2 million for $115 worth of living space,
he has booked into a flossy Park Avenue hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does this reduce his real estate costs; it also saves
him from having to make his own bed.
</P>
<P>
   It also relieves him of the obligation to throw those famous New
York dinner parties where everybody talks about real estate through
soup, fish, meat, salad, cheese, no-calorie dessert, decaf coffee
and piteous pleas for mercy from the dishwashers.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago I took a youthful fling at trying to write
humor myself and tried to cultivate Buchwald and learn his secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no secret to writing humor about Washington,'' he
told me. ``You just write what happened in Washington yesterday and
the whole country will die laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd heard old recordings of Will Rogers speaking that line back
in the 1930s. ``I'm not surprised,'' said Buchwald. ``I told it to
Will when he was first trying to break into the business back
during the McKinley administration.''
</P>
<P>
   My attempts to cotton up to the old master were only mildly
successful. The high point of our relationship came the day at the
Sans Souci restaurant across the street from the White House when
he invited me to his table to gaze upon several Kennedys, a brace
of senators, a Supreme Court justice, Charlton Heston and Barbara
Walters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I'll ever be able to repay this favor, Mr.
Buchwald,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call me Art,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the favor can be repaid at last. As a onetime
Washingtonian who came to New York full of doubt and terror and
learned to survive and love it, I have valuable advice for this
pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, never make eye contact with anyone, Art, until
absolutely certain that you're not dealing with a lunatic or a
cabdriver. ``Never look a weirdo in the eye,'' is the ancient
wisdom taught New Yorkers for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Cabdrivers may or may not be weirdos, but when they see a
pedestrian crossing the street and that pedestrian looks them in
the eye, they assume that this pedestrian is now fully aware that
lethal machinery is aimed at him and is, therefore, responsible for
taking the evasive action necessary to save his skin.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Art, I would never walk in neighborhoods where you can
look up and see a construction crane looming 500 feet overhead.
These things often fall down. Make a detour.
</P>
<P>
   In my New York era, I also used to avoid skyscrapers with the
kind of glass windows that blow out on windy days and make a
terrible mess on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if windows still blow out in high wind. Maybe
windows are better nowadays. All I say is that, when the wind is
rising, personally, I still stay away from skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   In my time, there was a gent in the theater district who dropped
chunks of concrete from roofs, and I stayed out of that
neighborhood until I judged that his need to express himself by
mashing somebody under concrete had taken another outlet.
</P>
<P>
   You can never predict when someone like the concrete-dropper
will crop up in this great city. Wise New Yorkers read the daily
papers closely and react accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Many people's worst New York nightmare is of being trapped
several hours in an elevator during a power blackout.
</P>
<P>
   The survival trick here is to insist on transacting all business
at ground level. You'll be astonished how many people will come
down 45 stories to see you. It gives them something besides real
estate to talk about at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, I forgot the subway. Take the subway, Art. It's terrific.
And whatever you do, don't joke about Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. This
is not Washington. Understand? The cops have their orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
