<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-ABORTION-BOS &LR;      07-23 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OVERRIDES CLINTON ABORTION BILL VETO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move aimed at maximizing the impact of the
abortion issue in an election year, the House Thursday voted to
override President Clinton's veto of a bill that would outlaw a
procedure critics call a ``partial-birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   The 296-132 vote was 10 votes more than the two-thirds needed to
override, and the measure now goes to the Senate, where the outcome
is uncertain. The Senate, which will take up the bill in September
at the earliest, so far is three votes shy of the number needed to
override the veto.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Charles Canady, a Florida Republican and prime
sponsor of the vetoed bill, predicted an ``uphill battle'' in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not succeed in the Senate, we'll be back in the next
Congress,'' he said. ``I want to ban partial-birth abortion. We are
doing everything we can. Unfortunately, Bill Clinton has been
standing in our way every step of the way ... Think of the babies
who are subjected to this horrible practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving immediacy to the debate was the recent attempted abortion
in Arizona that resulted in the delivery of a baby girl. The
doctor, whose medical license has been suspended, had relied on a
miscalculation of how long the teenage mother had been pregnant.
The baby survived with lacerations to the face and a cracked skull,
and has been adopted..
</P>
<P>
   Although the House passed the bill last October, the override
vote was delayed until now to make it a campaign issue, said
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is about defeating Democrats and election-year
politics, pure and simple,'' said Representative Nita Lowey, a New
York Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Two Massachusetts Democrats, Representatives Richard Neal of
Springfield and J. Joseph Moakley of South Boston, supported the
ban and voted for the override. Representative Edward J.Markey, the
Malden Democrat, did not vote but previously opposed the ban. The
state's seven other House members voted against the override.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Cardinal Bernard Law, chairman of the Pro-Life Committee
for the US Roman Catholic Bishops, who have actively campaigned to
outlaw late-term abortions, said Thursday, ``No nation and no
Congress, can, in good conscience, permit the killing of
partly-born infants. Soon, the Senate will have the same
opportunity. We pray that the Senate will make the right choice.''
</P>
<P>
   In his veto message last year, Clinton said the bill was bad
public policy and unconstitutional. He vetoed the bill because the
ban did not include an exception to protect a woman's health.
Opponents to the ban say the procedure is sometimes the only
alternative to protect the health and fertility of a small number
of women with crisis pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill targets the most vulnerable women, women who want to
be mothers who have found that something has gone terribly wrong to
either them or their babies,'' said Representative Vic Fazio, a
California Democrat. ``None of us support late-term abortions for
no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would have imposed stiff fines and prison terms
of up to two years on physicians who use the procedure. It also
would have allowed the partner of a pregnant woman and the parents
of a minor girl to sue the doctor for monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's debate, supporters of the ban described the grisly
procedure, in which the skull of a fetus is collapsed to get the
fetus through the birth canal, while opponents focused on the
health needs of pregnant women and the precedent of outlawing a
specific medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killing a baby as it is about to be born is simply an act of
barbarity,'' said Representative Tim Roemer, an Indiana Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   There are no official statistics on the number of abortions
involving this procedure, but Representative James Greenwood, a
Pennsylvania Republican, displayed a chart showing that 99.94
percent of all abortions occur before the 24th week, when a fetus
has matured enough to live outside the womb.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is based on a fraud, and the fraud is that this
procedure is used frequently in late pregnancies,'' said Greenwood.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Sue Myrick, a Republican from North Carolina,
said, ``Partial birth abortion is a horrific way to end the life of
a tiny, 9-months- old baby. It has no place in a civilized
society.''
</P>
<P>
   And Representative Louise Slaughter, a New York Democrat, said,
``For the first time in the history of the republic, this congress
is trying to outlaw a medical procedure. Ask yourself, what is
next?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
