<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THRILL OF GETTING TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm having a fantastic time. I've never had such dynamic
meetings in my entire 19 years of being an editor in chief. The
meetings are so exciting right now.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tina Brown about her new job at Miramax, quoted in the New
York Observer, which also offers another possible reason why Si
Newhouse rescinded his offer of the New Yorker editorship to
Michael Kinsley of Slate: ``Mr. Kinsley showed up for dinner on
Sunday night in his hiking boots.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PISTACHIO MOCHA CHIP PERSONALITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A survey taken by  &UR; Alan Hirsch  &LR; of the Smell &AMP; Taste Treatment
and Research Foundation, reported in Details magazine, has
determined that:
</P>
<P>
   _ People who like vanilla ice cream are gregarious but basically
private people.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who like double chocolate chunk ice cream are lively,
bored with routine and easily influenced.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who like banana cream pie ice cream are perfect.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who like chocolate chip ice cream are competitive and
can't stand losing.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who like butter pecan ice cream are perfectionists and
sexually reserved.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who like strawberries and cream ice cream are shy and
pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A source told People magazine that  &UR; Paula Jones &LR; ' recent
plastic surgery will result in ``a much smaller nose, and it will
look much more natural.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jon Dakss &LR; , an MIT graduate student who was such a fan of Sly
and the Family Stone that he created www.slyfamstone.com, was
contacted by the reclusive Sly ( &UR; Sylvester Stewart &LR; ), who asked him
for help in learning how to use the Internet. Dakss told Rolling
Stone that Stewart, who disappeared as a public persona more than
10 years ago, flew him to Los Angeles for a weekend of computer
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new computer noun, named after the woman whose exploits were
exploited by Internet news sources, is the ``Lewinsky.'' One equals
a trillion bits of information.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a story about larger disposable diapers, Advertising Age
reports that only 22 percent of children are potty trained nowadays
by the age of 2 1/2; in 1961, 90 percent were potty trained by that
age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COLOR PURPLE WAS JUST TOO MUCH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A new line of PMS nail polish, created by  &UR; Janai Lane &LR;  of the
San Francisco company Respect, has aroused the wrath of some
vendors in the Midwest. PMS stands for Polish Mood Shades; the nine
colors ($12 each) in the line change color with the wearers'
``moods,'' or heat, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you PMSing again, Susan?'' says a cartoon figure in an
advertising card for the product. ``Yes,'' says Susan, ``my nails
just changed to Bloated Blue.'' Among the changes: Vexed Violet
becomes Self-Centered Silver; Nympho Navy becomes Groaning Green;
Gotta Have Chocolate becomes Estrogen Emerald.
</P>
<P>
   At a PMS demonstration at a Dayton-Hudson store in Minnesota,
the sales clerks _ ``right wing sort of women,'' says Lane _ told a
Respect marketing officer that they were offended by Pyst-off
Purple. Shortly afterward, the Dayton-Hudson chain returned all
bottles of that color.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said she had no problem with the return. ``That color's the
most popular everywhere else. We just sent it elsewhere.'' PMS is
available at Raison d'Etre in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INFORMATION PULEEZE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A team of high-tech merrymakers is out with In Formation, a
satiric magazine just born in San Francisco and published on the
premise that ``every day, computers are making people easier to
use.'' The staff members are volunteers, most of whom work day jobs
in Silicon Valley start-ups. Ten thousand copies of issue No. 1
were funded primarily by editor/publisher &UR; David Temkin  &LR; of AtHome,
where many of the volunteers toil.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stories in the premiere issue is an investigative
report on the bar-coding of fish, an expose about the In-n-Out
business school and a Harper's Index parody, ``Numbers of the
Beast'':
</P>
<P>
   Since the number of the beast is 666, posits In Formation, 668
is the neighbor of the beast, 660 is the approximate number of the
beast, 1-666 is the area code of the beast, $699.25 is the price of
the beast plus 5 percent sales tax, 666i is the BMW of the beast,
and so forth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
