<HEADER>
A0115 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      07-23 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAWLEY FAILS TO APPEAR AT PENALTY HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. - The Tawana Brawley saga came sputtering to
its finale Thursday, much as it began 10 years ago _ with crowds of
people wondering, ``Where's Tawana?''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Stephen Jackson _ the lawyer for C. Vernon
Mason, one of the three Brawley advisers on trial here for falsely
accusing Stephen Pagones of abducting and raping Brawley in 1987 _
announced that Brawley would appear as a witness on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Jackson had to confess to a packed courtroom that
she was a no-show.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipation, then letdown, came near the end of the second
phase of this eight-month-long trial.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase ended 10 days ago, when the jury found Mason and
the other two advisers _ the Rev. Al Sharpton and Alton H. Maddox _
guilty of defaming Pagones' character.
</P>
<P>
   In the second phase, the jury will determine how much money the
three should pay him in damages. Pagones, who was an assistant
district attorney at the time of the accusations, is asking for
$395 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brawley has never testified about her accusations, which set off
some of the most bitter tensions of a racially charged decade. She
and her mother refused to cooperate with a 1988 grand jury, which
exonerated Pagones and concluded that Brawley _ who, like her three
advisers, is black _ had probably concocted her story about six
white men raping her and scrawling obscenities on her body.
</P>
<P>
   During the first phase of the trial, Judge S. Barrett Hickman
invited Brawley _ who is now 26 and living in Maryland _ to
testify. But she never replied.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson surprised everyone _ including, it seemed, his client's
co-defendants _ when he tried to invite her this week. At first,
Hickman denied the motion, saying it was too late; the question of
whether the rape happened, and whether the advisers lied about it,
had already been settled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the judge changed his mind _ as he has so often in
this drawn-out case _ and said her testimony might be pertinent,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Maddox, who is representing himself, disowned the
whole idea, saying he did not want Brawley to come to the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox is closer to Brawley and her family than are the other
two advisers. He was her lawyer, and last December, as the trial
got underway, Brawley made her first public appearance in a decade
at a Brooklyn rally in Maddox's honor.
</P>
<P>
   William Stanton, Pagones' lawyer, said Thursday he never
expected Brawley to appear. ``It's a poker game,'' he remarked.
Jackson was bluffing all along, ``and the judge said, `OK, I call
your hand.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Brawley had little incentive to appear. Stanton
declared that if she did appear and again accused Pagones of raping
her, he would file a complaint charging her with perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Brawley herself is a defendant in this case. Long
before the trial began, she was found liable by default for not
answering Pagones' subpoena. By testifying at all, she would be
opening herself up to cross-examination about the entire case.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen black supporters of Maddox, who have regularly
been coming up to the trial by train or chartered buses, seemed
disappointed by Brawley's absence Thursday. But several defended
her in angry tones when questioned afterward by the nearly
all-white press corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the devil!'' one black man, who identified himself only
as ``a brother from ancient Egypt,'' said of Pagones. ``Why would
she want to come here and look at the face of the devil?''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers on both sides are scheduled to give closing statements
Friday before the jurors _ four whites and two blacks _ head off to
their final round of deliberations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
