<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MCCURRY-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCURRY TO DEPART AS WHITE HOUSE PRESS SECRETARY  
 (bl)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sign of growing confidence at the White House
that it is weathering the Monica Lewinsky investigation, Mike
McCurry, who has used an agile wit and aggressive tactics to
promote the administration and defend it from scandal, will resign
as press secretary this fall, President Clinton announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The president referred Thursday to McCurry's skill at gliding
just beyond a question's reach. ``His ability to respond to
developments precisely _ and, when necessary, not so precisely _
have made him a unique and instrumental element of our nation's
public diplomacy around the world,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   With that sort of sleight-of-mouth, along with a lopsided grin
and a sharp appreciation for the needs of news organizations,
McCurry has managed to maintain cordial, respectful relations with
the press, even while insisting that he was ``out of the loop'' and
unable to answer questions about Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He will be replaced by Joseph Lockhart, who served as Clinton's
1996 campaign spokesman before becoming one of McCurry's deputies
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The transition, which will take place when Congress leaves in
October, is part of a broader White House changeover that has been
frozen since January, when Clinton was accused of having an affair
with Ms. Lewinsky and covering it up.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry and several other high-ranking Clinton advisers had
hoped to leave after the president's first term to take more
lucrative and less consuming jobs in the private sector. But they
delayed their departures for fear of creating an image of a White
House in panicked retreat.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``For a lot of us, there was a period of time in the beginning
and the first half of the year that it felt like it wasn't the
right time to be leaving,'' one senior administration official
said, on condition of anonymity. ``But now we've sort of settled in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McCurry, Rahm Emanuel, a senior adviser to
Clinton, is planning to leave this fall. Two aides said that they
expect that chief of staff Erskine Bowles will also leave by the
November elections. And Doug Sosnik, a close adviser to Clinton, is
also considering departing _ though he has been doing so for so
long that he has joked he left and came back.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of how much turbulence has shaken the White
House this year that the departure of some of the president's most
trusted lieutenants would seem a sign of growing stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
