<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL LOG  
 FENDER-BENDERS ON THE DIGITAL HIGHWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My colleague claims she suffers from BLK _ Bad 'Lectronic Karma.
She believes that her mere presence causes electronic devices to
malfunction: ``If I so much as look at my VCR, the clock starts
blinking 12:00.''
</P>
<P>
   I know how she feels. I had one of those weeks where nothing
worked properly.
</P>
<P>
   My first instance of BLK came when I was testing two new
multifunction cards from 3Com. It was time to check out 56K modems.
</P>
<P>
   I've always liked the idea of PC Card modems because they make
it so easy to upgrade _ the cards pop into a slot on the side of a
laptop. And a multifunction or ``combo'' PC Card lets you have a
modem and a network interface card (NIC) in the same device,
meaning you can dial up a remote computer or hook into the office
network without switching cards. Putting these functions on one
card frees up a slot.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who attach to our company networks at various branch
offices need the flexibility of both dial-up and direct local-area
network connections.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially important to me because I have an external
CD-ROM drive and a Jaz disk drive. Both are SCSI devices, so I can
daisy-chain them off of a single PC Card SCSI adapter.
</P>
<P>
   Before using a combo card, I had to keep swapping the LAN card
and modem card if I needed to use the CD-ROM drive at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   The two 3Com cards both had 56K modems. One had a 10 megabits
per second (Mbps) network interface card with an Xjack connector.
The other had the dual-standard 10/100 Mbps card, with a big fat
plug or ``dongle'' for the modem connection.
</P>
<P>
   I happen to like the dongles on the 3Com cards. Unlike many
modem dongles which are small and easy to forget when you are
packing up your system in a hurry, the 3Com dongle is big enough
that it stands out, but is still small enough that it is not a
burden to carry.
</P>
<P>
   I tested the card with the Xjack connector first. It worked as
advertised: The card connected to our network without any problems,
and the modem dialed every remote service I use. One of my services
supports the V.90 standard for data transmission, and there was a
noticeable increase in my connection speed.
</P>
<P>
   The 10/100 Mbps card was another issue.
</P>
<P>
   The connection to the local network went fine, but when I tried
using the modem, it would not hold a connection or would not
connect at all.
</P>
<P>
   I went through all the diagnostics, which said that everything
was working properly. Windows reported that it was not conflicting
with any other device and was working perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to enter the voice-mail hell that is technical
support. I'm not singling out 3Com; I've had problems with the tech
support of just about every company in the computer business.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the quality of the technical support, it's the
automated phone system. Once you get a human on the phone, problems
are usually taken care of without much hassle.
</P>
<P>
   After the required preliminaries of ``press 1 if you want an
endless loop, press 2 if you want us to put you on hold for 10
minutes before disconnecting and requiring you to call back and
start over,'' I got through to an actual person.
</P>
<P>
   Dan was quite helpful and seemed to know his stuff. But he
couldn't get the modem to work either. He said he wanted to check
one other source, and asked if he could call me back in about 10
minutes. He called back in about three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   We tried a few more things, and he finally declared that the
modem was fine, but that the dongle was probably defective. He
would transfer me to the parts-replacement people, and they would
arrange to get me a new dongle. Two days later, it arrived, and the
modem now works fine.
</P>
<P>
   My second karma deficit hit when I tried to return a laptop.
When I finish with a computer that the manufacturer has sent me to
evaluate, I remove all the programs I installed while I was testing
it. I put a lot of stuff on these machines. They have to mirror my
regular working computer so that I can test them by doing all the
things that I would normally do.
</P>
<P>
   This cleanup usually takes place in my office, where I keep all
the installation disks of all my programs.
</P>
<P>
   While I had a particular reason for cleaning up the hard drive,
it is not a bad idea to periodically back up your hard drive, wipe
it, reformat it and reload everything from scratch. Your hard drive
works hard and gets banged around in cars, trains and planes. This
periodic cleanup _ about once a year or so _ allows it to operate a
little more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   On this occasion, I was doing the cleanup at home. I backed up
my data on my Jaz drive, then went to the Control Panel and clicked
on ``Add/Remove Programs.'' It was then a simple matter of clicking
on the programs I wanted to remove and watching the software do its
thing.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until I came to Microsoft Office 97 Professional. I was
told that I needed the original CD-ROM in order to remove the
program. The CD-ROM was back in the office. Nothing I tried could
get me past that error message.
</P>
<P>
   I finally broke down and called Microsoft Technical Support.
They were very helpful, but said that uninstalling Office without
the disc is not recommended and is for the technically astute. You
have to delete entries in the Registry _ a misstep here can cause
your system to stop working.
</P>
<P>
   After dealing with the Registry, you have to manually delete all
the Office folders and a long list of files in the system folder.
</P>
<P>
   I found the instructions on how to do this in the Microsoft
Knowledgebase, the company's online support area. Be sure to make a
backup of your Registry before you attempt to do this.
</P>
<P>
   Most people will never need to uninstall Office at all, let
alone without the disc, and (as they say in MSErrorSpeak) ``it is
strongly recommended'' that you have the disc if you have to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Let me second that recommendation. I got back to the office and
couldn't find the disk, so I had to follow the instructions. I did
it, but I never want to repeat the experience.
</P>
<P>
   My final BLK involved the long-awaited arrival of the Apple
PowerBook G3. Great, I thought, I can finally review the unit and
stop the weekly complaints from Mac enthusiasts who think I'm part
of the ``WinTel Conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The PowerBook came with the best system protector I've ever
seen. Instead of that white Styrofoam stuff, it rested on a
designer plastic air pillow. Way cool.
</P>
<P>
   After charging the battery, I turned on the unit and discovered
that the right shift key didn't work. I called Apple for a
replacement. Unfortunately, the new unit arrived a day after I had
left town for a week-long trip. This is not a conspiracy _ I really
do want to evaluate the G3.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBAR: RELATED SITES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
