<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-GROWNUPS-SURF-NET-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION 
 NEW AFTER-SCHOOL GIG: TEACHING GROWN-UPS HOW TO SURF 
</HEADLINE>
  By PAMELA MENDELS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to miss Joshua R. Hammer as he paces the floor of the
main branch of the Queens Borough Public Library in Queens, New
York. He's the clip-board toting 16-year-old with neatly-cropped
hair, a soft-spoken demeanor and a T-shirt bearing the motto: Ask
Me How to Search the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer, a computer user since he was 9 years old, is one of
about 90 high school students earning pocket money this summer and
throughout the school year by teaching befuddled patrons how to use
the library's online resources.
</P>
<P>
   Like other participants in the library's ``Teen 'Net Mentor''
program, he spends his time assisting people _ including
library-goers five times his age _ how to do everything from
finding a book in the library's electronic catalogue to finding a
job on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to teach the people who may not know anything the basics
in five to 10 minutes,'' Hammer said earlier this week, as he
paused between turns at fixing an uncooperative printer for one
patron and spelling out the URL for a popular search engine for
another. ``I teach them the mouse. The buttons _ back, forward and
home. That most blue underlined things are links. Just the basics
so they can search themselves. People usually pick up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching neophytes ``to pick up'' the basics is getting to be a
new occupation for teen-agers around the country, as libraries,
schools and community groups turn to 'Net savvy young people to
bridge the generations and help those who grew up when the term
``mouse'' referred exclusively to a small furry mammal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' said Karen W. Smith, executive
director of the Tech Corps, a national non-profit volunteer group
based in Bedford, Mass., that seeks to help schools integrate new
technology in the classroom. ``Anytime kids are in a situation that
says 'We value what you know,' that's a very good message. These
programs also give kids the knowledge that what they are learning
is transferable to a marketable talent.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say how many programs there are involving
teen-agers who teach grown-ups. But within a few hours earlier this
week, a query about the subject to a library public relations
listserv garnered a dozen or so responses, with examples of
programs using teenagers to help everyone from military veterans to
participants in senior citizen projects.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, at the main branch of the Martin County Library
System in Stuart, Fla., teen-agers _ and some children as young as
fifth grade _ began teaching Internet basics classes to adults who
had enrolled in the library's new FloriNet Families Online program.
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing a library training course, the young
instructors work with grown-ups to teach them how to use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are hoping that one effect of the project will be to
forge closer ties between adults and young people. They are also
hoping that some of the embarrassment adults feel when first
encountering the Internet will be abated because they are working
with young people and ``do not feel the pressure they would feel
with a peer,'' said K. Janette Alley, a reference librarian and one
of the organizers of the project.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, a teen/adult technology program was used as a
way to introduce immigrants to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Edison Freire, who teaches science in a bilingual
program at Edison Fareira High School, asked a group of his
bilingual students to volunteer to work with Spanish-speaking
adults studying to earn high school equivalency diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to get my students to think of themselves as
leaders, and one way to do that is to let them work with adults,''
Freire said.
</P>
<P>
   The adult participants learned such essentials as how to find
Web versions of newspapers from their homelands. One result of the
program was the Latino Tech Collective Family Web Publishing
Project, which enabled the students to describe their lives on a
simple Web site.
</P>
<P>
   For Hammer and the other instructors in the Queens Teen 'Net
Mentor program, one challenge is quickly assessing what a patron
knows and doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers have become adept at recognizing telltale signs:
the patron who holds up a mouse and presses it as if it were a
remote control device; the patron who stares blankly at the
computer screen and does not know how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge is providing tactful assistance. Mahjabin S.
Ahmed, a friendly 16-year-old mentor who hopes one day to be a Web
designer or computer programmer, recalls trying to find the words
to soothe the anxiety of a 34-year-old man using a mouse for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him 'That's OK,''' she recalled. ``The computer
hasn't been around for 100 years. It's new and people need to take
their time to learn it.'''
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBAR: RELATED SITES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Martin County Public Library:
http://www.martin.fl.us/GOVT/depts/lib/
</P>
<P>
   _ Edison Fareira High School:
http://whyy.org/edison/freire/asnowden/edison.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Latino Tech Collective Family Web Publishing Project:
http://www.whyy.org/edison/freire/famwebproj.html
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Pamela Mendels, a Manhattan-based writer, was a reporter for
New York Newsday from 1987 to 1995.)
</P>
