<HEADLINE>
UNITED ASSET MANAGEMENT PROFITS FALL 7.9 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Asset Management Corp. said Thursday that profits plunged
7.9 percent in the second quarter, evidence of the Boston-based
investment company's struggle to stanch asset outflows and make its
acquisition strategy work.
</P>
<P>
   The company, a conglomerate of 53 acquired firms that is among
the nation's largest money managers, said it would intensify
efforts to help only its most promising subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   UAM's net income fell to $22.1 million, or $0.32 per diluted
share, from $24 million, or $0.33 a share, a year ago. The losses,
expected by analysts, come at a time when other asset management
firms with multiple units are growing earnings.
</P>
<P>
   While revenues rose 16 percent to $254.4 million from $219.6
million a year earlier, the gains came from fees earned on rising
assets in a growing stock market, and not from new business. UAM
lost business last quarter, as clients yanked out $4.3 billion in
assets from troubled subsidiaries. Around $1 billion of that total
came from UAM's liquidation of a failed unit, HMH Investment
Advisors, Inc. of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Negative net client cash flow has dogged UAM for years.
Customers pulled out $4.7 billion in the first quarter of 1998
after $16 billion in 1997 and $3.3 billion in 1996, prompting UAM
to reassess its original strategy of functioning as an umbrella
company for multiple firms. The outflows were mostly responsible
for total assets under management decreasing $3.8 billion last
quarter to $210.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that negative net client flow at certain UAM
affiliates continues to be unacceptably large,'' UAM chairman and
chief executive Norton H. Reamer said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts fault UAM's policy of buying 100 percent of
subsidiaries and leaving them free to operate as they wish, an
arrangement that can dent managers' incentives to boost earnings.
In a rethinking its strategy, UAM said it was intensifying its
partnership with high-performing units rather than keeping them at
arm's length. Still acquisition-minded, UAM is now interested only
in firms with major growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   On a brighter note, the company's operating cash flow, used to
fund acquisitions, repurchase shares, and pay dividends, rose 8
percent to $57.2 million from $52.7 million a year ago. UAM has
been buying back its shares in a bid to boost its flat stock price.
The company's stock slipped 1 1/8 to close at 27 3/4 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
