<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-IRAN-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL IS CAUTIOUS IN CONDEMNING IRANIAN MISSILE TEST  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: See also IRAN, IRAN-U.S. and ROSENTHAL-COLUMN) 
(js) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel on Thursday treated Iran's test of a
medium-range missile as confirmation of its insistent warnings over
many months about Iran's efforts to develop a long-distance
strategic threat.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli officials did not treat the test itself as an
immediate threat to Israel, noting that there was no indication yet
that Iran had a missile that could accurately hit targets in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also speculated that the test might have been intended
more as a political signal than as a test of technology. They noted
that it coincided with the arrival of Vice President Al Gore in
Moscow, where one of his goals was to try to press the Russians
into stopping their role in Iran's missile-development program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a developing threat, a serious threat in the Middle
East,'' Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said. ``What this means
is a greater budget allocation, more resources, more motivation and
more deterrence, and if, God forbid, there is a need for this, to
do whatever is necessary to protect the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatively low-key reaction, which was echoed in the modest
attention given the test by the Israeli radio, apparently reflected
a political ambivalence about the significance of the test. It was
noteworthy that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu issued no
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been issuing stern warnings for a year-and-a-half
that Iran was working hard to develop long-range missiles.
According to Israeli officials, Iran obtained some North Korean
Rodong missiles several years ago, but since then it has been
working to develop its own missiles, known as Shehab.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has already test-fired Shehab-3 and Shehab-4 missiles.
Israel's major concern has been that Russian scientists and
enterprises are playing a crucial role in the project. For that
reason, Netanyahu and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky _ the
government official most closely involved in the matter _ have
lobbied hard in Washington for the United States to press Moscow to
halt the assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington the issue has turned into another tussle between
the White House and Congress. Last month, President Clinton vetoed
the Iran Missile Sanctions Act, under which sanctions would have
been imposed on Russia for its activities in Iran, arguing that the
matter was better handled with quiet diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Moscow did appear to be taking steps to curb its help to
Iran in recent weeks. In an unprecedented development, Nikolai
Kovalyov, the head of the Federal Security Bureau, the Russian
intelligence agency, visited Israel this month for extensive talks
with Sharansky and other officials about the Iranian situation,
evidently to Israel's satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   The cautious Israeli reaction thus evidently reflected a desire
not to undermine the diplomatic efforts when they seemed about to
bear fruit, and especially when Gore was in Moscow.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The White House was equally cautious. Clinton's spokesman,
Michael McCurry, stressed that the missile tested on Wednesday was
a North Korean one, and neither he nor other officials in
Washington named Russia as a culprit in the test.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Sharansky suggested that Iran might
have fired the missile deliberately to demonstrate that there was
no point in trying to block its program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Iran did this now to show America that it's too late,
that the train has left, that they have rockets,'' Sharansky said.
``Our information is that there is still time before Iran gets a
long-range rocket. If we block all the leakage of information, we
can block the whole project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This testing was apparently not entirely successful, and we
have doubts that they even had electronics on the missile,''
Sharansky continued. ``It's possible this was less a technical
necessity than a political signal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis also seemed concerned that Iran's missile program
would be perceived solely as a threat to Israel. Modechai's
spokesman, Avi Benayahu, argued that the test should be seen as a
threat to Arab countries like Saudi Arabia and the entire free
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think if Iran finishes all these tests and concludes the
project, it's against not just Israel, but against Europe, against
American interests in the gulf,'' he said. ``We think it's global,
and there should be an international mission now to stop this
project.''
</P>
</TEXT>
