<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0129 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERTIMES-BLUES-ALBU     07-23 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-BLUES-ALBUM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS(AT)LARGE 
 A BLUES ALBUM WITH LIVELY LINER NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Miles Davis album ``Kind of Blue'' continues to be one of
the best-selling jazz albums of all time. The 1959 recording serves
as the cornerstone of countless music collections and remains
undiminished in its ability to draw new listeners to jazz through
its moody atmosphere and brilliant instrumental solos.
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, Sony Music launched a World Wide Web site to support
the latest reissue of ``Kind of Blue'' on compact disk. The online
project brings to mind half of another Davis title, ``Birth of the
Cool.'' The immortal ``Kind of Blue'' has no need to be reborn, but
the site itself is undeniably cool.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to brief but revelatory sound clips unearthed from
the original recording sessions and a gallery's worth of rare
photographs, a key feature of the site is its ability to interact
with ``Kind of Blue,'' provided that a copy of the new audio disk
is in the CD-ROM drive of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   With a correctly configured system, viewers can watch the
transcribed score of the first 32 measures of ``So What'' scroll by
as the tune plays, or click on a photo of John Coltrane to trigger
the saxophonist's solo on ``Freddie Freeloader.'' The Internet
supplies the images, which appear in a pop-up window about a third
of the size of a full browser frame, but the CD is the source of
the high-quality sound.
</P>
<P>
   These living liner notes are made possible by a bit of software
that Sony calls ``ConnecteD.'' The tiny piece of computer code
takes just seconds to download from the Sony site, and not much
longer to install. ConnecteD works in tandem with Shockwave, a free
``plug-in'' program that extends the audio and video functions of
Web browsers, to access precise passages of music from an audio
disk in the CD-ROM drive. The excerpts can be a complete track or a
single note.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Kind of Blue,'' Sony has used the technology to
synchronize two sections of the loping tune ``So What'' with
musicological analyses. It's also used to link 22 of the album's
solos to their performers' photos and relevant comments by Miles,
taken from his autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ConnecteD's benefits are not fully demonstrated here. It's a
thrill to follow a rectangle as it slides through a transcription
of the trumpeter's acclaimed ``So What'' solo while the music
plays. But only four musical excerpts accompany the dissection of
the composition by Todd Coolman, a bassist and jazz educator.
Coolman's scholarly analysis is replete with phrases such as ``the
goal notes of the melody alternate in each odd numbered measure
between D4 and A3.'' A few more audible examples would help to
illustrate his comments for readers who are not music theorists.
</P>
<P>
   And while the combination of text, pictures and sound in the
site's ``Solos'' section results in a nifty multimedia scrapbook,
one yearns for something more educational, perhaps a head-to-head
comparison of the two renditions of ``Flamenco Sketches.''
</P>
<P>
   To assure that Web content and music act as one, Sony intends to
wire the site so that access requires a copy of the latest reissue
(catalogue number CK 64935, easily identified by the bright-yellow
``definitive version'' sticker on the cover).
</P>
<P>
   Yet some of the graphically evocative site's most interesting
</P>
<P>
   material resides wholly on the Web. Staff photographer Don
Hunstein documented the ``Blue'' sessions, and all of those images
-- many of them previously unpublished -- have been dug out of the
company's archives and posted on the site, according to Rene
Arsenault, an A&AMP;R coordinator for the label's jazz program. Also
online are a video clip of Davis soloing during a live performance
of ``So What,'' and an audio interview with the drummer Jimmy Cobb,
the only surviving member of the session.
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable finds, though, are a trio of audio snippets
consisting of outtakes and studio chatter from the sessions. To
hear Miles interrupt the first take of ``Freddie Freeloader'' with
a growled ``That's too fast'' is akin to perusing Ezra Pound's
edits of T.S. Eliot. In another clip, the producer Irving Townsend
stops a song to complain about ambient noise, including vibrations
from the snare drum. ``That goes with it,'' Davis informs him.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenault hinted that additional outtakes may appear on the
``Blue'' site at a later date. ``There is more music,'' he said,
although he added that all the complete versions of songs have been
issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of Blue'' is the fourth entry in Sony's series of
ConnecteD titles, joining disks by Ben Folds Five, Ozzy Osbourne
and Yo-Yo Ma. The company says that the technology allows it to
convert any audio disk into an enhanced CD by placing the
multimedia content on the Web instead of the silvery platter.
Because the Web is a dynamic environment, tour schedules and other
information can be updated, although the company has yet to take
advantage of this feature. Unfortunately, those with slow modem
connections must cool it while the Shockwave files download, a
process that can take a thumb-twiddling minute or three.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the ``Kind of Blue'' site, the wait is worth it.
Davis's location in the jazz pantheon has led to any number of
tribute sites, like the recently launched milesdavis.com and fan
endeavors like Miles Ahead. But unlike those others, there is new
material here that gives new insights, albeit modest ones, into the
recording process.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview, Cobb recalls the ``Blue'' sessions. ``They
want to say that it's one of the greatest instrumental jazz records
ever made,'' he said. ``I had no idea that was happening.'' Forty
years later, the ``Kind of Blue'' Web site gives a better idea of
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Kind of Blue'': sonymusic.com/thelab/ConnecteD/
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Mirapaul is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.)
</P>
