<P>
   SUDAN-FAMINE (Panthou, Sudan) _ Despite an airlift of more than
12,000 tons of food over the last three and a half months, a famine
has begun to take a significant number of lives in Sudan. By James
C. McKinley Jr. With graphic and photo. 2,263 words. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-BISHOPS (Rome) _ Seeking to curb the independence of
bishops, the pope issues an apostolic letter that tightens Rome's
control over 108 bishops' conferences around the world. By
Alessandra Stanley. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD (Washington) _ The basically Democratic
government of Puerto Rico, pushing for statehood, has an
imaginative sales pitch for Congress' Republican leaders: With its
prayer in schools, anti-abortion beliefs and a low capital gains
tax, the island commonwealth should be every conservative
Republican's dream. Details of how Puerto Rico lobbies for
legislation to hold a referendum on the island's future. By Lizette
Alvarez. With photo. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-MANHUNT (Andrews, N.C.) _ There is a part of this town that
is rooting for accused abortion clinic bomber Eric Robert Rudolph
to elude the camouflaged G-men. Add together an underlayer of
anti-abortion sentiment, an innate distrust of government and local
pride in the ability of a ninth-grade dropout to outwit more than
200 investigators, and it begins to become apparent why a local man
has sold more than 200 T-shirts bearing the slogan: ``Run Rudolph
Run.'' By Kevin Sack. With photo. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   Possible reefers:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MCCURRY (Washington) _ Mike McCurry, who has used an
agile wit and aggressive tactics to promote the administration
while defending it from scandal, will resign as press secretary
this fall, President Clinton announces. By James Bennet
</P>
<P>
   ODWALLA-FOOD-SAFETY (Chicago) _ In what federal officials say is
the first criminal conviction in a large-scale food poisoning
outbreak, Odwalla Inc. pleads guilty to violating food safety laws
and agrees to pay a $1.5 million fine because of a 1996 outbreak of
tainted apple juice that killed a 16-month old child and sickened
70 others. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLONER-PROFILE (Undated) _ Dr. Ryuzo Yanagimachi, the
University of Hawaii researcher whose cloning of adult mice has
amazed fellow biologists, describes himself as a man devoted to one
passion _ probing the boundaries of scientific knowledge. He
surrounds himself with acolytes, often doctoral and postdoctoral
students from other countries. ``Many Americans are interested in
easy jobs,'' he explains. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
