<HEADLINE>
SOUND BITES STRAIGHT FROM THE NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ What they've said on the TV press tour:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``There's one year he told me he'd rather just sit in Malibu
and watch the hummingbirds mate.'' _ producer Don Mischer on trying
to persuade Johnny Carson to participate in the Emmy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``They just told me to shut up, basically.'' _ new ``ABC
Monday Night Football'' announcer Boomer Esiason, on advice from Al
Michaels and Dan Dierdorf.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Well, basically my last show was canceled.'' _ actor John
Henton, on what attracted him to a new show called ``The
Hughleys.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Do you think your butt can stand up to Jimmy Smits' butt?''
_ question for new ``NYPD Blue'' cast member Rick Schroder.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You know, average working class guy with an average ass.'' _
Dennis Franz on the appeal of his ``NYPD Blue'' nude scenes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Oh, I think `Fantasy Island' is more interesting. I have to
say that, don't I?'' _ Fyvish Finkel, comparing ``Picket Fences''
to his new show.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Don't we already know the answer to that?'' _ ``Fantasy
Island'' producer Barry Josephson, asked what President Clinton's
fantasy might be.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Wow, you know what? Ten minutes before the first `Clockwork
Orange' question. That's not bad.'' _ Malcolm McDowell, asked about
``Clockwork Orange'' 10 minutes into a ``Fantasy Island''
interview.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Really? Like what?'' _ Cindy Crawford, asked if her ABC
special's title, ``Sex With Cindy Crawford,'' might suggest
something.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I have a father. I have a brother. I've been married three
times.'' _ Susan Harris, on her qualifications to produce ``The
Secret Lives of Men'' for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Once in a while my wife complains about my jokes. I just
tell her to go cry into a big bag of money.'' _ Ray Romano.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Our advertising budget is probably about the cost of an iced
tea out by the pool.'' _ Margaret Drain, executive producer of PBS'
``The American Experience.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``As someone who dealt with both Howard Cosell and Sam
Donaldson, I do think that I richly deserve this award.'' _ Roone
Arledge, accepting the Television Critics Association career
achievement award.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Well, did you see that thing with the beach?'' _ Tom
Fontana, executive producer of ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' on
what his show would be like if the network made all the creative
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``That I'm very lucky'' _ Chris Noth, on what he thought when
he learned he'd play a character named ``Mr. Big'' on HBO's ``Sex
and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shakespeare, baby! All right? Hey, we're talking
Shakespeare! We're talking quality! `Crime and Punishment'! Who can
spell `Dostoyevsky'? Huh? There's a handout so you guys can figure
that out.'' _ Warren Littlefield, NBC Entertainment president, on
NBC movie versions of ``The Tempest'' and ``Crime and Punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If the Irish are so widely spread throughout society, why
did you choose to have a priest, a cop, a drunk and a union
organizer?'' _ question to John Wells, producer of ``Trinity,'' an
NBC drama about an Irish family.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It's been his big fear for three years. He keeps saying, `I
just don't want testicular cancer.''' _ Wells, who also produces
``ER,'' on how George Clooney will be written out of ``ER'' this
season.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I remember (Clint) Eastwood and I were fired by the studio
and then hired back for a lot of money. The guy was dead. There was
no joy.'' _ Burt Reynolds on getting even.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I'm playing a guy who sings `One for My Baby,' sleeps with
Ava Gardner, goes sailing with JFK. That's a great part.'' _ Ray
Liotta on playing Frank Sinatra in an HBO movie.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I gotta watch this crap?'' _ TV critic when a clip of
Shakespeare's ``King Lear'' was shown during a ``Masterpiece
Theatre'' luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
