<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FARMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCES AID FOR DROUGHT-STRICKEN AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ark., Fla., Ga., La., Miss., N.C., Okla., S.C., Tenn.,
Texas, N.D., Ill.)  (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Homeowners in 11 scorched Southern states will be
eligible for $100 million in emergency federal aid to buy fans and
air-conditioners and pay soaring electric bills, President Clinton
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The president also declared all of drought-stricken Texas an
agricultural disaster area, making farmers and ranchers there
available for government relief payments and low-interest loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Americans have been deeply concerned and troubled by the
human toll of the record heat wave that has spread across many
parts of the United States,'' Clinton said in appearance in the
White House briefing room. ``It has destroyed crops, led to
widespread power outages, and, worst of all, has resulted in the
deaths of over 100 people.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as he was declaring a disaster, the president could not
resist making a partisan political point. He said that House
Republicans had voted to eliminate the Low Income Home Energy
Assistance Program, the source of the emergency money for
air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress proceeds to try to eliminate all funding for this
vital emergency assistance, it would be an act of political
irresponsibility,'' Clinton said. ``It would put partisanship ahead
of the progress and the people of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The energy program, known as LIHEAP, was established in 1980
during the energy crisis to help the poor pay their heating bills.
Opponents of the program contend that it has outlived its
usefulness, as energy prices have fallen sharply over the last few
years. They say that genuine emergencies can be funded through
other social service programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question whatsoever that there is a need that must
be met here,'' said Rep. John Edward Porter, R-Ill., who advocates
elimination of LIHEAP. ``But we ought to take a look at the states
assuming responsibility for what is basically a welfare program.''
</P>
<P>
   The money will be made available to low-income homeowners in
Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, North
Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee and Texas.
Temperatures in those states have ranged from 16 percent to 26
percent above average since June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The sweltering summer has also exacerbated a farm crisis that
has seen agricultural income decline 35 percent from two years ago
and driven hundreds of farmers out of business in the northern
Great Plains.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where temperatures reached 100 degrees for the 18th
straight day Thursday, three quarters of the cotton crop has been
lost to drought. In North Dakota, auctioneers are being brought out
of retirement to sell land and equipment from bankrupt farms.
</P>
<P>
   The president's disaster declaration for Texas will help those
whose crops and livestock have been ravaged by the heat. Officials
said they could not estimate how much money ultimately would be
involved in the disaster relief program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
