A0148 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-FUNDING-HNS &LR;      07-23 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGGS SCALES BACK ANTI-GAY MEASURE AIMED AT SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The sponsor of anti-gay legislation aimed at the
city of San Francisco disclosed Thursday that he has drastically
cut back his proposal in an effort to pick up more support for it
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., drafted legislation last week to bar
federal funds from some government programs in San Francisco if the
city continued to require its private contractors to provide the
same benefits to unmarried domestic partners as they provide to
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of the Riggs' proposal, an amendment to the
appropriations bill for the federal departments of housing and
urban development and veterans affairs, states that ``none of the
funds appropriated by this act may be used to implement'' the
city's domestic partners' ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Riggs said he wanted the funding ban because San
Francisco was ``trying to force a particular political belief, a
doctrine if you will,'' on others.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs, who represents California's North Coast from Napa to the
Oregon border, denied his plan was an attack on gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's sexual orientation is their own private business,''
he said, adding that he has ``no problem'' with the city of San
Francisco offering domestic partner benefits to city employees. But
he said it was ``a tremendous stretch'' for the city to try to
force private businesses to offer domestic partner benefits, which
usually take the form of medical insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco board of supervisors adopted the domestic
partners ordinance, effective June 1, 1997, requiring city
contractors to provide the same benefits to the domestic partners _
gay and straight _ of their employees as they would to married
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights advocates hailed the measure as an important step
toward equality.
</P>
<P>
   Beau Phillips, the congressman's spokesman, said the new version
represented a scaled-back version of the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the amount of federal funds will be smaller'' under
the new version of Riggs's amendment, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said Riggs changed the measure because the original
version would have been subject to procedural challenges under
House rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amendment accomplishes the same thing,'' Phillips said.
``It is intended to stop the city of San Francisco from using
federal dollars to impose its will on contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., who acknowledges he is gay, said
Riggs was forced to soften his proposal because it lacked support
on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Ivers, spokesman for Log Cabin Republicans, a gay advocacy
group, agreed. ``It sounds to me like they gave up, but they did it
in a face-saving way,'' said Ivers.
</P>
<P>
   Ivers said Riggs bowed to pressure from Republican supporters of
federal housing for people with AIDs. Some 30,000 people with AIDs
in San Francisco would have lost at least some, if not all, of
their federal housing support under the original Riggs amendment,
according to Ivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear tonight that the Republican leadership is in full
retreat,'' Ivers said. ``We are going on the offensive now and
we're going to defeat both of them and we're not going to let them
change the subject. It's too late to put the toothpaste back in the
tube.''
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Stachelberg, political director of the gay advocacy group
the Human Rights Campaign, said the move by Riggs to soften his
amendment ``was very clearly a retreat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a clear sign that Mr. Riggs (and the Republican
leadership) knows that going after gay people is not going to win
you votes and probably ensures a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Stachelberg added, ``they are still going after the city of
San Francisco for passing a city ordinance that it has full
authority to implement. The intent of the Riggs amendment is still
the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
