<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILL'S' GAY LEAD PLAYS IT CHASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. - After the wreckage of ``Ellen,'' how does a
television series handle another lead character who is gay?
</P>
<P>
   With extreme caution, judging by ``Will &AMP; Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBC comedy, scheduled for Monday nights in the fall, is
about a pair of attractive New Yorkers, Will Truman and Grace Adler
(Eric McCormack and Debra Messing), who are a couple, except that
he's gay.
</P>
<P>
   Besides McCormack's Will, the show also features actor Sean
Hayes as Will's flamingly gay friend, Jack.
</P>
<P>
   With a gay executive producer, Max Mutchnick, ``Will &AMP; Grace''
could be on track to advance television's shaky standards for the
depiction of gays.
</P>
<P>
   Or to be accused of caving in to a double standard, which is
what happened this week when critics pounded Mutchnick for making a
chaste pilot episode.
</P>
<P>
   Chaste for the character of Will, who has supposedly just ended
a seven-year relationship and has no new lover in sight. Not so
chaste for Grace, who's in bed with a man in the pilot's first
scene.
</P>
<P>
   A contentious session at the TV summer press tour in Pasadena
points to the delicacy of Mutchnick's dilemma. He clearly wants to
develop a realistic lead character in Will. But giving Will an
early sex life might alienate viewers and kill the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me it's a no-win situation,'' said McCormack, a
heterosexual actor in a homosexual role. ``You know, we don't have
a (male-to-male) kiss in the pilot, or maybe for a while. So we're
going to get some crap for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we put a kiss in the first scene of the pilot, it would
be considered controversial. For everyone that went, `Good for
you,' somebody else would go, `Oh, it's a stunt.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mutchnick, his co-producer David Kohan and director James
Burrows argued that the show's focus is a nonsexual friendship
between a man and a woman, who'll become roommates. The series,
Mutchnick said, isn't ``Will &AMP; Wayne.''
</P>
<P>
   But still: Grace will, Will won't. At least for a while. NBC has
ordered 13 episodes. Mutchnick, who has written for ``The Dennis
Miller Show'' and ``Boston Common,'' said he expects Will to date
in at least one of them. Meantime, he said, viewers ``have to fall
in love with the man. Let's take baby steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever restraints the producers are feeling, they said NBC
isn't the source.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no absolutes,'' Mutchnick said of his
discussions with the network about Will's sexuality. ``We've just
been told, from everybody on top, everyone who is involved with the
show, `Write it honestly.' And that's the way we'll approach it.
... If it comes up and it's right, and it feels good and we can do
it in an entertaining way, it will happen. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The character is who he is. I don't think we're hiding at this
point. But I feel like you guys (the critics) want us to talk about
something that we're not _ it hasn't come up yet, you know? I mean
when it does, when it starts to feel awkward, we'll feel that too,
and we'll write to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Things started to feel awkward _ then all right, in an
entertaining way _ at the press session itself.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a male Philadelphia writer strode to the stage, at
Burrows' invitation, to kiss the director on both cheeks. Then
another Philadelphia reporter, a lesbian, made her trip up to give
Messing a kiss, after Messing told her, ``You have to come up and
kiss me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutchnick watched that and said, ``You're not going to like what
I'm going to ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
