<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-JAPAN-POLITICS-ART-     07-23 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-JAPAN-POLITICS-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE UNLIKELY TO BE HAPPY WITH NEXT PRIME MINISTER, POLLS
SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(th) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ If the Japanese public had its way, Foreign Minister
Keizo Obuchi would not become the next prime minister. But a day
before the vote to choose the man who will almost certainly lead
the country, the reserved Obuchi looked like a sure bet for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls show voters clamoring for his two rivals: the
veteran politician Seiroku Kajiyama and the upstart Health and
Welfare Minister Junichiro Koizumi. But the electorate's opinion
has little real influence because Friday's vote is to choose a new
president of the governing Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Party members will therefore be doing the choosing, although the
man they select is all but certain of being prime minister because
the Liberal Democrats control the lower house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week junior party members seemed about to rebel
against the back-room power-broking among factions that has long
settled the pecking order in Japanese politics. But Thursday more
and more seemed to be reluctantly coming to the conclusion that the
best way to achieve their goals was to toe the lines drawn by party
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been explaining my decision to my constituents, knowing
that some people would react very strongly against my choice of Mr.
Obuchi,'' said Yoshitaka Shindo, 40, a legislator whose district is
in Saitama Prefecture. ``I tell them about his general abilities
and decision-making abilities, and I think people understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Shindo, who is a member of Obuchi's faction, is
well aware that his choice bears significant political risks. Like
many younger members of the party, he knows that if Obuchi does not
move quickly to repair this country's ailing financial system and
set the economy back on track, he himself will probably lose his
job in the next lower house election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Obuchi-san falls, I will fall and the party will fall,''
Shindo said. ``But I am ready to commit collective suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the public's disgust with political business as usual
grows more apparent every day. Thursday's Yomiuri Shimbun, one of
Japan's largest papers, published a poll showing that the Liberal
Democratic Party's approval rating had sunk 8 percent since June to
a record low of 20.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a strong weapon for us,'' said Taro Kono, a 35-year-old
party member who is ignoring the lead of his faction leader, former
Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, and supporting Kajiyama. ``We're
going around knocking on members' doors and handing them a copy of
the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that this election, to choose a successor to Ryutaro
Hashimoto, who resigned after the party suffered a decisive setback
in upper house elections on July 12, is causing more soul-searching
among party members than any in the past. For the first time that
anyone can remember, there is a ``floating'' vote of about 10
percent to 20 percent of the party membership that refuses to be
pinned down by pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the race is decided yet,'' said Nobutero
Ishihara, a young legislator from a district in Tokyo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, party members like Kono and Ishihara have been pushing
for ways to insure the secrecy of each vote on Friday in hopes that
a truly secret ballot might result in a last-minute shift of
alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night the head of the party's election committee said
the panel would do its utmost to insure privacy around the voting
box. In the past it was not unusual for party members to scribble
the name of the candidate they supported onto a piece of paper and
show it to colleagues before stuffing it into a ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   Little effort was made to make the voting secret, either by
printed ballots to protect votes from being identified by the
handwriting or by providing a booth in which to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But whether a more secret process will tilt the vote out of
Obuchi's favor is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators who are struggling with their choice are coming
to the conclusion that while he may not be the best man for the
job, Obuchi is the best of the three contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best person to become party head is Mr. Kato,'' said
Yoshitaka Murata, a junior member whose district is in Okayama
Prefecture, referring to Koichi Kato, the secretary general of the
party and a leader of the Miyazawa faction. ``So we are forced to
choose between second best or even lower-rated people.''
</P>
<P>
   Murata considers Obuchi his best choice, even though in a poll
of his constituents Obuchi placed last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We politicians, while we listen to our constituents, our job
is also to persuade them,'' he said. ``I will explain to them why I
voted for Mr. Obuchi and why he is best and maybe they will
understand.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1928EDT &QL; 
