<SLUG> BC-BULLS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floyd joins Bulls as coach stand-in
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Chicago Bulls reopened the door for Phil Jackson
to return as coach on Thursday, saying Iowa State's Tim Floyd was
hired as insurance should Jackson decide to stay retired.
</P>
<P>
   In making the announcement, owner Jerry Reinsdorf and general
manager Jerry Krause put the ball back into the hands of Jackson
andMichael Jordan, who has said that he does not want to play for
anyone but Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson decides to return, Floyd, named director of
basketball operations, will handle other duties. If Jackson
declines the invitation, Floyd will coach the team _ with or
without Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's agent immediately squelched the idea of Jackson
returning. ``He's not coming back,'' Todd Musburger told a Chicago
television station. ``Although it's kind of them to say, `Come
back, Phil, your chair is available,' it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Bulls won their sixth NBA championship in June,
Jackson talked about retiring to Montana for a year. His dislike
for Krause was evident, especially after the general manager
summoned Jackson to his office before Chicago's first practice last
season and ordered him to tell the gathered media that 1997-98
would be his last year as coach.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Jackson said: ``Wild horses couldn't bring me
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson reportedly refused a one-year contract extension days
after the Bulls defeated the Utah Jazz in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving open the option for Phil, Michael and Scottie
(Pippen) to return to defend the championship,'' Reinsdorf said.
``And if they don't, we have a coach in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf said Floyd, who compiled a 243-130 college coaching
record, was the clear choice over Charlotte assistant Paul Silas,
Indiana aide Rick Carlisle, Cleveland assistant Ron Rothstein and
young Phoenix assistant Scott Skiles.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd told Reinsdorf and Krause during a meeting on Sunday that
he would not accept the coaching job as long as there was a
possibility Jackson would return, or if it meant that Jordan would
not come back. Floyd proposed the coach-in-waiting proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about Michael Jordan's wishes,'' said Floyd, 44.
``It's too great an opportunity to pass up. I always wanted to
coach in the NBA. If I have to wait my turn, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, who led the University of New Orleans to two NCAA
Tournament berths before leaving for Iowa State, said, ``I will be
prepared,'' if he is called upon to coach the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Phil doesn't return, I hope Michael will come back and play
for me; I really do,'' Floyd said. ``I would love the opportunity
to coach Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has said that he would not play for a college coach and
mocked Floyd as ``Pink,'' a reference to the rock group Pink Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan won't make an official announcement about his future
until the NBA lockout ends, and Floyd's hiring won't change that,
said David Falk, Jordan's agent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
