A0172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUFFIN-COX     07-23 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUFFIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruffin quietly takes helm of UNC board
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ In the 1950s, when segregation snuffed out the
aspirations of many black people, Ben Ruffin followed the advice of
a high school teacher and took classes in sewing.
</P>
<P>
   Tailoring seemed a reasonable vocation for the son of a
hard-working maid and an alcoholic father who faded in and out of
his family's life on Durham's poor West End.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin wound up aiming higher. Next month, in a historic moment
for the 56-year-old who once turned cuffs at Boykin's Tailor Shop
and for America's oldest public university, Ruffin will preside
over his first meeting as chairman of the University of North
Carolina Board of Governors. Elected two weeks ago in a surprising
16-15 vote that ousted sitting chairman Cliff Cameron, a retired
Charlotte banker, Ruffin is the first African-American elected to
one of the most powerful positions in North Carolina. In the
two-year term, he leads the prestigious board of mostly white and
male political appointees that sets policies and doles out $2.1
billion a year in state funds for UNC's 16 public universities.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, an increasing number of African-Americans have
headed the boards of public university systems. In Georgia,
Atlantan Juanita Baranco chaired the Board of Regents. It's still
relatively uncommon, and many in North Carolina view Ruffin's
election as significant.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ben's election represents a milestone in our state history,''
said Julius Chambers, 61, a former Charlotte civil rights lawyer
who now serves as chancellor of North Carolina Central University
in Durham. As a UNC board member in the 1970s, he resigned over
what he considered the state's foot dragging in desegregating its
public universities.
</P>
<P>
   A1981 settlement between UNC and the Reagan administration
brought improvements that are helping the state's historically
black colleges catch up to predominantly white institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin's election has spurred speculation that he might attempt
to shift greater resources to North Carolina's historically black
colleges, including his alma mater, North Carolina Central. Ruffin
said he won't do that.
</P>
<P>
   In similar fashion, Ruffin said he does not believe that his
one-vote margin in an election that historically has been
uncontested signals a potential for divisiveness among board
members.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not have personal goals. I plan to work with the board,''
said Ruffin, a board member since 1991 and, most recently, its vice
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the six black board members voted for Ruffin. The one
who did not, High Point businessman Bob Brown, said he voted for
Cameron, retired chairman of First Union Corp., because ''he has
been a friend of mine for 20-some years. I think Ben will do a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin reaches way back, to the strict upbringing of his mother,
Catherine, for what he says will be his cooperative attitude. She
taught him to be courteous.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I walked up and down Carroll Street, I know that my
mother required that I speak to everybody who was sitting on their
porch,'' Ruffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ruffin remembers the racial slights of the 1950s and '60s
whenever he ventured outside of his neighborhood. One of five
brothers and sisters, he grew up in a 2 1/2-room apartment. Back
then, Carroll Street was unpaved and steep _ illustrative of
Ruffin's career that has spanned the eras of segregation,
affirmative action and the gradual diversity of higher education.
After high school, Ruffin became a civil rights leader in Durham.
In 1964, he earned a bachelor's degree in education from North
Carolina Central.
</P>
<P>
   He later received his master's degree in social work from
UNC-Chapel Hill. In 1977, he joined Gov. Jim Hunt's administration
as a housing adviser and minority affairs director. He then became
vice president of North Carolina Mutual Life Insurance Co., a
powerful black-controlled business in Durham. In 1986, he joined
one of North Carolina's most influential companies, RJR Nabisco
Inc., parent of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. in Winston-Salem.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin, Reynolds' vice president of corporate affairs, said he
and his wife, Avon, do not smoke. Neither do their two daughters,
ages 17 and 21. Still he defends their right to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
