<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CONDEMNS INTERNET GAMBLING IN 90-10 VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted overwhelmingly Thursday to outlaw
most gambling in cyberspace, casting into legal limbo a burgeoning
$600 million-per-year industry.
</P>
<P>
   By a 90-10 vote, senators approved a measure to extend a federal
ban on interstate betting by telephone or wire to include the
Internet. Before passing the legislation, the Senate rejected,
82-18, an effort to exempt Indian tribes from the prohibition on
Internet wagering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet gambling is unregulated, accessible by minors,
addictive, subject to abuse for fraudulent purposes like money
laundering, evasive of state gambling laws _ and already illegal at
the federal level in many cases,'' said Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.,
chief sponsor of the measure. Permitting an exception for tribes
would render the prohibition meaningless as anybody with a computer
would have access to the Indian casinos, he added.
</P>
<P>
   About $600 million was wagered over the Internet last year,
according to Kyl's office.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-gambling bill, an amendment to pending funding
legislation, contains exceptions that would allow states to conduct
lotteries over the Internet. In addition, off-track-betting on
horse and dog races would be permitted so long as wagers are placed
on subscriber-based computer systems inaccessible to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Also permitted under the measure are the popular sports
``fantasy'' or ``rotisserie'' leagues, in which fans create their
own roster of professional athletes and bet on how well their teams
will do. However, the fees Internet sites charge for using these
sites could not be used to pay off bets.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals convicted of running gambling sites on the Internet
could be imprisoned for four years and fined $20,000 or three times
the amount wagered. People found guilty of gambling on the World
Wide Web could be imprisoned for three months and fined $500.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill argue the ban is necessary because of the
difficulty in trying to regulate virtual casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The easy access and anonymity for bettors makes it possible for
youngsters who get their hands on a parent's credit cards to run up
debt, they claim.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from states that have refused to legalize games
of chance expressed concern that residents cannot be prevented from
signing in and placing wagers on sporting events or the turn of a
card in virtual casinos operated from locations thousands of miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   A recent State Department report also criticized foreign
Internet gambling operations in places like Antigua for providing a
haven for money launderers.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schneider, a spokeswoman for the Internet gambling industry,
assailed the Senate for placing ``a blockade around the U.S.''
while other countries, such as Australia, permit cyberspace
gambling. She also noted with disdain that senators chose to carve
out exceptions for lotteries and parimutuel betting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not prohibition; it has exceptions,'' said
Schneider, who chairs the Interactive Gaming Council. ``It's a
little inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was part of a bill that provided $33.2 million
for the Justice, State and Commerce departments in fiscal year
1999, which begins Oct. 1. The overall spending bill passed 99-0. A
similar measure to outlaw gambling on the Internet is awaiting
action in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Senators who voted against the Kyl bill were Joseph Biden,
D-Del.; Larry Craig, R-Idaho; Thomas Daschle, D-S.D.; Pete
Domenici, R-N.M.; Russell Feingold, D-Minn.; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa;
Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii; Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.; Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska; and Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
