</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-RICO-RALLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICANS TO MARK 100TH ANNIVERSARY OF US CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KIEHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Noemi Price, who has lived in both Puerto Rico and
Massachusetts, will join thousands of other Puerto Ricans gathered
in Washington this weekend to mark the 100th anniversary of US
control over the Carribean island.
</P>
<P>
   But for Price, the hottest topic won't be the past, but instead
the future of her native land.
</P>
<P>
   Price knows what it means to be a full American citizen _ most
importantly, that she can vote in presidential and congressional
elections, something her family back home cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president has the power to say, `You people are going
to fight and die for us,' then we should have the right to put that
man in office,'' said Price, 48.
</P>
<P>
   While Saturday's Puerto Rico-USA Centennial Festival on the Mall
in Washington is intended to be a historical commemoration drawing
5,000 to 7,000 people, including some 500 New Englanders,
organizers also hope that it will serve as a political rally for a
Congressionally sanctioned plebiscite on Puerto Rico's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going down there with an agenda _ to fight and let
their voices be heard,'' said Carlos Linera, who favors statehood
and is a liaison in Massachusetts for the Governor's Office of
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The question of status _ whether to seek statehood, independence
or remain a US commonwealth _ has divided Puerto Ricans here and on
the island for generations.
</P>
<P>
   In a nonbinding plebiscite in 1993, 48.6 percent of Puerto
Ricans voted for commonwealth status, 46.3 percent for statehood,
and 4.4 percent for independence. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Under the commonwealth agreement reached in 1952, Puerto Ricans
do not pay federal taxes and cannot vote in U.S. presidential
elections. They have a nonvoting representative in Congress and
they are eligible for the draft and service in the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   Statehood supporters say the island's 3.8 million residents
would contribute millions to the U.S. in taxes and Puerto Rico
would be an ideal jumping-off point for trade with Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Independentistas, those who favor independence, say Puerto Rico
is culturally closer to Latin American than the United States and
will enjoy greater prosperity with political and economic
independence.
</P>
<P>
   In March the US House passed a bill requiring a status
plebiscite in Puerto Rico by the end of the year. Last week,
however, the chairman of the Senate committee hearing testimony on
the bill said it is not likely to get to a full Senate vote anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   While those who favor statehood are disappointed with the
delays, Price said they remain optimisic. ``We still have time and
there's a lot of work to be done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On July 25, 1898, during the Spanish-American War, the United
Sstates invaded Puerto Rico, then a Spanish colony. The United
States established a military government, and a civilian colonial
administration was set up in 1900.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
