<SLUG> BC-ARMY-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. KENNEDY CITES ABUSES BY US ARMY SCHOOL'S GRADUATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II Thursday
stepped up his campaign against the controversial US training
academy for foreign military officers by releasing a report
detailing new human rights abuses by academy graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Democrat will try again next week to cut
funding for the School of the Americas, operated by the Army at
Fort Benning, Ga., saying its graduates have committed human rights
violations when they return to their homes in South and Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard a lot of talk about reforming the School of the
Americas, but the evidence continues to mount about a total
disregard for basic human rights and civil rights among its
graduates,'' Kennedy said at a news conference. ``It's time to
bring an end to US taxpayer subsidies of these type of abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy released a report compiled by the Latin America Working
Group, a project of the National Council of Churches, which claims
that Colombian graduates of the School of the Americas are among
the principal architects of the escalating human rights crisis in
that country.
</P>
<P>
   The US State Department said that 69 percent of the 3,500
political deaths in Colombia last year were committed by
paramilitary organizations that operate in complicity with the
military. The report said 124 of the 247 military personnel cited
as responsible for human rights violations, which include murders,
kidnappings, disappearances and torture, were graduates of the
School of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Kevin McIver, a spokesman for the school, told The
Associated Press that its instructors teach Army doctrine, as
mandated by law, along with courses on democratization and human
rights. He said the school should not be held accountable for the
actions of each of its nearly 60,000 graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not an institution out there that doesn't have a
graduate who has gone astray,'' McIver said. ``We teach
professionalism, we teach US Army doctrine and we augment it with a
very demanding human rights program.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing graphic testimony at Kennedy's news conference was
Richard Velez, a Colombian television cameraman who was granted
political asylum by the United States last week. Velez said he was
beaten by the Colombian military when he videotaped soldiers
attacking and shooting at a group of peasants during a peaceful
demonstration two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy played the videotape at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Velez said he was forced to flee last October after members of
the 20th military brigade attempted to kidnap him. He left his wife
and two children in Colombia and said he fears for their safety.
The brigade is headed by Paucelino Latorre Gamboa, a graduate of
the School of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Last year 99 Colombian military officers were students at the
school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
