<HEADER>
A0185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAYTHEON-EARNS-BOS &LR;      07-23 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD POSTS RECORD SALES, NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. Thursday posted record quarterly sales and profits
on the strength of its growing electronics and aircraft businesses,
but warned that its struggling engineering unit won't recover soon.
</P>
<P>
   The midday warning to analysts was enough to cause Raytheon's
Class B shares to give back an early gain as some analysts said
they now plan to cut their earnings estimates for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon Class B shares closed at 58 13/16, down 1/4, after
hitting a 52-week high of 60 3/4 earlier in the day. &UR;  &LR; Class B
shares are the shares that existed before Raytheon issued 103
million new shares last December to pay for its purchase of General
Motors Corp.'s Hughes Aircraft business.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington, Mass. defense and technology company said net
profits for the quarter rose 29 percent, to $269.5 million, or 79
cents a share. A year ago, Raytheon earned $209.5 million, or 88
cents a share. Although absolute profits rose, per-share earnings
fell because the number of shares outstanding grew 40 percent after
the Hughes transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The results include several one-time gains and charges that
resulted in a boost to earnings of about $7 million, or 2 cents a
share. Without those special items, Raytheon's earnings were $262.6
million, or 77 cents a share. Analysts had been expecting profits
of 76 cents, according to a surveyed by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the period soared 53 percent to $5.1 billion,
reflecting the additional revenues from Hughes and the defense
business of Texas Instruments Inc., which Raytheon acquired in July
1997. In the second quarter of last year, Raytheon had $3.3 billion
in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's defense and commercial electronics business, as well
as its Beech and Hawker jet business, had strong performances, but
its Raytheon Engineers &AMP; Constructors unit, which builds power
plants and other large infrastructure projects around the world,
continues to struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Although sales increased 9 percent from a year ago, the unit
continued to experience a delay in new orders, which led to
lower-than-expected profit margins for the quarter. Operating
income for the unit was $30 million _ the same as last quarter _
and 33 percent below the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon has already taken steps to scale back its engineering
business, eliminating about 1,500 jobs since December. But company
officials hinted that additional layoffs might be necessary to
bring down costs because of lowered revenue expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Raytheon chairman and chief executive Dennis J.
Picard said the company is ``reassessing the structure and
operations of RE&AMP;C while implementing previously announced cost
reduction initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later whether additional layoffs were likely, chief
financial officer Peter D'Angelo said, ``We're in the process of
assessing that.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Angelo added that Daniel Burnham, the company's new president,
will spend the next couple of months reviewing the engineering
unit's operations before making any decisions about the future of
the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will spend some time getting his arms around the business,
with an eye toward geting that business right-sized and operating
at a cost-effective manner,'' D'Angelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the options that Raytheon has said it will consider is
whether to sell a portion of the engineering business to the public
as a way to increase shareholder value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
