<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-DEREG-REFERENDUM-B     07-23 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-DEREG-REFERENDUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT CLEARS WAY FOR ELECTRICITY DEREGULATION VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Setting the stage for a battle this autumn over the
ongoing deregulation of the state's electricity industry, the
Supreme Judicial Court Thursday cleared the way for a referendum on
the restructuring which is criticized by some consumers' groups as
overly generous to utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is accountability time for the electric light companies,
based on the decision today,'' said John J. O'Connor, chairman of
the Campaign for Fair Electric Rates. ``The restructuring of an
electricity industry does not happen every year, and it ought to be
done right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the positive things that could go forward in the
state's attempt to deregulate the industry are frozen by this
referendum,'' said Steve Cowell, president of Conservation
Services, which wants to pursue the current reforms approved by the
Legislature and Acting Governor Paul Cellucci. ``Power plants are
not being sold, competitors who enter the state are not because the
situation is unclear.''
</P>
<P>
   The SJC rejected a challenge to the referendum spearheaded by
business and industry groups that argued that because the new law
involves appropriations to ``state institutions,'' the referendum
is barred by the state Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But the court ruled that the two agencies in question are not
``state institutions'' as envisioned by the Constitutional
Convention of 1917-18. The court said that the Massachusetts
Renewable Energy Trust Fund and the Community Antenna Television
Commission are both essentially independent agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The framers reasoned that the exclusion (of referenda
involving appropriations) was necessary,'' Associate Justice Neil
Lynch wrote for the court. ``This reasoning, however, does not
apply...to special public corporations created for a particular
public purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The referendum will now appear on the ballot in November, having
survived challenges over its constitutionality and whether voters'
signatures were properly gathered. The court ruled last month that
the process of gathering signatures was valid.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Associated Industries of Massachusetts, which
spearheaded the lawsuit aimed at heading off the referendum, were
not available for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign before the November vote is expected to be
dominated by heavily financed interests representing the utilities
and business and industry against some consumer and environmental
groups that think the current deregulation scheme is too expensive
and does not do enough to assure that utilities are burning clean
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Not all consumer or environmental groups want to tinker with the
deregulation, however, which was the product of years of
negotiations among utilities, the Legislature, the Weld and
Cellucci administrations, environmentalists and consumer groups.
The Conservation Law Foundation and the New England Aquarium, for
example, have joined an umbrella group called Keep the Electric
Rate Reductions that is expected to help campaign against repealing
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the debate between the opposing sides concerns what to
do with so-called stranded costs that occurred when utilities made
spending decisions before deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked for the best way to lower those costs, and it was
decided that it was for the utilities to divest themselves of some
good assets, sell them, and use the profits to write down the bad
assets,'' Cowell said. ``It took a year and a half to get the
utilities to agree to that, and the results have been stunning.
We've gotten rid of more stranded costs than any state in the
nation that is considering utility deregulation.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who oppose the current deregulation scheme disagree,
saying that it should have saved consumers as much as three times
the currently projected savings of $10 million this year, and that
the law does nothing to encourage utilities to rid themselves of
polluting plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an electricity utility bill,'' said O'Connor, who also
is running for Congress in the Eighth District. ``They spent over
$3 million on lobbying the Legislature to get their version of the
law into practice and probably an additional $1 million in
contributions to senators and reps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
