<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-KHMER-ROUGE-     07-23 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-KHMER-ROUGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-KHMER ROUGE TRY NEW APPROACH IN ENCLAVE THEY CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAILIN, Cambodia _ The world doesn't understand Pol Pot, Col.
Seng Narin said as he leaned back on his front stoop, slipping his
feet comfortably in and out of his sandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the top leaders of the Khmer Rouge were fine,'' he
said. ``It was the lower ranks that engaged in excesses. That's why
we all got such a bad reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   The colonel's wife agreed. ``The leader must take
responsibility,'' she said, ``but sometimes he can't know
everything that is going on. Pol Pot got blamed whether he did
anything wrong or not. There were bad people who hated him and
killed on their own and claimed the orders came from Pol Pot.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not politically correct talk in Cambodia. Nearly
everyone in this country, whatever their differences, agrees on the
evil of Pol Pot. But Pailin, a muddy gem-mining town in the far
northwest of the country is not an ordinary place. It is home to
some 25,000 Khmer Rouge defectors who are consolidating an
autonomous zone _ surrounded by the thick jungles that protected
them during their 16-year insurgency _ with their own government,
economy, police force and army of 5,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Residents here will take part in the general election July 26,
and the defectors' handpicked candidate is virtually certain to win
the Pailin seat in the National Assembly _ a Khmer Rouge toehold in
any new government.
</P>
<P>
   Pol Pot died in April, and the last three Khmer Rouge leaders
who have refused to defect are on the run with no more than a
handful of armed men. The Khmer Rouge, who caused more than a
million deaths when they ruled the country from 1975 to 1979, are a
spent force.
</P>
<P>
   But in Pailin, under the leadership of Pol Pot's brother-in-law,
Ieng Sary, the residue of that brutal communist movement remains
intact and well organized. Many people fear that it could represent
the nucleus of a new, anti-democratic political force in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Formally, the defectors have joined the Cambodian mainstream.
Their military commander, Ei Chien, is now the legal governor of
Pailin. Their police officers and soldiers, still under their Khmer
Rouge commanders including Col. Seng Narin, wear new official
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   No one outside Pailin knows just what these tough former
revolutionaries have in mind. But the arrival among them a month
ago of the movement's five top intellectuals made political
analysts in the capital sit up and take notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fascinating situation,'' a Western diplomat said. ``The
Khmer Rouge may be politically in better shape than they were a few
years ago when they were still fighting the government. They have
managed to have their zone, their income; basically they still have
their army and they have regrouped most of their intellectuals. Not
bad for something that has been defeated and does not exist
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsaking the isolation and austerity of their communist past,
Pailin's leaders have opened their town to the outside world and
are trying to create a civilian economy in place of the warfare
that was once the only pursuit. It is not an easy task. The Thai
border is just seven miles away, but the illegal gem and timber
trade with Thailand that financed the war has dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   And Pailin is suffering from an ailment of other former
communist regimes: its people have little experience in commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they are trying. Minefields have been cleared with the
help of international aid, and a bumpy dirt road has been opened,
connecting Pailin to the nearest city, Battambang, 50 miles east.
</P>
<P>
   A newly opened marketplace is filled with traders from around
the country. Wireless-telephone kiosks, several small gas stations
and even a bank are signs of new links to a world that the Khmer
Rouge once rejected. Restaurants, tiny hotels, billiard halls and
dozens of brothels have opened in a frontier atmosphere. Even a
gambling hall, the Caesar International Casino, is under
construction, though it is not clear who will travel this far to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   In tin-roofed karaoke parlors, idle young men _ former Khmer
Rouge soldiers _ sing along with sentimental Cambodian love songs
late into the night. There is an innocence about these young men,
who have known much more of killing than romance.
</P>
<P>
   Pailin's leaders offer a smiling face to visitors. They readily
admit their failures, though they insist that they personally took
no part in the Khmer Rouge killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``National reconciliation and an end to the war: that is our
main policy,'' said Ieng Vuth, deputy governor of Pailin and the
son of Ieng Sary, who was the first Khmer Rouge leader to defect,
here in Pailin, nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please tell the West, don't think too much about the Khmer
Rouge,'' Ieng Vuth said. ``There is no more Khmer Rouge. The Khmer
Rouge have become ghosts now. It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are many people in Cambodia who fear the power of
ghosts. The country remains violent and unstable _ a legacy of the
Khmer Rouge years _ and the current election could produce a
contested result that would lead to still more infighting. In the
months or years to come, there may be new openings for a reinvented
and rejuvenated Khmer Rouge to reassert itself, with a new name and
a new political philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Any political rebirth may well involve the most recent defectors
to Pailin, the five leading ideologues of the Khmer Rouge, who
joined their old friends here June 11. In an interview, three of
these French-trained elders _ Chan Youran, In Sopheap and Kor Bun
Heng _ offered a display of erudition and graciousness that seemed
intended to show that they could not have been party to any
thuggery.
</P>
<P>
   Apologizing for the absence of champagne, Chan Youran, 62, who
held a number of official positions with the Khmer Rouge, raised a
glass of water and said: ``My friend, let us talk frankly. We are
here in Pailin not to form a Khmer Rouge movement like in the past.
We think honestly the Khmer Rouge is dead as a movement, as an
ideology, a communist ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his comrades offered a series of personal defenses: they
had had no idea of the extent of the killings; they were out of the
country for much of the time; they were intellectuals, not
policy-makers; they had done what they could to soften the system
from within; they, too, lost family members in the killing fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the liberation in 1975 by the Khmer Rouge,'' Chan Youran
said, ``we intellectuals, we continued to reject the communist
ideology, the communist regime. We wanted national unity, not class
struggle. But as you know full well, we were only intellectuals,
not leaders. This was the great dilemma for all of us, for 30
years, until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, the men said, they remain ignorant of events. They
said they had no idea of the status of the three remaining leaders
_ Ta Mok, Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan _ whose ranks they fled only
weeks ago. Nor did they admit to any firsthand knowledge of the
circumstances of the death of Pol Pot, who is said to have suffered
a heart attack. They didn't even know him very well, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Many ordinary Cambodians joined the Khmer Rouge in the 1960s and
'70s with ideals of nationalism, or out of anger over Vietnamese
incursions and U.S. bombing. They found themselves committed to a
revolution that took a dreadful turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fighting for our country's independence and against
the Vietnamese aggressors,'' said Nuon Nim, 51, a former Khmer
Rouge soldier who is now a schoolteacher here. ``But our leaders
took us step by step into a swamp, and we were stuck there and
could not escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the political designs of Pailin's leaders, most people
here say they have had enough of armed conflict. They support
themselves as best they can, scratching for rubies and sapphires in
the mostly exhausted gem mines or selling one another vegetables in
the market. Like others interviewed here, Nuon Nim said his
ambitions were modest: a chance to earn a living in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need to bring an orchestra to play for us to make
us happy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
