<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ABORTION-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OVERRIDES CLINTON VETO OF `PARTIAL BIRTH' ABORTION BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill.)  (lh) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Replicating last year's vote, the House voted
Thursday to override President Clinton's 1997 veto of a bill that
would ban the late-term abortion procedure that opponents call
partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Attention now shifts to the Senate, where abortion opponents
fell three votes short last year of the two-thirds majority needed
to override Clinton's veto. The Senate is expected to take up the
issue in September, two months before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the vote, abortion opponents said they had
intensified their lobbying, focusing much of their efforts on the
handful of senators who are considered vulnerable on the abortion
vote.
</P>
<P>
   In what seemed a virtual repeat of last year's showdown, House
members voted 296-132 Thursday to override the veto, 10 more than
is needed. It was the same number that approved the ban last
October. On Thursday, eight Republicans voted against the override
and 77 Democrats chose to support it, with Democrats picking up one
member who opposes the ban. Rep. Gregory Meeks, D-N.Y., who
succeeded Rep. Floyd Flake when he retired in 1997, voted against
the override.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would ban the abortion procedure, known medically as
intact dilation and extraction, except when needed to save the
pregnant woman's life. Clinton opposes the bill because it does not
include a broad exception to protect a woman's health.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats lost ground on the issue last year when a doctor
admitted that he had lied in stating that the abortion procedure
was seldom used and only as a last resort. Then, after the American
Medical Association endorsed the ban, support flagged further. On
Thursday, Republicans did not hesitate to remind C-Span viewers of
those two points. And they did not shy from delving into the
explicit details of the abortion, which they say is never needed
because alternate methods can be used.
</P>
<P>
   During the procedure, the fetus is partly delivered, then its
skull is suctioned and collapsed so the rest of the body can be
moved into the birth canal. Surveys show that many people feel
uncomfortable about late-term abortions, even those who back
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who heads the House Judiciary Committee
and who has likened abortion to slavery in its debasement of human
life, closed the debate to the applause of his Republican
colleagues by saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``That little almost-born baby whose arms and legs are flailing,
whose little chest harbors a beating heart, is a human being with
human rights even if his or her human life can be snuffed out by
the plunge of the abortionist's surgical scissor into the back of
the tiny neck. Health versus a life. You are trading apples and
oranges, chickens and horses. If you put those on the scale, life
weighs heavier.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats said Thursday that they did not endorse the
procedure, either. But, they said, they are not willing to
``trample'' on a woman's constitutional right to choose abortion,
as one member put it, to outlaw a procedure that is sometimes used
to protect a woman's health. The decision of which procedure to
use, they said, is best left to the doctor and the patient, not
Congress.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In general, Democrats who voted for the override say that the
procedure is abhorrent and that its restriction would have no
practical impact on abortion in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Showing renewed vigor, Democrats worked hard on Thursday to make
Republicans look like extremists for not taking a woman's health
into consideration. The Democrats also pointed out that 17 court
decisions had struck down similar bans enacted by states, and that
two others had limited them, illustrating their
unconstitutionality. But such a ban has been upheld by a federal
appeals court based in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also made it plain _ as did some abortion opponents _
that this was simply the first step in a long battle to outlaw
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GOP leadership has been waging war on abortion rights
since taking over this House in 1994,'' said Rep. Nita Lowey,
D-N.Y.. ``This is the 93rd vote on reproductive rights in less than
three years. The message is, let's ban every abortion, month by
month, procedure by procedure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
