<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HEAT-HNS &LR;      07-23 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCES RELEASE OF $100 MILLION TO AID DROUGHT-STRICKEN
STATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trims) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Promising money for air conditioners and relief for
farmers, the Clinton administration Thursday moved to aid states
tormented by an unrelenting heat wave that has cost lives and
destroyed crops.
</P>
<P>
   The president announced the release of $100 million in federal
emergency funds to 11 states for low-income people to help them buy
air conditioners and fans or pay electric bills.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says the states that will receive aid are
Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, North
Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declared all Texas counties eligible for disaster
assistance, making federal loans available to farmers whose crops
have been damaged by drought.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Texas will immediately receive $32,722,551
from the Low Income Home Energy Assistance program, which is
better-known for helping poor people in northern climates pay their
heating bills in winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When blizzards and high-energy costs put elderly and poor
citizens at risk, we step in. When smothering heat threatens the
lives of people, we can step in, and that is what I am doing
today,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Housing and Community Affairs will
receive the money and then disperse it to community organizations
around the state that work with low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the emergency assistance, state officials said a
family of four has to earn no more than $20,563 a year or an
individual no more than $10,063.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas Gov. George W. Bush thanked Clinton for the
help, but warned Texans that the heat's toll on lives and property
was far from over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas heat has become a deadly furnace. Scorching temperatures
and the ongoing lack of rain have cost lives, livestock and
livelihoods,'' said Bush, who joined several other state officials
to provide an update on the emergency.
</P>
<P>
   State health commissioner William R. ``Reyn'' Archer said at
least 80 people in Texas, including illegal immigrants crossing the
border from Mexico, have died as a result of the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry said the state's
farming industry, under a ``best case scenario,'' will lose $1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have estimated that more than 14 million acres
of crops in Texas have been damaged by the drought, with claims for
federal crop insurance expected to be as high as $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $32 million in federal emergency aid should buy plenty of
fans and air conditioners for poor people who are struggling to
survive in dangerously hot homes and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Bush estimated that each $1 million would buy 10,000
air-conditioning units, which he said ``will put a huge dent in
solving the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the federal aid was being welcomed in Texas, the
assistance program has been a political football in Washington,
where Sun Belt lawmakers have regularly attacked it as unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans have so far refused to appropriate any money
in next year's budget for energy assistance, ignoring a Clinton
request for $1.1 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The president used the announcement of the emergency money as an
opportunity to chastise the House leadership for trying to kill the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress proceeds to try and eliminate all funding for this
vital emergency assistance, it would be an act of political
irresponsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said they will try to restore the program's funds
when the full House votes on the appropriations bill. The Senate
also is not expected to go along with eliminating the program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bitzer, a spokesman for Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, said
the Texas Republican had supported funding for the energy
assistance program in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Bitzer added that Hutchison ``welcomes any assistance the
president is able to give our farmers, ranchers and others
suffering from this terrible heat wave.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman is scheduled to tour
drought-stricken farms from Oklahoma to Texas next week and hold a
round-table discussion with agriculture experts at Texas A&AMP;M
University in College Station on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, urged Glickman to expedite the loan
process, saying that some farmers have complained to him that it
often takes as long as 18 months to receive the loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an emergency that requires an urgent response, not
business as usual,'' Gramm said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of Agriculture August Schumacher responded, ``I
strongly disagree with Sen. Gramm that this will take 18 months.
Our offices are open for farmers to visit and to begin the paper
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher said that it should take no more than six weeks for
farmers to obtain the 3.75 percent loans once they have completed
their applications.
</P>
<P>
   But before the application process can proceed, he said, farmers
must provide proof of a 30 percent crop loss. Such evidence usually
can only be supplied during harvest season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Clay Robison in Austin contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
