<HEADLINE>
DOW PLUNGES 195.93 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While second-quarter corporate earnings have come in
largely better than expected, a smattering of disappointing reports
and renewed fears about Asia sent stocks reeling Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 195.93 points, or 2.15
percent, to 8,932,98, its first close below 9,000 since June 30.
The blue-chip measure has fallen more than 400 points from its high
of 9,337.97 on last Friday. Thursday's free fall was the
third-sharpest drop in the Dow this year, after a 2.34 percent
decline on June 15 and a 2.85 percent drop on Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing led the decline, falling 6.75 and accounting for 27.8
points of the Dow's rout, after reporting lower than expected
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index dove 24.33 points, or 2.09
percent, to 1,139.75. Microsoft, whose giant market capitalization
gives it enormous clout in the index, was the leading decliner,
falling 3.75 points to 113. The one-day fall wiped off $9.2 billion
of the company's market value.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fared better. It closed down 34.53
points, or 1.75 percent, at 1,935.22.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, a diverse group of companies, including Merck,
McDonald's, Coca-Cola and DuPont, have cautioned investors that
earnings in the second half of the year could falter in part
because of the continuing economic crisis in Asia. For some of
these companies, the red flag was the first this year, leading
stock analysts and investors to fret about how long the Asian flu
will persist.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said Thursday that second-quarter earnings fell 46
percent, to $258 million, or 26 cents a diluted share _ sharply
lower than analysts' estimates of 33 cents a share. The company
also warned that results for this year and next would be
substantially weaker than Wall Street forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. reported Thursday that profits
rose 2.3 percent on strong sales, its stock fell 5.375 to 51 5/16
on continuing worries about its credit card business. Delinquencies
are high, and the company anticipates a 15 percent decline in
earnings at the unit for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day it's Merck, the next day it's Disney and then it's
Boeing,'' said Marshall Acuff, equity strategist with Salomon Smith
Barney. ``People are starting to say, `If the best of the market
can't do it, who can?'''
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also rattled by two days of congressional
testimony by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who warned
that the Asian crisis was far from over and that the stock market
could fall sharply at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people were listening to the Fed chairman, and he was
right,'' said Charles Johnson, head equity trader at Blaylock &AMP;
Partners in Baltimore. ``These valuations are not sustainable in
terms of earnings.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before profit reports began in earnest in mid-July, stock
analysts forecast a 1.3 percent increase in earnings for the
companies in the S&AMP;P 500 in the second quarter. In the first
quarter, earnings grew 3.8 percent for the companies in the index.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 333 index members that have reported thus far, the
earnings of 202 firms, or 60 percent, exceeded analysts' forecasts.
That number is slightly above the average of 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, only 13 percent, or 44 firms, reported earnings
that were below forecasts, according to First Call Corp., a Boston
research company that tracks analysts estimates. That number is
below the 25 percent average for such negative reports. Based on
those figures, earnings are now expected to grow 4.1 percent in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But companies are exceeding estimates that have already been
ratcheted down sharply by analysts. At the beginning of the year,
growth in earnings a share for the S&AMP;P 500 in the second quarter
was forecast at 12.9 percent. The forecast dropped sharply to 6.1
percent in April and then to just 1.3 percent, according to First
Call data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it pretty easy to meet or beat expectations,'' said
Robert Froehlich, chief investment strategist at Scudder Kemper
Investments. ``If you lower the bar enough, even I can jump over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to investors' concerns about Asia was a warning from
credit rating agency Moody's Investors Service that it might lower
its ratings on some Japanese government debt.
</P>
<P>
   It said it was reviewing the government's high-grade credit
rating on yen and foreign currency-denominated debt and bank
deposits due to ``deep structural problems in Japan's economy that
have defied conventional policy remedies.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
