u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULF-COX     07-23 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Closed meeting draws fire from wary Gulf War vets
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Some veterans complained Thursday that a special
presidential oversight panel on Gulf War illnesses held closed
meetings last week without informing or inviting them.
</P>
<P>
   After frequent accusations from veterans in the past few years
that the Pentagon was not doing enough to investigate Gulf War
illnesses, President Clinton appointed the seven-member panel in
February to oversee the Defense Department's probe into what might
be afflicting more than 100,000 soldiers. The presidential panel,
chaired by former New Hampshire Republican Sen. Warren Rudman, held
its first meetings July 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman's panel heard from Bernard Rostker, special presidential
assistant for Gulf War illnesses, and members of his investigative
team. That has caused consternation among some Gulf War veterans,
who say they don't trust Rostker and the Pentagon's probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rostker is giving Rudman's panel information that is
inaccurate, then Rudman's panel has started off on the wrong
foot,'' said Paul Sullivan, executive director of the National Gulf
War Resource Center, which represents 53 veterans groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon said Thursday that Rostker and his team were
just bringing the panel, known officially as the Special Oversight
Board for the Department of Defense Investigation for Gulf War
Chemical and Biological Incidents, up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to tell them what we do,'' said Lt. Col.
Dian Lawhon, who is Rostker's spokeswoman. ``It wasn't like we were
trying to sell them a bill of goods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like an anatomy course before you go into surgery,''
said Roger Kaplan, deputy executive director for the oversight
board.
</P>
<P>
   Many veterans have acrimonious feelings toward the Pentagon
because the Defense Department at first insisted after the 1991
Gulf War that soldiers' symptoms were not from any service-related
illness. The veterans criticize the Pentagon as grudging and slow
in recognizing the soldiers' afflictions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, veterans say they're upset because they weren't invited to
the panel's meeting and didn't know about it until a week after it
was held.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises very grave concerns among veterans about the true
intent of Pentagon efforts to investigate Gulf War illnesses,''
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rudman said Thursday that he was just holding an
organizational session to find out what the Pentagon has been
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was strictly an informational meeting,'' Rudman said.
``It was not a public meeting. There will be public meetings. All
of our hearings will be public.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel expects to hold its first public hearing in late
September or early October, Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Rudman said, panel members had to get to know each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do that in front of a thousand people in an
auditorium,'' Rudman said. ``I had never met these people. We had
never met each other before.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudman said he obtained legal advice from the Pentagon's general
counsel's office to make sure the group would not violate any laws
by holding the closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
   That misses the point, Sullivan countered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be illegal,'' he said, ``but we don't need secret
meetings when Rostker has such a bad record of not telling the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudman dismissed Sullivan's complaints as baseless.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're entitled to say whatever they want,'' Rudman said. ``I
happen to believe in the First Amendment. But that happens to be
poppycock.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
