<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-GOLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS OF GOLD STOLEN FROM JEWS SAID TO BE GONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ In a twist to the Nazi gold saga, German officials
acknowledged Thursday that 26 crucial, secret files containing
records of gold stolen from Jews in concentration camps had
mysteriously disappeared from German archives long after World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery raised several questions about the fate of the
documents, including the possibility that they had been
deliberately destroyed to cover the tracks of former Nazi banking
officials entrusted by the Allies with high offices in postwar
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The development could prove a setback to efforts by Holocaust
survivors to reinforce claims against German and Swiss banks for
wartime losses.
</P>
<P>
   News of the documents' disappearance emerged from an unpublished
report by the Federal Archives office here, German officials said.
The report covered the archives' abortive efforts last year to
provide U.S. investigators with details of the files, which, among
other features, tally the amounts of dental gold delivered to
Berlin after it had been pried from the mouths of Jews at
Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The files were named for Bruno Melmer, a notorious SS officer
whose job from 1942 to 1945 was to amass personal gold and jewelry
stolen from Jews in Auschwitz and other death camps, part of a
widespread effort to accumulate looted gold to finance Hitler's war
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest part of the gold was sold to the Swiss National Bank
in return for convertible Swiss francs that were used to buy raw
materials to make munitions. A report by a panel of Swiss
historians this year said that Nazi Germany stole gold worth $146
million at wartime prices _ the figure today would be nine times as
much _ from individuals, including Jews, and plundered a further
$475 million at wartime prices from the central banks of occupied
lands.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are significant because claims against Swiss
institutions by Holocaust survivors have brought a deepening crisis
to Swiss banks. The banks are facing the threat of U.S. sanctions
because negotiations on compensation for Holocaust survivors
collapsed last month.
</P>
<P>
   The German report chronicled a series of lapses by German and
American officials in safeguarding the documents. ``To outside
observers it will seem incomprehensible that documents so closely
linked to the crimes of Nazism could be distributed so carelessly
and finally lost,'' the report said, according to a German official
who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The files were located in 1945 by American troops in eastern
Germany. The report said the documents were shipped to the United
States, where some were microfilmed. But sections, apparently
including the 26 Melmer files, were not.
</P>
<P>
   The documents included the Melmer files and other account books
that tallied gold receipts by the precious metals department of the
Reichsbank, the German Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably the documents were handed back to the German
authorities in 1948 and left in the care of the Bank Deutscher
Lander, the forerunner of the present German central bank, the
Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
   A top official at that institution, the report said, was Albert
Thoms, who had headed the Reichsbank department that processed
looted gold and whom the Allies rehabilitated after the war. At
Thoms' death in 1977, his estate was found to include confidential
documents that had been missing from bank archives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
