<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-MAYOR-540(2TAKES     07-23 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-MAYOR-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING UNDERMINES IRANIAN PRESIDENT'S AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: See also IRAN-POLICY, ISRAEL-IRAN, and
ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT) 
(js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ In a new setback to Iran's president, an Iranian
court on Thursday convicted the mayor of Tehran on charges of
corruption and mismanagement, sentenced him to five years in
prison, and barred him from public office until 2018.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, Gholamhossein Karabaschi, is a close ally of
president Mohammed Khatami. The trial had widely been seen in Iran
as politically motivated, and the outcome Thursday appeared to have
fulfilled what critics said was its goal: toppling one of the
president's most important lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was a victory for conservatives who had accused
Karabaschi of using his office to benefit Khatami, whose pursuit of
greater political and social freedom in Iran has angered the
country's old guard. It came at a time when political fissures
within Iran have become ever more evident, and in which Khatami's
rivals are trying to gain the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate court ruling in Tehran on Thursday, a new
newspaper that had become a bold voice on Khatami's behalf was
ordered to cease publication immediately.
</P>
<P>
   All this happened a day after the disclosure that Iran had
test-fired a new medium-range missile with the power to reach
Israel, an act that served to undermine the conciliatory tone that
Khatami has struck in his own foreign-policy pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the new developments suggested just how much power
Iranian conservatives _ the country's dominant political force
since the Islamic revolution of 1979 _ still wield despite
Khatami's landslide victory a year ago over a candidate supported
by that ruling religious establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Khatami won the support of nearly 70 percent of Iranian
voters, his authority as president is limited. Since he took office
last August, he has had to contend with repeated muscle-flexing
from rival institutions, including the Parliament, the judiciary,
and the office of the supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, all
of which are dominated by far more conservative figures.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, Khatami has already had to weather the ouster
of one top lieutenant, Interior Minister Abdullah Nouri, who was
impeached by Parliament members who accused him of being too
permissive in allowing student organizations to conduct street
demonstrations. And with Thursday's conviction of Karabaschi and
the court-ordered shuttering of the newspaper, Jameyah, Khatami may
now have to wrestle with whatever chilling effect those steps may
have on other supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in February, the newspaper had won many
admirers and a large readership by openly challenging the stances
taken by Khatami's conservative opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But in response to complaints from officials of Iran's powerful
Revolutionary Guard corps, a Tehran court ruled last month that
several of the newspaper's articles had been defamatory and false,
and the order to close was issued after an appeals court upheld
that ruling on Thursday
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it remained far from clear what role, if any,
Khatami may have played in Iran's decision to test fire the new
missile, which U.S. officials said had a range of about 800 miles
and could strike Israel, Saudi Arabia or U.S. forces in the region.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under Khatami, the Iranian government has tried to repair
strained ties with its Arab neighbors, and it has muted much of the
anti-U.S. and anti-Israeli sentiment that has long been central to
its public pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   But that change in tone has not extended to Ayatollah Khamenei,
who retains authority over all of the branches of the Iranian armed
forces and other national security institutions, and who foreign
diplomats in Iran said would almost certainly have had the final
say over any missile test.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel Thursday, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said he
regarded any missile testing by Iran as a ``very serious matter''
but did not believe that Iran's missile could reach Israel.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Iranian government made no public statements
about the missile test, which Clinton administration officials in
Washington have said was monitored by U.S. spy satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, most attention in Tehran was fixed on Karabaschi, whose
sentence was even harsher than had been urged by his more
vociferous critics. His lawyer, Bahman Keshavarz, said the mayor
would appeal the conviction within the 20 days allowed by law.
Keshavarz said he was ``100 percent certain'' that his client, who
is to remain free on bail until his appeal is heard, would be
vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   But others sympathetic to Karabaschi said the case had raised
clear doubts as to whether the mayor, because of his ties to
Khatami, could ever be treated fairly by judicial officials, who
are most closely aligned with Ayatollah Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
   Karabaschi, who had repeatedly proclaimed his innocence, was
found guilty on charges of embezzlement, mismanagement and misusing
public funds to help elect Khatami during last year's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ever before, this verdict raises questions about the
independence and credibility of the judiciary,'' Sadq Ziba-Kalam, a
political science professor at Tehran University, said in an
interview in Tehran on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Karabaschi, 45, has served as Tehran's mayor since 1989. He has
won admirers both for pressing a city-wide beautification effort
that has vastly improved the quality of life in the capital and for
his outspokenness on behalf of Khatami during last year's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Since judicial officials first brought the charges against him
in April, his case has been a focus of intense public and political
interest.
</P>
<P>
   His imprisonment prompted swift condemnation from Khatami's
government, and prompted a public outcry that soon began to spill
over into street demonstrations. Only after a series of high-level
meetings did Ayatollah Khamenei, in a sign of evident alarm, accept
Khatami's recommendation that the mayor be released on bond.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Iranians have watched transfixed late into the
evening as proceedings from the twice-a-week public trial were
broadcast in their entirety on the country's state-run television
station.
</P>
<P>
   Karabaschi was not present in court Thursday as the verdict was
read out in the Imam Khomeni Judicial Complex. But large numbers of
police and firefighters were posted outside, apparently to avert
any protest that might have followed the announcement of the
court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday evening, there had been no reports of public
demonstrations in response to the verdict, but foreign diplomats
and independent analysts in Iran said they believed a new round of
protests was almost certainly inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was read by Judge Gholamhossein Mohseni Ejaei, who
under Iranian judicical system has served as both judge and
prosecutor throughout the trial, and whose neutrality Karabaschi
has repeatedly challenged.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the prison sentence and the 20-year-ban on
holding public office, Karabaschi was ordered to pay a fine of
approximately $530,000 and to return to the public treasury the
equivalent of $6 million in what the court said had been misused
funds.
</P>
<P>
   An additional sentence of 60 lashes, imposed in accordance with
Iran's Islamic law, was suspended in what the court said was its
recognition of Karabaschi's high social standing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
