<HEADLINE>
LEEDHAM SEEKS TEAMSTERS VOTES IN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Mass. _ Teamsters presidential candidate Tom Leedham
Thursday pumped hands, passed out leaflets, and portrayed himself
as a longtime rank and filer who knows more about being a union
worker than his challenger, James P. Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our campaign is all about the rank and file,'' Leedham, 47, of
Oregon, said in an interview. ``Hoffa's slate is about power and
perks for officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Leedham drove home that message to Teamsters truckers and
forklift operators at James Ferrera &AMP; Sons on Will Drive in Canton,
grabbing the workers' attention as they walked out of the building
into the sweltering heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, I'm Tom Leedham. I started at a grocery warehouse. I'm not
a millionaire lawyer... I'm running for president,'' he said,
handing out leaflets that described him as a ``real Teamster who
knows what it means to have a boss breathing down your neck while
you throw 4,000 pounds of freight in a single shift.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lyle, deputy campaign manager of the Hoffa Now campaign in
Washington, bristled at the suggestion that his candidate has not
done the work of a rank and file Teamster. Lyle said Hoffa drove a
truck at a US Air Force base in Clear, Alaska, and loaded and
unloaded ships elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa ``has been a dues-paying member for 28 years, and he spent
his career serving the members as a lawyer,'' Lyle said. ``Unlike
Tom Leedham, he did not spend the last five years in the service of
Ron Carey.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa ran and lost to incumbent Teamsters president Ron Carey in
1996, but a re-run election was scheduled after the contest was
overturned and Carey was barred from participating because of a
campaign finance scandal. That re-run will be held in September by
mail ballot.
</P>
<P>
   A relative unknown in a campaign in which the biggest stumbling
block to victory is the Hoffa name, Leedham had been on the 1996
Carey slate of officers. Thursday he garnered backing from former
Carey supporters, as well as from a trucker who said he had
considered voting for Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he planned to vote, 54-year-old John Sheehan, a
warehouseman for 29 years, said: ``Not for Hoffa, that's for sure.
He's living on his father's name.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said they knew too little about Leedham to choose
between the two candidates. ``I was for Hoffa, but I need to know
more about (Leedham),'' said Ken Gifford, 30.
</P>
<P>
   Trucker Peter McLean said his vote would go to the candidate
with the best pension and benefits proposal. ``Anybody who can push
up the pension, I'll vote for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, Leedham has been traveling around the country, hoping
to capture enough votes in the upcoming election to garner
leadership of the 1.4 million-member International Brotherhood of
Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   The big question, though, is whether he can take on _ and beat _
Hoffa, the son of &UR;  &LR; former Teamsters president James R. Hoffa. The
senior Hoffa became president in 1957, but later served four years
in prison for jury tampering and defrauding the union's pension
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe the (Hoffa) name is a two-edged sword,''
Leedham said Thursday. ``I think we'll win because Hoffa is
surrounded by the same people who fought against union reform.''
Leedham, who started in the union at a grocery warehouse 21 years
ago, has served as secretary-treasurer of Local 206 in Portland. In
1996 he was elected an international vice president. He also became
director of the union's warehouse section, which has 400,000
members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
