<SLUG> BC-MA-INSURERS-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OKS TAX CUT FOR BAY STATE INSURANCE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a sign that Massachusetts insurers may finally get a
long-awaited tax break, the state Senate Thursday approved its tax
relief bill, then vowed to race against time to try to craft a
compromise version with the House before the Legislature adjourns
for summer.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said they were hopeful of finding middle ground in a
matter of days to resolve a debate over how much insurers should be
required to spend on community investment projects in return for
multimillion-dollar tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a compromise version, and it's very likely it
will be embraced by the House and Senate before July 31,'' said
Senator Warren E. Tolman (D-Watertown), referring to the date by
which lawmakers must reach a deal if a final bill is to be passed
in this session.
</P>
<P>
   Added one source at the House Insurance Committee: ``The ability
to work this out (by July 31) looks very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But some cautioned it was possible insurers might not see a
final bill until fall.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Thursday overwhelmingly passed a measure approving tax
cuts for insurers based in Massachusetts in exchange for $250
million in lower-income community investment over five years. A
House version of the bill, passed in May, grants most of the same
tax breaks but calls for only $150 million in investment. Either
bill would reduce the insurance industry's tax burden by $50
million to $69 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences (between the two bills) are not enormous,''
said Senator Stanley C. Rosenberg, chairman of the Senate Ways and
Means Committee, which reviews all financial legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon Hill sources said lawmakers might seek to work out
differences between the bills informally rather than convene a
conference committee. Rosenberg said the committee could work on
the issue into the summer and present a final bill for legislators
to vote on in absentia.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the state Senate Thursday passed a House-approved
bill allowing mutually owned insurers to form holding companies.
The law, which Acting Governor Paul Cellucci has said he will sign,
lets insurers raise capital by issuing stock but does not require
them to share accumulated profits with policyholders, who nominally
own mutual insurers. Nearly two dozen states have passed similar
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Senate and House insurance tax-cut bills would scrap
the 14 percent net investment tax now paid by Massachusetts life
insurers as well as eliminate two smaller but costly taxes paid by
property and casualty insurers headquartered in the state. The
State bill also grants a 1.5 percent tax credit on the amount
invested by any insurer working in Massachusetts in community
projects, and gives community advocates a greater say in how
insurers finance lower-income projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
