<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-OFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS OFF ON ASIAN ECONOMIC CRISIS FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks dipped sharply Thursday on worries about
corporate profits and the Asian crisis, extending a three-day
decline that snapped the market's latest record-breaking runup.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 195.93, or 2.2 percent,
to close at 8932.98. Since last Friday's record close, the 30-stock
Dow has lost 4.3 percent of its value, but is still up 13 percent
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Other major market measures also dropped. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 Index fell 24.32, or 2.1 percent, to 1139.76, its biggest
decline since early this year. The technology-heavy Nasdaq
Composite Index lost 34.53, or 1.8 percent, to close at 1935.22.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the sharpness of Thursday's decline suggested how
edgy investors are with stock prices in record high terrain. But
most dismissed the notion that the recent drop signaled the start
of the long-feared bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as the beginning of any sort of major
correction,'' said Mickey Levy, chief economist with Nationsbanc
Montgomery Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate explanation for Thursday's decline was a
series of disappointing profit reports that revived investors'
fears that stock prices have been bid up beyond what companies'
earning power can justify.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft manufacturer Boeing Co. announced that second-quarter
profits slipped a more-than-expected 46 percent to $258 million
even as revences rose. The news sent the company's shares tumbling
6 1/4 or 13 percent to 41 1/2. Boeing said that it may cut as many
as 8,000 more jobs than it had previously planned. Shares of golf
club maker Callaway Golf Co. lost one third of their value after
the California-base company said its 1998 earnings will fall well
short of forecasts. The stock fell 6 1/4 to close at 12 3/4.
Industrial products maker Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing Co. said
it will lay off 4,000 workers after second quarter profits fell 7.7
percent to $386 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new round of weak profit reports compounded investor jitters
set off earlier this week when Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan coupled a generally upbeat assessment of the US economy
with a warning that the Asian crisis shows no signs of ending and a
reminder that a stock-market drop looms somewhere in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``History tells us that there will be a correction of some
significant dimension,' the Fed chairman lectured the House Banking
Committee Wednesday. ``What it doesn't help you on very much is
when,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The latest worries about Asia, profits and the inevitable end of
the stock boom represent the latest zig in investors' zig-zagging
assessment of the economy and the potential for making money in
stocks. In the two weeks preceding this one, stock buyers seemed to
slough off long-held concerns and send many stocks to record highs.
</P>
<P>
   Not all corporate news was bleak Thursday. For example, AT&AMP;T
Corp. announced that quarterly profits jumped 60 percent because of
aggressive cost-cutting. Profits from continuing operations rose to
$1.49 billion, or slightly more than expected. AT&AMP;T shares rose
15/16 to 58 5/.
</P>
<P>
   But stock losers outnumbered gainers three-to-one as drug,
fashion and some - but by no means all -- Internet stocks tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks took the biggest hits. Pfizer Inc, which has almost
doubled in the last year largely on the strength of Viagra sales,
fell 4 3/4 to 111 5/8. Merck &AMP; Co. declined for a third day,
shaving 1 11/16 to close at 123 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest dollar losers of the day was Amazon.com, the
red-hot on-line bookseller whose shares lost 6 3/8 to close at 127
5/8 after reporting that it had lost a less-than-expected, but
still-considerable $21.2 million last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the fact that similar high-tech stocks did
not suffer correspondingly large drops Thursday suggests that the
current downdraft could well carry the market lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``This...still hasn't reached the Internet stocks,'' said Ned
Riley, BankBoston's chief investment officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
