<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCURRY-RESIGNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCURRY QUITTING AS WHITE HOUSE PRESS SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael D. McCurry, the unflappable press secretary
whose name has become synonymous with the White House, is resigning
his high-profile post, President Clinton announced Thursday,
marking the first senior staff departure since the Monica S.
Lewinsky investigation began.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, who has enjoyed unparalleled access to Clinton as his
spokesman, will leave in October to pursue a career change. He will
be succeded by his deputy, Joe Lockhart. Although Lockhart lacks
McCurry's deftness in foreign policy, he is a veteran of political
campaigns and in Clinton's words is an ``ideal replacement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended months of speculation about McCurry's plans by
making a surprise visit to the White House briefing room and
saying, ``The long-awaited coup in the press office is finally
taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   That coup was an exception to the routine in Washington: It was
not leaked in advance to reporters. ``It's rare in the White House
that I get to announce my own personnel decisions,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   He credited McCurry with redefining the role of the press
secretary in an era of 24-hour news cycles and cable channels
filling special niches, and said: ``Mike McCurry has set the
standard by which future White House press secretaries will be
judged. ... And few can hope to match his intelligence and wit from
the podium.''
</P>
<P>
   That intelligence and wit have made McCurry arguably the most
respected press secretary in recent times among White House
reporters, and one whose access to Clinton will be hard to match.
He is famous for cajoling as well as bullying correspondents, who
respect him for his integrity and ability to play both sides _
protecting the president and helping them.
</P>
<P>
   He once entered the White House briefing room wearing a large
paper bag over his head and pretending to be an anonymous source.
But there were other times he was dour and testy, especially when
confronted with repeated questions about investigations involving
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Powell, the press secretary for President Jimmy Carter,
said, ``Mike has done a tremendous job for the president, the
administration, and has been just an outstanding press secretary
for a job that is a lot tougher than when I held it too many years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCurry also has been criticized for admitting in the first
few weeks after the Lewinsky scandal story became public that he
did not want to know about Clinton's relationship with her for fear
of subjecting himself to a subpoena and subsequent legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   In a February interview with The Chicago Tribune, McCurry
suffered what he described as a ``lapse in my sanity'' when he
suggested there may not be a simple explanation of Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry has spent 22 years as a press secretary, with the past 3
1/2 years at the White House following two years at the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   He said Thursday he wants to spend more time with his wife and
three children, and that his decision to leave the White House was
unrelated to Starr's investigation or other scandals. ``I can
assure you it had nothing to do with anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry made it known last year that he was ready to leave his
$125,000-a-year post, as did several other senior aides who are key
members of Clinton's inner circle. The Lewinsky scandal pushed back
that decision for him.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, McCurry's successor, has worked for ABC and CNN,
leaving television in 1988 to work on the presidential campaign of
former Massachusetts Governor Michael Dukakis. Lockhart earlier
worked on the presidential campaigns of Carter and Walter Mondale.
In 1996, he handled the press for the reelection campaign for
Clinton and Vice President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said he was ``daunted and kind of intimidated'' to
follow McCurry's footsteps. ``It's like the poor fool who's going
to have to step in for Michael Jordan next year.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said he has some ideas for consultant work, looks
forward to accepting invitations to speak, and eventually will
probably like to teach, though ``I don't have a clue what I would
actually want to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government was
on his list, considering his previous appearances there, McCurry
quipped: ``If I end up going to Harvard, I'll leak it to The Boston
Globe first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
