<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MCCURRY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (subs to add 11 grafs at end)  
 McCURRY TO DEPART AS WHITE HOUSE PRESS SECRETARY  
(ART ADV: Photo of Mike McCurry is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sign of growing confidence at the White House
that it is weathering the Monica Lewinsky investigation, Mike
McCurry, who has used an agile wit and aggressive tactics to
promote the administration and defend it from scandal, will resign
as press secretary this fall, President Clinton announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The president referred Thursday to McCurry's skill at gliding
just beyond a question's reach. ``His ability to respond to
developments precisely _ and, when necessary, not so precisely _
have made him a unique and instrumental element of our nation's
public diplomacy around the world,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   With that sort of sleight-of-mouth, along with a lopsided grin
and a sharp appreciation for the needs of news organizations,
McCurry has managed to maintain cordial, respectful relations with
the press, even while insisting that he was ``out of the loop'' and
unable to answer questions about Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He will be replaced by Joseph Lockhart, who served as Clinton's
1996 campaign spokesman before becoming one of McCurry's deputies
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The transition, which will take place when Congress leaves in
October, is part of a broader White House changeover that has been
frozen since January, when Clinton was accused of having an affair
with Ms. Lewinsky and covering it up.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry and several other high-ranking Clinton advisers had
hoped to leave after the president's first term to take more
lucrative and less consuming jobs in the private sector. But they
delayed their departures for fear of creating an image of a White
House in panicked retreat.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``For a lot of us, there was a period of time in the beginning
and the first half of the year that it felt like it wasn't the
right time to be leaving,'' one senior administration official
said, on condition of anonymity. ``But now we've sort of settled in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McCurry, Rahm Emanuel, a senior adviser to
Clinton, is planning to leave this fall. Two aides said that they
expect that chief of staff Erskine Bowles will also leave by the
November elections. And Doug Sosnik, a close adviser to Clinton, is
also considering departing _ though he has been doing so for so
long that he has joked he left and came back.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of how much turbulence has shaken the White
House this year that the departure of some of the president's most
trusted lieutenants would seem a sign of growing stability.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other White House aide, McCurry has been the
public voice and face of the Clinton administration. Clinton called
him ``the standard by which future White House press secretaries
will be judged.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, 43, left his post as State Department spokesman after
the Republican landslide in 1994 to try to repair Clinton's
battered press relations.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an uphill struggle. In addition to confronting a
daily barrage of foreign and domestic issues, McCurry found himself
facing a blur of controversies, including the Whitewater land deal,
the 1996 campaign finance irregularities, the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct suit, the Lewinsky investigation, and the president's
decisions to permit the Chinese to launch U.S. satellites.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the press was changing, demanding constant
White House comment as the Internet and 24-hour-news networks
obliterated the traditional daily news cycle.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry sometimes turned the relentless demands of news
organizations to his advantage. After the Lewinsky charges broke,
the networks began cutting into regular programming to show
McCurry's briefing.
</P>
<P>
   He responded by trotting officials to the lectern before him to
describe the president's policy proposals. Essentially, he
force-fed policy to viewers expecting scandal. ``Note to stations
down the line,'' McCurry said with a broad grin, after a rather
mind-numbing description of a $10 billion school modernization bond
initiative. ``We're now returning you to your regularly scheduled
program.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, who has worked dawn to dark at the White House, said
Thursday that he planned to spend more time with his wife and three
children, to consult, to lecture and to teach. He said that he had
no plans to write a book.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he notified Clinton of his plan to leave in a
letter on May 29. Thanking the president for his chance to service,
McCurry wrote, ``I'm proud to be a part of the history you are
making.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry has been accused at times of misleading reporters, on
matters as diverse as whether the president's lawyers had hired
private investigators to the nature of meetings Clinton held with
Indonesian billionaire James Riady. In some cases, McCurry based
his answers on flawed information provided by other aides.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry has sometimes been caught between an angry president and
an angry press corps, and has served as a punching bag for both,
aides have said. Internally, McCurry is known for pushing to
release information quickly, believing that the appearance of a
stonewall would do more damage in the long term. But after losing
some of those battles, he has had to face the public as the
embodiment of a White House refusal to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday for the key to survival and success in his job,
McCurry said, ``Just keep your eye on what matters most, remember
that your first and foremost obligation is to the truth and the
American people, and to get everyone to get to that point sooner or
later. And if you can keep the crowd entertained on the way, that's
all the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
