<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-MOB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEEHAN SETS HEARINGS ON FBI-MOB LINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Troubled by recent revelations in the two-decade
relationship between the FBI and gangster James J. ``Whitey''
Bulger, US Rep. Martin T. Meehan announced plans Thursday to hold
congressional hearings on federal agencies' use of criminal
informants.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said the FBI's kid-glove treatment in the 1970s and 1980s
of Bulger and his ally, Stephen Flemmi, raised serious concerns
about ``establishing, maintaining and monitoring relationships
between agents and informants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a line which cannot be crossed,'' said Meehan, a
Massachusetts Democrat in an interview Thursday. ``There is no
excuse for informants getting a license to continue selling drugs
to kids or committing violent crimes. There should be no carte
blanche.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, a former state prosecutor who serves on the crime
subcommittee of the House Judiciary Committee, said the panel's
Republican chairman, Bill McCollom of Florida, has given him a
commitment to hold the hearing. However, it will be delayed until
the completion of US District Court hearings in Boston on whether
the 1995 indictments of Bulger, Flemmi and other reputed mobsters
should be dismissed as a result of FBI misconduct. Those court
hearings are scheduled to resume next month.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said it was too early to say who would be called to
testify, but FBI Director Louis Freeh would likely be the lead
witness in the examination of informant policies and practices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Massachusetts US Attorney Donald K. Stern and &UR;  &LR; Barry
W. Mawn, Boston's top FBI agent, acknowledged in separate
statements Thursday that the bureau's dealings with Bulger and
Flemmi fell below proper standards for controlling the criminal
behavior of informants.
</P>
<P>
   Both, however, said their offices have taken extensive steps to
prevent such breakdowns in the future and will prosecute any agents
who fail to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI and attorney general informant guidelines, together
with FBI administrative controls, are intended to provide the
necessary checks and balances and to ensure that often difficult
decisions are made at the appropriate level, based on complete and
accurate information,'' Stern said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``While admittedly no system is foolproof, clearly those
objectives were not met here, at least in certain critical
respects,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Stern issued the carefully-worded remarks on the heels of a
five-part Globe Spotlight Team series about Bulger and the FBI. The
statement represented his clearest public acknowledgement that
appropriate boundaries between informants and agents were crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said there are ``important lessons'' to be learned from
the federal court hearings before Judge Mark L. Wolf. But he
declined to elaborate, saying he was limited by the ongoing federal
court hearings. Stern's subordinates are trying to preserve the
government's case against Bulger, Flemmi, reputed New England Mafia
boss Francis Salemme and other reputed mobsters named in a sweeping
federal racketeering case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decisions that get made in this area in a case-by-case basis
can be very difficult,'' Stern added. ``It's important that we have
an accountable and carefully supervised program ... We need to
revisit the national guidelines and make sure they are the right
ones and are serving the right purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said such a review is already under way on a national
basis at the Justice Deparment and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  He and Mawn, special agent in charge of the Boston FBI
office, both noted that Connecticut Deputy US Attorney John Durham
is directing a team of prosecutors and agents investigating
allegations of misconduct by individual FBI agents. At the request
of both Stern and Mawn, Durham has been named a special assistant
US attorney in Massachusetts to conduct the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Mawn also expressed his faith in existing guidelines. Still, he
said, ``These controls are obviously weakened and nullified if the
FBI supervisor is corrupted and does not ensure complete compliance
on the part of the handling agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mawn was referring to disgraced former FBI supervisor John
Morris, who admitted during testimony in April that he accepted
$7,000 in bribes from Bulger and Flemmi, and former FBI agent John
Connolly, the two gangsters' primary handler.
</P>
<P>
   Using testimony from the federal court hearings, formerly secret
documents and extensive interviews, the Globe series detailed how,
beginning in 1975 and continuing for nearly two decades, Connolly
nurtured a relationship with Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   The stories showed how that relationship ultimately led to
embellishments of Bulger's value as a Mafia informant, as well as
providing him with a longstanding shield against prosecution by
other law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly has denied any wrongdoing. He insists Bulger's value in
helping the FBI destroy the Angiulo organized crime family more
than justified the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Until the national review of informant policies is completed,
Mawn said, he will take steps on a local level to ensure proper
handling of informants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously sensitized to these things so there will be even
more supervisory review at a higher level, particularly as it
pertains to authorized criminal activity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A key question before Judge Wolf is whether FBI agents gave
Bulger and Flemmi permission to commit crimes, effectively
immunizing them from the kind of prosecution they now face.
</P>
<P>
   In calling for hearings, Representative Meehan said the Bulger
case and others around the country make it necessary for Congress
to exercise its oversight role.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to McCollom, the committee chairman, Meehan wrote:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``While it is surely difficult to establish `bright-line'
rules for dealing with informants, federal law enforcement agents
clearly should not be giving informants a virtual blank cheque ...
ignoring evidence of continuing criminality on the part of
informants, exaggerating the value of information provided by
informants, and accepting cash payments from informants.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Thursday, Meehan said that prosecution of
organized crime ``is impossible without infiltrating criminal
entities. I'm sensitive to that. But this case and others raise
issues that clearly from a public policy perspective need to be
discussed before the Judiciary Committee's crime subcommittee.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Bert Brandenberg said the agency
would continue its ``long history of working with Congress. If they
have a hearing on this, we'll work with them on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
