<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LOCKHART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCOMING WHITE HOUSE PRESS CHIEF HEEDS HARD POLITICAL LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sidear with CLINTON-MCCURRY) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As he recalls it a decade later, the summer of 1988
taught Joseph Lockhart a lesson he would never forget.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's newly chosen press secretary was then the
deputy press secretary for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the
Democratic nominee for president. Polls showed Dukakis with a
double-digit lead over the presumptive Republican nominee, Vice
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Then came August.
</P>
<P>
   Bush came to life, attacking the Democrats again and again.
Dukakis remained almost eerily silent, telling those closest to him
that Americans would not get interested in the campaign until Labor
Day. His lead vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was defining for a lot of people in the campaign,''
Lockhart said Thursday. The lesson: ``News goes on 24 hours a day.
The assertion without a response quickly becomes conventional
wisdom and then a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a lesson he remembered in 1996, when he was national
press secretary for President Clinton's re-election campaign and
excelled in terse, sometimes snide ripostes.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton's Republican opponent, former Senate Majority
Leader Bob Dole, suggested in a speech that Clinton was naive in
his dealings with the former Soviet Union, Clinton's aides
countered that Dole had an outdated view of the world, one that
failed to take account of Russia's declining influence. Or, as
Lockhart said of Dole's address, ``Right speech, wrong decade.''
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the stocky, prematurely gray Lockhart, 39,
describe him as intense, even driven, yet patient and affable. But
he clearly relishes the rough-and-tumble of politics, and those who
know him expect him to take a more bare-knuckled approach to his
job than his predecessor, Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Patrick Lockhart was born July 13, 1959, in the Bronx,
New York City, and grew up in Suffern, N.Y. His father, Ray, a
former vice president at NBC, and his mother, Ann, are deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart graduated from Georgetown University, where he majored
in European history. He was a regional press coordinator for
President Jimmy Carter's 1980 re-election campaign and an assistant
press secretary for Walter Mondale's 1984 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart and his wife, Laura Logan, a former ABC producer, live
in Northwest Washington and have a daughter, Clare, 4.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the White House in 1997 as the deputy press
secretary, Lockhart worked in public relations, as a senior vice
president for Robinson Lerer Sawyer Miller in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, he worked for Rupert Murdoch's Sky
Television News in London ( Lockhart said he was hired just because
Murdoch wanted an American face on camera), where he reported on
economics. He has also worked for the Cable News Network and for
ABC. Lockhart was the producer for NBC News' Emmy Award-winning
coverage of the revolution in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   As for how he landed his latest job, Lockhart said Thursday: ``I
often find that six months of begging is counterproductive. This
time it worked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
