<HEADLINE>
`MUNSTERS' CO-STAR VEXES INCUMBENT IN N.Y. CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLITICS-1STLD-WRI     07-23 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUNSTERS' CO-STAR VEXES INCUMBENT IN N.Y. CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBS hed; filed in ``a'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Wired, wrinkled and wily, Al ``Grandpa Munster''
Lewis took his campaign for governor to the state capital Thursday,
upstaging his running mate's criminal justice platform with a
typically theatrical _ and occasionally substantive _ performance.
</P>
<P>
   The onetime co-star of the 1960s television series, ``The
Munsters,'' Lewis, 88, amused a small crowd with persistent
references to Gov. George Pataki as ``George Potato Head Pataki''
and insinuations that reporters are ineducable.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed to stumble a bit when pressed on exactly what he
would do to help the poor and middle class, except feed New York
legislators to sharks.
</P>
<P>
   After considerable prodding, Lewis said he would heavily tax
Wall Street moguls to raise money for the underclass, reform
campaign finance laws and socialize medicine. But his ``I am my
brother's keeper'' message was almost lost in a rapid-fire flurry
of quips and cracks and savvy sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `How can you talk about the governor that way?'''
Lewis said, his face contorted around an unlit all-day cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I beg your pardon,'' the Green Party candidate said
sarcastically. ``I didn't know he was the Duke of Windsor. I didn't
know he was Lord Montbatten ... The year before he was nominated
... if you and I went to the 10 largest cities in the state of New
York and interviewed 600,000 people, we wouldn't find one person
who ever heard of George Potato Head Pataki! It's a fact. He was
extracted from a junkyard by the number one junk keeper, Alfonse _
he doesn't like that name, he lists himself as `Al' _ Pothole
D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is a Republican and D'Amato is the Republican senator.
Both men are running for re-election this year.
</P>
<P>
   While Lewis stole the show and played to the cameras at a press
conference, his running mate, Alice Green of Albany, and senatorial
candidate Joel Kovel strived to generate some interest in their
plan to overhaul New York's criminal justice system, repeal the
harsh Rockefeller drug laws and shift the focus of officialdom from
street crimes to white-collar offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Green views criminal justice issues largely in shades of black
and white, and contends that a racist system and racist society is
intent on warehousing minorities in prison instead of dealing with
core causes of crime.
</P>
<P>
   She called ``Jenna's Law'' _ a measure to limit parole for
``violent'' first time offenders _ a ``purely emotional reaction''
to the murder of a young Albany nursing student and criticized the
Assembly for caving in to political demands.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, D-Manhattan, has opposed the
measure and refused to allow a vote before the Legislature
adjourned last month. However, after weeks of pounding by
Republicans, Silver announced that he will call the Assembly back
to pass Jenna's Law.
</P>
<P>
   One letter issued by state Republicans included nine photographs
of violent criminals, with the caption: ``These violent rapists,
killers and child molesters will soon be out on the street again
... all because of one man: Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver.''
</P>
<P>
   Green and Kovel said the poster was overtly racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost has a lynch-mob quality about it,'' Green said.
``The suggestion is that only blacks or Latinos commit these
horrendous crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry O'Brien, spokesman for the state GOP, noted that six of
the nine defendants whose mug shots were included with the letter
are Caucasian. He said Green's charges are offensive, and compared
her political tactics to those of Alton Maddox Jr. and C. Vernon
Mason, advisers to Tawana Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   A jury recently found that Maddox and Mason, black activists,
along with the Rev. Al Sharpton, had exploited a black teen-ager's
fake rape claims to smear the reputation of a white prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party is hoping that Lewis' celebrity will attract at
least 50,000 votes, which would give the group a line on the ballot
for the next four years. Without official sanction from the state,
the Greens cannot run candidates without going through the costly
and cumbersome process of mounting a petition drive.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said his candidacy will draw to the polls people who
usually don't bother to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appeal to the largest bloc of voters in the state of New
York and none of you know what it is, so I will tell you!'' Lewis
bellowed. ``It's the embarrassing number of 60 percent who don't
vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
