<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CLINTON BODYGUARD, ADVISER TESTIFY BEFORE GRAND JURIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's former chief bodyguard and one
of his top political advisers testified Thursday before federal
grand juries investigating an alleged presidential affair and
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after he went behind closed doors with grand jurors
investigating the president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
Secret Service agent Larry Cockell emerged and left the building.
His attorney said Cockell had been told he would not be called
back.
</P>
<P>
   Cockell answered all questions and did not invoke any legal
privilege to keep confidential anything he saw or heard while
guarding the president, said his attorney, John Kotelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's glad it's over with,'' Kotelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, former White House deputy chief of staff Harold
Ickes, who is part of a group advising Clinton on how to deal with
the Lewinsky matter, made a brief appearance before grand jurors.
He was told he would have to return another day.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the U.S. District Courthouse, Ickes said the purpose
of his testimony was still a mystery. ``My sense is, what they'll
want to know is what I heard and saw while at the White House, but
I don't know,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes earlier testified before a federal grand jury in
Alexandria, Va., as part of an inquiry into the unauthorized
release of information from the personnel file of Linda Tripp, a
Pentagon employee who prompted the Clinton-Lewinsky segment of
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation of the Clinton
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp secretly tape recorded 20 hours of telephone conversations
with Lewinsky, chats in which the former White House intern
allegedly said that she and Clinton had an 18-month sexual affair
and that he urged her to lie about their relationship. Clinton and
Lewinsky have denied under oath engaging in sex. Clinton has said
publicly he never urged anyone to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cockell testified Thursday afternoon, at least three
other Secret Service employees and a retired agent, Robert
Ferguson, appeared before one of the two grand juries Starr was
using in his investigation into whether Clinton or any of his
associates engaged in perjury, witness intimidation or obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony from Cockell, Ferguson and other Secret Service
employees was ordered a week ago after Supreme Court Chief Justice
William Rehnquist refused to intervene in lower court rulings
compelling them to cooperate with Starr's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Starr enlisted a grand jury that had not been
hearing evidence in the Lewinsky matter. He scheduled the regular
Lewinsky grand jury to meet an extra day this week, and Thursday he
borrowed another panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the independent counsel's office is attempting to
expedite this investigation and this is one means of doing it,''
said Kotelly.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said Cockell now wants his job back as chief of the
president's personal security detail, a post he voluntarily gave up
last week out of concern that he would be distracted by his
impending grand jury appearance. Kotelly said Cockell does not
resent having to testify, but he wants to return to his duties and
a relatively normal life.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, having his picture in newspapers and on
television each day has turned Cockell into a public figure,
Kotelly said. ``He will not be able to have the same type of
anonymity he had before and obviously he regrets losing that
because in some ways that affects his ability to do his job in
protecting the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, pressure intensified Thursday for Attorney General Janet
Reno to seek another independent counsel to investigate the
president, this time over fund-raising practices of his 1996
re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   Reno confirmed that she is reviewing a new report and
recommendation from Charles G. LaBella, head of her department's
campaign fund-raising task force, to authorize an independent
inquiry into whether Clinton, Vice President Al Gore or
high-ranking Democratic Party officials violated campaign finance
laws.
</P>
<P>
   At her weekly press briefing, Reno declined to discuss the
contents of LaBella's report, but said she would give the matter a
fair review before determining whether to invoke the law covering
appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I determine that it is triggered, I will trigger it,''
said the attorney general, who has resisted asking a three-judge
panel to launch an independent inquiry into campaign fund raising
even after one has been repeatedly urged by congressional
Republicans and, late last year, by FBI Director Louis Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, renewed his call for Reno to seek an independent inquiry
into fund raising by the Clinton White House. ``If she doesn't do
it this time, I think there had to be some kind of backroom deal
made,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a year ago, Reno appointed LaBella, a federal prosecutor,
to head the Justice Department's campaign finance inquiry, which
had been criticized by Republicans as mismanaged. Since then, 11
lower-level fund-raisers have been indicted, but nothing so far has
linked fund-raising improprieties to the White House or Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   LaBella delivered his report to Reno a week ago as he left
Washington to return to San Diego, where he will become interim
U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
