<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0244 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-MANHUNT-ART-2TAK     07-23 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-MANHUNT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNSFOLK URGE FUGITIVE IN BOMBINGS TO `RUN, RUDOLPH, RUN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(cb) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ There is a part of this town that is rooting for
Eric Robert Rudolph to elude the camouflaged G-men and their
droopy-eared bloodhounds, and not just because the six-month search
for the man accused of bombing an Alabama abortion clinic has been
good for business.
</P>
<P>
   As search teams of rifle-toting agents fan through the dense
rhododendron of the Nantahala National Forest, there is a degree of
local pride in the ability of a ninth-grade dropout to outwit more
than 200 investigators equipped with motion detectors and
helicopters with heat sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Factor in an underlayer of anti-abortion sentiment and the
innate distrust of government that is native to the mountains of
western North Carolina and it begins to explain why a local man has
sold more than 200 T-shirts bearing the chant: ``Run Rudolph Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph has been charged in the Birmingham, Ala., attack, which
killed an off-duty police officer and seriously wounded a nurse.
The authorities want to question him about three other bombings in
Atlanta in 1996 and 1997, including the pipe-bomb explosion at
Centennial Olympic Park on July 27, 1996, that killed one woman and
injured 111 people.
</P>
<P>
   Sukey S. Reid, a 55-year-old artist who lives in Nantahala,
Rudolph's boyhood home, said she was one of those who hoped that
the fugitive would be found and safely captured. But as she watched
six heavily armed agents climb into the woods this morning to begin
their daily search, she acknowledged feeling a certain empathy for
Rudolph, who has been on the FBI's list of the 10 most wanted
fugitives since May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's human nature,'' she said. ``Yeah, we all know
he's bad. But there's something about a human being being hunted
down by dogs in the woods. It's like he's an animal. People say,
`Oh, the poor little guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Like many people here, Laurie D. Barlow, a 30-year-old tanning
salon owner, questions the case against Rudolph and argues that
some of the evidence linking him to a series of bombings must have
been planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running now because he knows they're looking for a
scapegoat,'' she said. ``But he's a heck of a lot smarter than 200
FBI agents. They might be smart in the city but they sure don't
know the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Town leaders and others entrusted with protecting the area's
image are not proud of such sentiment, and they assert that it does
not represent anything close to a majority view.
</P>
<P>
   ``People around here don't condone what he's done,'' said Jim C.
Hutto, one of three barbers in Andrews and a member of the town
board. ``But the longer it goes on the more people lean toward him.
They think he's one man and they've got all these people and all
this sophisticated equipment looking for him. It sort of makes him
an underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   The perception of Rudolph as a sympathetic outlaw is prevalent
enough that the widow of the police officer who was killed in the
Birmingham attack came here Wednesday to confront some local
residents who in TV interviews have called Rudolph a folk hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a murderer, a terrorist,'' said Felecia Sanderson, whose
husband, Robert, was killed in an explosion Jan. 29 at the New
Woman All Women Health Care Clinic in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   The Asheville Citizen-Times, the nearest daily newspaper, also
took note of the area's ambivalence about Rudolph's capture in an
editorial on Tuesday. ``There's a natural inclination to root for
one man against the odds,'' the editorial observed. But in this
case, the newspaper said, such attitudes ``should dismay anyone who
wants to continue living in a country governed by law rather than
anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   The division of opinion here is simply the latest oddity in a
case that has been bizarre from the beginning. This is the same
investigation that led Rudolph's older brother, Daniel, to produce
a videotaped message to the FBI in March that showed him using a
power saw to amputate his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has offered a $1 million reward for Eric Rudolph, a
31-year-old carpenter whose family moved from south Florida into
these foggy hills when he was a teen-ager. He has been on the run,
presumably in the woods, since the day after the Birmingham
bombing, when police first identified him by tracing the license
plate number of a car seen by witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the multiagency task force that is pursuing Rudolph
announced that a hungry Rudolph had emerged from the woods on July
7 and made contact with George O. Nordmann, the owner of a health
food store in Andrews who has known Rudolph for years. Two days
later, Rudolph returned to Nordmann's house, which is deep in the
woods, and took a large quantity of food and Nordmann's blue 1977
Nissan pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nordmann, who was not home when the food and truck were taken,
did not report the encounter or the theft until July 11.
Investigators found the abandoned truck at a nearby campground on
July 13, setting off the nonstop, day-and-night manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Woody Enderson, the FBI agent leading the task
force, said that search teams had found a number of small campsites
that Rudolph may have used. At one such site, they found buried
trash that bore Rudolph's fingerprint. Enderson did not say how
long ago Rudolph may have been at the site, but other
law-enforcement officials said they believed he might have used it
more than two weeks ago to surveil Nordmann's house.
</P>
<P>
   Among the qualities that some residents find endearing about
Rudolph is his apparent consideration for Nordmann. He left five
$100 bills to pay for the food he purloined and left a handwritten
note in the truck identifying Nordmann as its owner,
law-enforcement officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the search has taken on the surreal quality of a daily
ritual, as has the interaction between the investigators and a
sizable encampment of journalists. Federal, state and local agents
gather each morning at the U.S. Forest Service's Appletree
campground, which has been transformed into a command post.
</P>
<P>
   As teams of six to eight agents leave the post for trails in
Tellico Gap or at the top of Winding Staircase Road, they are
followed by tire-screeching convoys of reporters and cameramen
desperate to send CNN and NBC their daily footage of agents with
their guns and dogs. The journalists film the agents as they
embark, but have respected the agents' requests that they be
allowed to search the woods alone.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, false sightings and fruitless leads have
become commonplace. On Tuesday night, a reported sighting _ later
proven erroneous _ sent investigators and reporters racing into the
darkness. On another day, when a gunshot was heard within the
30-square-mile search area, agents descended on a farmer who
explained that he was trying to exterminate a meddlesome rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Here in nearby Andrews, the town of 2,500 where the
investigation is based, residents long for a return to the sleepy
normalcy of their purposefully peaceful lives. They complain that
the crush of television satellite trucks has made it hard to get a
parking spot near the post office. Motels are so booked that one
giddy proprietor joked that he was hiding Rudolph in a second-floor
guest room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good for business,'' Mayor Jim Dailey said. ``It's
helped the motels, the bed and breakfasts, the restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   But some business owners fear that the Rudolph case and its
accompanying publicity may hurt the area in the long run. Already,
said John Paul Jones, the owner of the Bradley Inn in Andrews,
innkeepers and river rafting outfitters have received cancellations
from people who are scared to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph's recent contact with Nordmann has revived the area's
favorite parlor game, in which people debate whether they would
turn Rudolph in if he showed up on their doorsteps. Nordmann, who
has locked his store door and papered its windows with vitamin
advertisements, has not publicly explained his delay in notifying
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement authorities have neither charged nor criticized
Nordmann, at least partly because they do not want to discourage
witnesses from coming forward in the future. They have suggested
that Nordmann was scared and was wrestling with his conscience.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people interviewed here this week said they would
have to wrestle with theirs as well.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie P. Troy, a television repairman from Andrews, said he
thought that extreme tactics were justified to stop abortions and
that he would only report Rudolph for the reward money. ``I need
the money so I'd probably turn him in,'' Troy said. ``But if I
didn't need the money I'd probably let him go. He didn't do
anything to me personally. It's not my matter. That's the way
people think around here.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jeff W. May, a retired sawmill operator from Nantahala who
once employed Rudolph to do odd jobs at his house, said he, too,
was torn. ``I might try to talk him into surrendering,'' he said.
``And if he didn't I might just not tell anybody. I feel bad when
someone is down and out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
