<HEADER>
A0246 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OTWALLA-FOOD-SAFETY-5     07-23 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OTWALLA-FOOD-SAFETY-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-EVER CRIMINAL CONVICTION LEVIED IN FOOD POISONING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Ill., Md., Pa., Wash., Canada)  (js) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In what federal officials say is the first criminal
conviction in a food poisoning outbreak, Odwalla Inc. pleaded
guilty Thursday to violating federal food safety laws and agreed to
pay a $1.5 million fine for selling tainted apple juice that killed
a 16-month-old girl and sickened 70 other people in several states
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for federal officials to bring criminal charges in
cases like this, and the plea followed a lengthy investigation that
found that Odwalla, one of the nation's largest producers of fresh
juice, did not do enough to prevent contamination in its products.
Officials said Thursday that, as new kinds of dangerous bacteria
spread through the nation's food supply, they are expanding the
kinds of penalties and levers they can use to force companies to be
more rigorous in their safety practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlement of this case today highlights the attention
that we pay to these very important issues,'' said Dr. Michael
Friedman, the acting commissioner of the Food and Drug
Administration, which helped prosecute the case. ``It highlights
the very substantial responsibilities that industries have for
products that are safe to the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Smith DeWaal, director of food safety for the Center
for Science in the Public Interest, an advocacy group, said the
settlement would be ``a good deterrent for other companies; it
certainly ups the ante in terms of companies that would have food
safety problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Odwalla, based in Half Moon Bay, Calif., pleaded guilty to 16
counts of unknowingly delivering ``adulterated food products for
introduction into interstate commerce'' in the October 1996
outbreak. In that outbreak, a batch of its juice infected with the
toxic bacteria E.coli O157:H7 sickened people in Colorado,
California, Washington and Canada. Fourteen children developed a
life-threatening disease that ravages kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.5 million penalty is the largest criminal penalty in a
food poisoning case, federal officials said. Of that amount,
$250,000 will go to a nonprofit food safety organization, Safe
Tables Our Priority, and to food safety research centers at
Pennsylvania State University and the University of Maryland.
Odwalla will also be on court-supervised probation for five years,
meaning that it will have to submit a detailed plan to the food and
drug agency demonstrating its food safety precautions and that any
subsequent violations could result in more serious charges, Federal
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sentence or fine will ever mitigate the terrible tragedy
which lies at the heart of this case,'' said Joseph Johns, the
assistant U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of California, who
led the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Odwalla has settled more than a dozen civil suits, including
payments of more than $12 million to the families of the five
most-injured of the surviving children.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gallagher, a spokesman for Odwalla, said the fine
``finalizes and puts a dollar figure to an incident that we took
responsibility for two years ago.'' He pointed out that ``Odwalla
is not being charged with any laws relating to the conditions or
cleanliness of our processing facility.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He added: ``With respect to the size of our fine, we hope that
the visibility of that will raise awareness and send a message to
consumers about food safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Odwalla, which sells juices and nutritional shakes in the West,
Southwest and Midwest, became a success by capitalizing on the
growing U.S. taste for fresh-from-the-farm products. But it began
pasteurizing its apple juice after the outbreak, and hired experts
to overhaul its safety systems. Odwalla, which suffered substantial
losses after the outbreak, reported its first post-outbreak profits
last month. In June, the company reported net income of $140,000
for the third quarter, on sales of $15.4 million. It lost $1.8
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal charges in food safety cases are uncommon. It is often
difficult to determine the source of a food poisoning outbreak and,
once found, to assess how much responsibility suppliers,
manufacturers or distributors have for the contamination.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, authorities say, there are few criminal laws that
apply specifically to food safety.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported in January that in the weeks before
the outbreak, Odwalla began relaxing its standards on accepting
blemished fruit and began to rein in the authority of its own
safety officials, according to company documents and interviews
with former Odwalla managers. By those accounts, on the day the
contaminated juice was pressed, production managers brushed aside
warnings from a company inspector that a batch of apples was too
rotten to use without taking special precautions against
contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Odwalla officials have acknowledged that their safety systems
failed to keep out the E. coli, but they deny that the company took
any undue risks and say that, like many others in their industry,
they simply did not realize that E. coli O157:H7 could live in
apple juice.
</P>
<P>
   The Odwalla outbreak, along with several other recent cases of
wide-scale food poisoning, helped galvanize national attention
around food safety, prompting federal regulators to propose rules
that would require food processors to take new steps against
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Odwalla outbreak and a few others involving lettuce,
E. coli O157:H7 was primarily associated with an outbreak in 1993,
when four children died and more than 500 others became ill from
eating under-cooked hamburgers at the Jack in the Box fast-food
chain in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Food and Drug Administration issued a rule
requiring makers of fresh fruit and vegetable juices to display
labels warning that, as unpasteurized products, they ``may contain
harmful bacteria that can cause serious illness in children, the
elderly, and persons with weakened immune systems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
