<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-TESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES ASSESS TEACHER-CERTIFICATION FAILURE LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some of Massachusetts' best-known colleges had among
the highest failure rates on the new teacher certification test,
according to detailed scores released Thursday. The disappointed
schools vowed to revamp their curriculums in response.
</P>
<P>
   While it had been known that only 41 percent of candidates
overall passed the teacher test last April, the individual schools'
scores surprised and dismayed officials at colleges both public and
private.
</P>
<P>
   Among schools with a substantial number of students or graduates
who took the test, only 17.6 percent of candidates from
Northeastern passed; 36.5 percent of Lesley College candidates
passed, and 38.3 percent of Wheelock College candidates passed the
eight-hour exam, according to Department of Education figures.
</P>
<P>
   Even Boston University, whose chancellor John Silber, chairman
of the Board of Education, has lead the drive for improved teacher
quality, was disappointed: 65.7 percent of its candidates passed.
In a statement Thursday, Silber said that if Boston University
students do not manage a 90 percent pass rate within the next two
years, he will be among those recommending that BU close its school
of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not happy,'' said BU spokesman Kevin Carleton. ``Given
the much higher average'' SAT scores of ``our entering freshman, I
think we had hoped to do much better on the test than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   BU ranked second in percent who passed among schools with more
than 50 students taking the test. Boston College ranked first in
that group, with nearly 80 percent passing.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-hour exam tested would-be teachers in reading,
writing, and their concentration of study. The 1,800 candidates
taking the exam were mostly college seniors or recent graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Brandeis, Northeastern, and Clark University said
Thursday they are already planning signifigant curriculum changes,
especially in writing, based on their students' performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``These scores were a real gut check for us,'' said Northeastern
University spokeswoman Janet Hookailo. ``We are not going to step
back and wait for more test results. We have put all our teacher
education classes under administration review.''
</P>
<P>
   In the literacy portion of the exam, students from most schools
did far worse in writing than reading.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly 65 percent of 17 test takers from Northeastern
passed the reading portion of the exam, for instance, only 29.4
passed the writing.
</P>
<P>
   At schools where only a small number of students or graduates
took the exam, state education officials warned that the number
that passed may not be significant, or accurately reflect overall
standards. For example, the College of the Holy Cross in Worcester
did poorly, with fewer than half (44.4) of its candidates passing
the entire test, but it was only represented by nine test-takers.
All nine passed the reading and writing portions.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard Graduate School of Education, with seven candidates,
and Wellesley College, with six, were the only two schools with no
failing grades. Tufts University, with 16 candidates, came in third
place, with 81.3 percent passing.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Massachusetts at Boston had a 41 percent pass
rate.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the scores, University of Massachusetts President
William M. Bulger issued a recommendation that students be required
to pass the test before they are allowed to start the student
teaching portion of their undergraduate work.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, officials were
unhappy to learn that 45 percent of their 130 candidates failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not as strong as we thought we would be,'' said UMass
Amherst spokesperson Kay Scanlon. ``But we need more detailed data
to see what we need to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know how students' grade point averages compare
to how they did on the test. We need more information before we can
institute new programs.''
</P>
<P>
   At Brandeis, just over half of the 15 candidates who took the
test passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results are obviously not satisfactory for us,'' said
Dennis Nealon, Brandeis University spokesman. ``Brandeis would like
to see something much much closer to full passing. The university
will make it its business to have students perform better.'' But
Nealon, like others, said that deans would need more information
about the test before they could revamp college coursework. None of
the officials had seen the test, and many say they expected the
scores to rise from the second round of testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know exactly what the test is doing,'' Nealon said.
``There seems to be this cloak of secrecy about what exactly it's
testing.''
</P>
<P>
   BU officials say they will review the school grades of students
who passed and failed to see what changes should be made. Already,
it is clear that subject specialty classes such as math need to be
much tougher, spokesman Carleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner David Driscoll said there were no huge
suprises for state education officials because they were already
aware of the state's generally high failure rate. He said he hopes
the individual institutions can see their weaknesses as they sort
out scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, the second giving of a test means that the
scores go up,'' Driscoll said. ``My hope is that it will go up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
