<SLUG> BC-HBO/IMNET-DEAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HBO &AMP; Co. sets second purchase of week, Imnet for $225 million
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Atlanta-based HBO &AMP; Co. continued its two-week roller
coaster ride with the announcement Thursday of an agreement to
acquire Alpharetta-based Imnet Systems for about $225 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal sent each company's shares sharply in opposite
directions. HBO &AMP; Co. shares sank $5.62 1/2, to $27.25, on volume
of about 24.7 million shares. It was the second most actively
traded stock on Wall Street. Imnet shares rose 32 percent, or $5.18
3/4, to $21.43 3/4 on volume about 10 times its daily average. It
was the second-biggest percentage gainer on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, it's a great fit,'' said analyst David Francis
of Volpe Brown Whelan. But the deal's timing and price, Whelan
said, raise questions for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, merger talks collapsed between HBO &AMP; Co. and McKesson
Corp., a huge San Francisco-based drug wholesaler. Leaked
information of that stunning proposal caused the stock price of HBO
&AMP; Co., the largest health care software and services company, to
plunge.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, the company announced it had agreed to buy US Servis
Inc. for $50 million in stock. The New Jersey-based firm provides
outsourcing services for physician delivery systems and hospital
business offices.
</P>
<P>
   Such acquisitions have helped HBO &AMP; Co. break the billion-dollar
revenue mark and accelerate past its competitors. On July 13, the
company announced record second-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   A software company, Imnet specializes in capturing paper medical
records and images and storing them electronically. The two
companies have been business partners since 1996, with HBO offering
Imnet products under its Pathways software line. A merger had been
the topic of speculation for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, subject to regulatory and Imnet stockholder approval,
is expected to close in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Imnet shares recently have climbed after hitting a 52-week low
of $9.50 on June 2. It has annual revenues of about $50 million,
but lost money in two of the last three fiscal quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not like the valuation or the combination of this
acquisition,'' analyst Sharon Corr of Merrill Lynch told Bloomberg
Business News. She cut her rating of HBO &AMP; Co. to near-term
``accumulate'' from near-term ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the McKesson talks ``opened a Pandora's box of issues
not before examined by investors,'' Francis said. Those questions,
he said, include whether HBO &AMP; Co. can continue to expand operating
margins and make technology acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
