<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    300 jobs to disappear with the closing of Quebecor plant
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The former American Signature printing plant, which
experienced a bitter four-year strike that ended last year, will be
closed this fall, costing 300 jobs, a union representative said.
</P>
<P>
   It was purchased last year by the Canadian printing giant
Quebecor Printing. The plant prints catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll phase out as business goes or as the help goes,'' said
Eugene Spraggs, 62, a pressman and union steward who has worked for
the company for 38 years. Spraggs, who earns about $18 an hour, was
told of the closing Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no package, no severance. No vacation. No nothing.
It's rotten,'' he said. Quebecor spokesman Wayne Hanson would not
comment. ``There are meetings going on there through tomorrow
morning,'' he said. The strike started in 1993 after Fuji Bank of
Japan purchased the company and fired the entire work force but
rehired all but 47 union employees. It also reduced compensation by
nearly a third.
</P>
<P>
   The strike brought out hundreds of picketers, including civil
rights leader Jesse Jackson. It appeared to have ended last year
when a National Labor Relations Board administrative judge ruled
the strike was prompted by unfair labor practices, not wages.
</P>
<P>
   That meant, under federal law, strikers couldn't be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   However, many workers never returned to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Spraggs and James Osborne, president of Local 96-B of the
Graphic Communications International Union, said Quebecor recently
met with the NLRB and issued a letter saying it was rehiring dozens
of workers who never returned to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it looks like they won,'' said Spraggs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
