<SLUG> BC-STATEFARM-RATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State Farm to cut state premiums
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- State Farm's 1.4 million auto insurance customers in
Georgia are getting a break on their premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine on Thursday approved a 2.6
percent reduction, which will lower auto insurance costs by a total
of $21 million a year. Oxendine said State Farm, Georgia's largest
auto insurer, originally proposed to reduce rates by about $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed some (customers) getting rate increases,''
Oxendine said. ``We felt those were inappropriate. We disallowed
those increases, which pretty much overall doubled the amount.''
</P>
<P>
   State Farm could not be immediately reached for comment. It was
the 15th and largest rate reduction approved by Oxendine's office
this year. The others totaled about $9 million. Some were as high
as 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine attributed the cuts principally to increased
competition among auto insurers in Georgia. Other factors were the
improved economy, better law enforcement and safety on the
highways, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The $21 million in reductions also include a larger discount for
policyholders with 10 or more years of accident-free driving,
Oxendine said.
</P>
<P>
   Some policyholders with other types of State Farm coverage, such
as homeowners, may also receive an additional 5 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
