<HEADER>
A0252 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYES-COX     07-23 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Major stockholder wants Hayes to find 'strategic investor'
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Hayes Corp. officials Thursday remained silent in the
face of a call from an investor to consider putting the company up
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion by James J. Cramer, manager of Cramer Capital,
comes at a time when the company stock is sliding and its sales
picture somewhat shaky. Cramer, also editor of a financial Web site
called The Street.com, has recently boosted his fund's share in the
Norcross-based company to about 8.4 percent of the outstanding
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer said Hayes should seek a ``strategic investor'' or
perhaps look for a buyer, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Hayes, whose stock has lost 82 percent of its value
this year, declined to comment. However, they said Cramer had not
contacted the company with any suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cramer Capital has 1.7 million shares, its leverage is
limited, since about 80 percent of Hayes stock is held by insiders.
Dennis Hayes, who founded the company and remains its chairman, is
the largest shareholder with 4.9 million shares of common stock,
according to papers filed with federal regulators. Other large
investors include Rinzai Ltd., Kaifa Ltd., Rolling Profit Holdings
Ltd., Lao Hotel Ltd., Saliendra Pte Ltd. and Qwek Investments Pte
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes virtually invented the PC modem industry after its 1977
founding, but ran into trouble in the early 1990s and was forced
into bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   The company emerged from Chapter 11 with several strong quarters
of financial results, then began to struggle, laying off hundreds
of workers. Sales of the type of consumer modems the company was
built on have been erratic. With new technologies likely to replace
those modems in the next few years, the merger with Access Beyond
was engineered to give Hayes a chance to capitalize on the next
generation of devices for connecting computers to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes has in recent months announced deals in which it will make
cable modems and devices that allow copper phone lines to transport
data at high speeds. However, revenues still suffer, and the
company's stock has slid slowly downward.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes stock closed Thursday at $2.31 1/4 a share, down from a
high of $12.56 1/4 on Dec. 31, the day Hayes merged with Access
Beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
