<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FLOYD-BOS &LR;      07-23 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FLOYD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOYD NOT QUITE CHICAGO BULLS COACH _ OR IS HE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Tim Floyd stood at a podium Thursday and officially
earned the right to say he is the next coach of the Chicago Bulls.
His new bosses, Jerrys Reinsdorf and Krause, even presented him
with a five-year contract reportedly worth $9 million. Simple
enough. That means his first United Center press conference
signaled his first day at work, right?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. And no.
</P>
<P>
   What this entire city knows by now is that former Iowa State
coach Floyd is the newest Bulls employee. But there is a
possibility he may not coach until the 21st century. Then again, he
could be the head man on the 21st day of next month. Reinsdorf and
Krause want to be sure that former coach Phil Jackson no longer
wants the job from which he resigned last month. So, the executives
announced, they are giving Floyd the title of director of
basketball operations. One day he will be their coach. In the
meantime, they say Jackson will be asked _ again _ to come back to
the six-time NBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   All parties acknowledged that their reason for delay is Michael
Jordan. He is on record as saying he doesn't want to play for any
coach but Jackson. Jordan also mentioned Floyd by name last week,
saying he didn't want to play for the 44-year-old career college
coach. That led to a meeting last Sunday among Reinsdorf, Krause,
and Floyd. The men said they came up with their compromise at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bulls continue to say Floyd is their man. They say the
same thing about Jordan. And Jackson, too. That leaves them with a
new coach-in-residence; their former coach, who may be in the
Montana wilderness studying Zen; their superstar, who may or may
not be ``sticking to his guns'' and playing only for Jackson; and a
breakup of the team on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concluded that nothing should stand in the way of our
desire to bring back the championship team,'' Reinsdorf said,
occasionally glancing at his prepared notes. ``We also reminded
ourselves that we had told Michael Jordan that he could take as
long as he wanted to recover from the grind from last season before
deciding if he wanted to play next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, The Agreement. As you can imagine, the morning press
conference was preceded and succeeded by lively debates throughout
the city. The gist of one column in the Chicago Tribune: The Bulls
have done the right thing. The gist of another in the Sun-Times:
The Bulls are dolts.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of it all was Floyd, who could not sit still as
Reinsdorf spoke. He quickly emptied a bottle of water during the
executive's opening remarks. When it was time for him to speak,
Floyd _ accompanied by his wife, Beverly, 16-year-old daughter,
Shannon, and legendary Texas-El Paso coach Don Haskins _ said Bulls
fans can expect a man who is knowledgeable, energetic, and
forthright.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd also said he believes in defense, endearing himself to the
city's sports fans by referencing the 1985 Bears; he said he wants
to continue to run the Bulls' famed triangle offense; he asked the
media to ``give me a chance'' and not to refer to him as ``Jerry
Krause's boy,'' a phrase that has been uttered many times over the
last three years (supposedly, the two are fishing pals, although
Krause said Thursday they've put bait to hook together only ``maybe
three times'').
</P>
<P>
   He looked like a coach. He sounded like a coach (``To tell you
that I would not like to be a part of this team or its legacy would
be ridiculous; I would love to do that,'' and: ``There's not a lot
broken here''). But it was clear that he wasn't the coach. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Phil Jackson decides to return, Michael can have the coach
that he and we have always wanted him to have,'' Reinsdorf said. He
added, ``Should Phil not return by the end of the lockout, Tim will
succeed him as head coach of the Chicago Bulls. If Phil does
return, Tim will continue to serve as director of basketball
operations and would be involved in personnel matters, scouting,
and basketball business.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause was silent for much of the 40-minute briefing. He did say
that Floyd's lack of NBA experience was never a factor while citing
the championship (or near-championship) careers of former college
coaches Jack Ramsay, Dick Motta, and John MacLeod. Now the new
questions in Chicago:
</P>
<P>
   What's the likelihood of Jackson returning? Will Michael play
for Tim? How comfortable is Floyd with this?
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the possibility that Phil would come back? I have no
idea,'' Reinsdorf said. ``Every time we've asked him to come back,
he's said he doesn't want to come back. We'll give it a shot one
more time. Maybe Michael can talk him into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the issue of Jordan. Reinsdorf was spotted walking
out of Jordan's Chicago office Thursday _ ``I plead the Fifth,'' he
said _ leading to speculation that Jordan approves of the current
office structure. And Floyd said he called Buzz Petersen, a former
teammate of Jordan's, and asked him to find out what Jordan thought
of him. Petersen told Floyd that Jordan said, ``Tim, don't take
your name out of the running for the Bulls job.''
</P>
<P>
   That left the possibility, Floyd said, that ``Jordan could play
with me'' if Jackson says no again. And if Jackson says he doesn't
want Floyd around? ``I'll step away,'' the coach with the Southern
accent said.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, he is Coach Floyd. He just doesn't know when he'll be
able to call himself that without mentioning Jackson in the same
sentence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
