<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-NYT &LR;      07-23 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS ANNOUNCEMENT LEAVES WIGGLE ROOM FOR MANAGEMENT ON COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Reinsdorf and Jerry Krause appeared Thursday to make a
clumsy attempt at wiping their fingerprints from a plan that may
ultimately push Michael Jordan out of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulls' executives announced Tim Floyd as the team's
director of basketball operations _ a decision Jordan has not
supported _ they installed a surprising loophole.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls offered to keep Floyd in the position of basketball
operations director if Phil Jackson, whose strained relationship
with management helped expedite his departure in June after the
Bulls won a sixth title, wanted to reconsider and return to coach
Jordan next season.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no evidence offered by Reinsdorf to suggest
Jackson would come back to Chicago as head coach. Jackson's agent,
Todd Musburger, said his client was ``flabbergasted'' at
Reinsdorf's comments during a Bulls' press conference held in
Chicago on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That reaction left Reinsdorf's olive branch to Jackson viewed as
a public relation's ploy, and a way of deflecting blame should
Jordan remain steadfast in his stand to leave the Bulls unless
Jackson is the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so transparent and so disingenuous and so much the result
of this spin doctoring, if you will,'' Musburger said of
Reinsdorf's appeal to Jackson. ``There isn't an ounce of legitimacy
to what was said. Are we to believe that Phil, the head coach, and
Floyd, the coach to be, would occupy the same space in that
organization? It is positively ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, they have proved their skill at sucking the joy
out of the moment. Floyd should have been properly praised and
announced. Instead, he had to pretend he was window dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The day ended up as another addition to the soap opera saga in
Chicago, where dysfunction and turmoil has threatened to end a
dynasty before old age ever has a chance. In the middle of it all
is Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   After signing a five-year deal worth $2 million a year, Floyd,
who resigned as head coach of Iowa State on Wednesday, stood at a
podium in Chicago's United Center and talked about his desire to
work in concert with Jordan, and, if necessary, with Jackson as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would step completely away if Phil wanted,'' said Floyd, a
defensive-oriented coach with no NBA experience who had a 243-130
record as a collegiate coach. ``I would not take this job if I
thought it would push Michael Jordan out. This is about Michael's
wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of Floyd's hire did not disrupt Jordan's summer passion
Thursday. He was on a golf course in suburban Chicago and
unavailable for comment. But throughout the Bulls' search for a
coach, Jordan repeated his unwillingness to play for a young coach
like Floyd, whose fishing-buddy relationship with Krause is
considered another strike against Jackson's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd recognized this as he asked everyone to restrain
themselves from calling him ``Krause's boy.'' Floyd also asked
everyone to give him a chance, including Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Phil doesn't return, I hope Michael will come back and play
for me,'' Floyd said. ``I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has said he will not make a decision about his future
until after the National Basketball Association's lockout ends. In
one way, Reinsdorf also appealed to Jordan to help coax Jackson
back into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the possibilities that Phil would come back? I have
no idea,'' Reinsdorf said. ``Every time I've asked him to come back
he's said he doesn't wanna come back, but we're going to try one
more time. And maybe Michael can talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd also wants to talk to Jordan. Through a feeling out
process, he hopes to gain Jordan's respect and help him understand
how their relationship could work. However, the owner-imposed
lockout prohibits teams from having conversations with players.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a way around the situation by using third parties,
but from his earlier comments, it would seem Jordan has little
interest in getting to know Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Jackson has a drastic change of heart, or unless the
Bulls retreat from their position that only Floyd will coach if
Jackson does not, Floyd is their man. He has been waiting in the
wings for two years although Reinsdorf said he offered Jackson a
chance to return for another year before he departed Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he made the offer, but after Phil had spent two days
packing up his office,'' Musburger said. ``So if you're really
sincere about keeping someone you truly value, do you announce his
contract in the summer of 1997 as the last deal the Bulls will ever
do with you? And along the way, will you say to him in private, I
don't care if you win 82 games, you are not coming back? Is that
the way you treat a man you want to return?''
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson's return so improbable, Floyd may be left to coach
a championship team with an entirely different face next year, one
without Jordan and free agents Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman. It
would be as if Bulls' fans would have to go cold turkey after a
decade of watching their team carry on as the dominant franchise in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing hasn't changed,'' Reinsdorf said. ``We want to bring
everyone back and we want to win a seventh championship. We'll do
everything we can to win it and to bring everybody back.
Unfortunately, it's not just a matter of Phil, it's Michael and
Scottie and all the free agents. We have to be ready to field a
team next season. We have to have a coach in place.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
