r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     07-23 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPO WON'T REQUIRE THAT CRYING TOWEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ It is 11 a.m. under a blazing sun
alongside the Cowboys' practice field, the morning session has just
ended and Dave Campo leads a platoon of sweaty, exhausted players
to an adjacent fence, where fans are lined up 10 deep for
autographs.
</P>
<P>
   He signs for 20 minutes, grabbing caps and pennants, yearbooks
and handout rosters, chatting amiably with fans eager to get close
to a real Cowboys coach.
</P>
<P>
   What most of them don't realize is that they just don't get any
more real than the Cowboys' defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that it was only a few months ago that Campo didn't
even get within sniffing distance of his dream job _ the one Chan
Gailey wound up with _ and that he is essentially in the process of
rebuilding key elements of the Cowboys' defense from scratch, he is
in remarkably good humor these days.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkable, that is, if you didn't know the resilient,
forward-looking Campo.
</P>
<P>
   The first thought in preparation for a Campo interview is to
check the essentials. Notepad, pen, microcassette recorder, hanky,
sedative, sympathetic look.
</P>
<P>
   Check, check and check.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you can check the last three items at the door. Campo
doesn't need your sympathy or mine. A run-stopper in the defensive
line and someone to replace Brock Marion, perhaps, but no crying
towels are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Gailey, a coordinator from another organization, got the
job Campo would crawl across Texas in the middle of summer for, but
he is wasting no time in feeling sorry for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal to a fault, Campo got lip service from the media during
the Cowboys' coaching search, but not even an official interview
with owner Jerry Jones, who had his sights set on an
offensive-minded head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campo has as good a feel for the overall picture as any coach
I've ever been around,'' Jones says flatly. ``He has a head coach's
view of what's best for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo's expertise, of course, is defense. He owns the Super Bowl
hardware _ and Jones' undying gratitude _ to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I understand is timing and the right situation
and those kinds of things,'' Campo says. ``I feel like I've got
respect from this organization, and that's the thing I'm most
interested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all about winning, No. 1. The only thing that's really
important to me right now is 6-and-10. I don't like 6-and-10. I
like winning football games. As long as I have the respect of the
organization and Chan Gailey, that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Always a class act, Campo swallowed his pride and put his own
dreams on hold when Gailey first arrived at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Chan when he came in for his interview, `If you're the
head coach here, I've got my eye on the bull's eye, and I
understand the chain of command.' If the best I do is to be the
(defensive) coordinator of the Dallas Cowboys, I couldn't be with a
better organization,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and the Cowboys are lucky to have him. So is Gailey. About
to enter his 10th year with the Cowboys and fourth as the defensive
coordinator, Campo provides the head coach a much-needed security
blanket, allowing Gailey to concentrate on putting in the team's
new offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he feels that way,'' Campo says. ``I like him. He came
in without a lot of fanfare, but he's a very solid individual as a
person and he wants to be a head football coach. He's not settling
for just calling offensive plays,
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not very involved with the defense right now, but I
guarantee you that he will be. He knows defense. He knows what
we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, Campo says, is a dash of Jimmy Johnson combined with a
heavy dollop of Tom Landry. And that's an exciting combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point I'm making, is when it gets down to the nitty
gritty, if we don't do something right defensively, he's going to
have a question about it,'' Campo said. ``And I like that. All we
care about is what's the best way to get it done and win. I've
always been that way, which is probably why I'm here through three
(head) coaches. I'm flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of questions for a Cowboys' defense that
finished first against the pass but 24th against the run in the NFL
last season. Gone are starting defensive ends Tony Tolbert and
Shante Carver, which isn't all bad. In are speedy but raw Kavika
Pittman and rookie first-round draft pick Greg Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to be more athletic than we've been in the
past,'' Campo says. ``That has to convert to being playmakers. Time
will tell as far as how much progress they make, but I'll take guys
that are hungry, and can run, and are athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   Six opposing running backs rushed for 100 or more yards in games
against the Cowboys last season, led by Green Bay's Dorsey Levens,
who littered the field with would-be tacklers en route to 190 yards
on 33 carries in late November. After that, teams pounded
mercilessly at the soft underbelly of the Cowboys' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to slow down the run better than we did last year,''
Campo said. ``It got out of hand at the end. If we can get the ball
to the perimeter, we're going to be OK because we've got some speed
that can run it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you get into trouble is with the teams that can just
pound you inside. So having Leon Lett back, the emergence of a
Darren Benson, the improvement of Antonio Anderson, a Michael
Myers, plus Chad Hennings being a steady, solid, NFL player, it's
got to come from those guys. We've got to be physical inside and
then go from there to the outside. And Fred Strickland's got to
have a good year at middle 'backer.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Campo's plate is brimming. There's no time to feel
sorry for himself, and if he won't, we won't either.
</P>
<P>
   Care to split a Prozac with me?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
