<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLE-KIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER AGENTS REUNITE HOUSTON MOTHER, CHILDREN AFTER BOTCHED
SMUGGLING ATTEMPT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Ordonez) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ISABEL, Texas _ A young Honduran immigrant Thursday ended
an anxious monthlong wait on smugglers who were to deliver her two
young children to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of meeting with smugglers, however, Esmeralda Ordonez
and her fiance wept as U.S. Border Patrol agents reunited her with
her 2-year-old son and 6-year-old daughter. The smugglers,
evidently spooked by an intensive search by federal agents, gave up
on attempts to extort more money from Ordonez and abandoned the boy
in a Brownsville apartment complex at 2 a.m. with a telephone
number pinned to the toddler's shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the boy nor his sister, who had been found Tuesday
night, was harmed. The children shyly answered reporters' questions
during their reunion with mom and appeared to be in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   But, the tearful couple said they had been held for more than a
month by members of a smuggling ring who had been paid $7,000 but
wanted $3,500 more to complete the trip from Honduras to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The original price was $5,000 and the trip was to take eight
days, Ordonez, 24, said at the U.S. Border Patrol station near Port
Isabel, a fishing community of 5,000 people about 25 miles
northeast of Brownsville near the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threatened if we didn't send the money, they were going
to do something to the little girl,'' said Luis Enrique Sandoval,
32, a Houston construction worker who has dated Ordonez, who is in
the country illegally, for nine months and plans to marry her when
his own divorce is final.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we started worrying,'' he continued, fighting back
tears. ``They were telling us if we didn't send them the money _
the $3,500 _ that we would never see the kids anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol officials who helped recover the young siblings
said it has become increasingly common for smugglers to transport
children without their parents, pairing them up with other clients
who claim to be relatives. Smugglers are aware that South Texas
immigration officials have limited facilities in which to detain
whole families, and often release illegal immigrants on bond after
giving them a court date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes in spurts,'' said supervisory agent Francisco Lopez
of the Border Patrol. ``Sometimes we'll have several unaccompanied
juveniles in, say, a week's time and then we won't see any more for
two or three weeks, and all of a sudden we'll run into another
handful of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for Ordonez's children ended when Juan Angel
Maradiaga, 2, was found wandering by himself outside a Brownsville
apartment complex around 2 a.m. after authorities received an
anonymous call about the toddler, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, agents found his older sister, Vanelisa
Maradiaga, 6, with a group of more than 20 illegal immigrants
staying in several rooms in a hotel in downtown Brownsville. A
woman in the group first claimed to be the girl's mother but later
admitted that smugglers told her to lie, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that day, the children's mother had asked Sandoval to
contact Houston police and FBI agents and alert them the smugglers
threatened to harm her children if the extra $3,500 was not sent to
Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, FBI spokesman Rolando Moss confirmed agents were
involved in running down leads and assisting Customs and Border
Patrol agents working the case in the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez said she works as a saleswoman at a ladies clothing shop
in a Houston mall and has been in the United States for 16 months
without immigration papers. She decided to have her two children,
who were living with her sister in the town of Olancho in Honduras,
brought to Houston because she feared her ex-husband in California
was planning to take custody of them.
</P>
<P>
   Her former brother-in-law recommended a smuggler from El
Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother-in-law told me (the smuggler) brings in little
children and there wouldn't be a single problem,'' Ordonez said.
``And also (the smuggler) called me and said, `Look lady, nothing
will happen to your children. You'll have them over there in eight
days' and this and that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez said she sent the smuggler $2,000 as a deposit and her
two children left Honduras on June 18 for what was to be an
eight-day trip to Houston. She got calls for more money from El
Salvador where, she said, her children were held for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents said no arrests have been made of those
responsible for smuggling the two children across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez and her two children were detained for immigration
processing but could be released and allowed to return to Houston
to stay with Sandoval, officials said. If the couple marries, they
added, Sandoval, who is a citizen, could apply for legal residency
for Ordonez and the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to lose them,'' Sandoval said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
