A0277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-23 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG SCANDAL WIDENS EVEN AS TOUR RIDERS GET A DAY OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARASCON SUR ARIEGE, France _ Even as the race rested for its
single day off, the drug scandal enveloping professional bicycle
racing and the Tour de France widened Thursday as three more
officials and nine riders of a French team were taken into judicial
custody and four officials of a Dutch team were being questioned by
police.
</P>
<P>
   The three officials of the Festina team based in France are two
assistant coaches, Miguel Moreno and Michel Gros, and the team's
manager, Joel Chabiron. Also held were the nine riders of the
sport's top-ranked team who started the Tour on July 11 in Dublin,
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   They include two former favorites in the world's major bicycle
race, Richard Virenque and Alex Zulle, and the road race champion,
Laurent Brochard.
</P>
<P>
   They all were ordered detained in Lyons pending a judge's
decision whether to place them under formal investigation. They
were not placed under formal arrest but were due to spend the night
in a police station.
</P>
<P>
   The riders were expelled from the race late Friday after their
coach said from jail that he had supplied them with such illegal
performance-enhancing drugs as the artificial hormone EPO. They
have denied any guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The team's jailed doctor has said that the riders contributed
$70,000 to a pool to buy the drugs, which they have denied.
</P>
<P>
   The Festina officials and riders in custody joined the team's
coach, its doctor and a veteran masseur, who have been arrested in
the last two weeks after an official team car was seized at the
French-Belgian border on July 8 and found to contain what has been
described as a huge quantity of illegal performance-enhancing
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case, a car bearing the insignia of the TVM team
from the Netherlands was seized by police in March near Rheims,
France, and said to be bearing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Although two mechanics were arrested and the artificial hormone
EPO was found, the case languished until Thursday morning. About 8
a.m., according to Guido van Calster, TVM's team manager and a
former Tour rider, ``the police arrived at our hotel while we were
at breakfast and took away'' the team's coach, Cees Priem, its
doctor, Andre Michalov, and an unidentified mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant coach, Hendrik Redant, was brought in for
questioning later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Redant and the unnamed mechanic were later released while Priem
and Michalov were still being held Thursday evening in the police
station in the village of Pamiers, where the TVM team was staying
at the Hotel de la Rocade.
</P>
<P>
   Tour officials had no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   After Bruno Roussel, the Festina coach, said in a statement
through his lawyer last Friday that he had conducted a concerted
program to supply drugs to his riders, Tour officials expelled the
nine-man team. It ranks first in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Those nine riders were called into court in Lyons on Thursday to
aid the investigation. It has been conducted by police officers
from Lille, the northern city where Roussel, Dr. Eric Ryckaert, the
Festina team doctor, and Willy Voet, a masseur, are scheduled to
appear Friday in court.
</P>
<P>
   TVM started the year in eighth position among the approximately
40 professional racing teams. Its annual budget, supplied by an
insurance company, is a bit below $4 million, or $2 million less
than Festina, which is sponsored by a watch manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Tour officials said Wednesday that they had no plans to expel
the seven TVM riders remaining of the nine that started the race.
The reason, the officials said, was that no formal charges had been
brought against anybody on the team and that no official had said
the team was involved with drugs, unlike the Festina case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Addressing a report Thursday morning in the newspaper Le
Parisien, a judge in Ghent, Belgium, Eric Van de Sijpe, said that
he could confirm that the Festina riders had used EPO. It
multiplies the red blood corpuscles that carry oxygen to muscles
and is mainly used in endurance sports.
</P>
<P>
   EPO has also been blamed anecdotally in nearly two dozen deaths
of amateur and professional riders this decade. Because EPO
thickens the blood and because riders have pulse rates half that of
most other people, the hormone is believed to cause heart attacks
while the riders sleep.
</P>
<P>
   No known tests exist to detect EPO, which is a drug for patients
on kidney dialysis. The International Cycling Union, which governs
the sport, has been testing riders' levels of red blood corpuscles
for the last two years, suspending for two weeks any riders found
to have a level above 50 percent of their blood. Seven riders have
been caught this season and about a dozen last year.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Sijpe conducted an inquiry in March into a pharmacist who
was found to have sold large quantities of EPO and among his
alleged buyers was Ryckaert of Festina. His computer records were
copied by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seized the riders' medical files and in them there are
indications that they took EPO,'' news agencies quoted the judge as
having said. ``It's there in writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Festina officials and riders have charged that they have
been made scapegoats for a practice that is widespread in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Qualified confirmation was made by Dr. Max Testa, the Asics team
doctor and former doctor for the 7-Eleven team and its successor,
Motorola, which left the sport in 1996. In an interview, he said,
``I'm not really in a good position to say since I was working 11
years with American teams and they're clean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, drug use is quite prevalent. I would say at least
20 to 30 percent of professional riders do it. Part of the reason
is the pressure of all the races, the difficulty of finding a job.
You always have to be good. EPO, even if it is not detectable, is a
strong risk for riders because there is a lot of data about how
dangerous it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general situation is probably that it is mainly used by
the weakest riders. They're the ones who feel they need an edge.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
