<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA24-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visa is Atlanta's choice
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Sorry American Express. Atlanta prefers Visa.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message that the Atlanta Convention and Visitors
Bureau will be sending out as part of its marketing program.
</P>
<P>
   Visa was able to get the ACVB to spread that message through an
agreement to extend and expand a marketing partnership that began
in 1993. The new three-year partnership is estimated to have a $3
million value in both cash and in-kind contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a bureau have just signed the biggest agreement we have
ever had as an organization,'' said Bill Howard, ACVB's vice
president of public relations and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Olympics, Visa and ACVB agreed to a $3 million
partnership extended over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest increase in the Visa partnership will be an annual
$300,000 cash contribution to ACVB's cultural tourism campaign,
which already has BellSouth and Coca-Cola as sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   It was the cultural tourism piece that placed Visa's Atlanta
partnership bid ahead of American Express.
</P>
<P>
   In order to be able to use the slogan ``Atlanta prefers Visa,''
the credit card company has to dominate the market. Rob Robins,
Visa's executive vice president for marketing development and
acceptance, did not give specifics on local market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is a very strong market for us,'' Robins said. ``We
have over 50 percent market share in the United States. What we
hope to do is expand our total volume in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   American Express has made strong inroads in the Atlanta market.
Through its Delta Skymiles credit card, consumers get frequent
flier points on the airline when they use American Express. Given
the concentration of Delta customers in Atlanta, the Skymiles card
is particularly popular here.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between the two credit card companies here is
intense.
</P>
<P>
   At a Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce lunch Wednesday with the
Arts &AMP; Business Council, the main speaker was Mary Beth Salerno,
president of the American Express Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon Richardson, president of the ACVB, said he did not
attend that lunch (despite ACVB's cultural tourism program) because
he was in meetings with Visa executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sign the kind of deal we signed with Visa, we do not
anticipate any other major credit card company to come and get
involved with us,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   More arts support
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's smaller arts and cultural groups need more financial
support, according to leaders of the Arts &AMP; Business Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council held its annual lunch Wednesday for the Metropolitan
Atlanta Arts Fund to announce the 1998 winners of its grants to
help financially strapped cultural organizations with budgets of
less than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The fund was able to give a total of $180,000 in five separate
grants _ the most it has been able to give in its six-year history.
The organization's initial $3 million endowment has grown to nearly
$4 million because of the rise in the stock market in the past few
years, allowing it to increase grants.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough, according to Lynda Courts, chair of the
Arts &AMP; Business Council for the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce.
The fund received requests totaling $1 million from cultural
organizations, according to its chairman Grant Wilmer, an attorney
with Arnall, Golden &AMP; Gregory.
</P>
<P>
   Courts said the Arts &AMP; Business Council, working with the
Atlanta chamber, will decide later this year on a campaign goal,
which she said could double or triple the size of the arts fund.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
