u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CLONER-PROFILE-2T     07-23 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CLONER-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLONING PIONEER IS FOCUSED AND CREATIVE IN HIS RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii, Mass., Japan)   (bl)  
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is nearly 70, an age when many have retired. He works on the
windowless second floor of a converted warehouse in Honolulu, shut
off from the island paradise. And he can hardly tear himself away.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ryuzo Yanagimachi, the University of Hawaii researcher whose
cloning of adult mice has amazed fellow biologists, describes
himself as a man devoted to one passion _ pushing the boundaries of
reproductive biology. He surrounds himself with acolytes, often
outstanding postdoctoral students from other countries, like Dr.
Teruhiko Wakayama of Japan, who designed the critical experiment
resulting in the first mouse clone. ``Many Americans are interested
in easy jobs,'' Yanagimachi explains.
</P>
<P>
   His followers adore the experience. ``We are working in an
intense research environment,'' said Dr. Anthony Perry, a
postdoctoral student from England. ``It is a wonderful atmosphere,
extremely conducive to pursuing your curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yanagimachi has little in his life to distract him from his
abiding love of science, and of doing the most improbable
experiments. His wife, Hiroko, was trained as a child psychologist
in Japan, but she could not find work in her field in the United
States because of the language barrier, Yanagimachi said. So he
taught her electron microscopy, and she joined him in his lab.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who have no children, live just two miles from the
lab, where long hours and seven-day work weeks are the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can leave at 10 at night on a Saturday night, and you'd be
the first to leave,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues said it was that singleminded devotion, coupled with
unusual creativity, that animated Yanagimachi's work. ``He's a bit
of a legend, actually,'' said Dr. R. Michael Roberts, an expert in
early bovine embryos at the University of Missouri. ``He does
outlandish experiments that nobody thinks will work and somehow
gets them to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The cloning work was typical. Yanagimachi and Wakayama took on
the challenge just after scientists in Scotland announced last year
that they had produced Dolly the sheep, the first animal to be
cloned from an adult. While some questioned whether Dolly was
really a clone _ she was the only animal produced out of 400 tries
_ others said that even if cloning could succeed, it would be very
cumbersome and inefficient.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many said, mice, for reasons peculiar to their
biology, would be impossible to clone. But Wakayama and Yanagimachi
quietly went ahead, devising a new cloning method that was found to
be reliable and comparatively efficient, and churning out more than
50 mouse clones.
</P>
<P>
   The method was built on Yanagimachi's work on fertilization. A
few years ago, he discovered that he could take a mouse sperm cell
and dissect away its tail. Then he could inject the sperm head into
an egg and fertilize it.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Wakayama arrived at the lab. He has the
equivalent in mouse embryology of a gardener's green thumbs, Perry
said. ``He is technically brilliant. He can do it all. He is one of
the few who is worthy of a place in Yana's lab,'' Perry added,
referring to Yanagimachi by his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Following up on the work with mouse sperm heads, Wakayama and
Yanagimachi wondered if they could inject just the sperm nucleus
and a support structure, the perinuclear matrix, and fertilize an
egg. They could.
</P>
<P>
   So the next question was whether they could inject a nucleus
from another type of cell _ an adult cell _ into a mouse egg that
had been emptied of its own DNA and make the egg develop as if it
had been fertilized. In other words, could they clone?
</P>
<P>
   Yanagimachi never applied for research funds to clone, but that
was no detriment. Supported by a modest grant from the National
Institutes of Health, Yanagimachi followed advice given him by a
mentor more than 30 years ago: take the grant money and spend three
days a week doing the research you said you would do. Then spend
the other two days doing ``anything you want,'' Yanagimachi
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The adult cell that the scientists started with was already
fully developed. It was a cumulus cell, a glistening spherical cell
that surrounds an egg and nourishes it. Like other specialized
adult cells, virtually all of its genes were turned off -- all it
knew how to do was be a cumulus cell. Yet, somehow, when that cell
was put into an egg, the egg rejuvenated the cumulus cell's DNA,
enabling it to direct the development of an entire mouse. Now,
Yanagimachi and Wakayama have made more than 50 clones, including
clones of clones.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the new work, published Thursday in Nature, helps open
the door for the eventual cloning of human beings. Yanagimachi
politely but firmly declined to discuss that aspect of his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the humans on the face of the earth were infertile,
this may be justified,'' Yanagimachi said. ``But until then, we
should stick to reproduction the way that Mother Nature did it for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yanagimachi is nothing if not determined. Born Aug. 29, 1928, he
knew what he wanted to do from his earliest years as a student of
zoology at Hokkaido University in Sapproro Japan: research in
fertilization and embryo biology. But after receiving a doctorate
in animal embryology in 1960, Yanagimachi found himself shut out of
science.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan in those days, you could not find a job yourself,''
he said. Professors determined who could become a researcher, and
where they could work, he explained. Although most of Yanagimachi's
friends got jobs as scientists, the only job he could get was as a
high school teacher. He stuck it out for two years, rushing to the
university labs in his spare time to study fish. But, he said,
``many in Japan study fish.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He decided he wanted to study mammals. So he wrote to an
American scientist, M.C. Chang of the Worcester Foundation for
Experimental Biology in Shrewsbury, Mass., asking him if he could
come as a postdoctoral student. ``He said, `send references.' So I
sent five or six fish papers,'' Yanagimachi said.
</P>
<P>
   To Yanagimachi's surprise, he got the position. And there
Yanagimachi made his first major discovery -- a way to fertilize
hamster eggs in the laboratory. That work directly paved the way
for human in vitro fertilization, said Dr. Barry Bavister, a
professor of animal health and biomedical science at the University
of Wisconsin. It provided the method that finally allowed scientist
to fertilize human eggs in the lab in 1969. ``It was certainly a
technological breakthrough, but it also was a conceptual one,''
Bavister said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, Yanagimachi's postdoctoral fellowship ended, and he
returned to Japan. This time, he got a temporary lectureship at
Hokkaido University and was told that he might be able to get an
assistant professorship there. However, he recalled, ``another
candidate appeared, and he got the job.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended up at the University of Hawaii, where he has remained,
happily working in the same converted warehouse where he began 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an amazing guy, a powerhouse, a dynamo,'' Bavister said.
``There is almost no discovery in gamete biology that cannot be
traced back to Yana's ideas,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, said Wakayama, Yanagimachi ``is the most famous
scientific star.'' Two years ago, Yanagimachi received Japan's
greatest scientific prize, the International Prize of Biology,
awarded by the emperor. ``This guy, who couldn't get a job in
Japan, ended up with the Japan's most prestigious honor,'' said Dr.
David Epel, a professor of biology at Stanford University's Hopkins
Marine Station in Pacific Grove, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``America saved me,'' Yanagimachi said.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagimachi's cloning work has attracted the interest of a
venture capitalist, Laith Reynolds of ProBio America, who is
setting up a consortium of companies and scientists to clone
animals. So now Yanagimachi has a chance to change direction and
devote his life to cloning and its commercial applications. He
thinks not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay in basic science,'' Yanagimachi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
