<HEADLINE>
SENATE OKS DELAY IN NEW VISA CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - WASHINGTON _ The Senate agreed Thursday to delay
for five years a new, fraud-resistant visa card that Arizonans fear
would stifle trade by making it too costly for Mexican shoppers to
cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure, if endorsed by the House, would halt ongoing
plans to replace current border-entry cards, which were issued
free, with new visas that include an individual's photograph,
fingerprint and biographical data.
</P>
<P>
   The new visas cost $45 per person _ too much for many Mexican
families to afford.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona border communities and Gov. Jane Hull believe the
state-of-the-art visas, which are designed to discourage
counterfeiting, would have the unintended effect of restraining
trade as well.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-million current border cards would have to be
replaced in the Nogales area alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no objections to revamping the (border entry) system,
but it's the charge that I object to,'' said Nogales, Ariz., Mayor
Cesar Rios. ``Our economy is very much dependent on trade with
people from Mexico. Nogales has no property tax, so we're very much
dependent on the sales tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Borane, mayor of Douglas, Ariz., said delaying the program
until 2003 would allow opponents time to try to kill the $45 card
altogether. He said his city relies on Mexican shoppers for 40
percent of retail revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people have enough time to realize the impact this will
have, then hopefully something will happen in the interim and more
adjustments can be made,'' Borane said. ``It gives us an
opportunity to be a little more vocal.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-year delay was pushed by Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz. He
successfully inserted the measure into an appropriations bill that
cleared the Senate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl's measure would waive the $45 fee for children under 15 who
apply with a visa-holding parent. That is a significant exemption
because Mexicans of the same family often cross the border
together.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has already begun the transition to the new
cards. Under Kyl's plan, the department would be required to
continue processing existing border-crossing documents in a number
of Mexican cities, including the Sonora state cities of Nogales and
Agua Prieta, until the transition to the new visas is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., is pursuing a measure similar to Kyl's
in the House, which has not taken final action.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1978, the Immigration and Naturalization Service issued
border crossing cards with no expiration date. As a result, many
Mexicans are using badly outdated cards, putting INS officials at a
disadvantage when deciding whether to admit a card carrier into the
United States. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
