<HEADLINE>
FAA PROPOSES MORE INSPECTIONS OF 747 FUEL TANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Federal Aviation Administration Thursday proposed
measures that it said could reduce potential ignition sources in
the center fuel tanks of Boeing 747s.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed airworthiness directive is another in a series of
safety actions involving the jumbo jet's fuel system that have been
made in response to the crash of TWA Flight 800 two years ago. The
center fuel tank of the jumbo jet exploded for reasons still
undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, The Boeing Co. recommended in several service
bulletins to airlines that they take similar steps to those now
being proposed by the FAA. If adopted after a 45-day public comment
period, the federal agency's proposed airworthiness would make
action mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   It would would require the inspection of center fuel tanks for
damage and to make sure components such as the fuel monitoring
system inside the tanks are properly wired and that the wiring is
not worn or corroded.
</P>
<P>
   In certain 747s, operators would have to install so-called
``flame arrestors'' in the inlet lines of the center fuel tank
scavenge pump, which removes leftover fuel from the tank when it is
nearly empty. The flame arrestor would help prevent an outside
spark or flame from igniting fuel vapors in the tank.
</P>
<P>
   To further reduce wire corrison and lessen the danger that a
spark could be an ignition source inside the tank, silver-plated
wiring in the fuel quantity indicator system would have to be
replaced with nickel-plated wiring on some planes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed directive, replacement of the fuel quantity
indicator system components and wiring would have to be done over
the next two years, or within 20 years from the date the plane was
built, whichever is later.
</P>
<P>
   All other actions proposed by the FAA Thursday would have to be
done within 24 months. Operators would have to report the results
to Boeing within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Some 251 U.S.-registered 747s would require one or more of the
actions described in its proposed airworthiness directive, the FAA
said. Costs for the work, the agency said, would vary from $28,000
to $63,000. Those costs are usually borne by the airplane owner.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said this was the sixth fuel tank action it had either
taken or proposed for Boeing 747, 737 and 767 aircraft since the
TWA crash.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 800 crashed into the Atlantic Ocean just minutes out of
New York's John F. Kennedy airport on July 17, 1996, killing all
230 people on board.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for the National Transportation Safety Board have
been trying for months to identify the electrical ignition source
that caused the center fuel tank to blow up.
</P>
<P>
   While examining the fuel system wiring in the wreckage, as well
as three retired Boeing 747s and one still in service,
investigators found damaged wires on some early-model fuel probes.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have been focusing on a theory that a combination
of events involving damaged wires and corrosion on a fuel-measuring
rod could have introduced a spark or flame into the center fuel
tank. The center fuel tank was virtually empty and the vapors in it
heated up as the plane sat on the runway on a hot day waiting to
take off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NABISCO-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-23 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RJR NABISCO REPORTS BIG 2ND-QUARTER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. reported a $130 million
second-quarter loss Thursday from the effects of the strong dollar
on overseas cigarette sales, weakness in the company's food
business and tobacco-litigation settlement costs.
</P>
<P>
   The results amounted to a loss of 44 cents a diluted share,
compared with earnings of $243 million, or 71 cents a diluted share
in the second quarter of 1997. Revenue was marginally higher at
$4.292 billion, compared with $4.286 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had been warned by the company over the last few weeks
about weaker results, but were nonetheless dismayed by the picture
the report painted of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the one-time effects of a $219 million charge to
reflect revamping of the cookie-cracker business, and a $97 million
tobacco settlement charge, earnings totaled $186 million, or 54
cents a share, down 24 percent from a year earlier. The average
forecast was for 55 cents, according to First Call Corp., which
tracks earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is ongoing weakness in the premium
brands,'' said Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst for Salomon
Brothers, explaining what happened to international cigarette
sales. ``In Russia, volumes fell 70 percent, and in Japan, they
fell 20 percent. Globally it's hard to know the exact number, but
perhaps by 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman partly attributed the decreases to the strong dollar,
which makes sales abroad smaller when converted back to dollars
from the local currency. But he also noted that RJR's brands, like
Camel and Winston, are up against fierce competition, including
Marlboro cigarettes, a brand owned by Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there's some major depreciation in the value of the
dollar, I don't see any recovery this year in the international
tobacco business,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic net sales of cigarettes rose 15 percent in the quarter
despite a volume decline of 3 percent. The decline has been
generally the same across the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic sales increase reflected increased prices and sales
for the Winston and Doral brands. The development was applauded by
RJR's chief executive, Steven F. Goldstone, in a company statement.
``We are pleased with the performance of domestic tobacco company,
whose operating results were in line with expectations and industry
trends,'' he said. ``Reynolds continues to make meaningful progress
revitalizing its core brands with imaginative, intelligent
marketplace programs and a continued focus on cost management. We
continue to beleive the company will be best served by a more
predictable political and legal environment and we are committed to
doing our part to bring about such a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from tobacco, the company revealed more grim results in
its biscuit division, which includes venerable brands like Ritz
crackers, Wheat Thins and Oreo cookies. That division announced
results on Wednesday, and the numbers showed net income fell 29
percent for the quarter, from $102 million in 1997 to $72 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were down from $907 million last year to $864 million this
year in the biscuit division, and down in the international and
domestic food divisions overall from $2.191 billion to $2.131
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have ever thought you'd see the biscuit earnings
down 30 percent?'' said Emanuel Goldman, an analyst with Paine
Webber in San Francisco. ``Even A-1 steak sauce and some other
things were off 2.5 percent. That's something they're not happy
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman and other analysts blamed earlier management decisions
for the situation. Nabisco's chief executive, James Kilts, joined
the company late last year and has begun an ambitious program to
improve the sales force, revitalize lagging brands and rid Nabisco
of certain nonessential assets.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the company announced the sale of its
margarine and spread business to ConAgra; Kilts, while at Philip
Morris' Kraft division, had sold the same business to Nabisco. But
even the sale will cost the company several cents in earnings,
according to company management, since the price was not high
enough to be recorded as a net gain.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the biscuit nonperformers, the company said, was the
Snackwell's brand, as well as breakfast snacks. The company also
said higher costs related to selling depressed earnings in the
biscuit unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
