<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-GOVERNOR-COX     07-23 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-GOVERNOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Massey throws towel; Democrat in runoff gives nod to Barnes
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The race for the Democratic nomination for governor
ended Thursday much as it began almost a year ago: with a bombshell
announcement that a candidate was bowing out.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Lewis Massey suspended his campaign and
endorsed state Rep. Roy Barnes (D-Mableton) as the party's nominee,
avoiding a potentially bloody runoff that Massey probably could not
have won.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes fell only 8,671 votes short of winning a majority in
Tuesday's primary, finishing with more than 49 percent of the vote.
Massey polled about 28 percent, and although he forced Barnes into
a runoff, the runner-up faced a steep uphill climb against a
better-financed opponent.
</P>
<P>
   As late as Wednesday afternoon, Massey was vowing to wage an
aggressive runoff. But after talking to his supporters, his wife,
Amy, and his parents, Massey decided that such a scenario would
help nobody except Guy Millner, the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil Williams, Massey's campaign chairman and chief
fund-raiser, said he had ``laid out the landscape'' for the
candidate and told Massey his supporters would not be disappointed
if he didn't want to stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday night, Massey was telling people in his
campaign he had decided to pull out. Early Thursday morning, he
called Barnes and Gov. Zell Miller to inform them of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a quitter, and I wanted to fight,'' Massey said at a
news conference in Miller's office, where he was joined by the
governor, Barnes and other party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after a day on the campaign trail, I knew that to continue
to fight would not be in the best interest of the Massey family or
the state of Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   While Massey will no longer actively campaign, his name will
still appear on the Aug. 11 runoff ballot. An official withdrawal
from the race would have thrown the third-place finisher, David
Poythress, into a runoff with Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and Massey both entered the governor's race last August
after Lt. Gov. Pierre Howard said he would not run because of
family considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, who is Massey's political mentor, had been widely
considered the favorite for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Howard and Miller both said Massey had not sought their advice
before making his decision, but both praised him for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Lewis Massey does here today shows great judgment and
great character, putting his political ambition aside for the
people of this state,'' said Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Massey's decision to step aside allows Barnes to conserve
campaign funds he will need in the general election battle against
Millner, who already has pumped about $3 million of his personal
wealth into his own campaign this year. Barnes probably would have
spent more than $1 million in a runoff marked by combative campaign
ads; now, he will probably spend about $500,000 on positive ads.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also is spared the attacks on his record that a runoff
opponent presumably would have leveled _ assuming that Massey could
have raised TV ad money for his struggling campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, the Democratic Party will not be split
by a bitter feud just three months before the general election.
Republicans, on the other hand, face the prospect of a recount of
primary votes, which former attorney general Mike Bowers requested
Thursday in a last-ditch effort to prevent Millner from claiming
the GOP nomination outright.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said the lack of a contested runoff will be ``very
helpful'' to his prospects in the general election. ``This is one
of my better days,'' he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican Party Chairman Rusty Paul admitted that a
Democratic runoff battle ``would have been good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Millner hinted that since Barnes has effectively clinched the
Democratic nomination, Millner might soon begin his own attack on
the veteran state lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a longer general election gives us more of an
opportunity to let voters know his record,'' Millner said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Massey gains several things by getting out of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   First, he no longer must try to raise money for a campaign that
ran a distant second in the primary, or face the option of spending
his own money on a lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   He also will not have to see himself savaged in negative ads,
which the Barnes camp was prepared to start running as early as
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if Barnes had emerged from a runoff only to lose in
November, many Democrats might have blamed Massey. As it is, Massey
can gain the good will of Barnes supporters around the state, many
of whom are wealthy and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether Massey chooses to run for office again or goes
into private business when his term as secretary of state expires
next year, he will be better off without all the political enemies
he might have made.
</P>
<P>
   Massey pledged to campaign for Barnes in the fall, and said his
support was unconditional. Barnes also said no deal had been struck
between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Massey said he had made only one promise in the last two days,
and it had nothing to do with politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised my little boy and girl I'd take them to the pool
tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
