<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PATIENT-RIGHT     07-23 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PATIENT-RIGHTS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE SAYS VETO OF HOUSE `PATIENT PROTECTION' BILL IS
LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House said Thursday night that President
Clinton would probably veto the version of ``patient protection''
legislation that Republican leaders plan to take up in the House of
Representatives on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton described himself as a champion of patients' rights. But
in a formal evaluation of the House Republican bill, the White
House said, ``It covers too few people, it provides too few patient
protections, and it contains unnecessary and irrelevant provisions
that undermine the chances for a bipartisan agreement on a
patients' bill of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said it ``strongly opposes'' the House
Republican bill as now drafted. Accordingly, it said, ``the
president's senior advisers would recommend that he veto this
bill'' if Congress sent him the measure in its current form.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clinton said he wanted to work with Republicans to
establish strong, enforceable protections for patients this year.
</P>
<P>
   While the leadership bill is likely to pass in the House,
compromises would probably be needed in the Senate before any bill
could get enough support to overcome a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to define patients' rights and set standards for
health maintenance organizations has emerged as a big issue in many
elections this year. After initially resisting the clamor for
legislation, Republican leaders recently offered their own
proposals as an alternative to the Democratic bill.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich is the chief sponsor of the bill scheduled
for House debate on Friday. He introduced the bill on July 16 and
is taking it directly to the floor, bypassing committees.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leaders plan to take up their version of the
legislation later this month. Administration officials and consumer
advocates say it is weaker than the House Republican bill and
covers many fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic proposals are superficially
similar. They would guarantee coverage of emergency medical care in
certain circumstances, assure open communication between doctors
and patients and allow women in HMOs to go directly to
obstetricians and gynecologists without getting prior approval. But
a close reading of the bills shows that they differ in ways that
could have significant practical effects for patients.
</P>
<P>
   In its formal statement of administration policy, the White
House said that Gingrich's bill ``does not apply to the individual
insurance market, and therefore millions of Americans would not be
assured these patient protections.''
</P>
<P>
   Most provisions of the House Republican bill would apply to all
employer-sponsored health plans, covering perhaps 145 million
people. By contrast, the main provisions of the Senate Republican
bill would apply to 48 million people in self-insured group plans
that are now exempt from state regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that the House Republican bill did not
guarantee access to medical specialists for people with cancer,
heart disease and other serious or chronic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it said, the bill does not prevent HMOs from giving
doctors financial incentives to limit care, and it does not
guarantee ``continuity of care'' for patients whose doctors are
dropped from an HMO.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the White House said, the House Republican bill
would provide ``little or no recourse to patients who are injured''
because of a health plan's actions. The proposed fines of $250 a
day are ``wholly insufficient,'' it said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   House Republicans would allow patients to appeal certain
decisions by HMOs to an independent panel of medical experts. But
the administration said HMOs could develop their own definitions of
``medical necessity,'' so it would be difficult for patients to
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The White House criticized three provisions of the House
Republican bill as ``poison pills.'' One would limit damage awards
for pain and suffering in lawsuits by patients injured as a result
of medical malpractice. Another would allow much wider use of
medical savings accounts. The third would allow small businesses to
band together and buy insurance exempt from most forms of state
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The administration said the proposed tax break for medical
savings accounts would benefit ``the healthiest and wealthiest
individuals'' and might remove them from the general insurance
market, so premiums would rise for other people.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, it said, the proposal to create purchasing pools for
small businesses would let them ``discriminate by cherry-picking
healthier groups and individuals.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
