<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURILLO HASN'T LOST TOUCH WITH L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM SPRINGS, Calif. _ It's a month before his 73rd birthday _
``you could've got odds of 1,000 to 1 on that happening,'' he
admits _ so of course Bud Furillo has considered retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to hang it up last May,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And this city would be about as good a place to do it as any.
</P>
<P>
   But then Furillo wakes up at his home in nearby Palm Desert,
reads the sports sections in his den with his dog, Rip, and the
enthusiasm that propelled him through more than a half-century of a
career in sports journalism starts all over again.
</P>
<P>
   He simply can't wait to drive over to the radio studios of KPSI,
920 on the AM dial, and start prepping for his weekday, 4 to 6 p.m.
sports-talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the highlight of my day,'' said Furillo, who's been doing
his show in Palm Springs for four years, with the last 5{ months at
KPSI.
</P>
<P>
   He then qualifies his statement: ``It's the best thing I do all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   From Furillo, you won't get any smack talk, no blathering on
about what's wrong with sports today from the mouth of someone
who's been there and done that. Just as he did in his 10 years as
the ``SportsTalk'' host of KABC's popular show in the '70s and
'80s, Furillo keeps his ``Steam Room'' show more on the lighter
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much negativity in today's media anyway,'' said
Furillo, who started as a sportswriter in 1945 and considers
himself to this day as a newspaper man. ``Nothing positive comes
from negative thinking. And people still like to read nice things
about people.''
</P>
<P>
   With 39-year-old producer/co-host Steve Kelly to bounce off of,
Furillo pulls it off. But it doesn't mean Furillo ignores current
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   On his shows this past week, in fact, the Dodgers have been a
topic almost as hot as the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Furillo interviewed former Dodgers general manager Fred
Claire, who said he was asked about firing then-manager Bill
Russell by team president Bob Graziano right after the blockbuster
deal with the Florida Marlins. Claire said he thought it was better
to let things settle down and then talk about it around the
All-Star break. Soon enough, Russell and Claire were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Claire also admitted he didn't consider a trade for Cincinnati
reliever Jeff Shaw specifically because of his multi-year contract
that allows him to demand a trade. Claire said that's what happened
several years ago when he obtained Jesse Orosco from the New York
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, current GM-in-training Tom Lasorda came on, and Furillo
asked him about his relationship with Russell. Lasorda admitted
he's upset because Russell never thanked him for recommending him
for the manager's job when Lasorda stepped down in the middle of
the '96 season.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Graziano was Furillo's guest. Graziano admitted that
the team had seriously considered firing Russell last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hear any of that kind of stuff on L.A. sports talk shows?
</P>
<P>
   Even in Palm Springs, L.A. sports are the talk of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is full of former L.A. residents who want to keep up
on what's going on,'' said Furillo, who, when let go from KABC in
'87 because of ratings, went to work in Sacramento, where he'd be
closer to his ailing mother.
</P>
<P>
   Although Furillo returns to L.A. occasionally _ he'll be in
Anaheim next week to see the Yankees, and has plans to attend USC's
football opener against Purdue in August _ his health prevents him
from making more visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me _ nobody loved L.A. more than I did when I was
there,'' said the legendary bombastic sports editor of the former
Los Angeles Herald Examiner from 1967 to '78.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think it's a tragedy that no one seems to care about the
history of L.A. sports anymore. I find it offensive that no one
seems to have a sense of that city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no `now' without a `then,' and nobody knows that
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Furillo has a voice _ even if it's in Palm
Springs, where on a good night the signal from the 5,000-watt
station gets all the way down to Rialto _ he'll make sure no one
forgets.
</P>
<P>
   BLAH, BLAH, BLAH...
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks before the first ``Monday Night Football'' game, ESPN
starts ``Monday Night Countdown'' this Monday (4:30 p.m.) and
ESPN2's ``NFL 2Night'' starts the next day (4:30 p.m.), featuring
!bold!Sean Salisbury!off! as one of the studio analysts.... ESPN's
first NFL game coverage is Saturday, Aug. 1, with a Green
Bay-Kansas City exhibition....
</P>
<P>
   Summer Sanders replaces Willow Bay as Ahmad Rashad's co-host on
``NBA Inside Stuff,'' starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   _Diane K. Shah's!off! almost-all-access piece on the Tom
Lasorda-run Dodgers in the current issue of ESPN The Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _``Baseball is back,'' declares the cover story of Time
magazine's July 27 issue, with cartoons of Ken Griffey Jr. and Mark
McGwire. Just in time for that subscriber push at sister
publication Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   _CBS announces its new NFL broadcast pairings for the fall. They
are... you know, why not have them just fax the press release to
you like they do to every other panting sports media writer, OK?
Our calendar says it's still July. Call us in September.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   _The downside of televising live press conferences past the
opening remarks. Take Wednesday's ESPNEWS break-in coverage of
Carmen Policy's resignation as the 49ers president (which, on
ESPN2, interrupted a very important taped AMA motocross race). With
viewers unable to hear the questions coming off camera, our TV
shows us Policy and his former boss sitting at a table with a glass
of water and blank looks on their faces. Then they utter things
like: ``No.'' Or: ``That wasn't part of our thinking.'' And:
``You'd have to ask him about that.'' And then: ``To answer the
first part, maybe, but I can't get into that right now.''
Compelling TV? You know the answer to that one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES     07-23 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 ADVERTISING: AT&AMP;T AD FILMED IN VIETNAM WAS A LONG TIME COMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A television commercial begins with a man in his 20s
riding in a boat on a river. He disembarks, asks directions,
reaches the top of a mountain and pensively looks around. ``My dad
was here,'' he says. ``He never talked about it much. He said we
had to be there. Here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The man is subsequently seen on a telephone, using a card to
call his father. ``Ty, you still in Singapore?'' the father asks.
The man replies: ``No, I'm on leave. I'm in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a long pause. ``Vietnam?'' the father asks. The son
answers, ``Yeah.'' The father quietly says, ``Let's talk, son,'' to
which the son, choking up, responds, ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   That commercial, which began appearing just before Father's Day,
seems innocuous enough; after all, there is no combat footage or
archival film of antiwar protests. Yet viewers did not see the spot
until more than a year after it was filmed on location in Vietnam
by Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising in New York, as part of a continuing
image campaign for the AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Why was the spot shelved for so long? AT&AMP;T advertising and
marketing executives feared that it would evoke some of the
contentious, polarized feelings generated by the very war the
commercial is about. Only after an unusual lobbying effort by the
top-name talents who helped create the commercial _ which included
screening the spot for Vietnam veterans _ did the AT&AMP;T executives
relent.
</P>
<P>
   Those joining forces to fight for the commercial had been on
opposite sides during the Vietnam War. One was David Crosby, who
sings ``Long Time Gone'' in the background. Another was Edward H.
Vick, the chairman and chief executive of Y&AMP;R Advertising. He was
on hand to watch the spot being filmed in the Mekong Delta region
of Vietnam, where he won medals for his wartime service as a naval
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Also battling to save the spot was its director, Joe Pytka, who
has worked for advertisers like Nike and Pepsi-Cola in addition to
AT&AMP;T. He described his feelings about Vietnam as ``strong and
mixed'' _ encapsulating the views of many Americans who had been in
the muddled middle over the war.
</P>
<P>
   The war over a commercial about a war is indicative of a problem
facing mainstream marketers as they seek new and novel ways to
capture the attention of increasingly fickle consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Emotional advertising intended to stir feelings is often
inherently more appealing than advertising focused on product
benefits and features. But there can be danger lurking in such
campaigns: Ads that stir buzz, causing people to pay attention, can
also stir controversy, causing people to make complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a spot like that, you worry,'' said Stephen D. Graham,
vice president for worldwide marketing communication at AT&AMP;T in
Basking Ridge, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to create advertising that is highly relevant,'' he
added, ``demonstrating the importance of communication and its
importance to people who are important to each other. But you want
to make sure you're treating the subject in a respectful way, and
there's always risk involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick said that he understood his client's concerns about the
commercial, which also went through routine consumer research and
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T was being really sensitive to whether this would alienate
anyone,'' Vick said, adding that executives were worried ``that all
the Vietnam veterans would cancel their cards and all the antiwar
people would cancel their cards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a question of whether Vietnam is still too sensitive a
subject,'' Vick said. ``Our feeling was the fact that it is still a
sensitive subject set it up to be a powerful piece of
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, who had been an antiwar activist during the Vietnam era,
agreed with Vick about the commercial's visceral appeal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was inspired and I liked it tremendously,''
Crosby said. So when he heard about the decision to shelve the
spot, he added, ``I wrote AT&AMP;T a long letter saying, `I understand
you're nervous, but it's the best thing you could associate
yourselves with and you should have the courage to do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The commercial isn't really about the war for me,'' Crosby
said, ``it's about bridging father and son, two generations, two
countries, the two sides in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commercial is about communication,'' he added, ``and most
of the ills of humanity, like war, result from a breakdown in
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial is the first ``I've actually let my music be used
for,'' said Crosby, who wrote ``Long Time Gone'' and re-created the
original version for the commercial. The song heard in the spot is
sung by Crosby and Graham Nash; the original was sung by Crosby,
Nash and Stephen Stills.
</P>
<P>
   Pytka called Crosby's letter ``touching'' and said he welcomed
it because ``I'd given up on the commercial; I never thought it
would see the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial is less about the war, Pytka said, than about
``this incredibly strong father with his secrets and this son, who
are probably now going to connect as adults, as men, for the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the attempts to rescue the commercial, Vick enlisted
the help of the Vietnam Veterans of America in Washington, which
screened the spot last year for members of its executive committee,
board and staff. In a letter to Vick, George Duggins, national
president of the organization, wrote that they found the spot
``memorable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most likely, folks' thoughts would be somewhat private,''
Duggins wrote, ``but they will most likely remember the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   After the commercial finally began appearing last month, it
returned for the Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction so far? ``We had a lot of positive responses,''
Graham of AT&AMP;T said, adding that plans called for the spot to come
back for appropriate occasions like Veterans Day and Memorial Day.
It may also be shown during so-called event programming that AT&AMP;T
sponsors such as broadcasts of the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   There were concerns expressed by some consumers that the
commercial would be perceived not as prowar or antiwar but as
exploiting war to sell long-distance service or burnish a corporate
image. That happened last year in Canada, when Bell Canada ran a
commercial by the Leo Burnett Co. Ltd. agency in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The spot showed a grandson placing a thank-you call to his
grandfather from Dieppe, scene of an ill-fated raid during World
War II; it drew widespread praise but also some complaints about
commercialization.
</P>
<P>
   Of his agency's AT&AMP;T spot, Vick said: ``The subject was used in
an appropriate way. It would be different if it were guys going
back to drink Budweiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham of AT&AMP;T echoed Vick, saying that the commercial was
``very respectful and reverent to the relationship between the
father and son and to the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of respect for those who fought for this
spot,'' he added. ``I was the person who was the most cautious
about this to make sure it was absolutely right. And I think we
accomplished that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
