<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JERICHO-CASINO _ JERICHO, West Bank _ This is the oldest and
lowest city in the world. But, is it lucky? In the dusty expanse of
desert across the street from one of the oldest Palestinian refugee
camps, hundreds of workers are building a casino hotel aimed
largely at tempting Israelis to come gamble _ something they cannot
do next door in Israel. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Thursday, July 24.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COSSACKS _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The feared Cossacks
ride again? Russia's tradition-steeped warrior caste is undergoing
a revival of sorts, after being submerged for decades by the Soviet
Union. St. Petersburg officials plan to use the Cossacks to patrol
city parks and assist regular police in fighting crime -- sort of
the Guardian Angels, Russo-style. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Thursday, July 24, in both the (i) International and
(l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-US _ TEHRAN, Iran _ To look at this 18-year-old, it's easy
to imagine good relations between the United States. Farhat Malek's
hair is moussed, he smokes a cigarette and you can see the Michael
Jordan jersey peeking out from under the large Iranian flag draped
over his shoulders. He is hopeful, but realistic. ``Iran and the
United States have had a little war these last 20 years,'' he says.
Iranians are warm to Americans, but wary of any closer ties to
their government. They closely watch the recent calls by Iranian
and U.S. officials for a new relationship. But, after 20 years of
``little war,'' repairing the relations between the two countries
will require untangling a knot of symbollic and political
disagreements. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With IRAN-TOURISM _ TEHRAN, Iran _ It's not the first place you
think of when considering a travel destination, but more and more
American tourists are heading to Iran. The reason, Iranians want
them there. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by noon Thursday, July 23.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   EUROPA _ WASHINGTON _ Much of scientists' concerns about the
possibility of extraterrestrial microbes infecting Earth in samples
collected by space missions involve two moons of Jupiter, Europa
and Ganymede, where conditions are believed best to support life.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving Wednesday for release Saturday, July 25.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-BLACK _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., is stuck
between a rock and a hard place regarding upcoming tobacco
legislation. Clayton, always sensitive to minority issues, is
concerned about recent reports of a drastic increase in teen
smoking among blacks and reports that smoking is more dangerous for
blacks. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-DATA _ Key figures from recent reports regarding
minorities and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Moving Thursday for release Sunday, July 26.
</P>
<P>
   COAST-GUARD _ WASHINGTON _ Doing more with less has become a
mantra at the 208-year-old Coast Guard, and next year's budget may
bring little relief. President Clinton requested about $4 billion
this year for the agency, which is burdened with aging equipment
and a work force that has shrunk nearly 10 percent since 1992.
(Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Monday as a 1stlede for release Sunday, July 26.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GYMNASTS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton greets members
of the undefeated national championship University of Georgia
women's gymnastics team. (Abulhassan, Cox News Service). (For
Atlanta)
</P>
<P>
   Moving spot Friday in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   PBP-FIRES-TIMBER _ BUNNELL, Fla. _ With nearly a half million
acres charred in the Memorial Day fires, foresters and timber men
are scrambling to harvest burned wood before it rots. Wood can
usually be salvaged within 45 days. After that, fungus will ruin
it. Next week the state will start harvesting forests in Flalger
County and we'll go along with some of the crews. With so much wood
to chop, it's bound to be a pretty massive undertaking. Mills are
trying to set up additional irrigation systems in their yards
because watered wood will keep twice as long. The Department of
Agriculture is also trying to get weight limits on highways
temporarily lifted so truckers can haul more wood to out-of-state
mills. State says part of the problem is local mills got backed up
because of wood harvested early with the drought. (Staletovich,
Palm Beach Post). 40.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Also with box on timber industry)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   PBP-HMO-MAIN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Since the 1980s, HMOs
have made steady inroads in the health insurance market in South
Florida, spurred by cost-conscious employers, consumers and
governments. HMOs now hold 40 percent of the market in Palm Beach
County, an estimated 20 percent on the Treasure Coast. We look at
how HMOs have gotten to where they are today and explain why HMO
growth is expected to continue _ despite doctor discontent and
patient complaints. (Galewitz, Palm Beach Post). 50.
</P>
<P>
   WITH SIDEBARS:
</P>
<P>
   PBP-HMO-DOC _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ After a decade as a public
health administrator, Dr. Rod Cardiff was looking forward to
returning to private practice. He found an office on a busy Port
St. Lucie street in 1996, hired a staff, and started building a
family practice. Six months later, he contracted to serve patients
with Humana Inc., the first to offer a Medicare HMO on the Treasure
Coast. Within months, Cardiff's practice had jumped from 170 to 700
patients. Working with a giant HMO saved Cardiff, 50, from
advertising, and he enjoyed treating the mostly elderly population.
But on Jan. 28, Cardiff got a letter saying that all of Humana's
members were being reassigned and that his contract would end in 30
days. Humana spokeswoman Pam Gadensky said Cardiff was terminated
because his practice was not growing fast enough. But Humana told
Cardiff that he was spending too much sending patients to hospitals
and specialists. Without enough patients, Cardiff closed his
practice. He's now looking for another job. ``Medicine has changed
a lot,'' Cardiff said. ``The power HMOs have over doctors is even
greater than I thought.'' Though most Florida physicians work in
HMO networks, Cardiff's experience shows why growing numbers of
doctors are voicing discontent with the health plans. (Galewitz,
Palm Beach Post). 25
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PBP-HMO-COMPLAINTS _ Boca Raton, Fla. _ Helpless, Ron Finger
waited for months as his 16-year-old shrunk to 90 pounds. He was
waiting for his insurance company to approve a psychiatrist for
Tamara as she battled anorexia. But all HIP Health Plan could come
up with were psychiatrists specializing in the elderly. So Finger
violated the biggest rule in managed care: He found his own doctors
and placed Tamara at the Renfrew Center, an inpatient mental
facility with physicians trained to help teens overcome eating
disorders. Now the Boca resident is battling HIP over the $72,000
bill for the 90 days of treatment at the center. The HMO says it
doesn't have to pay because it never authorized the treatment. But
all Finger said he could think about was saving his child. ``At the
end of the day, we had to protect our daughter,'' he says. The
Fingers are not alone in trying to get managed care companies to
pay for unauthorized doctor or hospital visits. Florida's Agency
for Health Care Administration gets about 5,000 complaints a week.
(Warejcka, Palm Beach Post). 16.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PBP-HMO-FAMILY _ WELLINGTON, Fla. _ Feature on a family that's
having a nightmare with its HMO. The dad has multiple sclerosis.
The mom has breast cancer that's spread through her body. She wants
to go to the world reknown Sloan-Kettering in New York for cancer
treatment, but that's not what her HMO allows. (Warejcka, Palm
Beach Post). (Developing).
</P>
<P>
   PBP-CARE-MANAGER _ You live hundreds of miles away from Mom. You
worry: Is Mom taking her medication properly? Is she bathing
regularly? Does she ever get out of the house? Peggy Hammond will
check on her for you. Hammond, 62, is one new breed of
professionals called ``geriatric care managers'' that have cropped
up to meet the needs of an aging population. But the profession is
unregulated. Anyone can call themselves a care manager, no license
required. (Fuchs, Palm Beach Post). 30-35.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: With box of what to watch out for when hiring a care
manager plus a list of resources.)
</P>
