<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-REACT-COX     07-23 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-REACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `You know that child could have easily been yours'
 &HT;    By Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Tears seemed to fall softly across Georgia Thursday
as news spread of the death of a 2-year-old with E. coli, but they
spilled hard from the parents of other children who were infected
and survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so awful, so horrible,'' said Lisbeth Addison,
mother of Matthew Addison, 3, who was released July 5 from Kosair
Children's Hospital in Louisville, then readmitted and released a
second time July 11. ``That's the first thing I thought about this
morning when I woke up, was what they were waking up to. And, you
know, that child could have easily been yours.''
</P>
<P>
   When Addison and other parents heard that McCall Akin died
Wednesday at Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center, the news
provided at once a terrible reminder of their ordeal and a pang of
guilt that another's child wasn't quite as fortunate as their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It devastated us,'' said Anne Hilbert of Cherokee County,
whose son, Michael, was hospitalized at Egleston Children's
Hospital for two weeks in mid-June. ``We hated it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall's parents, Andy and Marisa, released a statement
Thursday. ``We would like to express our deepest gratitude to all
the people who prayed for our daughter, McCall, during her
illness.'' They asked that any donations be sent to Scottish Rite.
</P>
<P>
   While the Hilberts, Addisons and several other families have
been spared the loss of a child, they know some of what the Akins
family endured. They spent similar sleepness nights in a hospital
room next to a child moaning and trying to rip out IV tubes, a
child undergoing blood transfusions, dialysis and related problems
like liver disease. They know the trauma of E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for parents to be aware that this is a
serious pathogen,'' said Randy Addison, a pilot for United Parcel
Service. ``It's a pathogen with a bad attitude. It was a horrific
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the bacteria can cause long-term damage, the experience
might not be over for the children who had serious infections, like
Matthew and Michael who were on dialysis for several days. Some
children infected after eating contaminated hamburger during the
Jack in the Box outbreak in 1993 have needed kidney transplants.
Several became diabetic,and many have learning disabilities caused
by loss of oxygen to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the scary part,'' Randy Addison said. ``There's always
the potential for kidney failure, we'll have to have his blood
pressure checked, and he has a greater chance of developing
diabetes and gall stones.''
</P>
<P>
   For a parent of a stricken child, the parallels _ and the irony
_ are hard to avoid. The Addisons, like the Akins and families of
other children, moved into the hospital, setting up cots in their
child's room.
</P>
<P>
   Just as McCall Akins' grandmother moved in to be close to her
grandchild, so did Matthew's maternal grandmother. And, just as
there was sad irony in McCall's infection and death because she was
a vegetarian, there was some irony in Matthew's case, too. Lisbeth
Addison had read of the Jack in the Box cases two years ago and had
been concerned ever since, careful not to feed Matthew or his older
sister, Brooke, undercooked hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought Liz was being paranoid about it,'' Randy
Addison said. After watching Matthew fall ill on their way back to
Kentucky after visiting Georgia relatives, Randy's view changed
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   As with the other E. coli cases, Matthew first became ill with
diarrhea, then bloody stools and intense abdominal pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was heart-wrenching,'' Lisbeth Addison said of watching her
3-year-old worsen by the hour on their trip home on Sunday, June
21.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew became terrified to go to the bathroom, his mother said,
because the pain was so bad. By Tuesday, doctors admitted him to
the hospital. But that was only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give them any immodium (medicine that typically
stops diarrhea), and you can't give them any pain medicine,'' Randy
Addison said. ``Even with all the specialized care at our hands,
all we could do was sit there and fold our hands and wait for the
infection to take its course.''
</P>
<P>
   The Addisons and Lisbeth's mother took turns on the cots the
hospital provided in Matthew's room, but no one could sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was curled over in the fetal position, screaming,'' Randy
Addison said. Even the nurses sometimes left the room to cry.
</P>
<P>
   For days, Matthew didn't improve. Even though intravenous lines
kept him hydrated internally, he would beg for more water than the
Dixie Cup-sized allowance doctors said he could have every eight
hours. Again, the Addisons could do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, June 26, doctors decided Matthew needed surgery to
insert a special catheter into his abdominal cavity. That meant no
water after midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had these awful cracked, bleeding lips, and he was pleading
with me for water all night long, and all night long, I kept
putting him off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, Lisbeth reached her breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, he looked at me and said, `Mommy, I'm dying! I need
water!', and I lost it. I broke down, and I was hysterical.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurses did allow her to soak his lips with a wet washcloth.
</P>
<P>
   After the surgery, Matthew did not begin to improve for several
days. Lisbeth began to focus on bracing herself for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was losing him,'' she said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   She reached out to friends who had gathered and asked them to
help strengthen her. ``I can't tell you about the love and
outpouring of support, and what it means,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow pilots at UPS took Randy Addison's shifts for him so he
could continue to be on the payroll but remain at the hospital.
Friends brought home-cooked meals to the hospital. Friends baby-sat
their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of small improvements, Matthew suffered a
setback. But by the end of the second week, Matthew was looking
strong enough to go home. He had to have a second operation to
remove the catheter, but on Sunday, July 5, he was home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so emotionally exhausted,'' Lisbeth said, that it was
hard to rejoice. Also, knowing that the effects of the illness can
last for years, the Addisons were guarded.
</P>
<P>
   They had a right to be. On Thursday, July 9, Matthew was
readmitted to Kosair with intense abdominal pain. He was released
July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the healing can begin for the Addisons, but Lisbeth said
her heart breaks for the Akin family, whom she called Saturday at
Scottish Rite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Randy after I got off the phone that I felt totally
worthless,'' she said, explaining that she had wanted to comfort
the family in some way. ``It's hard because you feel guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
