<HEADER>
A0311 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-US500-SPEED-HNS &LR;      07-23 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-US500-SPEED-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CART begins campaign to lower speeds
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BROOKLYN, Mich. _ They call it the Handford Device, which doesn't
mean much to most people. But the CART cars will have the new gizmo
in place this weekend to try to lower the speeds for the U.S. 500
at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Just think of it as CART's version of the restrictor plates
NASCAR uses at Daytona and Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   The two-mile, D-shaped oval will be the first test for the
wing-like Handford Device, which reduces downforce by 300 pounds
and increases drag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt by slowing the cars down a bit, we increase safety,''
said Kirk Russell, CART's vice president of competition. ``It also
enhances the ability of the drivers to race comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mauricio Gugelmin zoomed around the track at more than 240
mph on a qualifying run last fall in California, CART officials
felt something had to be done to slow the cars at the big ovals.
Gugelmin was one of the first drivers to test the new wing
attachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels strange the first time you drive it,'' Gugelmin said.
``It's very draggy, like you've got a parachute on the back of the
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the same stability. We went 218 (mph) in
testing and learned a few things. I think we can get three or four
more mph out of it. It should minimize the advantage anyone has and
bring a closer race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Handford Device is a winglike aerodynamic piece fitted onto
the rear of the car. It is expected to reduce speeds by 15 to 20
mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any reduction of speed is welcome, however small,'' said
driver Gil de Ferran, who tested the wing a few weeks ago. ``It can
make a big difference in the event of an accident at these speeds.
I think this change will have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the drivers can't handle the speeds. That's not
the issue. It's just good common sense to see what can be done,
both from the safety end and to make the racing better for the
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether better racing will be brought about by slowing the cars
remains to be seen. Restrictor-plate racing in NASCAR makes for
some exciting races because it causes the cars to bunch together.
But the drivers believe it also causes accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The Handford Device is a much different way of slowing a race
car because it does not affect the throttle response. Instead, it
makes the car less stable in the turns and causes the drivers to
slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This device is a big step in the right direction,'' said
Michael Andretti, who drives the Texaco Swift Ford. ``It sounds
like an easy thing to do, but it's not. For now, this is the best
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed-reduction device was designed by Mark Handford of
Swift Engineering, which builds the chassis for the Newman/Haas
cars driven by Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi, and the Budweiser
car driven by Richie Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   That could bring up another problem if those cars are faster
than everyone else at Michigan. Andretti already has tested faster
than others. If he qualifies No. 1, some of the other CART teams
could cry foul and claim he had an unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Swift cars may have an edge,'' Hearn admitted. ``These
cars already have more downforce, so they may not lose as much
(speed) as the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti said he has complete confidence in Handford's ability
to make a device that will work for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked with Mark for years,'' Andretti said. ``He is
one of the best _ if not the best _ aerodynamicists around.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Herta, who tested the wing addition earlier this month,
isn't convinced the change will result in better racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car remained fairly stable for the most part, but it was
sliding a fair amount in the corners,'' Herta said. ``I think it
will be tougher to pass now than it has been in the past at this
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Ribeiro, who drives a Marlboro Mercedes for Team Penske,
thinks the real test will come when the cars are racing in a pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is going to reduce speeds,'' Ribeiro said. ``But
we will have to see how it runs in traffic. This is a much bigger
change than previous efforts to slow the cars. Testing and racing
are two different things. The effects the wing has on traffic still
are unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugelmin is the driver who stands to lose the most since he was
the man who mastered the superspeedways by getting the most speed
out of his Hollywood Reynard Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good handle on things at the superspeedways,''
Gugelmin said. ``But now, we are learning the new package like
everyone else. It is going to take a lot of adjustments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
