<HEADER>
A0313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-PALESTINE-4     07-23 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-PALESTINE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GROUPS CHARGE PALESTINIANS WITH DISTORTING HOLOCAUST FACTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Jewish organizations and Holocaust scholars are calling on
Yasser Arafat to reprimand Palestinian officials and journalists
who have recently made statements that appear to distort the
history of the Holocaust or deny its existence.
</P>
<P>
   In a personal letter sent to the Palestinian leader Thursday,
the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations
condemned an article on July 2 in the Palestinian newspaper Al
Hayat al Jadida that called the Holocaust a ``deceitful myth.'' The
article said Jews had disseminated ``frightful pictures of mass
executions and invented the shocking story of the gas ovens, where
Hitler allegedly burned them.''
</P>
<P>
   Inflammatory remarks about the Holocaust in the Palestinian
press have also raised concerns among U.S. negotiators who are
struggling to revive the stalled Middle East peace effort, said a
State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sorts of issues come up unfortunately all too
frequently,'' the official said. ``And when they do, we repeat the
view to the Palestinian Authority that it's got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, the Palestinian Authority minister for
higher education and research, Hanan Ashrawi, said she knew of no
Palestinian officials who had made statements distorting the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't deny the Holocaust,'' Ms. Ashrawi said. ``We don't
denigrate it. Actually we think recognition of the immorality of
the Holocaust is a basic moral component.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ashrawi said she was stunned to learn that U.S. Jewish
organizations were pursuing unattributed statements in Palestinian
newspapers as the peace effort was falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Jewish figure who initiated the campaign that accuses
Palestinian officials of denying the Holocaust is an outspoken
opponent of the peace effort, Morton Klein, president of the
Zionist Organization of America.
</P>
<P>
   Klein prompted the letter to Arafat and also an advertising
campaign this week in Jewish newspapers in 10 cities.
</P>
<P>
   Klein frequently gives speeches and writes editorials critical
of the peace effort because, he said, the Palestinians are not
honoring their commitments under the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hostile propaganda,'' Klein said of the Palestinian
press statements on the Holocaust, ``which is specifically
prohibited by the Oslo accords. This is not in isolation. If
everything else was going nicely this would not become a major
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials and Jews who monitor the Palestinian media say
they have documented a string of statements since the peace accords
were signed that minimize the number of victims of the Holocaust
and accuse the Jews of inventing the tragedy to win international
sympathy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The letter states: ``There can be little hope for reconciliation
if people, especially the youth, are subject to constant
indoctrination portraying their neighbors in such vile ways. We
call on you, and the leadership of the Palestinian Authority, to
denounce this historical revisionism and declare as unacceptable
all written or oral denigration and diminution of the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government and the Jerusalem Post refer to Al Hayat
al Jadida as the official Palestinian Authority newspaper. Yigal
Carmon, a former Israeli intelligence official who runs the Middle
East Media and Research Institute in Washington, said that the
Palestinian Authority pays staff salaries and that the editor in
chief is a member of the Palestinian Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ashrawi said that the Palestinian Authority had no official
newspaper and that the editors of Al Hayat al Jadida were
completely independent and ``write whatever they want to write.''
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. Jewish organizations take exception to something they
read there, Ms. Ashrawi added, they should write a response
directly to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Klein has a list of statements and incidents that he says point
to a trend of Holocaust denial among Palestinian leaders. Citing a
Reuters article, Klein said that in January Palestinians in Gaza
held a rally at which they lauded Roger Garaudy, who was on trial
in Paris for denying the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   According to the article, at that rally the Palestinian
Authority communications minister and its general secretary asked
the crowd to support Garaudy's views because movies and books had
exaggerated the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty Jewish scholars and leaders of organizations,
representing a range of political opinions about the peace process,
signed the newspaper advertisements that condemned the Palestinian
Authority for ``denials and distortions of the Holocaust.'' Among
them were Michael Berenbaum, president of the Survivors of the
Shoah Visual History Foundation and a former director of the U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Museum; Neal Sher, former executive director of
the American Israel Political Action Committee; and Emil
Fackenheim, professor emeritus of Holocaust studies at Hebrew
University.
</P>
<P>
   Berenbaum, who is also a professor of theology at the University
of Judaism in Los Angeles, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes my signature unusual is I generally am in favor of
the peace process and believe it is the only proper path for
Israel. Nevertheless, I believe the Palestinian Authority has to be
sensitive if it's going to pursue peace with Israel. It has to
resist the temptation to resort to tactics to increase its
credibility with its own reactionary fringes, just as Jews have to
resist that temptation as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Holocaust denial is an ``old habit'' for some Palestinians,
Berenbaum said, because ``the Palestinians perceive themselves as
having to pay the price for the victimization of the Jews in World
War II.''
</P>
<P>
   On Arafat's trip to the United States in January, the U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Museum invited him to tour the museum, then
revoked the invitation because of disagreements among its staff,
then extended it again. Arafat ultimately declined the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   While in Amsterdam, Netherlands, in March, Arafat toured the
Anne Frank House Museum. He pledged to share with fellow
Palestinians his impressions of the cramped house where the little
girl hid from the Nazis with her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story is not to be repeated for our children or for their
children,'' Arafat said, referring to Palestinian and Israeli
youngsters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
