</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL DROPS BILL REQUIRING SANCTIONS FOR RELIGIOUS
PERSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Neb., Conn., Miss.)  (th) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legislation to require the U.S. government to
punish foreign countries that permit or endorse religious
persecution was put off indefinitely Thursday by a Senate committee
because Republicans were deeply divided over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which pits social conservatives like the Christian
Coalition against business interests like the Chamber of Commerce
and the major farm organizations, is strongly opposed by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee removed the bill from its
docket Thursday because at least three of the panel's 10
Republicans planned to join the eight Democrats in voting to reject
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   It is not likely that any such measure will be enacted this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was brought down by the fissure in the Republican party
between conservative Christians, the party's foot soldiers, who say
the party's main focus should be on morality, and business leaders,
who provide the Republicans' financial base and want the party to
concentrate on issues like trade, taxes and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   In May the House approved a bill under which countries that
engaged in religious persecution would face an automatic suspension
of most aid from the United States, restrictions on trade with this
country and American opposition to loans from international
financial institutions. People who could show that they were
victims of religious persecution would be given special immigration
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Among the countries the sponsors focused on were China, the
Sudan, Pakistan and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by a huge majority, 375-41, far beyond the
two-thirds vote needed to override any presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   But the House bill stood little chance in the Senate because of
solid Republican opposition there to automatic economic sanctions.
For the last several months, Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., has been
working on a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of his legislation would have the government
publish a list of countries declared guilty of religious
persecution and would allow the president responses ranging from
mild diplomatic protest to strict economic sanctions. This is the
bill the Foreign Relations Committee was to vote on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a solution where you don't have to shoot someone to get
their attention,'' Nickles said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nickles modification did not satisfy the wing of the
Republican Party that represents business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, the leader of the Republican
opposition to the bill in the committee, said the bill would put
the United States in the position of alienating some of its most
valuable diplomatic friends and economic partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be supremely arrogant for us to grade every country
on earth,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who is not on the Foreign
Relations Committee but has been working closely with Nickles,
said, ``I think we should make the statement that religious freedom
is an important element of our foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tate, executive director of the Christian Coalition,
agreed, calling the bill ``a historic opportunity to protect people
of faith around the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument of the White House and the State Department,
endorsed by almost all Democrats in the Senate and by Hagel and his
Republican allies, is that it is a mistake for Congress to restrict
the president's running room on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month President Clinton was required by law to impose
rigid economic sanctions on India and Pakistan after those
countries tested nuclear devices. Congress quickly agreed that the
inflexible law was a mistake. Within days farmers complained about
their inability to sell wheat to Pakistan, and the ban on
agriculture exports was repealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a senator who's not opposed to religious
persecution,'' said Hagel. ``But in foreign policy, you rarely have
the opportunity to choose between all good and all bad. You have to
weigh the nuances carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Some measure involving religious persecution abroad could still
come before the Senate in September. Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., has promised a Senate vote on the bill passed by the
House before Congress adjourns in early October. Nickles said he
was still working on a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear from the lineup in the Foreign Relations
Committee on Thursday that no bill with teeth can pass the Senate.
And almost certainly, too little time is left in this session of
Congress to reconcile the differences between a watered-down Senate
bill and the strict sanctions approved by the House. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0449 </DOCNO>
