<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM TO PAY MEXICO CITY MILLIONS FOR FAILED SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Mexican unit of IBM has agreed to pay Mexico
City $37.5 million in cash and new computer products to resolve a
dispute over a failed data base system that it sold the city. But
three executives will still face trial on charges of conspiring to
defraud the city in the deal, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, announced Wednesday evening, appeared to be an
admission by the unit, IBM de Mexico, that its executives had acted
inappropriately in the course of selling the nearly $26 million
computer system two years ago. But it also underlined how the rules
of business are changing as opposition parties gain increasing
power in Mexico, where corruption has been a pervasive commercial
lubricant.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Mexico's governing party bought the system from
IBM without competitive bidding in 1996. But the district attorney,
who is from the opposition party that won city elections last year,
questioned the deal and pressed criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   John Reilly, an IBM spokesman for Latin America, said Thursday
that the agreement reached with city officials resolved the civil
dispute and underlined the company's ``commitment to customer
satisfaction.'' He insisted that the executives had not been guilty
of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogelio Ramirez de la O, an economist who is a prominent
consultant to foreign businesses here, said that ``IBM could never
have been forced to give up so much unless the government had
proved its accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement makes clear that IBM's dealings here were a
flop if not completely fraudulent,'' Ramirez de la O said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer giant's troubles here come on the heels of a larger
but similar scandal in Argentina, where officials are investigating
whether bribes were paid in order for its Argentine unit to win a
$250 million government contract. Earlier this month, apparently in
response to the criminal investigations in Argentina and Mexico,
IBM said it would no longer sign computer services agreements with
Latin American governments without first engaging in competitive
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The system purchased by Mexico City officials belonging to
President Ernesto Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI, in 1996 included 57 computer servers, 2,100 personal
computers, and software that the company said would help
prosecutors in 130 city offices keep track of hundreds of thousands
of criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   But District Attorney Samuel del Villar, who was appointed by
the opposition Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas in December to reduce
crime and attack corruption, said that shortly after he took
office, he discovered that the system was so overwhelmed with
glitches that it was paralyzing law-enforcement operations.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiations with IBM de Mexico aimed at making
the system operable, he said, he decided to pull the plug in May.
Last month, del Villar charged three executives and 19 current and
former city officials with conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the criminal case, he said, is an ordinance
outlawing large city purchases without competitive bidding. IBM de
Mexico sought to have the charges thrown out, but on Tuesday a
judge ordered the three executives to face trial.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, in a parallel action in the civil part of the
dispute, del Villar and IBM's general manager in Mexico, Alfredo
Capote, signed a legal agreement and later issued a four-paragraph
joint statement. ``After talks between the two parties,'' it said
in part, ``IBM de Mexico has demonstrated its disposition to work
together with the District Attorney's office'' to help the District
Attorney complete its technology-modernization program.
</P>
<P>
   Del Villar, detailing the agreement to reporters late Wednesday,
said that the company had agreed to pay $25.9 million, the cost of
the original contract, by offering that amount in credit for new
computer equipment and services. In addition, it agreed to pay
$11.6 million in damages to the district attorney's office. Del
Villar said the company had already made an initial payment of $2
million toward the damages and would pay the rest over a year in
monthly installments.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney added that ``this agreement is going to
help our office a great deal, especially in light of the budget
cuts we've suffered this year.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, the IBM spokesman, said that the financial terms of
the agreement were supposed to be kept confidential, and declined
to confirm or dispute the figures cited by del Villar.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any complex systems-integration project, technical issues
will arise,'' O'Reilly said, ``and we've always been 100 percent
committed to resolving them, in this case in a way that benefits
the law-enforcement process in Mexico City. This civil agreement
allows us to continue to work together with this customer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
