<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL CHILDREN FOUND HELPING IN ARIZONA'S ONION HARVEST 
</HEADLINE>
 KIDS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Four-year-old Octavio is too young to go to
kindergarten, but he isn't too young to be out in the onion fields
at sunrise helping his dad earn the struggling family's keep.
</P>
<P>
   Sifting through the dirt, Octavio would pick up an onion bulb in
each small hand and carry them to his dad, who would clip the roots
and green tops and add them to the pile in the plastic bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Down the row, Octavio's 7-year-old brother also was picking
onions. At the end of the day, the boy's father would be paid 50
cents for each filled 10-gallon sack. The boys earned no money,
just the pride of working side by side with their father and
contributing to the family finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious they were working,'' said Esther La Plante, a
federal labor inspector who fined the grower and labor contractor
for having the children at work. ``We didn't catch all the kids in
that one crew; they disappeared behind cars and behind trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvesting the fruits and vegetables that grow on Arizona's
farms and feed the nation is hard, harsh work, but Octavio was one
of a dozen children ages 4 to 11 found laboring in Maricopa
County's onion fields in May by U.S. Department of Labor
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department is fining the growers and labor contractors
involved nearly $20,000 for violating federal child labor
prohibitions. The violators were notified last week of the
penalties and have 15 days to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 4-year-old working in the onion fields is a disgrace,''
Secretary of Labor Alexis M. Herman said ``Farm worker families
sometimes feel they have no choice but to take their children with
them to the fields. But this 4-year-old was working not playing.
This should never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, 60 years after Congress made it illegal to employ
children under age 12 in agriculture, child farm workers remain a
hidden _ though not uncommon _ reality on the nation's commercial
farms.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the federal government began cracking down on
employment of young children picking crops. So far, labor
investigators found 50 child farm workers in Texas, New Mexico and
Louisiana, in addition to those discovered in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children who work in agriculture . . . are among the most
vulnerable of America's workers. They are often robbed of
educational opportunities, exposed to dangerous pesticides and
equipment, and often perform difficult manual labor in order to
bring food to America's tables,'' said John R. Fraser, acting
administrator of the Labor Department's Wage and Hour Division.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, about 200,000 children work on farms and in
agricultural processing, according to the Labor Department. But
children under the age of 12 who work the harvest illegally are
uncounted. The law says children can work on farms at age 12 if
their parents own the farms or if they are accompanied by their
parent. Otherwise, they must be at least 14 to be eligible to work
after school hours in non-hazardous tasks.
</P>
<P>
   There is general agreement that children 11 and under are too
young to toil in fields. But the government, growers and farm
workers also agree that for some farm-working parents, turning work
into a family affair is a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Leon, now an educator in Cashion, was a third-grader when
she joined her parents and siblings in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pride to know you earned that little bit of money with
your sweat,'' she said, recalling the days spent picking cotton,
onions, potatoes or lettuce. ``It was money to pay the electric
bills, the rent and to buy food.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon and others who helped harvest as young children, say
parents are forced by low wages and lack of available child care to
take their children with them to the fields. Once there, growers
refer to the children as ``little loose change'' and typically turn
a blind eye to the littlest workers.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three Valley growers fined this month say they don't
want young children picking their crops and have asked parents to
keep them out of the fields. But they say they cannot police their
crews of 200 or more workers closely enough to prevent kids from
joining their parents in the harvest. The third grower fined could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators found a 10-year-old girl and two boys,
ages 6 and 10, working Rousseau Farming's onion fields in Tolleson
on a Saturday. The grower was fined $2,975 as a result while the
labor contractor who supplied the workers was fined $1,175.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't there because we hired them, they were there
because their parents brought them along,'' said David Rousseau,
owner of Rousseau Farming, one of the Valley growers sanctioned by
the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his workers, Rousseau believes, have little choice but
to bring their kids with them. If they don't, he said, then
``either the kids are being left unattended or the family can't
afford to work because of the cost of child care.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators targeted five onion fields around the Valley on
two consecutive weekends in May. La Plante said she and other
investigators were careful to document the children at work,
watching and taking photographs and videotape, before writing up
the violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw some children clipping onions. Some gathered the onions
and some were working to fill their own sacks and buckets,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rousseau disagrees with the investigator's perception that
the children were doing actual work. Another sanctioned grower,
Eugene Waddell said the 8-, 9- and 11-year-old boys he was fined
for were there visiting their father and grandfather. Both growers
are appealing the penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is only the latest state where illegal child laborers
have been discovered. Around the country, investigators for the
Department of Labor are finding child labor violations during
surprise checks on farms.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the ``Salad Bowl'' initiative, inspectors are
targeting lettuce, tomato, cucumber, onion and garlic fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found other child-labor violations involving fairly
large numbers of kids in the Rio Grande Valley and southeastern New
Mexico,'' Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser notes that many growers and their labor contractors make
a bona fide effort to obey the child labor restrictions, but
unscrupulous employers will take advantage of the savings that
unpaid child labor brings them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfortunate fact is that there are some, a minority, who
feel that their competitiveness depends on their taking whatever
shortcuts they can take,'' Fraser said. ``That may mean using young
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Department of Labor officials say they are determined to stop
child labor violations on farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot accept a situation where children 4, 6, 7 or even 11
are working in the fields,'' said Bernard Anderson, assistant
secretary for the department's Employment Standards
Administration. &QL; 
Graciela Sevilla can be reached at 444-4783 or
grace.sevilla(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
