<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EARNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING STOCK PLUMMETS ON BAD EARNINGS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. dished out a platter of disappointing
news for financial analysts Thursday, reporting a 46 percent drop
in second-quarter profits and predicting lower-than-expected
earnings for this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was swift to show its displeasure as Boeing's stock
plunged 13.7 percent to a two-year low of $41.25.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most active issue on the New York Stock Exchange and
accounted for about 26 points of the Dow's 195.93-point tumble.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also said it will cut 18,000 to 28,000 jobs by the end of
next year through attrition and layoffs _ up to 8,000 more than
what has been previously announced. The company now employs 238,000
people in 27 states.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials have not said exactly how many job cuts will
occur or where they will originate, but the reductions are expected
to be spread throughout the company. Included in the overall number
are 12,000 previously announced reductions from Boeing's commercial
aircraft division, headquartered in Renton, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, job cuts could come from further consolidation of
Boeing operations throughout the country which the company expects
to announce next month.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in recent history, Boeing executives outlined
for analysts a series of financial goals to boost shareholder value
and disclosed profit projections, including earnings estimates of
$1 billion this year and $2 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing historically has not disclosed long-term earnings
projections or profit margin goals. But executives have promised
more detailed quarterly updates from now on as the company shifts
its focus from being technically adept at building airplanes to
being able to build a financial powerhouse. Boeing officials also
will use the periodic updates to reassure stockholders that it is
on the road to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a performance driven industry _ higher, faster,
farther,'' Boeing Chairman Phil Condit told analysts in a
conference call. ``We are now going to be a financially driven
company.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing's financial frankness was a rude awakening for
analysts who have been basing high profit expectations on the
company's past performance and limited accounting information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've told us more today than in the whole 20-plus years
I've been following the company,'' said analyst Paul Nisbet with
JSA Research Inc., who has a ``buy'' rating on Boeing stock. ``But
what we heard was shocking. Everybody thought they would be making
a lot more money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's punishment time,'' he said, referring to Boeing's
dramatic $6.50 drop in stock to $41.25.
</P>
<P>
   In separate conference calls with analysts and the news media,
Condit said the company expects to earn about $1 billion this year,
less than 2 percent of expected sales, but has set a goal of
boosting net return on sales to 7 percent by the year 2000 at the
earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Condit acknowledged that achieving the 7 percent goal in the
next two years ``is clearly a difficult goal _ not one that this
company has ever reached before.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted profits will double to $2 billion next year with a
net return on sales of 3 to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's earnings projections were far short of the $1.65
billion profit analysts were expecting for this year and $3.2
billion profit for next year, according to First Call's survey of
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time they are giving us a clue as to what is
going on,'' Nisbet said. ``Expectations were getting out of hand
because of the lack of guidance from the company.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said Boeing's long-term financial picture is still good,
noting that ``the company is doing too much business to not be
making money.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit predicted this year's total sales will be $56 billion,
jumping to $58 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company still expects to deliver 550 commercial aircraft
this year and predicts it will deliver 620 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said second-quarter net income fell to $258 million, or
26 cents a share, in the quarter, from $476 million, or 48 cents a
share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts surveyed by First Call, which tracks analysts'
estimates, had estimated quarterly earnings at 33 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 9 percent to $13.4 billion from $12.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter earnings were down because of lower profit
margins on commercial aircraft and additional late delivery costs
due to problems with the new generation of 737 jetliners, Condit
said. Boeing also took a charge of $78 million related to the
planned termination of the MD-11 aircraft line.
</P>
<P>
   The 737 program has been especially troubled, with production
inefficiencies and parts shortages, extensive changes required
after flight testing, and lower revenue due to the mix of models
being delivered, Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Boeing has made significant headway toward correcting
the problems, but no gross profit will be recorded on the new 737
program until the production rate increase from 14 aircraft to 21
aircraft per month is achieved later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also has been caught in a fierce price war with Airbus
Industrie, the European consortium.
</P>
<P>
   As a way to cut costs, Boeing executives said in December they
would cut 12,000 jobs from the company's commercial airplane
operations and in March the company announced it would cut 8,200
jobs as a result of consolidating its plants nationwide, with most
of those reductions coming in California.
</P>
<P>
   The new employment projections announced Thursday will mean job
reductions of 3,000 to 8,000 by the end of this year, bringing
Boeing's companywide payroll to 230,000 to 235,000. By the end of
next year, Boeing's job cuts will total 18,000 to 28,000, bringing
total employment to 210,000 to 220,000.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing normally has a 4 to 5 percent attrition rate per year but
it is too early to tell how many of the job cuts will come from
attrition or layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of 1998, Boeing had net earnings of
$308 million or 31 cents a share on sales of $26.3 billion,
compared with profits of $1 billion or $1.03 a share on sales of
$22.7 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing President Harry Stonecipher said the company is dedicated
to ``meeting or beating'' its newly outlined financial goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said before, don't bet against The Boeing Co. It's a
bad bet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
