<HEADLINE>
POLICY JOINING BROWNS AS PARTNER AND CEO 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day after resigning as the president of the San Francisco
49ers, Carmen Policy emerged as chief executive of a new group led
by the billionaire banker Al Lerner that is seeking to buy the new
Cleveland Browns franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner, a former 5 percent owner of the former Browns, said
Policy would get 10 percent of the team if his group was chosen by
the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner changed his mind about not pursuing the Browns after
talking to Policy for 15 hours on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability of doing it right with Carmen is higher than
doing it without him,'' said Lerner, who grew up in Brooklyn and
Queens and has lived in Cleveland for 39 years, during a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner's group was endorsed by Mayor Michael White of Cleveland,
who bore no rancor for Lerner's support of Modell's move of the old
Browns to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized the depth of his problem,'' Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   Policy said he did not know if his split with Eddie DeBartolo,
whose family owns the 49ers, would mend.
</P>
<P>
   ``A relationship broke down between close friends who headed
down different paths, and acquired new friends,'' Policy said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     07-23 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TIPTOEING RIGHT INTO A MAYBE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing ascertained about Tim Floyd, the new head coach of the
Chicago Bulls, maybe, is that he improves with time, maybe. Even 10
minutes' time.
</P>
<P>
   After being introduced by the Bulls' owner, Jerry Reinsdorf, at
a news conference Thursday in Chicago as the Director of Basketball
Operations if Retired Coach Phil Jackson Decides to Return and New
Head Coach if Jackson Opts to Remain Self-Dispatched, Floyd thanked
Reinsdorf and said, ``I had always been led to believe that Jerry
Krause is the owner of the Bulls.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd meant this as a kind of light remark, a jest, a quip, a
sally, something to evoke a little risibility among the throng of
ink-stained print and carefully coifed electronic reporters. They
weren't buying, however.
</P>
<P>
   For it is widely viewed that Krause is the core of the Bulls'
maelstrom, despite having been the aggressive general manager _
though a frequently bumbling public relations impressario _ of six
National Basketball Association championship teams in eight
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, who left his job as coach of Iowa State, had been
vigorously courted by Krause. The two are fishing buddies.
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of Floyd's remarks, which included verbal bows
to Jackson, Michael Jordan, the Bulls generally as well as to
family, former coaches, athletic directors and players, he said,
``I have two more things to add: I am not Jerry Krause's boy, and
don't call what Jerry Krause does fishing, either.''
</P>
<P>
   While neither Chaplinesque nor Groucho Marxian, the last was
funny enough to demonstrate a capacity to grow, at least in
relation to his hook-inspiring start.
</P>
<P>
   And rumors of his hiring were met with a tossing of verbal
tomatoes, given that Jordan has said that he has ``nothing
against'' Floyd, whom he disparagingly calls ``Pink,'' after the
rock group, ``but I don't want to start over with a young coach, a
college coach and someone who doesn't know the way I play the game
of basketball.'' The latter comes as a mind-boggler for who doesn't
know how M.J. cavorts on the court.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bulls' answer to a rocket scientist, Dennis Rodman, has
added that the hiring of Floyd as coach would be ``a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   If in fact the 44-year-old Floyd becomes the coach _ and Jackson
has made no known attempt to retire from having retired _ he
appears a plausible choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krause has hired two other coaches who never had NBA
head-coaching experience, Doug Collins and Phil Jackson,'' said
John Nash, general manager of the Nets, who have been successful
the last two seasons under John Calipari, who, like Floyd, never
before had NBA experience as a coach or a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Krause is two for two, that's a pretty good record,'' Nash
said. Many coaches with no previous NBA experience succeeded as
coaches in the league, Nash added, and he named three: Jack Ramsay,
Dick Motta and John MacLeod.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes ability to motivate people and to be technically
prepared,'' he said. ``There is an adjustment from college to pro,
but it's not that great. To me, bright people can transcend those
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jordan has waffled before. He retired from hoops, he
returned. He said he would never play for any other coach but
Jackson, and then said he was ``keeping my options open.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe the return of Scottie Pippen is more important to
him. Pippen, recuperating from surgery earlier last season, said he
would never play for the Bulls again. And, lo and behold, did. Then
he said he would never come back with them next season, and later
said he might.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf, seeking to plug a hole of fan discontent should
Jordan retire, said he wished to bring back all the people who won
Title No. 6 last season, including Jackson, who told me that he was
leaving on his own volition and that his relationship with Krause,
while poor, was not the deciding factor. So it was logical for the
owner to seek another coach if Jackson remains in Montana, or
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, meanwhile, said he would happily step aside and work hard
as the head of the vague new basketball operations should Jackson
return. Floyd also suggested that if he were the coach, Tex Winters
and Frank Hamblen, significant assistant coaches, would be
retained, which should bolster the comfort level of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd has had a superb 12-year college coaching career at three
universities, with 243 victories and 130 losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a chance,'' Floyd said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, this is not an unreasonable request. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
