<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT DESCRIBES A SUCCESSFUL YEAR AND TALKS OF MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Confident Microsoft executives Thursday outlined for
industry analysts a string of successes suggesting momentum
throughout the computer industry in markets as diverse as home
computers, business desktop machines, engineering work stations and
the giant computers that connect entire corporations and serve up
World Wide Web sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain this momentum, the company said it planned to
increase research and development spending to $3 billion a year
from $2.5 billion in the fiscal year that ended on June 30, and to
pump almost $200 million a year more into technical and customer
support.
</P>
<P>
   As Microsoft officials here were laying out some of the most
impressive results recorded by a major American corporation this
year, in Washington the Senate Judiciary Committee was hearing
complaints from executives of several competing software companies
that Microsoft uses predatory marketing practices to squelch
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Among those testifying was Robert Glaser, a former Microsoft
employee who is now chairman of Real Networks, a Seattle-based
maker of software that enables users to receive live audio and
video on their Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser told senators that Microsoft had developed a new version
of its media player for the Windows 98 operating system that
undermines his software.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft lawyer, Brad Smith, said any problem Glaser had
encountered was unintended, adding that ``we'll keep working with
them'' to resolve it.
</P>
<P>
   However, at a time when the company's business practices are
under attack by the Justice Department, several congressional
committees and 20 states and the District of Columbia, and under
investigation by European governments, Microsoft executives gave no
indication of abandoning the aggressive strategies that have made
it one of the world's most successful and feared corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while citing increasing market share against its
strongest rivals, including Sun Microsystems, Novell and Oracle in
applications as diverse as operating systems, data bases and
Internet commerce software, the company sought to play down any
possibility that the Justice Department's antitrust suit would have
a negative effect on its profit.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Jeff Raikes, its sales chief, suggested that Justice
Department investigators had misinterpreted a corporate sense of
humor as a strategic intention to eradicate competition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To demonstrate this corporate humor, Raikes played a music video
that the company had produced to motivate its sales force. In the
video, a spoof on the movie ``Men In Black,'' Raikes plays the role
of a rap singer wearing wrap-around dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   His lyrics include, ``We're the first, last and best line of
defense against the worst scum in the industry,'' and, referring to
Lawrence Ellison, the chairman of Oracle, ``Ellison is a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Microsoft officials expressed satisfaction with
advances in their share of several markets and with sales of
Windows 98, which they said was on track to match the first three
months' sales of Windows 95, the best-selling software ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has surprised a lot of people, including myself to some
extent,'' Raikes said.
</P>
<P>
   There were other areas where the company acknowledged it had
made less progress than it expected. Novell had proved to be a
tougher competitor than was expected in the network service market.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft executives asserted that they had taken five to
eight percentage points of market share away from Novell in the
last year, and Raikes said he would be disappointed if Microsoft's
market share did not grow an equal amount next year.
</P>
<P>
   As he does every year, Microsoft's chief financial officer
predicted that the company's growth would decline substantially in
the coming year because many of its products are mature and are
reaching the saturation point in the market. He also expressed fear
about the Asian troubles, adding, ``In fact, there is evidence it's
getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year Microsoft appears to zero in on one company for
attack, and analysts who attended Thursday's meeting said the next
focus would be on the corporate data base business that Oracle now
dominates.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison was in Washington on Thursday, testifying against
Microsoft's business practices. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
