<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASSHALL-PHANTOM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PHANTOM HAS LANDED IN FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By PERRY STEWART &QC;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The chandelier has landed.
</P>
<P>
   Heralded by an avalanche of publicity, frantic scrambles for
tickets and a scenery and equipment load-in of D-Day dimensions,
the national touring production of ``The Phantom of the Opera''
opened Wednesday night in the Nancy Lee and Perry R. Bass
Performance Hall.
</P>
<P>
   This is the moon landing of Fort Worth entertainment events.
Wednesday's show was technically termed a preview, one of three,
with Friday's performance being the official opening.
</P>
<P>
   Fiddlesticks. Try telling the folks who filled the hall
Wednesday that they weren't bona fide first-nighters. When a show
takes on the celebrity of ``Phantom,'' the night it arrives in your
town is the opening.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of Andrew Lloyd Webber's megahit musical had a dress
rehearsal Wednesday afternoon, and it obviously acquainted them
with the Bass hall. The first public performance went off with no
hitches _ the famous chandelier ``crashing'' on cue. It wasn't the
frightening spectacle that first-time ``Phantom'' viewers probably
expected. But it never is.
</P>
<P>
   (A scarier effect comes earlier, when the Phantom spies on
Christine and Raoul from a statuary high above the Paris Opera
House.)
</P>
<P>
   The Lloyd Webber score sounds good in the Bass hall, and the
singers sound even better. Brad Little is a talent of impressive
range, both as singer and actor. As the hideously deformed figure
who haunts the Paris Opera House, Little succeeds in evoking fright
and compassion. He builds his signature song, ``The Music of the
Night,'' from delicate whisper to powerful crescendo and brings
similar joy with ``All I Ask of You.''
</P>
<P>
   To the role of Christine, the beautiful young soprano coached
and mesmerized by the Phantom, Amy Jo Arrington brings winsome
charm, a saucy sense of comedy and a lovely coloratura. She and
Little team winningly on ``I Remember'' and ``Stranger Than You
Dreamt It'' and powerfully (with Jason Pebworth) on ``Wandering
Child.''
</P>
<P>
   Pebworth has the not-altogether heroic role of Raoul, the
spoiled young viscount who courts Christine.
</P>
<P>
   Director Harold Prince's unflagging pace is maintained in this
touring edition, and Maria Bjornson's sets and costumes add the
perfect mixture of brilliance and excess.
</P>
<P>
   The company as a whole is superior, as evidenced by the Act II
opener, ``Masquerade,'' a number that showcases every aspect of
musical theater as well as the 19th century ambience of the hall.
</P>
<P>
   This show has great fun spoofing the ornate aspects of grand
opera, particularly in backstage and rehearsal exchanges. Julie
Schmidt, as the resident diva unseated by Christine, is a key
player in those moments.
</P>
<P>
   Saluting Schmidt on ``Prima Donna'' are Pebworth, Richard
Reardon, Betina Hershey and David Cryer. Yes, this is the same
David Cryer who was the firebrand Rutledge in ``1776.'' The voice
is still there, and Cryer demonstrates comic savvy as the
beleaguered opera house manager.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, there is fine work from Jennine Jones as a ballet
mistress suggestive of the housekeeper in ``Rebecca,'' Steven
Stein-Grainger as an egotistic tenor and Stephen Len White as opera
``buffo'' archtype.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
