A0355 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-23 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Pacific Exchange May Merge   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In another merger that could weaken San Francisco's image as the
West Coast's financial capital, the directors of the Pacific
Exchange announced an agreement yesterday to join forces with the
Chicago Board Options Exchange.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pacific Exchange would keep its options trading floor in San
Francisco and move ahead with plans to build a major new trading
facility on Folsom Street.
</P>
<P>
   The original business of the Pacific _ trading stocks _ would be
sold to another exchange or spun off as an independent organization
within 18 months. The Pacific has stock trading floors in Los
Angeles and San Francisco. The CBOE does not trade stocks, only
options. An option contract gives the holder the right to buy or
sell a company's stock at a certain price by a certain date.
</P>
<P>
   Completion of the deal is not certain, because two-thirds of the
Pacific Exchange's 552 members must approve it. And, yesterday,
many were alarmed because the Pacific could lose more than 100
stock options _ including many of its hottest contracts _ to the
CBOE.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; That's because about 160 of the Pacific's 800-plus stock
options are also traded on the CBOE, and it looks like dual-listed
options will be traded on the floor where they have the greatest
market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is that we will lose 130 issues, including Cisco
Systems, America Online, Amazon.com and Netscape,'' said James
Burleson, a market maker for Joseph D. Heard and also chairman of
the Pacific Exchange's nominating committee. ``This would devastate
my business. I trade Cisco and Read-Rite among other
multiple-listed issues and could lose two-thirds of my
livelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   As the dominant U.S. options exchange with a nearly 50 percent
market share, the CBOE had more clout in the negotiations than the
No. 3-ranked Pacific Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   CBOE Chairman and Chief Executive William Brodsky left no doubt
yesterday that his organization will be ``the successor entity'' if
the deal goes through.
</P>
<P>
   Although no name has been chosen yet for the combined exchange,
the headquarters would be in Chicago and its top two officers would
be Brodsky and CBOE President Charles Henry. Pacific Exchange CEO
Robert Greber declined to say what he would do after a merger.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco exchange was the first center of trading for
industrial stocks in the West. It was founded in 1882, a time when
the California economy was starting to diversify from its gold and
silver-mining roots. By providing a market for their stocks, it
helped companies like Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric and Wells Fargo raise
capital and become the giants they are today.
</P>
<P>
   Neither exchange could say how many jobs the merger might cost
the city, which is home to nearly 400 Pacific employees and as many
as 1,900 employees of member firms.
</P>
<P>
   The merged entity would trade options on more than 1,700 stocks,
accounting for 65 percent of all trading of U.S. securities
options.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Chicago exchange does nearly three times as much
business and has nearly three times as many members as the Pacific,
it will likely control the new board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The two exchanges announced that they were in merger discussions
last week. Like brokerage firms and banks, exchanges are merging to
gain market share, cut costs and become more competitive in the
global marketplace. BankAmerica recently agreed to merge with
NationsBank of Charlotte, N.C., costing San Francisco the
headquarters of another long-standing financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   The CBOE reportedly spends about $60 million a year on
technology, and the Pacific spends about $20 million. The plan is
to save about $80 million in technology investments over the next
five or six years. About 80 percent of options trades on the CBOE
are handled electronically compared to only about 20 percent at the
Pacific, according to Pacific Exchange Vice Chairman Rob Kovell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination will result in considerable economies of
scale, particularly in the development of costly new trading
systems,'' said Brodsky.
</P>
<P>
   Some Pacific market makers applauded the deal. ``It will give us
a lot of CBOE technology,'' said Peter Napoli, a market maker with
Assets Mondial.
</P>
<P>
   But others traders wonder why the deal was necessary since the
exchange has recorded record profits for three years and trading
volume has been increasing at about 40 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   Burleson is worried about how new stock options will be
allocated to the two trading floors. ``Since the committee that
decides future allocations of new options will be skewed in favor
of the CBOE because they have more members, I fear our future
growth will be stunted.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Exchange spokesman Dale Carlson acknowledged that some
traders could be hurt but said that no decisions have been made on
how dual-listed options and new option issues would be allocated.
And even if the San Francisco options trading floor lost
dual-listed issues which are traded more heavily in Chicago, the
Pacific's average daily options volume would dip only 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Exchange officials met with trading specialists and
members yesterday afternoon in San Francisco and Los Angeles and
tried to assure them that the deal would be good for them. But not
everyone was convinced.
</P>
<P>
   One thorny issue is what to do with the equities trading floors
in San Francisco and Los Angeles. About a quarter of Pacific
members trade stocks, not options.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that they would try to work out a solution to keep
us a stand-alone equity exchange or merge us with another regional
exchange such as the Boston, Cincinnati or NASD,'' said Dennis
LoPresti, senior vice president of Wedbush Morgan Securities in Los
Angeles. ``But I don't want the CBOE determining our destiny. I and
a lot of others would like a commitment to keep us independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said they don't think the merger will hurt
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This appears to be good for both San Francisco and Chicago,''
said Kandace Bender, spokeswoman for Mayor Willie Brown. ``The deal
allows both exchanges to become stronger and supports a new trading
facility South of Market.'' City Supervisor Mark Leno added,
``Everything I've heard is encouraging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
