u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLLAPSE-RDP-445&AMP;A     07-23 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-RDP-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MISHAP'S IMPACT DEEPENS, COMPENSATION BID IS SPURNED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-COLLAPSE-RESTAURANT and other sidebars to come) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the long-term costs of the Times Square
construction site collapse became a sobering reality _ with at
least 600 people left homeless and Broadway productions and local
businesses shut down indefinitely _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on
Thursday dismissed as inadequate a $50,000 compensation offer made
by the owner and builder of the troubled Conde Nast building.
</P>
<P>
   The offer came as personal tales of dislocation and disruption
took on a more urgent, more stressful tone, particularly the plight
of 300 residents forced from their apartment building on 44th
Street. At the same time, pressure mounted to get the area back to
normal as quickly as possible, as businesses complained that they
were hemorrhaging money.
</P>
<P>
   Facing increasing demands that compensation be paid out quickly,
the developer of the Conde Nast building, the Durst Organization,
and the construction manager, Tishman Construction Corp., offered
$50,000 to assist those displaced by the collapse of the elevator
tower at the building site. But in announcing that the offer had
been made, Giuliani all but derided that sum as measly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly inadequate,'' a stern-looking Giuliani said.
``They could offer a lot more than that, because there's going to
be a lot more involved in the displacement that's taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hours after the mayor's news conference, Tishman
released a statement suggesting that there had been a
misunderstanding. The $50,000, the statement said, is earmarked for
those businesses and residents requiring immediate assistance, like
food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``sufficient funds will be made available to
adequately provide for all those who have been displaced or
suffered hardships,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion seemed to befit a day when uncertainty continued
to swirl around the accident, the cleanup and the consequences of
what Buildings Commissioner Gaston Silva has described as ``the
most serious and dramatic construction failure of this decade.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, city officials are clinging to their goal of wrapping
the Conde Nast building on 43rd Street near Broadway with a
reinforced black nylon netting by late Friday or Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Once the netting is in place, workers can begin to dismantle the
twisted remains of the damaged scaffolding tower. There are also
several canisters of oxygen on the tower that need to be removed.
Then, Seventh Avenue, Broadway and the Avenue of the Americas can
be reopened to vehicular and pedestrian traffic, perhaps as soon as
Saturday. And residents on West 44th Street and other closed
streets who have been left homeless for the last three days can
return to their apartments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One resident of 123 W. 44th St., Dennis van Golbereinge, a chef
at the Waldorf-Astoria, left his apartment at 8 a.m. Tuesday for a
run in Central Park. He has not been able to return, and because he
only has his running clothes, he cannot get access to his bank
account because he has no identification.
</P>
<P>
   His effective eviction also posed professional problems. ``My
laptop is my life,'' said van Golbereinge. ``I have 20 years of
recipes in there.''
</P>
<P>
   But 43rd Street between the Avenue of the Americas and Broadway,
city officials acknowledged, is a different matter, leaving the
fate of 275 people forced from the Woodstock Hotel in doubt
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be five days to a week after everything else is
open'' on 43rd Street, Silva said. ``And even then, it may not be
open' he added. ``We may end up putting sidewalk sheds to allow
pedestrians. We may open up one-half to pedestrian traffic on just
the north side. It's just a fluid situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Silva said that there were no more clues Thursday about what
might have caused Tuesday's accident, in which a temporary elevator
collapsed and rained tons of steel onto the streets below, killing
an 85-year-old woman and forcing the closing of a large swath of
midtown Manhattan. For now, he said, there are three leading
theories: that a 10-foot section of the 700-foot scaffolding
collapsed; that bolts or nuts were missing from the scaffolding and
tower assembly, and that a crane at the top of the building slammed
into the elevator tower.
</P>
<P>
   As for those who were displaced, there was a modicum of
encouraging news Thursday. Richard Kielar, senior vice president of
Tishman Realty &AMP; Construction Co., said that a walk-in emergency
assistance center would be opened Friday morning at the Hippodrome
building, 1120 Avenue of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours Thursday afternoon, emergency personnel allowed
some residents to return quickly to their apartments on West 43rd
Street between Fifth Avenue and the Avenue of the Americas and
retrieve some items. But after construction workers detected a
shift in the Conde Nast building at about 7:30 p.m., that glimmer
of hope was doused.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
