<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: was doused.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And there were other tales of lives that had been thrown out of
loop.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wingate, a spokesman for the American Red Cross in
Greater New York said an elderly diabetic man showed up at a hotel
where the Red Cross is providing shelter and said he had been
wandering the streets for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Badway, a maitre d' at Sam's Restaurant in Times Square who
is also an actor and a model, said he had been evacuated so quickly
from his apartment at 123 W. 44th St. that he left his
air-conditioning on and didn't take anything other than a credit
card and a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have resumes, head shots, my book _ emotionally I'm
starting to feel the fatigue of being homeless,'' he said. ``I'm
living out of a knapsack with dirty underwear and dirty socks.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Muziani, an actress who also works at the Rainbow Room,
had been waiting for two sizable checks that she had counted on to
help pay her rent at 123 W. 44th St. But the U.S. Postal Service is
barred from delivering mail to the affected area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to run around looking for the truck,'' she said. (Good
news, bad news: the Postal Service said Thursday that affected
customers can pick up their mail at the post office at 340 W. 42nd
St. _ but ID is required.)
</P>
<P>
   The circus-like atmosphere has extended beyond the thought of
people chasing mail delivery trucks or the sight of Times Square
sans automobiles. Several pets remained stuck in some buildings
Thursday, and that prompted a vigorous protest from animal-rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who work in the area and have been unable to return
to their offices said the novelty of the accident had worn off.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Tuesday when it happened, everyone was like, `Whew! Snow
day! Vacation! Long weekend!''' said Meg D'Incecco, national media
manager for Edelman Public Relations Worldwide, whose offices are
at 1500 Broadway.``But it's become more of a pain than an
adventure.''
</P>
