A0361 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISTORY-SFCHRON &LR;      07-23 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 A New Chapter in the Colorful History of Pacific Exchange   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Pacific Exchange bucked 116 years of bull and bear markets and
competition with larger exchanges before agreeing yesterday to
merge with the Chicago Board Options Exchange.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pacific Exchange, which trades hundreds of millions of
dollars worth of stocks and options each day, began as a modest
attempt by 19 local brokers to impose order on the booming but
infantile market for Western industrial stocks in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   California's economy was beginning to diversify from its
gold-mining roots, and the capitalists of the day needed a
centralized spot to buy and sell securities.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 18, 1882, a group of enterprising brokers met in the
basement of Wohl &AMP; Pollitz at 403 California St. and formed the
Local Security Board. Within a month, the organization underwent
the first of many name and location changes and was redubbed the
San Francisco Stock and Bond Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Trading began the day after the founding, with the stock of a
dozen companies changing hands. The exchange's members paid $7.50 a
month for the privilege of shouting bids from either side of a room
at 312 California St.
</P>
<P>
   The trading was mediated by a caller sitting in the middle of
the room, and disputed bids were put to a vote by members. Winners
tended to be the brokers with the most friends present. Sessions,
sometimes lasting only 15 minutes, were held at 11 a.m. and 2 p.m.
weekdays and 2 p.m. on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange's charter members included Carl and Gustav Sutro of
Sutro &AMP; Co., a San Francisco investment firm that is still in
business today.
</P>
<P>
   In its first year of operation, the San Francisco Stock and Bond
Exchange traded $9.5 million in stocks, including Hawaiian
Commercial and Sugar Co.; Safety Nitro Powder, which made dynamite
for gold mining; and public utilities such as San Francisco Gas and
Electric.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen stocks traded more than quintupled during the
exchange's first year to 62. Today, the Pacific Exchange trades
2,700 stocks in various industries and 800 options, primarily on
technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   In April of 1906, the exchange closed for the first time since
its founding because of the earthquake and fire that hit San
Francisco. Proving that you can't keep capitalism down, members
resumed trading in the basement of one member's home, sitting on
crates and observing the proceedings by candle light.
</P>
<P>
   Competition with other exchanges began in earnest in 1925, when
Western Union installed ticker tape to connect the San Francisco
exchange to the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the exchange wasn't all work and no play. The San
Francisco Stock Exchange Institute was founded as the
``educational, social and athletic auxiliary to the stock
exchange,'' according to a Chronicle account of the time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, the Institute staged a musical comedy in the Columbia
Theater featuring ``sixteen girls, all beautiful, flanked by a
snappy male chorus chosen from the younger members of the
organization,'' The Chronicle reported. The dancers' ``tricky
steps'' were guaranteed to ``intrigue the most blase of front row
fans,'' the account promised.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, the exchange replaced its ``open outcry'' trading
system with specialists _ individuals who oversee the trading of
particular stocks. In 1928, a seat on the Exchange went for a
shocking $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   But by early 1929, concerns about a lack of liquidity and
competition with East Coast markets were beginning to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Stock market officials touted the lack of a state tax, which
made trading cheaper here than on the New York Stock Exchange. They
also hoped that the expertise of San Francisco specialists in local
companies would encourage continued trading of those Western
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stock market crash of October 1929, the exchange
proceeded with plans to move to its current headquarters on Pine
and Sansome streets in early 1930. The exchange paid $2.5 million
to build a new trading floor behind the classical facade of the
former U.S. Sub-Treasury Building.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, women were allowed for the first time to
work on the trading floor as ``markers,'' but the exchange didn't
admit its first woman member until 1969, when Venita Van Caspel
joined.
</P>
<P>
   To cut costs and help California exchanges remain competitive,
the San Francisco Exchange in 1957 merged with its bitter rival,
the Los Angeles Exchange, to create the Pacific Coast Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for the new exchange seemed rosy to then-chairman
William Agnew. He told the Argonaut newspaper in 1957 that the
merged organization ``will continue to progress with this
magnificent region, for it is the securities industry's Exchange of
Destiny _ destined to grow and serve the entire Pacific coast.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1970s were a period of change and anxiety for the exchange.
Although it instituted the country's first computerized automatic
execution system, its stock business languished.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'70s the exchange fought off an attempted acquisition
by the New York Stock Exchange. It also blocked a move to close the
San Francisco trading floor and move all operations to Los Angeles,
where trading volume was twice as high as in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But exchange officials also made the key decision in 1976 to
begin trading options. Earlier this decade, options exceeded stocks
as the exchange's biggest business. With the merger announced
yesterday, the exchange is expected to sell off its equities
business and concentrate solely on options.
</P>
<P>
   Trading today could hardly be more different from the 1882
California St. operations.
</P>
<P>
   All of the stock exchanges in the country now are linked so that
investors can buy and sell shares on whatever exchange offers the
best price, whether the order gets executed in New York, Chicago or
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The ``open outcry'' system is still in force on the options
floor of the Pacific Exchange, but for equities, it was replaced in
1926 by a system of ``specialists'' _ individuals who oversee the
trading of particular companies. Computer screens have replaced the
chalkboards where trades were recorded in the early days.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Pacific Exchange traded 3.3 billion shares of
stock, up from 2.9 billion in 1996. It also moved 46.7 million
options contracts, up from 34 million the prior year. Each options
contract gives investors the right to buy or sell 100 shares of
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Pacific Exchange membership sold for a record
$380,000, though that number has fallen somewhat this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
