 &HT;    On deck: Pittsburgh Pirates
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Today and Saturday at 7:10 p.m., Sunday at 1:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Three Rivers Stadium
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: Fox Sports South and WSB (750-AM) will broadcast all
three games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight _ RHP John Smoltz (8-2,
3.53; 10-10, 3.91 lifetime vs. Pirates) vs. LHP Chris Peters (4-7,
3.97; 1-0, 6.75 lifetime vs. Braves). Saturday _ LHP Denny Neagle
(10-8, 3.62; 1-1, 3.54 lifetime vs. Pirates) vs. RHP Francisco
Cordova (8-8, 3.13; 1-3, 1.04 lifetime vs. Braves). Sunday _ RHP
Greg Maddux (13-4, 1.66; 14-13, 2.77 vs. Pirates) vs. RHP Jason
Schmidt (8-7, 4.15; 1-2, 7.54 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 184-208 but
is 12-6 at Three Rivers
</P>
<P>
   the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves are 5-1 against the Pirates in 1998;
all of those games were played in a 10-day period in April.Quickly:
The Pirates entered Thursday night's play having won six of
eight... The Pirates cannot blame their pitching staff for being
under .500 since June 6. The team ERA is 3.55, third only to the
Braves and New York in the National League. They have been
vulnerable late in the game. Of their 54 losses, 10 came after they
led in the seventh. ... The bigger problem has been run production.
The Pirates are averaging 3.93 runs a game this year, down from
4.47 last year. ... Still, they have two of the most difficult outs
in the league. Jason Kendall took a .335 average into Thursday
night, second in the NL, and with one strikeout every 13 at-bats,
ranks sixth as the toughest man to strike out. Tony Womack has not
grounded into a double play in 419 at-bats, the longest streak in
the league. He was tied with Oakland's Rickey Henderson with a
major league-high 39 stolen bases. ... Peters, tonight's starter,
has pitched beyond the fifth inning in just two of his nine starts,
but is coming off his best performance of the season, beating
Montreal 6-1 last Sunday (seven innings, five hits, one run, five
strikeouts). ... On the DL: RHP Marc Wilkins (strained right
rotator cuff), LHP Jeff Tabaka (fractured jaw) and RHP Jose Silva
(fractured right wrist).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: Young's 20 homers have already established a career
high. He entered the year with just 39 career homers in 418 games.
Right fielder Jose Guillen is tied with Andruw Jones and
Philadelphia's Doug Glanville and Bobby Abreu for the outfield
assist lead with 11.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: Mark Smith, a career .259 hitter who had nine homers
last year in just 193 at-bats, is down to .216 with just two homers
in 97 at-bats. Rookie reliever Javier Martinez has allowed 26 hits
with 23 walks in just 24 1/3 innings.
</P>
