<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer says Galarraga can top Maris mark
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Don't give up on Andres Galarraga breaking Roger
Maris' home run record _ he's got a 50-50 chance. And unless Mark
McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals gets struck by lightning, he's
almost a cinch to grab the single-season homer title.
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't the predictions of Las Vegas bookies, but of a
physicist at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland. He's
crunched thousands of numbers in his computer, which figures that
McGwire, who has 43 homers, has a 97 percent chance of hitting 62
or more.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Brown's computer also predicts that Seattle's Ken
Griffey Jr., who has 40 homers, has a 75 percent chance of topping
Maris' record, set in 1961. And it says there's a 99 percent chance
that either McGwire or Griffey will break the record.
</P>
<P>
   So what do computers know? It's true, numbers can lie, but
trends seldom do, Brown said Thursday. His predictions are based on
assumptions based on previous performances, but also that McGwire
won't miss more than a week of games due to injury or stress, and
that Griffey won't miss more than one. He also figures in how the
two sluggers have done so far against the teams they'll play again,
and how they've done against pitchers they're likely to see.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' Sammy Sosa, Brown says, has only about a 50 percent
chance of beating Maris, even though he has the same number of
homers as Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions are based on such variables as average homers per
time at bat, and rate of hits per game. Among other things, the
scientist looked at each player's propensity for injuries, illness
and for handling stress. He also says McGwire has a 92 percent
chance of breaking Babe Ruth's mark of 60 homers in 154 games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
