<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-SOURCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outbreak traced to beef
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Beef served last spring in Madison County schools is
emerging as the likely source of the state's largest E. coli
outbreak that infected more than two-dozen children at White Water
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we suspect the beef,'' said Dr. Paul Blake,
epidemiologist for the state Division of Public Health. ``It's not
definitive, but there is an indication of a strong link.''
</P>
<P>
   Health investigators have known about the genetic match between
the hamburger and White Water for weeks, but have refused to make a
firm connection because the particular strain common to the beef
and White Water cases has appeared elsewhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That has angered members of Safe Tables Our Priority, or STOP,
who said public health officials should have worked harder to find
a link sooner and communicated more with parents about the possible
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given them a false sense of security,'' by saying
pools are safe and not linking the outbreak to beef, said Nancy
Donley of Chicago. Donley worries that public health officials are
far more interested in protecting a meat manufacturer or a theme
park than alerting the public to a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said he was surprised by the criticism. State health
officials learned of the E. coli cases on June 19, a Friday, and
held a press conference the following Tuesday. ``We've been very
proud of the fact that we were able to move so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake said public health officials believed serious E. coli
cases linked to beef eaten by kids in April and May in Madison
County had been limited to one child. Officials were not overly
concerned because the contamination was discovered and the meat was
recalled quickly by the manufacturer, Bauer Meat Co. of Ocala, Fla.
A Danielsville boy with diabetes and other health problems was
hospitalized in connection with the beef.
</P>
<P>
   And, Blake said, public health workers checked absentee records
of school children to make sure there wasn't a ``large hidden
outbreak.'' They found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But now health officials suspect secondary infections, those
that are passed from person to person, might have led to the
outbreak at the popular Cobb County water park. Definitely proving
that is tenuous, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to do a trace back through a multiple-generation
transmission is about impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the White Water outbreak, Blake said the investigators are
still trying to determine how the park became contaminated. Health
workers recently revised questionnaires originally completed by
victims, family members and friends in an attempt to learn more
specific details. For example, health workers are now asking
parents the exact time of day when they visited the park and when
symptoms first occurred.
</P>
<P>
   They are also exploring other possible ways fecal matter could
have gotten into the pool. Previously, officials said there were
probably either fecal accidents on June 11 and June 17, each
followed by a day of residual contamination, or four days of fecal
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   But since learning more about the practices of White Water
visitors, other scenarios are possible, Blake said. Some mothers,
for example, were not using the diaper changers in bathrooms;
instead, they were changing infants on the plastic deck chairs,
leaving soiled diapers under them.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said toddlers or others could have gotten feces on their
feet from walking on a diaper and then could have rinsed the
bacteria off their feet and into the pool. There could have been
residue left on the chairs or on parents hands, he said.
</P>
<P>
   White Water, which has brought in a team of medical experts to
conduct its own investigation, would not discuss the team's
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to figure out how the organism got into the pool
and how it was transmitted,'' said Dr. Eugene Gangarosa, who is
leading the team. ``But I do not feel comfortable discussing
intimate details of the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pool is perfectly safe,'' said Gangarosa, the former
deputy director of the bacterial disease division for the CDC and a
former supervisor of Blake. ``I will have no problem taking my
grandchildren there in August when they visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
