<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Senate Backs Internet Gambling Ban   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
All bets are off the Internet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate voted overwhelmingly yesterday to shut down the
online gambling industry, condemning it as a corrupting influence
on young Americans and a major contributor to crime.
</P>
<P>
   Senators voted 90 to 10 to ban an estimated 140 offshore Web
sites _ with names like World Sports Exchange, InterCasinos and
NetCasino _ from letting U.S. high rollers play interactive
blackjack, video poker, roulette and other casino-style games over
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The ban is expected to sweep through the House and be signed
into law by President Clinton this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet gambling is unregulated, accessible by minors,
addictive, subject to abuse for fraudulent purposes like money
laundering, evasive of state gambling laws _ and already illegal at
the federal level in many cases,'' said Senator Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.,
the bill's chief author.
</P>
<P>
   Online wagers _ available 24 hours a day from the privacy of
homes and offices _ add up to an estimated $1 billion worldwide,
$600 million of it in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If it becomes law, the gambling ban would be the most
far-reaching Internet legislation since the Communications Decency
Act of 1996. That bill, which barred indecent and ``patently
offensive'' materials on the Net, was ruled unconstitutional by the
U.S. Supreme Court last year.
</P>
<P>
   The gambling legislation _ included as an amendment to a $33.2
billion spending bill _ would force Internet service providers in
the United States to use filtering software to block customer
access to cybergambling, Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet gambling already is considered illegal under a 1961
federal law that bars interstate gambling over telephone wires.
While that has deterred U.S. operators from establishing online
betting, it has not stopped offshore companies from setting up
global online casinos in exotic locales such as the Caribbean and
Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kyl's provision, gamblers face fines up to $500 and jail
terms of up to three months; individuals running gambling sites
could be imprisoned for four years and fined $20,000 or three times
the amount of bets accepted.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ban would not apply to:
</P>
<P>
   _State lotteries and off-track betting that employ
``closed-loop, subscriber-based'' computer systems unavailable to
the general public.
</P>
<P>
   _Sites for popular sports ``rotisserie'' leagues, in which
consumers pick professional athletes and bet on their statistics,
as long as fees are not used to pay off bets.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, meanwhile, rejected Native American groups' appeal
that they be exempted from the Internet rule because their casinos
and gambling operations are sanctioned under a separate federal
law. Kyl said that would create a mammoth loophole.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl's provision has been hotly disputed for more than a year,
stuck in a political tug-of-war between opposing interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the bill range from consumer advocate Ralph Nader and
the four major sports leagues to law-enforcement officials, the
Christian Coalition and regulated gambling operations. All of them
contend that unfettered access to gambling contributes to
bankruptcy, crime, family breakups and, in some cases, suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online gambling is a predatory attack on main street America.
With a click of a mouse, you could lose your house,'' said Tom
Grey, executive director of the National Coalition Against Gambling
Expansion in Hanover, Ill. ``People are wagering, and losing _
$2,000 an evening in front of their PCs, instead of watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Licensed U.S. casinos, such as the Las Vegas Mirage, say they
oppose cyberwagers because they are not subject to strict controls
over ownership or fairness of the games. For example, no one makes
sure that virtual slot machines occasionally pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Other supporters of the ban agree. ``Legalized online gambling
is legalized stealing,'' Christian Coalition spokesman Arne Owens
said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, however, argue that the bill is toothless and will do
little to dissuade online gambling ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's being proposed here is outright prohibition without any
attempt at regulation,'' said Sue Schneider, chairwoman of the
Interactive Gaming Council, a group promoting online gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Internet providers, who would bear the brunt of implementing
blocks against gambling sites, also protested the legislation. ``We
adamantly oppose the idea of turning ISPs into online traffic
cops,'' said Justin Newton, public policy director of the ISP
Consortium, a Minneapolis-based organization that represents 300
Internet service providers worldwide. ``It is technologically
impossible to track all the content that travels over our online
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said enforcement of the legislation could be
equally troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the California attorney general's office in
Sacramento acknowledged it would be difficult to pinpoint
individuals gambling online.
</P>
<P>
   And Sebastian Sinclair, an analyst with Christiansen Cummings
Associates, a New York gambling consulting firm, said the
governments of Antigua, the Dominican Republic and other offshore
gambling hotbeds have shown no willingness to extradite individuals
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many in the online gambling industry said the
legislation will do little to damper the proliferation of virtual
casinos. The industry has mushroomed from a dozen companies a year
ago to about 140 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to gamble, they gamble. You can't wiretap and
monitor everyone's personal computer,'' said David Herschman, CEO
of Virtual Vegas in San Francisco, &UR;  &LR; which skirts the gambling laws
with a game-show format that rewards consumers with cash and
prizes. ``There is no way to enforce it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
