u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-NOTES-COX     07-23 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves concerned about conditioning
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Certain things about the Atlanta Falcons' first
practice of training camp were predictable. It was hot, and things
were ugly from time to time as players went through a 2 1/2-hour
practice Thursday afternoon in Suwanee. All 80 players were
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good first day,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``I thought
we handled the heat pretty well. We looked a little ragged on
offense, but I didn't see anything that upset me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was concerned, however, that some players appeared to be
laboring more than he felt they should. During sprints, a few
players clearly struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see some guys in better condition,'' Reeves said.
``Some guys, like (tight end) O.J. Santiago, (rookie wide receiver)
Tim Dwight and (wide receiver) Terance Mathis, those guys can run
forever. But we've got some guys who need some work. We don't want
to be losing games because we're not in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler said, ``It was good. Guys were really
excited. We need to keep that going for two or three weeks.
Sometimes, that gets pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   On deck
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will have two practices today, from 9 a.m. to 11:30,
and from 3 p.m. to 5:30. They like will have two practices Saturday
as well, at the same times. Practices are open to the public, at
team headquarters, at Exit 44 off Interstate 85. Tomorrow is likely
to be the only Saturday of training camp, and team officials are
encouraging fans to bring the family, enjoy interactive games
adjacent to the practice fields, and have lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Turning up the heat
</P>
<P>
   When practice started, it was 93 degrees with a relatively
modest 43 percent humidity. Wispy clouds seemed to dim the effects
of the sun, and there even was an occasional breeze. ``This is a
vacation compared to Miami,'' said rookie wide receiver Jammi
German, who played at Miami (Fla.). ``Man, sometimes you just
couldn't hardly even breathe down there.'' Still, it was hot.
Mathis said, ``I wish this practice had been in the morning.
Tomorrow, it will be more intense. This time tomorrow, I think guys
will be a lot more sore.''
</P>
<P>
   QB watch
</P>
<P>
   In a variety of settings, including passing drills, 9-on-9
scrimmages, and a limited amount of 11-on-11 scrimmages (with full
contact, but no tackling), Chandler got all the snaps with the No.
1 unit, second-year man Tony Graziani got all the snaps with the
No. 2 unit, and Steve DeBerg all the snaps with the No. 3 unit.
Each man received the same amount of snaps. Rookie free agent Brian
Brennan spent most of the afternoon working elsewhere, for example
taking snaps from centers while offensive and defensive linemen
practiced technique. DeBerg's first pass was intercepted, but
through no fault of his own. It bounced off the hands of receiver
Kevin Thornal, who was on the practice squad last year, and
linebacker Ruffin Hamilton picked it off. In 11-on-11 drills,
Graziani was intercepted by safety Marcus Wimberly, who returned it
45 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Boon and bust
</P>
<P>
   There were quite a few dropped passes Thursday, and play was
generally spotty, which is to be expected for the first couple
days. There were NFL officials working some of the scrimmage
situations and first-string right tackle Corey Louchiey jumped
offsides on Chandler's first call. ... Defensive line coach Bill
Kollar was, as usual, the loudest coach. Very early in a drill, he
yelled at one foursome, ``Alright, go back and do it again. We need
to get on the same (expletive) page. This isn't for fun anymore; it
all counts now. It's for real.'' ... Tailback Jamal Anderson
fumbled on the final play of the 11-on-11s, with defensive end
Lester Archambeau recovering in the backfield. . . . Weakside
linebacker Cornelius Bennett made a nice play on a swing pass to
fullback Bob Christian, running the play down from the opposite
side of the field.
</P>
<P>
   What he said
</P>
<P>
   ``I got killed today; I was getting rocked. I was sliding and
shuffling my feet all over the place. But the good thing about
looking bad the first day is that there's a lot of room for
improvement. You can only look better.'' _ Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   In order to hydrate all 80 players and dozens more team
officials, the Falcons purchased 200 cases of bottled water, 300
cases of bottled juices and 100 cases of sports drink for the first
five days or so. Players take all their meals in the Falcon Inn
adjacent to the practice fields. All players stay there during
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   All 80 players passed physicals Thursday, and there were no
serious injuries. There were, however, and few nicks and dings that
might limit players in what they can do today. Starting right guard
Gene Williams suffered a back strain. Other injuries: backup guard
Scott Adams (strained hamstring), Mathis (back spasms), reserve
defensive tackle Nathan Davis (stomach illness).
</P>
<P>
   Home cooking
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the 13 players with connections to the state of
Georgia stood out. Linebacker Ben Talley, a Griffin native who is
trying to comeback from a horrible knee injury suffered in the '96
preseason with the New York Giants, was in the right place at the
right time on a couple of occasions, filling holes and defending a
pass. ... Running back Gary Downs, a Columbus native, made a few
nice blocks while working at fullback. The only players listed on
the roster as fullbacks are Christian and rookie free agent Darren
Fisk of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Quick money
</P>
<P>
   There are only two Falcons who have reporting bonuses written
into their contracts. Second-year linebacker Henri Crockett made
$6,000 by showing up Thursday, and Anderson earned $25,000.
Anderson's bonus actually is tied to his weight upon returning. He
has to show up weighing less than 240 pounds. Thursday morning when
players were weighed, he checked in at 238. Anderson did not,
however, earn his $25,000 offseason workout bonus, which required
that he be present for 51 of 64 supervised workouts in Suwanee.
Anderson's deal was worked out by former Falcon officials. ``They
wanted to make the whole thing (a $50,000 bonus) connected to
workouts,'' said Anderson, who lives in Salt Lake City in the
offseason. ``But I said, `Come on guys, I don't live here in the
offseason so I can't be here. Let's do at least part of it so I can
be rewarded for working out on my own. If I show up less than 240,
you'll know I've been working out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Et cetera
</P>
<P>
   The eighth annual Falcons/Red Cross Blood Drive will be today
and Saturday. Every donor will receive a pair of free tickets to
the team's preseason opener at the Georgia Dome, Aug. 7 against the
Tennessee Oilers. Blood can be donated in Suwanee, North Point
Mall, Gwinnett Place Mall, Town Center Mall, Northlake Mall and
Shannon Mall. ... Individual tickets to regular season games are
now available at the Georgia Dome or from Ticketmaster at
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
