<HEADLINE>
IS RETIREMENT IN JOE TORRE'S FUTURE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are moments, private and public, when Joe Torre
ponders the future and wonders if he wants to manage the Yankees
next season. The thoughts flash by swiftly because Torre is too
busy orchestrating what has been an amazing season and is still
trying to insure that it finishes with a flourish in October.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the moments exist, sneaking up on Torre: when he misses
sharing a quiet dinner with his wife, Ali. Or when he misses
hearing the newest song his 2{-year-old daughter, Andrea Rae, has
learned. Or when a reporter suddenly inquires about 1999 while
Torre is still engrossed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees continue their blinding pace and set a
major-league record for victories in the regular season and then
motor through the postseason to win their second World Series in
three years, would Torre, who is 58, consider resigning? Would he
stroll away as a two-time champion and become a full-time husband
and father?
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I wasn't having as much fun,'' Torre said. ``This
year, I'm having fun doing this. As long as it's fun, I'll keep
doing it. If it's not fun anymore, I'll leave. I don't know when
that will be. Right now, I want to do it for a few more years. But
that could change in a month.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a trace of uncertainty in Torre's voice, perhaps just
enough doubt to make the managerial watch a bit more intriguing in
November if the Yankees cooperate in October. After Torre steered
the Yankees to a championship in his first season as manager in
1996, a journey that was fraught with inspirational stories, his
wife asked him to quit and leave while he was on top.
</P>
<P>
   Torre had waited 4,268 games as a superb player and an
underrated manager to reach postseason play and finally had a World
Series ring. So Ali Torre wanted him home. Instead, he wanted to
defend a title and signed a revised three-year, $2.8 million
contract. So this season could be deja vu all over again in the
Torre household.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is still doing that,'' Torre said. ``My wife would
like me to quit. She doesn't tell me that on a daily basis, but she
does feel that way. She wouldn't want to insist that I quit. She
knows I wouldn't be happy if I did that right now. She's the most
unselfish person I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali Torre chuckled over her car phone after being told her
husband had described her as very unselfish. She insisted that her
unselfishness stretches only to a certain degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I would like to have him around a little more
often,'' said Ali Torre, 40. ``I miss his companionship. I've been
with him a long time. There are things that he wants to do
professionally, and I wouldn't want to put a damper on what he's
doing this year. He's happy doing what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But she paused and added: ``I'd be very happy when he decides
he's had enough. For now, he's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   They two met at a hotel bar in Cincinnati where Ali was a
waitress in 1981 when he was managing the Mets. They were married
in 1987. For now, Ali Torre expressed strong support for his
pursuit of another World Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'll feel the same way in six months,'' she
said. ``I do go through the dog days when I miss him. I don't know
if I thought this was taking him away from me, I might say that
it's time to stop. If I really needed him or our daughter needed
him to stay together, at some point, I might have to say that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Torre said he was thankful for his daughter because his
wife focused on her while he was immersed in the Yankees, Ali Torre
conceded that his daughter missed her father when he was on the
road. She blows kisses to Torre on television and shouts, ``Let's
go, Yankees.'' But Ali Torre was bothered last week when she told
Andrea that her father would be home the next day and the child
responded, ``Then he's just going to leave again.'' ``How do you
answer that?'' Ali Torre asked. ``I didn't know what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who has three grown children from two previous marriages,
acknowledged that Ali and Andrea's well-being would be the major
factor that could influence him to cease managing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from spending more time with my wife, being with my
daughter more is the one area that could make me do something,''
Torre said. ``I miss things.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees win again, there are merits both for staying and
leaving. Torre, who will earn $1 million for managing this year and
is scheduled to make $1 million in 1999, could decide to imitate
Phil Jackson and Jerry Seinfeld by leaving while he is king. Torre
could also decide that a title in 1998 means there is reason to
stay in the Bronx and try to win it all again in 1999. The more
championships Torre gets, the more he enhances his growing
credentials as a player-manager entry for the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go to the World Series and win a World Series and if I'm
still energized by it the way that I am now, I'd want to do it a
few times,'' Torre said. ``When you leave the game after finishing
first, you're going out as a champion. Being a champion, you always
have that under your belt.''
</P>
<P>
   In one breath, Torre sounded like a manager who would return in
1999. In the next, he sounded like one who would consider it
special to leave a game he has been in since 1960 with the newest,
shiniest ring on his finger. When Torre was asked if he really
envisioned himself managing a few more years if he were energized
by it, he hedged slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that way today,'' Torre said. ``I'm enjoying this
period. Whether it's because of what we're doing or the people
we're doing this with, I'm enjoying it. I don't know if that will
change or if that will be the case in another year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
