<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' fiery first day
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When Keith Brooking's big day finally arrived, he was
pumped. He was so excited, in fact, that the Falcons' rookie
linebacker from Georgia Tech got in the first fight of training
camp in the first full-contact drill of the first practice .
</P>
<P>
   That was the type of excitement generated all over the field in
Suwanee on Thursday, as coach Dan Reeves began his second training
camp with the Falcons. Eighty players are competing for 53 roster
spots.
</P>
<P>
   But Brooking's 45-second scrap with tight end O.J. Santiago took
center stage. It took several players and coaches to break up the
melee,which ended with Santiago, a second-year tight end, jawing
from afar: ``Don't be showing off for all the cameras. You're a
first-round pick, and everybody's watching you.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there were cameras _ and players _ around. Dozens of
media representatives were present. There also were approximately
60-75 fans on the hill overlooking the practice field, many only 60
yards from the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The 93-degree heat, 43-percent humidity and broiling sun were
enough to get tempers going. But throw in Brooking, who has been
openly eager to put the pads on after almost six weeks of drills in
shorts, jerseys and helmets, you get a very combustible mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things got a little hot,'' said Brooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have been wanting to hit somebody; it's been a long
time since I've been in pads. In a situation like that, the first
drill, the adrenaline was flowing, and I got a little carried away,
a little out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   After practice, both players cooled down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I'm going to do is go in the lockerroom and
apologize,'' Brooking said. ``That's part of football, and that
stuff stays on the field.'' Santiago agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider it a big deal,'' he said. ``We're
competitive. Some people might say, `You win some, you lose some.'
I say, `You win some, and hate to lose any.' It's part of the game.
It's over. We'll be cool.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day that was predictably ragged at times, Reeves was by no
means unhappy about the scrap, which came just a few snaps after
veteran defensive end Chuck Smith yelled at veteran offensive
tackle Bob Whitfield in the same drill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to happen when you start hitting the first time,''
Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The first hit of camp had nothing to do with physical contact.
Safety Devin Bush sported wild socks, which featured black and
white horizontal stripes nearly up to his knees. His teammates were
calling him ``Beetlejuice.''
</P>
<P>
   After about an hour of warmups and drills, the contact drill was
clearly the highlight of a 2 1/2-hour practice.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking and Santiago got tied up in a one-on-one blocking and
tackling drill where an offensive player blocks a defender as a
back tries to scoot through a hole three yards wide.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago blew Brooking out with a solid block, and when Brooking
thought Santiago kept going after the whistle, they locked up. Once
separated, Santiago went after Brooking, yelling all the while.
Santiago's helmet was torn off the the process, and he ended up
with a scratch near his left eye though nobody landed any solid
blows. The Falcons, who have had seven winning seasons in 32 years,
will practice today at 9 a.m. and 3 p.m. as they prepare for the
season opener on Sept. 6 at Carolina. The Falcons will play
Tennessee in the first preseason game on Aug. 7 in the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of nice,'' Reeves said of the tension in the air.
``You got a couple guys with the temperment it takes to play
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
