<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beat-up Braves down to one catcher
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Reserve catcher Eddie Perez left the team
Thursday morning to return to Atlanta, where his wife Marisol
underwent emergency gall bladder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was expected to rejoin the team tonight in Pittsburgh,
the club played the Phillies with a prevailing numbers problem.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Michael Tucker was scratched two hours before
gametime due to a tender ankle sustained running the bases
Wednesday night. Infielders Walt Weiss (left quadriceps) and Tony
Graffanino (stiff neck) were available on emergency basis, giving
the club just 10 position players at 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But foremost, Perez's absence left manager Bobby Cox with just
one catcher. Cox has traditionally carried just two catchers,
though he typically designates a candidate for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who his emergency catcher is currently, Cox replied, ``I
don't know. We don't have one. We got Graff, (Keith) Lockhart, and
(Ozzie) Guillen. I figure one of those could strap it on.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation did not faze Javy Lopez, who said, ``I'm going to
keep going. If I get hurt, I get hurt, either catching or hitting.
I cannot think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox's best bet for back-up help may have been in the bullpen.
Reliever Russ Springer keeps a complete set of catching gear at his
Louisiana home and uses it for offseason training.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker jammed his ankle in his second at-bat Wednesday, when he
raced pitcher Yorkis Perez to first base and jammed his foot into
the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Though he remained in the game and later hit a triple, his left
ankle had stiffened by the time he reported to the clubhouse
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A lesson learned?
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle's next start does not fall until Saturday night but
the left-hander used his bullpen session Thursday (the second of
two during his off-days) to shake off the worst start of his career
(nine runs in four innings against Chicago last Monday).
</P>
<P>
   Worried about the effectiveness of his change-up and simply
forgetting to use his breaking ball, Neagle blamed the Chicago
outing on mental shortcomings as much as physical ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to pitch like Nolan Ryan without a Nolan Ryan
fastball,'' he said. ``That's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 103 pitches he threw that night, Neagle estimated he
threw just 15 offspeed pitches, when his optimum mix is 25 percent
changeups and 20 percent breaking balls.
</P>
<P>
   He admits to being scared to throw the changeup, though he has
seen improvement in the pitch in his side sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Tecnincally, his problems have stemmed from too much twist at
the hip during windup and then not staying on top of the pitch as
he releases it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things,'' Neagle said. ``One, I'm getting to the point
where now I feel I've made a good correction that I'm going to feel
a lot more confident in my changeup this game. And the other thing
is mentally, making better pitch selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither side wanted to overemphasize what Mark Wohlers did
Wednesday night, but the fact that the right-hander retired the
side in order _ in just 11 pitches _ was the first encouraging
signal Wohlers has sent in a month.
</P>
<P>
   He threw first-pitch strikes to all three men he faced, threw
one effective split-finger fastball at 92 mph and said later his
concentration on his fastball is not the most effective way to
approach each outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concentrating on trying to get guys out instead of going
out there to try and prove I can throw my fastball for a strike,''
he said. ``Yeah, I'd like to throw more fastballs but I can be more
effective when I work more on getting outs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
