<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-DIVING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bryant trying to make her move to Moultrie pay off
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Katie Beth Bryant can only go so high in the
diving world in her best event. She's a 1-meter specialist in a
sport that welcomes only the higher 3-meter springboard event at
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, 18, who trains in Moultrie, finished seventh Thursday at
the Goodwill Games among 10 divers, the best of whom was Irini
Lashko of Russia. Bryant placed second among the four Americans.
Bryant said she prefers the 1-meter ``because it's lower to the
water, which means it's harder to finish your dives. I just like
the feeling of jumping, flipping as fast and as high as I can, and
see if I make it in.''
</P>
<P>
   The low board has tried to make it into the Olympics for years.
The World Championships accepted the event for men and women in
1991, but the Olympics has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Women's water polo is the only new aquatic event on the program
for Sydney in 2000, and the relatively new events of synchronized
diving from the 3-meter and 10-meter platforms may be next in line
because they are considered more spectator- and
television-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its limitations, Bryant said she's happy to stay with
1-meter ``as long as I can keep being internationally competitive.
This is so much fun, I can settle for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Before every dive Thursday, she smiled and blew kisses to
friends and family in the crowd. Her family, including her two
brothers and two sisters, arrived from Chatham, Ill. to cheer her
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm all serious and sad, I don't dive well,'' said Bryant,
who will attend LSU on a diving scholarship. ``I do best when I'm
relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant took up diving after giving up gymnastics. ``To me, it
seemed a little easier on your body,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest child, she left Chatham in 1995 when her coach moved
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that the best place in the United States to train
was Moultrie, Ga., so that's where I've been for three years,'' she
said. ``And they proved it to me. They're the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant describes Moultrie as ``a small town in South Georgia
with a big wonderful pool.''
</P>
<P>
   She represents Moss Farms Diving and lives on a farm with Scott
and Virginia Hart, whose son dives at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Now when Bryant goes back to Illinois, she said, ``They make fun
of me for saying y'all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
