</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-HUMMER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glover and Jones take cautious bite of the Big Apple
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- Times Square has been sanitized for your protection,
but there remain stubborn pockets of resistance. Hence, it took but
one stroll around their team hotel for Dion Glover and Jumaine
Jones to receive a primer in the weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a cross-dresser right away. That's been the strangest
thing so far,'' said Glover.
</P>
<P>
   The educational experiences of these Goodwill Games for the two
Georgia representatives on the U.S. basketball team have been
many-pronged.
</P>
<P>
   They have been lectured on the dangers of being big targets in a
tough city. Not that any of them have had a whole lot of time to
get out among 'em. Otherwise occupied by practices and games, many
sights go unseen.
</P>
<P>
   They have been offered a varied diet of international flavor. A
couple of 19-year-olds, however, are not going to heed all the
lessons of good nutrition. ''I just want a home-cooked meal,''
Glover said. ''I end up going to McDonald's almost every day.''
</P>
<P>
   A friendship has been further strengthened between Georgia
Tech's Glover and Georgia's Jones _ they'll leave it to the
graduates to keep hate alive. The two always seem paired. They came
up as the state's two dominant players, Glover from Decatur and
Jones from Camilla. They played AAU ball together, went through the
recruiting gristmill together and then found themselves among the
collegians selected to go against the world here at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   They're not Goodwill roommates, ''but we might as well be, we
spend so much time in each other's rooms,'' Glover said.
</P>
<P>
   In the pure basketball sense, they entered Thursday night's
semifinal against Lithuania still riding the international
basketball learning curve. Because of the U.S. team's need for
size, the 6-7 Jones has gotten a little more playing time (an
average of 23 minutes in first the three games) than shooting guard
Glover (16 minutes per). Jones was averaging seven points and three
rebounds a game; Glover nine and two.
</P>
<P>
   They both should return to their campuses a little hardened by
the experience. The calluses began forming in their first Goodwill
game, an 84-76 loss to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot different than college ball,'' Jones said. ''There
was a lot more banging than I expected. There's a lot more Dennis
Rodmans here (in terms of physical play, not appearance). Coach
Haskins (Clem, the USA's head man) has been on me to get a lot
tougher, more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And these guys just don't miss open shots. You leave anyone
open, they're going to hit it,'' Glover said. He tussled with
Puerto Rico guard Eddie Casiano in the first game and lost (Casiano
ended with 31 points, Glover just six on 2-of-7 shooting). But
Glover (13 points on 5-of-6 from the field) was a key during the
U.S. blowout of Brazil Tuesday that got them to the medal round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really come together. We were passing the ball much
better, playing like more of a team. That first game we were a
bunch of individuals,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   That much accomplished, it is time to think about things more
familiar. Atlanta and Athens beckon. ''Yeah, I'm getting a little
homesick,'' Jones said. How much more Goodwill, after all, can a
body take?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
