<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-TRACK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good night at the track
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Before the lights dimmed on a final night at
the track venue, Michael Johnson anchored the men's 1,600-meter
relay to a world record and Jackie Joyner-Kersee staggered home to
a gold medal in her final heptathlon Wednesday. Imagine that.
Nobody talked up the possibility of a world mark _ dipping into Ted
Turner's pocket for a $100,000 bonus _ and the 36-year-old JJK
hadn't finished a heptathlon since the 1996 Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men lowered the world mark to 2 minutes, 54.20 seconds,
breaking the record of 2:54.29 that Johnson also anchored at the
1993 World Championships. Jerome Young (44.4) sprinted to the lead
before Macon native Antonio Pettigrew (43.2) and Tyree Washington
(43.5) stretched the cushion to 30 meters when Johnson (43.1)
touched the baton. After Young's extremely fast start from a
standstill, the rest of the team knew that with their running
starts a record was possible. ``I didn't want to let these guys
down,'' said Johnson, beaming. Minutes after the record,
Joyner-Kersee finished sixth in the heptathlon's closing 800 meters
_ but less than two seconds behind Dedee Nathan, who needed to beat
her by three seconds for victory. ``Everybody was saying I was
going to quit (the 800),'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``When people were
cheering me when I came on the track, I thought I was going to
break down and cry but I had to run the 800.'' Overshadowed
Wednesday was redemption for the men's 400-meter relay team, which
failed to get the baton around the track at the last two World
Championships and was second to the Canadians at the Atlanta Games
_ the only U.S. Olympics loss. Maurice Greene held off a charge
from Canadian anchor Donovan Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women lost the 1,600-meter relay to Jamaica, while the
400-meter team nipped a Bahamas group that featured Atlanta
resident Pauline Davis and University of Georgia senior Debbie
Ferguson. The Americans won in the year's fastest time of 42.06.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
