<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAWLEY FAILS TO APPEAR AT TRIAL OF HER FORMER ADVISERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ More than a decade after she frustrated
investigators by refusing to testify about her allegations of
abduction and rape, Tawana Brawley failed to appear in court
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She has never testified under oath about her sketchy account of
being assaulted and held captive by a group of white men over four
days in 1987. Her absence Thursday exposed a deep rift among her
advisers in the final days of the defamation case brought against
them by Steven Pagones, the white former prosecutor they accused of
raping Brawley, a black teen-ager. The question of what damages to
assess could go to the jury as soon as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Brawley, now 26, was a sharp embarrassment to C.
Vernon Mason, the adviser who broke with his co-defendant, Alton H.
Maddox Jr., and invited Brawley to end her silence here, in the
damages portion of the case in which the jurors have already
determined that her story was false.
</P>
<P>
   The trial here was ``God's opportunity to correct history,''
Mason told a throng of reporters drawn by his promise that she
would take the stand. ``For all these years,'' he said, ``people
who care about her have wanted to share her story.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason stopped short of criticizing Brawley for failing to
appear. But it was clear that by inviting her so publicly he had
violated the central premise of the advisers that has won them
staunch backing from a core of supporters: to keep Brawley away
from the storm her account caused.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the courtroom, Mason's lawyer, Stephen Jackson, said he
was disappointed because her testimony was ``important to the
community'' in a case that drew national attention. Brawley was 15
when she was found Nov. 28, 1987, in a plastic bag with excrement
spread on her body and racial epithets etched on her skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke about the importance to the community,'' Jackson said,
``not only the African-American community, but the community at
large. I think it's important that Tawana come to court and bring
some closure to what has attracted some controversy and what has
caused all this damage and wreaked havoc to people's personal
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did not make it clear whether he was referring to havoc
in the lives of Pagones, who says he was anguished by baseless
charges, or Mason, who was disbarred in 1995. Mason has said that
he stands by his assertions that Pagones kidnapped, raped and
sodomized Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also addressed the strains within the defense that have
been obvious in recent days. Maddox had said he would not join in
calling Brawley and doubted Mason could produce her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my position that she should be here,'' Jackson said
Thursday. ``I don't understand why others would feel otherwise. But
so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the defense table, Maddox, who was suspended from law
practice because of the Brawley case, sat next to his old ally,
Mason. They did not speak. Both looked out to the well of the
courtroom, where they have spent more than eight months fighting
what may be their last case together.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Pagones'lawyer, William Stanton, was
asked what question he would have liked answered had Brawley
appeared. The question, he said, would be ``Why did she do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Pagones, 37, said, ``This is a fitting end to this entire
fiasco.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday's events marked the end of a perplexing chapter in the
Brawley trial. It remained unclear, for example, why Jackson had
said earlier this week that Brawley would appear. It was also
unclear whether Mason had risked a schism in the defense to argue
that he should be assessed lower damages than the other defendants
because he alone had tried to obtain Brawley's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Court was scheduled to begin Thursday morning at 9:30. Twenty
minutes later, with scores of reporters milling about in front of
the Dutchess County Courthouse, Jackson and Mason walked into the
crowd without the other members of the defense team and, more
notably, without Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two days, they had faced increasing skepticism here
as fraudulent Brawley sightings were reported in Poughkeepsie.
``Where's Tawana?'' someone shouted Thursday morning as Jackson and
Mason moved toward a forest of microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he and Mason had worked for 48 hours to bring
Brawley as a witness. He said he had spoken to Brawley's mother,
who ``did raise some issues'' about whether her daughter should
testify.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson said he had not had enough time to contact Brawley.
He said she was at an ``undisclosed location'' because reporters
had been pursuing her since July 13, when the jury ruled that
Pagones was defamed by the advisers, Mason, Maddox and the Rev. Al
Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Brawley's mother did not know where she was.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters then followed Mason and Jackson into the
courtroom. There, with the jury assembled, Jackson said he had been
working ``feverishly in an attempt to get her up here'' and began
telling the jurors that it was important for history that they hear
her.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton objected, saying Jackson was trying to influence the
jury. Justice S. Barrett Hickman of State Supreme Court directed
him to complete his explanation after the jurors had left the room.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few minutes, the defense had rested its case, setting
the stage for the final arguments on damages.
</P>
<P>
   When the jury had been excused, Jackson delivered his full
remarks and asked for more time to try to arrange Brawley's
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman denied the request. ``She's had 10 and a half years,''
he said, ``to come and tell somebody under oath what her story
is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
