<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Merger to Mean the End of Pacific Exchange as We Know It   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
So long ``P-Coast.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   To traders around the world, the options floor in the historic
Mills Building at 220 Montgomery St. has been affectionately
referred to as the ``P-Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Chicago Board Options Exchange, the offspring of
the mother of all commodities markets, the 150-year-old Chicago
Board of Trade, has been rather unimaginatively tagged the
``C-Boe.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Philadelphia Stock Exchange _ which is itself
merging with the American Stock Exchange and Nasdaq _ was called
the ``Philly.'' (What else?) And before it was absorbed by another
exchange, the New York Stock Exchange's options offshoot was
nicknamed the ``Knife.'' Well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   So, what new moniker will come from the proposed marriage of the
P-Coast and the C-Boe is anybody's guess. (My vote goes to PCBOE,
or ``Placebo.'' Or how about the Surf Board Options Exchange, or
SoBoe?)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the new merged entity is called, you can be assured it
will mark the end of California's revered Pacific Exchange as we
know it.
</P>
<P>
   The name issue ``is an open question,'' says Thomas Ascher, vice
chairman of the CBOE and an independent market maker.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the clear intent is to have one institution,'' Ascher
says.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was inevitable. Technology is forcing stock and
futures exchanges all over the world to consider drastic change,
such as mergers with competitors and the adoption of electronic
trading systems.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the AMEX-Nasdaq-Philly combination provided the wake-up
call for Montgomery Street to get down to brass tacks with LaSalle
Street, the heart and soul of Chicago's financial district in the
south Loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly sharpened everybody's focus'' to negotiate more
arduously toward a marriage, Ascher says.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, officials from the two exchanges engaged in
marathon meetings at Chicago's Standard Club, a prestigious social
club just a stone's throw from LaSalle. The negotiations continued
with unglamorous talks held at the terminal building of Denver
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid and profound changes in the financial landscape across the
Atlantic also applied pressure to make a deal. The advent of a more
integrated Europe had forged heated new competition for American
exchanges. Plus, French and German exchanges were aggressively
experimenting with electronic trading systems that challenged the
future of traditional open-outcry systems, which are still used in
Chicago and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Deutsche Terminborse, or DTB, wrangled a big chunk of
futures business away from London exchanges earlier this year by
implementing electronic trading.
</P>
<P>
   Such dramatic transformations made it clear that the Pacific
Exchange needed to do something quickly. About 80 percent of all
transactions at the CBOE are electronic, thanks largely to computer
trading systems that are more advanced than those currently used at
the Pacific Exchange. But only 20 percent of all transactions are
paperless at the Montgomery Street exchange, says Robert Kovell,
vice chairman of the Pacific Exchange and principal of Kovell
Trading LLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is driving the deal. We've spent a great deal of
money duplicating the efforts of the CBOE in regards to
technology,'' Kovell says.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved by the members of each exchange, the
Pacific Exchange will be able to share Chicago's technology and
upgrade its operations more quickly and efficiently, Kovell says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many loose ends remain untied. Will the new entity still
build a new facility South of Market or will it move to existing
space currently occupied by BankAmerica?
</P>
<P>
   And what will happen to the Pacific Exchange's sleepy stock
trading operations? Is the exchange's downtown Los Angeles floor
history, or will both equity trading floors get spun-off and merged
with other stock markets?
</P>
<P>
   Both Ascher and Kovell say the combined memberships will need to
resolve these issues. But one thing is certain, an options floor
will remain in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And that's welcome news to trader Karim Tahawi, who left the
City of Broad Shoulders for the Barbary Coast four years ago. He
froze his assets off in Chicago and doesn't want to go back.
``There are a lot of people who are here because they didn't want
to live in New York or Chicago,'' Tahawi says.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like they still won't have to.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF 94103,
by phone at 415-777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
