u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-620&AMP;ADD     07-23 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF OF SECRET SERVICE WHITE HOUSE DETAIL TESTIFIES BEFORE GRAND
JURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's personal bodyguard, Larry
Cockell, and Harold Ickes, a former senior White House aide,
testified on Thursday before the federal grand jury that is
investigating the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   On an unusually busy day at the federal courthouse near Capitol
Hill, three uniformed officers also testified, presumably about
what they had seen and heard while working in the West Wing of the
White House. The five men appeared before two grand juries, another
sign that the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, has
accelerated his six-month-old inquiry of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Cockell and Ickes have much in common: Their jobs required them
to spend many hours with Clinton, and both earned the president's
trust and confidence. But there is an important distinction in
their roles. As the Secret Service agent in charge of the
president's security detail, Cockell is charged with protecting and
defending Clinton's personal safety. But the president's political
survival was, and still is, the central mission of Ickes, first as
a deputy White House chief of staff and in recent months as an
unofficial adviser during the current inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Cockell's long-awaited testimony, which lasted precisely one
hour on Thursday afternoon, was made possible last Friday when
Chief Justice William Rehnquist denied a Justice Department request
to block Secret Service agents from testifying. Cockell's lawyer,
John Kotelly, told reporters that his client had very little
information about conversations the president had with Ms. Lewinsky
or his aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases where, you know, he's in private situations, secure
situations, like the White House, the president has privacy, and
the Secret Service respects that privacy,'' said Kotelly, who
declined to say what his client had told the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Kotelly said Cockell, who asked to be temporarily relieved from
his assignment last week, is eager to resume his usual duties,
though he is concerned the media attention will undermine his
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not be able to have the same type of anonymity he had
before, and obviously he regrets losing that anonymity because in
some ways it affects his ability to do his job in protecting the
president,'' Kotelly said. He added that that Cockell's superiors
had not decided when or if he would resume his position as the
chief of the president's protective detail.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes, a surprise witness, testified for about 25 minutes late
on Thursday, apparently before another grand jury. Before stepping
into a taxi, he said he did not relish the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't enjoy it, but it's your civic duty,'' he said. Asked
what prosecutors had quizzed him about, he said simply: ``Name and
address.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview on Thursday night, Ickes said that he
expects to return for more questions next week or the following
week. He probably will be asked about his meetings and discussions
with White House aides and lawyers after it became known on Jan. 21
that Starr was investigating whether Clinton had tried to cover up
a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern who
celebrated her 25th birthday on Thursday with her family in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's appearance marked the second time that Ickes has
answered questions from a grand jury impaneled by Starr. In June,
Ickes testified before a grand jury in Alexandria, Va., where he
was asked about the Pentagon's improper disclosure of details from
Linda Tripp's personnel file to a writer for The New Yorker
magazine. Mrs. Tripp is the Pentagon employee who surreptitiously
recorded conversations with Ms. Lewinsky and gave them to Starr's
office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another matter, the District of Columbia Bar Association has
notified Starr's office that members of his staff, including chief
deputy Jackie M. Bennett Jr., are the subjects of an inquiry into
possible ethics violations, according to a person with knowledge of
the situation, which was first reported on Thursday in USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   The person said that the investigation involved work done in
Starr's inquiry of Clinton, possibly linked to accusations that the
office improperly leaked secret grand jury material to reporters.
On Tuesday, Starr's prosecutors asked a federal appeals court here
to overturn a decision by Judge Norma Holloway Johnson of U.S.
District Court to compel prosecutors to prove they did not
illegally disclose grand jury material.
</P>
</TEXT>
