<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-GOODWILL-NYT &LR;      07-23 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS BEGIN DRUG TREATMENT ON PARALYZED CHINESE GYMNAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ After an expedition through red tape, doctors
at the Nassau County Medical Center in adjacent East Meadow began
Thursday night to pour an experimental drug into the veins of Sang
Lan, 17, the Chinese gymnast, in hopes of alleviating her
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Sang sustained a severe spinal injury Tuesday night when she
landed on her head during a routine warmup vault in the Goodwill
Games at Nassau Coliseum. Before the drug treatment started, Dr.
Vincent Leone, who is treating Sang, said her condition had not
changed in the last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still guarded,'' said Leone, who heads the medical
center's division of orthopedic spinal surgery. ``She's in very
good spirits. She knows exactly what's going on and she understands
the severity of her condition. But neurologically there's not much
improvement yet. There's no lower motor function, and she still
can't feel from midchest down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to preserve as much arm function as possible. I'm
a little pessimistic about the lower extremities. Her head and her
upper neck have dislocated themselves from the lower neck and the
rest of the body. It's a credit to her physical condition that she
still has functioning in her upper extremities.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that the experimental drug GM-1, also known as
Sygen, will help restore functions. Although the same medication
helped Dennis Byrd, the former Jets defensive lineman, walk again
after a spinal injury in 1992, Sang was told it would not
necessarily improve her chances of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The patient must start receiving the drug within 72 hours of
injury, but approval to use the drug was needed from several
groups. The approvals came, first from the medical center's
institutional review board, then from Chinese officials, then from
the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Gulotta, the Nassau County executive, said officials
of Fidia Pharmaceuticals in Washington, which makes the drug,
refused at first to send the medication because it could not reach
the company president, who was on vacation. Gulotta said he
enlisted the help of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and the company
shipped the drug Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The drug will be administered over six weeks in an effort to
encourage damaged neurological tissues to grow again.
</P>
<P>
   Leone said that Sang would undergo surgery Saturday morning to
fuse the C-6 and C-7 vertebrae and implant metal stabilizers.
</P>
<P>
   Sang's parents are expected to arrive from China on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Leone said the American doctors had met with Chinese doctors and
discussed Eastern and Western treatments. He said Sang would
receive acupuncture treatment as well, here and in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very difficult case,'' Leone said. ``It's very
tricky when you're dealing with spinal-cord injuries. We will try
anything to get her to walk again. It's unlikely she will, but a
lot of things are in her favor.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
