<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-JDPOWER-SURVEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT, WORLDCOM TOP J.D. POWER SURVEY OF LONG-DISTANCE CUSTOMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Sprint and WorldCom took top marks among
long-distance telephone carriers serving Southland households in a
J.D. Power and Associates survey.
</P>
<P>
   In the annual customer-satisfaction study, released Thursday,
WorldCom scored highest among the region's mainstream households,
meaning those that made fewer than $50 worth of calls each month,
while Sprint appealed most to high-volume callers. SNET, a New
England-based carrier, scored highest overall among mainstream
households, but the company does not offer phone service in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Among the losers locally, GTE and MCI both scored below average
among mainstream households.
</P>
<P>
   The survey polled more than 14,000 households nationally about
their attitudes toward their long-distance carrier and toward the
industry as a whole. Customers ranked phone companies on their
reliability, trustworthiness and quality of service, among other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Dresch, director of telecommunications analysis at J.D.
Power, said the survey found nearly half of customers felt it was
difficult to find a phone company they could trust, while a
majority were skeptical that pending mergers between major phone
companies are in the customers' best interests.
</P>
<P>
   So leery were customers of long-distance carriers that many
based their choice more on a company's image than on pricing,
Dresch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the credibility factor,'' he said. ``Consumers want
honesty, no gimmicks, no hidden charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeding customer unease was the fact that one in 10 U.S.
households had been ``slammed'' in the past year. Slamming occurs
when a long-distance carrier switches a household to that carrier's
service without the customer's consent.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of customers who voluntarily switched
long-distance providers in the past year increased slightly to 30
percent of all U.S. households, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
