s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-TAX-LAW-$ADV26-     07-23 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-TAX-LAW-$ADV26-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW IRS LAW: A GUIDE TO SHIFTING BURDENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
(af) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taxpayers engaged in disputes with the Internal Revenue Service
will enjoy significant new protections under a bill that President
Clinton signed into law last week, including a requirement for
judicial review before a home can be seized to pay back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The law has been heralded as an ambitious attempt to reshape the
culture of a feared agency into one that is more consumer friendly.
It establishes an outside board with authority to oversee IRS
management and policies, and strengthens the role of the taxpayer
advocate, an internal ombudsman.
</P>
<P>
   The law also includes a tax cut of sorts, a provision that cuts
to 12 months from 18 months the period that investors must hold
stocks or other assets to qualify for the lowest capital gains tax
rate, now 20 percent for most people.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the House Ways and
Means Committee, and other sponsors of the legislation say its most
important protection is in the shift of the burden of proof, from
the taxpayer to the IRS, in cases that reach United States Tax
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Archer says this change is intended to make the agency treat
taxpayers with more respect, though the provision will directly
affect no more than one tax return in 4,500: only 28,000 or so
cases a year are brought in tax court, and individuals filed 122
million returns this year.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in the burden will apply only to those taxpayers who
have kept proper records and have cooperated fully in auditing
before the case reaches tax court. For taxpayers who prevail there,
the new measure will provide greater opportunities to recover
accounting and legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   Tax experts, however, say these changes will come at a price:
Because IRS auditors know they will have to prove their case if it
goes to court, they will make greater demands on audited taxpayers
to provide documentation to support their returns.
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions in the law raise the ceiling to $50,000, from
$10,000, for taxes in dispute in small-claims cases, in which
taxpayers typically represent themselves in tax court, and
authorize up to $6 million a year for tax clinics to help
low-income people with their returns.
</P>
<P>
   The law also vastly expands relief for joint filers who contend
that they were unaware of tax cheating by spouses. Taxpayers who
can establish that they are ``innocent spouses'' will be liable
only for taxes due on their own income; the rule will apply both to
new cases and to those now in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also bars contact between auditors and appeals
officers of the IRS unless the taxpayer is also present. And tax
agents must tell taxpayers if they are going to make contact with
third parties, like employers or neighbors, except in criminal
cases or where the agency has reason to believe that such a notice
will allow a taxpayer to hide assets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, so-called financial reality audits _ those of
people who have lavish life styles but report modest incomes _ will
be restricted to cases in which the agency has ``reasonable
indications'' of unreported income. Until now, the IRS has had
almost unlimited authority to conduct such audits.
</P>
<P>
   New rules will also apply to property seizures, a step the IRS
takes about 10,000 times a year. In addition to requiring judicial
review before the principal residence of a delinquent taxpayer or
any member of his immediate family can be seized, the legislation
prohibits seizure of a home when $5,000 or less is owed.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also makes IRS collection agents subject to laws
similar to those that bar private collection agents from making
harassing or abusive telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the interest rate for taxpayers who are owed refunds
for more than 45 days will be increased by one percentage point _
the rate itself varies with the general level of interest rates _
to match the rate that the government charges those who underpay or
whose payments are past due.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, the chief tax writer in the House, said the new law
``gives David the taxpayer a stronger slingshot to use against
Goliath, the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, though the law has been praised for easing strains on
honest taxpayers caught up in disputes, it has been criticized on
another front: It will help tax cheats, two former tax
commissioners say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes will make it more difficult and more expensive to
enforce the tax laws against people who don't pay,'' said Donald C.
Alexander, who was IRS commissioner in the Nixon and Ford
administrations. ``And unless Congress provides more funds for
enforcement, which it won't, then these changes will help some
people get away with not paying.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon S. Cohen, who was IRS commissioner in the Johnson
administration, agreed. ``Every time you give a deadbeat a break,''
Cohen said, ``it hurts me, because I pay my taxes promptly and
honestly and those who do are being shortchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee A. Sheppard, who critiques tax policy for the magazine Tax
Notes, said the bill would so hamper IRS enforcement and collection
efforts that it ``should be called the mobsters and drug dealers
tax relief act.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
