<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDE NEARS END FOR ZANARDI FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Alex Zanardi said he became one of us with his
victory at last year's U.S. 500 at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   A Formula One expatriate, expert at beating opponents into and
out of the curves, the Italian driver had struggled in his early
races on American speedways. Though he had won six races in just
over a year and a half on the Championship Auto Racing Teams
circuit, none of the victories had come on the big ovals. In fact,
his average finish on the speedways was 12th and he had never made
the top three.
</P>
<P>
   Zanardi felt that to earn acceptance on the American circuit, he
had to make a breakthrough and start doing well in the big-track
500-mile races.
</P>
<P>
   His win at Michigan last year accomplished that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to win that race was special,'' Zanardi said.
``(Americans) tend to judge you not only on how you do on the road
and street courses, but especially how you do on the ovals.... I
think I gained some of the hearts of the fans by winning on the
superspeedway. I became a little more American and a little less
Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   He also became nearly unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 starts this season, Zanardi has won five times, been
runner-up twice and finished third once. He has won the past four
races and will break a CART record for consecutive wins should he
triumph again at this year's U.S. 500 at Michigan on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He is perhaps the most aggressive driver on the CART tour, with
a style some of his opponents say borders on recklessness. He is
surely the most feared. No driver wants to see his No. 1 red Target
Chip Ganassi racer screaming up from the rear.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of outrunning the circuit this season, Zanardi is
on course _ with eight races remaining _ to challenge the season
victories record of eight set by Michael Andretti in 1991 and
matched by Al Unser Jr. in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And it is likely Zanardi will have his second straight CART
season points title in his hip pocket long before the tour's final
race at California Speedway on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't make the Fontana race an afterthought. It is
likely the event will be the final CART run for Zanardi, who has
said he would like to catch a ride with a major Formula One team
and return to his home in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that Zanardi likely will leave us on a track nearly
identical to the one in Michigan where he feels we embraced him _ a
superspeedway. And his departure will be a blow to American
open-wheel racing, struggling in the shadow of NASCAR to attract
fans, to lose a genuine star.
</P>
<P>
   So as the CART season plays out over its final eight races,
let's appreciate Alessandro Zanardi while we've got him.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he's one of us.
</P>
<P>
   Walk, don't run: Sunday's U.S. 500 will be the first CART race
run with the Handford Device, a square rear wing designed to slow
down the racers.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers became concerned about escalating speeds on the tour
last season after cars hit speeds in the lower 230 range at
Michigan and then went more than 240 at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   But Zanardi predicted whatever decrease comes with the new
device soon will be overcome by teams and drivers seeking an edge
over opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think when we get to Fontana at the end of the season,
we'll be back over 230 miles per hour,'' Zanardi said.
</P>
<P>
   Zanardi added that slowing the cars is the wrong approach. To
lower speeds, track owners must alter the tracks by making the
turns sharper, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Running on retreads: Lake Speed has resigned as driver of the
No. 9 Cartoon Network Winston Cup car and been replaced by Jerry
Nadeau, who was recently fired by the First Plus No. 13 team and
replaced by Wally Dallenback, who lost his ride in the No. 46 to
... well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Other Winston Cup changes include Ted Musgrave giving up his
seat in the Roush Racing No. 16 car to Kevin Lepage, who finished
second in Sunday's Busch Kenwood Home &AMP; Auto 300 at California
Speedway, next month. And Darrell Waltrip will move back into his
No. 17 car after subbing for Dale Earnhardt teammate Steve Park
during Park's recovery from injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey Night: The 58th annual USAC Turkey Night Midget Grand
Prix will be held in Bakersfield this season, where defending
champion and 1998 Indy 500 pole winner Billy Boat is expected to
defend his title.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Thanksgiving eve race has been an annual event since
its first run in 1934 at Gilmore Stadium in Los Angeles. It was
held at Ventura Raceway last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts and bolts: Barring a conflict with his Winston Cup effort,
look for Jeff Gordon to drive at next year's Busch race at
California Speedway. Gordon, his wife Brooke and crew chief Ray
Evernham plan to own a Busch Grand National team next year with
Gordon driving in a few races. Look for his sponsor to suggest _
strongly _ that one of them be in Fontana.... Winston Cup fans will
soon have the ability to listen to radio conversations between
drivers and their teams on their home computers. The broadcasts
will be reached at NASCAR.com and will cost $12.95.... Joe Gibbs,
who will be Tony Stewart's boss next year when the Indy Racing
League star moves to Winston Cup racing, has given Stewart
permission to run in the Indy 500 next year. Gibbs wants Stewart in
Charlotte, N.C., later in the day, however, to run in the Coca-Cola
600.... Sunday's Pennsylvania 500 begins a stretch of 16 straight
weeks of racing for Winston Cup teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
