<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0411 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STRIPPER-MEMOIRS-A     07-23 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STRIPPER-MEMOIRS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-STRIPPER REVEALS HERSELF, IN A MEMOIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sherry Britton, the onetime striptease star who at
age 80 has taken to calling herself Stripteasaurus Sex, has not
been following Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's attempts to clean up the
city's sex clubs. She's been too busy, working on her memoirs.
(``One thousand pages; think I need an editor?'' she asks
cheerfully.)
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Fiorello La Guardia's attempts to clean up the city she
remembers clearly.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1939 and Ms. Britton was working at Minsky's Gaiety, at
46th and Broadway, a theater that no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law was, you couldn't show pubic hair, and there was a
girl named Margie Hart who had bright red pubic hair,'' Ms. Britton
says, ``Bright red. She had a detective friend who would warn her
when the censors were coming around and she would wear a G-string.
Then she started seeing somebody else and he got jealous and didn't
warn her and they closed us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Britton chuckles. There is a dichotomy to her language.
Sometimes she uses euphemisms and sometimes she does not.
Similarly, there was a dichotomy in Ms. Britton's act. At times,
she peeled off chiffon evening gowns to music by Tchaikovsky. At
times, she balanced two glasses of water on her bare breasts. Now
Ms. Britton forgoes delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That little ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Whoops! Call the mayor's morality squad!
</P>
<P>
   `` ... shut down burlesque in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Britton once inhabited the dreams of college boys. Now she
lives in a large apartment overlooking Gramercy Park. Her furniture
is classic and faded, and there is an impressive art collection
inherited from her husband, Robert Gross, a wealthy businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Three canisters of candy kisses are on the coffee table; Ms.
Britton offers up too much candy, which is as good a metaphor as
any for her. She started stripping at 15; was ``engaged'' (one
senses this is a euphemism) to 14 men, including, she says, Rex
Harrison, and will tell you that she loathed stripping _ it made
her feel cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't she marry Rex Harrison?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really dear and sweet,'' Ms. Britton says. ``But I'd
been married at 14 _ a fake marriage, it turned out _ and it was a
horrible experience and I simply couldn't get married again. When I
saw `My Fair Lady' the other night I was furious at myself that I
thought so little of myself I didn't marry him. Anybody who was
respectable, they were good enough to be engaged to, I just
couldn't marry them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rex Harrison, during the time of this affair, was married.
Memories are selective, newspapers inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Britton, in yellowed newspaper clips, is reported to be a
graduate of Tilden High School in Brooklyn, but this, like many
other parts of her life, is the work of an imaginative press agent.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Britton, who was born in New Brunswick, N.J., tells it,
she never attended high school. She was 2 when her mother walked
out, and she lived in foster homes or with her Aunt Bobbi and Uncle
Bumpsy, vaudeville performers. As part of his act, Uncle Bumpsy
unzipped his pants and removed an alarm clock that said, ``Time
flies.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Ms. Britton's father do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she says. ``I know he was beating my mother
up. That he was doing beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Britton, in order to escape the man she was living with _
who beat her _ went to work in burlesque. The first place she
stripped was a place on the Bowery, the People's Theater, where
admission was 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Britton exposed her breasts, then fainted.
</P>
<P>
   Having undergone analysis, she describes the episode in
psychoanalytic terms. ``I experienced what I now know was a
dissociative episode,'' she writes in her memoir. ``There seemed to
be two of me. One, onstage, undressing. The other saying, `What are
you doing, taking your clothes off for those morons?''
</P>
<P>
   But it was work. Ms. Britton moved uptown to the burlesque
theaters of Times Square. When La Guardia shut down burlesque
shows, at the end of 1941, she moved to 52nd street, to an upscale
club called Leon and Eddie's. Though she calls stripping ``the low
point of my life,'' she remembers this fondly, bringing out her
pink sequin G-string.
</P>
<P>
   Was the act changed?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't,'' Ms. Britton says, ``I still stripped. But I also
did production numbers. People addressed me as Miss Britton. There
was respect. All the celebrities came to see me.''
</P>
<P>
   But she never had the career she had hoped for. Her press agent
might say she was in 47 shows, but they were never on Broadway. In
``Peer Gynt,'' starring John Garfield, at the ANTA Playhouse, she
played ``A Greenclad Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Ms. Britton married Robert Gross, whom she calls ``the
love of my life.'' He encouraged her to go to college, and teased
her, when he was ill with cancer, that the moment he died she would
buy a memorial bench for him in Gramercy Park, which she did.
Thinking about him, Ms. Britton's eyes well up.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is changed.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Britton could live her life all over again, would she
strip?
</P>
<P>
   She thinks about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she says. ``But I would have a different view of it. I
would know it was a steppingstone. I'd not take it so personally,
what people said. I look at pictures of myself then. I should have
at least known I was pretty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
