<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO MISTAKING TIMES SQUARE FOR TOKYO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-COLLAPSE-RDP, NY-COLLAPSE-RESTAURANT,
NY-COLLAPSE-CONDENAST) 
(bl) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While Times Square stumbled through one more chaotic
day, thoughts turned Thursday to another moment of urban breakdown.
That was 14 years ago in Tokyo, where a fire in an underground
tunnel destroyed a telephone exchange, wiping out service for more
than 800,000 residents in a part of the city called Setagaya.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, customers were upset by the disruption, which would
last for many days. New Yorkers have no monopoly on complaining,
appearances to the contrary notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   But it took the telephone company less than 24 hours to set up
banks of emergency phones all across Setagaya, each equipped with
lights, tables and a list of important numbers. Naturally, company
officials were out there apologizing like mad, because that's what
Japanese businesses do when things go wrong. Outside one bank whose
cash machines had been knocked out by the fire, executives bowed to
customers _ and directed them to the ATMs of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   OK, enough of traipsing down memory lane. Besides, comparisons
between cultures can go only so far. But after the elevator-tower
collapse at the Conde Nast building in Times Square, it was hard
not to think about Setagaya and how company officials immediately
accepted full responsibility for a disaster that was not of their
doing.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, consider the questions that have been raised about
whether Douglas Durst and Dan Tishman, respectively the developer
and the builder of the Conde Nast tower, moved quickly enough to
shoulder their responsibilities in a disaster that has disrupted
thousands of lives and cost midtown businesses bundles of money.
Some of those questions may not be fair, but they are being asked
just the same by many New Yorkers, including Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, not one easily accused of being anti-developer,
clearly believes that the Durst and Tishman organizations were a
tad slow in offering compensation. Coincidentally or not, it was
only after he began to grouse in public that Durst and Tishman
personally issued a statement expressing sorrow that an elderly
woman had died and regret that so many lives had been turned upside
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like pulling teeth to get them to do something for the
businesses,'' a City Hall official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was similarly out front in 1996, flailing executives of
Trans World Airlines for insensitivity in taking too long to notify
grieving families after the crash of Flight 800. At the time, some
accused the mayor of showboating. But he was venting a frustration
that many felt, and feel once again in the less calamitous Conde
Nast mess. The frustration is rooted in a suspicion, widely held,
that the knee-jerk reaction of American business leaders is to
spend more time worrying how to deflect lawsuits than how to show
an anxious public that they truly care.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as Japanese companies understand, the public needs to
have its collective hand held, and right away.
</P>
<P>
   Although not about to attack a mayor with a mile-wide vindictive
streak, the Durst and Tishman people say they are getting an unfair
rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gravity of the situation was not in the least bit
ignored,'' said Mortimer Matz, a spokesman for the Durst
Organization. ``Emergency work was going on 24 hours a day. The
enormity of what was going on, assessing what was going on and
dealing with the city and all the emergency agencies involved _ it
was an enormous agenda all taking place at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was ignoring responsibilities,'' he said, ``or ignoring
compassion for those whose lives were disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar points were made by Richard Kielar, a senior vice
president at Tishman Realty &AMP; Construction Co. At first, the main
focus was on the damaged tower, he said, and that allowed little
time for writing statements of regret. Besides, Kielar added, ``we
wanted to come up with a statement that was somewhat substantive,''
offering details about compensation along with remorse.
</P>
<P>
   No one suggests malice on the part of these businesses, not in
this space anyway. But nagging questions about how responsibility
was shouldered seem unlikely to fade soon.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, getting back to Setagaya, once the telephones were
working again, the company sent out platoons of employees. They
visited every house _ every single one _ bearing small gifts and
apologizing once more for the inconvenience. Don't bet on seeing
that in Times Square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
