<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-RESTAURANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURATEUR FINDS SCAFFOLD MISHAP A RECIPE FOR DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-COLLAPSE-RDP) 
(bl) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steve Chang's journey to Times Square has taken him
across three continents. Along the way, he has sold ice cream and
corned beef sandwiches and golf equipment. Always, he looked ahead
to the day he could open his own restaurant. And when that time
came, it never occurred to him to look up.
</P>
<P>
   But the twisted elevator tower and scaffolding that collapsed
Tuesday from the Conde Nast building in Times Square threatens
Chang's dream. Just two weeks ago, he had opened Rio de Janeiro, an
extravagant all-you-can-eat churrascaria, where waiters
theatrically paraded dozens of cuts of meat, and customers dined
until they dropped.
</P>
<P>
   He had advertised his restaurant in New York magazine and in
Playbill, assuming that his address, 127 W. 43rd St., situated him
perfectly to capitalize on the surge of tourism that has made Times
Square one of the busiest neighborhoods in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it made him a victim of what the insurance companies
dispassionately call a ``business interruption.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were gaining momentum, people were calling and starting to
make reservations,'' Chang said. ``Then _ boom _ this thing
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The boom came about 8:25 a.m. Tuesday, just as Chang's
brother-in-law, Jong Ik Rhee, was approaching the restaurant to
open it for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the construction workers running out of the site and the
elevator move to the side,'' Rhee said in Korean as his daughter,
So Jung Rhee, translated. ``It was chaotic. After everything had
fallen, I saw that a window had been broken and the canopy broken
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhee was forced by construction workers and police to retreat
down the street. Nobody has been in the restaurant since, leaving
Chang with no access to his office and to what he estimates to be
tens of thousands of dollars worth of food with nobody to cook it
or eat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of food getting spoiled,'' he said. ``I have no
way to call my workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How am I feeling? I want to cry, but what can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most frustrating thing for Chang has been getting
information. Thursday, he remained unsure when 43rd Street would
open again. ``I don't know if this'll be resolved in days or
weeks,'' he said. ``I've heard that the street may not be opened
for many weeks, and that's discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his workers _ including his own daughter, Joanne, who
is the restaurant's general manager _ are not getting paid, and
Chang worries about the rent, which he would only say was ``big
money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm calling my creditors and vendors to hold off
payments for a month or two until I can get money from my insurance
people,'' he said. ``I even had to call my mortgage company to give
me a couple of months. What else can I do? I have no way to make a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang said his insurance covers him for business interruptions,
and that he is looking to the developer, the Durst Organization,
and the general contractor, Tishman Construction, for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I have the policy for this type of situation,'' he
said. ``We're hoping Mr. Tishman and Mr. Durst will somehow
expedite the compensation,'' he added, speaking of John Tishman and
Douglas Durst.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's neighbor on 43rd Street, Bruce Sterman, was less
sanguine. Sterman and his wife, Luba Pincus, own the Manhattan
Chili Company on 43rd east of Broadway, and Tuesday's accident was
the second time this year the restaurant was forced to close
because of construction problems at the Conde Nast building. On
Jan. 26, a crane collapsed, which forced the restaurant to close
for half a day and required sidewalk scaffolding for a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business had a clear 20 percent drop as a result of being
entombed in a sidewalk shed for a full four weeks,'' he said. ``We
were not insured for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterman said he was bitter about what he called the ``wiggling
and waggling'' on the part of the insurance and construction
companies, which he said were trying to avoid responsibility for
the problem earlier this year, and he said he feared getting the
runaround again. He said lawsuits would be a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people that are in my neighborhood; they're my
customers,'' said Sterman, who estimated he is losing $8,000 to
$9,000 a day while closed. ``I don't really want to sue them, but
they have forced me into that position. I've just been kicked
around by these big companies and they're starting again.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang, who was born in South Korea and worked in Paraguay and
Brazil before moving to New York in 1979, said he was most
concerned about people: those who had made reservations at the
270-seat Rio de Janeiro and his staff of more than 50. If he could
reach his workers, he said, he would tell them that they ought to
seek other work because he did not know how long the restaurant
would be closed. ``I can always hire them back when the situation
is back to normal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not include his daughter, Joanne, among this number,
though. He has put her to work organizing a satellite office at his
home in Riverdale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chang says it will be difficult. ``I'm very stressed, I have
absolutely no income,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's response? ``I'm just asking her if I can delay
payment,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
