<HEADLINE>
CANIZARES FEARS CLUBS STOLEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Missing luggage.
</P>
<P>
   It's usually no more than a nuisance for most travelers. For
Jose Maria Canizares, a professional golfer who was gearing up for
the most important tournament on the Senior PGA Tour, it had more
the feel of disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Canizares, sixth on the money list this year, was forced to play
the first round of the U.S. Senior Open with borrowed clubs
Thursday at Riviera Country Club after his bag disappeared on a
trip here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very bad mistake, because it's a very personal
thing,'' Canizares said after shooting an opening round of
2-over-par 73.
</P>
<P>
   When he got to the baggage carousel at LAX after his flight from
Chicago, all of his bags were there except the one carrying his
clubs, Canizares said. He since has been in constant touch with
American Airlines, but he has been told efforts to find the clubs
have been futile. He fears they were stolen in the baggage-claim
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look in Los Angeles airport, and it is very bad control,''
said Canizares, a Spaniard. ``Everybody comes in from the street,
and there are no police. Nobody to say, `Where are you going?' You
could get any bag you like.''
</P>
<P>
   He was given a replacement set of clubs by Ping, the
manufacturer with which he is under contract, but ``everything is
new. They feel different.''
</P>
<P>
   Canizares added, ``This could cost me $1 million. It's not the
(monetary value of the clubs). It's personal. You can't replace
them. This is my job. I don't play golf for holiday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
