<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT PANEL UPHOLDS PRUDENTIAL INSURANCE SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa.)  (af) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal appeals court panel in Philadelphia has upheld a huge
class-action settlement between the Prudential Insurance Company of
America and millions of its customers who had been sold unnecessary
life insurance by Prudential agents over a 13-year period ending in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement had been approved in March 1997 by Judge Alfred
Wolin of the federal district court in Newark, N.J., but lawyers
for some of the 10.7 million affected policyholders objected to the
settlement and sought to overturn it in the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision released Thursday, the appeals panel rejected
those objections and affirmed the basic terms of the settlement,
which calls for Prudential to repay an estimated $2 billion to
customers through direct refunds and enhancements to existing
policies.
</P>
<P>
   But the court did not approve the lower court's award of about
$90 million in legal fees. Instead, it ordered the trial court to
re-examine whether the fees accurately represented contributions
the lawyers had made to the ultimate settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Melvyn Weiss, the lead lawyer for the policyholders, said his
team ``feels very secure'' that the fees would withstand the
additional examination.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement had been the subject of extensive negotiations
involving not only Prudential and its customers, but also insurance
regulators in 30 states.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential had agreed in early 1997 to pay a fine of $35 million
to settle state allegations of deceptive sales practices. The life
insurance giant, based in Newark, has acknowledged that for more
than a decade its agents had improperly persuaded customers to cash
in old policies and purchase new ones so that the agents could
generate additional sales commissions _ a practice known as
churning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gratified that the court has upheld the class-action
settlement,'' said Robert DeFillippo, a spokesman for Prudential.
``The court has affirmed that the settlement will provide complete,
fair and equitable remedies to policyholders.'' The company has
begun to review claims under the settlement, DeFillippo said,
despite the uncertainty posed by the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 500,000 of its customers have applied for basic claim
relief, which entitles them to get enhancements to various
financial products offered by Prudential. Another 640,000 people
have notified the company that they believe they were misled, and
are entitled to additional compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have started the review of those claims and have started
sending out checks,'' DeFillippo said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential had set aside $2 billion in reserves to cover the
costs of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was greeted with dismay by Michael Weaver, a former
Prudential employee who has been an advocate of policyholders in
the dispute. Weaver, who maintains a World Wide Web site devoted to
the case, said that he had received numerous messages from
policyholders complaining about the difficulties they have
encountered in submitting claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the process was flawed at the inception, and has been
skewed to relieve Prudential of their responsibility to their
policyholders, the very people who owned'' the company, Weaver said
Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
