<HEADER>
A0423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLD-MILLER-HNS &LR;      07-23 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-MILLER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USA's Miller auditions &QL; 
through European play
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ROME _ Brad Miller has a lot to gain by playing for the U.S. team
in the FIBA World Championship of Basketball _ mostly because he
stands to lose a lot in the NBA's labor stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   So he has this suggestion for leaders of the players union and
league bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three words,'' he said. ``Fargo, North Dakota. Those people
don't know which way they want to go. I mean, they send the players
to Hawaii for their labor meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send them somewhere crummy. That way, they'll want to get it
over fast. If you send them to Hawaii every time, they'll have a
meeting every week. Send them to Fargo, N.D., and they'll be done
in a day. Instead, it's go meet for half an hour, then sit in the
sun and go to luaus. Go to Fargo, and there's nothing to do but sit
in a room and get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller knows it's not that easy to solve a labor crisis in the
NBA. But it's a good point.
</P>
<P>
   And it's players like him who stand to lose perhaps more than
anybody else in the labor dispute, assuming it isn't solved
quickly. Because he cannot work out for any NBA teams during the
summer, the 6-11 center out of Purdue would be stuck waiting for
the lockout to end, then hoping to latch on with a team as a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if it weren't for the fact Miller's options opened up
considerably for the same reason his NBA dream is on hold. As a
member of the U.S. team, Miller stands to gain from the tournament
by his exposure in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Undrafted a month ago by the NBA, Miller has become one of the
Americans' surprise leaders. He looked good in the first two
exhibition games in Monte Carlo, Monaco, showing his ability to
coaches of the French and Spanish national teams and to countless
European scouts. He hit all five of his shots against France and
probably was the best player on the court. Against Spain, his
playing time was reduced to give teammates a chance, but he was a
force on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the U.S. team has an exhibition game against Italy,
providing another forum where Miller can show his stuff. After
that, there is the 10-day run in Athens, Greece, for the World
Championship of Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the muddled NBA labor situation, Europeans
probably ought to get used to Miller. The way he sees it, he's
basically trying out for a job in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably come overseas for a while because with the
lockout, it's hard to do anything else,'' Miller said. ``You can't
play. So basically, you have to work out on your own, which I'm
going to do. But I'll probably go overseas and get a contract where
I can play until the lockout is over and then leave. That way, I
can get some experience over here playing against professionals And
you get time to really work on your own game because there's some
free time over here. There's no point in spending money working out
when you can make money working out.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this would have been necessary if Miller had been
drafted. Many scouts believe he has the sort of talent that should
have had him taken early in the second round, especially
considering the shortage of quality big men in the NBA. Miller said
he was surprised he wasn't drafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew what happened,'' he said. ``I really don't know.
But it's been working out so far, getting a chance to play on this
team after not getting drafted. I just don't let it drag me down. I
just look back and see that nobody drafted me and try to go out and
prove every time on the court why I should have been drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller admitted he had high hopes before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one team in particular tell me they were going to take
me with a certain pick or, if not, trade up to get me,'' he said.
``There were a few teams like that. But after a certain number of
picks, I quit watching the draft anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
