<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENTARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF TRACK, JAYS NEED A LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the season started, first-year manager Tim Johnson
had the highest of hopes for his Toronto Blue Jays. But unless they
do more than bumble along at a .500 pace, all Johnson can look
forward to is a rebuilding plan that could start as early as next
week.
</P>
<P>
   A stroll through the visitors' clubhouse at Fenway Park Thursday
revealed that this was not the same club that entered the season
considered a prime contender. Suddenly, a four-game series in the
third week of July has become crucial because the Blue Jays came to
town with a 51-51 record, trailing the Red Sox by 7 1/2 games in
the American League wild-card hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto had won only five of 14 games since the All-Star break.
Sure, Roger Clemens (12-6) is on a roll reminiscent of his Cy Young
form in his Toronto debut last season, and Woody Williams and Pat
Hentgen have nine wins each. But it simply hasn't been happening
for the Blue Jays, who offensively and defensively have been below
expectations all year.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of this series was reflected in the crowd that
quickly gathered around Clemens, who on Wednesday night had pitched
eight shutout innings in a 4-0 victory over the White Sox. Rumors
had surfaced that he would start Sunday in place of Hentgen, the
1997 AL Cy Young winner. They proved to be inaccurate, which saved
a lot of clubhouse grief. But there are a lot of people in Toronto
who wouldn't have been surprised if Clemens had been slotted
opposite Pedro Martinez in a duel of Cy Young defenders. The Blue
Jays need a shakeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's speculation,'' said Johnson of the possibility. ``That's
all it ever was, speculation. As for our record, it comes down to
one or two things. The pitching has been good, but the defense
hasn't been as good as we'd want it to be. The hitting has been up
and down. We hope to be closer. We're not. You can't dwell on it.
You have to go out there and keep fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the former Boston bench coach, knows the buck stops
with him, so he wasn't ducking issues. Yes, he said, it was a
temptation to pitch Clemens on three days' rest. But conventional
wisdom dictates strict adherence to the rotation, if possible. So
even though Clemens threw only 100 pitches Wednesday, Hentgen will
pitch Sunday. Clemens will next pitch Tuesday against Texas,
another wild-card contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stick with the rotation,'' said Johnson. ``They've been
doing a good job. So has the bullpen. I'm always optimistic.
Naturally, we'd like to win more games. But we need to be more
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens didn't want to be a part of any controversy when he
reached Fenway. He'd much rather talk about one of his sons, Koby,
playing in a national tournament in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, he said, he could go on three days' rest. But
realistically, the time is not right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching is not our problem right now,'' said Clemens.
``Besides, that's Pat Hentgen's day. He's a Cy Young winner, too.
If this were September, I would lean to a four-man (rotation) if we
needed that. But we have five capable guys and a guy throwing well
at Triple A in Kelvim Escobar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still playing .500 baseball, which is not good enough
for much right now. We got to do something different if we hope to
remain in contention for the wild card. We're pulling for all the
other guys. We got to keep Pat's confidence up and we've got to
score some runs somehow for (Juan) Guzman. He's been throwing so
well and hasn't got much to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays know that catching runaway division leader New
York is a foolish notion. But unless there is a major turnaround,
the club will finish closer to fifth than first, and that's
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there is a lot of room for improvement,'' said
Johnson. ``We're not just pointing to this series. We're trying to
win all the games. The pressure isn't only because we're here right
now. It doesn't matter who it's against. Whether it's Boston, the
Yankees, the White Sox, you still want to get as many victories as
you can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
