<HEADLINE>
IRANIANS RETURN TO U.S., READY TO JUST WRESTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Less than four months after members of the Iranian
national wrestling team were photographed, fingerprinted and
detained at O'Hare Airport in Chicago when they arrived for a
tournament, they returned to the United States on Wednesday night
for this weekend's competition at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   This time there was no red tape, no need for a public
explanation of customs procedure by the Clinton administration.
Instead, a State Department official and a former Iranian team
coach met the athletes and escorted them through customs and
promptly took them to the team's hotel in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the incident at O'Hare last April, the Iranians placed
third at the 1998 Freestyle World Cup competition at Oklahoma State
University. The current trip is the latest chapter in a run of
recent athletic competition between the two countries. Last month,
Iran scored a stirring victory over the United States in the World
Cup soccer tournament in France.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the list of Iranian athletes wrestling in the four-team
competition this weekend is Rasul Khadem, who won a gold medal at
the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta and was the world champion in 1994 and
1995 in the 198-pound weight class. He will be competing against
athletes from Russia and Turkey as well as from the United States
on Saturday and Sunday at the Theater at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Khadem and his teammate Abbas Jadidi, who was
runner-up in the 220-pound class in Atlanta, were welcomed by their
former coach, Hamid Kermanshah, at Kermanshah's Oriental rug
gallery in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It marked just the fifth time since 1979 that an Iranian
athletic team has visited the United States, according to Goodwill
Games officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surprising how open they were to coming back to America
after what happened to them in Chicago,'' said Kermanshah, who
coached the Iranian team in the early 1990's. ``They told me they
were forgetting about it, and it was time to turn the page on that
incident.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Maybe things like this can open the dialogue between
the countries. Maybe their coming here can help in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the gallery, Khadem and Jadidi signed autographs for about a
dozen Iranian fans and politely sidestepped any discussion about
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focused on wrestling,'' Khadem said through Kermanshah,
who translated. ``We have come only for the games and for the
sportsmanship. I hope I can do the best for my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Last February, 10 members of the U.S. wrestling team traveled to
Tehran to compete in the prestigious Takhti Cup. It was the first
time in 20 years that an American team had competed on Iranian
soil. The Americans plan to return to Iran in September for the
world championships in Tehran. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BABERUTH-HBO-NYT &LR;      07-23 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BABERUTH-HBO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUTE TO BABE RUTH IS `MOST WONDERFUL,' HIS DAUGHTER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   She celebrated her 81st birthday last week, but when Julia Ruth
Stevens reminisces about her father, she sounds 18. She smiles in a
dreamy way about Babe Ruth and clasps her hands over her heart when
she speaks of ``Daddy.'' There were tears in her eyes as she looked
out at an audience that had been invited to screen HBO's ``Babe
Ruth'' documentary Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most wonderful tribute to my father that I've ever
seen,'' she said of the film that will air at 8 p.m. Eastern time
on Aug. 16, the anniversary of the Babe's death.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' son, Tom, an engineer, was in the audience. So were
Yankees Manager Joe Torre and pitchers Graeme Lloyd and David
Wells, a Ruth devotee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the luckiest girl in the world to have him as a
father,'' Julia Stevens said. She was Claire Hodgson's daughter
from her first marriage. The Babe adopted her when he married
Claire in 1929. At a reception following the film, she offered fond
memories: her father surprising her by coming to her high school
graduation in 1934; walking her down the aisle at her wedding, and
traveling with her parents on a tour of Japan after the 1934
season.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the blood transfusion her father gave her, she said
her thought was, ``Wow, now I have his blood in me.'' It could have
happened yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always there when I needed him,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to dispel any notion that her father was something of
a wild man at home. ``He only rarely raised his voice, but if he
did, if he said `Julia!' you knew he was mad,'' she said. ``He was
like any father. Oh, he'd let out a belly laugh, of course. We
listened to the radio together. We loved `The Lone Ranger.' We
played bridge. He was good. He was a very good golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she substituted for her mother as her father's
companion at various events around town, ``because I loved the way
people reacted to him.''
</P>
<P>
   And although she said she loved the HBO documentary for digging
up unseen archival footage and clips from the Babe's silent films,
she nonetheless endured old and new tales about her father's
excessive good times with food, booze and sex. She heard the
journalist Heywood Hale Broun relate a tale about Ruth's romp with
``multiple female partners,'' and Charlie Devens recall the Babe
downing a quart of scotch on a Boston-to-New York train ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``A quart of scotch? That's an awful lot,'' she said. ``It seems
exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she said, ``I learned a lot tonight, but some of it I take
with a grain of salt. She said she finds solace in her belief that
the Babe's allegedly prodigious sexual exploits ``happened before
he married my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia had a sister, Dorothy, probably born in 1921, when Ruth
was married to Helen Woodford. Her birth was something of a
mystery, according to accounts. The HBO film speculates that her
mother was not Helen, but a maid.
</P>
<P>
   Did Ruth love having daughters? ``Oh, sure,'' she said. ``But he
would have loved a son.'' She nodded toward her son, who was born
in 1952. ``But he would have loved my son. I know he would have
loved Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Doehler was at the screening, too, because of a cameo role
he plays in the HBO film. Doehler was 14, one of 200 Babe Ruth
League players who traveled by bus to see Ruth's coffin at Yankee
Stadium nearly 50 years ago. But traffic delayed them and when they
arrived, the gate was closed. Only the family, some reporters and
photographers were left, preparing for the funeral procession.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Doehler said, Claire Ruth heard that the 200 youngsters
wanted to get in, but could not. The gate was opened. ``I was at
the head of the line,'' said Doehler, who would later be an
assistant baseball coach at Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone gave me a ball that had `Safe at home' written on
it.'' Doehler approached the open coffin nervously and placed the
ball inside. But it rolled down Ruth's left arm. ``Then I placed it
on his clasped hands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he recalled Claire Ruth telling him, ``It's so wonderful
of you to go to this trouble,'' as she led him to an open gate
where a hearse awaited.
</P>
<P>
   Doehler said the experience galvanized his love of baseball. He
signed a minor league contract with the Boston Braves. And in 1952,
one of his roommates at the YMCA in Eau Claire, Wis., was Henry
Aaron. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
