<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-RAPIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF FUGITIVE WANTED IN RAPES SAYS HE TALKED OF SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Convicted rapist and fugitive Steven B. Gordon, wanted for three
rapes of women in New Hampshire this month, remained at large
Thursday, despite efforts by the FBI and Dutch authorities to find
him in Amsterdam, where he was last believed to have been.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents obtained Thursday, meanwhile, show that even
though Gordon was not supposed to be released early from prison
unless he attended an in-prison sex-offender program, he never took
part in the program because it was only for pedophiles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, New Hampshire Superior Court Judge Linda S. Dalianis,
who originally sentenced him to six to 15 years in 1993 for the
rape of a New Hampshire teacher, let him out on parole in 1997 so
he could attend outpatient counseling at a sexual offenders clinic
in Tyngsborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe was unable to determine whether Gordon ever
participated in the Massachusetts program. Dalianis, who was
appointed to the bench in 1980, declined to comment on Gordon or
his case.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 28, a native of Quincy, Mass., is wanted by New
Hampshire authorities for the rapes of two Irish women in
Portsmouth, N.H., last Saturday, and of a Nashua, N.H. Realtor in a
house in Manchester July 7.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Thursday afternoon, Portsmouth Commander
Brad Russ said police ``hope to have him in custody in the very
near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have information coming to us every hour about a possible
location on this individual,'' Russ said. He said Portsmouth
detectives had tracked Gordon to Amsterdam, and are filing
paperwork with federal officials to allow extradition if Gordon is
found.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gordon's mother, who asked that her name not be used,
said she talked to her son at about noon Eastern time Thursday, and
he told her he was outside of an embassy in Amsterdam attempting to
secure a visa that would allow him to flee the Netherlands. She
declined to identify the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also talked of suicide, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I think I am going to kill myself,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester, N.H. police told the Globe Thursday that they have
now named Gordon as a suspect in the rape of the Realtor. Detective
Dan Brennan said comments Gordon made to his probation officer
``heightened our attention on him as a suspect.'' He did not say
when Gordon made those comments to his probation officer.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan said he did not believe police had made any contact with
Gordon yet. ``We are basically waiting, hoping that someone gets
through to him to get him to turn himself in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional telephone conversation Wednesday evening, a man
who said he was Gordon confessed to all three rapes to a Globe
reporter, saying he had felt out of control and apologizing to the
women.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe notified Portsmouth police Wednesday night that it was
reporting the next morning that Gordon had confessed to the rapes
and said he was at a youth hostel in Amsterdam. The paper also gave
police the phone number of the hostel.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is the newspaper's policy not to share information
it has gathered before it is published, the paper decided that
concern for public safety took precedence. The Globe did not
disclose any other information to the police, and did not violate
any agreement with sources for the story.
</P>
<P>
   At her house in a Boston suburb, Gordon's mother Thursday showed
a Globe reporter a pellet gun wrapped in cloth, which she said her
son told her he used in robberies he had committed. At first she
denied that he told her that he used the gun in the rapes as well,
but later she said he had.
</P>
<P>
   The black plastic gun, which resembled a .45 automatic, bore the
words ``Crosman Airgun.'' Removing it from under the cushions of a
plush chair in her living room, Gordon's mother said, ``He said it
was the gun he used.'' She said Gordon gave the weapon to his
brother, who lives with her, this month as a birthday present.
</P>
<P>
   At the kitchen table of her yellow ranch-style home, Gordon's
mother alternately cried and raised her voice as she talked to a
reporter. By her side was a white cordless phone from which, she
said, she urges her fugitive son to turn himself in whenever he
calls. Gordon has been diagnosed with a mental illness, she said,
and needs professional help.
</P>
<P>
   His mother said he had recently stopped taking two medications:
Lithium, which is used to treat manic depression, and Zoloft, an
antidepressant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a monster inside him that needs to be killed,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She leafed through a yellowed photo album of her six children,
frozen in the innocence of youth. Gordon is pictured throughout his
life, playing, wading in the ocean, stiffly posing at a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love looking at this album,'' she said, tears welling. ``It
makes me happy ... This is my whole life. It's not much of a life,
is it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Correspondents Colles Stowell and Rebecca Mahoney contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
