<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLLAPSE-CABARET-6     07-23 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-CABARET-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLAPSE OF TOWER IS HURTING HIT SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-COLLAPSE-RDP, NY-COLLAPSE-RESTAURANT,
NY-COLLAPSE-CONDENAST) 
(mk) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While New Yorkers continued to cope with the
disruption caused by the collapse of an elevator tower on Tuesday
in Times Square, four major productions, including the popular
``Cabaret,'' were coping with more: financially onerous shutdowns
of successful shows.
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent and imperiled is ``Cabaret,'' whose location at
the Kit Kat Klub on 43rd Street, a few steps from the accident site
at the Conde Nast building, left producers contemplating a shutdown
that could easily last another week or more.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Roundabout Theater Company, the producers of
``Cabaret,'' said they still had no official word on how long the
show, which won four Tony Awards, would be shut down. It had been
playing to full houses almost since its opening on Feb. 13 and was
grossing close to $300,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said two other nearby theaters closed in the
aftermath of the collapse, the Criterion and the Lamb's, could
reopen soon _ as soon as a 700-foot-tall black nylon net is
installed to enclose the damaged scaffolding and protect the
streets below. But because of its location, almost beneath the
scaffolding, the Kit Kat Klub could be closed much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Roundabout said an extended shutdown of
``Cabaret'' would be both financially and psychologically
devastating, leaving the theater scrambling to pay the cast and
perhaps denying farewell performances to the two most prominent
female performers, who had already been scheduled to leave the
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disaster for us, heading toward a catastrophe in
another week or so,'' Todd Haimes, artistic director of the
Roundabout, said. ``We still have to pay the costs of mounting a
production, even if we're not actually performing. Let's face it.
It's so rare to have a success like this, that to have it and then
be shut down, is just devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said it cost $210,000 a week to stage ``Cabaret, which
has 20 cast members, some of whom play musical instruments, and
seven orchestra members who do not appear as actors.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the show to another theater temporarily is not even an
option, given the difficulty of finding a suitable spot and the
expense of moving. As it is, ``Cabaret'' takes place in what used
to be the Club Expo; it was specifically refurbished as a
Weimar-era nightclub, with many theatergoers sitting at tables in
the play's cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Roundabout productions, ``You Never Can Tell'' and
``Side Man,'' have been closed at the Criterion, 1530 Broadway near
45th Street. Since both shows are part of subscription series with
a limited run, it will be difficult to recoup lost costs, Haimes
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man,'' about one man's obsession with jazz and its
effects on his family and friends, had been taking in about
$160,000 a week. ``You Never Can Tell,'' George Bernard Shaw's play
about an independent-thinking woman visiting a British seaside
resort, was taking in about $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   Less conspicuous, but also shut down, has been ``Smoke On the
Mountain,'' an offbeat Southern musical review, at the Lamb's
Theater, 130 W. 44th St.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Rossi Copeland, the producer, said the show, which
opened June 18, had been steadily building an audience, was
expecting its best week and was planning to film television
commercials next week. She said the show was playing at more than
60 percent of the theater's 350-seat capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two sold-out houses for next week,'' she said. ``This
is just killing us. The margin for a little show like this is very
small, and we're eating it up by the hour.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is never a good time for productions to be shut down, but
the timing of this week's disruption was particularly painful,
officials with the show said.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Smoke on the Mountain,'' which was first produced eight
years ago and has been touring the country for much of the time
since, is considered especially well suited for the summer tourist
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabaret,'' based on Christopher Isherwood's writings about the
decadence of Germany at the dawning of the Third Reich, has been
one of the hottest plays on Broadway for some time; it became even
more popular after its strong showing in the Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was supposed to be the last performance for Mary Louise
Wilson, who played the role of Fraulein Schneider. She is being
replaced by Blair Brown. And Natasha Richardson, who won a Tony for
her performance as Sally Bowles, is scheduled to leave the play
Aug. 2, with Jennifer Jason Leigh taking her place.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are Natasha's last two weeks,'' Haimes said. ``It would
be tragic if she doesn't get to finish her run.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said that although he would like more definitive answers,
city officials seem to be as forthcoming as possible given the
uncertainties of repairing the damage and securing the area.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Copeland said she found it impossible to get reliable
information on when the street and her theater might reopen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a police state out there,'' she said. ``I called the
mayor's hot line and all they would tell me was that the theater
was closed. I said, `I know it's closed. I'm the producer.' I've
done a lot of FBI work this week and no one has told me anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear what, if any, impact the disruption to Times
Square was having on theaters outside the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing really discernible,'' said Jed Bernstein,
executive director of the League of American Theater Owners and
Producers. ``Some shows are up, some are down; it's about what you
would expect for a summer week in July.''
</P>
<P>
   And, though traffic has been badly disrupted, the overall impact
of the accident has not been all bad for tourists and theatergoers,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a funny way, the inaccessibility is balanced by the
accessibility,'' he said. ``Times Square is a big pedestrian mall
right now and people seem to be enjoying it in a way they usually
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, for those who had tickets for ``Cabaret.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
