<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUMMER-CAMP-800(2T     07-23 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUMMER-CAMP-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONDS MADE AT THIS SUMMER CAMP LAST FOR GENERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  (js) 
 By JANE GROSS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EQUINUNK, Pa. _ It is shortly before 10 o'clock on visiting day
at Camp Blue Ridge, a 75-year-old sleepaway camp in the Poconos,
and parents are straining at the ropes that separate them from
their children for just a few minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   The cabins are so spiffy that quarters would bounce on the
tightly made beds. The campers are spruced up for the occasion, the
little ones in crisp hair ribbons and the big ones with legs shaved
smooth as silk. Girls from 6 to 16 hang from the porch railings,
searching the distant parking area for a beloved face.
</P>
<P>
   When the rope is removed, the adults and children surge together
in an exuberant tangle. Eight-year-old Lindsay Breslauer gulps back
tears as she looks for her family. Jackie Brook, an old hand at 13,
is more philosophical about her parents' tardiness. She tries to
comfort Lindsay, a first-year camper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother has to be fashionably late wherever she goes, even
her own wedding,'' the teen-ager says, giving Lindsay a warm
squeeze. ``But if she's not here in 10 minutes, I'm getting
adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   Visiting day at any summer camp is a ritual dance _ part love,
part conflict, part ``What did you bring me?'' But at Blue Ridge,
where many of the 240 girls are third-generation campers, there is
more going on than parents and children hugging, bickering and
exchanging gifts after weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   First at the rope were a set of grandparents who met here as
children and look forward to annual reunions with their own cabin
mates as well as their offspring. And inside each cabin there's a
mother remembering which cot she slept in and where on the wall she
had written her name.
</P>
<P>
   Camps like this, dating back to the 1920s, have become something
of a rarity, driven out of business by those with shorter seasons,
specialized programs or country-club amenities. But here, young and
old alike embrace a place where time seems to stop from the
beginning of July to the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   Like generations before them, the visiting parents and
grandparents, most from Long Island, arrived laden with goodies:
bagels and forgotten stuffed animals, new clothes and five-pound
sacks of cherries, enough candy to create a sugar high that will
last for weeks to come.
</P>
<P>
   The children, too, followed traditional scripts. Anxious and
excited, they were noisier than usual at breakfast. They scowled
when mom said, ``Your bangs are too long,'' cringed when dad
started shooting baskets and beamed when grandma liked the bowl
made in arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Manchel, the camp owner, considers visiting day one of
the most stressful of the summer, and by 2 p.m. she was checking
her watch. Before day's end, a couple of parents will have
complained about perceived slights against their children. A couple
more will have signed up younger siblings for next summer. One or
two children will be inconsolable when their parents leave at 4
o'clock. The rest will send mom and dad off with a cursory wave and
a mumbled ``luv ya.''
</P>
<P>
   Allie and Charlie Stein were among those glad to greet their
parents and just as glad to say goodbye. ``You can see your parents
whenever,'' said Allie, 11. ``Camp is to get away.'' Her
15-year-old brother, Charlie, who attends Camp Equinunk for boys
across the lake, nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   No hurt feelings, said Ellen and Glenn Stein, their parents, who
made the annual pilgrimage from Great Neck. ``Either we raised two
very independent children or they can't wait to get away from us,''
said Stein, a school psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Parting was not so easy for little Lindsay, her sister, mother
and aunt. The visitors ignored instructions to leave at 4 and
followed the child as she lined up for afternoon swimming. Mrs.
Manchel's reaction was swift. ``Go fast! This is not good for
her!'' she ordered, peeling the family apart.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's face crumpled. But Mrs. Manchel promised the child
that her group leader would jump in the lake fully clothed,
inducement enough to dry the child's tears and get her down to the
shore. ``I make it up as I go along,'' Mrs. Manchel said of her
improvisation.
</P>
<P>
   Camps that last only a week or two are all the rage these days,
preferred by many working couples who don't see enough of their
children during the school year. Niche camps are also popular,
specializing in, say, gymnastics or dance. Then there are
enrichment activities that will stand out on a youngster's college
application, like studying Russian or backpacking in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Many old-fashioned camps like this one have folded, unable to
persuade parents that eight weeks of campfires, canoeing and Color
War are worth nearly $6,000. But those that remain tap a vein of
nostalgia. The girls here sing the same songs their grandparents
sang and study their faces on sepia-and-white photographs, dating
back to the 1920s, that hang in HQ, or headquarters, the camp's
main office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Garbage pails, in age-old Blue Ridge slang, are called ``hungry
barrels.'' The youngest campers play on the ``vomit wheel,''
spinning in nauseating circles. Counselors are allowed to smoke
only at a spot called ``trill,'' for the trillium flower, at the
edge of the lake. Traditions of all sorts matter. Visitors are
always greeted with a chorus of ``a hearty welcome to you.''
Lifelong friends march to the mess hall six abreast with arms slung
over one another's shoulders. The first cabin to gather at morning
and evening lineup gets to raise or lower the flag to a scratchy
record playing reveille or ``Taps.'' The oldest campers, called
PC's (or ``privileged characters'') refuse to have their cabin
painted because it is a shrine to the past, covered with names in
shoe polish that go back generations. ``Where else can you go in
the world where after 30 years it's still the same?'' said Mrs.
Manchel, 60, who began as a camper 48 years ago, met her husband
here, worked for years as the head counselor and finally bought the
camp. ``They call home and say, `I'm on White Mountain' '' _ one of
four competing tribal teams _ ``and their mothers start singing the
song.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing so marks Blue Ridge as its music, zesty marches and
soulful alma maters written each year and added to the huge canon
of songs that are sung three times a day in the mess hall. To be
truly accepted here is to be picked to stand on a chair and lead a
song. First-year campers stare longingly at the older girls and
mimic their arm movements. Parents say it takes weeks after camp
before the children stop singing and waving their arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come home, all I see for a month is them leading,''
said Bob Fasbender, a New York City television producer with two
daughters here.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Herschcopf, father of 10-year-old Sara, said his wife, Toby
Finkelson, showed him how she used to lead songs when they were
dating, which he found a bit odd, even cultish. Ms. Finkelson died
three years ago. Now her daughter is carrying on that family
tradition and Herschcopf has become a believer.
</P>
<P>
   An informal survey of parents on visiting day suggests that the
spirit here, most evident in the singing, is what persuaded them
that this was the right camp for them. ``When we went into the
dining hall and heard them, we got goose bumps,'' said Randi
Mondshine. ``My daughter looked at me and said, `This is it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Manchel has struck a careful balance between upgrading the
camp and retaining its lost-in-time quality. She has added an
in-line skating course and a rock-climbing wall. The hotel where
parents once stayed for long stretches of the summer, when visiting
was allowed at any time, is now a state-of-the-art gymnasium and
97-seat theater, replacing Sunday night movies on the social hall
floor with a pillow and blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back hurts just thinking about it,'' said Mrs. Manchel, who
dashes around the campus like a woman half her age, teasing and
hugging children along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Some changes are out of the owner's control. Children visit the
infirmary not just for Caladryl lotion and salt-water gargles, but
also for Ritalin and Prozac. On visiting day, they ask their
parents to bring bottles of Poland Spring water instead of kosher
salami and rye. And the midsummer reunion spills from Saturday to
Sunday to accommodate divorced fathers unwilling to visit the same
day as their ex-wives.
</P>
<P>
   Among the visiting former campers was one who had brought her
fiance so Mrs. Manchel could pass judgment. ``I know her longer
than you do,'' the owner told him, sounding like a surrogate
mother-in-law. Another, now a reporter, wrote this article. Others,
working in New York City, begged Mrs. Manchel to let them return as
judges for the four-day competition of Color War at summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Carver, a counselor in her 12th Blue Ridge summer, had
her regrets before it was too late. Joanna, a college senior, was
supposed to work at a magazine this summer, but then June rolled
around and she couldn't stay away. ``This is my last summer,'' she
said. ``It is. I swear. Then I have to get a life.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
