<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-WELFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT TALKS BEGIN IN NEW YORK CHILD WELFARE LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Child welfare officials and advocates for foster children
announced Thursday that they had begun talks to resolve a
class-action lawsuit that seeks to replace the leadership of New
York City's troubled child welfare agency with a court-appointed
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came just two days before the scheduled trial
date, and both sides agreed to delay the start of the trial by one
week. The trial is now scheduled to start on Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was filed by a child advocacy group in
December 1995, said that the child welfare system is so ridden with
illegal practices, chronic mismanagement and indifference to
children that it cannot be fixed internally. Lawyers for children
say little has changed at the child welfare agency over the past
two-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
   Child welfare officials have countered that the system has
dramatically improved since the creation of the Administration for
Children's Services in 1996. City officials have often expressed
hope that the lawsuit could be resolved so they could focus more
resources on improving the agency and less on preparing for
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Leonora Wiener, a spokeswoman for the Administration for
Children's Services, described the talks as ``productive
discussions that may lead to the settlement of this action against
the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Robinson Lowry, the executive director of Children's
Rights, the group that filed the lawsuit, said the trial will
proceed if settlement talks fail. But Lowry, who has filed several
lawsuits against other troubled child welfare agencies around the
country, said most cases have been resolved before trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry declined to describe what a settlement might cover in this
case, but she said they usually ``consist of a court order
specifying what the defendant is obligated to do and a process for
monitoring and court enforcement.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0513 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0450 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MURDER-SENTENCE-NY     07-23 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDER-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER OF TWO WOMEN SENTENCED TO LIFE, NOT EXECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ In the second death-penalty trial in New
York since the punishment was reinstated in 1995, the jury
sentenced a convicted murderer Thursday to life in prison without
the possibility of parole instead of death by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   The convicted murderer, Dalkeith McIntosh, was sentenced in a
courtroom crowded with prosecutors and others who had argued that
death was the fitting punishment for a man found guilty of slaying
two women in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An all-white jury of eight men and four women deliberated for a
relatively quick seven hours over two days before handing down a
unanimous vote for life in prison for McIntosh, who is black.
Formal sentencing by Judge George D. Marlow, of Dutchess County
Court, is scheduled for Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh, 38, a Jamaican immigrant, stared hard at the jurors as
they entered the courtroom with their eyes downcast. But he
displayed no emotion as the foreman read the verdict. Afterward,
his lawyer said, he was fighting to hold back tears.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, William M. Tendy, whose face seemed to grow more
ashen and drawn with each passing day, made no effort to hide his
relief. ``I feel like a very, very large weight's been lifted off
of all our shoulders,'' he said after court adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   Tendy said that the unusually graphic and tearful testimony from
McIntosh's brothers and a sister, who begged jurors to take their
brother's horrific childhood into account, may have saved his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's appreciative of what we've done _ he expressed that to
us,'' said Tendy, referring to his team, which had to negotiate
with the United States Embassy to bring McIntosh's siblings here.
``He's less frightened now than I think I've ever seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 8, the same jury convicted McIntosh of fatally shooting
his estranged wife, Francine Williams, a 47-year-old correction
officer, in the head after a quarrel. The jurors also found him
guilty of murdering Williams' daughter, Eunice Williams, 23,
because she had witnessed the first shooting, and of attempting to
murder Anthony Williams, 6, whom he shot in the face. The boy, whom
McIntosh had raised as a son, testified against him in court and
was crucial to the prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a jury in Brooklyn sentenced Darrel K. Harris to
death by lethal injection for fatally shooting three people in a
robbery at an illegal social club. Legal experts have expressed
surprise that New York City jurors chose the death penalty while
the jurors in Dutchess County, which is largely conservative and
Republican, chose life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But on the jury's final verdict sheet, it was clear that on two
counts related to McIntosh's motivation for the shootings, at least
one juror had favored a death sentence. But on the other two
counts, the jury was unanimous, and those votes _ for life _
carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very hard,'' said a juror, Raphael Gonzalez, as he
was leaving the courthouse. ``Very, very hard.'' The other jurors
declined to comment, but as they ate brown-bag lunches together
after the verdict, they shouted and laughed in the jury room.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney William V. Grady of Dutchess County, now the
first prosecutor in New York State to seek the death penalty and
not get it under the current law, said he respected the jury's
decision, but insisted that he had been right to press for capital
punishment for McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon reflection, I still feel in light of the heinous nature
of these crimes _ which in essence were execution-style killings _
and the shooting of a young boy in the face, that the death penalty
was the appropriate sentence,'' he said. ``And, in essence, what
the jury has sentenced the defendant to do is to die in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor, Edward F. Whitesell, later recited a litany
of brutal crimes, in addition to a documented history of domestic
violence, that McIntosh had been accused of. That criminal record
was barred as evidence in the trial. Both prosecutors criticized
the state capital punishment statute for prohibiting victims and
their families from making statements in favor of a death sentence
to a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Grady said the provision was ``a serious injustice'' because
such victim impact statements, as they are known, are permitted
before sentencing in noncapital murder trials. ``Our most serious
statute is missing a key and essential part,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tendy said he was troubled by other parts of the law, but
tempered those remarks. ``This is not the time to criticize the
system that just saved my client's life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one from McIntosh's family, most of whom live in Jamaica, was
present for the jury's decision. But Tendy was trying to reach them
by phone this afternoon. Last week, McIntosh's siblings described
sadistic beatings that they said he received from their mother,
Mavis Green, almost from the day he was born. Sobbing as he
recounted some of the most savage abuse, one brother, Glennard
(Harold) McIntosh, 34, said, ``I remember my brothers and sisters
crying out to her, `No! No! You're going to kill him!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, arguing that such beatings never took place,
subpoenaed Green to testify in favor of a death sentence for her
son. But they dismissed her without explanation before she took the
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Tendy said he spoke to her after the verdict. ``She's extremely
relieved,'' he said. ``She's relieved that he's not getting killed.
She was worried.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of preparing for the McIntosh trial and many
more years of appeals now guaranteed, the lead lawyers on both
sides seemed to have little taste for trying a death penalty case
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a point in time,'' Whitesell said, ``when you
realize it's not just another murder case. You realize that you
have to stand up and make an argument for taking a man's life.
That's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility for saving that life seemed to have left
Tendy utterly drained. ``It's very emotional and it's very
frightening,'' he said. ``You don't eat. You can't sleep. And I
can't at this point imagine me doing this again. It's just too
hard.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
