<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORSIDE2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS IN PAIN, SHOOTS 74
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jack Nicklaus appeared anything but hip Thursday,
at times struggling to simply complete his golf swing.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an arthritic left hip that seems to be worsening, the
Golden Bear had a few of his more awkward moments during the first
round of the U.S. Senior Open at Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   At the 12th hole, Nicklaus fell out of his swing when his hip
gave out. The problem repeated itself at the 16th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in some discomfort,'' Nicklaus said. ``I had discomfort
all day. Today, I had a little problem with it. Usually, it doesn't
get into my golf swing, but today it did. It doesn't allow it to
happen past the ball. I can't get out of my own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is a testament to the 58-year-old's resiliency that,
bad hip included, he still shot a respectable 74 that placed him
just four strokes off the lead. Imagine what a healthy Nicklaus
would have shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes and goes a little bit. Today the problem (with the
hip) started around (the eighth or ninth hole),'' Nicklaus said.
``My hardest part was just playing golf. I didn't drive the ball
well. My iron game wasn't particularly good. I putted poorly and I
didn't chip very well. Other than that, I made one really nice
bunker shot and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Nicklaus played a courageous round, his hip problem
has become a consuming issue this week. Perhaps far-too consuming
for him. Before the tournament, Nicklaus admitted that he was
already ``sick'' of discussing it.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who was close to Nicklaus during Thursday's round
could not ignore the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bothering him,'' said his caddie, Scott Lubin, who
tried to downplay the subject. ``It's there. I ask him and he says
it's OK. He was steady. He'll be back tomorrow and make about eight
birdies.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus' playing partner, Jay Sigel, was just a shot off the
lead with a 71, but even he couldn't ignore the effects the faulty
hip took on golf's best-known player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack really feels, looks uncomfortable even walking, and it is
painful to watch him. It is a shame,'' Sigel said. ``He played
very, very well. I think ... in many cases he hit the ball better
than I did. He putted very well.''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem strange that the injury, which has become so
pervasive this week, originally occurred in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the hip happened about 35 years ago in San
Francisco. I hit an eight-iron to the green. By the time I got to
the green, I couldn't walk,'' Nicklaus said. ``They diagnosed it as
bursitis. I had 25 injections in 10 weeks in the hip area. That's
what they used to do, use cortisone. I think they destroyed part of
the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Nicklaus skipped last week's British Open precisely
so he could avoid any health problems during the Senior Open.
Nicklaus has won two Senior Open titles in only eight tries,
although he has not won any tournament since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Beside trying to regain his winning form, Nicklaus is pondering
hip-replacement surgery, which might be the only remedy to his
chronic problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never know from day-to-day what's going to happen,''
Nicklaus said. ``I don't have any (other) tournaments scheduled
right now. That doesn't mean I won't. I won't play until I can do
what I need to do. When I get home, I will spend a week and figure
out what I need to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
