<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0519 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PORN-SHOPS-ART-250     07-23 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-SHOPS-ART-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SUPREME COURT TO CONSIDER NYC SEX-SHOP LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Giving a glimmer of hope to New York City's sex
shops, U.S. Supreme Court Justice John Paul Stevens chose Thursday
to refer to the entire court a request by the shop owners to delay
enforcement of a law that bans sex-oriented businesses in most
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' action came a day after Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg
rejected a last-minute request for a stay. Ginsburg was the first
to consider the application because she handles cases from this
region, but federal law allowed the sex-shop owners to appeal to
one other justice before giving up. Their lawyers have said they
chose Stevens because they felt he would be most sympathetic to
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   As the request for a stay was circulated to members of the court
Thursday, city officials said they were already sending out
inspectors to determine which sex shops and strip clubs were not in
compliance with the new zoning law. Nevertheless, lawyers for the
shops described Stevens' action as a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us a great deal of encouragement,'' said Herald
Price Fahringer, a lawyer representing 107 adult-entertainment
businesses. ``My hope is that the Supreme Court will hold up
enforcement as the responsible thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped the Supreme Court would decide whether to grant
a stay by Friday. Court spokesman Ed Turner said the justices would
probably decide the matter quickly because applications for stays
are ``handled on a fast track.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Commenting on Friday's decision and on the application before
the court, Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
said: ``There is nothing to react to. In the interim, we will
proceed with the inspections and enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which was passed in 1995 and has been the subject of
court battles ever since, prohibits sexually oriented businesses
from operating within 500 feet of residential areas, schools, day
care centers, houses of worship or one another.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the sex shops, who had become increasingly
pessimistic in recent months as various courts ruled against them,
sounded almost giddy Thursday. They said they would ask the Supreme
Court to take on the full case this fall, adding that they thought
Stevens' decision to share the request for a stay with the entire
court could be a sign that he thinks the full case has merits.
</P>
<P>
   But people familiar with the court said it was not unusual for a
justice to refer an application for a stay to the entire court.
</P>
<P>
   The new law would affect 146 of the city's 164
adult-entertainment businesses. City officials have said they hope
rigorous enforcement will persuade most owners of sex shops to go
out of business, and in fact in recent days some shops in Times
Square have begun removing sex videos from their shelves or
requiring nude dancers to wear bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   In his application to the Supreme Court on behalf of the sex
shops, Fahringer suggested that many of the shops would close
immediately if a stay was not granted. ``Once the zoning resolution
is enforced, the petitioners will either have to close their
theaters and bookstores or face criminal prosecution,'' he wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
