<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-U.N.-NYT &LR;      07-23 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY APPEALING TO REBELS, U.N. CHIEF MAKES PEACE WITH MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan has
delicately defused a diplomatic crisis with the Mexican government
during a visit here by calling on the Zapatista rebels to return to
the negotiating table to resolve the smoldering conflict in the
state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Annan repeatedly praised President Ernesto Zedillo's strategy in
the four-year-old face-off between the government and a ragtag
guerrilla army with a broad base of support in Indian villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see that he is personally committed to finding a
solution,'' Annan said of Zedillo. ``The government is looking for
a political solution and does not seek a military confrontation. I
think this is the right approach.''
</P>
<P>
   While Annan's emphasis served to smooth ruffled feathers in the
government, it seemed sure to disappoint human rights and
pro-Zapatista groups, which have been agitating for the United
Nations to criticize the government and take a role in mediating
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Zapatistas published a long communique in which
they accused the government of lying about its intentions to seek
peace and of conducting a ``war of extermination'' against them. In
recent months government troops have launched attacks to dismantle
four town governments set up by the Zapatistas and to arrest their
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Annan walked into a minefield around the issue of Chiapas on his
two-day visit to Mexico. Offhand comments he made this month,
suggesting that the United Nations might be interested in a role in
Chiapas, provoked an irate response from the government, which said
it had no intention of seeking international mediation.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations officials were apparently taken aback by the
ferocity of Mexico's response. They said the United Nations could
only begin to consider intervening in an internal conflict when
formally invited by the local government and even then complex
approvals from the Security Council or the General Assembly were
required.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations leaders had not even been considering such a
possibility, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   But the dispute pointed up how sensitive the Mexican government
is about any hint of an international role in Chiapas. Earlier this
year, government officials hounded a Catholic bishop, Samuel Ruiz
Garcia, out of his role as a mediator in peace talks, which stalled
late in 1996, in part because he was openly seeking to involve
foreign groups in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   In their communique, the rebels of the Zapatista National
Liberation Army said the government had ``destroyed the only bridge
for the dialogue'' by forcing out Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas completely dominated the press coverage and public
debate about Annan's visit. As a result, Chiapas also forced its
way into the discussions between the secretary general and Zedillo,
even though it was not on the formal agenda.
</P>
<P>
   At a 90-minute meeting between the two leaders on Wednesday,
U.N. officials said, Zedillo gave a half-hour exposition of his
views on the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes two to tango,'' Annan said at a news conference on
Wednesday. ``I would urge the other parties to work in a sustained
and persistent manner with the government to seek a peaceful and
political solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
