<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN24-COX     07-23 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood steadies, wins 3-2
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The rest of the Braves rotation has maintained
all summer what makes Atlanta's starting pitching so extraordinary
is not up front but at the far end. Thursday night, Kevin Millwood
explained what that meant.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing Philadelphia an early run, Atlanta's fifth
starter allowed the Phillies just one more while the Braves
recovered for a 3-2 victory, Javy Lopez and Curtis Pride providing
the fireworks with back-to-back homers in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The decision left Millwood at 11-5 _ two runs allowed on eight
hits with six strikeouts _ after he had lost three of his last four
starts. The Braves swept a two-game set from the Phillies to open
their road trip, which continues tonight with a weekend series in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez gave the Braves their first lead of the night with two
outs in the sixth. Phillies starter Tyler Green started him with a
change-up away, and when he came back with a high fastball Lopez
crushed it over the wall in center for his 21st homer of the season
and a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves weren't done. Curtis Pride, an added starter when
Michael Tucker was scratched late, watched one ball and then
homered to the left-center gap three pitches later for a 3-1 lead.
The homer was his third, but his second in 12 at-bats, making it
the 10th time thus season Atlanta has hit back-to-back home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones, trying to work out of Bobby Cox's doghouse, had
already thrown out a man at the plate when he came up in the fifth
and waved at another Green curveball for his second strikeout. But
the ball bounced away from catcher Mike Lieberthal and Jones made
first with some heads-up running on the wild pitch. Ozzie Guillen
then lofted a soft single into right which Jones correctly read and
took third base.
</P>
<P>
   When Keith Lockhart then sent a liner into shallow center, Jones
again read the play, waited to tag up as Kevin Sefcik made a
running catch and then scored to tie it 1-1 when Sefcik could not
make a strong throw to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood labored early, allowing four hits while throwing 41
pitches just to get through the second inning. Atlanta trailed 1-0
after two and it could have been worse. The Phillies loaded the
bases twice in the second but managed just one run, that coming off
a Tyler Green sacrifice fly on a 1-2 pitch. Millwood then walked
Sefcik to load them again but induced a first-pitch pop-out from
Desi Relaford to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones' hitting streak is now 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
