<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD-     07-23 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEBATE OVER PUERTO RICO'S FUTURE HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for language refinements throughout; describes school prayer
in Puerto Rico more accurately in 2nd graf) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democratic governor of Puerto Rico, pushing for
a chance for his island to vote for statehood, has come up with a
tempting sales pitch for the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a place, Gov. Pedro Rossello and his lobbyists say, that
opposes abortion, hands out vouchers so children can attend
parochial schools, has sliced capital-gains taxes, allows school
pupils five minutes for prayer, and is busy privatizing many of its
major industries. The place, they add, hoping to clinch the deal,
is Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puerto Rico passed the `Contract With America,''' said an
important backer in Congress, Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, and it is
a point that the Idaho Republican never fails to make to
incredulous colleagues as he pushes his legislation for a
congressionally sanctioned referendum on Puerto Rico's status.
</P>
<P>
   It is an uphill battle to persuade his fellow Republican
senators, especially the majority leader, Sen. Trent, R-Miss., to
take the chance that Puerto Rico will not, as a state, send two
Democratic senators and six Democratic representatives to
Washington. That fear, along with the fact that Puerto Rico is
Spanish-speaking, has kept the Republican-controlled Congress from
acting quickly in accordance with the party's 1996 platform plank
that ``we support the right of the U.S. citizens of Puerto Rico to
be admitted to the Union as a fully sovereign state after they
freely so determine.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the party to live up to that pledge, Rossello is trying
to convince Republicans that the island will make a stellar 51st
state and that Puerto Ricans will not necessarily vote for
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It is a message that other statehood supporters are sending,
too. Just last month, Jack Marquez, a Puerto Rican who was
decorated for his service in the Vietnam War, established the
Puerto Rican American Foundation here. The lobbying group, modeled
on the influential Cuban American National Foundation and working
independently of the Puerto Rican government, seeks to spread the
gospel about Puerto Rico's conservative conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very conservative society,'' Marquez said. ``Not a
`West Side Story,' welfare-cheating society as it is portrayed in
some circles.''
</P>
<P>
   His group recently ran an advertisement on conservative talk
shows supporting a Republican bill for education tax credits,
saying, ``If school choice can work in Puerto Rico, it will work
for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of statehood counter that the Republican image is not
as pure as Rossello and his supporters have presented it. Puerto
Rico also has strict gun control laws and a universal health care
system. ``And we still have the view that the government is the
most important player guaranteeing social justice for the people,''
said Anibal Acevedo Vila, president of the Popular Democratic
Party, which supports keeping a variation of the island's current
commonwealth status. In other words, despite the governor's recent
efforts, many Puerto Ricans love big government, Avevedo Vila said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the U.S. House of Representatives voted 209-208 to set
Puerto Rico self-determination in motion. The 10-year process would
begin with a referendum allowing Puerto Ricans to choose among
three options: independence, statehood or commonwealth status.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was supported by proponents of statehood, including
Rossello and both houses of the Puerto Rican Legislature, as well
as the relatively small faction supporting independence. It was
vigorously opposed by commonwealth backers, who said the bill, in
putting forward a narrow definition of commonwealth for the
referendum, was unfairly slanted toward statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Now the onus is on the U.S. Senate. Lott has said there is
simply not enough time this year to grapple with an issue as
contentious as Puerto Rico's self-determination. But Sen. Frank
Murkowski, R-Alaska, who heads the Committee on Energy and Natural
Resources and vividly remembers Alaska's own struggle for
statehood, is forging ahead with a streamlined bill that at the
least would allow for a referendum and a set of approved
definitions.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollsters and consultants have advised party members
to seize on the issue of Puerto Rican self-determination, saying it
is a natural for Hispanic voters and one that tracks with the
party's support of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanics in this country hold many of the same virtues and
values as Republicans, but they continue to feel alienated by what
they characterize as the close-mindedness on the part of
Republicans in their approach to governing,'' two Republican
pollsters, Ed Goeas and William Stewart, wrote in a report on a
national study of Hispanic attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is complicated, especially in an election year,
confronting as it does questions of language and cultural identity.
Although Puerto Rico is predominantly Spanish-speaking, English is
routinely spoken in government and business, and it has a distinct
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should assume that the road to a status change will be
short or smooth,'' Murkowski warned at a recent hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Spain ceded Puerto Rico to the United States in 1898 after the
Spanish-American War. Congress granted U.S. citizenship to Puerto
Ricans in 1917 and made the island a commonwealth in 1952. Puerto
Rico has its own laws, taxes and government. Puerto Ricans who live
on the island are subject to U.S. military service, but do not pay
federal taxes, cannot vote for presidential or congressional
candidates, and are not entitled to most federal benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans are almost equally split between statehood and
commonwealth status. Relatively few favor independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 75 percent of Puerto Rican voters align themselves
with status options rather than candidates, programs or solutions
to pressing problems,'' Murkowski said. ``This orientation distorts
governance.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One important battle over the referendum bill centers on how to
define ``commonwealth.'' Commonwealth supporters pushed for a broad
definition that would guarantee American citizenship, among other
things. The House rejected that definition, and now commonwealth
backers say they will boycott the referendum, if it comes to pass.
Statehood supporters say a definition guaranteeing citizenship is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Without a guarantee of U.S. citizenship, most Puerto Ricans,
even those who see economic advantages in commonwealth status, are
likely to vote for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   In pressing their case for a referendum, which they believe will
lead to statehood and greater economic prosperity on the island,
Rossello and his chief lobbyist, Xavier Romeu, have painstakingly
listed the governor's chief accomplishments since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello has privatized the government-owned shipping industry,
the hotel industry and, most recently, the telephone industry. He
has cut the capital gains tax to 7 percent from 20 percent. He has
slashed welfare spending by 20 percent and made both English and
Spanish official languages. And Puerto Rico has seen a 19 percent
reduction in the personal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch does not thrill Democrats of Puerto Rican descent.
Rep. Jose Serrano, a New York liberal who supports the referendum,
practically grimaces at the thought of Puerto Rico as a
conservative bastion, describing it as pandering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do so much to please the master,'' said Serrano, who calls
Puerto Rico the last U.S. colony. ``People are desperate to make
their point. It's like we can make you guys wish you had another 50
states just like us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980723.0524 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADET-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      07-23 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURORS DELIBERATING FATE OF FORMER AIR FORCE CADET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: No verdict as of 9:30 p.m., CDT) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ In passionate closing arguments Thursday,
prosecutors portrayed capital murder defendant David Graham as an
arrogant executioner who played God to fulfill his domineering
girlfriend's demands to kill a romantic rival.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham's defenders, conceding that the former U.S. Air Force
Academy cadet covered up the 1995 slaying of 16-year-old Adrianne
Jones near Fort Worth, pleaded for a not-guilty verdict from the
five-woman, seven-man jury. Attorney Dan Cogdell said the state
coerced Graham's false confession and relied on flimsy
circumstantial evidence obtained by a ``confederacy of dunces''
known as the Grand Prairie Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The harshly conflicting arguments, following five days of
testimony, apparently caused jurors to proceed slowly with their
deliberations, which began about 4:30 p.m, CDT.
</P>
<P>
   There was no verdict by 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors opted not to seek the death penalty at the behest of
the victim's family. If convicted of capital murder, Graham, 20,
would automatically be sentenced to life in prison with no parole
for at least 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of extensive publicity in North Texas, the trial was
moved here from Tarrant County, where the murder occurred Dec. 4,
1995, and where co-defendant and former U.S. Naval Academy
midshipman Diane Zamora, Graham's ex-fiancee, was convicted of the
same crime and given a life sentence earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this trial, questions were raised about how blame
should be shared by the former sweethearts. Prosecutor Mike Parrish
said that in his own words, Graham described how he and Zamora
planned to kill Jones to satisfy Zamora's ``womanly vengeance''
related to Zamora's unfounded suspicion that Graham had been
unfaithful to Zamora with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told him to do it, and he did,'' Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow prosecutor Michelle Hartmann described Jones as the
unsuspecting victim in a trap set by Graham and Zamora.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the sacrifice on the altar of David Graham's ego, his
cowardice, his utter lack of humanity,'' Hartmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish told jurors that it remains unclear why Graham chose
Jones to falsely portray as a previous love interest, sending
Zamora into a rage. Regardless, the prosecutors said, his
confession proved his guilt because it included details about the
murder that he could have known only if he were present.
</P>
<P>
   With Jones' family watching from the packed courtroom's front
row, Parrish described what he called the most likely scenario for
Jones' death. He said the tragedy began with a phone conversation
in which Graham lied to Jones, his teammate on the Mansfield High
School cross-country track team, to lure her out of her house late
one Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Graham driving and Zamora hidden in the trunk, Jones got
into Zamora's car and was driven to near Joe Pool Lake, where
Zamora emerged from hiding and struck Jones on the head with a
heavy object, Parrish said. Jones surprisingly came to and tried to
flee but was pursued by Graham, who struck her in the head with a
potentially fatal second blow and, after she collapsed, shot her
twice in the face from close range, Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   The crime went unsolved about nine months, until Zamora's
college roommate told naval authorities that Zamora had confessed
to her. Within a few days, in early September 1996, Zamora was sent
home from the Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., and was arrested in
Texas and Graham was interrogated and arrested at the Air Force
Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo. Before their arrests, Graham and
Zamora met in Colorado and coordinated their stories, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said Graham callously asked authorities to guess what
object was used to strike Jones before she was shot to death and he
asked for a written promise that the death penalty would not be
sought against him. In addition to his formal confession, he also
penned jailhouse letters that confirmed his guilt, Parrish said,
including one that said, ``Whether or not I shot someone is beside
the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell urged jurors to consider lesser offenses, including
murder and aggravated kidnapping, but he emphasized his contention
that the state failed to prove Graham was at the murder scene.
Instead, the state relied on emotional appeals, Cogdell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They waved around bloody pictures,'' Cogdell said. ``... It
affected you and you'd be without a heart or without a soul if it
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the state's presentation ``a Wal-Mart prosecution'' in
which jurors were asked to peruse a series of attractive yet
conflicting scenarios that never mesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day by day, witness by witness, the state changed its theory
at least five times,'' Cogdell said to jurors. ``Every day they
wanted you to buy something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell also assailed Graham's confession, pointing out that its
very first sentence, in which Graham claimed he had a single sexual
encounter with Jones a month before her murder, was proven false by
a prosecution witness. That witness said she took Jones home the
night Graham claimed he had sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a Danielle Steele novel,'' the attorney said.
``It's full of prose, it's full of pretty language, it's full of
heart-tugging memories. But what does it say about the crime? Four
sentences ... that proved to be dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
