Zamora into a rage. Regardless, the prosecutors said, his
confession proved his guilt because it included details about the
murder that he could have known only if he were present.
</P>
<P>
   With Jones' family watching from the packed courtroom's front
row, Parrish described what he called the most likely scenario for
Jones' death. He said the tragedy began with a phone conversation
in which Graham lied to Jones, his teammate on the Mansfield High
School cross-country track team, to lure her out of her house late
one Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Graham driving and Zamora hidden in the trunk, Jones got
into Zamora's car and was driven to near Joe Pool Lake, where
Zamora emerged from hiding and struck Jones on the head with a
heavy object, Parrish said. Jones surprisingly came to and tried to
flee but was pursued by Graham, who struck her in the head with a
potentially fatal second blow and, after she collapsed, shot her
twice in the face from close range, Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   The crime went unsolved about nine months, until Zamora's
college roommate told naval authorities that Zamora had confessed
to her. Within a few days, in early September 1996, Zamora was sent
home from the Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., and was arrested in
Texas and Graham was interrogated and arrested at the Air Force
Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo. Before their arrests, Graham and
Zamora met in Colorado and coordinated their stories, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said Graham callously asked authorities to guess what
object was used to strike Jones before she was shot to death and he
asked for a written promise that the death penalty would not be
sought against him. In addition to his formal confession, he also
penned jailhouse letters that confirmed his guilt, Parrish said,
including one that said, ``Whether or not I shot someone is beside
the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell urged jurors to consider lesser offenses, including
murder and aggravated kidnapping, but he emphasized his contention
that the state failed to prove Graham was at the murder scene.
Instead, the state relied on emotional appeals, Cogdell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They waved around bloody pictures,'' Cogdell said. ``... It
affected you and you'd be without a heart or without a soul if it
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the state's presentation ``a Wal-Mart prosecution'' in
which jurors were asked to peruse a series of attractive yet
conflicting scenarios that never mesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day by day, witness by witness, the state changed its theory
at least five times,'' Cogdell said to jurors. ``Every day they
wanted you to buy something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell also assailed Graham's confession, pointing out that its
very first sentence, in which Graham claimed he had a single sexual
encounter with Jones a month before her murder, was proven false by
a prosecution witness. That witness said she took Jones home the
night Graham claimed he had sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a Danielle Steele novel,'' the attorney said.
``It's full of prose, it's full of pretty language, it's full of
heart-tugging memories. But what does it say about the crime? Four
sentences ... that proved to be dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
