<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT-GAME FAULTS REACH RACETRACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Del Mar, the purse is raised from $150,000 to $250,000 for
Saturday's San Diego Handicap, as a racetrack press release phrases
it, ``in anticipation of'' Silver Charm running. At Monmouth Park
in New Jersey, the purse is raised from $250,000 to $500,000 and
the distance is changed from 1 1/16 to 1[ miles for the Aug. 30
Iselin Handicap so that Skip Away will enter.
</P>
<P>
   And in general, horse racing feels more like boxing every day.
</P>
<P>
   As if the two ancient sports didn't have enough problems in
common, including public suspicion of the results and the
widespread perception of inhumanity. Now, more and more, horses'
handlers imitate fight managers by demanding as much money as
possible for races posing as little risk as possible, and tracks
imitate fight promoters by paying. The upshot: The showdowns the
fans want to watch rarely happen.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to blame owners and trainers for cashing in on the
drawing power of their marquee horses, whose careers can end at any
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Less understandable is the thinking of track executives. Raising
a purse to attract Silver Charm, the popular 1997 Kentucky Derby
winner, or Skip Away, the nation's top-ranked thoroughbred,
guarantees a bigger crowd for one day. But it takes money away from
purses for everyday races, cheats history and the public out of the
talked-about matchups upon which the sport was founded, and
encourages horse owners to think future purses are negotiable as
well.
</P>
<P>
   It's worthwhile if a track sweetens the pot to encourage two or
more ``name'' horses to race against each other, as Santa Anita did
in 1995, boosting its Derby from $500,000 to $700,000 on the
condition that the field included four winners of graded stakes at
one mile or longer.
</P>
<P>
   It's shortsighted if a track sweetens the pot so that a single
famous horse will liven up an otherwise drab race, creating a
mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   (And it's worse than that when the famous horse proceeds to lose
the race because he isn't ``cranked up,'' as Silver Charm did in
last month's Stephen Foster Handicap, which Churchill Downs
inflated from $500,000 to $750,000.)
</P>
<P>
   Some have criticized the San Diego Handicap purse increase
because Silver Charm is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, and Bob
Lewis is chairman of Thoroughbred Owners of California, which had
to approve the change. Others have pointed out that Silver Charm
probably would have run in the San Diego even without the purse
increase. But Lewis' conflict of interest and the question of
necessity are secondary concerns.
</P>
<P>
   When the fledgling National Thoroughbred Racing Association
becomes a full-fledged governing body, it should exert some
influence over scheduling and purses, encouraging tracks to raise
purses only to increase _ rather than dilute _ competition.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the NTRA might as well be the WBO.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; The weekend: &LR; !off! Silver Charm drew post 6, one from
the outside, and will carry 125 pounds, giving away eight to 15,
for the San Diego on Saturday. He and jockey Gary Stevens figure to
sit off the lead, to be set by Hal's Pal or Mud Route, early in the
11/16-mile race, a prep for the 1\-mile Pacific Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Among the weekend's four stakes at Del Mar, the other big one is
the Bing Crosby Handicap on Sunday. Son of a Pistol, coming off
back-to-back stakes victories, and Gold Land, the '95 Bing Crosby
winner, are among seven likely entrants in one of the top sprints
of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; Claim to fame: &LR; !off! Of the two winners in the divided
Oceanside Stakes on Wednesday, Ladies Din was the more impressive,
but Scooter Brown had the more interesting background.
</P>
<P>
   Scooter Brown, a 3-year-old gelding by Fly Till Dawn, has run
for four trainers already. He was claimed in consecutive maiden
races at Santa Anita, for $50,000 by Bob Baffert from Bob Hess Jr.,
then for $62,500 by John Sadler from Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was probably 20th on Baffert's depth chart,'' Sadler joked
after the Oceanside, Scooter Brown's fourth win in six starts since
the claim. ``He had so many great 3-year-olds, I think he had to
run one of them for a high (claiming price).''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; Comedown: &LR; !off! After the full program on opening day,
fields of seven or fewer horses account for half the races Thursday
and today.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar racing director Tom Robbins said he thinks the horse
shortage will be temporary, caused by the late arrival of some
barns and by a strong finish at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not a cause for concern,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; Notes: &LR; !off! Two memories of Brian Mayberry, who died
Monday at 60: 1.Despite being a third-generation racehorse trainer,
and thus a part of one of the world's more insular subcultures, he
had an active, broad mind. A conversation with Brian invariably
turned to politics or something else outside the track. 2.That
didn't make him any less passionate about racing. I'm thinking
about a horsemen's association meeting, in the stately Santa Anita
turf club a few years ago, where Mayberry rose to speak, went on a
profane, five-minute rant and stormed out, disgusted by the
proceedings. Of course, he might have had one or two.... Defying
our prediction, the Del Mar race timer did not malfunction on
opening day. On the other hand, the fire alarms kept going off
accidentally.... Said Bill Kingston, of the Hollywood Park
promotions department, during an appearance on intertrack TV
Monday: ``Thanks, one and all, to all you racing fans. It's because
of your support that this great racing industry survives.''
Survives? Thank !ital!you!off!, Bill, for that cheery message. &QL; 
!hair! &UR; !ital!Kevin Modesti is a Daily News columnist. His horse
racing column appears Friday &LR; s.  &UR; He can be reached at (818)
713-3616.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
