<SLUG> BC-FILM-RYAN-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAVING PRIVATE RYAN' A POWERFUL MOVIE OF SOLDIERS IN COMBAT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the American heartland, one farm displays four stars in the
front window. Each star represents a son serving in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Following D-Day, June 6, 1944, the mother of those sons gets
three devastating telegrams.
</P>
<P>
   Three deaths in one family is enough, the military brass decide.
The fourth son, Pvt. James Ryan, must be pulled out of battle and
sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Pvt. Ryan parachuted behind enemy lines on D-Day. The Army
doesn't know his exact location or even if he is still alive. It
just knows that wherever he is, there will be German soldiers and
desperate fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the story of eight U.S. soldiers _
Rangers _ sent to find one soldier and bring him out of danger.
Around this simple story director Steven Spielberg, writer Robert
Rodat and star Tom Hanks have fashioned a magnificent and stunning
picture of soldiers in combat.
</P>
<P>
   To say that ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the best war movie ever
made _ as ``Citizen Soldier'' author Stephen Ambrose has done _
bypasses many great films. But ``Saving Private Ryan'' definitely
ranks among the finest.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly the most realistic major war movie ever in its
depiction of the horrors, confusion and courage of infantry combat.
The combat scenes, shot with jolting, hand-held cameras from low
angles, give the film an incredible documentary feel that lets us
see through the eyes of a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   As good as that is, however, it would be meaningless by itself.
What elevates ``Saving Private Ryan,'' making it far more than a
well-staged action film, is its ability to convey the simple
humanity of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   This movie reminds us constantly that under the uniform of a
combat soldier is an ordinary civilian, homesick, scared, tired and
angry. He is not a hard-nosed professional, but a man eager to do
his job as well as he can, get it over with and go back alive to
his real world.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it is Tom Hanks, not some Hollywood action hero, who
plays Capt. John Miller. Hanks' common-man characteristics embody
the concept of the citizen soldiers of World War II _ most of them
never in uniform until after Pearl Harbor _ who fought and won the
war.
</P>
<P>
   We first see Miller aboard a landing craft approaching Omaha
Beach on D-Day. Like others around him, some praying, some vomiting
because of the stormy seas, he is scared of what lies just minutes
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   As the landing craft drops its gate, a slaughter begins. When
the first projectile wangs immediately through the helmet of the
fron4B9, we know this will be no traditional combat film.
</P>
<P>
   For the next half-hour, we are dragged up the beach and into the
slaughter with Miller and his men. Confusion and death reign. Men
are blown in the air and land with limbs missing. They are shot in
the water, and die silently. Their blood pours onto the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Progress is not made through heroism _ though courageous deeds
are everywhere _ but through sheer necessity. To stay on the beach
is to die.
</P>
<P>
   The D-Day assault is one of two major battle scenes that frame
``Saving Private Ryan,'' and both are amazingly realistic. Both,
particularly the first, are free of the sense of careful staging
and poetic violence found in most war movies. Events seem to happen
naturally with no character sure to die because the story line
takes him home next week or sure to live because he's a nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   Between the battles is the search. Miller is sent with seven men
to locate Ryan. As they get farther into hostile country, the men
begin to question what they are doing there. Why are their lives
less important than the life of Private Ryan? Don't they have
mothers too?
</P>
<P>
   ``This Ryan better be worth it'' becomes a familiar refrain.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, too, in his private moments, has doubts about the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd better go home and invent the cure for some disease or a
longer-lasting light bulb,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the men find Private Ryan alive was surely meant
to be the film's biggest question. That went out the window when
Matt Damon, who was virtually unknown when Spielberg cast him as
Ryan, became a star too big to leave out of posters after the movie
was shot.
</P>
<P>
   But we still must find out what kind of man he is. The squad
certainly does not expect what they find.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Miller remains a mystery to his troops, believing that
withholding part of himself gives him a strength and aura that he
needs in order to lead. He also wants to keep his home life sacred
and apart from the horrors he sees here, as though somehow by not
speaking about it, he can keep it, and himself, safe and unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's only confidant is Sgt. Horvath (Tom Sizemore). They
fought in Italy together. Pvt. Reiben (Edward Burns) is the most
outspoken of those opposed to the mission and charismatic enough to
get the other men to listen.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's many powerful and tense scenes occurs when the
squad takes a German prisoner after a bitter, costly fight. They
have no way to take prisoners on this mission. The ensuing argument
over shooting this enemy, now begging for his life, shocks the
naive Cpl. Uhham (Jeremy Davies) who has never been in combat and
is totally unprepared for what it makes men capable of.
</P>
<P>
   Good moments large and small abound. When the squad links up
with a larger unit with Nazi prisoners, Pvt. Mellish (Adam
Goldberg) holds up his Star of David and shouts ``Jude, Jude''
(Jew, Jew) at them.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks is perfect as Miller, his average-man look and style
molding itself exactly to the idea of the common civilian forced to
do things he would never have believed possible in his former life.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg, as usual with his serious films, has built an
excellent cast of fine actors and gotten the best from them. Edward
Burns, the writer, director and star of independent films (``The
Brothers McMullen''), was intended as the hot young newcomer. He
holds up well here as a challenge to Hanks' authority.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore, Damon and the rest of the cast are also all fine, with
Barry Pepper, as a sniper who prays before each kill, especially
memorable.
</P>
<P>
   But Spielberg is the star of this movie, not because he makes us
aware of his presence, but because he makes us forget it by putting
us so completely in the world of combat. The battle scenes in this
movie were amazingly hard to stage and shoot, and they are
unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   A squad of new World War II movies are in the pipeline,
including the much-anticipated ``The Thin Red Line,'' from the
James Jones novel. They have a high standard to follow in ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The graphic violence of ``Saving Private Ryan'' is not the
``Gee, that's cool'' beautifully choreographed violence of
Hollywood action films. Men do not get shot and fall neatly dead,
or ask their friends to ``Go get 'em for me, boys.'' They die
bloody and slowly and crying for mother or morphine.
</P>
<P>
   How can this be entertaining? That's the wrong word, but the
movie is riveting and fascinating. I can hardly wait to see it
again and to take my father, a D-Day veteran.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Schindler's List,'' Spielberg manages to show
something unspeakably horrible, without sentiment and without
flinching, yet makes us feel uplifted by it. The movie portrays
American soldiers as merely human and more to be admired and
appreciated for their humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg wanted to make a movie that honored men, such as his
father, who fought in the war. And he wanted to make a movie that
made war seem unthinkable. He has managed both magnificently well.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is rated R for intense, prolonged, realistically
graphic sequences of war violence, and for language. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
