<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-VACATION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS FIGHT SYMINGTON'S REQUEST FOR HONDURAN VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite his conviction on federal fraud charges last summer,
former Gov. Fife Symington wants to spend a weeklong Christmas
vacation with his family in Honduras this year.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors stepped in his way Thursday, filing papers in U.S.
District Court saying the onetime developer and Republican
political leader has no reason to take the trip, particularly in
view of the fact that he owes restitution to victims of his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``His desire to take a tropical vacation, even as he fails to
make any restitution payments, is insufficient to merit modifying
the conditions of release pending appeal,'' prosecutors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors David Schindler and George Cardona also said the
court should not tolerate even a minimal risk that Symington could
flee, nor should his victims face a risk that Symington will
``conceal assets in a foreign country or . . . spend money on
lavish foreign travel rather than make restitution.''
</P>
<P>
   John Dowd, Symington's attorney, bristled at the comments and
accused prosecutors of ``financial bigotry'' by holding the
Symington family's wealth against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens to be a family treat to him (Symington),'' Dowd
said. ``It's not lavish.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington's pretrial services officer, the person appointed by
the court to keep track of Symington's whereabouts, does not oppose
Symington's request.
</P>
<P>
   Symington was convicted in September of defrauding lenders who
extended millions of dollars in loans to his real-estate ventures,
most of which later went belly up. Many loans were not repaid.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced in February to 2{ years in prison and five
years' probation, but he remains free pending appeal of his case to
the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Symington's conviction has done little to change his lifestyle.
An heir to an East Coast steel fortune, Symington is often seen in
the chichi eateries of the East Camelback financial corridor, where
he still maintains an office at the Camelback Esplanade.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, since petitioning for personal bankruptcy in 1995,
he has claimed few assets of his own. Most of the family's assets
are in the name of Symington's wife, Ann, a wealthy heiress in her
own right who has financed his multimillion-dollar legal battles
through most of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Symington also made news late last year by becoming an
investor in Roy's, a trendy upscale chain of restaurants
specializing in Pacific cuisine that opened an outlet in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to asking this week for permission to travel to
Honduras, Symington asked the court for permission to travel with
his wife to Hawaii at the end of this month on restaurant-related
business.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are not opposed to that trip, apparently because it
is business-related.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to Judge Roger Strand of the U.S. District Court to
decide whether to modify Symington's travel restrictions to
accommodate the trips.
</P>
<P>
   Symington made a similar Christmas sojourn to Honduras last year
after his conviction but before his passport was lifted at
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is free to move about within Arizona, Symington must
now have the permission of his pretrial services officer to go out
of state and must stay within the continental United States. He
also must stay in contact with his pretrial services officer.
</P>
<P>
   Early this week, Symington asked Strand to modify those terms to
expand that travel. The Honduras trip is scheduled for Dec. 25 to
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors suggested Thursday that the vacation simply
cannot be justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defendant is a convicted felon facing a substantial term of
incarceration,'' they wrote. ``In addition, he has been ordered to
pay restitution to the victims of his crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely how much Symington owes is uncertain. Although Strand
imposed restitution as a condition of Symington's sentence, he left
the amount to be decided by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court, where
Symington is battling a group of pension funds that loaned him $10
million to develop a downtown project a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   That loan was never repaid, despite a court judgment that now is
well over $12 million, with interest.
</P>
<P>
   The pension funds are suing to keep the debt from being
discharged by the Bankruptcy Court. If successful, the pension
funds could attach any assets Symington claims as his own in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   All Symington's other debts were discharged last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd said prosecutors' concerns about Symington's restitution
are unfounded because ``there has been no final judgment in
Bankruptcy Court.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
