<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-23 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0638 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MAFIA!-REVIEW-HN     07-23 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAFIA!-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANGSTER PARODY FULL OF TIRED JOKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDY SUMMA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would Lloyd Bridges want to be remembered this way?
</P>
<P>
   His last major film turned out to be ``Mafia!,'' a degenerate
flop that's meant to send up gangster films _ but instead parodies
the parodies.
</P>
<P>
   The craggy-faced actor of such classics as the 1952 western
``High Noon'' and the pioneering TV series ``Sea Hunt'' is perhaps
best known for his hilariously goofy performances in ``Airplane!''
and ``Airplane II: The Sequel.'' These nonstop laughathons,
dependent on silly puns, crazy puns and groan-inducing puns,
presented Bridges to a whole new audience.
</P>
<P>
   The same audience that laughed at Bridges' wild antics in
``Airplane!'' is the one obviously targeted for ``Mafia!.'' But
they'll yawn through this 1 1/2-hour flatulence joke. Directed by
Jim Abrahams (``Airplane!,'' ``Hot Shots!''), ``Mafia!'' completely
bungles the intended comedic hits.
</P>
<P>
   Gangster movies such as ``GoodFellas,'' ``The Godfather'' and
``The Godfather Part II'' are long overdue for an ``Airplane!''
makeover. These films' deliciously intriguing and openly violent
underworlds are practically tailor-made for parody.
</P>
<P>
   But Abrahams doesn't choose these mafia masterpieces to send up.
Curiously, he chooses the 1995 Martin Scorsese retread, ``Casino,''
as his framework. And instead of poking fun at the hit man or
kingpin personas, Abrahams relies on such howlers as El Nino jokes
and vomit gags. These movies have never been highbrow, but
``Mafia!'' scrapes the bottom of the now-empty barrel for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows a juvenile Tiny Tim character named Vincenzo
Cortino (Jason Fuchs). After accidentally discovering an
underground drug transit system, Cortino is forced to flee Italy
for America. He sneaks out of trouble by hiding, um, in a mule.
Don't ask. It's not any funnier on screen, either.
</P>
<P>
   Then the little boy misses the boat to New York and has to swim
across the Atlantic to Ellis Island. There, at the immigration
office, Abrahams pans across the immigrants _ stopping long enough
to hear an Indian quip, ``But I had reservations!''
</P>
<P>
   The laughs keep coming as Vincenzo grows up to become the mighty
but accident-prone patriarch of the country's most powerful crime
family. Along the way, we are introduced to his hunchbacked old
mother, two n'er-do-well sons and his opulent empire built on good
old-fashioned ``decapitations and bloody violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in his twilight years, and a victim of an attempted
assassination, Cortino must hand over the keys to the kingdom to
one of his sons. One is a passive war hero, Anthony, played by Jay
Mohr; the other is a violent, irrational maniac (a weak nod to Joe
Pesci). Cortino chooses Anthony, and he promptly heads to Las
Vegas. There, he runs a crooked casino, where smart visitors ``mail
us the money to save on air fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid dated Democratic party-funding humor, tired slapstick
jamborees and more body excretion jokes, Anthony meets a wild
dancer named Pepper. He falls in love with her, and his
slot-machine empire soon crumbles. Then he finds out she's sleeping
with his maniacal but gifted brother.
</P>
<P>
   The film ends with a grossly underdeveloped ``Godfather'' trap,
complete with explosions and mafia doubletalk. Everybody dies, but
``Mafia!'' mines a golden comic nugget when (hold your breath!):
Barney, the purple dinosaur, gets whacked!
</P>
<P>
   There are a few chuckles _ and one or two truly hilarious sight
gags _ but there's nothing new here. The jokes are the same, but
with different deliveries. It's like watching a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges' 57-year acting career landed him in 161 performances _
some good (``Hot Shots!''), some bad (``Honey, I Blew Up the
Kid''). But I don't think even Bridges _ wherever in the cosmos he
is now _ would pay to watch ``Mafia!.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd probably just rent ``Airplane!'' again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
