<SLUG> BC-DEATH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY SUBCONTRACTOR ALSO AT FAULT IN HIT-AND-RUN SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
 AWARD-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't only a drunken driver who killed 11-year-old
Christopher ``Kipp'' Turner four years ago, a jury concluded
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a Southwest Gas Company subcontractor that failed to
provide a safe walkway at a construction site along Frank Lloyd
Wright Boulevard in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Maricopa County Superior Court panel awarded $6
million to Kipp's parents, Ted Turner and Deborah Luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relief as a father, and to be on the other side of the
legal proceedings,'' Turner said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been four long years,'' he added. ``It's time to live.
It's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he continues to have nightmares about the night he
watched in terror as his son died. The two were walking home April
12, 1994, to watch a videotape they had just rented when the boy
was killed by a hit-and-run driver, Edward Palenkas.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Palenkas and a friend had dinner and cocktails at
Reata Pass Steak House. Palenkas, who was drinking and had earlier
in the day taken prescription drugs, refused offers of a ride home
from the bartender and his friend.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting Kipp, Palenkas never stopped or slowed down,
Turner said. Police later traced the car to Palenkas using
fragments of a broken turn-signal lens.
</P>
<P>
   Palenkas pleaded guilty to manslaughter and leaving the scene of
a fatal accident. He was given five years' probation and ordered to
donate $20,000 to Mothers Against Drunk Driving or similar
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and Luck filed a wrongful-death suit in 1994. Their
attorney, Richard Treon, said the accident never would have
happened if Southwest Gas and its subcontractor, Arizona Pipeline
Company, had made a safe walkway for pedestrians alongside the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Gas and Arizona Pipeline were found 75 percent
responsible for the death, making them liable for $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Palenkas, who was not a defendant in the suit, was found 25
percent responsible by the jury. Palenkas and Reata Pass earlier
had settled out of court with Kipp's parents for a reported $1.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   Treon said evidence at trial showed that the utility and the
subcontractor ignored every provision involving safety and
pedestrians required in its city permit for placing pipelines in
the area of Frank Lloyd Wright Boulevard and 100th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of taking 15 minutes at the end of the day and
cleaning up the work site and making it safe for pedestrians, they
had huge piles of dirt along the roadway, forcing Kipp and Ted to
walk along the street,'' Treon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They violated a fundamental principal: You don't lead
pedestrians into the path of motor vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Turner said they want the verdict to send a message to
construction companies to make roadway sites safe for pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Southwest Gas said, ``It should be
clarified that Southwest Gas was a defendant in name only in this
case. Arizona Pipeline as a contractor bore full responsibility for
the defense and any adverse judgment in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Peter Spaw, who represents Arizona Pipeline, said the
verdict set a disturbing precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I just don't feel as though that was a right
decision,'' Spaw said. ``. . . I think it sends a wrong message to
drivers who drink and dads who don't watch their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the jury Thursday determined that Ted Turner was not to
be responsible in any way for his son's death.
</P>
<P>
   Kipp was an honors student who was preparing to skip from sixth
grade to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an exceptional young man, very tender and very
thoughtful and generous with his time,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me as a father, what's been difficult is that I had to go
through something like this to find out what kind of a person my
son was.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Victoria Harker can be reached at 444-8058 or at
victoria.harker &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
