<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PAROLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SHELDON SILVER CAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 24:
</P>
<P>
   After a do-nothing legislative session that ended last month,
New York State Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver has now called his
house back to Albany to do something foolish. He wants the members
to pass a sham parole bill called ``Jenna's law'' that is being
pushed by the Republican Senate and Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The law, named after a young woman killed in Albany last year,
is being promoted by the Republicans as a way to get tougher on
violent criminals. As it turns out, Jenna's law would not have
protected Jenna Grieshaber from the man accused of her murder. He
would already have served his time in jail. This bill also provides
no help for criminals who are destined to go free eventually, even
after serving 85 percent of their sentences as this bill requires.
If dumped onto the sidewalk with little counseling and education,
which are deemed jailhouse luxuries by the Pataki administration,
these ex-cons are prepared mostly to return to New York's
overcrowded prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Silver has stretched out on the pavement and allowed the
anti-parole forces to stampede over him. The speaker announced this
week that he wants assembly members to return to Albany next
Wednesday evening for a quick fix in time for this fall's
elections. The move is strictly defensive. Democrats in a few
conservative districts of the state have convinced Silver that
their Republican opponents will use Jenna's law as a club in the
fall campaign. The state Republican Party has already sent out more
than 150,000 posters showing Silver lined up alongside nine mug
shots of the state's most notorious convicted criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The attack is demagogic. But Silver's response has been craven.
He has said that caving to the Republicans on this issue would
``take politics out of'' the parole issue. In fact, it puts
politics into the making of public policy in a way that worsens New
York's problem with overcrowded prisons that serve as training
schools for criminals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-23-98 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
