<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(cb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T PROFITS TOP ESTIMATES BUT SALES INCREASE ONLY 1%
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter earnings at AT&AMP;T exceeded analysts' expectations
by 1 cent, but sales at the telecommunications giant continued to
grow at an anemic rate. C. Michael Armstrong, who became chairman
of AT&AMP;T last fall, acknowledged the problems with revenue growth in
a conference call with analysts. ``It's just not growing enough,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot for the company was its wireless operations,
which reported a sales gain of 11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI CONSIDERS SPINNING OFF UNITS
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico is studying the possibility of converting some bottling
operations into a separate publicly traded company in order to
improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   STATES TAKE ACTION AGAINST BROKERS
</P>
<P>
   More than 29 state securities regulators brought actions against
75 little-known brokerage and investment firms for using
high-pressure sales tactics to mislead and defraud thousands of
investors by pushing an array of speculative securities and
investment deals.
</P>
<P>
   TWO OPTIONS EXCHANGES TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Exchange and the Chicago Board Options Exchange have
agreed to merge into an exchange that would handle 65 percent of
the securities options trading in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT REMAINS CONFIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives told analysts about a string of successes
in markets as diverse as home computer and the computers that
connect entire corporations and serve up Web sites on the Internet.
The company also announced plans to increase spending for research
and development and for customer support. But shares of Microsoft
fell $3.75, to $113, in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   REUTERS ACQUIRES LIPPER ANALYTICAL
</P>
<P>
   Reuters Group has acquired the mutual fund data company Lipper
Analytical Services for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   A LOSS FOR RJR NABISCO HOLDINGS
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco Holdings reported a $130 million loss in the second
quarter because of weakness in its food business,
tobacco-litigation settlement costs and the effects of the strong
dollar on overseas cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX RESULTS CLIMB 17 PERCENT IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Earnings before a charge rose 17 percent at Xerox in the second
quarter as the company sold more service contracts and high-priced
digital copiers while it reduced costs.
</P>
<P>
   BANKER TRUST EARNINGS INCREASE 7 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust reported operating earnings rose 7 percent in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   PRUDENTIAL SETTLEMENT UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   A Federal appeals court panel has upheld a $2 billion
class-action settlement between the Prudential Insurance Co. of
America and millions of customers who had been sold unnecessary
life insurance. But the court did not approve the lower court's
award of about $90 million in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   PARTIAL RESPITE IN SOUTH KOREA
</P>
<P>
   A militant labor federation agreed to further talks with the
South Korean Government after calling off a general strike, but
workers at Hyundai, the nation's largest auto maker, vowed to press
on with their walkout.
</P>
<P>
   NO DEAL REACHED ON AUTO TARIFF PACT
</P>
<P>
   Argentina and Brazil, the two dominant countries in a
four-nation South American common market called Mercosur, have
failed to complete a long-awaited agreement for common car tariffs
that auto executives had hoped would be ready for signing at a
regional summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   IBM SETTLES WITH MEXICO CITY
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican unit of IBM has agreed to pay Mexico City $37.5
million in cash and new products to resolve a dispute over a failed
data base system that it sold the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
