<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCH-HIT LUNGE LIFTS METS OVER BREWERS, 6-5
</HEADLINE>
   (cb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The day after the day that Manager Bobby Valentine
called the best of the year for the New York Mets, they were
suddenly on the verge of one of their worst days.
</P>
<P>
   Three innings from a three-game road sweep of the Milwaukee
Brewers, and with their ace on the mound, the Mets let a 5-1 lead
slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't hit one ball to blacken your eye,'' an incredulous
Al Leiter said after the Brewers had dinked their way to four runs
on six hits in the bottom of the seventh inning against Leiter and
Greg McMichael to erase the four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after Wednesday's doubleheader sweep here, Valentine also
said that maybe the pendulum had swung back in his team's favor.
That certainly seemed the case Thursday as the Mets rallied for a
6-5 victory on Matt Franco's pinch-hit, run-scoring single over the
bag at third in the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what you call an emergency swing,'' Franco said of his
check-swing thrust at a slider from Chad Fox that was inches above
the ground. The hesitant lunge at the 2-2 pitch on the outside
corner was protective more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The ball spun up the third-base line and over the bag, past the
reach of Jeff Cirillo and into left field, scoring Mike Piazza from
second base with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the ugliest swing I had all year,'' Franco
said. ``I just hit it in the perfect spot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a joke,'' Fox said. ``And he knew it was a joke. He was
on first base laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   After John Franco closed out his 20th save with a perfect ninth,
the Mets (52-46) _ who won 8 of 9 games from the Brewers this
season _ were laughing all the way to Chicago, where they will
begin a four-game series with Friday's doubleheader against the
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago leads the Mets by three and one-half games in the
wild-card race. The victory was the Mets' fourth in a row and sixth
in their last eight games. Before that, they had dropped 17 of 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you turn the calendar and get into another week, things
happen differently,'' Valentine said Thursday. ``I guarantee you,
two weeks ago, when they got those four bloop hits to tie it, we're
not going to get a bloop hit down the line to win it. Things are
going our way now. We got some breaks today.''
</P>
<P>
   Every hunch Valentine played proved correct. A double steal on a
3-1 pitch, a count on which Valentine rarely gambles, led to the
Mets' third run.
</P>
<P>
   Then Valentine sent McMichael (2-3) back out to pitch the eighth
after the seventh-inning collapse. And the right-handed reliever,
whom the Mets traded to Los Angeles on June 4, then got back on
July 10, responded with a perfect inning.
</P>
<P>
   In his second start back from the disabled list, Leiter had
allowed just one run and three hits over his first six innings. The
Mets _ who had received runs batted in from Carlos Baerga, Rey
Ordonez, Todd Hundley, Brian McRae and Butch Huskey _ appeared on
their way to an easy victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter began to labor in the seventh. After allowing a
two-out, run-scoring, bloop single to Marquis Grissom on his 118th
pitch, Leiter was done.
</P>
<P>
   On came McMichael, who fired a two-strike wild pitch over
Piazza's head to make it 5-3. Two pitches later, Jeff Cirillo
grounded a run-scoring single to left, and it was a one-run game.
John Jaha and Jeromy Burnitz followed with bloop singles, and the
game was tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care about how Chad Fox feels,'' Leiter said of
Franco's blooper. ``I saw five or six in a row behind me and Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   After Milwaukee left-hander Mike Myers struck out John Olerud to
open the top of the ninth, Piazza just missed Myers' head a line
single up the middle for his third hit of the day. Up stepped
Bernard Gilkey and his .229 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   But Myers hit Gilkey on the left shin with an 0-2 pitch. And the
Mets had runners on first and second with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine sent the right-handed-hitting Todd Pratt up to
pinch-hit. Milwaukee Manager Phil Garner called on the right-handed
Fox. Valentine responded by pinch-hitting Matt Franco for Pratt,
even though Valentine later called Pratt his hottest hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, meanwhile, was 4 for 25 as a pinch-hitter this season,
after leading the Mets in pinch-hits a year ago. Franco quickly
fell behind, 0-2. ``I knew I was in trouble, but I didn't panic,''
he said. After taking two balls and lining a foul, Franco took one
last forgettable swing _ and found himself on first base, joking
with Mookie Wilson, the coach there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a feeling,'' Valentine said later. ``And I lucked
out. It wasn't the greatest at-bat. But it sure was a productive
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
