<SLUG> BC-BKO-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA RALLIES TO SPOIL PUERTO RICO'S HOPES FOR FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (cb) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took less than five minutes, but that was all
Australia needed to snatch away from Puerto Rico a spot in the
final of the Goodwill Games basketball competition at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Australia scored 14 unanswered points in the first 4 minutes 38
seconds of the second half to turn a 44-41 halftime lead into a
68-41 margin on the way to a runaway 86-74 victory that clinched
for the Australians a spot in Friday night's championship game
against either the United States or Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was an uncharacteristic performance by Puerto Rico.
Guard Eddie Casiano, who was averaging 24.7 points a game in the
tournament, made only 5 of 16 shots and finished with 12 points.
Puerto Rico also committed 20 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   It was Australia, however, that was missing the shots early,
while the Puerto Rican center Jose Ortiz was scoring 12 points in
the game's first 9 minutes on his way to 14 first-half points.
After falling behind by 26-18, however, Australia got back into
things with a vengeance, as two resounding slam dunks by Chris
Anstey sparked a 12-2 run that was capped by Anthony Ronaldson's
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Shane Heal led Australia with 13 first-half points as he
connected on three of Australia's seven 3-pointers. Even though
Puerto Rico shot a solid 54.3 percent from the floor, to
Australia's 45.9 percent, Puerto Rico trailed at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Like Casiano, Andrew Gaze, Australia's sharp-shooting guard, was
having a poor shooting night, too, making only 2 of 10 shots in the
game and scoring 10 of his 15 points from the free throw line. But
unlike the problems Puerto Rico faced without Casiano's points,
Australia was able to find other offensive resources. Anthony
Ronaldson, who had a total of 24 points in the three previous
games, exploded for 20 points, including a key 3-pointer in his
team's run at the start of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz could not match his explosive first half and fouled out
with a game-high 23 points with 5:19 left.
</P>
<P>
   Australian forward Andrew Vlahov fouled Jerome Mincy hard into
the Australian bench with 11:06 left in the game, instigating some
shoving. Vlahov and Mincy were each assessed a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of how his coach, Barry Barnes, had inspired the team
for the second-half burst, Vlahov said, ``Basically he thought we
played conservative in the first half and he told us to loosen up,
because when we get rolling, we get rolling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
