u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TRADERS-GUILTY-NYT     07-23 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRADERS-GUILTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 COMMODITIES TRADERS PLEAD GUILTY IN SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla.)  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two commodities traders who grew up as close friends
in Connecticut pleaded guilty Thursday to conspiring to profit from
the confidential trading strategies of a major investment company.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the defendants, Andrew Rhee and Thomas Kelly, could face
up to five years in prison and a fine of $250,000 on one count of
conspiracy each to commit wire fraud, an assistant U.S. attorney,
David Lewis, said in U.S. District Court in Manhattan. They could
also be forced to pay restitution, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The men earned $4.7 million in illicit profits from their
scheme, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors outlined a case in court papers that involved ``an
elaborate `front running' scheme'' in which the defendants
piggybacked their own deals onto the confidential strategies of the
investment concern, John W. Henry &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, 32, worked for the company as a commodities trader from
1995 to early 1998, and Rhee, also 32, ran his own trading company.
</P>
<P>
   In court Thursday, Kelly admitted to Judge Robert Patterson that
he had passed the confidential data to Rhee, and Rhee told the
judge that he had used the information from Kelly to make the
trades that gave the men their illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
   When an investment company like John Henry trades in commodities
like corn or soybeans, it often buys or sells so much at one time
that the price goes up or down. The defendants used their knowledge
of the company's trading strategy to profit from those price
movements, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the government outlined a trail of
circumstantial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kelly, who worked a day shift at John Henry's
headquarters in Boca Raton, Fla., was observed on Dec. 17 _ a day
he was supposedly on vacation _ entering the John Henry office
unexpectedly about 8 P.M. for no work-related reason, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was then observed examining trading sheets that set forth
John Henry's trading plans for the next day, the government said.
Prosecutors did not say who observed him.
</P>
<P>
   On the next day, the investment concern made a purchase of corn
futures contracts, which promise the delivery of a specific amount
of corn at a specific price on a specific date. Rhee also purchased
corn futures that day, prosecutors said, and later sold them for a
profit of about $48,000.
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, Dec. 4, 1996, Kelly left a black-tie dinner
and returned to his office, still wearing his tuxedo, even though
he was not expected or required to be at work that night.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that day, the John Henry management had decided to
liquidate a particularly large number of commodity positions, and
Kelly spent one hour that evening in the trading area, where he was
in a position to confirm the company's trading plans, prosecutors
asserted in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, John Henry made a trade in coffee futures, and so
did Rhee, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the government said, Rhee, trading on information
provided illegally by Kelly, executed more than 130 trades in
futures for gold, silver, copper, sugar, coffee, cattle, crude oil
and other commodities from the United States and six other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Rhee paid Kelly at least $300,000 and also paid many of his
bills, including more than $32,000 that Kelly owed to an interior
decorator, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that the scheme depended on Kelly's access to
strategies developed by John Henry's sophisticated computer
modeling programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that information was confidential to John Henry, and I
should not have disclosed it to anyone,'' Kelly told Judge
Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Rhee also acknowledged in court that he had been aware he was
taking advantage of John Henry's confidential data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intentionally used this information to make trading profits,
which I shared equally with Kelly,'' said Rhee, who is a graduate
of New York University School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Aronica, the lawyer for Kelly, and Barry Bohrer, the
lawyer for Rhee, said their clients would have no comment. Both men
are free on $1 million bond, pending their sentencing on Oct. 9.
Kelly lives in Darien, Conn.; Rhee lives in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   John Henry's general counsel, David Kozak, said by telephone
that the company cooperated with the federal investigation and was
``glad that this is being resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate action, the Commodities Futures Trading Commission
sued both men Thursday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, seeking
fines and other penalties in connection with the scheme.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
